				<font size=5><b>The State of State Taxes</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-The State of State Taxes</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Feature<p>THE STATE OF STATE TAXES
Wyoming gives citizens the best services for their tax dollars. Guess which state gives its citizens the worst? A report on the local conditions and the national mood.<p>By Jeff Blyskal<p>As election day approaches, antitax fever continues to roil an exceptionally cranky electorate, leaving state officials decidedly spooked. To assuage this anger, 21 states have cut a combined $2.7 billion in taxes already, and candidates are promising billions more, according to the Center of the Study of the States in Albany, New York. "We are seeing a huge, populist antitax rebellion," says 
Stephen Moore, director of fiscal-policy studies at the Cato Institute, a libertarian think tank in Washington, D.C. "It is real, it is incredibly intense, and it will lead to dramatic changes in the way states do business." <p>For example, Oregon voters are now getting set to vote on the Taxpayer Protection Initiative, a measure requiring majority voter approval of any new or increased taxes or fees. Last year, angry New Jersey voters booted incumbent governor Jim Florio out of office after he broke his 1989 campaign promise not to increase taxes and instead let fly with a $2.8 billion tax hike. That loss didn't go unnoticed by New York governor Mario Cuomo, who suddenly promised a $1.5 billion tax cut last August -- if reelected. His new colleague to the south, New Jersey governor Christine Todd Whitman, who slashed taxes dramatically once she took her seat in Trenton, says, "Taxpayers know that if you cut the supply of money, the government has to go on a diet." And if it doesn't, the fear in statehouses is that residents will flee. <p>However, as voters get set to knock state tax hikes back into their elected officials' calculators, some may be going about their civic duty in a purblind manner. Oregon provides decent state services for the tax dollar, which would seem to argue against passage of a highly restrictive bill. And angry New Jersey voters may have overlooked the fact that their state and local tax bite as a percentage of per capita income is only slightly higher than the national average, while government services are better than in most other states. <p>Meanwhile, New Yorkers annually get smacked by the heaviest state and local tax sledgehammer in the land, and in return they receive dismal state and local services.<p>Curiously, New York residents continue to obey their legislators like sheep before the tax prod. We left several telephone messages at the New York Taxpayers Alliance, which sources told us is the most effective antitax lobby in the state, to see if any New York tea party was brewing. The Alliance never called back.<p>No smart buyer determines the value of any deal by looking at just the price. The question is: What are voters really getting in return for their tax dollars? <p>That's tough to answer. Standardized measures of service quality are virtually nonexistent in the government sector, where "don't ask, don't tell" has long been the policy. "There are amazingly few good quality indicators to compare state-by-state performance," says Iris Lav, director of state and local programs at the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a Washington think tank that studies government spending. <p>To fill this information vacuum, Worth, in consultation with the Center for the Study of the States; the Corporation for Enterprise Development (CFED) in Washington, D.C.; and State Budget & Tax News in Columbus, Ohio, conducted a statistical analysis to find out which state delivered the best service for the lowest tax cost. We calculated each state and local government's levies as a percentage of per capita income. We then correlated those numbers with government-service ratings in five major categories over which state and local governments exert great influence -- education, welfare, health and hospitals, highways, and law enforcement. <p>(The rankings from our analysis can be found in "The State Of State Taxes - TABLE" further down in this file.)<p>We started this project with the harsh but realistic view that every state must work with the demographic and economic hand it has been dealt. That means we had little sympathy for poverty and illiteracy in the South or the urban and infrastructure decay of the Northeast. By the same token, we didn't make adjustments for the blessings -- including federal subsidies -- that some states enjoy more than others. State and local governments, ideally with their residents' input, set the agenda for government action. If education is a true priority, the state will produce better education. Furthermore, these states have had decades to develop service strategies -- it's their responsibility to make the most of what they have.<p>We also looked beyond conventional measures to gauge performance. Take welfare. We did not rely on the amount of money doled out by bureaucrats as a standard of quality, since the $5.3 trillion in taxpayer money spent on poverty programs over the last 30 years or so has not wiped out this problem. According to a 1992 Census Bureau report, the most effective way for the government to beat poverty is to educate its people and support economic development. So we measured how a state fosters job growth. <p>The overall winner: Wyoming. Runner-up: Alaska. At the bottom of the pile: New York. Wyoming beat the pack largely because of its high-quality education and health programs. Wyoming's students-per-teacher ratio of 14 is 30 percent lower than the national average of 20 students per teacher, and 89 percent of the population has a high school diploma or better -- the third highest in the nation. Since poverty tends to be associated with low educational attainment, it should be no surprise that Wyoming has the ninth-lowest poverty level. Wyoming also has the greatest number of public hospital beds per 100,000 population, and a very low infant-mortality rate of 6.8 per 1,000 live births, compared with 8.5 nationwide.<p>In Alaska, the student-teacher ratio is a better-than-average 17, SAT scores are 911 versus the national average of 902, and 94 percent of students are enrolled in public universities, where tuition is 75 percent lower than at private schools. The number of residents achieving high school graduation or better is high (89 percent), and poverty is low (10 percent). <p>Wyoming and Alaska residents also enjoy low out-of-pocket tax costs. That's partly because each state is annually subsidized with severance taxes paid by oil, gas, and coal companies that extract natural resources there. The Wyoming state government gets $254 million, Alaska almost $1.5 billion (our calculations took these figures into account). A state's population, however, determines the average amount of each resident's subsidy. Populous Texas, for example, sucks in $1.4 billion in severance taxes, but the per capita subsidy amounts to only $78. In Wyoming, the per capita subsidy is $550; in Alaska it's $2,600. Despite such subsidies, both Wyoming and Alaska rank high because each turned in a stellar service performance, not just because of their low tax bite. Nothing lasts forever, by the way: Alaska, after several years of slumping oil royalties, is considering enacting its first income or sales tax. <p>How bad can bad value for the tax dollar get? New York and Hawaii are the pits by a wide margin. Empire State residents suffer a barracuda-like 14.1 percent effective tax bite, and in return they receive government services that are shoddy in key areas. Student-teacher ratios are mediocre, and SAT scores on average are 14 points lower than the national average. And just 57 percent of students are enrolled in public colleges and universities. Sure, New York is home to many private schools. But given a choice between a New York state school and a private one costing four times more in annual tuition and fees -- $35,000 more over four years -- many students are choosing private schools. Consumers are clearly voting on perceived quality with their dollars and their feet.<p>Despite the fact that 81 percent of New Yorkers have a high school diploma or better, 15.3 percent of its residents live below the $14,764 poverty line established by the federal government for a family of four, versus a national average of 14.3 percent. And Democratic senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York believes that the state's poverty rate is actually understated because of the high cost of living there. The state also has a high crime rate, and the arrest rate for violent crimes is a lackluster 32 percent. Sixty-six percent of New York's bridges are functionally obsolete, the worst record in the nation. Overall, the state's highways are great, with 58 percent rated first-class. New York also posts an infant mortality rate of 8.5 per 1,000 live births, which is about average. <p>If you dream of beautiful beaches and universal health care coverage in Hawaii, a whopping 13.1 percent effective tax rate comes with the move. Hawaii offers only 100 public hospital beds per 100,000 people. Just 34 percent of the highways are first class, and 53 percent of the bridges are functionally obsolete. Also, crime rates in paradise are high, though the police do make arrests in an admirable 45 percent of violent crimes. The student-teacher ratio of 24 is substandard, but the poverty rate is low at 11 percent, and Hawaii's infant mortality rate is one of the best in the country.<p><p>Lately, delivering value for the tax dollar has been harder for state governments, as many have been forced to enact austerity measures that have pinched efforts to improve their residents' quality of life. As the service sector grows, sales taxes -- which typically dun product sales but not services -- bring in less money. States are undergoing a "low-grade fiscal crisis," says Ron Snell, fiscal program director of the National Conference of State Legislatures.<p>This dismal climate, though, hasn't precluded some states from slashing their taxes and working on their efficiency and productivity. For example, Texas comptroller John Sharp got the state legislature to approve an estimated $6.2 billion in savings since 1991. State officials intend, at least, to avoid cutting vital services. <p>The jury is still out on whether that can be done. For example, in 39th-ranked California, the effects of Proposition 13 are decidedly mixed. Proposition 13, which was approved by voters on June 6, 1978, held property taxes to 1 percent of assessed levels in 1975 and limited future increases to the annual rate of inflation or to 2 percent, whichever was lower. (When a property is sold, it is then reassessed at current fair-market value.) The measure knocked California from the fourth-highest-taxed state in the land to the 26th by 1988. Since the measure passed, state residents have enjoyed millions in property-tax reductions -- some estimates place it as high as $200 billion. <p>However, government unions and politicians have worked the media to blame these tax cuts for every ill wind blowing through the state, from the collapse of the Nimitz Freeway in the 1989 San Francisco earthquake to last year's murder of Polly Klaas. Quality in some services has eroded, while in others -- most notably law enforcement and health -- it has actually improved. "Anyone who says Proposition 13 has wrecked California is exaggerating," says Hal Hovey, publisher of State Budget & Tax News.<p>Debates about Proposition 13 are still heard in California, but many of them ignore this fact: The government has found ways around the property-tax restrictions. Lost property-tax revenues have been replaced with increased state and local user fees and levies, according to the California Taxpayers Association. And property-tax revenues to date have recovered 25 percent. <p>According to Stephen Kroes, research director for the California Taxpayers Association, California's taxes, fees, and other hidden costs today eat up the same 16 percent of personal income they did before Proposition 13. California now has a higher tax burden than 35 other states. Meanwhile, state spending is rising in some key areas. Between 1976 and 1990, inflation-adjusted per capita state and local spending in California, while up only 1 percent on education, rose 7 percent on welfare, 17 percent on fire protection, and 22 percent on police. <p>Furthermore, the circumstances that created billion-dollar budget deficits in the early '90s predate Proposition 13, according to a study that was released last April by the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities in Washington, D.C. The report says that these fiscal woes stem from structural problems in the tax system, including declining sales-tax yields and misguided policy priorities that have been in place since the mid-1970s. Recent defense layoffs, natural disasters, and immigration troubles exacerbated these problems.<p>Amid this fiscal tumult, how has California performed? By many measures, it has improved. Since 1977, the number of students per teacher in grades K-12 has declined 15 percent, from 33 to 28, according to Market Data Retrieval, an education-research firm in Shelton, Connecticut. Today, 80 percent of Californians age 25 or older have a high school diploma or better, versus 74 percent in 1980. Furthermore, the crime rate in California is down 5 percent since 1977 versus a 12 percent increase nationwide. And the percentage of first-class pavement on California interstates, freeways, and rural arterial roads rose from 51 percent in 1980 to 61 percent in 1992, according to Federal Highway Administration statistics.<p>These numbers shine an even harsher light on the lower-ranked states. Compare California's position in our rankings with New York's, and remember: New York never had a measure like Proposition 13. Small wonder 37 percent of Californians believe it was a net positive versus 25 percent who judge it a net negative, according to a 1992 Los Angeles Times poll. <p>As voters now mull over their ballot choices, they should consider this question: Can government cutbacks be accomplished without sacrificing service? We think yes. But as voters cut through the hype this fall and beyond, they should watch out for tax cuts blending into tax-shifting schemes and monitor real measures of quality in their state, not just the amount of dollars spent on local programs. 
---------------
Jeff Blyskal is a contributing editor of Worth.<p><p>The State of State Taxes - TABLE
---------------
The rankings listed below are derived from a basket of 14 
service-quality indicators provided by 11 government and private
sources. All data is from 1992 or later.<p>We started with total state and local taxes as a percentage of
of per capita income. By calculating state and local taxes in 
this manner, we eliminated distortions caused by differing income
levels between the states. The result is seen under the heading
"Tax Bite." Each state's tax bite was converted into a tax-cost
score ranging from 1 to 11.<p>We then produced a "State-Benefit Score" by assessing each state's
performance in five major areas -- education, welfare, health 
and hospitals, highways, and law enforcement.<p>To arrive at the "State-Benefit Score, we weighted the five 
benefit categories based on the national averages for government
expenditures compiled by the Advisory Commission on Inter-
governmental Relations: education, 49 percent; welfare, 21
percent; health and hospitals, 13 percent; highways, 11 percent;
and law enforcement, 6 percent. Thus high marks in education 
carried the most weight. Other expenditures, such as each state's
costs for debt service and administration, were not included.
The weighted scores for each category were converted into the
"State-Benefit Score," ranging from 1 to 11, with 11 being 
the best.<p>The "Tax-Cost" and "State-Benefit" scores were added together
to arrive at the total "TAX-VALUE SCORE." (In the event of a tie,
states are listed alphabetically.) The higher the "TAX-VALUE
SCORE," the better.<p>-- by Jeff Blyskal<p>(NOTE: IF YOU DISPLAY THE TABLE BELOW IN A MONOSPACED FONT, SUCH AS COURIER, THE COLUMNS WILL LINE UP CORRECTLY.)<p>THE TAX-VALUE RANKINGS
=================================================================
                             Tax Bite                           
                TAX-VALUE       (% of   Tax-Cost   State-Benefit
State                SCORE     income)      Score           Score
=================================================================
