		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Better Middle Class Tax Cut</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-A Better Middle Class Tax Cut</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Advisors<p>A BETTER MIDDLE CLASS TAX CUT
Why the marriage penalty should be eliminated.<p>By Elizabeth MacDonald<p>For the last two years, President Clinton has teased taxpayers with the possibility of a middle-class tax cut. Candidate Clinton promised he would pay for this tax break -- a $300 tax credit for all families -- largely through a rate increase from 31 percent to 36 percent for the wealthiest taxpayers. President Clinton did the second part, but quickly abandoned the other half of his campaign pledge upon taking office. Now the White House is refloating the tax-cut balloon, even though the president's economic advisors warn it would burst a $60 billion hole after four years in the 1993 deficit-reduction act. <p>There's a better way to give middle-class taxpayers a break without blowing the deficit out of the water. Obliterate the onerous marriage penalty, a tax-law glitch that has stung two-earner married couples for the last 35 years. Thanks to this penalty, these couples pay far more in taxes than they would have if they hadn't tied the knot. <p>According to a 1994 study by Princeton University's Center for Economic Policy Research, which looked at 96,589 tax returns filed in 1989, an estimated 52 percent of all joint filers will pay an extra $1,244 more this year on average than they would if they divorced. The total sting for married couples: $33 billion nationwide. <p>Meanwhile, the tax structure benefits households in which one spouse remains at home while the other goes off to work. According to the Princeton study, roughly 38 percent of all joint filers are subsidized by the tax law to the tune of $27 billion. That amounts to an annual $6 billion net marriage tax paid by American couples, which is equal to 40 percent of the cost of the middle-class tax cut Clinton promised. Ironically, Clinton's tax-law changes actually made the marriage penalty much worse since two new high rates were introduced. <p>The marriage penalty takes its first swipe through the progressive tax-rate structure. While the break points at which brackets change are higher for joint filers than for individuals, they are not twice as high. As a result, joint filers become subject to higher income-tax rates at lower levels of combined taxable income than if they filed as single individuals. For example, a single person who earned $75,000 in taxable income in 1994 will be taxed at 28 percent on the first $55,100 and at 31 percent for the rest. If that person married someone earning $75,000, they would owe 31 percent on income above $91,850 up to $140,000. <p>Households that have reached the golden age of income parity between the sexes get smacked the hardest. Kevin Roach, a tax partner at Price Waterhouse in New York, says that if those two $75,000 taxpayers filed individually, they would each pay a tax of $18,640 (not accounting for exemptions or deductions), or $37,280 total. If they made that trip to the altar, they would owe an additional $2,025 marriage tax. <p>The marriage penalty also occurs because the total standard deduction on a joint return is less than the sum of the deductions on two individual returns. Last year unmarried partners got a total $7,400 ($3,700 each) standard deduction, versus $6,200 for joint filers. Furthermore, in 1993 both joint and single itemizers had to reduce certain deductions by an amount equal to 3 percent of their adjusted gross income in excess of $108,450. Joint filers also get stung by the phaseout of their personal exemptions, which occurs at $162,700, versus $108,450 for individuals. <p>The story of the marriage tax begins in 1913, when the individual income tax was enacted. Back then, married couples were required to file separately if they each had income. Couples in community-property states were allowed to split their income 50-50 and therefore lessen their federal tax bite. Couples in common-law states, however, were required to pay tax according to which spouse actually earned the income.<p>Congress tried to fix this inequity in its Revenue Act of 1948, which let all married couples pay their taxes as if each spouse earned exactly half of their total income, regardless of what each actually earned. After much squawking by single filers, in 1969 lawmakers effectively eliminated income splitting and reduced the tax-rate schedule of single returns relative to that of joint returns. In so doing, the marriage penalty was born.<p>In 1981, Congress tried to fix this problem by letting two-earner married couples reduce their taxable income by 10 percent of the lower-earning spouse's wages, with a $2,000 maximum. In 1986, Congress repealed this deduction but slightly softened the marriage-tax blow by reducing marginal tax rates and increasing the standard deduction for joint returns. Clinton's creation of two more tax brackets kicked it right back into married couples' laps.<p>Throughout this tax-bill merry-go-round, Congress seems to have missed an obvious change in the American family. More two-earner households exist than ever before. According to the Census Bureau, between 1982 and 1992, the number of two-earner households rose 22.3 percent, to 33.6 million. Says Harvey Rosen, professor of economics at Princeton University and co-author of the study, "The code was written for the Beaver Cleaver family, but it's the '90s." <p>Fixing this problem won't be easy. A flat tax may do it, but "it would have to be as high as 21 percent in order to bring in the same amount of federal revenues," says New York tax attorney Lee Sheppard. "That rate, though, will slam poorer people." Tax experts agree that the current law is highly divisive. "Why is Congress increasing taxes based on marital status?" asks Sheppard. "Why should men with high incomes whose wives do not need to work be allowed to pay lower taxes?" <p>Instead, Sheppard thinks the U.S. tax law should allow all taxpayers, even married couples, to file as singles using the individual tax-rate schedule, as they do in Britain. Deductions would be taken according to who earned the income related to the writeoffs, and parents could split a child's personal exemptions. However, a British husband must report capital income in its entirety on his return, regardless of which spouse earned it. That's one tax change Americans would most likely balk at. <p>To fix that problem, splitting such income between spouses won't work. Changing the law to let taxpayers do just that would provide a fertile ground for more inequity in the tax system, as married couples could try to effectively lower their tax bills if they are in different tax brackets. One solution: Everyone should pay his or tax on that income according to who earned it.<p>It seems that Washington is finally listening. Two Democratic congressmen, Ernest Istook of Oklahoma and James Moran of Virginia, have introduced separate bills to get rid of the marriage penalty by letting married couples file as individuals. Republicans in Congress now want a bigger standard deduction and higher income thresholds at which top rates apply for married filers. They're also pushing for a $500 tax credit per child; Clinton is hinting at a $1,000 credit. Both Rosen and Sheppard, though, say a credit and a larger standard deduction do nothing to solve the marriage-tax problem -- income splitting and the differences in the tax brackets between joint and single filers are at the root of this mess.<p>Whatever the outcome, the federal government can't count on a steady cash flow from the marriage penalty making its way into federal coffers much longer. According to the Census Bureau, the number of married adults is roughly 60 percent, down from 72 percent in 1970. And more middle-aged and senior citizens are choosing to live together rather than get married. A 1994 study by the American Association of Retired Persons in Washington, D.C., says 1.6 million midlife and older people now share households as unmarried partners or roommates; 46 percent are aged 55 or older. "Taxes could be one factor causing this trend," says Deborah Chalfie, a senior program specialist at AARP. <p>For now, married partners usually won't get a benefit from filing separately because the break points for doing so are exactly half those for joint filers. One small piece of advice: High-income taxpayers who are planning to get married before the year is out may want to wait until the new year -- their tax savings could be enough to pay for both the reception and the honeymoon.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Taxation, Government Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

