	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-How IRS Does its Audit Snooping</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>How IRS Does its Audit Snooping</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-How IRS Does its Audit Snooping</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>HOW THE IRS DOES ITS AUDIT SNOOPING
The IRS is targeting its audits to cut the tax gap.<p>By George Guttman<p>Since 1988, Congress has been leaning on the IRS to cut the tax gap -- the amount that taxpayers owe but the feds don't get each year. The General Accounting Office says that amount ballooned from $87 billion in 1988 to $127 billion in 1992. One reason for this rise is a precipitous drop in the audit rate, down from roughly 5 percent in 1965 to just 0.7 percent today.<p>To fix this decline, the IRS plans to increase the $5.8 billion in extra taxes, penalties, and interest it demands from audited taxpayers by doing more audits. Last year the IRS unveiled a spanking new audit approach dubbed the market-segment-specialization program. Through this program, the IRS is lumping taxpayers with similar occupations, businesses, or tax issues into one of more than 100 market segments. Each segment has its very own IRS audit guide instructing agents to follow certain audit benchmarks and guidelines. <p>So far, guides have been publicly released for these nine groups: air-charters, attorneys, bed and breakfast owners, gasoline retailers, mortuaries, the entertainment industry, taxpayers claiming losses from passive investments, taxicab owners, and truckers. Regular wage earners who have their income tax withheld will be stuck in one of three segments, depending on their income. <p>IRS officials, long outgunned by sophisticated CPAs and tax lawyers, now say that grouping taxpayers and training auditors to become specialists in a given market segment will translate into bigger audit bucks. That means tougher times for anyone falling into a group covered by one of the guides. "The IRS is auditing us left and right in Missouri because of the guide," says a funeral director in Excelsior Springs, Missouri. And experts say businesses not yet covered by a guide aren't being touched. What's more, an IRS examination official says, "The audit chances for individuals whose income is subject to withholding will probably decrease because half of our 16,000 auditors will be assigned to business market segments full-time." <p>To get the inside dope on how to prepare for an audit shootout, we looked at three IRS audit guides. We were especially interested in the guide for lawyers because it hints at the tactics the IRS intends to use for all professional categories. So doctors and dentists need to pay attention to this one, too.<p>Among other things, we learned that the IRS plans to hunt for nonfiling lawyers by matching names it picks up from professional directories or yellow-pages advertising with its computer records. It will then compile a dossier on an attorney's educational and legal background by clipping newspaper articles. The IRS will then check for underreporting by comparing the taxpayer's income to where that person went to law school, presuming that a prestigious one indicates future affluence.<p>Besides poring through ledgers and expense reports, the IRS also plans to devote particular scrutiny to small firms -- the agency thinks the smaller the outfit, the easier it is to pocket cash payments or not report a contingent fee. Criminal and immigration attorneys are often assumed to be paid in cash. The IRS will also check whether a real estate attorney was paid with an ownership interest or a second trust deed in a real estate deal, taxable income that's hard to find. <p>Next, IRS agents will look for unreported income spirited away in fancy cars registered with state motor-vehicle departments, boats listed with the Coast Guard, and airplanes filed with the FAA. Finally, the IRS will fight tooth and nail any deductions taken for, say, lavish trips to visit clients in Aspen in January -- such trips smack of a vacation.<p>According to the bed-and-breakfast guide, the IRS apparently intends to take a shotgun approach with small businesses by haranguing the owners over everything in sight. The guide says to look for unreported income in the form of room-cancellation charges, fees for pets and kids, and referral fees. The IRS will also question owners on whether they personally used the business's food, housing, and utilities. If so, certain business writeoffs may be disallowed as personal expenses. <p>If, like many small businesses, the B&B has reported a loss for three years out of the past five years, the IRS may check to see if the inn took out any newspaper or magazine ads during that time. If there were none, then the IRS will be more inclined to reject the B&B's professed intent to make a profit and deem the operation a hobby that cannot deduct losses in excess of income. <p>High-income taxpayers with sophisticated investments may want to check the passive-activity loss guide to bulletproof their investments. This guide shows that the IRS loves it when taxpayers forget to attach forms. If a taxpayer reports a passive loss but does not include form 8582 (Passive Activity Loss Limitation), the IRS will probably audit schedule E for investment losses or schedule C for equipment or vehicle rentals. Auditors are also told to be highly suspicious of schedule C's entitled Real Estate Management and schedule A's with large investment-interest deductions. <p>By reading their market-segment guide, taxpayers and small businesses can keep better records and modify certain practices to ease a protracted audit. Tax Analysts (800-955-2444), a D.C. publishing group, is the cheapest source for the guides; it charges $25 apiece. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership, Taxation, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

