<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Best Charities for your Money</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Best Charities for your Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						How to be cautious when you're feeling generous.<p>By Troy Segal<p>Every year, it seems, some fresh charity scandal hits the headlines. The occasional news of high-living nonprofit honchos or of outright fraudulent practices among charity organizations is enough to cast doubt on the entire industry. Last January, for instance, Pennsylvania officials received a $300,000 settlement from the American Association of State Troopers for "unfair, deceptive, misleading" practices during a telemarketing campaign. The association claimed to raise funds for local police barracks, when in fact just roughly 7 percent of the $1.4 million collected went to the charity's cause -- which was in Florida.<p>Elected officials have been kept busy blasting scurrilous nonprofits over the last year, thanks to a two-year investigation by the Congressional Subcommittee on Oversight into 200 public charities. "Insiders have turned their charity into their own personal cash cow," says subcommittee chairman J.J. Pickle. "Some charities are abusing the public trust."<p>Donors are catching on. According to a 1993 Gallup poll commissioned by the Council of Better Business Bureaus, half the 1,000 people surveyed felt charities were less trustworthy than they were ten years ago. A whopping 81 percent were very or somewhat concerned that the amount a charity spends is not directly related to its stated mission. <p>Yet Americans continue to be very generous. According to the American Association of Fund-Raising Counsel's (AAFRC) Trust for Philanthropy, individuals gave roughly $102.6 billion to charities last year, 28 percent more than they gave five years earlier, thanks in part to the 1993 tax increases. <p>Smart donors ought to look more closely at exactly where their charitable donations are going. Some charities spend around 70 percent of their cash donations on expenses such as fund-raising, executive salaries, travel, and entertainment, rather than the cause itself, according to the Philanthropic Advisory Service in Arlington, Virginia, an arm of the Better Business Bureaus that evaluates charities. Furthermore, a recent study by the New York State Office of Charities Registration found that 95 percent of state and federal tax forms filed by 215 charities failed to report their expenses correctly. Chances are, charity scofflaws are flying under the watchdog's radar. While the number of IRS-approved charitable organizations has exploded over the last decade, the IRS audit army hasn't. The number of audited nonprofits has dropped from 5 percent to 2.2 percent since then. <p>To make sure your donations aren't dropping into a black hole, we compiled a ranking of the ten most efficient charities in the country -- and the ten least -- out of over 300 nonprofits. The American Institute of Philanthropy (AIP), a St. Louis-based nonprofit group that analyzes charities, helped us come up with the list. To make our grade, a charity must have more than $1 million in annual income, be able to accept tax-deductible contributions, and receive less than half its funding from the federal government, since groups that receive federal grants don't have to compete for that money in the private sector and therefore will have lower overhead costs. Since many Americans give money rather than goods, we conducted an income-only analysis. That's why AmeriCares, a nonprofit that provides emergency aid to disaster victims, didn't make our top ten. After donated medical and food supplies are subtracted, the amount of revenues AmeriCares actually plows back into its cause drops to 78 percent for 1993.<p>The winner: The National Hispanic Scholarship Fund of Novato, California. It ranks first on our list because 95 percent of the money it spends goes toward its cause -- sending impoverished Hispanic students to college. It also spends a relatively small 2 percent on fund-raising. Number two: The Shriners Hospital for Crippled Children. About 94 percent of its expenses goes toward assisting disabled kids.<p>The least efficient nonprofit was the Walker Cancer Research Institute of Aberdeen, Maryland. It landed in last place because a staggering 95 percent of the $6.1 million it raises goes toward overhead and fundraising, while a measly 3 percent is sunk into drug research and education programs. "It's very competitive out there," says Steven Blumenthal, the institute's vice president. "Direct mail is a difficult way to raise money. So we only have very little left over after we pay our bills to spend on research and other program services." The eight-year-old "Just Say No" International in Oakland, California, which lists former first lady Nancy Reagan as honorary chairperson, also ranks in the bottom ten since fund-raising and other overhead costs chew up 78 percent of its budget. "We're still new and young," says spokesman Steven Delphin. "We meet all of the standards of the Better Business Bureaus."<p>Of course, many charities justifiably incur high administrative costs. For example, spending large sums on solicitations is typical when a charity is new or devoted to a controversial cause, as AIDS was in the early 1980s. And overhead costs can zoom when a nonprofit oversees complex, labor-intensive programs in far-flung corners of the world. Lee M. Cassidy, executive director of the National Federation of Nonprofits, a Washington, D.C., advocacy group, says, "If charities are alleviating pain and suffering, they work." <p>However, even AAFRC literature tells donors that they have a right to know how their dollars are being spent. "It's okay to question a charity now. It used to be wrong, like questioning God," says AIP president Daniel Borochoff, a former researcher at the National Charities Information Bureau. <p>Not anymore. When a charity's behavior is technically aboveboard, in some instances "little money ends up where donors think it's going to go," says James T. Bennett, co-author of Unhealthy Charities (Basic Books, $25). Economists Bennett and Thomas DiLorenzo analyzed the financial statements of three of the nation's largest health charities and found that much of their money either sits in a huge cash hoard or is used to build up an endowment. The authors say that even though it relentlessly fund-raises, the American Cancer Society has $361 million in cash and securities and more than $100 million in real estate and equipment. As of 1990, the Texas chapter of the ACS owned land and real estate valued at $11.2 million; its employees also got to use its 56 cars and trucks, which are worth over $800,000. <p>However, many charities are true to their cause and not their pockets. Here's how to give with confidence:<p>-> Do some homework. Never donate blindly to a telephone or mail appeal. Experts say such solicitations are rife with scams. Instead, to get a good look at a charity's operations, volunteer for a local organization or chat with its officials. Then ask for its Form 990 federal tax return, or call your state attorney general's office to get a charity's documents -- 43 states require nonprofits to submit these documents each year. <p>But be warned: Form 990s are about as easy to decipher as a quantum-physics textbook. Zero in on lines 22-25 and part 3, where the organizations break down their expenses. Compare these numbers to the following averages posted by the AAFRC: At least 80 percent of a charity's revenue should go toward its cause and no more than 20 percent toward general management costs. For a letter grading of over 300 charities, send $3 and a self-addressed envelope to the American Institute of Philanthropy, 4579 Laclede Avenue, Suite 136W, St. Louis, MO 63108.<p>-> Make sure your charitable contribution is a bulletproof tax deduction by donating only to those groups with IRS-approved tax-exempt status. Just 575,690 of the 1.1 million tax-exempt groups are IRS-approved charities. For a list of these groups, visit your local IRS office and ask to see publication No. 78, Cumulative List of Organizations. <p>-> Keep up with tax changes. New tax laws require receipts for cash donations of $250 or more made in 1994; a canceled check or credit card statement no longer counts as proof. If donations of used items -- clothes or furniture -- exceed $500, taxpayers should attach an itemized list noting dollar values and the charity's name and address. Typically, items should be valued at 15 percent to 20 percent of the original retail cost, says Claudia Hill, president of Tax Mam, a tax-consulting group in Cupertino, California.<p>-> Give appreciated property. Donors can reap two tax benefits by donating stock, bonds, art, or real estate that has appreciated in value. You avoid capital-gains tax on a sale of the appreciated items and you receive a charitable writeoff. Such deductions got a big boost from the 1993 Tax Act: Donors subject to the Alternative Minimum Tax can now claim the full, appreciated value of property donated after 1992. Previously, they could write off only the original purchase price. <p>Giving appreciated property works well in a charitable remainder trust, where tax-deductible donations of capital can throw off income for life. "You'll have more money working to provide income for you," says Warren M. Bergstein, a New York City CPA specializing in individual tax planning. Such trusts are expensive to establish and maintain, though, and may be practical only for six-figure donations. For smaller amounts, try charitable annuities or a pooled-income fund, which is basically an income-oriented mutual fund.<p>-> Be skeptical of charities that pitch their financial acumen as a way to increase investment returns. "Investing with a charity could give you a greater return on your money than investing yourself," says an ad from the United Jewish Appeal Federation of New York. Not quite. Outright gifts generate bigger writeoffs since the deductions for planned gifts are reduced by the interest income you receive. Furthermore, a charity's annuity or fund rates generally lag their counterparts by two percentage points. And once the investment is set up, it can't be cashed out.<p>
THE BEST AND WORST CHARITIES FOR YOUR MONEY<p>The Ten Most Efficient Charities<p>1. National Hispanic Scholarship Fund (415-892-9971)
2. Shriners Hospital for Crippled Children (800-237-5055)
3. America Red Cross (202-737-8300)
4. Child Welfare League of America (202-638-2952)
5. Parkinson's Disease Foundation (800-457-6676)
6. National Mental Health Association (800-433-5959)
7. The Fund for Peace (212-661-5900)
8. Mexican American Legal Defense & Educational Fund (213-629-2512)
9. The Nature Conservancy (703-841-5300)
10. Starr Commonwealth Schools (517-629-5591)<p>
The Ten Least Efficient Charities<p>1. Walker Cancer Research Institute (410-538-8976)
2. Pacific West Cancer Fund (206-575-8553)
3. National Emergency Medicine Association/National Heart Research (800-332-6362)
4. Children's Wish Foundation International (404-393-9474)
5. National Law Enforcement Officers Memorial Fund (202-737-3400)
6. Cancer Fund of America (615-938-5281)
7. "Just Say No" International (510-451-6666)
8. Help Hospitalized Veterans (619-291-5846)
9. Christian Relief Services (703-550-2472)
10. National Children's Cancer Society (800-622-0190)
---------------
Figures as of 1993
Source: American Institute of Philanthropy<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

