<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-The Billion Dollar Tax Break</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Billion Dollar Tax Break</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-The Billion Dollar Tax Break</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Feature<p>THE BILLION DOLLAR TAX BREAK
The wealthy can count on two things: Death and really good lawyers. The  inside story on how the Newhouse  family beat the IRS.<p>By Thomas Maier<p>"Please state your name for the record."<p>"Samuel I. Newhouse Jr."<p>"Sir, would you tell the court whether you are now employed?"<p>"I am."<p>"What is your present employment?"<p>"I'm chairman of Advance Publications, chairman of Conde Nast Publications, and I may have a number of other titles."<p>On a dreary January day in 1989, Si Newhouse, a slight and almost unassuming man, sat in a witness chair, raised his hand in U.S. Tax Court in Washington, D.C., and swore to tell the truth about the inner workings and financial structure of the largest privately held fortune in America. It was a rare public appearance for America's most powerful and secretive media baron. At issue was a nearly $1 billion unpaid tax bill levied on the estate of Newhouse's late father's estate in 1983. It was the largest case of its kind ever brought before the court, and the stakes for the Newhouses were enormous. Were Judge John J. Williams to rule against the family, there was some doubt whether the multibillion-dollar Newhouse empire -- the largest family-held fortune in the United States -- could remain intact.<p>Together with his brother Donald, Si Newhouse controlled more than $10 billion worth of media properties. Much of the empire had been inherited from their father, Sam, who died in 1979 and left his two sons with a diversified and immensely profitable company. Advance Publications then encompassed some 30 daily newspapers (including the only papers in New Orleans, Cleveland, and Portland, Oregon), as well as Parade, the national Sunday-paper supplement; television stations and cable systems across the nation; and the Conde Nast stable of glossy magazines.<p>Once in charge of the empire, the brothers spent the '80s relentlessly adding to it. Si bought Random House, the publishing conglomerate, for $70 million in 1980; in 1985, he paid nearly $200 million for The New Yorker; and in the course of the '80s he spent an estimated $75 million reviving Vanity Fair magazine. All this spending would have been difficult, if not impossible, were it not for Sam Newhouse's final achievement -- a brilliant estate-planning maneuver that confused the issues of ownership and control of the company. It was an elaborate plan, a perfectly executed gamble. If it worked, the Newhouse family fortune would be saved and solidified for generations to come. <p>As co-executors of their father's estate, the Newhouse brothers had arrived in court to defend their father's financial legacy a decade after his death. The case hinged on a dispute over the worth of Sam Newhouse's stock in Advance Publications. The valuation of stock in closely held private corporations is, of course, a timeless bone of contention between taxpayers and the IRS, because no market mechanisms exist to easily value such holdings. In this case, the IRS claimed that Sam Newhouse's stake in the family company was worth $1.2 billion when he died. The family, on the other hand, put Sam's worth at $178 million and in 1980 filed a return listing a net tax bill just shy of $48 million. The IRS claimed that the estate owned an additional $609 million in taxes and slapped the family with a $304 million penalty. As the case developed, signs emerged that perhaps the government had even underestimated the worth of Advance. Shortly before the trial began, magazine analyst James Kobak completed a report valuing Sam Newhouse's share of the company at more than $2 billion when he died in 1979.<p><p>The seeds of the Newhouse tax strategy were planted decades before Sam Newhouse's death. Worried that his heirs would have to sell off family assets in order to pay estate taxes, Newhouse had constantly revised Advance's company charter, creating an ownership structure that made it not only difficult to discern who controlled the company but also highly unattractive for family members to cash out of the company. He owned the company's common stock, and he granted his immediate family -- his two brothers, his wife, and Si and Donald -- preferred stock. A set of changes written into the charter in 1956 granted the company's preferred shareholders the right to voluntarily liquidate their holdings at any point. In reality, it was doubtful any of them would choose that option, because in 1949 the preferred stock had been fixed at a low price -- so low, in fact, that the family members were virtually locked in as long as Sam Newhouse controlled the company. Sam had learned from the bitter struggles over money that had torn apart the families of other newspaper tycoons; he was determined that his family not fall prey to internecine struggles.<p>The plan was also designed to keep the fortune intact after Sam died. Whoever laid claim to the common stock and its voting rights would still need the approval of the preferred stockholders to gain full control of Advance -- this made it conveniently possible to undervalue the common stock. After all, what was Sam's stock worth to a potential buyer if the other Newhouses, who could block a sale, didn't want to sell theirs? <p>The IRS viewed the charter changes as a ruse designed to make it appear -- at least for tax-estate purposes -- that the preferred shareholders were equal owners of the company, on the same plane as the common stockholder, Sam Newhouse. Thus, the IRS argument went, Si Newhouse and his brother could claim the value of Sam's estate holdings was much less than the total value of the company. <p>The Newhouse defense, on the other hand, hinged on proving that possession of the common stock did not grant Sam Newhouse exclusive control of the company he built from scratch. Under the gentle questioning of his defense lawyers, Si Newhouse was able to draw a picture of the family enterprise as a business run not by the father but by a group of equals. To many familiar with the inner workings of the company, this was like saying that Henry Ford didn't run the Ford Motor Co. <p>"Was there ever a time, Mr. Newhouse, when your father, S.I., dictated a decision to the rest of the group?" asked Albert Turkus, head of the Newhouse defense team.<p>"No, there was -- I never remember him dictating a business decision," Si Newhouse replied. "It was totally outside of his nature.... It never would have occurred to him to dictate a decision."<p>Anyone who was familiar with the family and its business may have also been taken aback by Newhouse's next contention. "Did there ever come a time, Mr. Newhouse, when you became aware of the fact that there were any differences in the nature of the different shareholders' interest?" Turkus asked.<p>"Yes."<p>"Would you describe that for the court, please?"<p>"Well, I can't pin it down to a period, but after a while, there started to be stories in Time and some of the other magazines, and we started to get written up. People began to notice us, and there were references in these articles to classes of stock, and that's when I first became aware of -- that it was -- that there were differences in the stock."<p>Newhouse explained that he began receiving checks in the 1950s and only after that became aware of the stock differences in the company. By this time, he was nearly 30 years old, was married with children, and had attended countless meetings where all aspects of the family business were presumably discussed. Yet, he testified, he had to learn who owned what in the family's multibillion-dollar business by reading it in a magazine.<p>The testimony went on with Newhouse continuing to give disarmingly opaque answers to Turkus's questions. He maintained that he'd spent his career up to this point working hard for the family business and giving very little thought to the ownership structure of Advance. "We didn't think about stock," Newhouse replied to one inquiry. "We never thought about the corporate legalities, the corporate aspects of it. We were involved together -- the family business -- so I can't tell you when I really thought about it all being equal. I've always felt we were equal. There was never any thought that there was an inequality about any of us in the family." <p>In their cross-examination, the government attorneys -- Robert Shilliday and co-counsel Howard Levine -- tried in vain to poke holes in Newhouse's testimony. Near the end of their cross-examination, the government attorneys grilled Newhouse about Advance's 1976 takeover of Booth Newspapers. Advance had paid $150 million for the company, which owned a string of Michigan dailies as well as Parade magazine. The prosecution was hoping to show that Sam Newhouse himself had controlled the deal. "You were involved in that acquisition?" asked Levine.<p>"I certainly was," Newhouse replied.<p>"All right," Levine said. He then asked Newhouse to describe the deal in detail. <p>"Well," Newhouse said wearily, "it's a little bit like trying to describe love ..."<p><p>Though the two sides did not meet in court until 1989, the IRS had been building its case for much of the decade. The driving force was Joseph Baniewicz, the IRS's media expert. In 1983, Baniewicz recommended that the IRS reject the tax forms filed in 1980 by Si Newhouse and his brother on their father's estate. After launching a massive audit of the Newhouse empire, Baniewicz had become convinced that Sam Newhouse's 1,000 shares of Advance common stock controlled the company. His valuation was based on a premise known as subtraction theory. Quite simply, he estimated Advance's total worth and subtracted from that sum the cost of all the stock not owned by Sam Newhouse at the time of his death. <p>As a result of this approach, Baniewicz figured that at the time of Sam Newhouse's death, the family-held preferred stock was worth about $267 million, and that the 1,000 shares of Class A common stock with voting rights left by Sam Newhouse were worth no less than $1.2 billion. Baniewicz was also convinced that the Newhouses deliberately set out to mislead the IRS by seriously undervaluing the worth of Sam Newhouse's shares in the company. In the halls of the IRS, Baniewicz's indignation prevailed, and on May 18, 1983, the service issued a notice of tax deficiency along with a $304 million fraud penalty. <p>But Baniewicz's theory had one fundamental miscalculation: It was impossible to believe that any buyer would pay the IRS's idea of fair market value for Advance common stock, given that the stock was all but worthless without the assent of the preferred stockholders. In other words, the IRS's subtraction theory subtracted one crucial variable -- the power of the preferred stockholders. <p>It fell to Robert Shilliday, an Atlanta-based tax specialist for the IRS, to handle these proceedings. Shilliday, who had full authority in the case, had originally hoped to avoid a trial. In 1986, as a sign of good faith, he even agreed to drop the $304 million penalty Baniewicz recommended. Aside from that, his case closely followed the arguments of the IRS analyst. In his opening statement to Judge Williams, Shilliday alluded to the Newhouses' alleged "trick" with their taxes and their financial "sleight of hand."<p>Whether or not his argument held any merit, Shilliday was outgunned and outmaneuvered by Newhouse's legal team at every turn. When Baniewicz took the stand, for instance, Turkus was quickly able to persuade Judge Williams that the IRS analyst was not qualified to assess the value of the Newhouse empire. "Mr. Baniewicz never sought advice from real-world buyers on how they would approach valuing the stock like this," Turkus argued. "I'm not suggesting to this court on behalf of [the Newhouses] that there's anything wrong with Mr. Baniewicz having an opinion.... [But] the fact that he engages in that exercise does not make him. . . an expert in the things which the government is asking him to testify about here today."<p>Judge Williams agreed to let Baniewicz's testimony stand only if Shilliday could promise that later witnesses would back up the IRS analyst's theories about the value of the common stock. Shilliday nodded, and said he would provide, with some caveats, such testimony from media consultants John Morton and James Kobak. <p>Costly errors plagued Shilliday's case. For instance, one witness Shilliday hoped to call, Richard Meeker, the author of a critical biography about Sam Newhouse, was identified in a pretrial memorandum as a former associate of Sam Newhouse's. This was important because Meeker was supposed to testify to Sam Newhouse's iron grip on the business. But the defense pointed out that Meeker was 50 years younger than Sam Newhouse and was hardly in a position to provide an eyewitness view. The government soon dropped Meeker as a witness, and Williams threatened to hold Shilliday in contempt. Shilliday didn't fare much better with John Morton, whose testimony was thrown out after Shilliday improperly asked him to make a legal judgment about the Newhouse tax case. The judge excoriated Shilliday. "Your lack of understanding in this case is exceeded only by your lack of preparation," he said, terming Shilliday's work the "worst performance I have seen on the bench."<p>Shilliday's courtroom misfortune was far from over. Another witness, William Worthington Jr., a former Chemical Bank official, had what Shilliday thought might be a smoking gun. In 1977 Worthington had drafted a memo that questioned the prevailing view within the bank that all classes of the Newhouse stock were identical. He pointed out that after the old man died, the estate could face a serious IRS challenge. To Shilliday, this memo indicated that there was doubt about the legality of the Newhouses' tax plan among their own bankers. But Worthington testified that he didn't believe that the Newhouses were trying to deceive the IRS. More important, his memo failed to take into account the company's 1956 charter amendments, which gave the other Newhouses who owned preferred shares the option of blocking a potential sale. When Shilliday tried to admit Worthington's memo into evidence, Turkus argued that it reflected only Worthington's individual view, not the opinion of the bank. Judge Williams agreed and excused Worthington as a witness. <p>By the time James Kobak took the stand, the case had come to seem like a grisly mismatch. Kobak was the analyst who had prepared a report saying that Advance Publications' common stock was worth more than $2 billion, but that report had been dismissed before Kobak took the stand. The problem was that Kobak had taken so long to complete his valuation that the government could not unveil his numbers until a scant two months before the trial was scheduled to begin. Turkus had successfully argued that the Kobak estimates came "on the eve of the trial," too late to affect the proceedings. <p>Even so, for a time it looked like Kobak would be the government's most effective witnesses. Until the defense was able to deflate his testimony under cross-examination, that is. Under Turkus's questioning, Kobak admitted that he had made a $39 million mistake in his valuation of Vogue, Conde Nast's prized fashion magazine, and the related Vogue Guides. When asked about another discrepancy, Kobak offered a less than satisfying response: "My ladies may have picked that up from a clipping. . . and wrote it wrong," he said abashedly.<p>While the prosecution could not even get testimony to stick from witnesses sympathetic to its arguments, the defense team was able to get solid testimony from some of Advance's toughest competition. Both Rupert Murdoch, who owned at that time both the HarperCollins publishing house and Mirabella, a key competitor of Vogue, and Douglas McCorkindale, the executive in charge of acquisitions for Gannett, America's largest newspaper chain, testified that the structure of Advance's ownership would made the company an unattractive takeover target. "Just looking at it overall, we are not interested in getting into situations that get messy and get involved in litigation," said McCorkindale. Murdoch testified that he wouldn't pay a nickel for the Newhouse common shares without some other agreement with other family members. <p><p>On February 28, 1990, nearly a year after the trial ended, Judge Williams issued a 100-page ruling that was nothing short of total victory for Si and Donald Newhouse and the generation of younger Newhouses who, in the form of complicated family trusts, stood as heirs to their grandfather's fortune. In short, Williams agreed with the Newhouse lawyers. He ruled that Advance Publications, the family's newspaper and magazine conglomerate, was worth about $1.5 billion at the time of Sam Newhouse's death, but that his 1,000 shares of common stock were worth only $176 million. As a result, the family owed $48 million in taxes, almost exactly the figure that the Newhouses had claimed a decade earlier. <p>Many observers viewed the decision as a virtual giveaway to the Newhouse family. As the economist Paul Samuelson later observed: "The [plan's] beauty, of course, is that the Newhouses can apparently have it both ways. For estate purposes the value of the company is artificially lowered. But should the family ever want to sell, it can easily recover the company's full market value by offering all the firm's securities as a package."<p>John J. Coffee, a Columbia University law professor and one of the government's expert witnesses, concluded that Sam Newhouse knew exactly what he was doing when he had his company's charter rewritten. "They were consciously thinking about this [strategy] all along," says Coffee. "There were about 11 changes in a 20-year period, with all these arcane changes and wordings. There's no ordinary company that goes through these type of changes in their structure."<p>In the end, the Newhouse tax case probably had a greater effect on journalism and publishing -- the tax savings helped Newhouse finance the acquisition of Random House and The New Yorker and the revival of Vanity Fair -- than it did on the annals of estate taxation. Though unusually large sums were involved, tax experts say that Judge Williams's ruling was not precedential; the case was simply too singular. "Most enterprises that big are not in family hands," says New York-based tax attorney Lee Sheppard. "You could almost say this case was sui generis." The moral of the story, Sheppard says, is that "when the IRS goes after people with unlimited resources, the IRS almost always gets outgunned." 
---------------
Adapted from "Newhouse: All the Glitter, Power and Glory of America's Richest Media Empire and the Secretive Man Behind It."  Copyright 1994 by St. Martin's Press.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Taxation, Estate Planning, Government Adgency

