	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Meet the IRS's New Computer</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Meet the IRS's New Computer</b></font><br>
				<font size=4>By Elizabeth MacDonald</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>MEET THE IRS'S NEW COMPUTER
Here's what's ahead for tardy taxpayers.<p>By Elizabeth MacDonald<p>If you're among the 13 million individuals who file or pay taxes late each year, a new IRS computer system is going to make things a little tougher for you. The IRS is placing high hopes on its penalty-abatement system, due out next year, which it believes will crack down on delinquent taxpayers who undeservingly get their failure-to-file or failure-to-pay penalties abated. <p>If you owe the IRS and you don't file your return or pay up by April 15, the IRS will slap you with both a late-filing and a failure-to-pay penalty, equal to a combined 5 percent of the unpaid tax, up to a 25 percent maximum, (if you get a four-month extension, you'll still owe a failure to pay penalty if you don't send in at least 90 percent of what you owe). Tardy taxpayers can then try to use a "reasonable cause" -- such as saying that they lost their records -- to get their penalty abated. <p>For the past three years, the General Accounting Office has been after the IRS to reduce the amount of money it loses in penalty abatements as well as to make the system fairer. Since 1991, the agency has forgiven roughly $9.3 billion in penalties and fines after taxpayers wrote back with their reasonable causes. Over that period, taxpayers who filed or paid late were responsible for about $1 billion of that amount. The GAO has told the agency "that we're inconsistent, that we were too subjective" in excusing the fines, according to IRS spokeswoman Johnelle Hunter. <p>To fix this problem, the IRS has been testing this new system since 1991 on taxpayers in Dallas and Los Angeles. Early tests show that the system rejects many more abatement requests. In a recent test at the IRS service center in Fresno, California, the agency assessed 21,398 failure-to-file and/or failure-to-pay penalties, amounting to $880,114, against Los Angeles taxpayers. Along with these penalty notices, the agency also sent a new IRS form, number 9264, "Request for Removal of Tax Penalty -- 1040 Filers." Recipients were asked to check off on this form one or more boxes next to 11 categories of reasonable causes for their delinquency. These include, for example, a death in the family or a fire. The IRS computer then assigned weights to each checked excuse, scored the request form, and directed the IRS examiner to either abate the penalty or let it stand. Some reasonable causes carry more credibility with the agency than others. Says IRS spokesman Henry Holmes, "Illness or death may swing more weight than one of these other reasons, like absence [being out of town and unable to file]."<p>Results show that the IRS abated 2 percent of these taxpayers' penalties and wiped clean $243,009, or 28 percent of the total fines. Since 1991, by contrast, the agency on average abated 8 percent of the failure-to-file and failure-to-pay penalties it assessed and excused 16.5 percent of the amount taxpayers owed.<p>Tax experts say that any laxity in the new system won't last. "The IRS can easily change and most likely will change its scoring system to make it tougher on taxpayers," says Leon Berk, tax partner with N&L Partnership in Royal Palm Beach, Florida. <p>What should you do if the computer takes an interest in you? First, don't automatically pay up. "When someone gets a notice, they just pay without thinking," says Nancy Gallagher, a New York public accountant. "It's a great way for the government to raise money." Second, since the IRS provides for other ways to get a penalty abated, avoid form 9264. Here's how to make your strongest case to the IRS:<p>Let's say you filed and paid your taxes late because your home was burned in a fire and your records were destroyed.You get an IRS notice saying you owe penalties. File form 843, "Claim for Refund and Request for Abatement." On the top of the form type "Demand for Abatement of Penalties." Go to line 11, write in "See attached," and on a separate piece of paper, give your explanation. In this case, you'd have to enclose fire-department and insurance reports showing the extent of the damage. You'd explain that the delay was caused by the difficulty in getting copies of W-2s and other tax documents necessary for accurate preparation of your return. As the Internal Revenue Manual states, damage to tax records is a reasonable cause. Therefore, you can request that your penalty plus interest should be abated.<p>Next, send your abatement request to the IRS employee named on your notice, attaching a copy of your IRS bill plus any documents substantiating your claim. Also, type your IRS 14-digit document-locator number, found on your notice, on the top of this form. This points the IRS directly to your file, thereby avoiding additional interest costs caused by IRS delays. <p>If you can't file on time next April 15, get a four-month extension by mailing form 4868 to the IRS. If you owe money, you'll avoid a failure-to-pay penalty by estimating your tax and sending a check for at least 90 percent of the amount owed along with that form. If you can't pay that amount, send in form 9465 to get an installment plan -- you'll still owe a failure-to-pay penalty and 8 percent interest. When you finally do file and pay up, attach 4571, "Explanation for Filing Return Late or Paying Tax Late," to the top of your return, and cite your reasonable causes to get your penalties excused. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government Adgency, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
