<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Give Later, Get a Tax Break Now</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Give Later, Get a Tax Break Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Strategies for the philanthropist in you.<p>By Troy Segal<p>Charities, foundations, and colleges, caught up in the hard sell that philanthropy has become, are pitching a new breed of trust and annuity. In effect, these devices allow benefactors to designate donations they plan to make in the future. In return, the benefactor gets an upfront tax deduction as well as ongoing income from the assets they pledge.<p>Are these trusts and annuities mere gimmickry, or are they really a good deal? Think hard before you answer. If charity is your principal motivation, you might do better giving cash or appreciated securities that will immediately benefit the recipient. If tax avoidance is your principal motivation, gifts made in the here and now also usually provide the biggest and most immediate benefits.<p>Still, many would-be philanthropists prefer the new tools, not least because of the higher tax rates that arrived with the Clinton administration. Furthermore, some people like the idea of demonstrating their commitment to a favored institution but still need the investment income that an immediate gift of assets would deny them.<p>Enter the charitable remainder trust. These irrevocable trusts, used primarily for large donations, earmark funds for an institution but continue to pay the donor and his or her spouse a yearly income for life. When the donors die, the funds in the trust are transferred to the institutional beneficiary.<p>There are two basic types of charitable remainder trust: the annuity trust, which distributes a fixed dollar amount to the donor each year, and the unitrust, which distributes a fixed percentage of the trust's assets. The payouts to the donor are generally taxable for both types of trust.<p>The tax break for both types comes from the deduction that is created when the trust is established. The amount of this deduction is calculated by using Internal Revenue Service tables to figure what the gift will be worth when it is actually transferred to the institutional recipient.<p>Of the two types of trust, the annuity version provides the larger upfront deduction. This is because fixed dollar payouts shrink the trust principal less over time than the unitrust's percentage-of-assets payouts. For instance, suppose a 60-year-old donor wants to establish a $100,000 charitable remainder trust. According to PhilanthroTec, a Matthews, North Carolina, software publisher, a donor who sets this trust up as an annuity paying a fixed $6,000 a year would be entitled to value his gift, for purposes of the tax deduction, at $40,314. If the donor chooses a unitrust paying 6 percent of total assets each year, his gift would be valued at only $36,163. <p>One caveat: The annuity-trust beneficiary cited above must understand that he will never receive more than $6,000 a year from his trust. The unitrust beneficiary, on the other hand, receives 6 percent of the trust's assets each year no matter how much they increase. Thus, of the two, the unitrust offers the best protection against inflation.<p>The costs of creating and administering charitable remainder trusts usually make them impractical for smaller contributions. As an alternative, donors might consider a charitable-gift annuity. For these, the donor grants immediate possession of the gift to the institutional beneficiary, rather than placing it in a trust. New York's Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts, for instance, offers an annuity with guaranteed annual payments for life starting at age 55 for donations of $10,000 or more.<p>In setting annuity payments for these types of gifts, most charities, including Lincoln Center, use a schedule adopted by the American Council on Gift Annuities, which represents 1,400 organizations. The schedule is calculated to help the organization ultimately keep at least half of the original annuity investment. Thus the payout rates aren't the most generous, ranging from 4.7 percent to 11 percent a year, depending on the donor's age. "I won't pretend this is a great investment," says David Clough, director of planned giving at Lincoln Center. <p>Often, a portion of an annuity payout is tax free as return of principal. The donor also gets an upfront tax deduction for his gift; how much depends on his age and the number of years for which payment is deferred. Younger donors -- in their 30s and 40s -- beware. "You shouldn't tie yourself up in that sort of fixed-income investment," says William H. Mears, senior vice president at Brown Brothers Harriman Trust in New York City.<p>Inflation hedgers may prefer a charity's pooled-income fund to a charitable annuity. A $5,000 investment -- most institutions won't take less -- goes into a sort of mutual fund that distributes interest earned until the donor's death. Pooled-income funds generally invest in Treasurys or high-grade corporate debt; some are venturing into equities. Payouts from pooled-income funds are fully taxable. The charitable tax deduction available to the contributors depends on their age and the fund's highest yield over the prior three years.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

