<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Let Your Family Protect Assets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Let Your Family Protect Assets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
How family limited partnerships can minimize estate taxes.<p>By Donald Jay Korn<p>Estate-tax avoidance usually involves giving assets away. What you don't own can't be included in your taxable estate. However, handing over your holdings has a hitch: Your securities, bank accounts, and properties belong to someone else. <p>Enter the family limited partnership. As a general partner in such a partnership, you can give away assets for tax purposes yet keep control of them. "Family limited partnerships are powerful vehicles for diffusing asset ownership," says Alan C. Klein, a partner in the accounting firm Arthur Andersen. <p>Klein says FLPs can work for business owners, professionals, real estate investors, and other people with substantial, diverse wealth. Besides estate-tax relief, they offer income-shifting to lower brackets and asset protection (increasingly valuable in this land of happy litigators).<p>When you and your spouse establish your partnership, you'll name yourselves as general partners, perhaps with a 1 percent interest in the FLP. You'll also be the sole limited partners, owning the other 99 percent. <p>Then, transfer virtually any asset, except pension plans or shares in S corporations, to the FLP. "I wouldn't transfer a principal residence, either," says Alan Jahde, a director in the Denver law firm Boris, Nemkov & Jahde, "because you'll lose tax advantages." The transfer is not a taxable event, because you're just shifting wealth.<p>Next, give away limited-partnership interests to family members, usually children but perhaps grandchildren, parents, or others. This can be done all at once or over a period of years. As long as you're the general partner, you make all the decisions regarding the assets in the FLP. You even can pay yourself a salary for managing the FLP. "If the assets in the partnership generate taxable income, that income is passed through to the partners," says Jahde. So most of the income could be diverted to your children, who might be in a 15 percent federal tax bracket while you might be in a 39.6 percent bracket. <p>As is typical with limited partnerships, general partners in an FLP make all management decisions and bear all the liability. Limited partners, however, have limited liability. <p>Once you shift assets into an FLP, they're out of easy reach of creditors or litigators. In case of a judgment against you, your assets will be stowed in the FLP, largely owned by your relatives, who may not be parties to the action. <p>FLPs do cost money. "Expect to pay around $3,000 for the upfront legal drafting plus up to $1,000 per year for administration, including tax-return preparation," says Klein. The cost is worth it if you're saving hundreds of thousands in taxes and protecting sizable assets but impractical if your assets are modest. <p>Then there are taxes. When partnership interests are transferred to other family members, taxes are incurred. You will pay no tax, however, if you give away up to $10,000 worth of assets each year - $20,000 if you're a married couple - to any number of recipients. Thus, if you have four children, you and your spouse could give them a total of $80,000 worth of limited partnership interests per year and owe no gift taxes.<p>You should also consider giving away up to $600,000 apiece during your lifetime, essentially using up your estate-tax exemption while you're still alive. A 1993 IRS ruling also makes it easier to transfer more than $10,000 per person to an FLP in any given year. That's because an asset held by a limited partner is worth less than its face value since it is controlled by another person - the general partner. Suppose, for example, you and your spouse place a $1 million property into an FLP. You might think that you could transfer only 2 percent a year, or $20,000, to each child, tax-free. However, the children who receive the limited-partnership interests won't control the property, and they can't sell their interest without the general partner's consent, so a 2 percent share isn't really worth $20,000. <p>Instead, you might give each child a 3 percent share each year and claim a 33 percent discount, bringing the value of your gift from $30,000 down to $20,000. Using the same reasoning, you might give away $900,000 worth of assets and use a minority discount to value that gift at the $600,000 exemption level. Get an outside valuation to establish the size of the discount.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Business, Family Finance, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
