<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-How a Tax Tactic Can Backfire</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-How a Tax Tactic Can Backfire</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Giving kids money now may boost tuition bills later.<p>By Donald Jay Korn<p>Shifting assets and income to children in the form of gifts has long been a trusted method of reducing income taxes. But an ominous cloud is forming around this tax tactic: Giving money to your children - even just $1,000 a year - can diminish your chances of getting financial aid to help defray onerous college bills. <p>Welcome to the world of EFC, which stands for expected family contribution, a key part of the financial-aid process that college applicants must go through. This game has become highly formalized; all standard financial-aid forms, once they are filled out by a parent, result in an EFC. <p>Colleges use the EFC to calculate the split between what a parent must contribute to a child's college education and how much aid the college will kick in. For instance, parents earning the minimum income - roughly $20,000 - will be expected to put 5.6 percent of their assets toward their child's education. But here's the bad news: If a child has assets of his or her own, he or she will be expected to kick in 35 percent of them for college bills. <p>That means parents with an income of $20,000, holding a $20,000 CD, would be expected to contribute about $1,120 for college. If their college-bound daughter owns the CD, the expected family contribution rises to $7,000. That's a big difference.<p>"Some parents are caught between a rock and a hard place," says F. Bill Billimoria, an accountant and financial planner at Billimoria Financial in Arlington Heights, Illinois. "The more they try to reduce income taxes by shifting assets, the lower the amount of financial aid they'll receive." <p>The rules are harshest on families with annual incomes between $50,000 and 150,000. Families with incomes of $200,000 or more, on the other hand, are too affluent to expect any financial aid for their child. For them, gifting assets to children remains a smart tax tactic. With children 14 years of age or older, shifting can mean big income-tax savings. For example, in 1994, investment income produced in a child's account is taxed at the child's lower rate: no more than 15 percent on taxable income up to $22,750. For children under 14, shifting assets produces no income-tax savings; their investment income will be taxed at their parents' marginal (or top) rate after the first $1,200. In both cases, however, shifting assets can be a good way to reduce a family's estate taxes. <p>How can you figure what your family's contribution to college is likely to be? Here's a rough rule of thumb: With income of $100,000 and a net worth of $100,000 (including retirement and 401(k) plan contributions), your expected financial contribution will be $25,000. Above that level, your assets are assessed at 5.6 percent and your income at 4.7 percent. At that level or above, with only one child attending college, you won't qualify for help at even the most expensive schools.<p>With two children in college, however, your prospects for aid brighten. Your parental share on behalf of each child is only half the total EFC; with three children, one third; and proportionately for four or more. So with several children in college at the same time, even families with income and net assets above $150,000 could qualify for substantial aid.<p>If you qualify, the lower your EFC, the greater the amount of aid that you or your children are likely to get in the form of grants, loans, or student work payments. Keep assets in your name, and if minimizing taxes is your goal, invest in municipal bonds, low-yielding growth stocks, or shares in mutual funds that rarely make taxable distributions.<p>Within the limits of prudence and honesty, you can make some of your assessable assets disappear. The standard form for federal aid that many colleges require excludes such assets as home equity. Prepaying your mortgage thus turns cash into a non-assessable asset. Another way you can reduce the EFC's bite is to pay attention to timing. The tax year during which your high schooler's junior year ends produces the income that appears on your first aid application. So take legitimate steps to reduce your income that year, such as deferring capital gains or compensation, for example. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
