<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-A Checklist for Reluctant Filers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-A Checklist for Reluctant Filers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
One last chance to save yourself money and trouble<p>By Stuart Weiss<p>You still haven't done your taxes? Understandable. Time and again you've been told that the Clinton tax package is going to whack you, and maybe it will. But you certainly can't put it off any longer. Here's one simple bit of advice: If you don't know your tax liability at April 15th and have to extend the return, pay 110 percent of your 1992 tax liability to avoid penalties. <p>Now, can you, in fact, expect a bigger tax bill? If your taxable income is over $115,000 for singles or $140,000 for married couples filing jointly, you can. At those figures the 36 percent marginal rate takes effect. There's a good probability you'll take that hit with gross income above $155,000 if single and $180,000 if married. (Typical taxpayers with those incomes will take deductions and exemptions totaling $40,000.) The top marginal rate, 39.6 percent, applies to taxable income over $250,000, single or married. Typically, gross income over $300,000 will leave you in the $250,000-plus taxable bracket after deductions and exemptions.<p>If you're single and in the higher brackets, your accountant can't do much for you legally, except perhaps to congratulate you for earning so much money and bill you accordingly. Some married people, however, may pay less tax by filing separate returns than a joint return. This can happen if one spouse has substantially more itemized deductions, such as medical expenses, than the other spouse. In fact, more couples this year than in the past are expected to benefit from that option. <p>Here are some other noteworthy wrinkles and quirks for taxpayers to consider:<p>-- Meals and entertainment. For 1993, 80 percent of these expenses are deductible. Starting in 1994, the deduction is 50 percent. <p>-- Club dues. These are no longer deductible in 1994. But taxpayers who prepaid this year's dues in 1993, hoping to take a 1993 deduction, may be inviting an audit. "To claim any type of deduction for a club, you have to know what your business usage is," says James Vonachen, a tax partner at Clifton, Gunderson & Co. accountants in Denver. "If you prepay it, how do you know what your business usage in going to be in 1994?"<p>-- Disaster. Although the Southern California earthquake occurred in 1994, the casualty losses it caused can be deducted on 1993 or 1994 tax returns. This rule only applies to designated federal disaster areas.<p>-- SEP, Keogh, and 401(k) plans. Make the maximum contribution and make it as early as possible to get the maximum benefit from tax deferral. Remember, if you haven't filed yet, you can still contribute to a plan before April 15. Most taxpayers are no longer eligible for deductible IRA contributions, but they still benefit from tax deferral on the investment earnings of their contributions.<p>-- Erroneous W-2 forms. Double-check your W-2s, and make sure your employer didn't mistakenly lump your 401(k) contribution or employee reimbursements into your gross income. Tell your employer to file a corrected W-2C with the IRS.<p>-- Social Security numbers. Double-check all your accounts. If your number appears on your children's securities or bank accounts, the IRS will wonder why you didn't report the income from those accounts. The children should have Social Security numbers even if you pay their taxes.<p>-- Mortgage payments. You may have paid more interest than your lender reports on your Form 1098 information return. That can happen when a late-in-the-year payment doesn't reach the bank in time. In calculating your deduction, use your figures, if they're accurate, and not the lender's. Note the discrepancy on your return.<p>-- Business. Bunch expenses toward businesses or investments and away from itemized deductions, which are limited. For example, if you have rental property, allocate most of your tax-preparation fee to offset rental income. Same thing if you have a consulting business on the side: Subscriptions to the Wall Street Journal, professional dues, and so on should be listed on your Schedule C for self-employed business.<p>-- Audit flags. The test to get the home-office deduction got tougher in 1993. You used to have to prove that the space in your home is used exclusively for business. Now you have to also show that you spend most of your time there. That wipes out many side businesses and most consultants who visit clients all day.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Family Finance, Retirement

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
