<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-The Last, Best Tax Shelter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-The Last, Best Tax Shelter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Real estate partnerships can still relieve tax pain<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>Where can an investor get an after-tax return of 8 percent every year for ten years, even if the investment never earns a dime? How about low-income housing partnerships?<p>Yes, partnershipsare back. And yes, it does sound too good to be true. But with income-tax rates exploding again, high-bracket tax-payers at least owe themselves a look at what may be the last, best tax shelter.<p>In 1986, Congress ripped the roof off most tax shelters. Gone are the windmill farms, the repositories for frozen bull semen, the dry holes masquerading as oil wells, the real estate deals cobbled together from pie-in-the-sky assumptions and kindergarten economics. But few people realized at the time that Congress also created new tax credits for investing in low-income housing, offering investors one of the best tax shelters ever Cliff Carper, senior vice president of Kemper Securities, calls the credits "one of the few giftsever given to taxpayers by the federal government." <p>To encourage the construction of apartments for the working poor, Congress offered real estate developers both a write-off and a tax credit based on the cost of constructing, renovating, or even purchasing such buildings. Unlike shelters of old, which merely reduced taxable income, a tax credit directly offsets taxes owed. The difference is dramatic. For example, an ordinary $10,000 deduction at the 36 percent rate would save $3,600 in taxes. But a $10,000 credit is simply subtracted from the taxes owed, saving the entire $10,000. For someone in the 36 percent bracket, that $10,000 credit is equal to a deduction of $27,800. <p>At first, few investors took advantage of the tax credits, either because they didn't know about them or they are well-maintained, suburban, garden-style complexes. But even Congress seemed uncertain about whether to keep the credits or not. The program nearly lost its funding twice and finally did lose its support for 14 months in 1992 and 1993<p>Under the law, the federal tax credits each state receives are awarded to local developers who team up with investors, usually organized in limited partnerships. The partnerships buy apartments, and the investors can use the credits against their taxes after the units are rented to low-income people.<p>Individual taxpayers are allowed to buy enough credits to shelter up to $25,000 of income each yearwhich works out to be $7,000 in credits for those in the 28 percent bracket, $7,750 at the 31 percent rate, $9,000 for 36 percent, and $9,900 for 39.6 percent. Although the tax credits won't raise or trigger the alternative minimum tax, they cannot be used to reduce a taxpayer's AMT if he or she is subject to it. Corporations or trusts can also use the credits, often in larger amounts.<p>Low-income-housing deals are typically structured to give investors a tax credit of about 15 percent of their total investment (including commissions, fees, etc.) each year for ten years. This makes for a total tax credit of 150 percent. That means a $66,000 investment would save $9,900 in taxes each year, saving a total of $99,000 over a decade.<p>Some smaller partnerships, known as private placements because they are not registered with the Securities and Exchange Commission, deliver up to 180 percent in credits over ten years thanks to lower underwriting and sales expenses. Conversely, some large public programs with high expenses deliver as little as 120 percent in credits. <p>It's a good thing the credits are high, because in a low-income housing partnership, there is little or no cash flow and and in most cases little chance for real estate appreciation. Apartment buildings typically appreciate in value as rents rise, but in low-income properties rents climb slowly, if at all. Says Brad Davidson of Partnership Valuations, an appraisal firm in Annapolis, Maryland, "Some places may have no residual value at all."<p>Are tax credits alone enough to justify the investment in such a partnership? Only in the good programs. Although the low-income-housing industry is much better regulated today than it was back in '86, there is still a wide range in quality of the deals. If the apartments are completely worthless at the end of 15 years--the first year they can be sold by law--the rate of return on a 120 percent credit is a paltry 3.5 percent. Although that's an after-tax return, it's not as good as a tax-free bond. But a partnership promising 150 percent worth of tax credits returns 8 percent after tax. And one of the 180 percent private placements would return 12.4 percent. <p>Of course, experienced investors know these kinds of returns don't come without risks. If the proper mix of residents isn't maintained (at least 20 percent low income), the IRS will require anyone who took tax credits from that investment to pay back a prorated portion of the money they saved. <p>With increased state and local supervision, such givebacks aren't as big a danger as in the past. Still, investors should select tax-credit programs on the basis of the sponsor's track record in complying with government regulations. Richard DeAgazio, executive vice president of Boston Capital Partners, a sponsor of tax-credit programs, advises investors to "avoid anyone who has not been in the affordable housing business for at least five years with no foreclosures." Easier said than done, says Thomas Gau, a financial planner in Torrance, California. "Since the tax credits were made permanent, at least 30 limited partnerships have come to market from people with no experience in low-income housing," he says.<p>A track record of delivering what's been promised is important because a diversified program may contain 20 or more apartment complexes. To build or renovate them all can take time: About three years is typical on large projects. During that time, investors will get few or no tax credits, so watch for sponsors who have a history of taking too long to build.<p>Perhaps most important, with competition for credits heating up, the percentage of each investment dollar coming back to investors as tax credits is likely to drop. "The private placements that are now at 180 percent will likely fall to 160 percent, and some public programs could go down to as low as 100 percent," predicts John MacLachlan, president of Community Housing Funds, a private placement sponsor in Marble Falls, Texas. To avoid unpleasant surprises, investors should restrict themselves to partnerships that specify at least the majority of the properties they will buy so the amount of credit is known in advance.
As always, investors need to be wary of programs that promise too much: A partnership that assumes some value in the properties at the end of 15 years can project rates of return of 15 percent a year or more. Those projections may be right. But ask to see the investment return from the tax credits alone, just in case.<p>Margaret Opsata has been covering real estate issues for 20 years.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Taxation, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

