	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Cover: Number One</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Cover: Number One</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						In His Newest Field<p>
By Monica Corcoran<p>
Ted Turner's got an insatiable appetite. Between bites of a lunch of cold poached salmon, which he spears aggressively with his fork, he talks about something else he has a taste for: Land. His land. All 1.3 million acres of it -- enough, in other words, to make him America's largest individual landowner.<p>
Although Turner never inherited much land, he came by a sizable advertising company when his father died in 1963. Hardly sated, he trailblazed a career in the cable industry and built Turner Broadcasting Systems, a media conglomerate he recently sold to Time Warner for $7.5 billion. His wealth enables him to pull up any for sale signs in his path.<p>
Turner began chewing up the scenery in 1978. That year, at 39 years of age, he paid $2 million for the 5,000-acre Hope Plantation in South Carolina. Since then, he's spent $150 million -- a mere 7.5 percent of his net worth -- on land, land, and more land. He now owns eight ranches, three plantations, and an island. (He doesn't count his New York "property" -- his stake in Time Warner -- but he can't help mentioning it as a semi-holding.)<p>
Not surprisingly, Turner had a lot to say about land when we met up with him in Los Angeles before a cable-industry awards ceremony. Long after finishing his lunch, Turner was still talking.<p>
ON LAND AS THE SPICE OF LIFE: "Back when I was single, I had a lot of different girlfriends, and I went to the same place every weekend. But now that I'm happily married, I take the same wife to different places every weekend. So there's a li'l variety."<p>
ON WHAT HE PAYS FOR LAND: "The least expensive land I bought was desert for $30 an acre. The most I ever paid for anything was about $1,000 an acre."<p>
ON LAND AS AN INVESTMENT: "I could make a fortune developing my land, but I've chosen not to. Land only gives you a good return when you start subdividing it or building on it and charging rent. Or if you sell it. I won't do any of that. I didn't buy the land as an investment. I bought it because I liked it."<p>
ON HOW TO PROFIT FROM LAND: "Go west. You can get a lot of acres for cheap. Stay out of New England because there's already too many people there."<p>
ON LAND AS A FAMILY LEGACY: "My father, even as a little boy, never forgot that his father lost his farm during the depression, and he bought a couple thousand acres in South Carolina."<p>
"I'm going to leave my land to my children in a trust. When the last one passes away, it's going to revert to my foundation. There will be money left to take care of the land and to protect it."<p>
ON LAND AS PERMANENCE: "When I was a kid, Gone With the Wind was my favorite movie. I always remembered that Scarlett's father said, 'The land is the only thing that lasts.' I figured if I had a place like Tara, it would be the only thing that lasted."<p>
ON LAND AS IMPERMANENCE: "The Indians thought that they owned the land. We think that we own the land....The land will be up for grabs again."<p>
ON LAND AS FOOTWEAR: "Years ago, I was really worried about a world war. I figured if everyone was starving and going around barefoot I could kill an alligator or two and have alligator shoes. I've got all my needs met on my land."<p>
ON GETTING (MORE) LAND: "Everybody I know is a land scout. Hardly a week goes by that I don't get mail from real-estate people. I once bought land just from looking at a picture. But I don't do that anymore. I have people who go and look at it. I'm too busy for that."<p>
ON BUYING LAND: "Well, I'm trying to fill in. You ever make puzzles when you were a kid? First, you put the corners in. Then you try to get the border done. And then you try to fill it in. So I've got property on both coasts and in Montana, which is a Canadian border, and in New Mexico, which is a Mexican border. Now I'm trying to fill in."<p>
KEYWORDS:
people, wealth, property
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
