	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-From the Editor: First Things First </b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Koten<p>
It's hard for me to look at that photograph on the cover and not want to dump everything I own in Manhattan and move. Every time I fly from the East Coast to the West (which I do a lot), I look down on the vastness of the American landscape and fantasize about owning a piece of it -- not just a suburban acre or a city lot, but something with a vista. <p>
Although I haven't progressed beyond dreaming about land, a lot of other people are way ahead of me. They're out there buying a mountain meadow in Montana or a bit of woods in upstate New York. It's easy to question the wisdom of this; with the stock market roaring ever upward, buying land certainly seems a contrarian move. Then again, contrarians are often the ones who get in early on the next big thing.<p>
We decided it was time to look at land from a number of different perspectives. First, we asked contributing editor Clint Willis to look for raw land selling for $150,000 or less. He came up with a bunch of investment schemes to make money -- with properties from Maine to Oregon.<p>
William P. Barrett took on the task of finding the largest private landowners. We considered any form of ownership -- individual, corporate, partnership, or trust -- as long as the beneficial interest of the stake rested ultimately with an individual or a family. To find these people, many of whom shun publicity, Bill picked through records and culled tips from appraisers, assessors, and other land experts. Then he called the landowners. His list of 100 is, we think, the only one of its kind.<p>
Finally, Richard Todd -- the writer we so often turn to when we want to give our readers something special -- reflects on his 150 acres in rural Massachusetts.<p>
This month, we also welcome Scott Burns as a regular columnist in our "Investing" section. Scott, who has long written about money issues for the Dallas Morning News, has always impressed us with the quality of his insights and the clarity of his prose.<p>
As always, you can write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. My E-mail address: <A HREF="mailto:john_koten@worth.com.">john_koten@worth.com.</A><p>
KEYWORDS:
property, land, invest, forward thinking
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
