<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-At Present Time</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-At Present Time</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Holiday Gifts<p>
By Ted C. Fishman<p>
Information technologies have transformed industries, revolutionized the workplace -- and reduced the agony of gift giving. With new products proliferating as fast as ideas, there's a good chance the person who has everything doesn't yet have the latest gizmo that just appeared yesterday. So we took stock of this moment in the digital age and came up with some gifts that are both fun and productive -- they boost brain power, help their recipients connect with others, or enable folks to enjoy their time alone.<p>
Perfect for the person on your gift list who makes lists, the Timex Data Link 150 Watch ($120) stores up to 150 names, addresses, dates, and other pieces of information. Load your facts into a computer using the software that comes with the watch, hold the watch up to the computer screen, and let a few flashing lights transfer the data. Among other uses, this storage capability makes the Data Link 150 a great navigator: Enter directions, then check them later en route. <p>
The Swatch Access ($50) also helps its wearers get from one point to another with greater ease -- in this case, onto the ski lift. The watch features a computer chip that can be read -- through clothing -- by lift-ticket scanners. The Access isn't accepted everywhere yet, but it works at several ski resorts in Europe and the western United States. Swatch has another watch, The Beep ($99), that incorporates a numeric beeper into four standard-sized nondigital styles. The watch stores up to 20 messages.<p>
If you want to give the gift of keeping in touch, the world's smallest cellular phone, Motorola's StarTAC ($1,000 and up), can make you forget about pagers. A mere 3.1 ounces, it fits nicely in a shirt pocket or small purse, yet it has most of the features cell-phone users crave, including a silent mode in which the phone vibrates instead of rings, long battery life, and a "smart button" that makes it easy to operate with one hand. For those who prefer no hands, the StarTAC also has a jack for a headset, a good way to talk while driving.<p>
While it may not look that exciting once the gift wrap is off, the SupraExpress 336 Sp with ASVD modem ($129) is another great-sounding way to maintain contact. It sports a speakerphone with caller identification and such functions as an answering machine. New technology allows the modem to split a single telephone line into two, so you can talk to the person your PC is linked to -- a handy way for two people far apart to work on a single document simultaneously (or to battle each other in multiplayer games like Doom and Quake).<p>
Modems aren't the only way to get the good stuff into a computer, of course. The CD-ROM version of the Encyclopaedia Britannica ($299), the world's most comprehensive reference work, is easy to navigate and fun to explore. The "natural language" search engine makes finding information a snap. And what the Britannica doesn't explain is likely to be found in Softkey's Multipedia ($59.95). This indispensable collection of 16 reference titles includes four bilingual dictionaries for English speakers, a home medical reference, the Oxford dictionaries of art and music, and -- this is our favorite -- Barron's Dictionary of Finance and Investment Terms.<p>
For mutual-fund information, consider Morningstar's Ascent 2.0 ($45), the new version of Morningstar's  fund-analysis software. It's easy to use, yet exhaustive, with a database of 7,600 mutual funds and 70 fields of data on each; of course, it also includes Morningstar's star ratings for each fund. <p>
Frothier ratings can be sampled in Michael Jackson's World Beer Hunter ($35) from Discovery Multimedia, created by the world's leading authority on all things beery. This is essentially an international pub crawl: You just select a country, and Jackson suggests where to find the best stool and pint. He can settle such questions as the difference between German pilsner and India pale ale, too.<p>
If that special someone has special handwriting, give WriteType ($299.95), software that enables users to print documents in their own handwriting. After the writer fills out and returns a form, Signature Software sends a font that looks like his or her handwriting -- so much so that even the shapes of letters change according to where they fall in a word.<p>
A fun gift for someone who wants to stay out of touch is the CyberFlix CD-ROM game Titanic: Adventure out of Time ($49.95). Titanic re-enacts the 1912 maiden voyage of the doomed ship, with players in the roles of several passengers caught in an espionage caper. The ship has been re-created with stunning authenticity; first-class air travel will seem downright shabby next to the luxuries once available to well-heeled ocean-goers.<p>
If you can get your pictures into a computer -- via a scanner or a digital camera, or by having a film lab "develop" the snapshots onto a disk -- Family Album Creator ($49.95) from Creative Wonders will ensure that they do not turn that computer into a digital shoe box. The program also organizes pictures into various album-like formats and allows users to attach notes, sound clips, and short video segments to the album pages. These arrangements can then be easily shared among family and friends by merely trading disks.<p>
The best television may, in fact, be a computer -- if you give someone the newest generation of video boards. Used together, the 3-D Pro Turbo PC2TV ($299) and the ATI-TV ($129), both from ATI Technologies, put television shows on a PC monitor -- over the full screen, in a small box in the corner, or in the background as "wallpaper" while another application runs in front. Images or segments can be captured on the computer, as can the closed captions that accompany most television shows; instead of watching Wall Street Week, let the computer transcribe the program, then scan the text for the good parts.<p>
The Key Tronic Lifetime Wireless Trackball with keyboard ($130) and the Acecat III ($129) also make fine gifts for a techie. The keyboard works up to 50 feet away from the computer -- browse the World Wide Web from a lounge chair -- while the Acecat replaces the mouse with a stylus that mimics the inking qualities of drawing pens. This makes the Acecat an ideal tool for retouching scanned-in photographs or, when packaged with the easy but powerful painting program Dabbler, a tutor for learning how to draw.<p>
Books may be an old-fashioned medium, but at least reading them doesn't require an electronic rodent. Publisher John Wiley & Sons has been reissuing classic investor books, picking those with proven, enduring insights. It's nice to know that even if you end up giving someone all the available books new ones are in the pipeline for future gift-giving occasions. This season's addition to the Wiley Investment Classics (all books around $20) is Charles P. Kindleberger's Manias, Panics, and Crashes, and next spring Wiley will put out Benjamin Graham's The Interpretation of Financial Statements and Philip L. Carret's The Art of Speculation. So far, the series consists of Gerald M. Loeb's cautionary book, The Battle for Investment Survival, published in 1935, when caution was surely in order; Charles McKay's Extraordinary Popular Delusions and the Madness of Crowds, the still-entertaining 1841 treatment of mass psychology in the market; Reminiscences of a Stock Operator, the fictional memoir published in 1923 by Edwin Lefvre and said to parallel the life of the legendary speculator Jesse Livermore; Phillip A. Fisher's Common Stocks and Uncommon Profits; and Fred Schwed Jr.'s Where Are the Customers' Yachts?<p>
A valuable and more recent investment book comes from our own senior financial editor, Jim Jubak. The Worth Guide to Electronic Investing (HarperBusiness, $17.50) helps individual investors with computers harness that computational power -- probably greater than what the entire firm of Merrill Lynch had 25 years ago -- by identifying the best programs for selecting, analyzing, and tracking investments. Plenty of guides address different investment packages, but Jubak's provides strategies for integrating computers into a lifelong investment strategy.<p>
Two books that help make sense of the investment -- and almost every other -- environment are Gary and Guity Becker's The Economics of Life (McGraw-Hill, $25) and Peter L. Bernstein's Against the Gods: The Remarkable Story of Risk (Wiley, $27.95). The first collects the best of Gary Becker's writings over the past 11 years for BusinessWeek and other places. Becker, a Nobel Prize winner and adviser to Bob Dole's presidential campaign, never met a free market he didn't like and, in true University of Chicago fashion, has plenty to say on how freer markets would right the world. Yet Becker is far from the expected right-winger, and his arguments in favor of legalizing drugs and selectively expanding immigration, among others, challenge liberals and conservatives alike. Against the Gods is another challenging book, one that may change forever the way people think about the world. A master at taking important but arcane and statistic-heavy material and putting it in plain, engaging English, Bernstein turns his attention to risk and its measures. The book surveys the concept of risk from ancient times through the Enlightenment and into the present to argue that progressive attempts to measure and insure against risk are as important to the economic development of the world as any of the usual suspects -- namely, science, capitalism, and democracy. Readers will never think about insurance agents the same way again.<p>
For armchair CEOs, consider a corporate page-turner from veteran Wall Street Journal reporter Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg, The Rain on Macy's Parade: How Greed, Ambition, and Folly Ruined America's Greatest Store (Times Books, $27.50). Or try Peter Canning's American Dreamers: The Wallaces and Reader's Digest: An Insider's Story (Simon & Schuster, $27.50). Lila and DeWitt Wallace began Reader's Digest in a Greenwich Village storeroom in 1922 and over the next 50 years turned it into a $6 billion publishing empire. Theirs is both an inspiring story of an institution built on the principles of decency and a chilling tale of how, late in life, the Wallaces, despite tremendous wealth and influence, could neither protect their dream from the corporate wolves nor end their days with the dignity they deserved.<p>
Ken Dornstein's Accidentally, On Purpose (St. Martin's, $26.95) is a fascinating book that delves into the underground economy of personal-injury insurance claims and litigation, tracing the scams back a century when "slip and fall artists" perfected the art of turning banana peels into gold. Dornstein, a former private investigator, is particularly gripping in describing how billions of dollars are reamed from the economy by a ruthless underworld.<p>
Truly frugal people often don't approve of gifts at all -- unless, that is, receiving a gift helps them save money. For them, Paint Your House With Powdered Milk (Hyperion, $7.95) may save Christmas, too. Author Joey Green (who also penned Polish Your Furniture With Panty Hose) suggests unexpected uses for hundreds of brand-name products. Some are actually plausible. Green is especially good at conjuring death for bugs: Maxwell House Coffee, Scotch Transparent Tape, and Kingford's Cornstarch all do the trick.<p>
Finally, for the person with no time to read (or kill bugs) but plenty of time to listen -- on the daily drive to work, maybe -- there's Dogbert's Top Secret Management Handbook, by Scott Adams (HarperAudio, $12). Dilbert books should be (and often are) read aloud while important office work is being put off, and, luckily, the best reader of all, Adams himself, has put his interpretive skills on tape. He delivers his latest book in a deadpan style frighteningly close to that of other business books on tape. But the advice is better and funnier. Here's Dogbert to managers on calculating how late to arrive for a meeting: Multiply the number of people attending by three, then show up whenever you want.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
