<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-King of Bangor</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-King of Bangor</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Stephen King is the richest man in town, but he doesn't lord it over his neighbors. Instead, they get richer off one another.<p>
By James Conaway<p>
Tarry on West Broadway Street in Bangor, Maine, and you are bound to see them. They arrive in Winnebagos and 4x4s, rented sedans and minivans piled with bicycles and collapsible pools; they emerge in Bermudas and armed with cameras and warily approach the wrought-iron fence embellished with winged bats and spiderwebs. Beyond sits a cranberry-and-white Victorian mansion in the Italianate-villa style, with turrets, a broad front porch, and a tower. "Electronic surveillance and alarm equipment is in use," reads the sign. "Please do not enter the grounds."<p>
The tourists' manner suggests that the warning isn't necessary, that something lurking on the other side of the fence just might turn them to jelly. This would be Stephen King, the house's owner, who has written innumerable books in the horror genre and is considered the most successful writer on earth, reportedly earning as much as $43 million in a single year. In September, he had six titles on The New York Times's paperback best-seller list simultaneously, all constituting a single serial novel, The Green Mile. The same month, two new hardbound novels appeared, Desperation and The Regulators (written under King's well-known pseudonym, Richard Bachman). His miniseries of The Shining is expected to be broadcast on ABC early in 1997.<p>
I came to this city of 33,000 looking for the prolific author and his effect on the place, curious about the role played in millennial America by the richest man in town. I was having more trouble locating him than finding the manifestations of his bounty, but then elusiveness is a prerogative of the wealthy. King's is made more intriguing because he has chosen to live where he is so much richer than everybody else. <p>
He lives in Bangor's best neighborhood, in one of Bangor's best houses, which he bought in 1980 for $135,000. Directly behind it lies a three-acre bluegrass expanse that cost King $1.2 million. It is a certifiable field of dreams, built on a city park by the writer in 1992 and given to the town for a category of baseball novitiates accustomed to more rudimentary conditions -- Little Leaguers. The Shawn T. Mansfield Baseball Stadium seats 1,500 and has concession stands, bull pens, and umpires' quarters. King paid another $125,000 for equipment for its upkeep: a turf aerator of the sort used almost exclusively on golf courses, a "top dresser" to spread sand, a mower, a dumper, and a bunker rake to smooth the infield's Beam Clay, which was trucked all the way up from New Jersey, the same kind that is used in Yankee Stadium.<p>
Every year King makes an additional contribution. "Stephen came by last spring," said Ronald St. Pierre when I found him smoking a cigar and supervising the laying of brick at the stadium's entrance. "He asked me what I needed for upkeep this year. He said, 'Just bring the bills by the office.'"<p>
St. Pierre, treasurer of an engineering firm, is the pro bono maintenance boss. He belongs to a supervisory committee that includes King, the president of an insurance company, a lawyer, and a businessman named Dave Mansfield, who acts as a Little League coach and manager. Mansfield was surprised when King offered to name the new park after Shawn, Mansfield's son who died at 14 from cerebral palsy. "I thought he would name it for the King family. It's not only for my son but for all the others who didn't have a chance to play. The handicapped have easy access. It's a very friendly environment."<p>
King, an ardent baseball fan, coached Little League between 1990 and 1995. He wrote an article for The New Yorker about his son Owen's team and its 1989 championship season. St. Pierre said King gave him a signed copy of the magazine. "People are always asking him for his autograph, which he doesn't do, and here I have something like that and I don't even know where I put it. I don't read his books," he added sheepishly. "He teases me a little bit about that....I miss him, miss his wit. He once said, 'You may think I'm weird, but weird paid for this ballpark.'"<p>
Once, the richest man in town sat in the first pew of his chosen church, his fortune lay in the local bank, and his industry occupied the riverbank or the railroad siding. Raw materials came from the town's surrounds, and he embodied the direct link between his product and the town's economic health. <p>
The wealth of what's left of Bangor's old-money families came mostly from timber. But though a rough-hewn statue of Paul Bunyan, a reminder of glory days, holds up the broad Maine sky in the town's grassy park, the forest that produced the legend of the Blue Ox and made Bangor the lumber capital of the world is gone -- and the shipbuilding and related fortunes with it. The dwindling of the big trees and the demise of the commercial sailing vessel left Bangor stranded between the Penobscot River and the ocean, an hour to the east. Shoe and boot manufacturing provided some jobs, but this business is now just about gone.<p>
"There's been no recent influx of business," said the president of Bangor's Chamber of Commerce, Peter Daigle. "We didn't enjoy the boom of the late '80s, but then we didn't have as far to fall." The average household income in Bangor is $29,619, and the average individual's annual take is $13,531. <p>
As I drove through Bangor's downtown, I listened to a King novel, The Stand, on cassette. It's about an unstoppable mutant virus and a malevolent federal government, with a cast of mostly bottom feeders ("his breath rattled in and out like a sound of October wind in dead corn husks"). I passed empty storefronts, their stair-step Victorian facades like the weathered faces of the men from the Greater Bangor Area Shelter who sat on benches nearby. Skateboarders -- baggy pants, shaved heads, rattails -- stood on a corner. Most businesses have moved to the mall, on the outskirts of town. It's now Bangor's second-largest employer.<p>
Betts Bookstore is downtown, though in a refurbished commercial district called West Market Square. Its proprietor, Stuart Tinker, a chubby fellow in a sports shirt, was talking by telephone to a collector on the West Coast about a King first edition when I entered. "It's a fair price," he said.<p>
Bangor has a number of bookstores (the University of Maine, just up the river at Orono, contributes to the intellectual climate), but Betts is the one that caters to fans of Stephen Edwin King. In 1990, Tinker and his wife decided to stock King's oeuvre, which now accounts for about 20 percent of sales. There are 45 titles listed on the Betts Bookstore Stephen King coffee mug. First and rare editions pull in a surprising amount of money. For instance, the oversize edition of the short story "My Pretty Pony," with a digital clock on the stainless-steel cover, published by the Whitney Museum of American Art as a fund-raiser, was available for $2,500. Tinker had already sold his limited edition of Firestarter, the one with the asbestos cover, for $9,000.<p>
Through a page on the World Wide Web, Tinker said, he receives inquiries from as far away as China and Russia. Out-of-town visitors often buy the latest paperback and maybe something special, like the signed edition of The Stand with a Bible-like black leather cover and gilt-edged pages nestled in red velvet inside a miniature wooden coffin (available for $995). "Yesterday this guy from New Zealand came in with his daughters. They were spending a week in California and flew to Boston and up here just for the day. They wanted to see where Stephen King lived. Now, that's not cheap."<p>
King's notoriety attracts enough visitors to affect the tourist trade, small though it is. (Bangor may be the one place in Maine that likes tourists.) "Bangor's become a destination. I've seen it in my E-mail," Tinker said. "Few people here realize the effect Stephen King has had on the city...on restaurants, motels, stores. People plan their honeymoons around King. They want to see the place he writes about."<p>
The biggest generic employer in the area is still "the forest" -- remnant white pine fed into the mills to the north that pump the sweetish smell of paper pulp into the air. But in Bangor, the biggest employer is the Eastern Maine Medical Center. It was built to serve those working in what is left of the outlying wood-fiber industry, but the largest single donation for the new children's wing ($750,000) came from King and his wife, Tabitha.<p>
Likewise the renovation of the Bangor Public Library (a classical edifice on Harlow Street built in 1911), which came about because of $2.5 million from the Kings. "Tabitha drove by one day," said library director Barbara McDade, "and saw that the front steps had been closed down -- they were unsafe -- and she called and said, 'What can we do to help?'"<p>
That was the beginning of an $8.5 million capital drive to build a new wing and to open the stacks to the public. "We decided accessibility would be the whole thrust," said McDade, referring to an ongoing concern of the Kings'. Tabitha King, who grew up outside Bangor and attended the local John Bapst High School, "considered this her library," McDade added. She paid for the engineering study and sat on the building and fund-raising committees. "She was a strong force," McDade said -- it sounded like an understatement to me -- and her husband gave a rare public reading.<p>
The library contains more than half a million volumes, has a phenomenal reference desk, and is highly regarded by Bangorians. It receives 2,000 visitors a day; no less than 67 percent of the populace have library cards. "Some outsiders say that's because there's nothing else to do in Bangor," said McDade, "but that's not true."<p>
For whatever reason, the library circulated about 1,200 books a day in 1995, more than 10 books per capita per annum. About a third of the operating budget comes from an endowment, but that is not enough for major repairs and certainly not enough for the new projects that had everyone so excited when I was there. The capital campaign had been a success, and I asked McDade what things would be like at the library if the Kings did not live in Bangor.
"We'd still be trying to get $100,000 from the city council," she said, "to fix the front steps." <p>
King, 49, is rooted in Maine. He lived with his mother and foster brother in the little town of Durham, south of Bangor, after King's father, a seaman, went out for cigarettes in 1949 and never came back. King's mother took subsistence jobs to support the family, and Stephen grew up reading secondhand paperbacks. <p>
He attended the University of Maine in Orono, where he met Tabitha Spruce, from nearby Old Town; her father owned a convenience store. King wanted to be a writer, and according to Edward Holmes, the English professor who taught him creative writing, "he found people here who took the idea of fiction seriously."<p>
King married Tabitha around the time of graduation and started teaching high-school English. He wrote novels and short stories and lived for a time in a trailer; he couldn't get the novels published. Then, in 1973, he started a novel about a teenage girl with supernatural powers, became discouraged, and tried to toss it. Tabitha reportedly picked the manuscript out of the proverbial trash can. It became the 1974 best-seller Carrie. When it was accepted for publication, King was working in a laundry. He telephoned his old professor that night with the news. "I wasn't too surprised," Holmes told me, "but I was astonished at the degree of his success."<p>
The Kings tried living elsewhere for a short while, but they came back to Maine and bought the big house on West Broadway that Tabitha had fallen in love with as a teenager, a house built in 1870 by a prosperous livery-stable owner. Here King settled into his astounding professional fecundity. <p>
For the next ten years or so, the best-selling novelist was generally available to other Mainers. A Bangor writer named Ardeana Hamlin asked King to address a "gifted and talented" class of teenagers she was teaching in nearby Dexter, in 1987, and King arrived in a green Mercedes, wearing cowboy boots and a leather jacket and carrying the crumpled manuscript of The Tommyknockers with coffee stains on it.<p>
He asked one of the students to take off his sneaker and put it on the table, Hamlin recalled. He gave them the assignment of describing the sneaker and how to tie it.<p>
King was candid with the class. When one student asked him if he had ever considered seeing a psychiatrist, King said, "No. If I did that, the darkness might all go away."<p>
 The classified section of the Bangor Daily News carries Happy Ads ("The McPherson Family would like to thank their children...for all their help last weekend in making the Anderson Family Reunion a success," "This bitter sweet 'Pickle' turns '50' which is older than dirt"), as well as those seeking blueberry rakers and bricklayers.<p>
The newspaper has been in the same family for more than a century. Its scion, Richard "Rick" Warren, a lean man in aviator glasses, is the publisher. Six bamboo fly rods hang on his office wall, and he owns several miles of prime salmon beat in New Brunswick. When I asked him about the effect of Bangor's famous novelist on the city, he said, not disapprovingly, "King generates a lot of traffic. His house must be the most visited in the country -- seven days a week, 52 weeks a year. I can attest to that because I live across the street."<p>
He put the Kings at the top of the donors in Bangor, adding, "It would be a mistake to think that they're the only significant givers." He referred me to the plaques in the Medical Center rather than divulge names from the dwindling ranks of timber heirs, "who might not appreciate it." <p>
The Kings' names are there. Other names belong to descendants of Bangorians whose money no doubt found its way into good works, as well as directly affected the city's economy. But some of these heirs tend to live off large land trusts, according to one student of the city.<p>
Listening to my Stephen King novel on tape, I had the impression the author knows as much about institutional neglect as corporal disaster ("a jagged splinter of plastic was lodged in one oozing eye"). Topical detail and brand names are deftly intertwined with physical appetites in a youthful argot heavy on put-down and obscenities. Surely that accounts in part for the appeal of King's stories to teenagers, who read them by the millions (King will sell about 25 million books in 1996). The story of The Stand involves the supernatural but is really about the failure of what was called, when King was young, "the system."<p>
One of the Kings' controversial involvements is with Shaw House, a home for runaway teenagers downtown. The Kings' role hasn't been publicized, but the Maine Grants Information Center at the University of Southern Maine lists them as giving $30,000 in 1993, support that has continued.<p>
I went there and found half a dozen young people sitting on the grass in front of the rudimentary building, quietly talking, and a basement piled with donated clothing. There were 16 beds in what one of the supervisors, Jayne Rogers, called a "low barrier" facility, meaning that referrals aren't necessary for the children to be accepted. "Some of them come for a couple of nights, when they need a respite from home, and then we have the chronic ones on the street all the time. We refer some out for counseling."<p>
Most of the funding comes from the local community, and so does the criticism. "Wherever kids hang out, people say they're ours," says Rogers. These include the saturnalian midnight gatherings of young people in West Market Square, redolent of cannabis, that are complained about by many of the remaining store owners. "Bedtime is 11 o'clock, but this is a homeless shelter. If kids show up at 3 a.m., we let them in."<p>
The Stephen and Tabitha King Foundation had assets in 1993 of $4 million and made gifts of more than $2 million to causes as various as Hope House, for recovering alcoholics ($40,000), the YMCA ($40,000), the United Way of Penobscot Valley ($30,000), the Pine Tree Chapter of the American Red Cross ($29,000), the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute ($10,000), the United Negro College Fund ($5,000), and the National Poetry Foundation ($40,000).<p>
But most of their aid seems directed toward Bangor's children -- Shaw House, the Medical Center, the baseball field, other undisclosed projects. A prominent Bangorian, insisting on anonymity, told me of a blank check Tabitha King had given to a fund-raiser for a children's playground.<p>
And a friend of the Kings' said, "It's a shame, in a way. Everybody's got their hand out."<p>
The Kings are products of a so-called moralistic culture, according to Mark Woodward, the editorial-page editor for the Bangor Daily News. "The moralistic culture stresses community participation and the commonwealth over individual rights and elitism," Woodward said. It explains the cooperative nature of New England frontier life, particularly that of Maine. Caught between a wilderness and a cold ocean, suffering the privations of long winters, logging, fishing, and subsistence farming, Maine's people grew more interdependent than they might have been in more comfortable climes. The better off reach down to those below, the theory goes.<p>
I took this notion to Christopher Spruce, Tabitha King's brother and the general manager of the two radio stations in Bangor owned by the Kings. (One of them, WZON, is named after King's novel The Dead Zone.) "I grew up with Tabby and knew Steve early in their relationship," said Spruce in a comfortably cluttered office in an old building downtown. "It's in their natures to do this. When the need is there, people can ask them for help -- and get it."<p>
He agreed that charity has its disappointments. "I try to imagine what it's like for them. I don't know if I could take it. Whatever you do, it's never enough....If tomorrow they said, 'We're not doing this anymore,' nobody should raise an eyebrow."<p>
The radio station was bought in 1983 after King heard it was for sale. "He bought it to preserve rock and roll on AM," Spruce said. Later, King changed it to a sports station. "We have some of the most intensive local coverage anywhere," Spruce said. Games involving King's beloved Boston Red Sox are broadcast regularly, "but mostly we have live local sports."<p>
I asked Spruce what Bangor would be like if the Kings had decided to live in, say, Laguna Beach. "There would be no ball field, different radio stations. The hospital wing would have been built, but it wouldn't be so nice. The library would be a different configuration. It's more than monetary, it's emotional and intellectual: They're woven into the fabric of the community. Imagine unraveling a sweater, trying to tell which strands were theirs. You could put the sweater back together again, but there would be holes."<p>
It's a question of your attitude toward the future," Stephen King told me. "I've written all these books and the money rolls in, and what do I do with it all? I mean, how many suits can I buy? I have a Levi's body anyway. I put on an expensive suit and after an hour it looks like it came from f------ Robert Hall."<p>
His old running shoes were propped on the coffee table in the office where King's money is disseminated and his fan mail and scheduling handled. It's discreetly situated near the airport and has no listing in the telephone directory and no writing on the door. Journalists and fans who manage to find their way to the office are not encouraged to stay. I gave up hope of talking to the richest man in Bangor, but after several days in town I received an unexpected invitation to meet him at the office.<p>
He wore jeans and a T-shirt bearing the silk-screened likeness of a Venus flytrap and a fly about to enter it. "I don't have any interest in empire building, sequestering wealth, living off the sweat from the glass, and letting the principal go to subsequent generations." The sweat from the glass is interest, its contents a potential obsessive nightmare. "I don't want to end up like Howard Hughes, sitting in a hotel room watching Ice Station Zebra over and over again."<p>
He looks like the photographs: buck teeth, squinty eyes behind thick, steel-rimmed glasses, a slightly manic expression. The beard is gone, and the hair is beginning to gray. "Giving away money is like drugs -- you say you're only going to do it once." And, "Giving's for the giver, too. The more you talk about it, the more it dissipates." He meant charity's satisfactions, based in large part upon anonymity. King referred to the Bible quotation "When thou doest alms, let not thy left hand know what thy right hand doeth."<p>
But he does, helter-skelter, calling supplicants "blowflies" and "piranhas" and evincing a brand of humor that goes back to the 1960s. "People come up to us and I'm reminded of that cartoon, the one about the coyote who looks at the roadrunner and sees a chicken dinner."<p>
"You get on the mailing lists," explained Tabitha King.<p>
She wore a T-shirt, too, baggy shorts, and granny glasses. Her chestnut hair is bobbed. Like her husband, she is a novelist but also the chief dispenser of King largesse. "If people know you're willing," she continued, the measured yang to her husband's hyperbolic yin, "they're more inclined to ask. Increasingly, you have to deal. In the beginning it was simple, a little money for the American Cancer Society, and then the organizations started coming forward. Then there were the local requests -- a library, a recreational facility," some other things. "We looked at each other, and said, 'We could do something about this.'"<p>
The effects of this admission now occupy roughly half her time: "I do more of the board service, more than I anticipated, but there's an infinite amount to be done and too few hands."<p>
About 10 percent of the King income is given away, a practice that goes back to his childhood. "My father 'did a bunk' when I was two," said Stephen King. "There was no such thing as latchkey kids then. My mother worked at different jobs and raised us, too. She still responded to the begging letters," not necessarily those from the Methodist church they attended but those from any benighted soul. "Our most serious problem today is that we spend billions on a military machine for Republican fat cats scratching each other's backs."<p>
His mother's 10 percent amounted to about $500 a year, which she could well have used. "I see Nancy Reagan and guys who look like they never missed a meal get up at the Republican convention and talk about how great Reagan was. Well, the Gipper never gave." 
As if to emphasize this allegation, he clamps down on a toothpick and makes a feint toward their Welsh corgi. "Nothing makes me sicker at my stomach than to hear these guys talk about making it on their own," he said. "Talent comes hardwired, it's in the system. You don't go out and say, 'Let me work 40 hours a week so I can become a successful writer.'"<p>
An employee brought him a stack of books, and he began to autograph them. I asked why they chose to live in Bangor. "The area's full of my relatives," Tabitha King said. "We both went to Orono, and we needed a town with a decent airport and schools where our children didn't have to ride a bus. We were both comfortable with a small town." <p>
"One of the great things about Bangor is that it's small enough to see the results," said Stephen King. "You have a vision for Bangor," he told his wife. "There are things you want for it, things I want. Like the library. Where else are you going to find 18 copies of Peyton Place? It's an immense satisfaction."<p>
Of Shaw House, Tabitha King said, "It's controversial, but people don't realize that the only choice for those kids is prostitution or dying in the snow. Their existence is a blunt fact. The social safety net is a joke. The only alternative is some kind of private charitable response." She is capable of some hyperbole of her own, also rooted in the 1960s.<p>
But she's in the habit of carefully reading the annual reports of the organizations appealing for money, to see how it is spent: "You keep an eye on how flashy the brochure is."<p>
King nodded toward his wife. "She's more hardheaded than I am. 'Give, but don't be a chump.'"<p>
There is a suggestion that the advantages of wealth are not worth the growing responsibility, and yet the books keep coming. The Kings want to protect their three children from the burdens of wealth, and yet they are already grown, the eldest son an aspiring novelist, their daughter a restaurateur in Portland, Maine, and their youngest son -- the former Little Leaguer -- a sophomore at Vasser. "We'll make sure the kids don't inherit too much," he said. "They know what it's like, they can't go out of the house without getting their picture taken. They don't want it."<p>
The Kings have modest appetites, considering. "There's no Bahamanian retreat," he said, "no yacht, no plane." They watch a lot of movies and baseball, basketball, and hockey games; he smokes five Merits a day and also prays, although he hasn't been to church since childhood. "I don't own my money, I'm a custodian. How do I do the best with it?" He shrugged. "If I die, it goes to her. She can do with it whatever she wants. That's cool."<p>
Lately they have begun assigning royalties from various novels to specific causes. "I don't know how much will be around when we croak," she added. <p>
At the end of the 20th century, the significant money in this town still pumps at an industrial-revolution rate. This rich man could qualify as a Manchester capitalist on one level, but his politics are egalitarian and his gifts wear the individual, somewhat demonic human face once obscured by tact and convention.<p>
This rich man not only does not sit in the first pew, but he stays home Sundays (or goes to ball games). His money, managed in far-flung Gotham, finds its most meaningful way into the local economy through taxes and good works. The remote industry that fuels it is an adjunct of media, and his radio stations -- a dalliance -- influence the citizenry more subtly but no less persistently than once did the deacons. <p>
The night before I left Bangor I returned to West Broadway, still listening to The Stand (it's a long book, reader). A single lamp burned on the second floor of the King residence; the tourists were gone, and banks of spotlights shone on the baseball field. The frontiers of Bangor's most exclusive neighborhood, I noticed this time, were quite rudimentary: a video store, a Citgo station, a Best Buy used-car lot, a House of Pizza. Two women sat smoking on a concrete stoop across Hammond Street while their children gamboled in the dust and a one-armed man in a T-shirt strolled past.<p>
Bangor has little violent crime, but the side of the American dream reflected here seems only distantly related to mansions or turf-dressing equipment. Likewise, fictional King country is the seedy strip between security and despair, light and darkness. His novels, the source of fabulous income and extensive giving, are populated not just by diseases and fiends but also by unemployed adults, abused kids, neglected spouses, forgotten oldies, drifters, users, and all manner of the physically, mentally, and emotionally challenged: people, in short, every one of them in need of a break.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
philanthropy, charity, wealth, fame, author

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

