	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-St. Nick's Reading List</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Top-quality unusual gifts in the mail, not the mall<p>
By Anne Field<p>
So hopelessly behind in your holiday shopping you'll pay anything to get it done? Or perhaps you're the organized, picky type who'll spend a little more if it means finding the right thing. In either case, there's a world of top-of-the-line mail-order catalogs that you can turn to, offering everything from a deluxe car-seat cover to the ultimate crystal bowl -- with no lines to wait in. Of course, with over 10,000 catalogs to choose from, you'll also find a lot of schlock. For those interested more in quality or unusual fare than in rock-bottom prices, these catalogs may provide the gifts you need.<p>
Calyx & Corolla (800-800-7788). Unless she's an allergy sufferer, even the hardest-to-please mother-in-law has to like flowers, right? For the non-afflicted, Calyx & Corolla features fresh cut flowers that are shipped directly from the grower. Or try a year's worth: For $375, your recipient gets a bouquet once a month. <p>
The Celebration Fantastic (800-235-3272). An idiosyncratic assortment of high-end novelty items, from a $199 cardigan with multicolored pictures of cappuccino cups to a $35 Cat in the Hat silk tie. For $99, the Holiday Club will send someone special an eight-ounce shipment of chocolate-covered Oreos that have the appropriate decorative toppings on each of five holidays -- Christmas, Valentine's Day, Saint Patrick's Day, Easter, and Halloween.<p>
Chambers (800-334-9790). High-quality linens, towels, and other items for bed and bath. You'll find such luxury goods as leather-trimmed, chrome-plated brass bathroom furnishings, including a $129 tissue-roll holder and a $149 toilet brush. Too pedestrian? Then turn to the chrome-plated or brass "tub valet," which costs $330; it extends across the width of a bathtub, with compartments for soap, washcloths, bath salts, and two candleholders. <p>
French Creek Sheep & wool (800-977-4337). Shearling coats, jackets, vests, and such, designed and manufactured mostly on a 40-acre family-owned sheep farm in Pennsylvania Dutch country. And you'll also find shearling car-seat covers ($145 a pair), lined boots (beginning at $115 a pair), baby buntings ($225), and other sheep-related items, including a watercolor print of several woolly critters for $45 and a copper ram wind chime for $42. <p>
Levenger (800-544-0880). Billed as a reader's catalog, Levenger offers some of the world's most glamorous office supplies. Try a $199 replica of the famous Skyline fountain pen from the 1930s, with its teardrop shape and 14-karat-gold engraved nib. The more newfangled stuff includes a $24.95 leather mouse pad and a $799 ergonomically correct chair based on a design by Herman Miller.<p>
Steuben (800-424-4240). As you would expect, this catalog is visually exquisite, with an array of glistening sculptures, vases, bowls, and the like. It's also big -- 144 pages with almost 250 products. Prices range from high to higher: from $85 for a crystal four-leaf clover to $35,000 for a decorative bowl with swan carvings.<p>
Scientifics (609-547-8880). For everyone from serious science buffs to precocious preschoolers and even space travelers: Vacuum-sealed astronaut-style servings of french fries and pizza are $5.50. There are three full pages of telescopes (a model for neophytes sells for $249) and various astronomy-related stuff. <p>
Sylvia Woods Harp Center (800-272-HARP). Harps, harp accessories, harp recordings, harp jewelry, harp books, harp-shaped rubber stamps -- they're all here in this simple black-and-white catalog. Special bonus: Assorted harp-related historical tidbits are sprinkled throughout the catalog. Top-of-the-line harps top out around $30,000. <p>
Then there's Hammacher Schlemmer (800-543-3366), the oldest continually published catalog in the country, which always boasts the most gloriously impractical gift of the year. This year's annual Hammacher Schlemmer tribute to overkill: the $139,000 Variable Attitude Submersible Hydrofoil, which gives any James Bond manqu the ability to cruise not only on top of and under the water but through the air at speeds nearing 85 miles per hour. Piloting lessons included. 
KEYWORDS: 
frivolity, present, mailing, junkmail

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
