	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Dinner at the Subliminal Grill</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Hey, big tipper -- been seeing the AmEx centurion a lot lately?<p>
By Tom Nawrocki<p>
The tournedos of beef were to die for, the wine was playful yet sophisticated, and the service was not too shabby. But is that the real reason you're tipping 20 percent? Or is it because there's a credit-card logo on the tray holding the bill?<p>
It may be the tip tray. According to a report in the October issue of the Journal of Applied Psychology, diners at two restaurants in upstate New York left tips that were an average of 4.29 percent higher if they saw a credit-card insignia -- even if they paid cash. <p>
One of the researchers, Heather Belmont, had an ulterior motive: A student at Ithaca College, she was also working as a waitress at the time. As a biased participant who was aware of the study's desired result, she had to keep her figures out of the final data. But she kept the tips.  <p>
KEYWORDS: study, gratuity

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
