<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-On Thin Ice</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-On Thin Ice</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Tom Nawrocki<p>
When hockey's florida Panthers made it to the finals of the Stanley Cup Championship last spring, where did team owner H. Wayne Huizenga go? Not to Disney World but to Wall Street. The Blockbuster magnate announced that he would take his Panthers public, in an IPO due this fall.<p>
But don't upgrade that team pennant to stock yet. The Panthers, just in their fourth NHL season, are no blue-puck investment. "If you're good for most of a five- to seven-year cycle, the value of a franchise is enhanced," says Peter Russ, who follows the Boston Celtics Limited Partnership -- the only publicly traded pro team in any sport -- for money-management firm Shelby Cullom Davis & Company. "But short-term success can hurt a team's bottom line." Especially when players' salary demands accelerate faster than media revenues.<p>
Even the Celtics, with 16 NBA championships, have returned just 8 percent annually to their shareholders. The team hasn't won a play-off series in the past three years. "The Celtics can afford one or two more years of mediocrity before it affects the value of the franchise," says Russ. The Green Bay Packers probably considered such pressure back in 1950, when they offered shares priced at $25 to loyal fans. Packers stockholders bought into a nonprofit organization, so they get no dividends or ticket privileges. Plus, the shares can't be bought, only inherited. "You can't make any money off of being a shareholder," says a Green Bay Packers corporation spokesman.<p>
But will Panthers investors ever see green? Hard to say, but note that Huizenga has no plans to go public with his Miami Dolphins or Florida Marlins. "He'll take all the goodies from his two best teams," scoffs Russ, "and let the public share his lesser franchise."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
