<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Ted's Tally</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Ted's Tally</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Reported by Jennifer Barton<p>
Not long ago, Ted Turner railed against his fellow billionaires, calling them "ol' skinflints," unable to open their charitable purse strings for fear of falling off the Forbes rich list. "Why don't they sign a joint pact to each give away a billion and then move down the Forbes list equally?" he suggested to The New York Times.<p>
Among multibillionaires, there are some spectacularly generous philanthropists -- Walter Annenberg, for one. But what about the others? How much do they donate to charity? What nonprofit organizations get their money? And, finally, are any of them "anonymous"?
To find some answers, we checked news clips, biographies, and philanthropic associations. We called the billionaires and their foundations to get as complete a picture of their giving as possible. We limited our search to the past five years and to the rich list's top tier, those worth $2 billion and more, using the July 15 issue of Forbes as our guide. Because we were interested in how the new crop of billionaires spends its charitable dollars, we ignored inherited wealth.<p>
Reactions to our questions ranged from "no comment" to enthusiastic cooperation. One thing to bear in mind: Anonymous donations are few and far between -- 1 to 2 percent of all giving. Another thing: A gift of $1 million from a billionaire is comparable to a gift of $100 from someone with $100,000.<p>
William H. Gates
<a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>, 41 years old
$18 billion
Foundation: The Road Ahead Foundation, funded by proceeds from Gates's book (The Road Ahead). Grants paid, 1996: $3 million.
Gifts: $34 million to the University of Washington, $6 million to Stanford University (toward the $38.5 million William Gates Computer Science Building), $2 million to United Way. A Microsoft spokesperson says Gates has given away about $60 million over the past ten years.
Comment: "I have made a decision that most of my money will go to charitable causes. It will be later in life, after I'm 50 or 60" (The New York Times, 4/30/95).
Gifts (in past ten years) as a percentage of total wealth: 0.33.<p>
Warren E. Buffett
stock market, 66 years old
$15.29 billion
Foundation: The Buffett Foundation. Grants paid, year ending 6/30/95: $7,108,483.**
Foundation gifts: Include $2 million to the Population Council to fund clinical trials of RU-486.
Private gifts: $680,000 to Girls Inc., raised through the Omaha Classic (annual golf, tennis, and dinner outing).
Comment: According to Buffett: The Making of an American Capitalist, by Roger Lowenstein, Buffett has said he will leave his money to his foundation. "'When I am dead,' he observed, 'I assume there'll still be serious problems of a social nature as there are now.'... Buffet could have been peeling off tens of millions for society's 'serious problems' every year and still would not have diminished his pile of chips by even 1 percent."
Lowenstein also writes that an experience in the 1970s with Grinnell College soured Buffett on giving to universities. According to Allen Greenberg, Buffett's son-in-law, who manages the foundation, "'Warren would rather choke to death than write a check to a university.'"<p>
Paul G. Allen
Microsoft, 42 years old
$7.46 billion
Foundations: Allen has several foundations, including the Paul G. Allen Charitable Foundation. Grants paid, 1994: $2.1 million.
Gifts: In the past several years, Allen, through his foundations, has given away more than $100 million for AIDS research and to libraries, museums, and theaters, as well as $1 million to the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence Institute.
Comment: When asked by The New York Times (10/29/95) what it's like to be a billionaire, Allen responded: "It's...a lot...of...money.... Hopefully, you find some way to put that in charitable hands, to do something good for society as a whole."<p>
John W. Kluge
<a name="AMEX:MMG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10613"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Metromedia</b></a>, 82 years old
$6.84 billion
Foundation: John W. Kluge Foundation. Grants paid, 1993: $5,688,702.**
Gifts: More than $100 million to Columbia University, as well as donations to the Library of Congress, Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, and the Ronald Reagan Presidential Foundation.
Comment: Kluge "gives where he feels it is worthwhile to give," says a spokesperson.<p>
Philip H. Knight
<a name="NYSE:NKE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14254"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nike</b></a>, 58 years old
$5.12 billion
Foundation: Philip H. Knight Charitable Foundation Trust. Grants paid, 199294: $2.4 million.
Private gifts: $25 million to the University of Oregon (according to the University of Oregon); $25,000 toward Tonya Harding's legal expenses (according to Just Do It, by Donald Katz); and $100,000 to Portland schools (according to The Oregonian, 4/25/96).
Comment: Knight feels that his giving is a "private matter." He says the gifts listed above are neither "inclusive nor accurate" but declines to give corrections, says a spokesperson.<p>
Lawrence J. Ellison
<a name="NASD:ORCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14337"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oracle</b></a>, 52 years old
$4.92 billion 
Private gifts: In 1994, Ellison pledged $5 million to the University of California at Davis to create the Lawrence J. Ellison Ambulatory Care Center.
Comment: A spokesperson at Oracle says Ellison declines to comment.<p>
Richard M. DeVos
Amway, 70 years old
$4.44 billion
Foundation: The Richard and Helen DeVos Foundation. Grants paid, 199296: $60 million.
Comment: The DeVoses give mostly to Christian causes, local hospitals, and community organizations through their foundation, says a staff member at the foundation, adding that "their motivation for giving comes from a deep spiritual commitment to responsibly share their God-given blessings."<p>
Kirk Kerkorian
Investments, 79 years old
$4.36 billion
Foundation: The Lincy Foundation, funded by Kerkorian's wholly owned Tracinda Corp. Grants paid, 199195: $54 million (includes $3 million to some of Barbra Streisand's favorite causes).
Comment: The foundation gives primarily to Armenian and humanitarian organizations in the U.S. "People we give to know us," says James Aljian, chairman of the foundation.<p>
Jay van Andel
Amway, 72 years old
$4.32 billion
Foundation: Jay and Betty Van Andel Foundation. Grants paid, 1993: $3,491,910.** 
Comment: Casey Wondergem, spokesman for the foundation, says the Van Andels give in the Grand Rapids, Michigan, area, to museums, zoos, and other cultural institutions. According to Wondergem, the Van Andels donated $11.5 million toward the construction of a $50 million local arena.<p>
Donald E. Newhouse
Publishing, 67 years old
$4.3 billion
Samuel I. Newhouse Jr.
Publishing, 69 years old
$4.3 billion
Foundation: Samuel I. Newhouse Foundation (donors: Samuel I. Newhouse and Mitzi E. Newhouse, both deceased). Grants paid, year ending 10/31/94: $7,242,258.**
Comment: Paul Scherer, Donald Newhouse's accountant, would not comment on whether or not the Newhouses donate to the foundation. He says, "They give to the charities they are interested in, just like you and me, if something strikes them."
Says Thomas Maier, author of the biography Newhouse: "Considering the huge amount of money the Newhouses make, they give an extraordinarily small amount to charity" (according to data from fiscal year 1991).<p>
Sumner M. Redstone
<a name="AMEX:VIA"></a><b>Viacom</b>, 73 years old
$3.8 billion
Gifts: More than $33 million in 199195. Includes gifts made personally and through the companies Redstone controls.
Comment: "The primary recipients of his personal contributions are medical research in cancer and childhood diseases, as well as education. He also believes in giving of his time and expertise, which he does through teaching. Mr. Redstone is a frequent lecturer at Boston, Harvard, and Brandeis Universities," says Viacom spokeswoman Susan Duffy.
Gifts as a percentage of total wealth: 0.87.<p>
Ronald O. Perelman
Leveraged buyouts, 53 years old
$3.74 billion
Gifts: $116.3 million, 1991 to the present. This represents personal gifts and corporate gifts made through <a name="NYSE:REV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=48062"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Revlon</b></a>, wholly owned by Perelman until this year. Includes $20 million to the University of Pennsylvania, $20 million to the Guggenheim Museum, and $12 million to the Salvation Army.
Comment: Perelman's three principal areas of giving are education, medical research, and culture, says Jim Conroy, a spokesman.
Gifts as a percentage of total wealth: 3.1.<p>
Steven A. Ballmer
Microsoft, 40 years old
$3.66 Billion
Comment: We did not locate any personal foundations or information about Ballmer's philanthropy. A Microsoft spokesperson says Ballmer "prefers to keep his donations private."<p>
Walter H. Annenberg
Publishing, 88 years old
$3.62 billion
Foundation: The Annenberg Foundation.
Gifts: The foundation gave out nearly $1 billion from 1991 to 1995, including $2 million to the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, $100 million to the Peddie School, and $50 million to the United Negro College Fund.
Comment: Annenberg's focus is education, particularly public-school restructuring and reform in the U.S. In 1993, he pledged the largest single gift to public education in the U.S.: $500 million. Of the multibillionaires, Annenberg is by far the most philanthropic.
Gifts as a percentage of total wealth: 27.<p>
William R. Hewlett
<a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a>, 83 years old
$3.6 billion
Foundation: The William and Flora Hewlett Foundation. Grants paid, 199195: $184.5 million.
Private gifts: Include $77 million to Stanford University, given jointly with the late David Packard, and $1 million to the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence Institute.
Gifts as a percentage of total wealth: 7.3. Hewlett is second to Annenberg in this survey.<p>
Gordon E. Moore
<a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, 67 years old
$3.4 billion
Foundations: The Intel Foundation (corporate); grants paid, 1994: $3,100,380. Moore Family Foundation (Moore is a donor); grants paid, 1994: $1,615,042.**
Private gifts: $16.8 million to the California Institute of Technology.*
Comment: Moore didn't return phone calls.<p>
Keith Rupert Murdoch
Publishing, 65 years old
$3.3 billion
Comment: When asked about Murdoch's philanthropy, spokeswoman Marcia Horowitz says, "He does not disclose that information." We didn't find any personal foundations for Murdoch nor information on charitable gifts.<p>
Jay A. Pritzker
Financier, 74 years old
$2.95 billion
Robert A. Pritzker
Financier, 70 years old
$2.95 billion
Foundations: The Hyatt Foundation, which funds the $100,000 annual Pritzker Architecture Prize. The Pritzker Foundation (donors are members of the Pritzker family); grants paid 1993: $2,430,606.**
Comment: A spokesperson for Robert Pritzker says that he likes giving to medicine, the arts, higher education, science, and engineering, but the spokesperson declined to give dollar amounts. Jay Pritzker could not be reached for comment.<p>
Edgar M. Bronfman
<a name="NYSE:VO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41797"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Seagram</b></a>, 67 years old
$2.76 billion
Comment: Bronfman has no personal foundations. He's chairman of the Samuel Bronfman Foundation (Joseph E. Seagram & Sons, Inc., of which he is a major shareholder, is a donor). Amy Goldberger, director of media relations at the company, says his "personal gifts are vast," but she declined to name dollar amounts or institutions to which he's donated.
Private gifts: $5,000 to SafeSpace, New York City.<p>
H. Ross Perot
Computer services, 66 years old 
$2.6 billion
Private gifts: Perot has given $100 million, including $23 million to the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center at Dallas and $2.6 million to Auburn University.
Comment: "Ross Perot has faithfully shared his blessings with countless individuals and organizations.... His most direct focus has been, and still is, aimed at helping underprivileged children.... A multitude of others in need are provided food, clothing, shelter, medical care and education through Perot's donations to organizations such as the Salvation Army, United Way" (press release, Perot '96, Inc.).
According to Gerald Posner, author of Citizen Perot, "Perot is very generous in his giving. The two aspects that make him different than many other donors is he does not need his name on the gift. That's the plus side. The downside is when you get Perot's money, you get him. He views a gift as an investment, and if you don't spend it as you agreed, he'll ask for it back."<p>
Henry L. Hillman
Industrialist, 77 years old
$2.4 billion
Foundations: The Henry L. Hillman Foundation; grants paid, 1994: $1,512,500.** The Hillman Foundation; grants paid, 199195: $15,518,615.
Comment: The Hillman Foundation is partly funded by Hillman's privately owned company. It focuses on organizations within Pittsburgh and southwestern Pennsylvania.<p>
Lee M. Bass
Oil, investments, 40 years old 
$2.38 billion
Foundation: Bass Foundation, a family foundation to which Lee and Sid Bass donate. Grants paid, 199195: $13,608,041.
Private gifts: A quail hunt, donated by Bass, which sold for $5,400 at an auction put on by the Texas Wildlife Association.<p>
Samuel C. Johnson
Johnson Wax, 68 years old$2.3 billion
Foundations: Corporate contributions from majority-owned S. C. Johnson & Son, Inc., and the S. C. Johnson Wax Fund exceeded $40 million over the past five years, says a spokesperson.
Private gifts: $2 million to Cornell University; $1 million to the Nature Conservancy.<p>
Robert Edward (TED) Turner
<a name="AMEX:TBS/A"></a><b>Turner Broadcasting</b> 57 years old, $2.29 billion
Foundation: The Turner Foundation, Inc. Grants paid, from 1991 to present: about $18 million.
Private gifts: $75 million total pledged to Brown University, the Citadel, the McCallie School. Turner also gave a grant to paleontologist John Horner, who discovered the remains of a sauropod on Turner's Montana ranch.
Comment: Jonathan Roseman at the foundation says Turner is "very committed to giving and encouraging other individuals to give."
According to The Atlanta Journal, 8/23/96, Turner said that if the very rich don't start giving soon, "we may have another French Revolution and there'll be another Madame Defarge watching them come...to the town square and boom! Off with their heads!"<p>
Robert M. Bass
Oil, investments, 48 years old 
$2.13 billion
Foundation: Anne T. & Robert M. Bass Foundation. Grants paid, 1994: $500,000.**
Private gifts: $25 million to Stanford University and $20 million to Yale University, from Robert and Anne T. Bass.<p>
Philip F. Anschutz
Oil, 57 years old
$2 billion
Foundation: The Anschutz Foundation (Philip Anschutz and the Anschutz Corp. are donors). Grants given, 199395: $727,000.**
Comment: According to the 199495 Colorado Foundation Directory, the Anschutz Foundation gave $10,000 to the Heritage Foundation, $5,000 to the Manhattan Institute for Policy Research, $5,000 to the American Legislative Exchange Council, and $1,500 to the Capital Research Center.<p>
Sid R. Bass
Investments, 53 years old
$2 billion
Foundation: The Bass Foundation (see Lee M. Bass).
Private gifts: $20 million to Yale.<p>
Donald L. Bren
Real estate, 64 years old
$2 billion
Foundation: Donald L. Bren Foundation. Grants paid, 1994: $101,000.**
Gifts: According to a spokesperson, Bren gives personally and through his foundation and the Irvine Co., which he owns. In the past five years, Bren has given $10 million to local schools in Southern California. He has set aside 21,000 acres of the company's land to form the Nature Reserve of Orange County and is a benefactor of UC Irvine.<p>
Marvin H. Davis
Oil, 71 years old 
$2 billion
Comment: Of Davis's giving, 70 percent goes to medical charities, says spokesman Michael Sitrick. Davis has provided funding for the Barbara Davis Center for Juvenile Diabetes and puts on the Carousel of Hope, a benefit for children's diabetes. "Everyone in Hollywood turns out," says Sitrick.
Christine Lerner at the Children's Diabetes Foundation in Denver says Davis has given close to $12 million since 1977.<p>
Jon M. Huntsman
Plastics, chemicals, 59 years old 
$2 billion
Private gifts: Huntsman contributed $100 million in 1995 to the Huntsman Cancer Institute, focusing on genetic research. Smaller gifts include $1 million to the St. Vincent de Paul soup kitchen and 2,000 turkeys for Thanksgiving at Salt Lake City Food Bank.
Comment: "We like to help people who are suffering. That is the main motivation behind the cancer gift," says a spokesperson.
Gifts as a percentage of total wealth: more than 5.<p>
*Giving U.S.A., published by American Association of Fund-Raising Counsel.
**Guide to U.S. Foundations, Their Trustees, Officers, and Donors, 1996, published by the Foundation Center, New York City.

