		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Letters</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						I HEAR AMERICA EARNING<p>
"The Richest Towns in America" (July/August), by Jeff Blyskal, must have been quite an undertaking, with so many wealthy enclaves tucked away and often relatively little solid information to go on. I love to see such reports, as they give evidence to trends in wealth creation, migration, and disintegration.<p>
As a Chicago resident, I'm surprised that many North Shore communities rank ahead of Lake Forest, a time-honored benchmark of wealth for the Midwest. Perhaps my greatest surprise is that of the very low ranking -- in my opinion -- of Tuxedo Park, New York, at No. 55. In relative terms, Tuxedo Park makes Atherton, California, look like a cheap, nouveau-riche enclave of superficial notables. Tuxedo Park, where the gentlemen's garment gained its name, was and still is the embodiment of civilized wealth in America. It is a pity that statistics fail to quantify the true sense of wealth that Tuxedo Park has -- and has always had. 
Peter Hayes Millen
Chicago, Illinois<p>
"The Richest Towns in America" suggests a correlation between cost of living and desirability: "The higher costs in New York suggest the area is more desirable than Kentucky or Arizona and simply worth the price." As an economist and nonNew Yorker, I can tell you that is not always the case. Perhaps Kentuckians, Arizonans, and others pay less for housing because they earn less -- because they are willing to forfeit higher wages for a perceived higher quality of life elsewhere. Costs, including housing, are a reflection of what the market will bear. How much people can and will pay depends on income. Some studies that explore quality-of-life issues suggest that people are paid a premium to live and work in undesirable places, not the other way around.
Richard M. Stein
Westville, New Jersey<p>
I purchased your July/August issue solely for the cover story about America's richest towns and neighborhoods. What could have been a fascinating article became nearly meaningless, however, because of the lack of maps accompanying the tables. I work for a mapping company and consider myself knowledgeable about this country's major cities and suburbs. But how many people outside of the immediate area have heard of Hewlett Bay Park, Muttontown, or Centre Island, New York? 
Scott Bornkessel
Houston, Texas <p>
"The Richest Towns in America" would more accurately be titled "The Richest Enclaves in America." You'd be stretching the definition of "town" to include Russell Gardens, Flower Hill, Munsey Park, and Oyster Bay Cove, to mention just a few Long Island localities. Each qualifies as a small residential municipality, but each is more accurately part of a larger town. Beyond the adjacent area, these names would not be readily recognized as separate entities even by many longtime Long Island residents.
Una L. Mahar
Vienna, Virginia<p>
HOME SWEET ATHERTON
Just a note to clarify "Atherton's Little Acres" (July/August), from an Atherton resident's perspective. It is only very recently that Atherton has become a high-profile, high-wealth town. It began as, and to some degree remains, a quiet suburb of San Francisco. There is still, thank heavens, a relatively balanced mix of people, including those who paid considerably less than $1 million for their Atherton acres (in some cases as little as $7,000).
Mary Perkins
Atherton, California<p>
WHO YOU CALLING FOGIES?
Will somebody please tell Susan Lee ("Young Fogies," July/August) that Worth is a magazine targeted at the small investor! A writer is supposed to address her audience, not smugly tell us that we are incompetent to buy stocks, as well as bonds ("Bonds Away!" May). For whose benefit is Lee dispensing financial advice, her pals in the mutual-fund companies?
Robin J. Arzt
New york, New york<p>
I certainly hope Susan Lee was writing with tongue firmly in cheek. I am an amateur investor -- and have been for 25 years -- who maintains a portfolio of 15 to 25 stocks. I like being in control of how I invest my money. To me, mutual funds are for those individuals who do not, or will not, take the time to do their own money management.
Tom Reincke
Fort Wayne, Indiana<p>
JACKIE'S BOOKSHELVES
Having also attended the Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis auction preview at Sotheby's, and having perused in greatest detail the auction catalog, I was amused by much of Robert Plunket's article "Jackie's Last Word" (July/August). However, I found Plunket's supercilious comment that Mrs. Onassis's library was not that of "an inquiring mind" to be offensive. The lady's personal library contained hundreds of volumes, covering a wide spectrum of specialized interests, such as architecture, art, theater, French literature, world and American history, ballet, philosophy, and biography. Perhaps Mr. Plunket has not previously been privy to the reading material of an inquiring mind with such cultural refinement.
Donna Heuman
Menlo Park, California<p>
DATE CHANGE
The Navellier Performance Funds placed an advertisement in the September issue of your magazine. Because of a typographical error, the dates in the ad were incorrect. The correct dates should be from December 29, 1995 (inception), to May 31, 1996. We apologize for any inconvenience.
Arjen Kuyper
Operations Manager
Navellier Funds
Reno, Nevada<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
