	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Gotta Serve Somebody</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Gotta Serve Somebody</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						For personal-services firms, your chores are their business<p>
By Anne Field<p>
The most sought-after commodity these days isn't gold or pork bellies: It's time. Indeed, the average American's work year has increased by 163 hours over the past two decades, or the equivalent of one month, says Juliet Schor, author of the modern exhaustion classic The Overworked American. And the pace never lets up.<p>
That's where personal-services people come in. For $15 to $150 an hour and up, they take care of those time-consuming, irritating chores: registering the car, walking the dog, waiting for the cable guy. All the stuff Mom used to do -- only now she's out of the house, in the office, churning out buy-sell orders. "Everyone needs a wife," says Molly Hanford, who runs More Than Just Errands, a personal-services firm in Philadelphia. Here are some of the services these folks provide:<p>
Handling mundane essentials. For $20 to $60 an hour, firms like More Than Just Errands, Work! in San Francisco, and TimeSavers in nearby Mill Valley will do just about anything that's legal. Jessica Van Lieschout, an interior designer who divides her time between Aspen, Colorado, and Marin County, California, uses TimeSavers two to three times a week to drop off dry cleaning, mail packages at the post office, walk the dog, do xeroxing, make raspberry jam for fund-raisers -- whatever she needs. Another client paid TimeSavers co-owner Kim Carbone $150 to shop for and buy an anniversary present for his wife. Carbone bought a $4,000 pair of diamond studs -- and the wife was none the wiser.<p>
Dealing with red tape. Renewing a car registration and getting a passport are the banes of a time-deprived person's existence. When Geoff Lewis, a magazine editor in New York, let his car registration expire, he ignored the problem as long as he could. But a half day before his vacation, he knew he couldn't put it off any longer. So he paid It's Easy in New York $20 to do the job for him. If he'd needed to pay a moving-violation fine, It's Easy could have taken care of that, too. In Washington, D.C., Travel Document Systems helps people obtain passports and visas for $40, or $60 for a rush job.<p>
ber-cleaning. Rent-a-Mom in Reston, Virginia, doesn't just clean. For a minimum of $60, its "moms" will also organize drawers and closets. TimeSavers will reorganize an entire house, setting up filing and bill-payment systems, cleaning out closets, and coming in regularly to maintain the setup.<p>
Buying your wardrobe. For a $255 annual fee, Susan Dresner of Successful Ways & Means in New York will take inventory of a client's closet, then choose stores that sell garb most suited to that person's body and lifestyle. For an extra $95 an hour, she'll do a pre-shop, carefully selecting an array of attire for the customer to choose from when he or she gets to the store.<p>
Moving. Some firms take care of the entire awful job for you -- working with architects and contractors to help prepare your new home, then packing and unpacking your stuff and supervising the move. For the ultimate in pampering, the Intrepid New Yorker in New York will find you the right neighborhood, house, schools, and nanny, as well as chimney sweeps and brass polishers, then oversee the whole project from beginning to end. Cost: $2,000 and up.<p>
Because hiring strangers to take care of intimate details can be unnerving,  you want to make sure to use a place that's on the up-and-up. Always ask for references. As important is longevity: Chances are, a long-lived firm has been around partly because it's reputable. Also find out if the company is insured, and ask to sign a contract. The toughest part of the whole deal is finding a firm in your area. If you call a place that doesn't do quite what you need, ask for suggestions. Most companies will be glad to help: Personal service, after all, is what they're all about.<p>
Service Calls<p>
The Intrepid New Yorker,  212-534-5071
It's Easy in New York,  212-586-8880
More Than Just Errands,  215-564-2727 
Rent-a-Mom,  703-437-8571 
Successful Ways & Means,  212-877-1417 
TimeSavers,  415-388-6338
Travel Document Systems,  800-874-5100 
Work!  415-255-2325

					</font>
