<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-A Foliage Portfolio</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-A Foliage Portfolio</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
A myriad of ways to see the leaves before they leave<p>By Rudy Maxa<p>In the northeastern and mid-Atlantic states, the hills are about to be alive with dead leaves. Which means prime touring season for fall-foliage lovers. But how do you know where to go? When are the colors at their most spectacular?<p>In the last couple of years, some state tourism offices have begun offering toll-free phone numbers with recordings that detail autumn's progress. North Carolina visitors can receive updated color reports by calling 800-VISIT-NC; Massachusetts has a toll-free number for foliage updates in the Northeast (800-632-8038). If you really want to get particular, call the forest office in any state for on-site reports.<p>There are even more sources of information on -- you guessed it -- the World Wide Web. Not just leaf updates, but entire driving itineraries with precise directions as well as listings of sights, B and B's, and eateries along the way.<p>"Stop at Kilgore's General Store (Main Street; 802-326-4681), which makes its own breads and soups," advises a Web site called the All-Time Best Foliage Tour of Northwestern Vermont (http://www.newengland.com/itins/itin.vt.bestfoliage.html). The write-up even notes that service can be slow at Kilgore's, located in the town of Montgomery Center, but there's always J.R.'s, also on Main Street, known for its "standout sandwich of fried eggplant with garlic mayonnaise." For what the site calls "the last word in foliage panoramas," ride the Jay Peak aerial tramway just down Route 242 a piece. Or you can choose Route 58 and go through Hazen's Notch; Route 58 is a gravel road "through deep woods ablaze with the yellow foliage of birches."<p>Now that's detailed information. For basic driving tours of New England, check out the Web site at http://newengland.com. For some leaf gazing along the Mohawk Trail (Massachusetts Highway 2), click into http://www.freeways.com/fun/greatdrives/mohawk.html -- a site that claims the drive from Orange to Williamstown, Massachusetts, is one of the country's more scenic stretches of roadway in the fall. North Carolina updates its Web site (http://www.commerce.state.nc. us/commerceress/fall2.html) with precise information, such as last year's notation: "Sandhills Community College in Pinehurst reports that the dogwoods and Bradford pears are beginning to turn reddish-brown."<p>Late September and early October are prime viewing times in the Northeast. Prime time slips further into October, of course, the farther south you go. It's best to avoid weekends, when most sight-seeing takes place; on roads such as the Blue Ridge Parkway in North Carolina and Virginia, traffic can be bumper-to-bumper.<p>Want to avoid the crowded roads? Take to the sea. Several cruise lines offer fall-foliage tours, most of which begin in New York in September and make stops along the New England coast, then turn around in Canada. This year, for example, Holland America Line's Veendam offers five cruises, at a starting price of about $2,500 per person. But all five jaunts were sold out by early summer; the cruise line is accepting bookings for next fall (800-426-0327).<p>Regal Cruise Line's Regal Empress (800-270-7245) offers a single, 12-day foliage cruise out of New York; prices begin at $1,300 for an inside cabin ($1,800 for an outside cabin). The September 29 sailing was nearly sold out by early summer, so plan ahead for next year. Princess Cruises' Royal Princess (800-421-0522) has scheduled four ten-day East Coast foliage tours, but all are already sold out. The moral: If you want to admire the leaves from a deck chair, book early for future falls.<p>Land, water...that leaves the air. At some rural airports, pilots offer flight-seeing foliage tours -- just keep an eye peeled for signs advertising flights. It's probably the most breathtaking way to see the carpet of reds, golds, browns, and yellows that blankets the East Coast. And, as with cruises, you leave the driving to someone else.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

