<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-The Art of Propaganda</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-The Art of Propaganda</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						A poster can be an investment of historic proportions<p>By Anne Field<p>It's a safe bet that when James Montgomery Flagg designed his poster "Wake Up, America!" in 1917, he wasn't thinking of creating an investing opportunity. The immediate goal of his work, printed at the behest of the Mayor's Council of New York City, was to warn Americans about the perils of staying neutral in World War I. And this would be no one-of-a-kind work of art; the posters were put up all over the city. Today, a copy of "Wake Up, America!" costs as much as $7,000. <p>Other propaganda posters provide a similarly dramatic window into 
history, at more affordable prices. Russian posters from the early Soviet era start as low as $200 and run up to $40,000 or, occasionally, more. World War I and II posters rarely cost more than $7,000 and often go for as little as $150 to $300. And experts feel these prices have plenty of room to grow.<p>What makes one work more valuable than another? Many of these posters' creators were well-known painters and illustrators, ranging from Gibson Girls originator Charles Dana Gibson, who headed the quaintly titled U.S. Division of Pictorial Publicity during World War I, to Russian graphic artist El Lissitzky. But the lack of a designer name doesn't mean lack of value: A poster for Oktober, a 1927 movie marking the tenth anniversary of the Russian Revolution, was recently offered for $22,000, despite the anonymity of its creator.<p>That's because other factors are important as well, not the least being the condition of the piece. Since posters weren't meant to have a long life, they tend to age poorly and so are usually graded to indicate what kind of shape they're in. Generally, you'll see either 
a letter, from A+ on down to D, or specific words, from mint to poor. (World War I items often get top marks because many people at the time, expecting the war to be the one to end all wars, tried to preserve their posters by keeping them under their beds.) Another ingredient that lifts prices is scarcity. Finally, works produced through the older technique of lithography tend to be more valuable than newer, photo-offset posters. With lithography, the artwork is drawn with a grease pencil directly on a sheet of limestone, then inked and pressed on paper, producing colors that are especially luminous.<p>Bolshevik Bravura. While the common image of Soviet propaganda is a larger-than-life Lenin staring ahead with a piercing gaze, those posters are typical of a later era. More fascinating artwork was produced in an earlier period -- 1917 to 1937, when artists were allowed to engage in a startling amount of experimentation. That innovation continued until the late 1930s, when Joseph Stalin clamped down on anything smacking of the avant-garde and mandated social realism as the only suitable style for all official propaganda.
Some major names participated in Soviet poster art, and their work tends to be the most desirable. Works by El Lissitzky, which have gone for as much as $100,000, are the top of the market for now. A 1930 poster by photomontage artist Gustav Klutsis recently sold for $36,000; even one of his postcards carries a price tag of $1,000 or so. Then there are the "ROSTA windows" -- hand-stenciled sections of daily bulletins posted in shop windows by the Russian Telegraph Agency during and just after the 191820 civil war. You can't get one window for less than $2,000, and they usually come in sets 
of at least four. A group of six by Malyutin recently sold for $11,000. <p>But many posters are much cheaper; anonymous pieces from the Russian civil war might cost $200 to $500. Though they often depict scenes of violence -- they were meant to mobilize the country against invaders and so-called White Russians, who fought the Bolsheviks in the revolution -- they can be almost hypnotic in their urgency and drama. These posters just started to reach the West under perestroika. Since then, museums have been snapping them up like crazy, and no one knows when the next crop of goodies will be unearthed. As a result, prices have doubled or even tripled over the past five years. "The supply is here now, so now is the time to buy," says collector and dealer Jim Lapides, owner of the International Poster Gallery in Boston.<p>Military Manipulation. Posters of World Wars I and II are considerably less rare -- and easier to collect. Every major fighting power issued its own propaganda, urging men to enlist and citizens to buy war bonds, conserve their resources, and keep their mouths shut. The rarest U.S. pieces are recruiting posters, many of which were designed by well-known artists. Much more common are those that hawk bonds: They were printed in huge quantities and posted everywhere, from banks to stores and post oces. <p>The costlier World War posters tend to be the work of high-caliber artists and illustrators like Flagg, who used his own face as Uncle Sam's in his famous "I Want You" recruiting poster. German works are more expensive; Nazi posters are practically nonexistent, since most were destroyed in bombing raids or by German citizens fearing the ire of Allied occupiers. German World War I posters are almost as scarce but of a particularly high artistic quality. Hans Rudi Erdt's rare "The U-Boats Are Out" sells for around $10,000; posters by German master Ludwig Hohlwein can go as high as $15,000.<p>Lots of World War posters are dirt cheap, however, and many cost less than $1,000. Norman Rockwell's ubiquitous "Four Freedoms" posters cost about $200 apiece. Anti-espionage posters (for example, Cecil Beall's picture of two workers sharing secrets at a bar while an image of Hitler eavesdrops in the background) go for $250 to $300. And the investment outlook for posters in this group is positive. "In 20 years it will be the 100th anniversary of World War I; there was a spike in prices for World War II posters during the 50th-anniversary celebrations," says Tony Fusco, president of Fusco & Four, a Boston marketing consultant specializing in art. "If you want to put away something for retirement, put away your World War posters."<p>Propaganda Pitfalls. The biggest trap for the beginner is the little matter of spotting a fake. Of course, you want something from the original poster run, not a reproduction, which is hard to discern with photo-offset stuff. But a reputable dealer knows the telltale signs. The type of paper or ink, the shades of colors, even the size of the paper can send off warning signals. As with any collectible, you have to read up on the subject. Attend some shows; the International Poster Show appears every year in New York, Chicago, and San Francisco. Informative books on the subject include The Bolshevik Poster (Yale University Press) and Persuasive Images: Posters of War and Revolution From the Hoover Archives (Princeton University Press). Fusco also suggests you go to at least five auctions before attempting any real bidding. "Auctions don't guarantee the authenticity of their goods," he says. So be sure of your eye before you plunk your money down. <p>Finally, more than many collectibles, posters require a big commitment -- and a very personal one. An image of a Russian peasant, blood dripping from his hands as he fights his enemy, may not be the first thing you want to see when you wake up in the morning. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
