	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Secret Millionaires in the Kitchen</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Secret Millionaires in the Kitchen</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Inside an oven mitt the hand of genius sweats<p>The rich may be different from the rest of us, but they don't 
necessarily stand out in a crowd. In fact, since there are more than two million millionaires in this country, it's a sure bet most of 
them are anonymous to most of us -- the man shaking sand out of his towel at the beach, the woman in front of you at the ATM. The same might be said for the objects in our lives: Products, tools, and ingredients surround us unnoticed, yet a lot of them have made someone a lot of money. Take the humble kitchen. Fortunes have been made there by men and women who came up with good ideas and followed through. Now they're basking in the sun, if not in the glow of fame.<p>
BEADED ANTIQUE FLATWARE 
Towle Silversmiths<p>With 41 percent of the flatware market in his grasp, LENNY FLORENCE is the silverware king, and he ascended that throne in classic rags-to-riches fashion. As a child, he says, "I knew what I was going to wear one year because my brothers wore it the last." His first break came in high school, while he was working at a jewelry store. A customer was so impressed with Florence that he paid for his education. After graduation, the man promised Florence 50 percent of Raimond Silver if he could lead it out of debt; Florence did, making more than $1 million for himself. He then built a company that copied the designs of expensive silverware and merged it with Towle Manufacturing. Florence says he has met six of the last seven U.S. presidents, been honored by the Vatican, and built 
a home for retarded children in Israel.<p>
ENAMEL-ON-STEEL COOKWARE
Chantal Cookware<p>Martha Stewart with a German accent. That's HEIDA THURLOW -- mechanical engineer from Dsseldorf, former devoted homemaker, now businesswoman with more than $10 million in annual sales. Thurlow's parents wanted her to take over the family's steel-
furnace-linings business, but she moved to Houston in 1969 and married a steel-importing compatriot instead. To make him happy she took up cooking, but when she couldn't find the right cookware -- "There were no fun colors, no lids I could see through," she says -- Thurlow designed and produced her own enamel pots and pans. Now divorced, she skis in Park City, Utah, where she has a second home, and dives in the Cayman Islands.<p>
ZAK ZANY ZOO ANIMAL OVEN MITTS 
Zak Designs<p>IRV ZAKHEIM was in his 20s when he gave up his dream of playing professional baseball, but he quickly found the hot hand in another field: sales. First he sold life insurance and puka-shell necklaces in Hawaii; next came embroidered pot holders. His winning pitch, however, was Zak Zany Zoo Animal Oven Mitts. More than ten million have been sold in the last dozen years, grabbing 75 percent of the specialty oven-mitt market and netting him a rambling old Victorian home in Spokane and a vacation home on Deer Lake in northeastern Washington. While the oven mitts are still hot, Zakheim's main business these days is licensed children's dinnerware. Think Toy Story plates.<p>
GOOD GRIPS UTENSILS 
Oxo International<p>SAM FARBER, who already had a modest fortune from his own kitchen-supply company, was enjoying splitting his retirement between southern France and the Berkshires in western Massachusetts when another business idea took hold. Moved by his wife's arthritic struggles with kitchen gadgets, he wondered why there were no easy-to-use tools. He came up with a line of utensils called Good Grips, which were an instant success. He sold this company, Oxo International, less than three years after starting it for $6.25 million. Though still involved in day-to-day affairs at Oxo, Farber swears that he's retired now. He dedicates his time to the Outsider art -- created by untrained and often institutionalized men and women -- that he collects, writes about, and promotes.<p>
EXCALIBUR NONSTICK COATING
Whitford<p>Maybe Wharton graduate DAVE WILLIS had no choice but to go into business for himself. Says Willis, "My father, who has his own oil business, always used to say to me, 'When you start your own business...' I was never sure, but when I got fired from my first job, it was the obvious next step." He and a friend started a 
chemical company; when they sold it a few years later, Willis received $792,000 and ownership of a dry, talcum-like lubricant, polytetrafluoroethylene. "I wasn't poor," says Willis, who was then 34, "but I had four kids. I had to work." Willis and his partner created Whitford and produced nonstick coatings. Kitchen uses now account for 60 percent of Whitford's business; its materials are incorporated into such cookware lines as All-Clad, Cuisinart, and Chantal (yes, Willis knows Heida Thurlow -- in fact, he knows her number by heart). <p>
VIKING MODEL VDSC 305 SS
Viking Range<p>FRED CARL was once what he calls a "fifth-generation builder." Among other things, he customized kitchens in the homes of the wealthy. Then, in the mid-1980s, when he was renovating his own kitchen, he designed the Viking Range. Although Carl does well by 
continuing to target the wealthy -- purchases by such folks as Tom Cruise, T. Boone Pickens Jr., and Martha Stewart, among others, help him top $20 million in annual sales -- his comfortable life hasn't changed much. "I hang around the house, play a little golf, read, draw, sketch," says Carl, who has spent his entire life on the same block in Greenwood, Mississippi. What has changed is Carl's stock portfolio: 
"I feel very good about my son's long-term future," he says.<p>
BUTTERFLY BOWL 
Namb Mills<p>The folks at Namb Mills want you to believe that PAULINE CABLE got the recipe for the secret Namb alloy from a Los Alamos physicist working on the Manhattan Project. Cable denies it: "There's no truth in it at all whatsoever." Her ex-husband did work at Los Alamos, but as an accountant. The Cables had been newspaper 
reporters in Dayton, Ohio, before moving to Santa Fe in 1941. In 1953, she took over a small sand-casting foundry in Namb, New Mexico, where she concentrated on making bowls from the Namb alloy, which conducts both heat and cold especially well. The first year, Cable had $2,500 in sales; she reached close to $1 million in annual sales by 1982, when she sold the company to the Hillenbrand family of Indiana. She has since retired to Tucson.<p>
GINSU KNIVES
Ginsu Consumer Products<p>"We amazed all of America with the Ginsu knife," says BARRY 
BECHER, who with his partner, ED VALENTI, helped revolutionize gizmo marketing -- with an already existing product, no less (the knives came wholesale from Quikut, an Ohio cutler). Lore has it that the knife got its name from the combined names of the partners' wives. Valenti dismisses the myth: Neither he nor Becher has been married to a Ginny or a Sue. "We wanted something Asian and exotic," says Valenti. "In English, Ginsu means never having to work another day in your life." In other words, that's what selling first a million knives at $9.99 apiece and then over two million at $19.99 means. Though Valenti and Becher sold their company in 1984, the knife hasn't lost its edge. Ginsu Consumer Products is now owned by Warren Buffett's <a name="NYSE:BRK.A"></a><b>Berkshire Hathaway</b>.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
