<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-No Contest</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-No Contest</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						How to ensure that your will be done<p>By Alexander Bove Jr.<p>Few legal battles generate more bitterness than a will contest. Children are pitted against parents, brothers against sisters, and for what? Money, that's what. Some claim it's a matter of principle, but the rule is, the larger the estate, the higher the principle.<p>It's hard to make a will that's entirely contest-proof, but that doesn't mean you should worry about losing a contest. A study by the American Bar Association found that more than 99 percent of all will contests are unsuccessful.<p>Nevertheless, many people lose sleep over the possibility that their estates will be contested, and for those people, there are a couple of options. One is a no-contest provision, which penalizes a contesting beneficiary by causing a forfeiture of that person's bequest. But for this approach to be successful, you must give that person something worth losing. "A no-contest clause in your will does not mean that a contest is prohibited," says William Zabel, an estate lawyer in New York City and author of The Rich Die Richer and You Can Too. "It merely means the contestant will lose his share if he attempts to interfere with the probate of the will."<p>Another common strategy is to place your property into a living trust rather than distribute it through a will. You can maintain control of the assets in your living trust as the trustee. On your death, a successor trustee would automatically take over and distribute the assets as you have directed. The advantage of a living trust is that the assets avoid probate and so are not subject to a will contest. And although a disgruntled heir could try to break the trust, the contestant would face considerable legal fees, and the odds of succeeding are even slimmer than the odds of winning a contest.<p>Even without those safeguards, a will contest is an uphill battle for the contestant. For one thing, there are very few people legally able to mount a contest. Common will contestants include a spouse, a child or grandchild, or even more-distant relatives -- but it must be a person who would have a claim on the estate should the will be overturned. Less common but just as viable would be someone mentioned in a previous will but left out of the current one. People are often worried about a divorced spouse contesting a will, but an ex-spouse usually has no standing to make a contest. In addition, prenuptial contracts can contain an agreement that neither spouse will contest the other's will.<p>Should someone decide to contest your will, the most common claims are that the will was not properly signed; that the testator (the person who made the will) was not mentally competent at the time of signing; and/or that the testator was induced to sign the will through fraud or undue influence. A will can be contested only because of how it was completed, not on the basis of what it contains. And any of these problems can be obviated by a properly prepared and signed will.<p>Incompetence, for example, is difficult to prove, and the burden of proof is on the contestant. By themselves, eccentricities are generally not accepted as convincing evidence of incompetence, so leaving your estate to chickens or directing that your body be buried on the moon will not by itself disqualify your will. Fraud might occur when a person is persuaded to sign a document that she thinks is, say, a neighborhood petition, when, in fact, it is a will (it has happened). But if you know what you're signing, fraud, too, is difficult to prove.<p>So if you're concerned that shafting someone is going to incur a contest, don't fear: An heir's anger at how little he or she was left is not good grounds for a contest. When he died around the turn of the century, Harry Preston of Philadelphia left his wife, Anna, the absolute minimum allowable under Pennsylvania law -- a third of his estate. In doing so, Harry described her as a "fiend in human form," an "unnamable beast," and a "she devil," by whom Harry stood "in daily fear of being murdered while asleep." Which might well have happened if Anna had seen what he wrote about her in his will, but the harsh words were not grounds for a contest. Anna took her lumps -- and her third.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Estate Planning

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
