<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Last Tango in Tonga</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Last Tango in Tonga</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Millennium approaches, from Seattle to the South Seas<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Got plans for a night out three years from now? If not, you had better hurry, because faster than you can say "Alka-Seltzer," folks are making reservations for New Year's Eve 1999. Even the islands of Tonga will be booked -- as soon as someone builds the
hotel. Closer to home, New York's Rainbow Room blocked out 200 of its 1,000 spaces two years ago before it stopped taking reservations. It has a 600-person waiting list, though the $1,000 per head doesn't include bubbly. <p>Over at <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Walt Disney</b></a> World, Mickeyphiles are also shut out: The resort's hotels are already filled, even though no millennial events have been announced and no price has been set. At least the big-name entertainers -- Goofy, Donald, Pluto -- can't back out. You won't be quaffing Moet at the Seattle Space Needle, either. In 1991, a group of 12 families reserved all three of its levels for themselves and friends. <p>Many potentially world-class events still have room, but these tend to be of the pie-in-the-sky variety. Brad Roberts, a former tennis coach now operating a travel company called First Light 2000 in London, has leased a huge parcel of land on New Zealand's Chatham Islands, where he plans to offer millennium packages. "It's the first area to see the sunrise of 2000," says Roberts, who has a letter from London's Royal Greenwich Observatory echoing his claim. As for transportation and the islands' accommodations, he admits, "You've caught us with our trousers down." <p>Indeed. The largest place to stay on Chatham's ten islands has just 12 rooms. "We've had some inquiries about New Year's 1999," says Denise Sutherland, co-owner with her husband, John, of the Chatham Island Lodge. "I guess we have a lot of preparation to do." <p>Over on the islands of Tonga, 1,580 miles north of Chatham, the Eve of 2000 buzz is big. According to Simote Poulivaati, manager of the International Dateline Hotel on the island of Tongatapu, half of his 76 rooms have been booked by First Dawn Celebrations. Operated by Londoner Wayne Morris, First Dawn will fly you from Los Angeles to Tonga, where you'll greet 2000. Then it's off to Western Samoa, on the opposite side of the date line, to catch the millennial sunrise once again. The damage: just $10,000 to sing "Auld Lang Syne" twice during the six-day trip. Morris has room for 450 celebrants, and he hasn't started accepting reservations yet. The motto for this date-line hopper? "Be the first -- and the last."<p>Poulivaati says he's heard talk of "a Mike Tyson boxing event" and "a Billy Graham appearance" as possible crowd magnets. Also, a rumor that an American might build a 300-room, five-star hotel in early 1999 has spread throughout Tongatapu. So far, though, only one event is planned. "Our king will make an address and do something on the Internet," says Poulivaati. "We only hope he's still alive by then. He's in his 70s and weighs nearly 300 pounds." <p>Perhaps the best deal in the South Pacific can be had on the Tongan island of Vava'u, where retired Kentucky oilman Carter Johnson eagerly awaits the right inquiry. "Don't call about booking a room because I won't give you a price," says Johnson, owner of the 47-room Paradise Hotel. "But for $2.3 million, I'll sell you the whole spread. I'll even throw in my four-bedroom residence."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
