	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Soul of the Revolver</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Soul of the Revolver</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Soul of the Revolver</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> SOUL OF THE REVOLVER <p>Are you among the millions of financially comfortable people who carry big credit-card balances every month, paying crazy charges and wondering why you don't just cut it out? Steve Szekely, master of plastic, says he sympathizes. And approves.  <p> By Mike Steere  <p> Seven square inches of silvery plastic with the blue-white-and-gold emblem of Visa International -- here is mine own slain albatross. I didn't shoot it. I revolve it.  <p> Month after month I carry a credit-card balance that in almost two years hasn't gone up much or down much. Noisy self-recrimination, oaths to charge no more, to get to zero next month, in six months-- all that I've sworn and suffered has yet to bring down the balance. Becoming a "bad" -- credit-card talk for a defaulter-- isn't even an issue. I could zero the balance today by taking a bite out of cash savings, but I don't.  <p> I revolve for no logical reason.  <p> I revolve because I'm a revolver.  <p> Revolving taints the rest of my personal finances, which are disciplined and sound. It makes me feel ridiculous.  <p> No, it makes me feel sinful.   <p> It makes card issuers feel good. The sin of revolving, repeated in 50-million-plus American households, is the great redeemer for the banks and pseudo-banks that issue credit cards. About two-thirds of the country's 78 million creditworthy households revolve, according to Robert McKinley, president of RAM Research Group, an information clearinghouse that publishes bankcard news and statistics. Last year, bankcard revolvers paid about $56 billion in finance charges, providing 80 percent of issuers' revenues.  <p> Were we all to be born again as transactors -- zeroing our balances every month, paying no finance charges, but getting all the bank card goodies for free -- plastic, as we know it, would cease to exist. When nobody else is listening, credit-card professionals call transactors "deadbeats," because most transactors are unprofitable guests of the system, if they don't actually cost money.  <p> Nobody, however, is worried about a mass conversion to transacting. Indeed, leading issuers have chosen to live or die on finance charges. The current card-marketing free-for-all, which brokeout in 1992, could be called the War of the Revolver. With issuer slocked into no-fee, low-rate offers, there's no one else worth fighting for, because finance charges are virtually the only source of profit.  <p> Revolvers have always been the revenue-producing lords of plastic. In the 1990s, the revolver is God.  <p> In this credit-card cosmology, Steve Szekely is a holy man, a seeker, a guru. A consultant. A longtime industry analyst who is highly regarded for clarity of thought and expression, Szekely (say it zuh-Kelly) recently went independent. Before that, he spent 13 years with Payment Systems Inc., which is based in Tampa, Florida. First, he was PSI's eyes in Washington, gathering financial news in the capital. Then, he moved to Florida and spent eight years doing credit-card research using a national consumer panel. <p> It was his grand and inclusive view of the business that drew me to Szekely. An introductory phone call took in the Crusaders' sacking of Constantinople and Spain's pillaging of the Incas-- both the Crusaders and the Spanish court got in over their heads to bankers, Szekely says. His larger point is that, yes, there's been a lot of loan-related suffering, a lot of evil. But it has involved the huge institutional debts of governments and businesses and people so powerful that they're really governments and businesses. Personal credit -- e.g., Mr. Regular's Pittsburgh Steelers co-branded Visa -- didn't do it. So don't expect Szekely to approach consumer debt as a dark force in the republic.  <p> Szekely is aggrieved by the moralizing tone in most press reports about credit cards. Plastic-bankrupts-nice-folks horror stories-- which are flacked by consumer groups and dutifully featurized by broadcasters and in newspaper lifestyle sections -- get on his nerves. The notion of the victim cardholder, he says, insults consumers, the vast majority of whom don't get into trouble. Current loss rates, pushing 5 percent, are generated by only about 2 percent of cardholders.  <p> Szekely is irked, too, by the gloom and doom that often pervades business reporting. A New York Times headline: a shaky house of plastic with no quick fix in sight. From "Debt Be Not Proud" in The Chicago Tribune's "Your Money" section: "Plastic is the culprit that could wind up hurting the economy."  <p> Card debt has climbed, along with delinquencies and write-offs. Issuers and debtors may well get pinched if there's economic trouble, as they did in the last recession. But Szekely and other debt watchers insist that the numbers don't point toward a looming national crisis. Card-industry profitability slumped a bit in1995, but cards still outperformed the rest of banking by almost two to one. When you consider that issuers did this well while fighting a price war, which brought interest rates to historic lows, the atmosphere of panic seems strange.  <p> "If you don't like something, it's easy to talk about Armageddon, apocalypse," Szekely says. Disapproval, informed by folk morality that stigmatizes personal debt, is the real story behind the stories, which say more or less the same thing: Plastic is apact with the devil, for which we will pay terrible prices. Szekely says that the last time he looked Americans spent about as much on bankcard fees and finance charges as on tobacco. But nobody, so far, has died of revolving.  <p> "Are credit cards evil?" He is asking so he can answer. "To the extent that meeting wishes and needs is evil, to the extent that somebody should not have gratification.... I believe that people should have the discretion to buy what they want to buy when they want to buy it, assuming they can afford it. But my definition of being able to afford has a future component to it!"  <p> Yow, one-man bankcard opera. I fly to Tampa to take a front-row seat.  <p> In a collarless short-sleeved shirt, Szekely gives off a living-in-Florida-and-loving-it glow. He's enviably trim for a guy in his late 40s. Male-pattern hair loss sharpens a downward-pointing wedge of black hair over a face that comes to a Magyar-Italian ethnic edge. The face is a Lugosi update.  <p> We're having an early matinee, poolside at his house, and the topic is basic numbers. Profitable life for an issuer begin sat about $100 per card per year, Szekely says. A bankcard account in active use that generates less revenue is a wash, if not a loss.  <p> Time was, nonperformers paid their way, or most of it, with yearly fees. But on a no-fee account (roughly two-thirds are now no-fee, according to Szekely), revenue comes in but two ways: through interchange -- the issuer's cut of the charges paid by merchants for transaction processing -- and through the finance charges paid on month-to-month balances.  <p> The first (transactor money) averages about 1.25 percent of purchases. The second (revolver money) is annual interest, which averages about 18 percent for bankcards, according to RAM Research-- shockingly higher than the current barrage of low-rate offers. <p> The magic $100 in revenue, says Szekely, comes with about $8,000 to $10,000 transacted per year. The rough threshold for a revolver, though, is just $1,000 carried from month to month. The numbers say that bankcards recapitulate Aesop: Low, slow revolvers beat all but the fastest transactor hares. A few specialized issuers bet on the hare and win, but this is a small niche of the market. American Express, the biggest transactor player, has roughly a tenth as many cards in force as Visa (26.7 million versus 238.9 million; MasterCard has 149.4 million cards in force and Discover 44 million).  <p> Since most cardholders revolve, and since the national average for balances on active accounts is about $2,000, prospering with bank cards looks like a no-brainer. When average is profitable, who needs a consultant?  <p> It's not that simple, says Szekely. Aggregate numbers don't point to the best customers. "All the action," he says, "is at one end."  <p> Szekely cleaves revolvers into low enders and high enders, based on income and financial exposure. Low enders borrow on plastic because circumstances force them to. These revolvers are bad news: Real need scares the hell out of those who extend unsecured credit. Here lurk too many $300 balances paid down in minimum monthly installments from struggling low-income cardholders.  <p> High-end bads are even worse -- just as risky and more expensive. Ah, but the high enders who pay up. "They spend lots of money over an extended period of time and take an even longer time to pay it back," Szekely says. "But they do so dutifully. That's the holy grail."  <p> Szekely's high types borrow on their cards for reasons that don't necessarily make sense. The driving force is gotta, not necessity. Gotta have the Jerry Garcia tie I saw on lunch hour,Windows 95, a custom bicycle instead of a factory-built one. Some are doing reasoned pre-spending against a raise or bonus. Others are temporarily cash pinched but still honoring their gottas. Whatever the stress, it isn't financially life threatening. The best of the best are high earners, the better to shoulder a big balance without feeling it. If the rich are A students, Szekely's highs get Bs. Their income is in the 60th to 90th percentile. <p> Szekely says there are five million to ten million individual account holders in this bright, gold-bearing vein in the U.S. mountain of plastic. They're the only customers worth having. They're why issuers have dropped fees and, more crucially, driven interest rates to historic lows, while burying us in billions of direct-mail solicitations.  <p> After Szekely makes a few broad verbal strokes, I can picture his high enders. Some of them live in my building. I go out to eat with others. Good Lord, I am one of them. They (we) can't possibly be hard to find and target.  <p> Wrong, says Szekely. "They're an elusive animal."  <p> We start another open-air session with bankcard tarot. Mulling the questions of the hour -- Who is this perfect revolver? How do you get him or her on your mailing list? -- Szekely studies Visa, MasterCard, <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Amex</b></a>, and Discover cards, with his and mine on the table. We took them out as an aid to concentration. Looking at my worn and much-revolved Visa, he shows a slice of teeth and chuckles.  <p> Szekely and other card gurus can rattle off the parameters of revolverhood. The young, the recently relocated, those who earnless money than their neighbors, Szekely says. K. Shelly Porges, a Northern California marketing consultant and former marketing executive for both American Express and Bank of America, says that credit-phobic Chinese-Americans are the slimmest ethnic pickings. But other ethnic and minority groups tend to be above-average revolvers. Physicians, notoriously bad at financial management, are an exception to the rule that the affluent don't revolve. John Almash, formerly a senior vice president at MasterCard and now a researcher and consultant in Ossining, New York, would rather meet a revolver than a transactor on a blind dinner date. "Maybe a revolver would be more fun," he says.  <p> This stuff is great entertainment, but Szekely says such indicators fail as targeting vectors. Revolving turns on the "who" rather than the "what," and marketers' data bases can be remarkably blind to "who." Demographics such as zip code, income level, gender, and age do great things for some sellers, but not for card issuers. Demographically speaking, Mr. and Mrs. Revolver look like everybody else.  <p> Issuers have taken to using new kinds of data crunching from credit bureaus. Szekely says that the bureaus, which have long helped creditors stay away from bads, are privy to information-- such as number of bankcard accounts and size of balances --that may open a window on current and past revolving. Using this information and newly devised formulas, bureaus score consumers on probable revenue generation.  <p> The fact that issuers go to the same data wells to try to avoid write-offs and to target revenue producers says something important about revolvers. As Porges puts it, "The difference between a very good customer and a very bad customer is very little." Potential bads and ideal high enders, both big-balance carriers, can be indistinguishable, especially from the stratospheric altitude of mass-card marketers. Rewards and risks are found in the sameplace, and they're hard to separate. In aggressively managed account rolls, like those of plastic's growth leaders, profits and write-offs rise and fall in sync.  <p> There are hints abroad of new, potent statistical models that pull responsible revolvers out of the great gray mass of everybody, while purging Ma and Pa Bad. These techniques process credit history and such factors as magazine subscriptions and auto-brand ownership, using fuzzy logic, neural nets, and other arcane computer tricks. In a wonderfully patronizing don't-try-this-at-home quote to The New York Times, Richard Greenawalt, president of a company called <a name="NASD:ADVNA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12489"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Advanta</b></a>, warned lesser issuers away from his firm's level of techno-wizardry. "Some people will get hurt," he said. "There are thousands of details in what we do that are hard to copy. "Other growth leaders associated with advanced cyber-marketing,such as <a name="NYSE:COF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42309"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Capital One</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:FUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15687"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First USA</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:KRB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12449"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MBNA</b></a>, are silent on the subject, like the navy guarding the whereabouts of nuclear subs.  <p> Identifying the revolver -- the better to mail him or her Visa and MasterCard offers -- is only part of the issuers' problem. At last count, according to RAM Research, there were about 430 million Visa, MasterCard, and Discover cards in force in the U.S., nearly two for every adult and child. As Szekely keeps pointing out, all this prolific plastic is not equal. Only about 300 million cards are actively used. High-balance revolvers have more than their share of cards -- five or more apiece, Szekelysays. Typically, two or more of the accounts get almost all of the profitable month-to-month balances, while others might be paid down every month and still others just sit there. The payload gets switched around, to an ever growing number of alternatives. Cardholders close almost 9 percent of card accounts annually. <p> So even if the data told issuers exactly what a primo revolver looked like, they'd have a hard time knowing where to find one. We have here a shell game played in bad light, fast, with a few hundred million shells, with constant additions and subtractions. The best guesses form the basis of mailing lists, which number in the millions on big, national promotions. Issuers blitzed the country with some 2.7 billion solicitations last year and got a response rate of less than 2 percent, according to Behavioral Analysis, an organization that monitors industry mailings.  <p> Calling this market "mature," as card folk are wont to, is euphemizing."Glutted" or "frantic" is more like it. But, as Szekely says, with the industry's earnings figures singing backup, there's still a lot of money to be made in plastic. The money is in revolvers.<p>  <p>Should I be flattered? Somebody is expending enormous effort, sending out billions of pieces of mail, on the off chance that somebody like me will say yes.   <p> Or furious? The issuers are betting against common sense and resolution, and they're winning.   <p> Szekely makes a great case for revolving as a perfectly reasonable and honorable financial-management choice. Say your joy in life is televised sports, and all that stands between you and heaven, embodied in a 48-inch TV with built-in stereo speakers, is the purchase price. Buy now on plastic, and gratification may well justify the finance charges. Just add the interest to the price and calculate. Is it worth it -- yes or no?  <p> Beautiful, Steve, but this TV buyer of yours is really a cross-dressing transactor. You said your own panel studies imply that revolvers generally don't weigh. They're surprised when they add up what they owe and what it's costing. They say they never meant to let the balances get so high. The whole revolver phenomenon, at the level of the golden high enders, is based on people who can't quite see what they're doing, doing things they neither need nor intend to do.  <p> It's clear now why issuers have a hard time picking revolvers out of the crowd. The bigger mystery is the inability of revolvers to see their own revolving. They -- we -- can't get a fix on the balances, the finance costs, the new charges that keep the balances from ever going down.  <p> Plastic blindness is more than a metaphor. Researchers have found that cardholders consistently and seriously low ball what they borrow and owe on bankcard accounts. Lawrence Ausubel, an economist at the University of Maryland, calls this "the under estimation hypothesis." His analyses show that bankcard holders admit to about $4 out of every $10 they owe on plastic. By contrast, they're 68 percent accurate on auto-loan balances. Somehow, dollars and cents are harder to see when you're looking through plastic. <p> Szekely has serious reservations about Ausubel's methodology, his reasoning, his results. But I'm running with the prof on this one. I am, after all, a revolver, and the Ausubel stuff has me ringing like a big brass gong. It also brings me to the ultimate question: Why do high-end revolvers -- the bank card industry's bottomless pot o' gold -- do it? By definition, they don't have to. They've got enough to purchase what they need, enough extra to save up for the shiny what-the-hecks and wouldn't-it-be-cools that they're now borrowing to buy. The finance charges might be painless, but they're a minus that could be a plus, helping to buy still more goodies. (Last year, mine would have paid for a round-trip to Paris.)  <p> At this point, Szekely and other pros back away. At first, the lack of engagement with the inner revolver seems surprising. But it makes sense. These people are professional trackers, readers of spoor, twigs, turned-over leaves. Understanding the quarry's motives might be helpful, but the signs that lead you to it count for more. Revolving might be psychological, but as Porges says,that doesn't mean psychology is the best way to find revolvers."Why" might not make a dime for the issuers who pay the cardheads. And the experts and their subject matter are at odds. The card pros want to get next to revolvers. Revolvers want to quit revolving. <p> I've never known a revolver who didn't want to, who didn't have a plan to, reach zero, once and for all, by a certain date. Most of them never make it. If they do, they usually don't stay zeroed for long. The impulse doesn't change. Nor does the low-level self-loathing. In my case, money is really the least of revolving's cost. The big one is the feeling.  <p> Ausubel seems to have the best explanation for the revolver's trap, his under estimation hypothesis. If you never know where you are in relation to zero, you'll have a very hard time getting to zero. In his recent paper "The Credit Card Market, Revisited," Ausubel hypothesizes about his hypothesis, speculating that card holders under report for the same reason other people under report arrests for drunken driving and filing for bankruptcy: because they're ashamed.  <p> If the professor is right -- and I'll bet this month's Visa charges he is -- shame itself is the revolver's shameful secret. This might not be why revolving begins, but it's the reason it's so incredibly hard to end. There would probably be a lot less revolving if people weren't ashamed of it. Call something a sin, and people will do it sinfully. "It's like sex," says RAM Research's McKinley, trying to shine a little light into this strange zone of compulsion, guilt, and denial. More like solo sex, in that most people do it but can't stand to picture themselves doing it.  <p> Szekely acknowledges the power of shame in the revolver's dilemma. All his personal-finance advice is about getting card use out of the soul and into broad daylight. Tune out all the neo-Puritan and Poor Richard hooey -- the anti-plastic knee jerk that drives Szekely wild -- and you can make reasoned decisions, item by item, dollar by dollar, about how to use bankcards. Revolving needn't be a bad deal at all if you look at it in advance, do the numbers, and decide to pay the price. But daylight also makes it easier to stop revolving. The shame-free revolver is a transactor waiting to happen.  <p> "Why not?"  <p> The cards are put away. Szekely is asking why I think I shouldn't revolve. Are the finance charges a problem? Is there any doubt I'm good for the amount owed? No and no again.   <p> "So what's wrong?" I'm exercising a choice, he declares, that is all mine to make. "No. Big. Deal."  <p> Szekely looses a word storm on the whole unjust, hypocritical world that would heap shame on me, my kind, and plastic.  <p> Cash on hand, Szekely insists, is an "artificial constraint." We soar from quotidian dollars and cents on the wings of bank cards, which also break the bonds of time. "You're dealing with disposition of assets," he says. "Your cash holdings are an asset. You have another asset -- your future earnings potential. You can leverage that by using credit cards." For as long as he's talking, buying with plastic -- revolving, if I so choose -- is like a healthy celebration of self and the spoils of a common people's revolution. For millennia, bankers have given the royal and wealthy personal credit lines, Szekely says. "Why shouldn't they do it for the consumer?"  <p> "I would never," he says, "claim that credit cards are exclusively responsible for our economic well-being." Then he does something darn close. "Gotta have the spending power!" Szekely crows. Visa, MasterCard, and Discover stuff the consumer economy's horn of plenty. If you want the goods and the wealth, you want the plastic. You want revolvers, too.  <p> Yes! For a wonderful moment, I own Florida itself, or at least the many parts of it where plastic passes for money. It's mine, because I and my kind paid for it.  <p> Glory be. I still owe on the damned Visa card. Maybe I'll die owing. But the shame and sin have been lifted. I'm a revolver, Steve, and I'm okay.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Banking Industry, Family Finance

