				<font size=5><b>Mending Wall</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Mending Wall</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> MENDING WALL <p>With age, it's the ageless that grows more real and more beautiful. A writer's encounter with New England's immortal stone walls.  <p> By Nelson Aldrich  <p> "I'll be building walls till the day I die," Barry Patch told me sometime ago.   <p> He leaned down, I remember, over the ruins of the old stonewall he was working on and plucked out a rock that looked like a bear's shoulder blade. On a freestanding drywall such as this,the stones have to fit as tight and smooth as nature or a three-pound hammer (no mortar) can make them. But they also have to slope inward as they go up, about one inch per foot for three or four feet on this particular wall.  <p> Mr. Patch pondered the stone for a moment and set it down in a gap. He turned it this way and that -- no go -- then tossed it into the wall's central core, where it fell, chu-unk, as snug as a chipmunk in its hole.  <p> I asked him how high he could go with a wall like that. "Half way to the stars," he said, "if I could make the base wide enough."A fine New England answer: the romance of the stars; the prudence of going (only) halfway.   <p> "When you buy meat, you buy bones," runs an old New England maxim. "When you buy land, you buy stones." Centuries ago, when the region's farmers began to clear their lands, some believed the devil had seeded the ground with rock -- to test their faith and their backs.   <p> If it was a test of faith, then the Yankees were not found wanting; an 1871 Department of Agriculture survey counted 20,505 miles of stone walls in Connecticut alone -- almost enough to circle the globe. All that hard-won order and beauty made an enduring monument to thrift, hard work, sobriety, and endurance -- the traits we Yankees take as romantic and like to think of as our own.   <p> My romance with walls began last summer, when my wife and I paid a visit to some friends who live down the road from our country place in Connecticut. We went to admire their new swimming pool; I stayed to admire the walls encircling it. I liked the roughness of it -- the sight reminded me of a line from Thoreau: "There is a soberness in a rough aspect [of a wall] which addresses a depth in us."   <p> My depths, however, were to prove anything but sober on the subject.  <p> The stonemason, a big, handsome man named Jim Frazer Jr., was still working around the pool. For the hell of it, I asked him to come along to our place and have a look at a tumble down 300-footwall between the field in front of our house and an uphill stretch of driveway. "Let's see," he said, and strode off to walk the length of it. He returned looking solemn. "Eight thousand dollars,"he said.  <p> I studied the wall as it was, all scattered and for lorn under ropes of poison ivy and wild grape. Then I thought of the wall as it might be -- to visitors, a witness to our tender concern for the New England landscape; to us, gazing out from the house, a stroke of pictorial genius.   <p> In a bold stroke of contractor mind reading, Jim said, "This road, leading up into that lane of sugar maples up there, it reminds me of one of those watercolors my mother loves so much.I tell you what, don't pay me anything down. Pay me as you can, as we go along. I'd really like to do it for you."   <p> "So let's do it," I said. We shook hands, and then, passing under the sugar maples with walls on either side, he said, "You know, I have to warn you. You let me fix up that wall down there, and you're going to want me to fix them all."   <p> He was right. I'm rebuilding walls like a man possessed. There are probably two miles of them on our place, and we've made a good start on just about every one that you can see from the house. Besides the driveway wall, we've built a curved and terraced retaining wall around the patio, and another, simpler retaining wall by the ruins of the barn. There's a free standing wall to keep children from falling into what had been the milking room, now a badminton court, and a circular wall that once supported a silo. Then, too, there's the 50-foot  wall I need as a backdrop for our tea roses and grape arbor.   <p> Why am I doing this?   <p> Douglas Richardson, a stonemason in Salisbury, Connecticut, in the northwest corner of the state, tells me that weekend householder shave created a strong market for walls, new and rebuilt. "It is pure aesthetics," he says.  <p> Aesthetics it is for my wife, too. Stone, for her, is the perfect setting for the drama of her flower gardens. I'm not immune to the looks of the things, either. But I'm a New Englander, and stone walls are New England's archaeology, the stubborn evidence of a time, a place, and a people before now. Again and again, in winter especially, I'll be tooling along some highway, trying to ignore the Heritage malls and Pilgrim motels, when a darkline of stone cutting through the woods catches my eye, reminding me of the place as it was when some God-fearing Yankee heaved the stones out of the soil, laying claim to his New World home.  <p> Archaeology, someone once said, is a sentimental science. If so, perhaps wall building is a sentimental craft. Certainly for Barry Patch, the man whom Jim Frazer hired to build most of our walls, and for Frazer himself, there's a powerful romance in stones. The two grew up together and learned to work with stone by helping local farmers after school. Their favorite pastime, then and now, is to scavenge the countryside for Indian stone artifacts -- arrow heads, axes -- and there is stone in their Swamp Yankee drawl. It's in their movements, too -- watching them "stack stone," you might suppose they were playing a very deliberate game of chess.   <p> Douglas Richardson is another stone romantic. In 1988, he quithis job (and the ulcer that came with it) as a television-network executive to wrest a living from the craft he'd learned during his college years, apprenticed to Italian stone masons in Pennsylvania."There's something elemental about arranging rocks," he told me. "They're the world's first building material, after all. Brick walls and concrete walls -- anybody can build them who can use a level. But stone walls are different, beautiful. I've just finished the foundation of a barn. That's all -- a foundation.But a foundation is everything, isn't it? And breath taking to look at as well."   <p> Most of the derelict walls you see in New England were never as fine and beautiful as the ones Patch and Richardson build. The Yankees who put them up -- to keep livestock in, to divide pasture from cornfield -- weren't sloppy, though. Sometimes they went as far as digging three- or four-foot trenches, so the foundation would lay below the frost line, protected from heaving in spring. But by and large they made do with whatever rocks came to hand. Come March there'd be plenty of time to go out "mending wall," as the title of Robert Frost's poem has it.  <p> Barry Patch, on jobs like mine anyway, uses a good many of the old rocks in the wall he's rebuilding. Some are "trash," which he throws into the core of the wall; others are "building rocks"-- flat on the top or bottom, or squared off in some useful way. There are never enough of these, so he relies on Jim to truck in supplies of smooth-ish, flat capstones he can lay along the top of the wall, the "icing on the cake," as he puts it.   <p> Many wall builders believe the best rock for capping is schist mixed with mica, which splits clean and easy, while others prefer granite. Contractors buy stone from developers and farmers, excavators and big landowners, all of whom are happy to get rid of the stuff. To developers, walls are just old property lines, and farmers today are equally indifferent, with barbed wire to keep the cows in and their metes and bounds on file down at town hall. "Those old Yankees," Barry says, "they're mean bastards. You tell 'em you're looking for building rocks, and they say, Huh, huh. Shoulda been here ten years ago -- before we buried the damn things.Huh, huh!'"   <p> There's also a black market; in 1988, The New York Times reported that in Westchester County, just north of New York City, stones were being stolen from walls, reservoirs, roads, and even cemeteries. A few years ago, someone made off with a 15-foot section of one of our walls, and in the northwest corner of Connecticut, around Sharon and Kent, I've heard that clients are anxious enough about buying stolen rocks that they ask contractors for a bill of sale, to prove ownership of their new walls.  <p> Richardson says the different styles of walls you see in New England can be accounted for by the nature of the local rock, not by the ethnicity of the builders. "Italians own the reputation for building good, tight walls," he says, "but every culture in the world, including the old Yankee, had its own greatness in the craft."  <p> If there's a lot of mica schist in the ground, then you'll find walls that are as tight as a layered cake. If not, you'll find "farmers' walls with class," as Patch describes mine -- rough but not jagged, bonded through and through, and squared off along the top and at the ends. Always, though, the ancient recipe is the same: two stones over one, one stone over two.   <p> Am I being sentimental? Most of us want to know about one another's work. And with stonework, of course, at least for a banker, writer, or some other kind of "symbolic analyst," there's the knowledge that muscle goes into it, and some blood. Patch always stops talking when he picks over a pile of rocks; the work requires concentration and fantastic visual memory. He never wears gloves;he says it spoils his touch. Consequently, the dirt and the stonedust dry out his fingers so badly they look like a mud flat during a drought. "See there," he said one day, holding out a hand,"the cracks run so deep you can see right down to the red meat."He binds the fissures with masking tape.  <p> John Jerome, in his memoir Stone Work, writes that he moved from New York City to rural New Hampshire looking for a "more accurate alignment with the physical world." He found it, inpart, through building a wall. Slowly laying stone upon stone put him in "the present tense more effectively than pushing the button to close elevator doors."   <p> "It's hard to work with stones without working with time," says Christopher Hewat, a former mason, now a sculptor. Of course we all work with time and in it; trouble is, most of us work with what wall builders might call paper time. People do give up paper time for stone: Richardson did. But most of us can't; we can't let the money go, the buoyancy, the mobility, the view! <p> I can't. I've been bobbing along up there on paper time for too long. I remember complaining about this to Barry Patch one afternoon last April. "Don't worry," he joked. "You won't have to hang on much longer." It's true. I am 60, and my wife finds my passion for stone walls distressing. How much, she wonders,will they add to the value of the place? At 60, she feels, my interest in my two-year-old daughter's welfare should put a brake on my lust for mending wall. At my age, hearts don't just "go for it"; they might just go. I should get real, look at the bottom line.   <p> Perhaps so. But when I look at the "real" world of the investor,what I see is the uncertain, contingent, fluctuating market,whose bottom line has none of the virtues of an actual bottom: no stability, no both-feet-on-the-groundness.  <p> "Good fences make good neighbors" is something every New England schoolchild learns -- and also its negation, "Something there is that doesn't love a wall." No market forces hover over Robert Frost's walls; nothing threatens to vaporize their absolute value-- or, with it, the values of the community. There's only the tension between civilization and chaos, solitude and union --between stone walls and whatever it is that wants to tumble them down. Investment values, I tell my wife, are the enemy of all this. I don't want ownership; I want possession. I want reality as in "real property," mine and my family's. I want rootedness, historical connection, defiance of the randomness and brevity that underlies all human activity.   <p> Investment capital cares nothing about who or what possesses the things it's invested in. And to know this is to feel dispossessed.There was a moment a year ago when someone persuaded me that the casino-derived wealth of the Indians in the state was sending the price of property sky-high. Feverishly, right then and there,I decided to liquidate (sinister word) our place. The rumor proved untrue, and the investment value of our house slumped, followed instantly, in my market-distracted mind, by all its other values:the historical, the symbolic, the aesthetic. The dismal science had obliterated the sentimental one. I was just a bettor in a big casino, my piece of New England a chip.  <p> How are we supposed to love a place and its imagined future-- throwing money into stone walls, planting trees, building gardens -- when actually, decisively, it all belongs to the market? I can't. All I can do is banish the thought of what really owns my realty -- not least by building stone walls that some passer by may see centuries from now, cutting through the sere winter woods.  <p> And I'll build them myself. From now on, short though Barry Patch thinks my future may be, I will be spending some of its tacking stone -- standing with both feet on the ground, investing sweat and, if I'm sloppy, a little blood. It's bound to do my heart good as well.  <p>  <p>

					</font>
