		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Ready, Aim, Fire Back</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Ready, Aim, Fire Back</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> READY, AIM, FIRE BACK <p>So you go the ax. You don't have to get the shaft.  <p> By Dick Noel  <p> After 19 years with the same employer, I recently lived through every modern executive's nightmare: I was abruptly fired from my senior-level position. You, too, may be vulnerable and wondering,What should I do if they suddenly cut me loose?  <p> In spite of working without a written contract, I refused these verance offer, refused to resign, and refused to meet with the outplacement counselor. Five months after my termination, I forced a settlement that left me a happy, retired 53-year-old with a comfortable lifetime income and a healthy nest egg.  <p> What should you do if you're called in for that fateful interview? First of all, keep your emotions under control. Ask for a written list of the reasons for your termination, as well as the details of the proposed severance package -- severance pay, benefit coverage,etc. -- and a copy of your personnel file. Tell your superior you do not wish to meet with an outplacement counselor but will get back to him or her in a few days. Then pick up all the written materials and leave.  <p> Before you agree to anything, talk to a lawyer -- I hired a shrewd litigator with a reputation for toughness. In addition to the notes and written materials from your severance interview,the lawyer should look over the company's employee manual, performance evaluations, and any relevant correspondence from superiors, including notes regarding any promises. I had a recent Christmas card from the CEO of my company's holding company -- my boss's boss -- telling me what a great job I was doing. I also had 18 consecutive positive performance reviews -- followed by one negative review from the boss who eventually fired me.  <p> Have your attorney send a demand letter to your ex-employer,stating that you have no doubt a jury would conclude you have an implied contract that has been breached. If the company is interested in avoiding an unpleasant lawsuit, it'll probably respond by saying it has done nothing wrong but is willing to hear what you have to say. At this stage, any proposal acceptable to you will most likely be unacceptable to your employer, so submit a package that would make you more than happy. If your employer responds with something reasonable, you can settle quickly. More likely, you'll get an unacceptable take-it-or-leave-it counter proposal-- or, as in my case, a door slammed in your face.  <p> At that point, if your lawyer feels the case is strong, file suit for breach of implied contract and/or breach of good faith and fair dealing. Allow several weeks for the complaint to sink in. Then discuss with your lawyer the idea of a one-on-one conference with your superior's superior (the higher the better) to try to settle the case. If your attorney thinks you have the proper negotiating skills, he shouldn't stand in your way.  <p> If you use this approach, try to arrange a meeting at your home.I had my boss's boss come to my house, which relaxed me and put some emotional pressure on him. Take charge and present your terms -- sizable but not outrageous, leaving room to negotiate.You now have leverage you didn't have before: The complaint will soon become a public matter; senior company executives will be scheduled for depositions. Stay noncombative, stressing the benefits of settling: Both parties save on legal expenses, you save the strain on your family, and your employer avoids negative publicity,many lost employee hours in and out of court, and a possibly substantial jury verdict.  <p> Attorney Mike Brow of Burlington, Vermont, estimates that 70 to 90 percent of wrongful-discharge suits are settled before going to trial, and this is how my case ended -- decidedly in my favor. But don't think a jury trial can't also end well. Accordingto Jury Verdict Research of Horsham, Pennsylvania, plaintiffs win 70 percent of all discharge suits involving breach of contract and 64 percent involving lack of cause, with median judgments of $130,000 and $99,884, respectively. I've been in front of juries as defendant, plaintiff, and expert witness, as well as having served on a few, and the bottom line is this: Corporate giants get little sympathy.  <p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

