<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Driver Education</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Driver Education</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Driver Education</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> DRIVER EDUCATION <p>Golf schools where the classes are as fun as the homework  <p> By Rudy Maxa  <p> Giving Families the Business  <p> Is there a golfer alive who doesn't want to improve his or her game? No. Are there hundreds of golf schools that want to help those golfers? Yes. Can you expect the same level of instruction-- and the same level of fun -- at all of them? Absolutely not. <p> Some variables to consider: What's the student-to-teacher ratio?Four to one is good. How much golf will you actually play? Make sure a school isn't all lectures on theory and video tapes on form. And will you have fun? "So many of them have been realgulags," says James Dodson, an editor at Golf Magazine. "They used to be like a prison. You listened to talk about 'reverse pivot' and then hit balls until your hands bled."  <p> Here are a number of schools that promise something better: <p> Nicklaus/Flick Golf School (800-642-5528): Co-founded by Jack Nicklaus and Jim Flick, this school emphasizes developing a consistent swing. Schools are in Palm Beach County, Florida; Scottsdale,Arizona; Pebble Beach, California; Harbor Springs, Michigan;and Park City, Utah. The Florida and Arizona schools operate year-round except in the summer; the others run in the summer only. All offer nearby luxury-hotel packages. The Scottsdale Princess, for example, offers a Nicklaus/Flick deal startingat $3,195 per person for four nights, based on double occupancy.That includes just about everything but dinner.  <p> Pine Needles Lodge & Golf Club, Southern Pines, North Carolina(800-747-7272): A single-course resort, Pine Needles runs year-round three- and four-day seminars that boast a four-to-one student-teacher ratio for all levels of players. A four-day, three-night program that includes playing the course with your instructor costs $1,595(based on double occupancy) and covers all meals, lodging, instruction,greens and cart fees, taxes, and tips. Peggy Kirk Bell also teaches five-day "Golfaris" (short for golf safaris, though no wild animalsare involved) seven times a year: five for women only, one for couples, and one for kids.  <p> David Leadbetter Golf Academy (800-424-3542): The man famed for mending Nick Faldo's swing wants to do the same for you atone of his six schools in La Quinta, California; Bradenton, Lake Nona, and Naples, Florida; Chicago; and Alpharetta, Georgia.All are year-round except for the Chicago school, which is open from April through October. A three-day course at the Bradenton school, for example, costs $1,375.  <p> Dave Pelz Short Game School (800-833-7370): According to Pelz,the short game accounts for 70 percent of all shots. Hence his three-day programs -- at the Boca Raton Resort & Club in Florida(September to June) and the Ranch at PGA West in La Quinta, California(October to May) -- stress wedge shots and putting. Prices runfrom $1,775 (excluding lodging) to $3,200 (including lodgingand Pelz himself teaching theory).  <p> Golf Digest schools (800-243-6121): For the benefit of those who don't live near a golf mecca, these schools travel around the country to various resorts. Programs run from a half day to five days, with special programs available for women only,a short-game clinic, and a "playing school" with lessons on a golf course rather than at the range. A three-day course, including lodging, goes for $2,715 based on double occupancy.  <p> If attending a school sounds too intense, call the PGA at 407-624-8400:Your local PGA office can recommend pros who will work one-on-one for a reasonable fee. Heck, says Dodson, one of the greatest short players in the game, Paul Runyan, lives near Los Angeles and offers lessons for $100 an hour.  <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
