	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Clearer Than a Bell</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Clearer Than a Bell</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Clearer Than a Bell</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> CLEARER THAN A BELL <p>PCS phones are to cellular what compact discs are to records--so much better that they're the inevitable next generation  <p> By Aaron Rosenbaum  <p> Stuart Zuckerman, a principal of Zuckerman Brothers, a residential real-estate developer based in the Washington, D.C., area, doesn't have a traditional office. He coordinates his subcontractors by phone from job sites around the region. Zuckerman found cellular service inadequate because of its poor sound quality -- and frequent episodes of no service at all. Regular phone and beeper services were simply not convenient for him. So in January, Zuckermans witched to a personal-communications system called Sprint Spectrum. <p> "There's no comparison between the two," Zuckerman says. "This new technology eliminated nearly all of the problems that we had with our cell phone."  <p> American Personal Communications -- in partnership with <a name="NYSE:FON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11560"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sprint</b></a>, <a name="NASD:TCII"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14870"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TCI Cable</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:COX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43269"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cox Communications</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:CMCSK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13034"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Comcast</b></a> -- launched Sprint Spectrum's PCS service in the WashingtonBaltimore region last November, and the service is expected to be available in other major metropolitan areas across the country within a year or two. Unlike the cellular-phone system, which has two providers in each market, PCS will have three or more. While most PCS service providers remain coy about their launch dates, <a name="NASD:OMPT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47791"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Omnipoint Communications </b></a> in the greater New York area has announced it will begin operating its systems this year.  <p> As a digital device, the PCS phone is to a cell phone what CDs are to tapes and vinyl records. In addition to its superior sound quality, a PCS phone can receive and send wireless voice communications through walls and inside tunnels. The new system also duplicates state-of-the-art cell-phone features such as three-way calling,caller ID, call forwarding, call waiting, numeric messaging, and voice mail. Because the bandwidth is wider, more calls can be completed at once, so that at peak times common cellular problems with getting through are avoided. And while cellular calls can often be overheard by unwanted cell-phone users, eavesdropping on a PCS call is nearly impossible.  <p> Unlike cellular, there's no burdensome contract or activation fee. The mobile PCS phone units, now made by <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:NOK.A"></a><b>Nokia</b>,and <a name="NASD:ERICY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41776"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ericsson</b></a>, can be purchased off the shelf for $100 to $200,then programmed remotely with a call to a Sprint Spectrum number.And if you later buy a new PCS phone, you can keep the same number.<p>The monthly minimum operating cost is $15. For a heavy user such as Zuckerman, who uses his PCS phone about 15 hours a month, Sprint Spectrum offers 10 peak hours and 10 off-peak hours for$150 per month (with no contract). Cellular One, which requires a one-year contract, charges $169 for the same amount of time on its cell phone. For 30-minutes-per-month service, Sprint Spectrum charges about $25, as opposed to $29 for Cellular One, which further restricts its 30 minutes to off-peak hours. Additional peak minutes cost 31 cents from Sprint Spectrum, as opposed to 29 cents from Cellular One.  <p> At this point, the primary drawback to the PCS is that users can't place calls from outside their service area. This won't change until there is a nationwide network of regional systems in place, which would require all cellular and PCS providers to develop special roaming agreements covering all combinations of vendors. While the Federal Communications Commission may requirethe companies to offer these agreements, it hasn't happened yet.(PCS technology also causes some interference with hearing aids,which may pick up a pronounced buzzing sound from the digital signals.)   <p> In the meantime, there is sure to be increased competition among PCS providers. Four heavy hitters in the telephone industry (<a name="NYSE:BEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10197"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BellAtlantic</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:NYN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11044"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nynex</b></a>, U S West, and <a name="NYSE:ATI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16964"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Airtouch Communications</b></a>) formed a joint venture in 1994 called PCS PrimeCo, which was intended to compete in the PCS market. PCS PrimeCo has invested $1.1 billionin licensing fees and will be investing  almost $1 billion increating a nationwide network. It hopes to start up its service-- which will eventually cover 11 major cities -- by the endof this year, though there are rumors that the partnership has been troubled by internal squabbling, and there remains some doubt over when its product will reach the market.  <p> I tested the Sprint Spectrum PCS service in the Washington area for a month, comparing it to the local cellular service. The results were impressive. The sound quality is like that of a good cordless phone; most cell phones are a step below that. Although disconnection did happen occasionally, particularly on calls placed near the edge of the service area, there was always some warning, such as a slight warbling in the sound. <p> PCS phones are as small as the best  cell phones and provide more talk time on a single battery charge -- up to three times as much as a cellular phone running on an equivalent battery. The PCS phone can also act as a pager, because it's able to store voice mail and numeric messages from a caller even with the phone turned off or out of calling range. The system sends such messages through as soon as you reenter the service area.  <p> Until PCS technology becomes available across the country, it will be most useful to those heavy business users who don't travel much but seek better quality, standard messaging features, and longer battery life. The already reasonable prices are bound to drop even further as PCS and cellular battle for market share, but PCS's superior quality would seem to mark it as the wave of the future. Zuckerman, for one, is never going back.  <p>
KEYWORDS:Telecommunication Industry, Technology Industry<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

