	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Peter McMillan Takes A Flier</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Peter McMillan Takes A Flier</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Peter McMillan Takes A Flier</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> PETER McMILLAN TAKES A FLIER <p>The story of an ordinary institutional broker -- barely worth his million bucks a year -- who developed some extraordinary ideas about real risk and real reward  <p> By Donald Katz  <p> By the time of the late-autumn cocktail gathering at the Australian Embassy in Washington, D.C., Peter McMillan had grown used to public wonderment over the quixotic and crazily dangerous thing he had done. The aviator, 36 years old and still resembling some tousle-haired frat jock dressed up in a sport coat and gone slightly pious for a day, stood beside the Australian ambassador, his hands clasped behind his back. A crowd composed of air-force officials, National Geographic Society executives, third-world diplomats, and a collection of other local elites listened attentively as the ambassador, Don Russell, spoke about heroes and the power of dreams and of the bits and pieces of childhood that sometimes arise to carry people out and away from the general flow in ways that make others think they've lost their minds.   <p> It had been more than a year since McMillan checked out of the rarefied upper-middle tiers of a San Francisco financial-services establishment to spend every bit of the million dollars he'd saved -- and then some -- on a single-minded determination to build an airplane and fly it more than halfway around the world. As for the gatherings in his honor in cities here and abroad, they had less to do with the trip per se than with his decision to make it in a craft designed not long after the Wright brothers floated their winged motorbike off the ground at Kitty Hawk. <p> McMillan had, in fact, chosen to transfer a significant stock portfolio, his IRAs, all of his available credit, and just about every other dollar he could lay his hands on into a great parade float of an open-cockpit World War I bomber made out of cloth and wood and wire. McMillan's Vickers Vimy biplane, built from a 1918 design, usually flew at 75 miles per hour, often just a few hundred feet above the mountains and treetops. It was powered by a pair of 360-horsepower engines driving gigantic wooden propellers that tossed icy water and wind directly onto the young stockbroker's leather-helmeted head.  <p> For his part, McMillan couldn't have said if his former colleagues back in the trading room at Montgomery Securities regarded his repudiation of the faux warrior culture of the investment house and his weird rejection of a seven-figure yearly income as bemusing, threatening, or simply aberrant. McMillan was a guy who could have had it all in the world of money and yet somehow became confused about the applications and profitable rewards of risk. He'd blown it all in pursuit of some romantic revivification of a forgotten Australian flyboy named Smith -- that and a measly15 minutes out near the footlights that he would never be able to take to the bank.  <p> But the crowd gathered amid the Australian Embassy's blond-wood elegance did understand McMillan's will to adventure and reenactment. The guests stood before stunning aerial photographs of the Taj Mahal and the Sydney Opera House, shot from the gunner's perchin the nose of McMillan's plane. They gazed up at a single stretch of antique cloth stripped from the wing of the original Vimy biplane, in which two Australian pilots had made the first flight from an airstrip near London to Adelaide, Australia, in 1919.  <p> "We are here to consider the kinds of adventures we used to read about as kids," the ambassador said. "We gather to consider what is involved in going forward in the face of everyone around you saying that what you are doing is completely absurd."  <p> McMillan spoke later. "I think that the flight was a way to demonstrate to myself that while I might have been born into a time of wimps and paper shufflers," he observed in his slightly scratchy voice, "maybe I could be as good as people who weren't. Maybe I couldn't be truly heroic in the older sense, but I could at least try to do something that would allow me to know how real heroes felt."  <p>
Peter McMillan grew up in North Carolina, the son of a would-be aviator who became a doctor instead. His father took him to the Outer Banks to see Kitty Hawk and the Wright Brothers museum, and they would travel to the airport just to watch the planestake off and land. At night, Peter reads.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

