<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Ticket Masters</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Ticket Masters</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Ticket Masters</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> TICKET MASTERS <p>Good brokers want to be your friend. Don't be afraid.   <p> By Teri Karush  <p> If you think ticket brokers are just scalpers with 800 numbers, you're sort of right. Like scalpers, ticket brokers charge premiums that rise or fall in accordance with your desperation -- at least in the 41 states that don't regulate ticket resales. But unlike scalpers, brokers are legal and above board, and they're renewing efforts to present their operations as customer-friendly rather than shady. With a mix of caution and diligence, consumers can use brokers to get good seats at less than outrageous prices.  <p> Perhaps the best way to use a broker is to find a reputable agency and stick with it. Or even better, find two you trust and play one off the other. Brokers are more likely to negotiate fees with regular customers, who may also find more desirable seats passed their way. "Ultimately, ask your friends for a recommendation," says Lance Haver of the Consumers Education & Protective Association in Philadelphia. "The best information is always word of mouth. "For out-of-town tickets, choose a broker located near the event venue. That keeps the broker from having to buy the tickets through a middleman, whose fee would get tacked on to your purchase price.  <p> How can you tell a shady broker from a reputable one? One big warning sign: There's a phone number but no office where you can go to pick up your ticket. Too-good-to-be-true prices are another indication the tickets (and the broker) may not be legit. A legitimate broker will explain fees and cancellation policies without being asked and is available 365 days a year and through curtain time in case anything goes wrong. Make sure the broker is registered or licensed if either is required by the state.  <p> You can also call the National Association of Ticket Brokers to see if there have been any complaints against a particular agency. The NATB, located in Burlington, New Jersey, has a code of ethics and a complaint board that works with state officials to help resolve reselling problems. "A lot of brokers were scalpers as kids," says Barry Lefkowitz, the executive director of the NATB. "As they've grown up, we're seeing more and more legitimate small businesses evolving in the industry. Ticket brokers do for the entertainment consumer what stock brokers do for investors." <p> In most states, brokers can charge as much as the market will bear: For hot events, brokers commonly peddle tickets for three times or more their face value. Several states limit broker premiums to a certain percentage above face value -- although loopholes such as New York's "reasonable expenses" clause enable brokers to charge much more (anything over 32 percent is considered unreasonable). Louisiana, Michigan, and Minnesota permit resale for face value only. It pays to know how much brokers can legally charge in your state; if you need Broadway seats, for example, a New York agency is limited by the 32 percent rule, while agencies across the river in New Jersey can extract unlimited pounds of flesh. And any broker who skirts the resale limit is one to be avoided. <p> The nature of the business means that brokers deal in high-demand, high-priced tickets. "They are a luxury," says Lance Haver. "Be prepared to pay for a luxury."  For example, in February, the cheapest seat at July's Olympic opening ceremony in Atlanta --a $212 face value -- went for $1,000 if you called the right broker. That might not sound like such a bargain until you learn that another broker was asking $2,000.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

