		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Offspring Break</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Offspring Break</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Offspring Break</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> OFFSPRING BREAK <p>Kids deserve a vacation of their very own  <p> By Anne Field  <p> We like to think of a vacation with the kids as a series of idyllic <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kodak</b></a> moments. Fact is, it can also be so exhausting that you feel like you need another break when it's over. The good news is that more hotels, resorts, and cruises are offering affordable relief in the form of children's programs. Some are included in the base price, some are extra, but they're almost always a godsend for parents and kids alike. "They let you be a person, not just a parent,'' says Dorothy Jordon, author of Great Adventure Vacations With Your Kids (World Leisure), to be published in May. Here are some of the best.  <p> ADVENTURE TRIPS. Several of Abercrombie and Kent's family-oriented tours include organized children's programs. At the seven-day trip to the B Bar Ranch outside Yellowstone National Park in Montana, for example, children participate in their own ranch activities, including horseback riding, Western crafts, and an evening of singing songs around a campfire. A ten-day tour of Costa Rica provides supervised pool play and nature walks for children under six while parents and older kids raft in the Corobici River or go on other excursions. (800-323-7308; $1,935 for the B Bar Ranch trip; $1,750 for the Costa Rica tour.)  <p> Temptress Voyages' cruises in Belize and Costa Rica feature nature and hiking activities for children (4 through 17) when the Temptress ship is in port. Each evening, guides give kids a briefing about what they'll see the next day. On rainy days, kids may do anything from baking cookies to painting. They can also dine with their new friends from a separate kids' menu. (800-336-8423; six-night cruises per child are $895 for Costa Rica and $500 for Belize.)  <p> SKI RESORTS IN SUMMER. At Beaver Creek Resort's Matawin Teepee Village (Beaver Creek, Colorado), children aged 6 to 13 can campout over night in a tepee and engage in such Native Americaninspired activities as archery and arts and crafts. Kids over five can attend a day camp or take day trips involving hiking, horseback riding, fishing, and rafting. Toddlers and babies go to a junior version of the day camp. (970-949-5750; $45 to $65 a day.)  <p> The Targhee Institute at the Grand Targhee Resort (Alta, Wyoming) offers programs on various ecological themes. The "Earth, Air, Fire and Water" session teaches kids to identify local fossils, minerals, and edible plants; "Liquid Gold" covers water formation and related topics. There are also a day camp for kids three and up, and day care for kids aged two months and up. (800-targhee;$25 a day.)  <p> At the Resort at Squaw Creek (Squaw Valley USA, California),the Mountain Buddies program runs full- and half-day sessions seven days a week. Each day has a theme: On dinosaur day, for example, campers make cardboard stand-up dinos and play duck,duck, dinosaur. Kids can also swim, hike, and participate innature-related science projects. (916-581-6624; $55 a day, $25 a half day.)  <p> THE CARIBBEAN. At Aruba Sonesta Resorts (Seaport Village, Aruba),in addition to the usual swimming and arts and crafts, kids aged5 to 12 hike along nature trails on the hotel's private island and take such field trips as a rock-hunting expedition to Aruba's north coast. The evenings feature movies, bingo, and miniature golf. (800-sonesta; no additional charge.)  <p> El Conquistador's Camp Coqui (San Juan, Puerto Rico) accepts campers as young as three. There's a heavy dose of education mixed with appropriate activities -- say, a talk about marine biology after swimming. In addition to salsa and merengue lessons, kids learn indigenous arts on a 100-acre island used only by hotel guests. For older kids, there are Ping-Pong tournaments and disco parties. (800-468-5228; $38 a day.)  <p> Holiday Inn Sun Spree Resort (Montego Bay, Jamaica) offers a nursery for little ones six months to two years old. Bigger kids enjoy such activities as a tour of a sugar plantation and a ride on a glass-bottomed boat. Kids can eat in their own dining area; teenagers dance in their own disco. Teens also stage a reggae concert and make puppets for a puppet show. (800-holiday; free for children under 13, $50 for ages 13 to 17.)  <p> CRUISES. Camp Carnival runs from 9 a.m. to 10 p.m. on all of Carnival Cruise Lines' cruises. While activities are much the same as on other cruise lines, notable features include a kids-only aerobics class, karaoke parties, makeovers for teenagers, and photography workshops. One ship, the Super Liner Holiday, which sails from Los Angeles to Baja, Mexico, has more than 60 video and arcade games -- your eight-year-old will be thrilled. (800-438-6744; no additional charge.)  <p> Premier Cruise Lines' Big Red Boat is the most kid-friendly cruise around: Five programs, divided into age groups, run from 9 a.m. to 10 p.m. for kids aged two and up. A typical tour starts with a three-day visit to <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a> World, then continues with acruise to the Bahamas for another three or four days. The piecede resistance: During cruisetime, if your kids are at least two,you can leave them in the kids' area overnight. Says spokesman Brad Parker, "You could conceivably leave your children 24 hours a day." After three days of fighting crowds at Disney World, you might think it's not such a bad idea. (800-327-7113; no additional charge.)  <p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
