	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Amateur Bulls on the Loose</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Amateur Bulls on the Loose</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Amateur Bulls on the Loose</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Review  <p> AMATEUR BULLS ON THE LOOSE  <p>  <p>THE MOTLEY FOOL INVESTMENT GUIDE <p>By David and Tom Gardner, Simon & Schuster, $24  <p> THE WHIZ KID OF WALL STREET'S INVESTMENT GUIDE <p>By Matt Seto and Steven Levingston, William Morrow, $22  <p> THE BEARDSTOWN LADIES' STITCH-IN-TIME GUIDE TO GROWING YOURNEST EGG <p>Hyperion, $19.95  <p> THE BEARDSTOWN LADIES' COMMON-SENSE INVESTMENT GUIDE <p>Hyperion, $10.95, paperback  <p>  <p>By Eric Tyson  <p> Wonder whether the U.S. stock market is cresting? Consider this sign: The number of investment clubs registered with the National Association of Investors Corp. has ballooned from 3,600 in 1980 to more than 18,700 today; the previous high of 14,100 clubs, reached in the early 1970s, coincided with the beginning of a dismal decade for stocks. Another sign? The uptick in stock-picking books by unknowns claiming strategies and performances that make Warren Buffett and George Soros look like bush leaguers.  <p> Beating market indexes and top money pros isn't easy, but you'd never know it by reading the recent books from Matt Seto, the Gardner brothers, and the Beardstown Ladies. All claim simple stock-picking systems. The boasts they make!  <p> Take The Beardstown Ladies' Common-Sense Investment Guide, newly issued in paperback. The now famous authors trumpet annual returns in excess of 23 percent during the past decade. Not likely. The club's M.O. is selecting highly ranked stocks from the respected Value Line Investment Survey, but Value Line itself runs an SEC-audited mutual fund that invests solely in stocks it rates highly. Over the past ten years, it has underperformed the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index. Seems the Ladies should've taken over management of the Value Line Fund by now. When asked to document their performance, though, a spokesperson says the club chooses "not to make our investing return an issue, we're not out there to be bragging." Maybe the Ladies haven't seen their own book jackets lately. <p> Matt Seto's book, The Whiz Kid of Wall Street's Investment Guide, grew out of a Wall Street Journal article portraying Seto as a prodigy whose stock picking and predictions were putting Wall Street's investment pros to shame. For Seto, investing is a science, and a simple one at that: "If you read the company's numbers correctly and foresee the good news coming, you're sitting on a gold mine." Seto is probably sitting somewhere else now: For a second Journal article, on January 3, 1995, Seto read the tea leaves and predicted 1995 would see interest rates rise and the Dow climb only 2 percent; his top stock pick was <a name="NASD:COTIF"></a><b>Cott Corporation</b>,then at $9.75. Well, as almost everyone knows, interest rates plunged and the Dow soared 33.5 percent; Cott closed the year at $5.50. Seto, much like the Beardstown Ladies, backpedaled when asked to substantiate the 34-percent-annual-performance claim blazoned across his book's cover.  <p> The Motley Fool Investment Guide, by Tom and David Gardner, is humorous and breezy, but it has an attitude problem: The Gardners sound like political-talk-show hosts on a mission. They're convinced the financial establishment, brokers, financial publishers, mutual-fund companies, and the like are feathering their own nests by making investing unnecessarily complicated. The brothers' idea of simplicity? Select high-yielding, low-priced Dow Jones Industrial Average stocks and wait for the 25 percent annual returns to roll in with minimal risk, of course. Their system resembles the newsletters they criticize for promoting rear view-mirror strategies, though,to their credit, they can document their market-beating returns (albeit over a short period).  <p> The greatest shortcoming in these "investment" guides is their limited focus. Despite their titles, these books are pulpit-pounding sermons on stock picking, to the exclusion of mutual funds, real estate, and other investments. Novice readers need to beware the plain-folks voices: They're quiet when it comes to such issues as dividend taxation and the difference between short-term and long-term capital-gains taxes, the generally wise strategy of funding tax-deductible retirement accounts, and diversification and asset-allocation decisions. The Beardstown Ladies, in the new Stitch-in-Time Guide to Growing Your Nest Egg, attempt to tackle some of these broader issues, but they prove neither savvy nor trustworthy. A chart listing precious metals, futures, and stocks as both high-risk and high-return investments is not only inaccurate but may lead to bad decisions.  <p> Even for those who want to concentrate on stock picking, these books are not the right place to start. The original Beardstown guide, its 172 pages on investing full of cute drawings and blank space, can be read in a couple of hours. But to beat the stock market, more than money and a couple of hours are required: Lots of time must be invested, too. Start with Burton Malkiel's A Random Walk Down Wall Street, a great investing primer. Or try James Collins and Jerry Porras's best-seller, Built to Last, which analyzes long-term corporate winners. As a dividend bonus, you won't have to face any outrageous performance claims.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:COTIF">Cott Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
