<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Investing Briefs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Investing Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Investing Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Investing<p>AN EASY ROUTE TO EXTRA RETURNS<p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>It's a simple strategy, but it works. Buy the ten stocks among the Dow Jones Industrials with the highest dividend yields each new year and hold them for 12 months. Since the end of 1928, this strategy has outperformed the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index by 2.8 percentage points a year. Granted, it didn't work wonders in 1995, generating a total return of 37 percent, which just matched the S&P 500's phenomenal 37.1 percent. Still, it outdistanced the average equity mutual fund by 5.9 percentage points, according to Lipper Analytical Services.<p>This success isn't a statistical quirk. Stocks offer juicy yields when they're out of favor because companies generally keep dividends steady even if the share price falls. Buying the ten highest-yielding Dow shares each year forces investors to ignore market sentiment and stick with a powerful, value-based, contrarian strategy, says Jim O'Shaughnessy, president of O'Shaughnessy Capital Management in Greenwich, Connecticut. This premium yield compensates investors when the market is down and when a stock is in the doghouse for a long time. <p>The strategy could be especially timely in 1996. The top-yielding Dow stocks often outperform the S&P index in market declines, says O'Shaughnessy. In 1973, for example, the S&P 500 lost 14.66 percent, but the high-yielders gained 3.88 percent.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
