<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-The 60-Minute Rocket Scientist</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The 60-Minute Rocket Scientist</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-The 60-Minute Rocket Scientist</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Investing<p>THE 60-MINUTE ROCKET SCIENTIST
Tips for turning your computer into a high-powered investing tool.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Software that analyzes stocks, bonds, and mutual funds has made the most powerful and complex mathematical tools of Wall Street's market wizards accessible to any investor willing to fork over the cost of a program. The right on-line sites and the best electronic news sources can keep investors a jump ahead of the crowd for less than the cost of a subscription to The Wall Street Journal. But the easy availability of all this information__performance data on 6,000 mutual funds, fundamentals on 7,000 stocks,earnings estimates from every analyst on Wall Street, and much more__has turned the individual investor's traditional dilemma inside out. Once, the problem was a lack of information; now investors risk being overwhelmed.<p>I spent the better part of two years sorting through the options and issues__all of which shifted on me repeatedly__and I've emerged from my explorations with The Worth Guide to Electronic Investing: Everything You Need to Know to Use Your Home Computer to Make More Money in the Stock Market. My goal in writing this book (to be published in May by HarperBusiness) is to help investors ferret out the best data and combine them into sound investment strategies. I ran hundreds of programs on my computer (more than a hundred are reviewed in the book), spent time on all the on-line services, and visited too many Internet sites to count. Here, adapted from that book, are some of the most important things I learned:<p>*SUBVERT THE SYSTEM. Remember that the user, not the software, sets the rules. For example, Reuters Money Network (called WealthBuilder in the Macintosh version) comes with a setup routine that is so cumbersome and annoying that many users will stuff the program back into its box__which would be too bad, because this is one of the best programs around for both beginners and more experienced investors. But you can bypass the setup, even if you don't know a hard drive from a bagel. Just head for the "expert" option, which appears after about four screens on which the program asks for details about portfolios, income, and expenses.<p>Skip that__it will take days. Choose "expert," set up the modem, enter a few preferences, and download stock quotes, news stories, and fundamentals on stocks and funds. (From Reality Online, 800-346-2024; $24.95 for Windows, $49.99 for Macintosh; monthly memberships for $12.95 or $19.95.)<p>*DON'T BE AFRAID TO PUT PROGRAMS TO UNEXPECTED USES. Academic research shows that most investment return is a result of the asset class an investor picks rather than specific asset choices in that class. But it's hard to find an easy-to-use, inexpensive program that will break a portfolio into asset classes and calculate returns from each. A simple trick can turn the newest versions of Quicken (version 5 for Windows, version 6 for Macintosh) to just this task. When an investor enters a new stock or other asset into a Quicken portfolio, the program asks for the type and goal of each asset__offering default answers such as stock, bond, etc., and college, retirement, etc. Instead of using the default terms for type, use the "new" command to write in the names of the specific asset classes you want to track: income, large-cap growth, etc. Then, in the program's "portfolio view," tell Quicken to group assets by type. The program will automatically calculate the percentage of the portfolio in each asset class and apply simple performance measures such as percentage gain. Investors can use the goal menu simultaneously to track assets by, for example, industry. Fill in the sector for each asset and use "portfolio view" to group assets by goal. (From Intuit, 800-816-8025; $39.95 for disk versions, $59.95 for CD-ROM; Windows and Macintosh.)<p>*BE AMBITIOUS. Many investors use software to track the performance of the stocks and mutual funds they own. Why stop there? Use the computer's facility for comparing alternative investments to set up a shadow portfolio that tracks stocks on your wish list. This gives you a feel for price trends and volatility. Users can also keep a folder of news on stocks to assemble dossiers on management and strategy. Programs such as Dow Jones News/Retrieval Private Investor Edition can set up several different portfolios (and easily update the price of each issue) and provide a steady flow of investment news. Another option is Stock Investor from the American Association of Individual Investors. It can create a targeted shadow portfolio. That is, an investor can design a portfolio called, say, "Motorola" that will consist of high-technology stocks that might replace a stake in <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>"Motorola"</b></a> . Fill this portfolio by creating a screen based on factors crucial to the stock's success. For example, use Motorola's current growth rate and return on equity to search for companies that do better on those measures__and Intel will pop up. (From Dow Jones Business Information Services, 800-815-5100; $29.95 a month; Windows and Macintosh. American Association of Individual Investors, 800-428-2244; $150 a year for nonmembers, $99 for members; DOS and Windows.)<p>*EXPLORE THE FUTURE. It's fairly simple to create quick and dirty versions of the "what if" models used on Wall Street to test what would happen to a security if interest rates went up or the economy sputtered. Stock Analyst from Quant IX Software can portray the risk and reward of an investment under different economic scenarios. First, plug in such basic economic variables as the current inflation rate and the yield on three-month Treasurys. Then add projections of a company's earnings and dividends. Stock Analyst will value the company's stock. Now, suppose the company is a utility.Keep the company's fundamentals constant and change the economic variables to see how hard the stock would be hit by a rise in interest rates. Or say it's a growth company.Keep the economic factors steady and change earnings to see how vulnerable the stock might be to an economic slowdown. (Quant IX Software, 800-247-6354; $69; DOS; Windows scheduled for late 1996.)<p>*APITCUTE IS WORTH A THOUSAND COLUMNS OF NUMBERS. The opening graph of the Stock Selection Guide from the National Association of Investors is the single-best fundamental tool I've seen for grasping the character of a growth stock. That's because it uses pictures instead of words to capture a stock's essence__and then, unlike a paper chart, allows an investor to visualize alternative futures. For example, what could better characterize a stock such as <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> than the rock-solid line that graphs the company's sales for the last ten years? It climbs at a steady 15.9 percent a year from 1988 through the present with hardly a quiver. Just as revealing is that the more erratic earnings line moves well above the historic trend in the three most recent quarters. This graph poses the crucial investment question succinctly: Will the stock price follow the ten-year historical earnings trend or reflect the new, higher growth rate of the last few quarters? By drawing and then redrawing the graph, with a few clicks of a mouse, an investor can create charts of five-year earnings projections or see if Hewlett-Packard has ever matched its recent rocket-like growth. (National Association of Investors, 810-583-6242; $69 for nonmembers, $49 for members; Windows and Macintosh.)<p>*COMPUTERS ARE A GODSEND FOR THE MATH-PHOBIC. The McGraw-Hill Pocket Guide to Business Finance contains all the formulas that bedevil investors. But its use requires reading strange mathematical squiggles and using a pocket calculator. Now this book has been turned into a software program, the McGraw-Hill Financial Analyst, so all an investor has to do is "turn" to the work sheet that best fits the case at hand, type in the numbers, and hit the return key. The 201 formulas calculate everything from the required return on an investment to the future value of a stock with growing dividends. (McGraw-Hill, 800-722-4726; $69.95; Windows.)<p>*BUT NEVER TAKE A PROGRAM'S WORD FOR IT. Many stock-screening programs let an investor compare companies to competitors by sorting stocks with a Standard Industrial Code number. That can be misleading. For example, the SIC numbers in Morningstar's U.S. Equities program erroneously lump Hewlett-Packard, which makes computers, printers, and test equipment for engineers, with Pitney Bowes, which makes postage meters and mailing systems. Both companies, the program says, are in SIC 3570, the category for "manufacturing machinery computer equipment."<p>Fortunately, investors can use the same software to set a benchmark for an industry. In the retail sector, for example, pick an upscale store to track margins against, or a thriving established store with which to compare same-store sales. Add some retailers popular with Wall Street analysts, since they will be comparing any retailer to those favorites. Skim analysts' buy recommendations electronically from sources such as Standard & Poor's. Download the fundamentals on four or five companies into a single file to pull up when examining enticing retail possibilities. (Morningstar, 800-876-5005; $145 annually with quarterly updates; DOS only.)<p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

