	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Q&A:The Business of Doing Good</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Q&A:The Business of Doing Good</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Q&A:The Business of Doing Good</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Features<p>Q & A: THE BUSINESS OF DOING GOOD
Bill Shore, of Share Our Strength, turned hunger in America into a business, and charitable giving into a service industry. <p>By Larissa MacFarquhar<p>In 1984, Bill Shore founded the anti-hunger organization Share Our Strength on the paradoxical premise that a charity should be run like a business. <p>Shore, 40, a former congressional staffer who worked for Senators Gary Hart and Bob Kerrey, thought a charity should try to meet donors' needs, as well as the other way around. This strategy has driven SOS's growth from an organization with an annual budget of $30,000 to one with a budget of $16 million and roughly 50 employees today. Meanwhile its collaboration with <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a> has made SOS the best-known anti-hunger group in the country. Larissa MacFarquhar spoke with Shore about his organization.<p>WORTH: What prompted you to create Share Our Strength?
BILL SHORE: The Ethiopian famine in late 1984, which made me want to complement the work I was doing in government with something more hands-on in the private sector.
The idea was to build a charitable organization that not only redistributed wealth but created new wealth. I didn't want to be just another charity fighting for its little slice of the pie. <p>Why not?
Most nonprofits are trying to accomplish very difficult tasks with that tiny portion of the financial universe that consists of what's left over: the money you and I and businesses donate at the end of the year. That makes about as much sense as trying to get a truck up to the top of a hill by asking people to push it a little bit on their way home from work rather than building it an engine. Nonprofits need to build reliable moneymaking engines that fuel their efforts, because all the charitable intentions in the world aren't enough to solve big problems like hunger. <p>What is SOS's engine?
One of our most profitable projects has been a series of food-and-wine tastings called Taste of the Nation. The first year we did it, 1988, it raised $252,000; last year it cleared $4.1 million. We'd been contacting chefs and restaurateurs, and realized they'd be happier to participate in a food-and-wine benefit that cost them $800 than to send us a check for $50 once a year. <p>Why the resistance to donating cash? 
I think people are looking for a way to feel connected to an organization, and looking for a way to contribute something that nobody else could. If the National Kidney Foundation asked me to contribute $5,000, I'd probably say no. But if they said, We know you used to be a swimmer in high school, would you referee a swimming event for us?, I'd probably say yes__that would be fun. People involved with SOS feel connected to us and usually become donors without us even asking. <p>How did Taste of the Nation come to be sponsored by American Express?
A few restaurant-industry people knew the company was having difficulty getting restaurants to accept their card because they charge a higher transaction fee than MasterCard or Visa. They came to us and said, It would be beneficial for you two to become partners; restaurants would respect American Express for being involved with SOS, and SOS would benefit if American Express became a sponsor of Taste of the Nation. So American Express began paying a sponsorship fee in the neighborhood 
of $500,000. <p>And that led to your Charge Against Hunger program?
Right. American Express said, Let's think about doing something larger, [and] we worked out what would become Charge Against Hunger: American Express agreed to donate three cents to SOS every time the card was used in the last two months of the year, up to $5 million. For the three years we've done it, it has added up to about that. Also, Amex is getting an increasing number of merchants to match the contribution when the card is used in their stores. So the total will be $6 million or $6.5 million this year.<p>Could other charities replicate your approach? 
I think a lot can. Somebody told me the American Heart Association is considering lending its name and logo to medical products. The key is to build up the value of your name and establish a constituency that respects and feels connected to what you're doing. <p>Where do you get the remaining $7 million of your annual budget?
The visibility we get with American Express has helped us build relationships with a slew of companies. We've worked out an arrangement with Gallo and with Fetzer, for instance, where they give us $10 or so for every case of particular wines they sell to certain restaurants. The idea is that if a Fetzer and a Beringer chardonnay are about the same in price and quality, restaurateurs involved with us will buy the Fetzer. <p>We've also created a few products: fiction anthologies, children's stories, cookbooks, sweatshirts. Many top chefs would love to help us develop a line of food products, but we're proceeding cautiously with that because it would require up-front outlays of cash and be considerably more risky than licensing our logo.<p>If you sold a line of products, would you lose your nonprofit status and have to pay taxes?
Possibly, but I would welcome that. It would validate that we're creating wealth. I've felt for some time that the distinction between "for-profit" and "nonprofit" has become outmoded. There are what I call community-wealth enterprises: for-profit companies that give their profits back to the community. Paul Newman's company, Newman's Own, is a great example. After taxes, it donates 100 percent of profits to charity. <p>How does SOS spend its money?
When people think of a hunger organization, they think of getting food to people. That's a necessary task, and we do it, but it's a low-impact strategy for creating lasting change. So we give grants to organizations that work to affect policy at federal and state levels__like the Food Research and Action Center here in Washington. <p>We fund research at Tufts University's Center on Hunger, Poverty, and Nutrition Policy on the link between nutrition and cognitive development in children. We give money to failure-to-thrive clinics that treat kids with malnutrition. 
The Boston City Hospital's Grow Clinic, for instance, we give about $50,000 a year. We give about $450,000 a year to New York's Children's Health Fund: They drive health-care vans to welfare hotels and shelters, and treat homeless kids for malnutrition and other things. Last year we gave $300,000 to a Native American nutrition project at Johns Hopkins University. <p>And we give grants to food banks. They store surplus food from producers like Kraft or Nabisco and redistribute it. They use our funds for warehousing and transportation. <p>The fact is, the hardest work at SOS now is not raising money but spending it so that it not only helps people now but puts them in a position where they're not going to need more help in the future. <p>Does your charity-as-business philosophy extend to staff salaries? 
We hired a consulting firm [that] surveyed similar organizations and determined for each position the low, high, and midpoint salary. They advised us that if we were interested in keeping staff we should set our salaries between 80 and 100 percent of the midpoint. That's what we've tried to do. The problem is we're still not competitive with for-profits. <p>What does the future hold for SOS?
We need to expand into other industries. People who work in finance, sales, advertising, or public relations could be enormously valuable to us as consultants or as members of our board. And there is potential in the most unlikely places. I just met with one of the more successful real-estate agents in Rochester, New York, and she's developed a program in which the parties to a transaction__the brokers, the attorneys__each contribute $10 to an organization that works with homelessness. She figured out that if everybody involved in a real-estate transaction in this country gave $10, it would raise something like $377 million a year. If only 5 percent of those people got involved, it would still be a lot of money. <p>How large will SOS become? 
One of my biggest gripes with the nonprofit community is that it tends to think small. We've got to build a much, much bigger effort if we want to make a dent in the fact that 39 million people live in poverty. One of the ironies is that the better we do our job, the more ammunition we provide people who believe that the government doesn't need to be involved in fighting poverty. But look at the numbers: $16 million a year makes us a very large anti-hunger organization, but the federal government spends $40 billion a year just on food-assistance programs. There's no way organizations like ours could ever come close to replacing that.<p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

