	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Vegas Calling</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Vegas Calling</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Vegas Calling</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Features<p>VEGAS CALLING
At last, the Hard Rock Casino gives the people what they want: cooler music to lose money by.<p>By Elizabeth Royte<p>On a sunny Tuesday afternoon in Sin City, to the tune of ringing slot machines and tumbling dice, I learn that 1,564,898,299 acres of Amazonian rain forest remain unmolested by the logger's saw and the farmer's torch. At a craps table, a large man behind a tiny nose ring cries out, "Roll it, Baby," then roars in delight as Baby makes him $50 richer.<p>My information about the natural world comes from an electronic ticker over five slot machines, whose drop the Hard Rock Hotel and Casino will donate to Conservation International and the Natural Resources Defense Council. Unfortunately, these socially responsible slot machines host not a single gambler. "Rain-forest acres?" says a croupier when I ask if anyone plays the machines. "I thought that ticker was a jackpot. I never noticed the numbers were going down." No matter, really. Nearly every other seat in the house is full, and the expandable coffers of Peter Morton, the genius behind the Hard Rock restaurant empire, continue to fill.<p>That a casino today even nods to social consciousness surely signals a brave new Las Vegas. Morton calls his latest venture, which opened last spring, "Vegas for a New Generation." He means this literally__his hotel targets gamblers between the ages of 21 and 45, as opposed to the industry median of 46__and he means it metaphorically, in the sense that old-generation gamblers prefer to take their camp without irony and their losses without a backbeat.<p>The Hard Rock is an experiment in niche marketing, a way for Morton's Hard Rock America to get a piece of the $40 billion gambling industry. As gambling's legal and moral constraints disappear across the country, a new, younger audience will surely emerge. Morton is betting that rock and roll, that hoary marketing device, will lure this segment of the market away from all the other casinos__as well as the riverboats, racetracks, and lotteries__and into his hotel. But will the kids buy into it, or will the Hard Rock be recognized as yet another Vegas theme park, designed to distract while the corporate hand separates a fool from his money?<p>Subtlety is unknown in Las Vegas, and the Hard Rock does not break tradition. A 90-foot Fender guitar looms over the porte cochere. Tom Petty wails "Runaway Train" into the parking lot. A giant inscription over the hotel's front door reads, when this house is rockin', don't bother knockin'. Inside, the Sex Pistols set the tone: the only notes that matter come in wads.<p>Things are clearly spelled out, you have to give Morton that. This is the casino that rock built, and I, a music lover with some disposable income, should be the ideal customer. I'm old enough not to roll my eyes at Tom Petty but still contrarian enough, in the classic rock-and-roll sense, to put the establishment through its paces, to make it win me over. Thus the inscription over the registration desk: here we are now entertain us__lyrics by the late Kurt Cobain of Nirvana. It's a simple acknowledgment of roles. I am the human target, and the Hard Rock will be working 24-7 to nail me.<p>I stroll around the grounds until I feel at home. The circular casino lies at the center of the hotel, surrounded by a sports and race book, restaurant, bar, cashier's cage, registration desk, and concert hall. Among the impedimenta of gambling, I note the guitars of Stevie Ray Vaughan, Pearl Jam, Soul Asylum, Chris Isaak, Depeche Mode, Guns n' Roses, R.E.M. I study the costumes of Madonna, Chrissie Hynde, the Cranberries, and the Red Hot Chili Peppers, and the leather jackets of any mainstream rocker you can think of.<p>Over my head hangs a chandelier made of 32 gold-plated saxophones; Zildjian cymbals cover the lighting fixtures in the hallways; atop groupings of slot machines, many of which use the necks of actual Fender Stratocaster guitars for handles, sit Elton John's rhinestone-covered piano from his "Bitch" tour, a drum kit from John Densmore of the Doors, a Harley-Davidson, and a red '59 Corvette convertible. It looks just like a Hard Rock restaurant, but more spread out. "The principles of marketing to diners and gamblers are the same," Morton tells me later from his office in Los Angeles. "The Hard Rocks are museums of rock and roll. We're succeeding here because, for Las Vegas, this is a totally unique and different product."<p>Indeed, no other gambling emporium has spent a million-plus on a sound system that pumps music nonstop into the casino, elevators, restaurants, gym, and even the pool, underwater. The music is programmed by modem each day from Hard Rock America's corporate headquarters in Los Angeles, and the songs on the six 300-disc CD players repeat as seldom as every three weeks.<p>I can't say I hate the music:I hear David Bowie's "Let's Dance," the Beach Boys' "California Girls," the Pretenders' "Back on the Chain Gang"__all nice songs. But I can't help noticing that this is just the shiny, happy side of rock and roll. I suppose that if I were running an amusement park I'd avoid anything edgy and dark, too. But the Hard Rock has staked its reputation on a certain hipness, and as night falls I'm still hoping to find it.<p>Instead I meet a mustachioed septuagenarian sliding down the inside of elevator number two (the writing on the wall: don't let the elevator bring you down__Prince). He's been here three days, he's up $15,000, and he's a little wired after two days without sleep. "I love the music, I wish they'd turn it up!" he shouts at me. "You don't mind losing so much if you're boppin' to the music." Boppin'? I wish him luck and hurry to the caf.<p>Ken, 45, a high-rolling blackjack player, is enjoying a late-night tuna steak. "The decor doesn't matter to me at all," he says. "I like this place because it's upbeat, the staff and the gamblers are young, and they're more personable than at other casinos. This town really needed a place like this. You can only take so much Frank Sinatra."<p>Morton would be pleased: Ken pushed most of the buttons. But Ken is 45, and he wouldn't know Alice in Chains from Alice Kramden. It's just a happy accident that Morton's demographic net hauls in people like Ken who dig the youth scene and enjoy playing the big fish in a little pond__elder, high-rolling statesmen to those guppies testing the waters at the table games. At most casinos, the slot machines get the most play, but at the Hard Rock, younger gamblers lean toward the more complex games:craps, roulette, and blackjack. Someone has to teach them how to play, and people like Ken are happy to oblige.<p>I turn to Andre, who's dabbing tiny spots of butter onto his baked potato. "I came to the Hard Rock for the food," he says almost defensively. "My parents like those other places, where you pay $3.95 for prime rib, but I like to know where my fat is coming from." I almost laugh aloud. Andre, who fits the demo seamlessly, gambles at the Hard Rock not because he likes the music, or is taken by the decor, or thinks the cocktail waitresses look cute in their leopard hot pants, but because here he can count calories. "And the memorabilia?" I ask. Andre sighs. "Everywhere I go," he says, "they've got the shirt Hendrix wore in Monterey."<p>Andre heads for the gym, and I watch Ken lay down $500 and $1,000 bets on the purple baize of the blackjack table, trying to recoup $40,000 from yesterday's excitement. We switch tables once to escape three noisy, drunken brothers. I'm mesmerized by the speed of the dealers' hands, the terrible outflow of cash. Busty waitresses bring us sodas. I stay nearly two hours without thinking of moving.<p>Casinos trade in illusion, all of it formulaic. The lights are low, mirrors abound, sight lines are short, exits are disguised__the better to keep at bay hints of time and space beyond the gambling floor. At giant showplaces such as the Flamingo, the Mirage, or Caesars__where the casino floor is 117,000 square feet, as opposed to the Hard Rock's 30,000__every detail reminds the patrons that they're gambling, from the flashing lights and Sinatra to the rich colors and outlandish costumes. But at the Hard Rock, the iconography of Vegas is largely absent. The floors are hardwood, the air is smoke-free, and desert sunlight streams through the foyers. The only thing vulgar about the place is that it's here at all.<p>The clientele is atypical for Vegas as well. Perhaps the hotel is too upscale for Vegas hoi polloi, with its $22 steaks and, the week I was there, only one $5 blackjack table. The morning sees its share of elderly people in shell suits, but as the day wanes, so does the median age. Still, the casino isn't exactly larded with hipsters in black leather. The only person I meet who'd look out of place in a Gap ad is an angrily unemployed construction worker who sits at the bar for two days straight, talking in staccato bursts about nothing, furiously punching a poker machine, and nursing glasses of cranberry juice.<p>Because of legal gambling's peculiar calculus__a lot comes in and very little goes out__you'd expect operators to avoid reminding patrons that they're probably going to lose. While other casinos and state lotteries hype the good life that lies beyond the next roll of the dice, the Hard Rock consistently nods to loss. The five-dollar chips are stamped with a line from the Red Hot Chili Peppers: give it away. A foyer is inlaid with the lyrics from the Eagles' "Desperado": don't you draw the queen of diamonds, boy, she'll beat you when she's able. <p>That's a refreshing bit of honesty, I thought at first. But really, the quote wouldn't be there if it didn't work, if the marketing experts hadn't determined that it would spur the target group to gamble even more.<p>With all this quoting about, I think I might turn a corner to see Beck's i'm a loser, baby, so why don't you kill me? in ten-inch letters. But that might, finally, be going too far, reminding patrons of gambling's enormous social costs. If the Hard Rock has any qualms about glamorizing gambling for the younger generation, they're not in evidence. "Our research shows that young people love to go to rock-and-roll concerts and gamble," Morton tells me. "Our target audience is a 30-year-old yuppie who drives a BMW convertible and goes to Bruce Springsteen shows."<p>Bruce isn't there to wince at this, so Ido it on his behalf. But the more important point is that Morton is creating a powerful lure for yuppies-in-training as well, and may be contributing to a nationwide rate of pathological gambling among high-school and college-age youth that's double that of adults. After leaving the casino, I poke around the scientific literature and learn that gambling is the fastest-growing teenage addiction in the country. Not only is there a plethora of new ways to gamble__more states now have lotteries than don't, and it recently became possible to gamble via modem on the computer__but many of these new institutions and opportunities lack adult gatekeepers. Naturally, the Hard Rock does all it can to exclude minors, but it also does all it can to attract them__from booking Sheryl Crow in the Joint, the hotel's 1,400-seat club, to cultivating a nonstop party atmosphere. <p>Morton, a 60 percent owner of the hotel, and Harveys Casino Resorts, with 40 percent, spent $100 million building this youth magnet. Hard Rock America is privately held and won't divulge how much money the hotel is making, but Morton will say it's on track to produce revenues of $100 million in its first year. <p>"We're substantially ahead of projections," he says. The Hard Rock's retail store, which hawks mugs, T-shirts, beach towels, bath gel, key rings, teddy bears, water bottles, and golf balls to an apparently logo-starved constituency, reportedly takes in $80,000 a day__75 percent ahead of forecasts. Each day, the hotel turns down 300 requests for weekend stays. Things are going so well that Morton plans to expand the place next year, to a total of 700 rooms.<p>My second night at the casino I retire at 1 a.m. but wake when my neighbors bounce into their room at 5:30. Their giggling drives me nuts__are they rolling in dough? I call security on them. Then I put the do-not-disturb sign on my door, noting that it reads, i hear ya knockin' but ya can't come in. This is starting to get to me. <p>It turns out__and no one should be surprised__that rock lyrics make beautiful ad copy for casinos. Morton didn't need to hire writers to promote his hotel; the lines are already there, in classic songs about loss and risk and bright lights and sex and money and gambling. A hotel brochure is broken into segments: "Back in the High Life" touts the restaurant; "Welcome to the Hotel California" extols the swimming pool; "My Momma Told Me, You Gotta Shop Around" describes the wonders of the retail store. Morton knows his guests don't feel pandered to when he turns songs into slogans. They feel flattered. They can sing every reference. <p>Ever since Phil Collins outraged his fans by singing "Tonight, Tonight, Tonight" for Michelob, marketers have exploited rock and roll to reach their target audience__upwardly mobile youth unencumbered by mortgages and tuition. David Bowie stumps for Schweppes; Janis Joplin, from the grave, sells Mercedes-Benzes; the Beatles spurred the Nike Revolution. There have been some notable holdouts: Springsteen refused to let Ronald Reagan adopt "Born in the U.S.A." for his 1984 campaign, and R.E.M. wouldn't sell "It's the End of the World as We Know It" to hype Windows 95, despite a reported offer of several million dollars. These days, a band more often makes the news when it says no to an ad agency than when it says yes. <p>"Rock and roll has become corporate, but what can you do?" says Kevan, 25, sitting at the bar. "You shouldn't question it too much." The lead singer of an L. A. punk band, he's in town with a few mates from Scotland__rockers all. Kevan, from Leeds, England, wears a pink denim jacket, several earrings, and black sunglasses, which stick to his forehead through some sort of torsional force. He has shaved hash marks in his eyebrows; his beard is one thin stripe coming up from his chin and two thin stripes slanting across his cheeks. "The shaving is a real bitch," he tells me. <p>Kevan longs to sell out, once his band gets signed. He figures it's the natural progression. "As long as you still believe in what you do, selling out is okay," he says. "I want to make a ton of money." This young man is depressing me. Here he is, superficially the embodiment of punk anarchy__with his sissy pink jacket and his tattoos and his go-to-hell hair design__and all he wants is to walk in Peter Morton's shoes. "The Sex Pistols ripped everybody off," he says. "The Hard Rock casino is the rock-and-roll swindle all over again. It just makes me laugh." <p>He orders another rum and Coke, then lights a Marlboro. "You come to Vegas to lose money, drink, and have a good time. This place is just what you'd expect."
I sip my beer and consider Kevan's wisdom. I start to think he's right. What did I expect? The good people that surround me came to gamble, not have a significant cultural experience. This is Las Vegas, not Austin; it's a casino, for Chrissakes. As my next interview victim, a rock-loving 23-year-old, says to me, "We're being marketed to anyway, it might as well be rock and roll."
Iturn to Elizabeth, a perky 21-year-old wearing cropped hair and a striped T, and ask, "Do the words 'industry weasel' mean anything to you?"<p>I read in a newspaper that the Hard Rock is "relentlessly hip," and I couldn't tell at the time whether that was a compliment or a complaint. The sentiment, at any rate, misses the point. The hotel's idea of hip comes from a completely consumerist, top-down perspective. The jackets and guitars that festoon the casino weren't lovingly collected by fans but bought with more than $2 million of Morton's money by a full-time professional curator. If anybody's T-shirt was sweaty when purchased, it surely is no longer.<p>The Nirvana diorama makes a perfect metaphor for all that's been bothering me about this place. Here are Kurt Cobain's thermal shirt, his guitar, and his leather jacket. The front page of the Seattle Post-Intelligencer, with news of Cobain's suicide, sits among photos of the band, amid a scattering of rocks and gravel. But there's nothing organic about any of this. Everything has been meticulously arranged to elicit a reaction. And I resist. Even the letters of tribute that fans have slid through cracks in the display case__a bit of wholly spontaneous fetishism__have been culled and rearranged in an artful tableau. "We take out the bad notes and leave the good ones," the hotel's marketing director tells me.
Finally Ithink I understand what Peter Morton is after. He doesn't just want to spark an emotional response; he wants to control it.<p>At long last, I spy a gambler at the rain-forest slots: Dominique, a woman in her late 30s. Black catsuit, white face, black bangs. When Dominique first heard of the Hard Rock, she says, "I thought it was pretentious and ridiculous, just another tax write-off for Peter Morton. I thought it would be a complete failure, that it would be filled with geriatrics from Ohio." But one night at about 3 a.m., when she had run out of luck at the Rio, she decided to stop by. She ordered a Coke with a cherry, and the waitress told her the Hard Rock didn't serve food with red dye. "I thought that was bogus at first," she says, "but now I think it's conscientious."<p>She's come around in other ways as well. "I assumed the Hard Rock was the land of young and good-looking people," she says. "In L.A., the place had a reputation for being stuck-up. I felt that attitude__that I wasn't pretty enough to be here. I was wrong. Everyone is friendly, the casino's small, and now it's one of my favorite spots." Dominique is playing the rain-forest slots because she's hoping for some grace from the gods of gambling. She feeds $100 into a machine__it takes less time than reading this paragraph__and rings up $150 in profits. She smiles as she scoops up her coins, then glances at the diminishing acres. "Do you think the ticker's going to speed up because I won?" she asks. <p>The ticker seems unaffected by anything__real or symbolic. The numbers just keep dropping, representing nothing but the idea of loss. Morton sits on the board of the Natural Resources Defense Council, and he gives that group and Conservation International more than $150,000 a year from his own pocket plus whatever the slots take in. By the time I leave the Hard Rock Hotel, the rain forest has 1,561,275,286 acres left__a drop of more than three and a half million in just three days. <p>I share a taxi to the airport with a young, intelligent, and music-obsessed software designer from San Francisco. "I think this is the coolest place in the world," he says. We creep past the flashing lights of the strip and discuss marketing strategies. We talk about what it's like to fit the demo. "I do feel targeted, yeah," he says, grinning. "They nailed it. And it doesn't bother me at all."<p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

