				<font size=5><b>Going Bankless</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Going Bankless</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>GOING BANKLESS
Brokerages' super-accounts are crashing the banks' party.<p>By Jerry DeMuth<p>Returning to their Bergen County, New Jersey, home from a winter in Puerto Rico, Doris and Stanley Goldstein were faced with three months' worth of stock-dividend checks, credit-card and checking-account statements, two other bank accounts and two brokerage accounts to reconcile, and numerous fees and charges to make sense of. <p>"I told my husband, 'Something is wrong,' " says Doris Goldstein. Now the Goldsteins receive one monthly statement that lists all their activity__dividends received, interest earned, deposits, withdrawals, gold-card activity, and checks written. <p>The Goldsteins' account isn't at a bank__it's a Smith Barney Financial Management Account, one of numerous banking-type accounts available at brokerage firms, including Dean Witter, Dreyfus, Fidelity, <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, Paine Webber, and Prudential. These accounts offer just about everything banks offer, even loans (based on margin borrowing). They also provide a range of investment choices__mutual funds, money-market accounts, tax-free funds, certificates of deposit, bonds, stocks, and other securities. <p>But only 1.3 percent of households with annual incomes of at least $24,000 use brokerage firms as their primary financial institution, according to USBanker magazine. That's probably because the accounts require hefty minimum balances, from $10,000 at Dreyfus and Fidelity to $20,000 at Merrill Lynch; for additional services, even higher minimums may be required. However, those balances can include securities as well as cash. <p>Brokerage bank accounts also lack federal oversight and FDICinsurance. But some, such as those at Fidelity and Smith Barney, are protected by private insurance. Annual fees range from a high of $100 at Merrill Lynch to zero under some conditions at Fidelity. There may also be fund-transfer fees and a charge for printed checks. But check writing is free, and the $500 minimum once standard with brokerage money-market accounts has disappeared.<p>Dean Witter, 800-869-3326; Dreyfus, 800-377-2200; Fidelity, 800-544-6262; Merrill Lynch, call your local branch; PaineWebber, 800-762-1000; Prudential, 800-222-4321; Smith Barney, 800-634-9855.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
