	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Back in the Bleachers</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Back in the Bleachers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>BACK IN THE BLEACHERS
Baseball springs eternal in Florida and Arizona<p>By Rudy Maxa<p>It happens every March in Florida and Arizona, and it's called spring training. Well, it doesn't happen every March: Last year's labor turmoil delayed and curtailed the spring season, but this year, things are back on schedule. Through the entire month of March, the major-league teams have games slated almost every day against one another. Tickets for some hot clubs, such as the American League champion Cleveland Indians and the defending World Series champion Atlanta Braves, could be hard to get for weekend games, but seats for most teams should be readily available. <p>Florida is still the spring-training capital, though eight teams__most of the western squads, plus the Milwaukee Brewers and Chicago Cubs__call Arizona's Cactus League their spring home. The other 20 teams prepare for the regular season in Florida, mostly in towns along the coasts. The easiest way to find out where each team plays, and to get maps to all of the stadiums, ticket information, and game schedules, is to pick up a copy of Spring Training Baseball Yearbook, a 116-page magazine available each February at Barnes &Noble, B. Dalton, and larger newsstands around the country. <p>Spring training was discovered as a vacation hot spot five or ten years ago, says Myles Friedman, the editor of the annual publication. "But it's still very intimate, with ballparks that seat between 6,000 and 10,000," he says. "That's compared to a major-league stadium that seats between 40,000 and 60,000." This intimacy makes it much easier for fans to get autographs from their favorites and even chat with a player now and then over a fence.<p>If you just want to drop in on a team in Florida or Arizona and catch a game or two, check out Spring Training for the team or town of your choice. Each listing provides all the pertinent information on the games; prices range from $4 for bleacher seats to $18 for box seats, and many tickets can be secured through national ticket agencies. <p>But if you really want to savor baseball, if total immersion with like-minded fans is your idea of a great way to spend a week, then you should talk to Russ Everett of Broach Sports Tours in Charlotte, North Carolina. From March 24 to 30, Broach runs a rolling baseball fest whose participants depart Charlotte on a luxury European motor coach for the 13-hour drive (with rest stops every two hours) to Florida. The tour touches all the bases in the Grapefruit League, starting with Dodgertown in Vero Beach, winding through Baseball City, St. Petersburg, Clearwater, and Fort Myers before ending in Tampa. Fans see 13 teams spread over seven games (the tour hits the New York Mets twice), including the Indians versus the Toronto Blue Jays in Winter Haven. On the way back to Charlotte, the bus stops in Atlanta for an exhibition game between the Braves and the Boston Red Sox.<p>The cost for the whole enchilada is $469 per person, based on double occupancy, or $625 for a single traveler. (The tour company can pair you with someone, if you prefer.) If taking a bus from Charlotte to Florida and back isn't your idea of fun, you can meet the group in Florida and just participate in the six days of baseball for about $100 less. Call 704-333-9191 for details.<p>Included in the price: all lodging, game tickets, and transportation. Not included: beer, hot dogs, peanuts, and Cracker Jack. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Sports Industry

