	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-The Day Off That Pays Off</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Day Off That Pays Off</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-The Day Off That Pays Off</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> THE DAY OFF THAT PAYS OFF <p>You know all the little financial things that you should have taken care of by now but never got around to? Today's the day. <p> By Ken Kurson  <p> Everyone's done it: received a phone bill and wondered if it wasn't way higher than it had to be, paid a year's life-insurance premium and wondered if the insurer would survive until the policy was due, charged a big purchase yesterday and been stung by the interest payment today. Putting your financial house in order can be summarized in three words it's a drag. But here's an idea: Play hooky and spend one day doing all the little things you've been putting off for too long. No, it won't free you to ignore your finances for the rest of the year, but the little program outlined below should give you a day that's productive without being painful.  <p>  Here's what you need to get started: <p>*The most recent bill, statement, or policy from the five facets of your financial life you're going to tackle today. <p>*The White Pages and Yellow Pages. <p>*A Touch-Tone phone you'll reach so many phone trees it'll feel like Arbor Day. <p>* A book of cross word puzzles. Nothing beats a puzzle to combat the boredom of being put on hold and you'll already have the pen in your hand. <p>*A magnifying glass. Sometimes the details on insurance policies, bank statements, and credit-card bills really are in fine print. <p> If you do your work well, we'll provide a few suggestions along the way for rewarding yourself for addressing the various tesserae of your financial mosaic. Ready? Begin.  <p> Banking Rule No. 1: Keep your monthly bank statements. Rule No. 2: Organize them. Rule No. 3: Analyze them.  <p> First, find the part of your statement that lists the fees and expenses. (If you've broken rule No. 1, you can obtain copies from your bank, usually at no charge.) It's no surprise that these fees have been rising. For example, say you deposit a check that someone wrote to you, only to discover that the check writer had insufficient funds to cover the amount. In 1993, the percentage of banks that tacked a fee onto that already annoying situation was 65.5. By 1994, the number had jumped to 81.7. (Thrifts were even sterner, going from 71.2 percent to 93.5 percent.) At anaverage fee of $6.89 ($8.36 for thrifts), it's the kind of thing that can easily wipe out a month's return on an interest-bearing checking account.  <p> Beware of strict minimums, too. Part of the reason you need this day of financial house cleaning is that you don't like to sweat the details on a daily basis. So if keeping an eagle eye on every cent you spend to avoid dipping below the minimum isn't your idea of time well spent, you're bound to incur a charge every now and then. It should concern you and prompt you to consider moving your business if your account costs more than the industry average. Some salient averages: monthly checking charges, $6.14 ($5.58 at thrifts); transactions at another institution's ATM,95 cents a piece; stop-payment requests, $13.29; overdrafts, $14.92.  <p> Armed with your statements, you shouldn't have trouble finding an institution with a pricing structure that matches the way you do business. As always, there's no harm in asking your bank to provide incentives for you to keep your account there including waiving a stop-payment fee or overdraft charge now and again, though you shouldn't count on going to that particular well too often. (For information on consolidating your banking and brokerage accounts, see "Going Bankless," page 126.)  <p> Ready for a treat yet? Some superstation is bound to be showing The Lucy Show or The Beverly Hillbillies. Kick back for a few moments and let Mr. Mooney and Mr. Drysdale boost your confidence in the people looking after your money.  <p> Credit What you should have learned already is that the way to get something from a financial provider is to call up and ask for it. Banks are often willing to lower their credit-card rates and fees for good customers (you haven't missed a payment lately, right?). Your current issuer will probably match the best rates you've been offered.  <p> Nothing shook up the staid but profitable business of credit like the announcement in September 1992 that <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> wasteaming with Household Bank to offer rebates of 5 percent ofall charges toward the purchase or lease of a GM car. And nowcards are being tied to everything from computers (<a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a>) to beer (the Coors Extra Gold Card).  <p> If only these cool cards weren't such rotten deals. The dirty little secret of the credit business is that the interest rates on rebate cards average about 5 percentage points higher than those of the best non-rebate cards. "The interest rate is the bottom line," says Robert McKinley, the president of RAM Research Group, which tracks the credit-card industry. "Most premium or rebate cards charge 9 to 12 points over prime. That's just way too much."   <p> Suppose, for example, you carry a balance of $3,000 and charge $400 per month. Since a typical rebate card will award benefits equal to 1 percent of the amount charged, the $4,800 you spend annually on new charges entitles you to a refund of $48. But the extra 5 percent on your $3,000 balance will cost you $150. In other words, you lose $102.  <p> Rebate cards, then, are useful almost solely for cardholders who never carry a balance. Even for these people they're questionable, because rebate cards often come with high annual fees. When you call for the details on a rebate program that interests you, be sure to inquire about the annual fee, and don't be afraid to ask that it be waived or that the interest rate be lowered. <p> If you're still curious about rebate cards (and for some people,they do work beautifully), you can subscribe to Rebate Credit Cards, a quarterly newsletter from RAM, for $39, or you can get a recent sample copy for $10 (see "The Day's Directory," page125). It's not what you'd call a light read, but the information is comprehensive and clearly presented.  <p> It's now midday. For a credit-card story over lunch, rent the Brat Pack schlock favorite St. Elmo's Fire: Demi Moore impresses her friends with all the super cool furniture she bought with plastic until a series of missed payments brings the repo man a-calling.  <p> LIFE Insurance Take a look at your current life-insurance policy, where you'll find the name and location of your insurer, among other fundamental details. Scores of insurers, even those with big names, fail each year, and getting your money back (for a cash-value policy or an annuity) from a defunct company is a big hassle not to mention costly, since state insurance regulators typically allow those claims to be paid off at 80 to 90 cents on the dollar. So investigate the rating of your insurance company.  <p> Simply call the company's toll-free number, identify yourself as a policyholder, and ask for a recent report card, which is generally free. Or if you bought from an independent agent, make him or her earn some of that fat commission. "Your agent can get all of a company's ratings and send them to you, unabridged and without the insurer's editorializing," says Mark White, a vice president on the insurance side of Jack White & Co., a San Diego discount brokerage and insurance dealer. "Any professional agent ought to have that information at his fingertips."   <p> While you have your agent on the phone, ask about commissions. Agents, unsurprisingly, tend to recommend the products that pay them the highest commissions. Moreover, unlike the load on a mutual fund or the interest rate on a credit card, both of which the government requires be disclosed in a standard format, commissions on insurance typically remain unknown to consumers. <p>Don't be shy about asking an agent what he or she is being paid for selling you a policy. Commissions generally amount to 50 percent of the first year's premium on a cash-value policy (that is, whole, universal, or variable these cover 80 percent of the life-insurance universe), and 10 percent of each year's premiums on property-and-casualty policies, according to Jeff Yates, executive vice president of Independent Insurance Agents of America. Beware if your agent is getting more, and remember that in some states negotiating for a partial rebate of commissions is possible. <p> If you have a cash-value policy, your agent or insurer can provide a little-known but valuable document called an in-force ledger. This is basically a score card that shows the exact cash value of your policy and projects that value into the future. Some agents automatically send these statements, but there's a good chance you haven't been getting yours.  <p> Another important piece of paper to have is your medical-information file sort of a medical credit report. The file lists any health problems that may affect your rates or eligibility for life and health insurance, so you'll want to make sure it's accurate and up to date. The Medical Information Bureau will send you one for eight dollars.  <p> Breaktime: Check the TV guide for Double Indemnity, insurance's finest moment on film, which seems to be rebroadcast on cable just about weekly.  <p> Long Distance The skirmish for your long-distance dollar has taken to the television screen with a fierceness that would make Ed Rollins blush. The big three <a name="NYSE:FON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11560"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sprint</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> will promise virtually any dowry should you choose to take them as your mate. They will even offer to let "those other companies" know that you're satisfied with the service you're getting and don't want to be bothered by solicitations to jump ship.  <p> With so much pressure being brought to bear, what's a person playing hooky for a day to do? First, gather your last three phone bills. Count the number of interstate long-distance calls made and calculate their average duration. Consider the time of day you tend to dial, and note how many of your calls reach foreign ears.  <p> Now you're ready to let your fingers do the walking. "Call your carrier rep and say, Here are the calls I make, what's the best you can do for me?' " says Lynne Butler, senior analyst at Market Dynamics, a Bethesda, Maryland, company that publishes the newsletter Long Distance for Less.  <p> A favored ruse of the long-distance slugfest is to offer promotions that promise a reward for switching from one's current carrier. That you may be satisfied with your current provider is no reason to miss out on the 50 bucks or better yet, to get paid for not switching. Go ahead and call your carrier to see if it will match the deal. Chances are it will, shrewdly spreading the rebate over several months to ensure your continued devotion.  <p> AT&T is generally a shade pricier than Sprint and MCI, but this behemoth has a flagship program that is proving popular. True Reach offers a 25 percent discount on all domestic calls for customers whose long-distance bills total more than $25. Bills between $10 and $24.99 receive a lowly 10 percent discount. But who wants to sit around figuring out if their bill is going to total $25? Clearly, it's for those pretty sure to make at least $25 worth of calls a month.  <p> If simplicity is your goal, the clear choice is Sprint. The Sprint Sense program offers a flat rate on interstate calls:10 cents a minute from 7 p.m. to 7 a.m., Monday through Friday and all day on weekends; 22 cents a minute from 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. during the week. There's no minimum usage before the discount kicks in. So any interstate ten-minute call after 7 p.m. costs a buck, plain and simple. What's more, a cash-back program offers a rebate of 10 percent of the year's total long-distance bill after 12 consecutive months in Sprint Sense. And unlike AT&T and MCI, which both vary rates slightly depending on the distance of some out-of-state calls, Sprint's rates are one-size-fits-all. <p> MCI's big deal is Friends and Family, but the company modified the best-known element of the promotion under the duress of heavy AT&T advertising suggesting that "calling circles" belonged next to McCarthyism on the list of intrusive practices. "That's right,we responded," says MCI customer representative Caroline Smith. "You don't want the list, we don't ask  the list." MCI's best possible deal on ten-minute evening (5 p.m. to 11 p.m.) call matches that of Sprint, but unlike MCI, Sprint doesn't care whatservice the person you're calling uses or how far away he or she lives.  <p> As if you don't have enough long-distance choices, there are also the  
so-called resellers. Companies such as Voice Net and Ameracall buy excess line capacity from the big three and sell long-distance service for less than the major leaguers. And since you access these companies by dialing a five-digit prefix or an 800 or 950 number, you don't need to replace your regular long-distance carrier to take advantage of prices that are scraping the cellar, particularly during the daytime.  <p> Time for a little treat: Fire up the Victrola. Remember Tommy Tutone's Big '80s classic, "867-5309"? You're going to save money; you've earned this dance.  <p> The final hurdle Take a deep breath, for you're about to call one of the nation's largest bureaucracies: the Social Security Administration. Open Monday through Friday, 7 a.m. to 7 p.m.,the agency is a patience tester no matter what, but the shortest waits are before 9 a.m. and after 4 p.m., Wednesday through Friday. When a human being finally replaces the saxy Muzak (no phone trees here we're talking about the U.S. government), ask for a copy of your earnings history. You'll get a form. You'll fill it out and send it back. And then you'll know if all your FICA donations that is, yours and those that your employer makes on your behalf are being recorded correctly. "Do this every five years," says Thomas Grass of the human-resources consulting firm Watson Wyatt Worldwide. Though they occur infrequently, discrepancies between the amount you've paid and the amount shown on your earnings history grow more difficult to reconcile as time elapses. Catch them early and you'll save yourself heartburn later.  <p> It's evening. Your mouth is dry and your fingers are ink-stained. Your ear rings and your neck cramps from shouldering the phone. Your eyes are glazed by cathode rays and you're wondering if life wasn't simpler in the eras of most of the shows you've watched. But look over there, in the corner where a mountain of bills, receipts, statements, and policies once teetered precariously. It's now an easily managed pillar of information, testimony to the organizational fire power you've expended. You sigh and reflect. It's been a day well spent.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency, Telecommunications Industry

