		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-What Comes After Success?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>What Comes After Success?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-What Comes After Success?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> WHAT COMES AFTER SUCCESS? <p>Why would anyone leave the lucrative security of a director's post at a major Wall Street investment house?  Nancy Havens-Hasty wants to prove she can go it alone.  <p> By Larissa MacFarquhar  <p> Nancy Havens-Hasty was one of the first female investment bankers on Wall Street possibly the first. In 1971, after graduating from Harvard Business School, she accepted an offer from the corporate-finance department of Kidder, Peabody. Then she moved on to Oppenheimer as an arbitrageur before settling in 15 years ago at <a name="NYSE:BSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10191"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bear Stearns</b></a>, where she rose to become co-head of the100-person high yield/bankruptcy department and the first woman elected to the firm's board of directors. Recently, she left to start her own hedge fund in a one-room office with a staff of two. Hedge funds, made famous by people such as George Soros and Julian Robertson, are limited partnerships of no more than 99 investors; each must have a minimum net worth of $1 million or annual earnings of at least $200,000. These funds are allowed to engage in riskier investment strategies than mutual funds are, and use options, short selling, and borrowed money in search of high yields. Writer Larissa MacFarquhar spoke to Havens-Hasty about her latest excellent adventure.  <p> WORTH: You were a Bear Stearns director. Why in the world would you give that up?  <p> HAVENS-HASTY: I was about to turn 50, I'd begun to think quality-of-life thoughts, and I realized that what I really got off on at my job was the straight forward investing figuring out the risk-reward of a situation, making the investment, and watching it go up or down. Now I can make pure investment decisions, whereas when I was on the brokerage side sometimes we would buy positions for the sake of a long-term relationship with a particular customer. It's nice to have just one goal, which is to make money.  <p> W:  You arrived on Wall Street in 1971, the year after Kate Millett's book Sexual Politics became a best-seller and the Justice Department filed its first sex-discrimination-in-the-work place suit. What was it like then being a woman in finance?  <p> H-H:  I'm battle-scarred, but it's also been fun, in some ways, being first. In the beginning there were a lot of silly barriers. My first office was called the bull pen, and it was definitely the first time they'd had a cow in there. A man there didn't want me to go to a particular job because the president said "damn" and used a spittoon! Some of the wives didn't want me to travel with their husbands.  <p> It was very difficult at first to convince people to send me to corporate clients, though corporations were way ahead of Wall Street in their acceptance of women. I ended up having a lot of clients that were considered less desirable within the firm. I had a lot of S & L's. I was a physics major and I had worked for <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>, but I had none of our computer clients. I did have everything that had anything to do with being female. I had a pie company. I had a manufacturer of fabric. Once, somebody suggested I become a cosmetics analyst. I never wear makeup!  <p> W:  Did you try to make yourself more acceptable to your bosses? <p> H-H:  I did, but especially at the beginning, I didn't do a good enough job presenting myself as someone who cared deeply about my work. There was an assumption right through the '80s that the men were more serious about their jobs than I was, and I didn't do enough to combat that. If I could do my career over again, I would take fewer vacations, and make a thing of it: you know, advertise the fact that I hadn't had one in a year. I would never mention the possibility that I might be going out on dates. I'm not naturally the kind of person who, if my work is done five minutes before my boss leaves, waits until five minutes after he leaves to go home, but I would do more of that if I had the perspective that I have now.   <p> W:  So how has being a woman affected your career?  <p> H-H:  It took me longer to get every promotion than it would have if I had been a man, but I was very lucky to be at a place like Bear Stearns, which is very bottom-line-oriented. These days, finance is a fairly nondiscriminatory profession because results are all that count. It's not like you can schmooze your way through bad numbers, you can't. They're right there in black and white.  <p> W:  What about the career/kids issue?  <p> H-H:  Put it this way: My second son was born at noon, and I was on the phone with my trader at 1:30. It was May of 1990, and I was in charge of the hot department at that time: bankruptcy. And when you're running a major department on Wall Street, especially a sexy department, if you leave for too long, they find someone to replace you. I had had a local anesthetic, but I knew I had a very short window of time before the epidural wore off and they put me on morphine or something, so I took advantage of that window! My trader was blown away. He said, "Nancy, you just had a baby," and I said, "Yes, but Greg, I want to know where these bonds are!" During the following three weeks that I took off, I probably talked to the office ten times a day.  <p> W:  Why start a hedge fund now, when many are having trouble outperforming bread-and-butter mutual funds?  <p> H-H:  Hedge funds are entirely driven by the individual managers and their investment strategies. So, for instance, while the people who specialize in shorting didn't have such a great year in 1995, the people who specialize in risk arbitrage had a wonderful year. There's almost nothing you can say about hedge funds in general.  <p> W:  What's your investment strategy?  <p> H-H:  I'll be investing in risk arbitrage and distress the two things I've been dealing in for the last several years. I'll also invest in junk bonds, but only high-quality junk bonds, if that's not an oxymoron: the ones that I believe have less than a 1 percent chance of having problems. I specialize in event-related investing, like bankruptcy. In a bankruptcy there's an event that ends the bankruptcy. In a merger, the merger happens. In a liquidation, the liquidation has a date. I like to be as insulated from the market as possible, and event-related investing allows me to be.  <p> W:  That sounds rather conservative. Aren't most hedge fund managers risk-takers looking for high returns?  <p> H-H:  To some degree that's true. But with a hedge fund you can actually make your plays more conservative because you have the flexibility to use instruments you can't use if you're running a mutual fund. In a market like this, where the averages are hitting new highs every day, if we find overvalued stocks, we can short them.   <p> I'm a very conservative investor. If you look at the numbers that I've turned out over the years, you'll see that I have a lower volatility than the indexes I'd be compared with, like the bankruptcy index. I don't do as well as they do in the best periods, but I do substantially better in the bad periods.  <p> W:  Do you ever take vacations? <p>I do, but I spend the first three or four hours of each day on the phone. That's why I like to go away out west. You can wake up at 6, spend three hours on the phone, and still get to your ski lesson at 9:30.  <p> One of my priorities in starting this fund was to eat breakfast with my children, and I'm pretty much doing that. I don't have many more hours at home, but when I'm there, I'm a lot less exhausted. What used to exhaust me before was the constant negotiations with customers, with other heads of departments but when you are dealing only with markets, with impartial forces, it doesn't take as much out of you.  <p> W:  At big firms, the logistics of doing business are taken care of. What's it like dealing with that yourself?  <p> H-H:When I was at Harvard Business School, I took this course called Starting New Ventures, and I decided I would never start one because there was just no end to the awful things you had to do. And in fact, getting the office set up has been even more difficult and time-consuming than I expected. This morning I spent an hour trying to get my computer to fax something! When Iwas at Bear Stearns, my assistant just called the computer person. <p> W:  Do you worry your fund will fail?  <p> H-H:  Not too much. I tell myself, You've done it before you should be able to do it again! But when you're starting out you cannot afford to make mistakes. You just can't. So this next year is extraordinarily crucial for me.  <p> You know, it doesn't take a genius to do well on Wall Street. It takes somebody who is incredibly thorough and finicky, a real perfectionist, and someone who is fairly competitive and doesn't like to make mistakes. But it's not rocket science. It's just hard work and being brutally honest about admitting that, when something's going down, you have made a mistake and should cut your losses. This is what I really love to do.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

