				<font size=5><b>The Sum of Our Dreams</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-The Sum of Our Dreams</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Feature  <p> THE SUM OF OUR DREAMS <p>What are your dreams? What annual income would you need to fulfill them?  <p> Contributors: Jane Birnbaum, Sara Corbett, Monica Corcoran, Carol Marie Cropper, Erik Cushman, Gretchen Reynolds, Donovan Webster  <p> Jerolim Vukic, 53  <p>Owner of a men's hair salon,  <p>New York City <p>$50,000 <p>"I'd go to the beaches in Florida, California, and all around the world. I'd rest nice in the sun and swim in the water. I love the water. I'd buy T-shirts, key chains, and hats for all my friends. I'd buy a speedboat and go fast."  <p>  <p>Christine Gingerich, 18 <p>Baker,  <p>Free Union, Virginia <p>$1,000 <p>"We're Mennonite Christians. We don't really have salaries. But I'd use that money to buy a few personal things--shoes, clothes. The rest of it I would send to missionaries working in the fields." <p>  <p>Fred Mark Dry, 46  <p>Attorney,  <p>Chicago <p>"$1 million a year, or the equivalent in future years based on inflation." <p>"I'd quit working. I'd live life. I'd work out, read all the books I've been meaning to read, spend more time with my family, spend more time on my sailboat. There's nothing really I want to buy. Maybe a bigger house. But I have everything else I want--the sailboat, the Mercedes. I'd just like the chance to enjoy it all more."  <p>  <p>George E. King, 40  <p>Construction worker,  <p>Mount Solon, Virginia <p>$35,000  <p>"I'd buy me a piece of land."  <p>  <p>Tom Lapsley, 38 <p>Bar owner,  <p>Santa Fe <p>$10 million <p>"I'd play a lot of golf, open a lot more bars. I'd have houses in New Mexico, Colorado, Boston, Hawaii, Italy, France, Hong Kong, San Francisco. My houses would be full of art, too. My country home, it'd be full of ... Rembrandts. But I myself wouldn't change much. I'd just be a very rich version of me."   <p>  <p>Mona Cavalli, 53 <p>Food vendor,  <p>Santa Fe <p>$250,000 <p>"I'd go to Africa on safari, to see the giraffes before they're gone. I'll stay in a tent, but I want a glass of wine when the day's over. I'd also go to Egypt, but after menopause so I have a sense of humor."  <p>  <p>Roque C. Garcia, 58 <p>Food vendor,  <p>Santa Fe <p>$500,000 <p>"I'd make myself a home on the land I already own, help my brothers and sisters pay debts. My hitos--my little grandchildren--can have whatever they want. I'd send 'em to college. Buy them little pickup trucks. I'd also invest in water like the French. They just put tap water into bottles and sell it."  <p>  <p>Noor M.E. Talaty, 47 <p>Newsstand manager,  <p>New York City <p>$35,000 <p>"That would be plenty. I only need $12,000 for rent. I would use $8,000 for food for my family in India and the rest for education. My children will have to work hard and get scholarships. My dream is that they become respectable people and lead a good life.I don't care about vacations or movies. In the past seven years, I've worked every day and haven't seen a single movie."  <p>  <p>Wendy Tokuda, 40+ <p>News anchor,  <p>Los Angeles <p>$10 million "just for breathing" <p>"I'd still work in news, but fewer hours. I'd set up a charitable foundation for at-risk children. I'd spend more time with my own children. And I'd have a small organic farm where I'd grow tomatoes and have a horse, chickens, and bees."  <p>  <p>Jack Jones, 76 <p>Drum maker, potter,  <p>San Juan Pueblo, New Mexico <p>$60,000 <p>"I'm a Christian. I support Oral Roberts's ministry. I'd give about 10 percent of my money to him to do ministry work in the poor countries. Also, my mother is living up in Utah with my other close kinfolk. They raise sheep and cattle, and maybe I'd buy some feed for them. It's a pretty bleak area up there."  <p>  <p>Yule Caise, 27 <p>filmmaker, actor,  <p>Venice, California <p>$60 million <p>"I'd like a salary on par with Michael Eisner's. I'd continue making the kind of films I love. I would go on a campaign to erase illiteracy and be the banner-holder of the renaissance of education for black America. I'd create a school that my mom would be head of. She'd be one of the highest-salaried teachers in the world."   <p>  <p>John Buchanan, 49 <p>Archival researcher, artist,  <p>Brooklyn, New York <p>$80,000 <p>"Money would buy me time, and I know what to do with time. I'd push my own art as far as I could. I'd go to southeast England and see the gardens ... find a wife in Southeast Asia ... buy the house I live in. But a windfall, in terms of money, for an artist could be highly destructive, because you stop doing your work."   <p>  <p>Christina Willis, 26 <p>Student,  <p>Missoula, Montana <p>$300,000 <p>"I'd like to buy a house on Cape Cod, in the Seattle area, in Montana, and a Swiss chalet. And then I'd like to be able to travel between those locations without having to spend too much time at some asinine job."  <p>  <p>Lise Stoessel, 41 <p>Nursery-school teacher,  <p>Charlottesville, Virginia <p>$1 million <p>"I'd support the arts ... Waldorf education and organic and biodynamic agriculture. I'd give my kids a good education ... travel the world ... build a house using environmentally-correct building methods. Yeah, I'd definitely use some of that million a year to get off the grid."  <p>  <p>Sharisse Tompkins, 31 <p>IRS revenue agent,  <p>Mesquite, Texas <p>$100,000 <p>"It would cover about all expenses and some new clothes and playtoys. We'd pay off our three-bedroom house with a garage you can't fit a car into ... go on some vacation ... buy a piano. I've been sort of broke the last eight years. All my money goes to day care. When you start making a decent amount, you have kids and that takes it all."  <p>  <p>Isabel Arevalo, 55  <p>Housekeeper,  <p>Los Angeles <p>$26,000 <p>"I have no dreams. The money would be completely eaten up by reality. There's the mortgage and a severely developmentally disabled grandchild living in my home with my daughter and her husband. My husband worked 15 years at a hospital doing housekeeping. He developed heart trouble and was laid off. Now that I'm old, I'd like some comfort: get a new job, go to school, cook and decorate cakes and make little party decorations for baby and bridal showers."  <p>  <p>Terry Beck, 41 <p>President of a computer business,  <p>Grand Prairie, Texas <p>$1 million <p>"I would use it for charity--maybe Christian schools. I would enjoy nicer vacations with my family ... probably build a home in the Tennessee mountains for my wife and her family. But I'm kind of satisfied. The more you get, the more you want, so if you're not satisfied with what you've got, you're never going to be satisfied."  <p>  <p>June Potthast, 60+ <p>Retired, Chicago <p>$500,000 <p>"I wouldn't want to live in a big mansion. I'd visit my brother in Long Beach and I'd buy him a couple of different colored sports jackets ... give some money to my retired friends who don't have enough. Let's see, I'd probably buy some new coats for my dog, Piko, too. He comes first now. I lost my sister and my mother, so I live alone with him."  

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
