<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Tough Lady, Tough Art</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Tough Lady, Tough Art</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Tough Lady, Tough Art</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> TOUGH LADY, TOUGH ART <p>She wasn't rich enough to be accepted by the art world. So Elaine Dannheisser went to work, building a collection the establishment couldn't ignore.  <p> By Arthur Lubow  <p> Elaine Dannheisser has always been interested in art, but it was not until she visited Europe for the first time in 1953 that she discovered her calling as an art patron. "When I came back, I read all I could about Gertrude Stein and Picasso," she says."I was so sorry that I didn't live in Paris in the 1920s and '30s.  Then I said to myself,  'I could do the same thing now.'" The center of the art world had shifted from Paris to New York, where Dannheisser lived. she was well situated to pursue her new vocation.   <p> The daughter of a florist-supply shop owner, Dannheisser grew up in Brooklyn. Her husband, Werner, was a German immigrant who had made a fortune by manufacturing engraving machinery across the river from Manhattan in Long Island City. Werner shared Elaine's love of art. He was particularly fond of French art of the 1920s and '30s, which he collected before he met and married Elaine in 1952. In the first year of their marriage, they bought an Utrillo together. "Top, top, top Utrillo," Elaine says. "Now, looking back on it, we should have been buying Picasso." The Dannheissers were ardent Francophiles, spending summers on the Riviera, visiting the Matisse chapel, the Maeght collection, and the other modern-art museums of Provence. Elaine read books about 20th-century French art and religiously attended auctions. She would clip magazine articles on art collectors.  <p> To be the wife of a prosperous husband in New York in the 1950s invited a certain way of life. "I would meet with a group of women for lunch at the Colony," Dannheisser, now a widow in her 70s, recalls of her ladies' club days. "Every time you had to wear a new outfit, with everything matching. I thought, 'My God, that's not what I want out of my life.'" Hoping to penetrate the art world, she resolved in the early 1960s to do volunteer work for an art museum. That decision would lead her on a path of studying, volunteering, donating, collecting, and in general hustling for more than 30 years.  <p> New York has three major modern-art museums: the Modern, the Whitney, and the Guggenheim. Dannheisser selected the Guggenheim, because she liked its Frank Lloyd Wright building on Fifth Avenue and because she lived nearby. She worked in a small office on the main floor, licking envelopes. She lasted a couple of months."There was an awful woman who was the head of development," she recalls. "Nobody stayed long."   <p> She placed her name on the waiting list for volunteers at the Whitney, and one day in the mid-1960s, the museum called. She became a full-time volunteer, reporting daily to her desk to coordinate fund-raisers and arrange art tours and studio visits for members. Her Whitney period ended with the arrival of Thomas Armstrong as the new director in 1974. "Elaine was a hard worker who wasn't treated very respectfully," says Berta Walker, a Provincetown, Massachusetts, art dealer who was a Whitney administrator at the time. Elaine felt that she lacked the social credentials to pass muster with Armstrong. He seemed to ignore her efforts to become more actively involved in the Whitney. "I was making all kinds of gestures and he wouldn't bite," she says. "He had bigger fish to fry." She still bristles when she tells the story of an invitation that she received to a tour for Whitney members of some private collections in Westchester County, just outside New York City. Knowing the tour would be over subscribed, she sent back her acceptance with a check the same day. She was so enthusiastic that she telephoned a friend and urged her to apply. The friend was accepted. Dannheisser was not. "I wrote Tom Armstrong a letter saying he was alienating his membership," she says."I hand-delivered the letter to his apartment house. He never even answered it."   <p> Armstrong admits he overlooked Dannheisser in favor of other collectors. "She obviously interpreted my behavior as not flattering to her," he says. "It wasn't intentional. Elaine was not a proven situation in those days. I suppose that I desperately tried to identify myself with people who had established themselves as very much engaged in collecting and could immediately help the Whitney Museum. It was a miscall. I didn't realize she could be brought along."   <p> After she quit the Whitney, Dannheisser was "floundering around, taking art courses." One day, late in 1977, her husband called her from his office to charge her with a new responsibility. For tax purposes, the Dannheissers had set up a foundation years before. To conform to a change in the tax code, they had to donate between $100,000 and $150,000 by the end of the year or else face an excise tax. Werner told Elaine to find a worthy recipient. <p> At last, Elaine had something more than her volunteer time to dangle before the museum directors. Thinking this could be her opportunity to forge a relationship with the grand old lady of the modern-art world, the Museum of Modern Art, she went to see a board member, who suggested that she become active in the prints division. "I thought that was a real put-down," she says. What she wanted was to launch her career in the art world by joining the MoMA painting and sculpture committee, which advises the museum on acquisitions. She called the head of development at MoMA and told him she would like to donate $100,000 or $150,000." He called back and said not to waste my money," she says. "He knew what I wanted. He said, 'It's not going to happen.'"   <p> So she knocked once again on the door of the Guggenheim, where, in the years since her brief tenure licking envelopes, she had become friendly with some of the staff. A lunch was arranged for her to meet Thomas Messer, the museum's director. They hit it off. As Messer recalls it, he suggested over lunch that Dannheisser might consider helping the museum acquire a significant painting and, if so, one of the Agnes Martin paintings then being shown at the Pace Gallery would be especially welcome. They went to the gallery directly from lunch and bought the picture. (Dannheisser says the Martin purchase was made some time after that introductory lunch.) The Guggenheim received the Dannheissers' contribution and became the new focus of Elaine's energies. Through Messer and the Guggenheim, Dannheisser made the leap from volunteering time to donating money.  <p> During messer's tenure, Dannheisser spent between $750,000 and $1 million on the acquisition of four paintings for the Guggenheim. "I wish I had ten Elaine Dannheissers as my friends," Messer says. Like most museums, when it wanted to buy something, the Guggenheim had to locate a patron willing to bankroll the purchase. Dannheisser's most important contribution to the Guggenheim washer acquisition of a Mark Rothko painting in 1978. She says it was her idea to buy a Rothko. Messer, who emphasizes how grateful he is, remembers that he and curator Diane Waldman decided which painting to buy in conjuction with the Guggenheim's Rothko retrospective. Presented with their choice, he says, Dannheisser agreed. At the time, the Rothko estate was reeling from legal turmoil, and the paintings were difficult to obtain. The estate was very choosy about where the paintings wound up, placing major pictures only with museums or first-rate collectors. Dannheisser says she wasn't interested in buying a Rothko unless it was "a great one" and she could get a great one only by buying it for a museum. Fifteen years later, she is still proud that the painting she bought was on the cover of the catalog to the Guggenheim's Rothko exhibition. Later she bought a Robert Rauschenberg and a Kenneth Noland for the museum.   <p> Then Dannheisser underwent a final metamorphosis: She started a collection. Over the years of their marriage, she and Werner had bought a number of paintings, most notably a Picasso and a Dubuffet, both of which still hang in her living room. In 1980, she decided to start collecting in earnest. That summer, Messer and his wife visited the Dannheissers at their weekend house in East Hampton, Long Island. Elaine says that the idea of buying a space to exhibit contemporary art came to her overnight. When she told Messer over the lunch table, he was enthusiastic. She recalls: "He said, 'That's a great idea. Why don't we do it with you? We'll get some great curator.' That sounded very exciting. Then I realized, 'My God, I'll be walking behind someone, writing out checks.' So I didn't do that. I did it myself."  <p> The first challenge was persuading Werner to buy her an exhibition space. She knew she would need a large warehouse. "With young artists you can't buy just a few things," she explains. "You can with blue-chip. But with young artists you need a broad spectrum. "Werner, who died of Parkinson's disease in 1992, was far more cautious than Elaine. "His middle name was 'Let's wait and think,'" she jokes. She believes that, after almost a year of vacillation, he acceded to her request for two reasons. First, he sold his factory, so he had cash on hand. About the same time, Elaine was diagnosed with cancer. He wanted to cheer her up. In 1981, he bought her the two lower floors of a former warehouse in Tribeca, which was once the butter-and-egg district of the city. Today, the Duane Street building is a few doors down from Bouley, one of the best restaurants in New York.  <p> Starting with what she describes as "a small budget of maybe $30,000 or $50,000 a year" (the budget eventually doubled), she became a collector of contemporary art. She was not alone. The1980s were the boom years of the art market. "Immediately, Werner and I started going to all the art fairs," she says. "It gave me a chance to know all the art. You got to know the dealers all over the world. The art world doesn't rise and set in New York." She joined the board of the New Museum, a downtown center for cutting-edge art, where she audited lectures and joined semimonthly studio visits. She would go to every dinner and party and opening for fear that if she didn't, she might miss making an important contact. "I was into the networking of the art world," she says."Then the East Village thing happened. Every Sunday, you went to the East Village, come hell or high water, and you boughtsomething impulsively. I read all the magazines. I lived and breathed art in the '80s. That's all I did." Art dealer Douglas Baxter, now at the Pace Wildenstein Gallery, says, "Besides taking care of Werner, her main occupation was her interest in art.She was like a professional."  <p> Dannheisser was collecting paintings by many of the celebrated artists of the time: David Salle, Eric Fischl, Ross Bleckner, Anselm Kiefer, Sigmar Polke. Reminiscing in her duplex apartment on Park Avenue, she describes how, after several years of buying paintings, she revised her acquisition strategy. "One day," she recalls, "I walked into my place on Duane Street and said, 'My God, this looks like a rich woman's East Side apartment.'" She sold almost all the paintings. (For a single Fischl, which she had purchased for $12,000 in 1981, she received $1.4 millionin 1989.) In 1985, when she was already in her 60s, she started buying video, conceptual, and installation art. "I don't think we're living in a time of painting," she says. "We're living in a period of new technology and electronics."  <p> As art prices appreciated at vertiginous rates in the 1980s, collectors scrambled to buy work by young painters whose prices seemed certain to soar. Since the demand exceeded the supply, gallery owners typically offered the best work only to their most loyal customers or, if they were hoping to build an artist's reputation, to museums. By focusing on conceptual and installation art, Dannheisser entered an area with fewer competitors than she had found in her quest for paintings. "I loved [Francesco] Clemente, and I never got a major Clemente, because Angela [Westwater, Clemente's dealer at the Sperone/Westwater Gallery] would never sell me one," she says. "Sometimes you would buy something else to get what you wanted. You had to be supportive of a gallery to get anything. It was such a cobweb of nuances. You couldn't walk in and say to one of these women and they were mostly women 'Iwant this.' They would look at you as if you were crazy. Mary[Boone] never wanted to sell me a great [Julian] Schnabel, soI never bought one and now I'm very happy."   <p> Certainly, art in the late 1980s was a seller's market. But once Dannheisser focused on more controversial and, in many cases, bulky sculptures that a collector could not display in an apartment, she began demanding and getting the important pieces a collection needs to garner respect. "You have to ask, 'Is this a major work? Is it a signature piece of the artist?'"Angela Westwater says."I think Elaine has come to that thinking. I don't think her standards were always at the heights they reached. I think the process of identifying works that were major pieces became important to her later on." Dannheisser matured along with her collection."There's a confidence that comes with more experienced collecting, which gives one the patience to wait," Douglas Baxter says. "When people are less experienced, they're a bit more edgy about not being the first to get something which may only lead to a dealer not wanting to give them immediate gratification."  <p> On a warm afternoon last spring, Dannheisser conducted a personal tour of her collection. She was wearing her usual curly gray-blond wig. Her green eyes were accented by plucked eyebrows and turquoise mascara. She had a powdered-on tan complexion. She was wearing a red Sonia Rykiel jacket with gold buttons, a cranberry-colored silk blouse, and Moschino plaid trousers. Dannheisser has a perky manner but seems perpetually a bit off balance which may be a result of cataract operations more than half a century ago that left her blind in her left eye.  <p> Entering the first-floor gallery on Duane Street (the basement below provides studio space for two artists who help take care of the collection), Dannheisser and a visitor were aurally bludgeoned by the soundtrack of a Bruce Nauman video that intoned, with maniacal insistence, "Think! Think! Think!" By the door was a Rebecca Horn assemblage composed of two paintbrushes mounted to a motorized contraption, and, beneath them, a bunch of crude wooden picture frames attached by metal rods at different angles to the wall; the wall and the frames are splattered with blue and black paint. A Joseph Beuys on the other side of the roomis a mysterious array of a galvanized iron bucket, a cheap white enameled basin, a glass jar with an encrusted bottom that sits on a film-reel canister, and a stack of old film prints on top of which are two rubber stamps bearing the artist's name.   <p> In an alcove that normally houses a Nauman work, Learned Helplessness in Rats, Dannheisser had placed a Robert Gober bed and, above it, a Gober barred window. There was a large Nauman drawing (later manufactured into a neon sculpture, which Dannheisser kicks herself for not buying) that was one of the collector's first ventures into conceptual art. It depicts two men in superimposed poses, thrusting guns and penes into their own and each other's mouths. On seeing it offered for $10,000 in a Chicago gallery in 1985, Dannheisser knew immediately that she must have it. "I always was a very impulsive person, and I always make my mind up very quickly," she says. "I tell myself, 'If you have to think about it, you shouldn't have it.' I never intellectualized about it. I never had to meet the artist. I never had to understand it completely. If it did something to me, I would buy it."  <p> Dannheisser weaved swiftly through the handsome exhibition space, identifying each work by its maker's name a Reinhard Mucha here, a Carl Andre and a Matthew Barney and a Cindy Sherman there. The art was not organized by any evident principle, but occasionally, a fortuitous juxtaposition arose. For instance, the source of the maniacal "Think!" was two TV monitors, one on top of the other, each showing a man's head (shouting "Think!") bouncing up and down like a basketball. Right nearby was the famous Koons of three basketballs floating in an aquarium. Dannheisser seemed to have a special affection for certain artists, such as Nauman, Gober, and Richard Serra. "He's very important to me," she would say. She describes the sort of art she prefers as "tough art." On a countertop just outside the bathroom, in the one somewhat homey touch, was a pair of portraits of Elaine and Werner by Robert Mapplethorpe.  <p> Considering that she was surrounded by her collection, Dannheisser seemed none too comfortable on Duane Street. She hadn't been coming down there much recently. Of course, it was difficult to feel comfortable with Nauman's voice shouting "Think!" every few seconds. "It drives you crazy," Dannheisser said. "Maybe I should shut it off." She was happy to leave for lunch, at a place she chose a SoHo art hangout, Mezzogiorno. When she walked into the restaurant, she was greeted effusively by a fellow diner, Antonio Homem, co-proprietor of the Sonnabend Gallery. She was mid-pasta when another famous art dealer, Leo Castelli, entered. Dannheisser tried to catch his eye but couldn't. On the way out, she stopped at his table, and Castelli too spoke to her with urbane warmth. Dannheisser glowed.    <p> Once Dannheisser resolved to build a collection of her own, she stopped underwriting purchases for the Guggenheim. Other museums began courting her. Even more important than her financial support although, especially for the smaller institutions, that could be significant the main prize now was the growing collection. Childless, the Dannheissers were inclined to bequeath their art to a museum. Although Elaine's strongest museum relationship was with the Guggenheim, she had not committed herself. And her ties to the Guggenheim began to fray after Messer left in 1988 and Thomas Krens replaced him as director. "Tom Krens was another Tom Armstrong," she says. "Arrogant, hot shot, slick, very condescending."She felt that in his pursuit of super-rich benefactors, suchas Ronald Perelman and Samuel LeFrak, he was ignoring the less rich. Busy setting up new branches of the Guggenheim as far afield as Spain and Italy, Krens had little time available, and Dannheisser didn't make the cut. She was offended when he dispatched Lisa Dennison "a second-tier curator," she sniffs; "he didn't even come himself" to ask her to give the museum her major work by Beuys, to appear in a 1992 show to mark the museum's opening of its branch in SoHo. (She refused.)   <p> Her relationship with the Guggenheim hit bottom at a dinner for benefactors in late 1994. Having been bored at some previous Guggenheim events, she brought along a friend. When they arrived, they found they had been seated separately. "I was put with five Japanese women who don't speak English," Dannheisser recalls. "And the seat next to me was empty." A couple of months later, she resigned from the Guggenheim board. "Tom Krens never even sent me a 'sorry' note," she says. "He really is unbelievable."(Krens would not comment.)  <p> Disenchanted now with both the Whitney and the Guggenheim, where would she turn? Although she had served on the board of the New Museum and on the board of advisors of the Dia Foundation, which are the best-known New York institutions devoted exclusively to contemporary art, neither institution was large enough or distinguished enough to satisfy Dannheisser's ambitions.  <p> Her thoughts returned to the Modern. She was no longer the unknown Park Avenue matron with a Picasso and a Dubuffet, the woman who volunteered for museum work and was directed to the prints division. She was a leading collector of Nauman, Koons, and Gober favorites of the Modern's painting and sculpture curator, Kirk Varnedoe. When TV newsman Morley Safer last year sought a prominent collector to defend the contemporary art that he was savaging on 60 Minutes, Dannheisser was the one he interviewed. She was a personage. In 1989, Agnes Gund, then the chairman of the MoMA's painting and sculpture committee, had invited her to join the panel, which meets every couple of months. "It came about as a mutual synergy," says Gund, now president of MoMA. "Everyone was aware that she was a collector with an interest in art that very few people had. She was in the forefront of collecting certain people."  <p> Although membership on the committee carries a high price an expected annual contribution of $25,000 it is a position people vie for. Membership had been Dannheisser's goal at the start of her museum patronage career. But her ambitions had swelled with her collection. What she wanted even more now was to join the museum's International Council, which convenes semiannually for a week of meetings and dinners. Last year, with Gund's sponsorship, she was asked to join the council. "The minute I resigned from the Guggenheim, the relationship with the Modern became more relaxed," she says.  <p> Dannheisser is warmly disposed toward Varnedoe, but her primary relationship at the Modern is with Gund. Gund has made Dannheisser feel appreciated. "When we have lunch, Aggie says, 'I'm so glad you're going to come on the board,'" Dannheisser says. "I think they have respect for my ideas and what I think." Although not a bridge player, Gund has accompanied Dannheisser to her bridge club. Last year, when Dannheisser underwent a gall bladder operation, Gund visited her twice in the hospital. "And she has no airs," Dannheisser says approvingly. "She's very down to earth." For her part, Gund says, "I've gotten very fond of Elaine. I don't feel I'm doing it as a job. I'm doing it because I like her." <p> Although the details are still to be worked out, Dannheisser has decided that the Museum of Modern Art will be the final resting place of her collection. In return, she expects or, it might be more accurate to say, demands a few things: She will be asked to join the board of trustees, her collection will be spotlighted in a special show, and a catalog of the collection will be published. She plans no stipulations on how her art must be displayed. She says she doesn't even much care if the Museum of Modern Art sells off some of her acquisitions. "They want to be able to sell things and buy others in my name, which is fine with me," she says."I'm not one of those people that love everything they have. I get rid of things myself to buy the work of another artist." <p> Once some legal matters are settled, perhaps as early as this fall, Dannheisser will be asked to join the MoMA board. "We would like to have her on the board," Gund says. "It's not going to be something where she has to sit in the middle of the road and scream, 'I want to be on the board.' But it hasn't been dealt with yet." Her ascension to the board will be a quiet affair. The festivities will come when the museum presents a selection of Dannheisser's work in a special show. The party to celebrate the opening will be the perfect payoff for the countless networking parties she has attended. Looking back, Dannheisser is not quite sure how it all happened. "Once I climbed Mount Etna it's a long story and when we got out of the jeeps, I wondered, 'What amI doing here?'" she says. "And then someone pushed me, one leg and then the other, until I got to the top. When I was building my collection, I never realized it was going to be such a good collection. I just went with it. And I still don't understand sometimes what people are raving about." <p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

