	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Information-Age Billionaires Need Love, Too</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Information-Age Billionaires Need Love, Too</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Donald Katz<p>Michael Bloomberg, information-age billionaire and self-proclaimed Colonel Sanders of the high-tech financial-news scene, slaloms through the copper rain forest of sculptures and fountains in the lobby of Manhattan's Grand Hyatt Hotel. He descends via escalator into a crowd of media and technology pros gathered for yet another conference called to discuss the whys, wherefores, and imminent profitabilities of the convergence of old-fashioned media and new digital technologies. Bloomberg acknowledges the freshly composed smiles and hearty hellos"Mike ... Hey, Mike"that rise from within the large crowd. It's clear that most of the conference attendees know exactly who he is, and from Bloomberg's perspective, this is the world as it ought to be.<p>"I was out late last night at a dinner party with some Wall Street people," Bloomberg had mentioned on the way from his Park Avenue office to the new-media conference, an affair sponsored by the venerable banking house Alex. Brown & Sons. "There was a journalist there and two other couples, and they all knew who I was, even though I didn't know them. You know, you get in that situation, and ... well, you love it. On the other hand, it's very humbling when people don't know who you are. Even people in the business you would think would have to knowespecially after all that money we spend in advertising."<p>Every day it becomes more difficult to imagine an urban American failing to recognize Mike Bloomberg's name. In the car on the way downtown, a voice hailing from the New Yorkbased Bloomberg Information Radio station had intoned the Bloomberg name a dozen times between machine-gun updates of the latest prices and market trends. Other Bloomberg radio outlets were meanwhile repeating Mike Bloomberg's last name in France, Belgium, and Spain. Dozens of public television stations and several cable TV networks were reciting the Bloomberg mantra during Bloomberg Business News reports. Other televised Bloomberg news items were being beamed via satellite to London, Frankfurt, and Milan. The New York Times business section had that morning run a number of short articles attributed to Bloomberg's army of 375 business reporters stationed in 56 worldwide bureausthis just a few pages from a huge advertising banner that spelled bloomberg in vertical type down one side of a full page.<p>On the previous Sunday morning, some 6 million copies of a personal-finance supplement called Bloomberg Personal had fallen out of newspapers in 18 American cities, and as soon as the big <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> building rises over Times Square, five long blocks west of the Grand Hyatt Hotel, the bas-relief bloomberg sign that now curves bulbously around the corner of West 45th Street and Broadway will be joined by a computer-driven megasign that will cover an entire facet of the new office tower with all kinds of real-time information flashing beside yet another multistoried bloomberg.<p>But these are only the more public displays of Mike Bloomberg's cultural and economic status. A large percentage of the men and women at the conference had come from offices outfitted with special computer terminals with the word bloomberg inscribed above the on/off switch. A "Bloomberg," as such a terminal is known, is by now more essential to a great many financial professionals' desktops than pencils or Prozac.<p>A Bloomberg is the only way to get Bloomberg Financial Markets, a service that instantly offers up information about activity on dozens of global markets. It will deliver the latest news about any public company, as well as historical details about the company's securities and business results. Years before other computer screens went Technicolor, Bloomberg's were already presenting the firm's elite clients with intricate multicolored charts and graphs delivered on demand. A Bloomberg will impart the most arcane and many-variabled analyses of bond prices, or audio renditions of a CEO addressing shareholders, or instantly comparable data about that CEO's stock options and related pay-outs, or gossip from the vaulted halls of the Bundesbank, or reports on the weather and traffic outside a user's window, or up-to-the-minute results of the latest cricket match in Perth or sumo wrestling combat in southern Japan.<p>The Bloomberg is a control freak's dream machine. It displays an instant sense of the measurable world held in momentary stasisparticularly that part of the world connected to money. The machine generates a mechanical and electronic reduction of dozens of societies in motion, with all the related data edited, considered from hundreds of different angles, refitted to any number of customized matrices and analytical methods, digitized, and then mainlined through telephone wires. The Bloomberg is a miniaturized CIA for money workers who crave the illusion of control, and Bloomberg users will tell you that jockeying the screens quickly becomes an addiction. In certain Wall Street houses the Bloomberg junkies around the office are called "infomaniacs." <p>Some 53,000 Bloombergs sit on desktops worldwide, each costing its user $1,100 a month or more, and despite the recent rush of older and more deep-pocketed rivals into the desktop land grab, Bloomberg's user population has grown by 40 percent annually for all but one of the past five years. Bloomberg has become a global brand according to any number of standards.<p>Yet Mike Bloomberg can still perceive a generalized awareness gap separating Bloomberg, the extremely profitable financial information system; Bloomberg, the nascent media and multimedia empire; and Bloomberg, the driven and emotional working-class wise guy from Boston who recognized the value of computerizing financial equations for professionals when most of them were still using scratch pads and bound volumes of charts.<p>Pioneer and billionaire though he may be at age 53, Bloomberg will rest only when that gap finally closes.<p>"Sure, okay, I'm a media mogul," Bloomberg replies when asked to confirm the obvious. "I'm not married to Jane Fonda, and I don't raise buffalo in Montana like Ted Turner. But I do have a 6 millioncirculation magazine. I've got a 100,000-circulation magazine. I've got worldwide television and radio tuned to me. I've got the fastest-growing computer-networking company. So by those standards, yeah, a media mogul."<p>But in true contemporary media-mogul fashioneven as his name flies across thousands of wireline systems, through the air, and through outer space, and is festooned across urban vistas and recited over and over from digital minarets everywhereit isn't enough.<p>Bloomberg regards his notoriety and a flourishing New York social life as indications of how far he's come from a working-class boyhood. His father was a nose-to-the-grindstone bookkeeper at a small dairy in Somerville, Massachusetts, and Bloomberg grows reflective and soft-spoken when he describes childhood Sundays when his father took him along to work. His mother still lives in the small house where Michael and his sister grew up.<p>Bloomberg's own two children make weekend jaunts with their father to horse shows in Virginia and to meetings at their private schools; he describes the distance between his own hardscrabble youth and the privileged life he provides for his children with the shorthand joke "My kids wouldn't date me." Bloomberg's capacity for self-knowledge is one reason friends and colleagues take pleasure in his success and even enjoy his obsessive efforts to insert his last name into every view and soundtrack.<p>"Do I care what people think?" Bloomberg self-inquires when the conversation turns to the vagaries of legacy, fame, and personal satisfaction. "Am I flattered when people say, Oh, there's Mike Bloomberg'? Well, yeah. The other night I was having a drink with this woman after a party, and she says, I found it so-o-o fascinating that people kept deferring to you at the party.' Now keep in mind where she's coming from. A widow who doesn't want to stay that way. You were the center of attention,' she says. Yeah, because there were a bunch of bankers there after me to do deals, and I was clearly wealthier than the rest."<p>Bloomberg is not, as yet, mentioned with regularity in New York gossip columns, but he is beginning to socializedivorced as he has been for two years nowwith women who are. "Then again," Bloomberg notes, "how many single heterosexual billionaires do you think there are, fer Chrissakes?"<p>For all the fun he obviously has at work and play, Bloomberg seems to suffer a fate similar to that of other business kingpins who charm or philanthropize themselves into elevated social circles. Once they're inside, the very perspicacity (or paranoia or field-commander insight) that aided their climb to power seems to undermine the possibility of their ever gaining a satisfying sense of where they stand. "It's like with academics," Bloomberg says of his nonbusiness areas of personal pursuit. "You can't measure performance or value, so they all get lost in back-stabbing and politics."<p>Since he's too smart to misread a banker on the prowl or a widow on the make, Bloomberg remains most comfortable in business, which offers a measure of what can be trusted and believed. "After a point, dollars, as has been said so often," Bloomberg says, "are just ways of keeping score."<p>Bloomberg is different, though, from most of the others dominating information businesses. For he has known the intimate association of menand that's what they all werefor whom ego and the use of money as a way of keeping score were entwined and celebrated in ways not on display in America since the turn of the century. <p>Back at Salomon Brothers during the late 1970s, "Bloomy" was known around the equities desk as the sane one. A partner of the firm at age 30, Bloomberg had risen to the top of the equities desk at the investment bank alongside two legendarily wild and crazy guys of the moment's Wall Street scenea brilliant and personally excessive fellow named Jay Perry, and a brilliant and profoundly Machiavellian fellow named Dickie Rosenthal. <p>Bloomberg had come to Salomon in 1966 after working his way through Johns Hopkins University and then attending Harvard Business School. "Goldman Sachs offered me a job at $14,500 a year and Salomon offered one for $9,000," he recalls. "But Goldman had some very specific role and position in mind. At Salomon, they said, We don't know what you'll do, just come in and learn.' And I thought that made more sense."<p>Eventually Rosenthal (who taught Bloomberg how to fly and later died at the controls of his own plane) jockeyed himself into the upper echelons of the firm over Perry (who also died young, of leukemia, not long thereafter). In 1979 Bloomberg left the equities hot zone for the decidedly unsexy information-systems side of the business. Sixteen years ago, most stock and bond traders still tended to sit at their desks with books and pamphlets piled all around them. They would hit the books to figure out yields, and they would scour their desks for the company "B-page" that listed the securities the firm had on the books that day. Quotron screens were by then offering general price information on desktops, but none of it was customized to the needs of a bond-oriented firm or an individual.<p>Bloomberg, who had studied engineering and physics at Johns Hopkins and was not afraid of technical matters, worked to set up a computer system that allowed traders to quickly assess all sorts of information about securities, as well as news and even messages from colleagues. It did irk him to note that as soon as he left the trading desk, the financial markets came alive and trades that used to move in 10,000-share units were suddenly jumping around in 100,000-share pieces. But then again, in 1981, Salomon Brothers was merged with the Phibro Corp. commodities-trading firm, and Bloomberg and the 61 other partners at Salomon Brothers got huge payouts of cash and convertible bondsportents of the surreal Wall Street windfalls to come.<p>Bloomberg's take was reportedly about $20 million. "I became a charter member," he recalls, "of the lucky-sperm club."<p>But late that same year, Bloomberg was asked to leave the company. "I loved Salomon Brothers," he says now. "I would have stayed there forever if they hadn't thrown me out."<p>In Bloomberg's version, he "lost the confidence of the executive board," for reasons having to do with his being a strongly opinionated "pain in the ass." But it's hard to find evidence of particularly fiery clashes or former colleagues who remember him as a great challenger of authority. It seems that the Bloomberg tempermost often described in terms of his penchant for slamming telephones against hard surfacesflourished more fully once he was out on his own. "Everybody would be a lot better off if we yelled and screamed and said so when we're annoyed," he says. "Keeping it in and pledging to get somebody later is how wars start."<p>Immediately after leaving Salomon, Bloomberg combined some of his own new capital with $30 million in seed financing from <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> to launch a service business called Innovative Market Systems. The new company offered a hardware-based financial information and analysis system similar to the one he had managed at Salomon Brothers. Bloomberg anointed the product with the bland moniker Market Master.<p>"I didn't want my name on the product or the business at first," Bloomberg says. "I didn't want people to think it was just me. Pretty stupid, huh?"<p>One thing Mike Bloomberg loves to do these days is give a speech. He holds forth in a fast, slightly nasal, streetwise manner at varied gatherings several times each week, invariably without the aid of text or a single note. He contends that his appearances are essential to his role as his organization's perambulating brand name. Hence the line, one of his favorites, about being his organization's Colonel Sanders. "Reuter is dead," he says. "Dow is dead. Jones is dead. Knight is dead. Ridder is dead. So we have an advantage. I'm alive."<p>In the few days before the Alex. Brown conference, Bloomberg had gotten up to speak before a conclave at Johns Hopkins, where he is the chairman-elect of the board of trustees. He'd spoken at a First Boston conference and traveled to Frankfurt to give a speech. And he'd held forth in his rapid-fire, free- associative way via satellite to a group in Sydney, Australiafrom a studio in Denver. Bloomberg describes with great enthusiasm a 1994 speaking event in Tokyo at which he was positioned three stages above a huge audience wearing translation headphones. "Bill Gates was there tooand this was a year and a half ago ... when Gates was bigger than he is now, and I was smaller than I am now. It was heady stuff."<p>At the Alex. Brown conference, Bloomberg's words seem to emanate directly from fierce synaptic processes playing out in his head. He easily unravels a vision of technology advancing so rapidly that the Bloomberg delivery system no longer holds a technological edge. "The purely technical battles are ones we will lose," he says quickly, "because once you fill a screen faster than the eye can take it in, or offer resolution the eye can't discern or audio better than the ear can perceive, you can't take it farther. There is no stopping technology. ... You already see pictures of terrorists and African bushmen using cellular phones. Five years from now you will have unlimited bandwidth at zero cost, and infinite computing capacity, too. So this is why two thirds of the 2,000 people working for our company are working on content. And the content is why Bloomberg will eventually have a channel on every cable system in the world."<p>This last reference is to the new 24-hour Bloomberg Information TV system, which is provided free to cable operators and which top-of-the-line desktop Bloombergs now receive. When the system is fully in place, Bloomberg TV will appear in little anchor-person windows in one corner of every Bloomberg screen. If you don't activate the system for a given period of time, the Bloomberg presenter will reappearthe news anchor as screen-saver.<p>As his speech progresses, Bloomberg speaks even more quickly and without pause. In the back room, the columnist George F. Will, who is scheduled to speak during the lunch break, takes in Bloomberg's performance. "Now here is a man," says Willa fellow not unaccustomed to self-appreciation"who is in love with the sound of his own voice."<p>Later, at a smaller "breakout session" attended by a dozen investors and money managers, Bloomberg continues to describe technological advances, including some that will not entirely change life as we know it: "For instance, you see a pile of boxes in a warehouse and you want to know which box has the ribbed condoms inside. Well, there'll be a chip in the box to tell you. Hit the button, and you'll know where the condoms are." New technologies will become simple commodities, Bloomberg argues, shifting power from phone and cable companies and into the hands of the providers of content. <p>Bloomberg has already made himself rich by marrying "content," as everything from dictionaries to digital pornography is known in the new media scene, with the communicative capacities of the computer. He has accomplished without much celebrationas he will observethe very thing that hundreds of entertainment, media, and communications companies are investing in and forging alliances to pull off. "Today the gatekeeper is still the distributor," he says at the breakout session. "You don't give [John] Malone [leader of the TCI cable television empire] or [Gerald] Levin [CEO of <a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Time Warner</b></a>] a piece of the action, and you're really fucked."<p>At this, the eyes of a woman wearing a Nancy Reagan knit suit and sitting across from Bloomberg appear to begin watering. The man next to her looks down and starts tracing nervous circles on the tablecloth with his water glass.<p>"The business-information market our business is in really is much smaller than people think," Bloomberg continues. "The Wall Street Journal sells 1.8 million copies a day. Now the population of the United States is 250 million. So less than 1 percent get The Wall Street Journal, and you can make the argument that few people who care about business don't get it. Non-O.J. news and business information describe a small marketplace. Business news is upscale and you can sell advertising against it, but it's small."<p>"How can you say that?" the man drawing circles pauses to ask. "Look at business television. Look at CNBC." <p>"CNBC!" shoots back Bloomberg, who would prefer to envisage his own ventures as competition for CNN instead of CNBC. "CNBC's ratings are an asterisk, a big zero! UPI and Reuters are trying to replicate CNBC, but there's very little there. All CNBC has done is replace the boardroom at the retail brokerage office. The old guy in Florida who used to go sit around at Merrill Lynch and watch the ticker for entertainmentmaybe buying 100 shares here and thereis the viewer of CNBC. CNBC also offers you next week's prices.' Analysts come in and tell you next week's price. Even though they just don't know. It's no better than infomercials. Who gives a shit?"<p>"I guess I should watch my language," Bloomberg muses later. "I'm sure there are people who don't like me because of it. An article in The Wall Street Journal once called me profane.' My mother read it, and she said, Ya see, just like I always told you.' I said, Oh, bullshit.'"<p>"What he's evolved is a magnificent front," says Morris W. Offitt, one of Bloomberg's buddies from the Salomon days and now a Wall Street banker-to-the-rich. "The brashness and the tough-guy routine are drawn from trading-room style. He's quite ... well, tender."<p>"People might not like me because I'm brash," Bloomberg says matter-of-factly. "People might not like me because I'm Jewish, because I'm short. Sometimes people just aren't going to like you. I'm not particularly refined at times, and I should probably watch myself. People will say to me, Sure, it's easy for you to say whatever you want and speak your mind now that you're wealthy and powerful.' I usually reply, How do you think I got wealthy and powerful? Thank you.' But the truth is, I've always been a wiseass. I was a wiseass back when I thought a six-pack and a ride on the Staten Island Ferry was a great date.<p>"Then again," Bloomberg says reflectively, "maybe I would have been even wealthier and more powerful if I had learned to keep quiet. Who knows?"<p>It turned out that soon after Bloomberg began selling his expensive but quickly delivered and carefully packaged information (his name went on the machines in 1985), the number and kind of customers willing to pay for it began to multiply by the day. Among Bloomberg's first paying customers were brokerage-house analysts and global monitors at the World Bank. Traders of government bonds and other debt instruments were also early fans of Bloomberg boxes, but a more generalized craving for financial data seemed to intensify as the bull market propelled the financial-services industry toward enormous cultural prominence.<p>The potential value and imagined security borne of superior access to financial information has been a subject of interest to money professionals since the Battle of Waterloo and the genesis of haute finance. It was in the summer of 1815apocryphal though much of the tale isthat Nathan Rothschild and his banker brothers are said to have used their private system of carrier pigeons and "post boys" to ascertain the joyous news that General Wellington had prevailed against the Frenchand then to spread through London the terrible news that Wellington had failed and all was lost. The Rothschilds bought heavily into the plunging London currency and equity markets, as the story goes, before sitting back in the parlors of various overstuffed clubs to wait for the truth of the great British victoryand the attendant windfall profitto arrive by slow boat.<p>During the 1980s, the galloping increases in raw computing power and the flourishing of complex securities markets created new capabilities and demands for high-tech information delivery. Traders looked over their shoulders for fear that faster "analytics"the specialty of the original Bloombergswould allow a competitor looking at a different screen to blindside his or her trading strategy. Portfolio managers on the phone with someone trying to sell them a few million dollars' worth of bonds needed to believe they had access to the same data as the seller.<p>The general public also clamored for information access, the perception being that the Wall Street wealth machine was connected to breaking news. Takeover rumors in particular created the belief that fast access to news would make you rich. In 1988, still in the afterglow of the market-crash trauma of a year earlier and the resulting perception that information insiders got out before the fall, full-page ads from Bloomberg's competitors began to appear in newspapers, offering "Wealth Insurance." "Can a $29.95 membership in Dow Jones News/Retrieval really help ensure your personal wealth?" the ads inquired.<p>The answer, according to Bloomberg and most other money pros, wasand still isabsolutely not. As Nicholas Leeson, the cocky 28-year-old Barings PLC trader, recently demonstrated via losses that cost his nose-in-the-air old-line banking firm its solvency, access to a great wall of glowing screens cannot impart the ability to truly see.
"Success," as one of the Bloomberg Information Radio ad lines puts it, "is simply information plus imagination."<p>"That individual investors would necessarily do better if they could afford Bloombergs is a myth," Mike Bloomberg says. "In the end, investment success is about judgment, a bit of luck, and some diversification to make up for the fact that nobody is that smart or that lucky all the time. Some of the pros managing other people's money with our terminals at hand don't do any better with their personal portfolios than non-pros. On the other hand, I certainly hope the perception that the technology is requiredin some cases so that fiduciaries can have machines as a prophylactic against lawsuitscontinues to spread. People are essentially herd players."<p>Bloomberg saw early that technology would continually enforce the imperatives it creates. If your competitor has a remote paging system and you have only a phone answering machine, the perception of his or her superior access to quicker connections argues for the purchase of a new pager. Bloomberg stats-hounds now have access to some 7,000 different analytical protocols. A customer with an idea for a new way to compare prices or securities or market reactions can phone a Bloomberg software specialist, who will customize mathematical filters and algorithms on the fly. <p>But there are only so many serviceable angles from which to observe prices, and many business and financial managers don't put much stock in intricate technical analysis or instant responses anyway, so Bloomberg has continuously flooded the virtual files behind his clients' screens with more information. He has added 20 services a month to the system for several yearsanalyses of arcane Far Eastern securities located just a keystroke away from horoscopes and fishing columns and a service for ordering flowers.<p>Several years ago, Bloomberg's much larger competitorsnotably the hidebound and bureaucratic century-old British house of Reuters and the hidebound and bureaucratic century-old American house of Dow Jonesvowed to present new high-tech "Bloomberg killers." But Bloomberg and his army of kid reporters continue to flourish, though lately even Mike Bloomberg has wondered how long the bull market in Bloomberg can last.<p>Some observers of the recent slowdown in the spread of Bloomberg terminals (growth is down to 1,050 terminals a month, as compared with 1,100 a month in recent years) say that Bloomberg should abandon his custom-made, monogrammed terminals and sell his stuff as software anyone can use. "Yeah? Well go buy a PC and put Windows on it," Bloomberg scoffs. "It'll crash every day. We do better with our own hardware." (Bloomberg is a pragmatist, though, and later he acknowledges that he is considering selling the software and wire feeds that would allow his services to appear on non-Bloomberg PCs.)<p>"Our growth has only slowed a bit," Bloomberg says. "The problem is that Wall Street is contracting. I can't do much about Goldman Sachs going from five floors in a building in Hong Kong to three floors. They are going to need fewer terminals. They let go 10 percent of their workforce, they need fewer terminals."<p>Bloomberg's new vision of growth involves forging into the world of general news and information and selling "110 percent of what I have"by which he means constant repackaging of the upward of 2,000 news stories his reporters gather and the 30 different interviews with CEOs and other business figures they generate and update during a day. Bloomberg seems to be moving from a customized and narrowed system into a mass-media marketplace. The strategy mirrors the way business and financeand its data and institutions and myriad heroeshave muscled from their specialized corner into the general cultural purview, but many people wonder whether Bloomberg isn't taking a terrible chance.<p>So the bankers and deal makers of the media scene tell Bloomberg he must hedge his bets and go public or sell off equity to raise cash for his new ventures. For more than a year, periodic rumors have told of leveraged buyouts, initial public offerings, and takeovers. Bill Savoy, the money manager who runs the $4.6 billion portfolio of <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> co-founder Paul Allen, has tried to get Bloomberg to talk turkey on the phone, and Bloomberg just says, "No thanks," and then says he has to go.<p>Bloomberg is approached several times a week, orif he's among the right crowdseveral times at once. As he starts to leave the Alex. Brown conference, talking of Rollerblading (" ... so I hadn't learned to stop, but I'm going down this hill trying to keep up with a great view of this gorgeous woman, and I totally wipe out and"), he is interrupted by a grinning banker. "Mike!" says the man, grasping Bloomberg's hand and moving close to murmur into his left ear.<p>"No, thank you," Bloomberg says in full voice as he straightens up and breaks away. "Not for me."<p>Another man, in pinstripes and tortoise-shell glasses, approaches and begins to whisper in Bloomberg's other ear. "You're welcome to come in and talk to me," Bloomberg says in a loud voice before the whisperer finishes whispering. "But I'm just not interested."<p>Bloomberg rushes out to the street, where buses and taxicabs decorated with his name ply the avenues. "Sometimes you do find yourself looking at it all and wondering if you can keep it going," he says, drawing in a long breath. "It's a scary thought."<p>The lobby of the main Bloomberg Business News offices, on the 15th floor of a Park Avenue building, is invariably overflowing with visitors and employees and noise. Young Bloomberg reporters in rumpled shirts and ties hobnob over wooden bowls of fruit beside better-tailored Bloomberg sales personnel and techies in Hawaiian shirts. Employees wearing ID tags come into the noisy lobby and yell the names of visitors, while against one wall of the lobby a group of Japanese visitors hovers over the Bloomberg Traveler laptop, which glows and changes atop a table as they type. Even the tropical fish seem to be moving around in their long tank in high gear, as if they'd absorbed the urgency of the corporate culture surrounding them.<p>Several groups of visitors mill around in anticipation of their turn in one of the four glass-walled conference rooms along one side of the lobby. With hardly any enclosed rooms built into the Bloomberg headquarters, Bloomberg himself once huddled for two hours in one of the glass-walled rooms with CBS chairman Laurence Tisch. He got a big kick out of his reporters' reactions and the rumors that immediately circulated out of the office about takeovers, since Tisch was only trying to get Bloomberg to increase his donation to the United Jewish Appeal.<p>In the Bloomberg television studios, executives tethered to lavalier mikes wait to participate in one of the many live interviews and forums the company produces daily. After each TV interview, the Bloomberg journalist who asked the questions writes a story and puts it into the computer system and out onto the newswires. The voice portion of the interview is digitally edited as a radio spot at one of the many jet-pilot consoles and loaded into the network as well. The video portion travels out as television. <p>At one edge of the whirl of activity resides Matthew Winkler, who started up and now runs the Bloomberg news operation. Winkler's desk is piled high with a decidedly analog mess of paper-borne data. He wears a credentials tag around his neck and holds a phone to his left ear. "Nobody has been executed yet," Winkler is saying to a caller. "But the firing squad was assembled."<p>A PR official from Banc One has phoned to complain that a story about the bank's losses from derivatives trading was presented as a headline well before the text came over the Bloomberg. The loss had been known to professional observers of the company for some time because of Securities and Exchange Commission filings, so the PR guy is arguing that the headline without the story could have confused the dedicated marketplace. <p>Winkler agrees.<p>"I tell our reporters that we write for dopes and pros," Winkler says. "We have to be wise to the fact that what a reporter thinks is news might not be news to the pro. Today's problem could have been avoided if the headline had simply referred to the SEC report."<p>Winkler is widely regarded as a smart, tough, and driven manager of his reportorial troops. A quote by a former employee in a recent Columbia Journalism Review article compared Winkler's personnel skills to Captain Queeg'swhich didn't bother him muchand his charm to that of fringe political guru Lyndon LaRouche. "That did get to me," Winkler says. "Largely because I don't really know if Lyndon LaRouche is charming or not."<p>Winkler first learned about "the Bloomberg" when he was stationed in London for The Wall Street Journal during the mid-1980s. One day he realized that one of his sources was answering his questions about money and markets with impossible speed and confidence. Winkler finally asked the guy how he did it.<p>Back in New York at WSJ headquarters, Winkler came across Bloomberg and his gee-whiz system again. He was appalled to learn that the WSJ was using Bloomberg's bond information as news. At the time, the Bloomberg bond analyses depended on data from Merrill Lynch, and Winkler thought the source was less than journalistically independent. Though Bloomberg bond news is now drawn from a multitude of sources, newspaper editors occasionally voice a similar concern over the acceptance of free Bloomberg wire reports, the sense being that news given away as brand advertising may be less objective and independent than news sold on the open market. But many of those editors still run Bloomberg news items, and most acknowledge that while the reportage might be short on analysis, the system remains a professional source of pure news.<p>Winkler's distrust of Bloomberg inspired him to cowrite a 1988 Journal feature about the man behind the box. He says he went to some lengths to discover dark secrets about Bloomberg and his business. "The worst thing I came up with was that he gets mad and breaks phones," Winkler says. It was Winkler's story that caused Mike Bloomberg's mother to say "I told you so" about his language.<p>Winkler went to work for Bloomberg not long after that, and much of the news-market skepticism that originally greeted his young army of journalist-irregulars eventually fell away as Winkler drove quality standards higher. A media newsletter recently identified Winkler as one of the most highly remunerated business journalists in the countrythough comparative salaries and titles are frowned on in Bloomberg company culture. The news anchors on the TV service all rotate regularly to avoid anyone becoming more important than the news he or she reads. "I want all our employees to hurt us if they leave us, but I don't want anybody to be able to hurt us fatally," Bloomberg proclaims.<p>"But then again," he adds, rising from his desk in a relatively unprotected sector of the floor housing the Bloomberg radio technology and personnel, "I run this business by trial and error."<p>A stream of celebrities and senior policy mavens flow past Bloomberg's alcove almost every day now, because Bloomberg made a deal to have PBS talk-show host Charlie Rose broadcast his nightly show from a Bloomberg studio. Bloomberg says he looks at Rose's presence as "good for the troops." ("We had Faye Dunaway in here today," he said one afternoon. "You think a reporter who sees superstars like that in here every day will want to go somewhere else? Bullshit!") Bloomberg also seems to admire what he perceives as Charlie Rose's social capabilities. He calls Rose "the ultimate WASP" and notes that Rose dates a woman with acknowledged New York social credentials. Bloomberg says he is interested in potential introductions.<p>Bloomberg talks a great deal about his social life and social aspirationsand about women, with and without generally acceptable rectitudebut he didn't even get up from his work to walk 30 feet to meet Dunaway. He drops his single-guy-on-the-town allusions into conversation, but then he'll spend his weekends sharing hotels and houses with his ex-wife and kids. ("We still jog together and stuff," he says of his former wife, whom he met while at Salomon Brothers. "But I was too obsessed with business for her, and she was too obsessed with macrobiotic food for me.")<p>After Faye Dunaway left, Bloomberg did get up from his desk to travel downtown to offer advice to a gathering of 900 high school students. He told the students about things to do and say in a job interview, and he talked about hard work as a means of transcending an economic station. "I went to a public high school with hundreds of kids too," he told the students. "I worked my way through college. I am the average guy. I'm 53 years old, and I am the average guy."<p>Bloomberg's pleasure atop a podium and interest in charitable and social endeavors cause some friends and employeesand a lot of bankersto suspect that he's ready to back away from hands-on management of the franchise. Others say that the organization has reached a transition point at which a managed corporate structure needs to emerge from the trial-and-error style of the founding entrepreneur.<p>"Bullshit," says Bloomberg.<p>"When everyone in the world knows who Mike Bloomberg is," Matt Winkler says, "then he won't need Bloomberg Financial Markets or Bloomberg Financial News. Then I think he will be able to relax and back away. He says he's like Colonel Sanders these days, but he's a Colonel Sanders who sprints into the kitchen every few minutes to taste the chicken and order the recipe adjusted."<p>"People think I don't have an exit strategy," Bloomberg says a few days later over lunch, a playful look in his eyes. "But I do. My estate will eventually give it all to charity."<p>Bloomberg had ordered a bowl of clear soup 20 minutes earlier. When the soup finally comes, it's the wrong kind. And Bloomberg, who has broken handheld consumer technologies and screamed obscenities at well-paid employees who can't get jobs done to his satisfaction, continues to wait patiently. "You know," the hard-charging billionaire says to the flustered waiter, "it's only soup."<p>Then he launches a typical stream of personal updates. He notes that he didn't like the Financial Times' recent estimate of his personal worth (about $2 billion), nicely making the point that the estimate was there to be looked up. He reports running over a chipmunk while driving near his Westchester County, New York, estate. "I really felt shitty," he says. "Had a tear in my eye. I won't fish because I don't want to kill things. I'll eat a steak, but I'd never walk up and shoot Bessie. Guess I'm kind of a romantic."<p>Bloomberg then says he'd become annoyed with a woman at a party the previous evening because she was complaining about taxes. "Frankly, Madam,' I said to her, I want to pay more taxes. I want more gray hair, more birthdays, and more taxes every spring.' Around then," he says, flashing a grin of genuine accomplishment, "I could tell they were all waiting for me to leave."<p>Later, Bloomberg says, "I know a lot of people would cash out at this point and have a bit more fun than I have. I'm at least going to start to give two days a week to Johns Hopkins when I become chairman next year. But there are still too many new things left to do with the business. <p>"It's ironic, though. Somebody could walk in my office and offer me a trillion dollars for my business. A trillion dollars. Think of all the good that could be done with that money. The day after the transaction there would be an article in the paper," Bloomberg says, his voice trailing off as he nods a smile at the waiter, who is finally bringing his lunch. "But then the day after that would arriveand nobody would know who I am."<p><p>

