	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Lion King, Shorn</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-The Lion King, Shorn</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Features<p>THE LION KING, SHORN
As Salomon flails, John Gutfreund tells his own bitter tale<p>By Christopher Byron<p>Every morning at around eight, a white-haired Wall Street legend walks off the elevator of a Fifth Avenue office building and goes to work. His name is on the door in raised gold lettering. The door itself is carved pear wood, of the sort that bespeaks permanence and respectability.<p>Unfortunately, once he's inside there isn't much for this 65-year-old man to do. Instead of a bull-market hubbub, his workplace displays an almost deathly calm. On some days the only person he sees is his receptionist, who spends much of her time talking to friends on the phone.<p>Welcome to the grim little world of John H. Gutfreund. Once chairman of Salomon Inc. and the most powerful man in American finance, he now spends his time nursing relationships that would once have been beneath his dignity: money raiser for a small software company, advisor to an obscure Indian mutual fund. He's been working on a deal that could finally return him to the world of high finance--but in a low-key role, as a consultant to one of Salomon's rivals on Wall Street. Nothing is signed yet, so Gutfreund won't reveal the firm's name. He can't afford to blow it.<p>Gutfreund's fall from grace has been extreme: As a sacrificial lamb in the 1991 bond marketrigging scandal at Salomon, he plummeted further, faster, longer, and on less evidence of wrongdoing than any other Wall Street chieftain. While household names like Ivan Boesky and Michael Milken have preserved much of their clout even after serving hard time, Gutfreund has been marginalized despite being cleared of almost all wrongdoing. He has been stripped of much of his wealth and remains hamstrung by a $300 million shareholder lawsuit that intimidates prospective business partners and could make him a pauper.<p>This past summer has been especially bittersweet for the man who once ruled the financial jungle. Gutfreund has enjoyed planning his tentative reincarnation as an elder statesman of Wall Street, activating old contacts and granting his first comprehensive interview in years. It's the start of a long, painful return to life. But he has also watched as Salomon, which he raised from obscurity to immense power, turns into a financial morass for Warren Buffett, the investor he enlisted to save the company back in 1987.<p>In this spectator role, however, Gutfreund at least can indulge in a kind of schadenfreude--for his venom toward the folksy billionaire, whom he blames for his sad state, is clear.<p>"Buffett is a genius, but he's really in a jam now," he says with ill-concealed relish.<p>"It's very difficult when friends shun you because they think you're a crook."<p>John Gutfreund knows this: No matter where he goes or whom he sees, he is treated as a villain. This spring, he faced down the perception during a talk he gave at Dartmouth's Amos Tuck School of Business. He faced it down again when he returned to his alma mater, Oberlin College, for his 45th reunion. And he faced it down once more when Fortune recently reported that he had been "barred from the securities business for life."<p>Gutfreund, who hasn't been barred from anything, sued the magazine, which printed a correction. But he was devastated to realize that his bad-guy image is so entrenched that even business editors believe it. That's partly why he resolved to end four years of brooding isolation. The result has been a kind of personal catharsis, a pouring forth from a man who has kept too much bottled up for too long.<p>Gutfreund's side of the story never got a public airing in the heat of the 1991 scandal. Yet as the former Salomon chairman gives his own blow-by-blow account, the scenario he spins isn't especially flattering. His tale is sprinkled with admissions of failures and missteps, as well as a rather testy defensiveness. Still, his perspective is important historically and provides a telling glimpse into the management culture of 1980s finance, a culture too often built on quicksand.<p>Gutfreund sums up the nub of his defense thus: "I'm simply not a details man." For the bond-rigging scandal in particular, the excuse seems valid. The law-breaking occurred three levels below Gutfreund, and other Salomon officials didn't seem worried about it at first. But it's also a cop-out that's piercingly relevant as Salomon's current crisis escalates. Gutfreund built a company where "details men" weren't highly valued. As with so many Wall Street leaders, his goal was to forge big-money deals. Ensuring that the pursuit was honest and well-documented was a chore for the backroom boys.<p>Under Gutfreund's leadership, Salomon earned a reputation for lax record keeping. Computer systems were unable to produce routine audit trails, and even so basic a matter as the physical security of stock and bond certificates seemed casual, with the result that millions of dollars' worth were stolen from Salomon's vault. Whenever evidence of suspicious behavior was unearthed, Salomon's institutional impulse was frequently like a macho reaction to pain: Ignore it until it puts you in the emergency room.<p>Such an attitude bedevils Salomon to this day. Gutfreund is by no means responsible for the company's current woes: In spite of everything, the year he left was very profitable for Salomon. But his seat-of-the-pants legacy may be seen in the fact that twice in recent months Salomon has taken embarrassing write-downs for failing to reconcile its general ledger accounts--the corporate equivalent of forgetting to balance one's checkbook.<p>Gutfreund appears now to realize the significance of such a culture--and to understand what's at stake. "I look at a company like Barings," he says, "and I see a firm that only yesterday looked as solid as the earth itself. Then along comes some out-of-control kid, one thing leads to the next, and suddenly there's no more Barings. It gives one pause."<p>Right through the 1991 bond scandal, however, Gutfreund was as much a practitioner as anyone else of Wall Street's worst habit: Hoping it'll go away.<p>For 13 years, John Gutfreund ruled supreme as Salomon's chief executive officer and eventually as its chairman. From his beginnings as a Korean War vet working the municipal-bond desk, he had risen to recruit his own worldwide army of 9,000--including a cadre of the most feared investment bankers in the history of high finance. Not for nothing did Business Week tout him on a 1985 cover as "The King of Wall Street."<p>To the public, the morose-looking Gutfreund was best known as a symbol of the 1980s, poster boy for a greedy ethic lampooned by Michael Lewis and Tom Wolfe. He earned millions, lived in a spectacular apartment overlooking the East River, and had an equally grand abode in Paris. Limousines and jets transported him everywhere, and he cut a swath in society with second spouse Susan, a former stewardess who seemed the very incarnation of a trophy wife.<p>Within the world of finance, however, it was another story--a far less cartoonish one. With Gutfreund in command, Salomon Brothers changed the face of Wall Street, engineering the sort of lightning-fast megadeals that have come to dominate investment banking. Like the legendary mail room at the William Morris talent agency, Gutfreund's Salomon spawned a phenomenal array of talents: William Simon, James Wolfensohn, Henry Kaufmann, Lewis Ranieri, John Meriwether, Michael Bloomberg, and many more. The place was mythical among bankers--and Gutfreund was Lion King of its testosterone-soaked trading floor.<p>Then came the bond scandal, and in just 16 weeks Gutfreund saw this world tremble and collapse. Wall Street, true to form, trampled right over him. For many people, Gutfreund's humiliation was fodder for the 1980s morality play. But the truer villain here--and the only person to serve prison time--was Paul Mozer, an intense and self-absorbed young trader for Salomon. Ironically, Mozer didn't even register on Gutfreund's radar until too late. "I barely knew the man," says Gutfreund. "If I'd spoken to him for more than a total of 30 minutes in five years, it would be a lot."<p>The whole thing had started back in the summer of 1990, when Mozer got into a spat with the U.S. Treasury. The dispute arose over debt auctions in which Wall Street's "primary dealers"--Salomon was the largest--would submit bids for government securities. These bids might be for a dealer's own account or for one of its clients. No one was allowed to buy more than 35 percent of whatever was being auctioned.<p>Mozer had publicly chafed at this limit and, according to later charges by the Securities and Exchange Commission, soon began evading it. Mozer, who declined to comment for this article, ultimately settled a civil suit by the SEC without admitting or denying the agency's allegations. He accepted a plea bargain in a related criminal prosecution and was sentenced to four months in prison.<p>By bidding both in Salomon's name and in the name of unwitting Salomon clients, the SEC says, Mozer could illegally snag extra securities for Salomon to trade. In February 1991, however, the maverick had the bad luck to place a fake bid on behalf of a client that had submitted a real bid through another channel. Sharp-eyed Treasury officials noticed that the combined bids exceeded the 35 percent limit.<p>Though no one yet thought this was more than a minor foul-up, Mozer figured he was in trouble about two months later when he got a letter from Treasury raising the issue. So he went to his boss, John Meriwether, and fessed up--sort of. Noting that the government had flagged a violation, Mozer acknowledged making an unauthorized bid but dismissed it as a one-time lapse in judgment. Meriwether believed him.<p>It was just the sort of problem Salomon was ready to overlook. That was doubly true for John Gutfreund, who says he was less active in daily operations than most people realized. Occupied since the mid-1980s with charitable causes, diplomatic activities, and New York's social whirl, he saw himself becoming Solly's Mr. Outside--the face the firm showed to regulators and the world. "Sure, I used to wander the trading floor," he says of tales that he could hear a nickel drop across the room. "But I didn't really get involved in anything. I was like a general walking among his troops."<p>Gutfreund says the business of actually running Salomon fell to Tom Strauss, his president and chief operating officer since 1987, and to the department heads under him. Still, Mozer's screw-up didn't go unnoticed by Gutfreund. After speaking with Mozer, Meriwether called together Strauss and the company's general counsel, Donald Feuerstein. The group quickly agreed that Gutfreund needed to be told about the incident.<p>The three men met with their boss in late April as he was preparing to depart on a business trip. Gutfreund says no one seemed to think the fake bid was terribly serious, and that the session lasted a half-hour at most. But Feuerstein says he told Gutfreund that Mozer had probably committed a crime--and that telling regulators would be both a good idea and a smart safety measure.<p>Most of the meeting, then, was devoted to discussing whom to tell about the phony bid. Should they tip Treasury, which was already steamed at Mozer? Or should they tell the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, which also had regulatory power and which liked Salomon better? Neither Meriwether nor Strauss would comment for this story, but the other two participants say the meeting broke with the understanding that Gutfreund and Strauss would chat with Gerald Corrigan, president of the New York Fed, as soon as an opportunity arose.<p>Trouble was, neither man wanted to do the deed. "Bottom line?" says Gutfreund. "I just didn't get around to doing it. There was no pressure of time." And there were plenty of other pressures to distract him. Scarcely had the meeting broken up when Gutfreund resumed his hectic life as Mr. Outside. He flew hither and yon over the coming weeks, and by the time he had returned from a trip to Europe, Mozer's fake bid was a distant, half-repressed memory.<p>That was hardly the case for Mozer himself. According to SEC charges, he kept submitting illegal bids. At a late May auction, Salomon roped a stunning 86 percent of an offering of two-year notes. Other dealers had bet that these notes would drop in value, however, and were waiting to buy them cheap in the secondary market. By cornering the resale market, Salomon caught its rivals in a classic "short squeeze," forcing them to pay exorbitantly to cover their bets. All of Wall Street was livid, believing Salomon had broken the rules. An unsuspecting Gutfreund returned from a trip to Tokyo and walked into the firestorm. Oblivious to the larger pattern--no one at Salomon had connected the events of February and May, he says--the chairman convened a crisis meeting. Mozer attended, says Gutfreund, and nodded brazenly the whole way through.<p>Inside Salomon, concern was slowly building about Mozer. Yet neither Gutfreund nor Strauss had talked to the New York Fed, so government regulators were still unaware of the trader's record. Company counsel Feuerstein, in particular, was getting worried about this fact. He apparently didn't talk to Gutfreund, but says he urged Strauss several times to call Corrigan. And when the SEC opened a formal inquiry into the May squeeze, Feuerstein hired an outside law firm.<p>An internal probe began in early July, and within a month the ugly truth was in full view: Mozer had caused the squeeze--and it was no isolated event. Investigators reported that in at least nine auctions, including the February one, the rogue trader had violated Treasury rules. The aggregate worth of Salomon's illegal overbids was enormous: $15 billion.<p>Now Gutfreund's foot-dragging took on a sinister cast. He had known of a problem since April but had done nothing. An uncharitable observer might even paint him as a co-conspirator. "Sure," Gutfreund says now, "I procrastinated in bringing up an unpleasant topic with the head of the New York Fed. What can I say? With the luxury of hindsight, I can see that it was a mistake."<p>An even bigger mistake would follow. According to Gutfreund, he was advised that Salomon was under no legal obligation to disclose its prior knowledge of Mozer's February overbid. On August 9, therefore, Gutfreund approved a press release revealing that the May bond auction had been rigged. The statement didn't mention that he and others had known of a Mozer problem for months. Gutfreund notes that he didn't draft the release--but he was certainly aware of what it omitted.<p>In any case, the secret didn't stay quiet for long. The following Monday, The Wall Street Journal quoted Salomon insiders saying that Gutfreund had likely known of Mozer's activities far earlier. Federal regulators were rousted into action. Gerald Corrigan of the New York Fed--to whom Gutfreund still hadn't talked--called the Salomon chairman the next day. In icy tones, he told Gutfreund that his actions called into question the competence of the entire firm. Gutfreund says Corrigan told him, "We're looking at revoking Salomon's status as a primary dealer"--a step that could have threatened the company's viability.<p>Gutfreund was shocked: He believed his handling of the matter had been correct, given the facts available at each step. But Salomon director Charles Munger--a representative of investor Warren Buffett --was incensed to hear that the company hadn't told the whole story. He quickly forced Gutfreund to issue a second press release, admitting that Salomon had sat on news of a false Mozer bid for months. This revelation marked open season on Gutfreund. Within two days The New York Times joined the fray with a front-page story featuring photographs of Gutfreund and Strauss.<p>"The second I read that story I knew I would have to resign," says Gutfreund. He resolved on the spot--against the advice of his wife and his lawyer--to bow out gracefully for the sake of the company. "You've heard the TV commercials that say, 'I found my job through The New York Times'? Well, I'm the guy who lost his job the same way."<p>Only at this point, says Gutfreund, did he call his biggest investor, Warren Buffett, to talk about the crisis. This would prove to be the costliest delay of all.<p>Gutfreund had recruited the financial savant from Omaha, Nebraska, in 1987 to keep Salomon from the hands of Ronald Perelman, then viewed as a corporate raider. Through his vehicle, Berkshire Hathaway, Buffett had plunked down $700 million for a special issue of preferred stock designed to hold the aggressor at bay.<p>For his consideration, the billionaire gained two seats on Salomon's board but not much else: Gutfreund rarely bothered to call him. As a result, Buffett had spent the summer of 1991 stewing as he learned from the newspapers and from his representative, Munger--anywhere but from Gutfreund --about his deteriorating investment. Still, both Buffett and Gutfreund were level-headed businessmen, and the best course of action was clear. "I briefed him on the situation," says Gutfreund, "and I asked him to fly to New York to step in as interim chairman. He agreed."<p>When Buffett arrived, he met with Gutfreund and Gutfreund's lawyer, Philip Howard. On the issue of severance, says Howard, the billionaire coldly refused to put anything in writing. "It was all understood," says Howard, referring to what Gutfreund claims was a verbal agreement to pay Gutfreund his vested retirement rights, various stock options, his 1991 bonus, and two years' salary. In total, the amount came to more than $25 million.<p>An irate Buffett evidently understood nothing of the sort. Shortly after taking over, he had Salomon's board pass a resolution denying anything but token compensation not just to Gutfreund but also to Meriwether and Strauss, both of whom had also resigned. Then Buffett moved to deny the three their retirement and stock benefits. Such rough handling from a businessman known for his probity sealed the idea that Gutfreund was guilty of something.<p>Practical men, Meriwether and Strauss negotiated settlements that gave them about $20 million and $8.5 million, respectively. But Gutfreund, who thought he had acted nobly by falling on his sword, took the insult harder. Feeling deceived, he demanded to go to arbitration. He wound up getting nothing--and that, along with a $100,000 fine from the SEC in 1992 for failing to supervise Mozer's superiors, set the tone for his downward spiral.<p>So recently astride the world, Gutfreund became the embodiment of damaged goods. Some friends stuck by him, developer Alfred Taubman and mogul Laurence Tisch among them. But for most of Wall Street's machers, John Gutfreund became the man who wasn't there, a lion shorn by events that were murky, hard to follow, and neatly summed up in a rhetorical thought: If Gutfreund didn't do anything wrong, why did he quit? And why did Buffett ream him so good?<p>The battering to Gutfreund's pride was extreme. What most observers expected would be a short slump turned into years of phones that never rang. "By last winter, John was a total basket case," says one longtime friend. "He seemed barely able to function at all." Adds a former colleague: "I've worried more than once whether I'd pick up the papers one day and read that John had done something really foolish."<p>Gutfreund says he never saw himself in such a dire state. But he does describe something like shame at his fall. "I figured when I retired, I'd be able to put $1 million or $2 million of my own money into interesting deals that came along," he says bitterly. "Now $100,000 would be a significant amount. A number of people had asked me to manage $10 million or so of their money. But it just didn't seem right when I didn't have any of my own in the pot." <p>It's hard to feel too sorry for Gutfreund: He's still well-off, and he's edging back into the game. But his hard-won humility is welcome in someone who is a former Master of the Universe.<p>Benched from the big leagues of money, Gutfreund remains an astute color commentator. On certain subjects with which he has experience, moreover, he shows the true zeal of a convert. "Controls are deficient throughout all of Wall Street," he warns. "The day will inevitably come when companies get hurt."<p>Ironically, Gutfreund's comments come in early July, just days before Salomon predicts a huge second-quarter loss of $65 million. The hit is completely unexpected and serves as the latest embarrassment for a staggering regime installed by Warren Buffett. To all appearances, Salomon Brothers as Gutfreund knew it is now falling to pieces. More than two dozen top officials have quit this year. Every time one problem is fixed, another one erupts. And though it hardly speaks well for the durability of his work, Gutfreund can't hide a morbid satisfaction at the pain Buffett is feeling.<p>"Running an investment bank is like running a Hollywood studio," he says with a measure of pride. "You have to contend with the huge egos of talented people. If you don't keep them happy, they just pack up and go elsewhere."<p>Gutfreund's smile will likely keep growing this autumn--for his business hopes are brightening even as Buffett faces a tough choice. When he came in as a white knight in 1987, the billionaire bought $700 million in preferred stock, exchangeable for Salomon common at $38 a share. The first tranche comes due in October--about $175 million worth. Given Salomon's woes, Buffett must take the stock: Cashing out would show he's lost faith in the company. But at a recent market price of $36 a common share, the Omahan will be throwing good money after bad.<p>It's a nice illustration of Buffett's bind. But where does all this leave Gutfreund? Well, he's still fighting for his back pay and benefits, and he'll achieve a sad vindication if Salomon flatlines on Buffett's watch. In the meantime, he can boast that he finally has better prospects than the company he left in disgrace. For a humbled legend who once imagined retiring in grand style, it's bitter consolation. But it's consolation nonetheless. 
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
