	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-The Family Name</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Ernie Olde is a fourth-generation money man, heir to a proud financial tradition. His forebears would be thrilled to know he built Olde Discount into the nations most profitable brokerage. But what would they make of the anger, hurt, and legal trouble that have accompanied his rise to the top?<p>By William P. Barrett<p>Several times now this century, an E.J. Olde has been laid to rest at the highest point of Clinton Grove Cemetery, a 140-year-old burial ground near the northern Detroit suburb of Mount Clemens. The name has been passed down along a prominent line of money men, beginning with the very first Ernest J. Olde, a German immigrant who made good as a business owner and real estate baron. Today, great-grandson Ernie is wealthier even than <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a>, his biggest rival.<p>This latter E.J. Olde--culmination of his family line and most successful propagator of its name--is fourth in the declension. He turns 58 this month, a tall, broad man with graying blond hair and, of late, a pronounced paunch. The company he founded, Olde Discount, is the countrys fourth-largest and arguably most profitable discount brokerage, with about 200 offices nationwide. Ernie himself is worth perhaps $800 million. For all this wealth, however, many who know him describe a chronically angry and unhappy individual.<p>Oldes turbulent personality has put him in a standoff with a world whose rules he seems to disdain. Over the years, court and regulatory pleadings have accused him or his firm of everything from securities-law violations to discrimination. Olde has become a virtual exile from the U.S. With his 37-year-old second wife and their two small children, he shuttles among plush residences in Florida, Canada, and the Cayman Islands, a tax haven that seems now to be his main residence. He is absent for long stretches from company headquarters in Detroit.<p>Public photographs of Olde are rare, and he has unlisted telephone numbers in three countries. He didnt respond to requests for an interview, and, after receiving a list of questions, his attorney said that Worths information is grossly inaccurate and part of a sensationalist, malicious attempt to discredit Olde Discount. The company asked for ten days to answer and, after two weeks, supplied a partial response. Oldes top aide, Randal Mudge, had called earlier--but mostly to note that the company that publishes Worth is owned by a unit of Fidelity Investments, one of Oldes main competitors. Mr. Olde does value his privacy, said Mudge. Hes not going to be available to discuss his personal life.<p>Oldes personal life is of interest to many investors, however, for it helps explain the unusually aggressive ethos that pervades the business he has built.<p>On the financial-services map, Detroit is well off the interstate. Yet in 1994, while many big brokerages suffered downturns or laid off employees, Olde Financial, the parent company of Olde Discount, won a place of honor by adding hundreds of workers and earning a hefty $65 million on revenue of $300 million. Discount leader Charles Schwab Corp. made more money, $135 million, but it needed more than three times the revenue and seven times as many customer accounts. Olde Financials profit margin and return on equity may be the best in the brokerage industry.<p>Almost 90 percent of this extraordinary money machine is owned by a single man: Ernie Olde.<p>Olde (pronounced OLE-dee) is a smart businessman with an inventive mind. His refashioning of Olde Discount during the 1980s as Americas full-service discount broker--unlike most other discounters, his brokers give stock recommendations--has been wildly successful. He has exploited market niches brilliantly and attracted customers through simple measures such as slashing fees or offering free trades. His television advertisements are fixtures on CNBC, making Olde a household name for many investors, and he was among the first in the industry to advertise via direct mail and radio.<p>By ignoring derivatives and underwriting, Olde has avoided the big hits that have stung other securities firms. He runs an aggressive, hard-nosed, vertically integrated retail operation that seizes on new ideas and keeps a tight lid on costs. My child has the American work ethic, says Virginia Olde, Ernies mother and one of his biggest fans. One way he cuts expenses is by hiring hundreds of young, driven college graduates willing to work long hours for the training. Another is by putting Olde offices in strip malls.<p>The guy is by far the most brilliant man Ive ever known, says Dave Fleetham, a certified public accountant who worked for Olde for several years. He has very high energy. Sometimes unnaturally high: Once, when Olde visited one of his businesses and found a door locked, he lost patience and kicked it in. Bam! recalls Fleetham. It buckled right down.<p>The story bolsters other ex-Olde executives descriptions of a boss for whom conventional niceties are just obstacles to be surmounted in the pursuit of a goal. Several people even recall Olde bragging that he once sued his own mother--although she denies the story and theres no evidence of such a suit. More prosaically, as a driver, Olde has been convicted of five moving offenses since 1990.<p>Ernies biggest goal has always been accumulating money. Thats all he was interested in, says one person who has worked closely with him. A labor-relations tribunal wrote a few years ago: He is solicitous about his money, and has little tolerance for those who waste it. In fact, Ernies passion for the bottom line is so fiery that one of his own executives once sought to exclude him from a Canadian collective-bargaining session for fear his temper would scuttle the talks.<p>The roots of this money obsession run deep into Olde history, back to all the other E.J.s and their indomitable drive to succeed. But how would Ernies forebears feel to know that, in 1995, their name finally stands for massive wealth--but also for questionable dealing and unfathomable family sadness?<p>The first Ernest Jacob Olde, the family patriarch, was born in Germany in 1847 and came to the U.S. as a boy. In 1862, at age 15, he settled with his family in Mount Clemens, then a spa resort of 1,500 souls. The hardworking young immigrant had a head for money and eventually operated a wide variety of businesses, serving for 25 years as president of the local savings bank.<p>A civic pillar, the original E.J. headed a committee that put a Gideon Bible in each of Mount Clemenss 1,375 hotel rooms during a single day in 1913. His death ten years later from a stroke at age 75 was accompanied by press tributes to his financial prowess and extensive land holdings. He was buried at Clinton Grove, in the family plot he had purchased several decades earlier, leaving behind his wife of 45 years and six children--one of whom was the second E.J. Olde.<p>This E.J., too, was a successful businessman, with his own real estate and construction holdings. In time he might have exceeded his fathers wealth, but he was plagued by ill health. He died at 45 in 1928, just five years after his father, following an operation for thyroid problems. E.J. II came to rest just a few feet north of his father, in his shadow to the very end. He left a wife and three children, including E.J. III.<p>The Depression apparently stripped the Olde family of much of the wealth it had accumulated--and as a result, the third E.J. Olde embarked on his financial career without much of a head start. Still, the Olde zeal shone through. A 21-year-old college student around the time of his fathers death, E.J. III eventually took a job at Household Finance Corp., a nationwide small-loan company. He was a debt collector in Detroit, recalls Virginia Olde, who married him in 1936.<p>Shortly after World War II broke out, E.J. III was promoted to branch manager of the Household Finance office in Port Huron, Michigan. But by wars end, with a growing family to support, he had decided to form his own small-loan business. He got darned tired of taking orders, says Virginia. The only available lending license was in Marine City, a working-class town of 5,000 along the St. Clair River facing Canada, about 40 miles northeast of Detroit. The Oldes moved there in 1946, when their oldest child, E.J. Olde IV--just Ernie, to those who knew him--was seven years old.<p>Marine City proved to be a good pick. Founded in the early 19th century as a shipbuilding center, the town, like many border settlements, had an aura of intrigue and a reputation as a center for smuggling. E.J. III quickly established a E.J. Olde Loans, which specialized in lending money to local customers whose credit was too shaky to get a bank loan. The key to profitability was knowing the borrowers--and Ernest Olde knew them well. In a little pond, he became a big, prosperous fish, a popular fellow, and, like his grandfather, a civic leader. He led fund-raising drives and served as president of the local chamber of commerce.<p>It was in this milieu that young Ernie came of age. He would blossom into an outgoing kid, hardly an academic star but popular with others for his good humor and relative affluence. At tiny Marine City High School he had a starring role in the senior play and a place on the football team--No. 66, right tackle. Says classmate Ed Terhune, who now runs an automobile dealership: He was a generous, good guy. He always had a nice car and money in his pocket. He cared about people.<p>Still, in E.J. IV the Olde work ethic seemed to have sputtered out. The youngster never worked in his fathers firm and, in 1955, the year he graduated from high school, his classmates voted him two superlatives: Laziest and Biggest Eater.<p>Ernie olde is still a man of large appetites, but hes no longer lazy--if indeed he ever was. Virginia Olde says her son was always a hard worker, even if his friends never knew it. And as the business world approached, young Ernie certainly caught fire. He spent summers hauling bricks at local construction sites, for example, and bought a car with his earnings. At the University of Toledo, says his mother, Ernie was so eager to start making money that he finished his studies a half year early. He earned a degree in business administration and served as junior-class treasurer. Clearly, the family traits were beginning to express themselves.<p>During high school Ernie had begun dating Suzanne Conrad, a girl from the wealthier upriver town of St. Clair. Suzannes family had real money: Her father, Howard Conrad, was president of several utility companies. But Ernie was an up-and-comer, and the match seemed a good one. They married in 1961, following Suzannes graduation from Wellesley College in Massachusetts. At the time, the young groom was an engineer for Chevrolet Gear & Axle in Detroit. But just a year later he would move into the sexier securities business, joining First of Michigan Corp.--apparently with some help from his well-connected in-laws.<p>With his drive, savvy, and ingratiating personality, Ernie excelled as a retail broker. Simply put, he was good at convincing strangers he should handle their money--so much so that Kidder, Peabody & Co. hired him in 1967 to open its first Detroit-area office. He started strong at this new post, too, and was helped along by his father-in-law, who allowed him to handle the pension fund for one of his utilities. Still, in 1971 Ernie left Kidder in a dispute over strategy. In an unrelated deposition years later, he would explain the circumstances: I basically believed in the retail business and they basically believed in the institutional business, and over a series of weeks and months, it was determined that I should leave.<p>Even Oldes departure from Kidder, however, turned out to be a blessing. In 1971, bankrolled in large part by Suzannes family, he opened his own retail brokerage, Olde & Co. And from the beginning it made money. He has a brilliant mind, says Eugene Leich, an early partner in the venture. He understood the marketplace. His stuff was innovative and very forward-looking.<p>Ernie had become a real man on the move. Within a few years, he and Suzanne had bought a 22-room, 5,000-square-foot house in fancy Grosse Pointe Park. Their young brood consisted of a daughter, Christine, and a son, Ernst--the fifth E.J. Olde, heir to a family tradition his father seemed destined to take to new heights.<p>Despite its early success, however, Olde & Co. was still small beer compared with the powerful national houses and even local operations like Roney & Co. Ernies big chance would come in 1975, when the Securities and Exchange Commission abolished fixed-rate commissions. Before this change, investors had no real incentive to switch brokers. Now, brokerages could compete on price. Ernie understood the implications: He saw huge growth looming at the low end of the market and decided to capture some of it.<p>Thus was born Olde Discount.<p>It wasnt an easy transition--and it apparently unleashed a darker side to the Olde drive. Ernie was riding a crucial business trend, but the success that followed tore into his personal life. Trying to harness the boom in discount brokering, he worked like a madman, living fast and seeing little of Suzanne and his kids. Meanwhile, all his worst traits--his temper, his unpredictability, his money lust--surfaced under the pressure. It was as if he had started to believe that his financial talent allowed him to behave however he pleased. Ernie was just impossible to work with, says Leich, now a broker at <a name="NYSE:PWJ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11148"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PaineWebber</b></a>. He could be charming one minute and a tyrant the next.<p>Problems began to arise. The firm got hit with three fines in three years for matters such as bad record keeping. In 1978, the SEC censured the firm and Ernie himself for failing to rein in an errant broker. Partly because of Ernies volatile personality, Olde Discount had trouble keeping top talent. Turnover became part of the firms tradition, with Leich and other early executives leaving by 1979. Soon Olde Discount consisted of a revolving cast of minor characters who took their lead from an overworked, increasingly imperious boss.<p>One result of Ernies new habits was the collapse of his marriage into bitterness and reproach. In November 1977 he filed for divorce. The fight dragged on in court for two years amid charges that Ernie wouldnt pay child support and had threatened to hide his assets. (He denied the charges.) Suzanne Olde testified that their two children, Christine and E.J., then 14 and 11, werent close to Ernie. I think the problem is that their father was gone a great deal of the time, she said.<p>Suzannes mother, Martha Conrad, was far more blunt about the family dynamic. Here is her assessment--under oath--of Ernie: A German general ordering this, ordering that. It was never Will you do something? It was always Suzie, do this or do that. Go to this, or go to that. ... His children were neglected.<p>The divorce seems to have combined with other traumas to strip Ernie of familial restraints on his behavior. In 1979, his earliest role model--E.J. III, the stalwart loan man in Marine City--died of a heart ailment at age 72. The elder Olde had sold his business and retired just two years earlier, and his burial at Clinton Grove was the first interment of an E.J. there in more than a half century.<p>That same year, perhaps in need of some reliable support, Ernie convinced his well-liked younger brother, Jim, to leave his career as a schoolteacher and athletic coach and join Olde Discount as executive vice president. Jim had come down with Hodgkins disease in 1974, but the often-fatal illness had been in remission since he had relocated from Michigan to the drier climate of Phoenix. The new post was apparently a hectic one that required travel. On a family vacation to the Detroit area in 1983, Jim Olde became ill and checked into a hospital. The Hodgkins had returned in a big way. Jim never saw Arizona again, dying within a month at age 41. His remains were interred at Clinton Grove, and Ernie Olde was more alone than ever before.<p>Ernies son, meanwhile, had also been having problems--and by all accounts, his relationship with his father, who thought him a slacker, was prime among them. Like Ernie himself, E.J. was no genius in school. But childhood buddies remember him mostly as a great kid whose only real failing was a lack of ambition. Though he was in several advanced classes, E.J. preferred talking cars to doing homework.<p>Ernie tried to get the boy to shape up. Craig Fahle, a childhood friend, remembers the time Ernie coached their Little League team. He was a hell of a lot more demanding on E.J. than on the other players, recalls Fahle. If it wasnt picture perfect, Ernie was unhappy. E.J. felt he could never live up to his dads high standards. For the son of a rich man, E.J. was curiously penniless in high school. A caption in his senior yearbook reads: E.J. + MONEY = Miracle. Friends say Ernie would give E.J. a top-of-the-line Toyota Supra, only to take it back when he was angry.<p>The youngster finally began acting out in destructive ways--drinking and taking drugs. Less serious warning signs had been there for years: During the divorce proceeding, Suzanne Olde testified that she once found 11-year-old E.J. on the street taking tennis balls and putting lighter fluid on them and throwing them.<p>Through these troubles, ernie somehow remained focused on his driving goal. I want to be the richest man on Griswold Street, former executives recall him writing in memos, referring to Detroits financial district. As a result, the 1980s would become an extraordinarily productive time for Olde Discount. In the three years after Jim Oldes death, the firms offices doubled to a total of 95 nationwide. Soon after, Ernie launched what was perhaps his greatest idea--a stock-research department called Special Ventures.<p>Stock research is the only real difference between discounters and full-service stockbrokers. Ernie wanted to close that gap while maintaining his price edge--and to increase his profit considerably in the process. But traditional research costs money, so Ernie had to come up with a new way of doing things. The method he chose was simple: Olde Discount would push smaller stocks in which it made a market--meaning it could sell them to customers from its own inventory. Thus, on many trades Olde would profit on the commission and also on the markup between a stocks bid and ask prices. At first, the research that backed these recommendations was often skimpy, although the firm has since beefed it up.<p>The birth of Special Ventures would result in another growth spurt for Olde Discount. It would also generate chances for loose dealing--and by this time, Ernie had been deprived of most calming family ties and counsel from longtime colleagues. Before long, according to confidential memos from Oldes own lawyers, he began a push into illegal front-running.<p>Front-running occurs when a securities firm buys a companys shares knowing it will soon recommend the stock. When share prices rise on the recommendation, the brokerage can sell the stock to its own customers for a profit. Such a scheme was detailed in two memos from the well-regarded Chicago law firm of Fagel, Haber & Maragos, which Olde Discount had hired to handle regulatory matters.<p>In the first memo, dated June 1, 1988, the firm warns that regulators might conclude Olde Discount was taking advantage of its customers and blame Ernie Olde. The second memo, dated July 2, 1990, goes even further, accusing Ernie himself of front-running for personal gain. Both memos--which Olde Discount executives have called ill informed and wrong--surfaced during the criminal trial that resulted from Ernies 1990 firing of his own president, Herbert Burns, for allegedly embezzling $5,000 worth of postage.<p>The two-week-long Burns trial is one of the most bizarre events in Oldes career, painting an unsparing picture of Ernie as a paranoid leader who monitored his top lieutenant with a hidden video camera and a secret tape recorder. In an especially strange twist, Burnss lawyer, Geoffrey Fieger--now the attorney for death doctor Jack Kevorkian--tried unsuccessfully to admit testimony about an incident in which Ernie allegedly ordered an Olde executive to drive him through a customs barrier at the Detroit-Windsor Tunnel because Ernie was smuggling cocaine from Canada. Ernie has denied the accusation.<p>More relevantly, Fieger argued that the entire prosecution was a ploy by Ernie to destroy Burnss credibility in case he squealed about the alleged front-running, and that Burns had been using the Olde postage meter to pay off valid company debts. The jury apparently agreed, acquitting Burns after a mere two hours of deliberation. Burns didnt get away completely clean: Regulators later disciplined him on a side issue. Neither Ernie nor his firm was ever charged with front-running.<p>The Burns verdict was only one of a number of legal problems that piled up throughout the 1980s and early 1990s. Burns filed a $20 million lawsuit against Olde Financial that is now in arbitration. A retired Olde Financial senior vice president received a big settlement--other former executives say $1 million--after he sued the company, alleging self-dealing and commingling. A group of Canadian workers sued Ernie himself for $23.5 million, claiming among other things that their termination from an Olde printing company was accompanied by efforts to juggle the books. That suit, in which Olde denies any wrongdoing, is still pending.<p>Olde Discount also continued to have regulatory difficulties. In 1986 the New York Stock Exchange fined Olde a hefty $60,000; in 1992 it levied a $35,000 penalty for violations of securities rules. Between 1986 and 1993, the National Association of Securities Dealers fined Olde seven times. Olde Discount officials have characterized these matters as minor.<p>Then there are the accounts of racial and sexual bias. To Olde watchers, the most recently publicized charges--made by a group of female former employees--are old hat. Around the Olde organization, Ernie has long been known as someone who wants only young white men working for him. Indeed, a former Olde Discount recruiter says in a 1993 lawsuit that he was fired after violating instructions not to hire women, handicapped persons, black persons, persons with various other ethnic backgrounds, and anyone over 50 years old. Olde denies the charge; the case is in arbitration.<p>Despite these problems, Ernie has continued to profit handsomely from Olde Discount. Since 1991, according to regulatory filings, he or companies he owns have been paid more than $75 million by Olde Financial in salary, bonus, rent for properties leased to the company, and payments for services rendered. In 1994 alone, Ernie and his companies received more than $23 million in payments.<p>In 1982 Ernie moved from Detroit to Florida, which has no state income tax. Within the past year or so he has moved into a lush home in the Cayman Islands, which has hardly any taxes at all. Now he shuttles between these two places and a farm fronting Lake St. Clair in Stoney Point, Ontario, about 40 miles east of Detroit. Hes also said to spend time in Italy and Aspen, Colorado. The one place for which he apparently has little patience is Detroit proper, where his son, E.J., spent much of the 1980s growing into a very disturbed young man.<p>Since his teenage years, E.J. had worked occasionally for his father at Olde Discount--not on the financial side but on unglamorous tasks such as real estate supervision. Former Olde employees recall heated arguments between Ernie and the son he saw as a disappointment. In one curious incident, E.J. drove a company car to his college, Western State College in Gunnison, Colorado, and refused to give it back. Several Olde Discount managers were pressed into service as repo men in the mountains of Colorado.<p>E.J. dropped out of Western State after two years, returning to the Detroit area in 1989. He kept working for Olde Discount but his lackluster performance, erratic behavior, and trips to rehab caused increasing friction with Ernie. E.J. would be ready for the barrage whenever his dad entered the room, says Joe Taylor, who was fired as president of an Olde-owned courier firm in 1990. He felt he couldnt do anything right in his fathers eyes. I can recall Ernie telling me, I dont know what Im going to do with the kid.<p>Sometime in the summer or fall of 1992, E.J. left the Olde payroll. Still, the boyish-looking youngster sometimes returned to the Olde complex at Griswold Street and West Lafayette Boulevard, aimlessly walking the hallways. Hed sit down with top executives for conversations they would later recall as bizarre, paranoid, and delusional, ranting about a conspiracy involving various friends and his father. It was clear he needed psychiatric help.<p>About 10:40 a.m. on Friday, October 23, 1992, Dale Stamper stepped out of the elevator on the tenth floor of the Olde building at 131 West Lafayette, a former home of the Detroit Free Press. The maintenance supervisor--a pal of E.J.s--was heading up to check a roofing project. As he turned into the stairwell, he saw a lifeless figure, clad in a green jacket and khaki pants, hanging by the neck from an orange extension cord. Stamper recognized the corpse of his young friend--an image he still sees in nightmares.<p>The body was formally identified by Randal Mudge, Oldes top aide. Ernie was out of town.<p>On Monday, October 26, 1992, 25-year-old E.J. Olde joined his more illustrious forebears in the family plot at Clinton Grove, the youngest E.J. Olde ever to be buried there. Many of his friends, especially those from high school, missed the service: No death notice had appeared in the newspapers. <p>Sometime during 1993, however, Ernie did pay public tribute to his sons memory. A bronze sculpture--a boy clad in shorts, sitting with his arm around a puppy--appeared over E.J.s grave. Cemetery officials say Ernie commissioned the unusual work. A memorial to E.J. was also placed on a wall at Olde headquarters.<p>Meanwhile, Ernie remains in firm control of other matters. At Olde Financial he still has final word, though he now leaves most daily operations to well-paid subordinates. The firms performance has been so stellar lately, however, that its very success may be raising a question among regulators and prospective clients: Has Olde been doing too well?<p>Oldes latest annual 10-K filing says the firms number of regular customer accounts has stagnated recently--not a good sign. First-quarter 1995 earnings were off a shade, which is curious in a bull market. And The New York Times has reported that Olde Discount is among a group of brokerages being questioned in an SEC probe. (Neither Olde nor the SEC will comment.) Several nasty arbitration cases are also nearing resolution, while discrimination claims continue to attract national attention. Living reclusively on Grand Cayman, Ernie looks ever more like an exile.<p>On the personal front, however, friends say hes a little happier these days. Hes gotten married again, for one thing. It happened in 1991; his bride was Sue Shaheen, a Canadian 20 years his junior. Ernie reportedly met her when their cars were stopped together at a traffic light. Later in 1991, Sue gave birth to a girl. She and Ernie named the new baby Erica Jean--E.J. Olde once again.<p>Maybe they knew the old family name could do with some fresh hope.<p>
OLDE DISCOUNT: QUITE A DEAL, BUT FOR WHOM?<p>By William P. Barrett<p>At Olde Discount, Ernie Olde offers his clients what seems like a great deal: a full-service brokerage at cut-rate prices. How can he provide this bargain and still reap such high profits? The answer lies in the sort of full service offered by Olde.<p>At most discount brokerages, the people who answer the phones dont much care what stocks their customers buy: Theyre paid a flat salary and offer no expert opinions. At Olde Discount, however, representatives are given incentives to cold-call clients and suggest that they buy little-known stocks recommended by Oldes researchers--a twist on regular full-service shops, which follow a broader range of stocks.<p>According to employees who have left the company, Olde pays its brokers only $1,200 a month. To rise above that, employees rely on trading commissions or credits. If they sell shares of well-known issues such as IBM or General Motors, they get to keep 10 percent or less of the firms commission. But if they book trades involving 200 or so stocks on a Special Ventures list, they may take home three times as much. Why the difference? Generally speaking, Olde can sell customers these stocks from its own inventory--allowing it a nice potential profit on the markup.<p>Oldes Special Ventures list consists mainly of small Nasdaq stocks, and the firms researchers rate most of the issues a buy. While some SV stocks are well-known, like McDonalds and PepsiCo, most are obscure. Ever hear of Melamine Chemicals or Modine Manufacturing? For Olde, trading in such issues is so lucrative that the firm will waive its commission for any buy order of 1,000 shares or more.<p>If customers want to buy a non-SV stock, meanwhile, Olde brokers will often consult a company-issued cross-sell directory and suggest a lesser-known SV stock instead. Some examples from an Olde list dated January 1994: Customers interested in Southwest Airlines would be directed to Atlantic Southeast Airlines; Hewlett-Packard buyers might be directed to Acuson.<p>A Worth survey of SV issues recommended by Olde in March 1994 suggests they underperformed broader market indexes over a year, but not by much. This showing is respectable--except that buyers of many SV stocks take on more risk due to the volatility of smaller issues. In addition, the spread between bid and asked prices means that most SV buyers start off in the hole. Olde says its own studies show better results.<p>Olde also encourages margin buying--allowing customers to buy stocks with funds lent by Olde itself. This is a valid strategy, but its risky and best practiced by experienced investors with substantial assets. Olde has made it a backbone of its largely low-rent business, however: On a handout given to trainees, the firm suggests explaining margin buying to customers who say they have no money. Over the past four years, Oldes margin lending has gone up tenfold. In 1994 revenue from such loans reached $60 million, one fifth of the firms intake.<p>Accompanying all this is extreme pressure on Oldes young hires--and on their customers. In classes, Olde gives trainee brokers suggested dialogues to help snag deals quickly. Once the client says Yes,  one memo urges, keep asking for more. A sample closing line: Lets buy 2,000 shares--or would you be more comfortable with 1,000 shares? Or: I like all five of these stocks. Which ones do you like best? Great! Lets buy those. Other dialogues tell how to discourage clients from consulting with their spouses--or from requesting any information in writing.<p>Of course, Olde Discount can show regulators a manual that contains four pages of factors its brokers are supposed to review with customers before soliciting a trade. That looks good. But then theres the 1993 memo that Dan Katzman, an Olde vice president, sent to his brokers--along with three-minute egg timers. We simply do not have enough time to spend a half hour a day with each customer, wrote Katzman.<p>This type of pressure is directed at hundreds of new hires every year, often eager, clean-cut white men taken fresh from college. Olde Discount has become something of a farm team for full-service brokerages and larger discounters such as Charles Schwab. Despite the stressful atmosphere, therefore, many employees are grateful for the intense training they get at Olde.<p>Besides, if theyre good at making money for Ernie, they get rewarded. I was earning $60,000 after one year, says one former Olde broker. The problem is that I couldnt sleep at night.<p><p><p>

