	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Downshifters</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>They want to work less, own less, want less. They call it voluntary simplicity, and its neither as easy nor as odd as it sounds.<p>By John Brant<p>On a crystalline spring evening in Oregon, a warm clear light bathes the pews of downtown Portlands Old Church. A fresh breeze combs the high trees along the Park Blocks. Far away on the eastern horizon, Mount Hood gleams in the days dying sunshine.<p>Dick Roy stands at the church door, greeting friends and counting the gate. The turnout--around a hundred--represents a fair cross-section of professional Portland. Gathered are the citys physicians, architects, and senior executives, its park-district board members, art-museum docents, and PBS subscribers, the kind of people youd want directing your corporation, examining your contract, or paddling your canoe. In the midst of this shining evening, in the prime of their lives and careers, at the heart of one of the nations fairest and most prosperous cities, these citizens have shown up for a lecture about voluntary simplicity. Theyve come to learn the curious, difficult, transforming art of wanting and working less.<p>Most everybody here seems to know Roy, either from his former life as a corporate attorney--a partner in Portlands most prestigious firm, a Harvard Law School graduate sought for his easy manner and lucid way of solving business problems--or from his new life, which he began in 1993. In the fall of that year Roy stunned Oregons legal and corporate communities by resigning from his firm to throw himself full time into the promulgation of simple, environmentally responsible living, a calling he and his wife, Jeanne, had been following privately for years.<p>We never needed very many material things to make us happy, and we reached a point where we were financially independent, Roy says during a lull in the ticket collection. I decided that from then on I could donate 100 percent of my income to what I thought was important, or else 100 percent of my time. I chose the latter.<p>Shortly after he left his job to start the nonprofit Northwest Earth Institute, which is sponsoring tonights talk, a profile of Roy appeared in the Portland Oregonian. The reader response was overwhelming--the Roys received more than 600 calls and letters, mostly from people seeking to make similar changes. Downshifting had clearly struck a responsive chord in this thriving city, just as it has in less-favored communities across the nation.<p>Downshifting is an infelicitous term for a movement toward simplicity, a gesture toward grace. It refers to choosing to make do with less. Like Melvilles Bartleby the Scrivener, the downshifter prefers not to: not to sacrifice relationships with family, friends, and community in exchange for career advancement; not to defer hopes and ideals in the name of making a living; not to fall prey to the lures of heedless consumption.<p>Evidence of this preferring-not-to is burgeoning across America. Earlier this summer the Merck Family Fund published the results of a national public-opinion survey examining Americans views on consumption, materialism, and the environment. An eye-popping 28 percent of the respondents said that during the past five years they had made voluntary changes in their lives that resulted in their earning less money--not including those who had simply retired. The most common changes were reducing work hours, changing to a lower-paying job, and quitting work to stay at home. <p>According to the survey, 68 percent of those who downshifted did so to pursue a more balanced life; 66 percent wanted more time; 63 percent were seeking a less stressful life. Fifty-three percent downshifted to spend more time with their children. A resounding 87 percent of the downshifters described themselves as happy with their change, while only 35 percent reported missing the extra income.<p>Moreover, the polls related findings suggested that these downshifters are acting on convictions held by a much wider segment of the general population. Seventy-one percent of the respondents said they had more possessions than their parents did at the same age, 66 percent reported being more financially secure, and 61 percent indicated they lived in a nicer apartment or house. Only 49 percent, however, described themselves as happier than their parents.<p>More and more people are both enervated by the frenetic pace and demands and frustrated by their inability to find viable alternatives to life in the fast lane, says David Shi, president of Furman University and author of two influential books about simple living. Two-income homes, working mothers, the 12-hour workday--people are just worn-out.<p>For these exhausted citizens, downshifting seems to represent both a means of escape and a compensatory historical law. Our abiding national imperative has always been to work harder and longer, to want and claim more, to spread out as far as our appetites and the landscape will allow. But running concurrently through our history has been a countering dream: Thoreaus pond, cabin, canoe, and garden; a career of service; a goal of sufficiency rather than surfeit.<p>In struggling toward some version of this vision, the great majority of downshifters fall short of the 100 percent commitment of Dick Roy. Instead, a father cuts back on his office hours to spend more time with his young children; a teacher shares her fifth-grade classroom to avoid the burnout affecting so many of her colleagues; an accountant resigns from her large firm to work at home and choose her own clients and hours. Because of its diffuse and disparate nature, downshifting defies precise measurements and marketing analysis; thus far, no ones figured out how to get rich off it. Its a movement comprising millions of individuals making countless personal choices. <p>In certain settings, however, downshifters are emerging in particularly bold and representative relief. Here in the Pacific Northwest, downshifting tenets are taking root among prosperous professionals in organizations such as Portlands Northwest Earth Institute and the New Road Map Foundation in Seattle. The feeling is strong that if you cant do it in the Pacific Northwest--if a person cant manage a healthy balance between work, family, and community and if the region cant decide on a path of responsible, sustainable economic growth--then it cant be done anywhere, Roy says, moving toward the front of the church. Theres a great hunger here for achieving that balance, which has to be built upon personal responsibility and some degree of voluntary simplicity. <p>At the lectern, Roy explains the Earth Institutes mission of carrying the voluntary-simplicity message into the workplace. Thus far, he says, 110 organizations and 2,500 people have participated in the institutes classes and workshops, whose texts are drawn from writers ranging from Wendell Berry to Anne Morrow Lindbergh to tonights speaker, Duane Elgin.<p>In 1981, Elgin, formerly a scholar at the Stanford Research Institute and a self-described MBA gone bad, wrote Voluntary Simplicity, which has since become a standard work in the field. We can describe voluntary simplicity as a manner of living that is outwardly more simple and inwardly more rich, Elgin explained in that book. The objective is not dogmatically to live with less, but is a more demanding intention of living with balance in order to find a life of greater purpose, fulfillment and satisfaction.<p>Elgin, a bearish, bearded, soft-spoken man, takes the lectern. Apocalyptic thinking tinges some aspects of the voluntary-simplicity movement, and Elgin speculates that looming shortages in global supplies of nonrenewable resources will eventually force people in wealthy countries to consume less. But Elgins message is largely optimistic and inclusive. He finishes his talk by addressing some myths about voluntary simplicity: that it entails living in poverty, abandoning city comforts for rural hardships, eschewing beauty, or adopting a life of drop-out, screw-off hedonism. You dont just go down to the coffeehouse and hang out with other prime-of-life slackers, he concludes. Through simple living youre actually dropping in: to community, to family, to relationships.<p>The crowd laps it up. They ask spirited questions, sign mailing lists, and continue the discussion during the coffee hour afterward. In between signing copies of his books, Elgin scornfully mentions a snotty article about the downshifting phenomenon that recently appeared in a prominent national magazine. The tone of that article deeply bothered me, he says. These are peoples lives were talking about. Downshifting and voluntary simplicity arent mere West Coast woo-woo. Theyre not just a few more passing trends. The foundation of simple living entails development of the spirit and the inner life. Simple living is a matter of the heart.<p>Embodying these words, Dick Roy stands deep in conversation with a knot of earnest, middle-aged men and women. Were living at a time when much of the underlying nature of society is inherently destructive, he says in a patient voice. The good news is that, in America, in Portland, we also have an enormous amount of free will. Jeanne and I, he adds, gesturing across the room to his wife, decided to focus our energy on free will.<p>Dick Roy serves as a prototype of one genus of downshifter, the men or women whose very success causes them to challenge the premises of the American dream. These philosophical downshifters, however, might represent only a visible and vocal minority of those heeding simplicitys call. Increasingly--perhaps epidemically--Americas professionals are having downshifting thrust upon them. More and more, downshifting is becoming synonymous with economic downturn, says Gerald Celente of the Trends Research Institute. Aging baby boomers are being downsized and responding, I dont want to work for a corporation any more. I gave them 15 or 20 years of my life and lost my job for all my trouble. Now Id rather work less, earn less, and spend less. <p>But preferring not to doesnt come easily to a man or woman reeling from job loss. Thats clear on a June morning in Cleveland as a group of downsized professionals gather in a long windowless room above the Asian market. Like the 90 or so idled executives whove driven to this meeting, the neighborhood stands in transition, a jumble of potholed streets, brick warehouses, and neon-bright minimalls, bisected by Interstate 90 as it roars toward the downtown office towers jutting along the lip of Lake Erie. Those gleaming towers lie barely a mile away. To the jobless climbing from their cars on this hazy morning, however, they seem as distant and unattainable as the Andes.<p>The downsized dont waste time staring into the distance. The defining moment of their week awaits. Straightening their ties, brushing off their blue blazers, fingering their briefcases, they file quickly into the meeting room, grab coffee in Styrofoam cups, swap hail-fellow-well-mets with their neighbors, and settle into folding chairs. The mornings speaker is introduced, a psychologist who will talk about the stress of unemployment. Then, each in turn, the members of the Career Initiatives Center rise for their exercise in self-marketing.<p>They include Steve Nemeth, a production manager who has hit the bricks three times in the last eight years; Tony Markatos, released five and a half years ago from his aerospace job in Southern California and never fully employed since; and Peter Kovalesky, a cost analyst late of a defense-industry job. One by one they state their retooled, carefully crafted career plans--looking to utilize my ability to help midsize companies solve their communications problems; seeking to help articulate clear goals for venture capitalists--until its Doug Daleys turn.<p>Hi, Im Doug Daley, and my career path has been more like a mine field, he says in a light, ironic voice. Eyebrows are raised around the room. Im a corporate attorney with over 25 years experience, but since losing my job with University Hospitals, Ive been reconsidering my profession. Ive recently come to the conclusion that to enjoy being an attorney, you have to be a shark. Well, Im a dolphin, not a shark. Now Im looking for a position in a not-for-profit or a social-service agency.<p>Daley sits down amid sympathetic titters. On the surface, he and his modest ambitions seem admirable but hardly arresting; you certainly wouldnt mark this graying, conservatively dressed, middle-aged lawyer as a revolutionary. Yet Doug Daley is in fact a man standing at the crossroads of two central trends: the diminishing of the traditional job culture and the hunger for a simpler, more meaningful life.<p>The facts and numbers of the downsizing era form a dispiriting litany, a chant that, in Cleveland, sounds like a requiem for an entire way of life. From 1980 to 1990, Fortune 500 companies cut more than 3 million jobs nationwide. The Cleveland area, with a relatively high percentage of multinational corporate headquarters and traditional reliance on heavy manufacturing, was particularly devastated. From 1981 to 1991, 87,500 manufacturing jobs--23 percent of the pre-downsizing total--were lost in the Cleveland area.<p>Through the heaviest hemorrhaging in the 80s, the great bulk of the jobs lost were in the blue-collar sector. In the last part of the decade, however, with the impact of technological innovation and global competition, the bell began to toll for white-collar employees. Especially stricken were the middle managers of large manufacturing enterprises, the contract parsers and number crunchers and payroll jockeys, just the sort of people gathering this morning.<p>The purpose of CIC, a nonprofit cooperative, is to provide support, training, and community for professionals encountering a shifting job market. And most of the members will eventually find new jobs. The positions, though, will likely be with much smaller companies and at a 20 percent cut in pay. And these people will likely be looking for work again within five years.<p>Given this, Doug Daleys proposed career shift begins to sound more hardheaded than whimsical. Rather than try to outguess the next flip in the job market or await some ham-handed, politically motivated mass action, Daley and a growing number of workers are choosing to shorten their perimeters, spend and consume less, and seek satisfaction from sources beyond the exigencies of an insecure workplace, a capricious marketplace, and an increasingly bankrupt government. Simplicity, these people will tell you, equals security.<p>At the conclusion of the Monday morning meeting in Cleveland, the downsized make a bullrush for the door, then tear across the parking lot toward the CIC offices. They anticipate a morning of intense networking, a hungry casing of fresh job listings, and a hot-eyed rush to the phones to follow up leads. Daylight is burning, and many of these people are feeling antsy. It would be different if my services werent required, Tony Markatos, the former aerospace systems analyst, tells me passionately. But corporations need what I can give them. I just have to break through. I just have to get my story to the people doing the hiring.<p>Markatos rips off across the parking lot toward the desks and phones. Doug Daley ambles patiently in his wake.<p>On a rare sun-drenched saturday morning, Linda Farris and Paul Wilson sit over coffee at the big kitchen table of their home in southwest Portland. They live on a quiet street shaded by high Douglas firs and graced by rambling houses with imaginative gardens; Wilson and Farriss own house sings with the additional resonance of being paid for. The paid-off mortgage came as a byproduct of three years of mindful frugality.<p>Children of the 60s, Farris and Wilson never planned to chase money. They envisioned lives of service, emotional and intellectual fulfillment, and environmental responsibility, ideals their generation imbibed like mothers milk. Indeed, after the two graduated from elite, liberal Reed College in Portland in 1972, their standard of living barely blipped. Even after Farris labored through medical school and Wilson earned graduate degrees in forestry and law, they got around in just one car. They took buses and arranged Byzantine schedules and bought used books but never considered themselves needy. They were driven by motives other than money. <p>But gradually, incrementally, without much conscious effort, the couple started to prosper. They finished school and paid off their loans. With a double professional income and no kids, they could easily afford the restaurant meal, the weekend getaway, the winter ski trip. They bought a second car.<p>I really enjoyed getting that car, Farris recalls with a laugh. I figured, Im a doctor now! Why shouldnt I have my own car? <p> Farris opened a small internal-medicine practice. Wilson rose through a series of public-policy posts to become administrative director of the environmental law program at the Lewis and Clark College law school in Portland.<p>It was fun, says Wilson, an intense, articulate man with a graying, neatly trimmed beard. After ten years of married life, we had a double income and some time and inclination to enjoy it. We bought art. We went out for a lot of $50 dinners. We started drinking nice wine and putting together our own cellar.<p>A few years after their daughter, Kat, was born in 1984, Farris and Wilson learned of the work of Joe Dominguez and Vicki Robin. Dominguez and Robin, authors of the best-selling Your Money or Your Life, had developed a program for attaining financial independence through moderate, commonsensical frugality, painstaking analysis of every penny earned and spent, and prudent investing. The goal was to stop working for money and to use the resulting time and energy for volunteer and creative pursuits. The idea appealed strongly to Wilson and Farris but on a safely theoretical basis. My attitude was Listen, Im sorry, I spent enough years pinching and counting pennies to start doing it again now,  says Farris. I figured, Im employed, Im a doctor, I deserve to enjoy life a little. <p>So on they rolled through the end of the easy money 80s. Portland was booming, life was on the increase. Finally, in 1990, the couple found time to listen to audio tapes of a Dominguez and Robin workshop. We began going through a transition, says Farris. The program was the best tool we could find for reducing our environmental impact. We started following it, but its only been in the last few years that we started getting really serious about it.<p>During those recent years, according to Wilson, the family saved a ton of money. They paid off their mortgage and, more important, were able to downshift their careers. Farris trimmed her hours significantly. Wilson left his job at the law school to spend more time with the family and pursue freelance projects. He writes, runs his own mediation consulting business, and has served on the board of several environmental organizations. He helped design the curriculum for Dick and Jeanne Roys Northwest Earth Institute.<p>Farris and Wilson refer to themselves as liberated. Yet they acknowledge that liberation comes at a price. You cant downshift and realistically expect to remain in a mainstream position of power or authority, Wilson says. Sometimes--often--I look at the people who are making the major decisions in government and other institutions and realize that Ive chosen to remove myself from that level. I might tell myself I could do better, but the truth is Im not willing to jump through the hoops to attain and hold those positions.<p>Wilsons conflict hints at downshiftings darker side, the anxieties and dilemmas that dont appear in public-opinion polls or other studies treating downshifting as a cultural phenomenon rather than as one experienced uniquely by each downshifter and his or her family. For example, the Merck survey found that 60 percent of its downshifting respondents were women, indicating it might be more difficult for men--however intensely they might be questioning the dominant cultural paradigms of acquisition and career success--to cut loose from those paradigms.<p>Similarly, it is one thing for an accomplished, secure, financially independent, middle-age professional such as Linda Farris to change or scale back her career, and quite another for a young person out to prove and support herself. One of the things our economy is best at is providing people with the opportunity to strive and distinguish themselves, says Dick Roy. The drive to excel, to make your mark, is extremely well ingrained. A life of voluntary simplicity--at least as weve developed it so far--doesnt provide a younger person with the same clear-cut opportunities for satisfying that drive.<p>Meanwhile, older downshifters, especially those doing so more of necessity than choice--face challenges of a different order. Ive got an age problem, an overqualified problem, and a defense-industry-background problem, says Peter Kovalesky, who at 52 recently lost his job as a cost analyst with Westinghouse. But I look on my unemployment as an opportunity to do something different. My wife and I run a volunteer, peer-counseling program for 18 teenagers. Now Ive got a chance to grow the program. I think its the greatest thing in the world.<p>Kovaleskys optimism, however, will most likely temper once his severance pay runs out and he and his wife are forced to subsist on her salary as a public-school teacher and whats left of his unemployment insurance. Sure, weve got our bad days, he says. Days when my wife comes home from school and shes so tired. Public schools arent the places they used to be, you know. There are days when I want to be able to say to my wife, Hon, go ahead and retire. Days when Id just love to have an office to go to.<p>Dick Roys early career followed a classical Horatio Alger arc, showing no signs of the seismic midlife shift to come. He was raised by a single mother under struggling circumstances in the small eastern Oregon town of Baker City. An ROTC scholarship got him through Oregon State University, where he studied civil engineering. While at Oregon State, he also met and married Jeanne Hawley, an energetic young woman from Portland who shared Roys bedrock middle-class ambitions. Upon graduating, Roy was commissioned as a naval officer, and in 1963 the young couple left for a remote posting in Alaska. After leaving the Navy in 1965, he earned a masters degree in engineering at Stanford, then a law degree at Harvard. While Dick read the law at Harvard during the height of Vietnam-era cultural ferment, he and Jeanne read the environmentalist philosophers and marveled at the photos of Earth taken from the Apollo spaceships. <p>We made a lot of our most important decisions at that point, Roy says. We wouldnt have more than one child of our own--two of our three kids are adopted. We would have a garden and recycle everything possible. We would have just one car.<p>Dick Roys present car is a small, eight-year-old, dun-colored Honda, which just now is carrying him west through heavy Friday noon traffic from Portland to suburban Beaverton. He has a lunch meeting with a group of employees at a medium-size electronics-manufacturing firm who have signed up for the Earth Institute course in voluntary simplicity. He dips off the freeway and passes the massive, futuristic world campus of <a name="NYSE:NKE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14254"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nike, Inc.</b></a>; headquarters of the vastly successful Tektronix Inc. lie nearby. This green, hilly former farmland is the heart of both Portlands high-tech boom and its new urban sprawl.<p>Portland is growing at a stunning pace, not only in population but also in economic vibrancy, and the city is fighting to maintain its small-town, environmentally sensitive soul. Aware of their abundant blessings and sobered by the destruction of signature local resources such as wild salmon and old-growth timber, an increasing number of Portlanders are haunted by the intimation that here, finally, the right economic balance must be struck, the mythical good life achieved. Sustainability, voluntary simplicity, and personal rightsizing have become civic passions.<p>Churning along in his reliable little Honda, Roy seems like just the person to cultivate and channel those passions. I think Im ideally suited to bring the voluntary-simplicity message into the workplace, he says. Because of the success I had as an attorney, Ive got a great deal of credibility within the business community. We need to make it clear that downshifting, choosing to live more frugally, arent just fringe ideas divorced from the normal working persons concerns. The workplace is where people put most of their energy and talent and aspirations. And its certainly where people spend most of their time.<p>The offices of Deanco Corp. hum with the silent melody of a well-run company. This is Roys first visit to the company, yet he wheels around the unfamiliar halls with an easy grace. A fit, vigorous, steely-eyed man, he looks every bit the former attorney and naval officer.<p>In a large conference room a dozen people look up pleasantly from their Gardenburgers and containers of pasta salad. The class, equally divided by gender, is made up of young, bright, relaxed, open-collar administrators and engineers, along with one spike-haired dude from the shipping room. Roy welcomes them to the program and for the next half-hour lays out his heretical yet nonthreatening rap.<p>He reviews the reading in the upcoming course. He talks about voluntary simplicity and describes the circumstances of his own downshifting. He lists all the corporations and bureaus that have taken his course, ranging from <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> and Columbia Sportswear to the Environmental Protection Agency and the U.S. Attorneys Office. Then, changing gears, he describes a group of people in Seattle who, through conscious frugality, live comfortably on less than $500 per person per month.<p>See, if you really take this seriously, Roy says lightly, you can get rid of everything and really start enjoying life.<p>The flourishing, confident folks at Deanco respond with polite, oh-sure-someday laughter. Dick Roy waits for a tactical, appraising moment--long enough to let the first seeds of doubt take root around the the room--then laughs along with them.<p>Doug Daleys got a live one on the phone, an angry, frightened, and confused woman just laid off from a major firm in Cleveland. I think CIC might be just the place for you, he says softly, rocking forward in the chair, gesturing for the kibitzers around the front desk to pipe down. Its the day after the self-marketing session, and Daley is putting in his volunteer hours as day manager at the CIC. He explains the centers mission to the woman, then covers the mouthpiece with his hand. Shes calming down, he whispers, with a smile and a wink. Sure, people change their minds about their jobs once they come here, Daley tells her. As a matter of fact, I changed my mind myself.<p>Daleys own growth through joblessness began in 1991, when he temporarily left his position as associate general counsel for University Hospitals of Cleveland to have hip surgery. After graduating from Ohio State University law school in 1969, Daley sailed into corporate practice. At Midland-Ross, a former Fortune 500 company since dissolved in a leveraged buyout, his work required extensive international travel. Two subsequent jobs, each bearing increased responsibilities and salaries, followed. Still, despite his success, Daley harbored doubts about his profession. The low esteem the public holds for lawyers really started to bother me, he says.<p>While Daley was recuperating from hip surgery in 91, he was shuffled out of a job. Daley decided to take a break from the law. For a year and half he sold mens suits in a department store, rocking back on his heels, humming along with the Muzak, counting the clicks of the escalator. Finally, disgusted at the waste of his time and talents, he quit the store late in 1993. I decided it was better to be an unemployed lawyer than an underemployed clerk, he says. Daley started dipping into his retirement funds to pay his bills and spending time at the Career Initiatives Center, looking for another legal job.<p>Daleys purpose wasnt to downshift, but while going through the centers self-assessment test, he began questioning his professional goals. At the same time, he found enjoyment and satisfaction in performing networking and counseling chores around the center. Hes turned his job search in that direction.<p>The historian David Shi points out that while voluntary simplicity has gone in and out of vogue for centuries--Jesus, Buddha, Thoreau, and Gandhi, after all, could all be construed as their respective eras equivalent of downshifters--it has always represented a minority report. Voluntary simplicity--consciously, deliberately choosing a more frugal, simple way of life--runs against the grain of our consumer culture, he says. Unless they have no choice about the matter, and if history is any indication, a majority of Americans are never going to live simply.<p>Indeed, even in Cleveland, the fat life seems always at hand. Downtown, in the shadow of the various corporate headquarters, baseball fans fill the new, jewel-like Jacobs Stadium for Indians games. The Cleveland Clinic, Case Western Reserve University, and the citys museums and cultural institutions are all flourishing. Down at the Flats along the Cuyahoga, young professionals sip drinks at sidewalk cafes and watch the giant barges lumber through. A few blocks away, the postmodernist blade of the brand-new Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum thrusts confidently into the future.<p>But here at the CIC, in the booming shadow of the interstate, the future bears a more layered cast. Morning winds down, and with it the early euphoria and sense of purpose. A dozen or so diehards are still poring over job listings and bleakly considering an afternoon of cold-calling prospective employers, but most of the members have flaked off for home. Doug Daley still energetically mans the front desk, fielding phone calls, directing traffic.<p>Watching him work, Im reminded of an observation Paul Wilson had made in Portland. Whatever world youre in, one part tends to reinforce the next, he said. The mainstream job culture is full of reinforcements--a salary, a structure for your time, an office to go to every morning, clothes to wear, people to talk to, a title or profession to label yourself with. When youre safely in that world, it all makes perfect sense, and you couldnt imagine living differently.<p>But it works the same way in a simpler life, Wilson continued. You might start riding a bike to work for exercise, for instance. But riding a bike makes you aware of the air youre breathing, which leads to rethinking your consumption and recycling patterns. You cut down on all the stuff cluttering up your house and realize you really dont need such a big house. And without a big house, you dont need a high-pressure, self-destructive job to pay for it. One morning, you wake up and wonder how you ever could have lived that way.<p>Doug Daley looks like he hasnt been on a bike for decades, and global warming is probably the least of his concerns. Yet he, too, is striving for an artful and sustaining balance while struggling to leave one world for another.<p>This makes me feel good, he says, gesturing toward the desk and the phone. Helping each other out makes a lot us feel good.<p>Sometimes I look back and regret its taken me this long to come to these conclusions, to make these changes, but thats who I am, thats how I got here, Daley says. If a lot of money doesnt follow, thats all right. I figure Ive got 15 to 20 years more in my working life. Ive already spent that long being unhappy, personally and professionally. For the second half of my life, I want to be able to get up in the morning and go to work with the semblance of a smile on my face.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Employment, Lifestyle

