	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>John Grisham, Meet Jenny Jones</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-John Grisham...JennyJones</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> JOHN GRISHAM, MEET JENNY JONES <p>David Ramus is a best-selling novelist for the 1990s: a pony-tailed ex-junkie with a dysfunctional family, a string of wives, and a Frenchman on his tail. It's great for book sales but a bit maddening for the art-world folks to whom Ramus still owes millions. <p> By Vincent Coppola  <p> So glad you could make it." Judy Carlisle smiles and welcomes the FBI agent who's trying to put her former husband in prison. Many other enemies of soon-to-be-famous novelist David Ramus have joined her today, making for a grim choir in the gray-green U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Atlanta.  <p> For the occasion, the 40-year-old Ramus is dressed in funeral black, as befits a trendy writer. The pony-tailed former art dealer doesn't glance back at Carlisle, his third ex-wife, to whom he owes more than $200,000. Seated at a crowded defense table, Ramus just shakes his head bleakly as a dozen attorneys take turns denouncing and defending him.  <p> "We're not talking isolated instances of fraud and dishonesty," fumes one lawyer, setting the day's tone. "We're talking wholesale fraud and dishonesty."  <p> When summoned to the stand, the embattled Ramus opens with grand bravado, declaring himself a man whose "great love was art." Unfortunately, he adds, he was also an alcoholic and an addict. "People don't trust me," he says, groping for humility. "I understand why." His voice is as resonant as a Pentecostal preacher's. <p> But soon Ramus wilts under a barrage of questions. The writer turns to Judge James Massey, seeking aid as the lawyers swarm at him. "I invoke my Fifth Amendment rights," he says, sweating. "Your Honor? How should I say it? I take the Fifth? The Fifth?" <p> Before the hearing is over, Ramus has invoked his constitutional right more than 100 times, refusing even to identify his signature on a bounced check. The FBI man snorts in disgust, realizing he won't get any clues here about the whereabouts of millions Ramus says he lost in the art market from 1991 to 1993.  <p> Carlisle whispers bitterly: "He thinks he's smarter than everybody."<p>But Judge Massey isn't impressed by Ramus. "This is a no-brainer," he says, tossing control of the author's tangled affairs to acourt-appointed trustee. "He can't block off ... his past." <p> Six weeks later it's May, and David Ramus's past hasn't just caught up with him, it's threatening to roll right over him. Besides being bankrupt, the novelist is reviled in the highest circles of the art world. He's being dogged by a former French paratrooper bent on justice. And the U.S. Attorney in Atlanta has just announced three felony fraud charges that could put him in prison for 30 years. With the exception of Cathy, his fourth and current wife, everyone who knows Ramus seems to be suing or vilifying him. <p> But in a bizarre 1990s twist, all this might actually be good news. Ramus's trial will likely coincide with a marketing blitz to support his appearance on best-seller lists this fall. Having received $1 million for domestic rights to his first book, Thief of Light, he's being promoted as John Grisham with earrings and a tattoo on his butt. The criminal charges should combine with a $200,000 publicity budget and a 125,000-copy first printing to propel Ramus to instant fame.  <p> Thief deserves much of the success it will get. The book is a pulpy but full-tilt thriller about art dealer Adrian Sellars, a man addicted to heroin and high risk. Sellars has a lucrative sideline, commissioning fraudulent paintings that Japanese gangsters use to bribe politicians back home. When the arrangement falls apart, he's targeted by razor-wielding yakuza. The made-for-Hollywood scenario may not be plausible, but it's gut-wrenching in its honesty: Many of the plot points, including a harrowing heroin withdrawal, come from Ramus's life.  <p> The book is also a dead-on account of the furious hustle that went on behind the genteel scrim of Madison Avenue's art galleries, auction houses, and salons during the speculative 1980s. In Thief, Impressionist masterpieces are merely "pictures" and appreciation means a jump in retail value. Empty seats make inflated bids at overheated auctions, while "recently unearthed estate pieces" flow through the back door from nearby galleries. In 1995, as the art market begins to perk once more, it's a timely portrait. <p> Again, Ramus knows what he's talking about. The 1980s art bubble was his habitat, the pivot on which his life has turned. First, this unforgiving market landed him in a psychiatric ward, wracked by withdrawal pains and with a herd of creditors on his tail. Then, at his lowest point, it supplied the material for his reinvention as a blockbuster novelist. It's been quite a turnaround for Ramus, a college dropout whose previous experience with creative writing was limited to bad checks.  <p> On a drizzly spring day, Ramus allows a visitor into his rented Atlanta house. In person, the writer's mildness seems at odds with his flashy image: He's like a piano teacher who wants to pass for a pirate. After greeting his guest, he glances into the front yard, fearful that a process server, or an irate Frenchman, might be lurking in the azaleas. Then he locks the door and sinks into a brown velvet sofa. Brushing back his shoulder-length hair, he tries to explain how he came to land on the cusp between fame and misfortune.  <p> Like his new novel, Ramus's story quickly accelerates beyond the twists and turns of standard fiction. It's a dysfunctional family saga, played out against an art market that reached obscene levels of greed just as Ramus himself spun out of control. "I was one of those people born without a barometer as to who he was," he says. "So you try to grab on to something to define yourself. If it's not your reflection in some woman's eye, maybe it's drugs. Or money."  <p> Or all of the above.  <p> Ramus grew up amid the wealth of Palm Beach, Florida, in a family where illusion often masked a harsh reality. His maternal grandfather, Milton Freshman, was an auctioneer who moved to Florida from Atlantic City after World War II. Freshman always kept a chauffeured Rolls-Royce outside his elegant Trosby Auction Galleries on Royal Poinciana Way. As a liquidator of prominent estates, he was a legendary businessman, but as a Jew, he wasn't invited through many front doors.  <p> Richard Ramus, David's father, was a burly man, six feet five inches tall, who married Freshman's daughter Connie, a profoundly troubled young woman. From the start, Richard struggled to live up to the expectations of his richer in-laws and took it out on his family. "My husband was unaffectionate, super sensitive, angry," says Ramus's mother, now named Connie Kaufman. Indeed, Richard Ramus exudes bitterness even today. "David is my son," he says before hanging up on a reporter. "Unfortunately."  <p> Kaufman herself suffered savage bouts of depression. One time David found her overdosing on pills in a Holiday Inn. Another time she slit her wrists. As she was wheeled away on a gurney, she screamed at her terrified son: "Who are you to save my life?" Ramus's parents divorced when he was about ten, remarried, and divorced again when he was a teenager. "Our home was stormy," Kaufman says now.  <p> Palm Beach, meanwhile, was idyllic. For a role model Ramus chose his uncle Bobby Freshman, whom he remembers as "romantic and beyond cool." With his friend Reed Galin, now a correspondent for CBS News, Ramus lounged at the beach, played tennis at the country club, rode his bike along the coast. "It must have been such a dichotomy for him," says Galin. "He knew he was lucky, but at the same time he had this really troubled family." Indeed, the youngster's loneliness was palpable. He began drinking and liberated pills from his mother's medicine cabinet, passing them out like jelly beans in an attempt to make himself more popular. <p> Ramus did poorly in school. His real education came when he passed through the neoclassical faade of his grandfather's auction house. There he'd spend hours. Paintings told stories to Ramus; he could sense every brush stroke, understand every emotion, feel life pulsing beneath the varnish and oils, a gift marvelously apparent in Thief of Light. Nonetheless, Palm Beach began to seem like a prison. His friendship with Galin faded, while his relationship with Richard Ramus festered. "David always wanted to do it better than his father had," says Galin.  <p> If so, he seemed destined to fail. Searching for a sense of family, the younger Ramus also stumbled into a disastrous marriage. It ended when his young wife cleared their apartment into a rental van and drove off. He dropped out of the University of Florida after just a year studying painting. "I had no talent," he says."But it was clear to me who did, as clear as if a light was shining on them. I began to believe I could be a great art dealer." <p> His opportunity would come, but at the price of losing his only hero. In 1973, Bobby Freshman died of a heart attack on the golf course. Soon afterward, patriarch Milton Freshman developed Alzheimer's disease. Despite some misgivings, Richard Ramus was tapped to take over Trosby Auction Galleries. David swallowed his pride to become vice president. "I wanted very much to have a father," he says. "A wise father in a gray suit and a striped tie. A man I could go to and say, Dad, what do I do now?' "  <p> But Richard Ramus wasn't much of an example. The business was already shaky due to years of high-expense living by the Freshmans. In 1979 the elder Ramus moved shop to Atlanta, but he couldn't stave off the inevitable. Within three years, Trosby had declared bankruptcy. More than 200 clients were left unpaid for a half-million dollars in jewelry, antiques, and furniture the Ramuses had sold. Richard got a slap on the wrist from the Georgia Auctioneer's Commission for mixing company funds with clients' money. David was never censured, and quickly began distancing himself from his father's ethics. "That's the irony here," says Bernard Karr, a New York antiques dealer who knows both men.  <p> By 1980, David Ramus had started up a side business appraising art for insurance companies. With the collapse of Trosby, this would become his route into independent art dealing. He was just 25, but his timing couldn't have been better.  <p> Before long, Ramus found a valuable 19th-century painting covered in dust on a local woman's porch. The lady wouldn't sell for a penny less than $15,000, so he brought in a collector who put up $7,500 and cosigned a $7,500 note. It was the young man's first taste of speculative debt.  <p> In New York, Christie's agreed to auction the painting. Ramus was sure he'd get $30,000. But he encountered what he says was a "knockout ring," a scheme in which dealers collude to lower the winning bid. His first big deal looked set to top out at $25,000. Heart pounding, only a few dollars in his pocket, Ramus began bidding to force the price up. It was a huge risk but when he ended by getting his price, the rush was as good as drugs. He began rising fast.  <p> "I didn't learn the right lesson," he says now. "The right lesson was to take the safe $25,000 and buy another good painting to sell. But I have this thing there's never gonna be enough on the plate for me."  <p> His appetite carried over into his personal life. He dated women who were emotionally adrift, eager to believe in the dashing art dealer. In turn, they would mother him and get high with him. A marriage to Atlanta heiress Lisa Dettelbach flared bright and fell apart. Then Ramus met Judy Carlisle, a custodian's daughter from Michigan who had come south to study art. "He was so charming, so tasteful," Carlisle recalls, her voice dripping venom. "An artist with all these sensitivities." Their common-law marriage produced a daughter in 1987.  <p> Ramus was in the fast lane now, living on Park Avenue in New York City, wearing Armani, and advertising in Vanity Fair just as the art market exploded. Two Mercedes gleamed in the driveway of his Atlanta condo. He flew to Paris to buy off the walls of the best galleries. A million dollars in paintings,Renoir, Matisse, Monet, Degas, passed through his galleries each month. Another fortune vanished up his nose. Even conservative collectors found him seductive, an avatar of all that was right with the 1980s. <p> "I was working my ass off," says Ramus. "And I was partying. Drinking, smoking pot, snorting coke." His world was as chaotic as a Kandinsky. "You knew when you got invited to David's house, you'd get ripped out of your mind," says Ramus's current wife, Cathy, who was part of the same scene. "We'd smoke pot, eat caviar, drink vodka out of little shooters." In darker rooms, Ramus would vacuum up cocaine and pop the Dilaudid tablets he got from a friendly dentist.  <p> One night at Chez Jacqueline, a restaurant in lower Manhattan, Ramus approached the daughter of a New York movie icon.  <p> "Have you ever smoked opium?"  <p> "No," she replied, "but I've got some heroin. Come with me to the bathroom."  <p> "That was it," says Ramus. "I knew what heroin did. It was what I was looking for, something to fill the hole inside me."  <p> "What is a painting worth?" asks David Ramus philosophically. "It's a couple of dollars worth of oil paint on a couple of dollars worth of canvas. It becomes valuable only when enough people have a shared perception that it's worth money."  <p> During the go-go 1980s, however, everyone suddenly shared this perception. Many even believed art got more valuable daily. And because they did, it did. Fine art doubled in price annually. In 1987, Van Gogh's Irises sold for $53.9 million. Dealers and art investors expected to see a $100 million painting before long.  <p> Amid the insanity, Ramus thrived. He jetted to Tokyo, Kyoto, and Osaka, where corporate buyers snapped up all the French Impressionist paintings he could deliver, even bad ones. "I made a lot of people a lot of money," he says proudly. But by now he was buying paintings on payment schedules that would make a used-car dealer blanch. He was confident that the surging market would always bail him out. "I could walk into any gallery and say, I love that. How much is it?' " he says.  <p> In the South, Ramus became something of a celebrity. A group of prominent collectors funded a million-dollar line of credit for him at an Atlanta bank, allowing them to share in his profits. Among his new partners were swells such as millionaire banker Scott Probasco Jr., carpet magnate Nathan Lipson, and blue-blood businessman Noel Wadsworth. These men had no idea whom they were bankrolling. "Everybody is happy," says Ramus. "But nobody knows I'm a performing addict, snorting vast quantities of heroin." <p> In December 1989, the performance came to a crashing halt when Ramus's body gave out. He detoxed in an Atlanta psychiatric ward, an experience he captures to the last twitch and spasm in Thief of Light. Then he flew to the Betty Ford Clinic to get his head together. While still hospitalized, he sold a painting by the French artist mile Bernard for $1 million, clearing a $250,000 profit. He might have kicked heroin, but he was still addicted to another kind of rush.  <p> In the fall of 1990, however, the art market's fever finally broke. "It was like somebody threw a switch," says Ramus. Pundits blamed slumping Tokyo real estate, overambitious auction houses, rumors of war in the Middle East. Whatever the cause, it was no short-term phenomenon, the bubble had burst. At some auctions only one in five pieces sold. Sotheby's stock fell almost 65 percent.  <p> Ramus flew into a panic: His life was based entirely on rising prices. "My dealers stop buying," he says. "I have a $40,000-a-month payment here, a $30,000-a-month payment there, $10,000 over there. A $6,000 interest bill. A judge decides I should give [Carlisle, with whom he had split] $14,000 a month in temporary alimony. I can't sell a thing to save my life, so I start taking whatever I can get. A $300,000 picture goes for $50,000. I've got people screaming at me for money. If you're the loudmouth that's going to hurt me the most, you get paid."  <p> Hundreds of dealers saw their businesses wither and die this way and thousands of fine-art "investors" were stuck with big losses or paintings they never wanted for their own walls. That's not why Ramus has been spending so much time in court lately. To understand why everyone wants his hide, consider instead this fact: On June 30, 1992, the balance sheet at David Ramus Ltd. listed assets of $3.1 million. A year later, when Ramus shutdown his business, he was $4 million in the hole. "The question occurs:Where did the money go?" says Peter Quist, one of the attorneys at this spring's bankruptcy hearing.  <p> On this issue Ramus is rather vague. But he hardly allayed his debtors' suspicions by leaving nothing in the window of his defunct Atlanta gallery but a magician's hat and some playing cards. <p> Jokers.  <p> For three years now, Jean-Pierre Guillaume has pursued Ramus as doggedly as Inspector Javert stalked Jean Valjean in Les Miserables.It was Guillaume and his wife, Suzanne, who pressured the U.S. Attorney's office to indict the former art dealer this May. As with many of Ramus's creditors, Guillaume's gripe concerns a painting that Ramus sold without handing over the proceeds. This practice, prosecutors allege, could explain much of the money missing from Ramus's business.  <p> Guillaume is the son of renowned Paris art dealer Paul Guillaume, who was an intimate of Picasso and Modigliani. The Frenchman first met Ramus while living on a peanut farm in southern Georgia. Guillaume was getting divorced, and his art collection was to be divided in the settlement. Ramus came to appraise it and did a good job, too, says Guillaume.  <p> The real trouble started in 1991, when Guillaume consigned a painting, William Merritt Chase's Wash Day in Brooklyn, to Ramus for sale. The art dealer got $145,000 for it from millionaire Atlanta developer Thomas G. Cousins but he didn't notify Guillaume of the sale and, federal prosecutors say, kept the money for himself.  <p> Guillaume sued and won, but Ramus defaulted after making just two reimbursement payments. Then, according to a judgment by Fulton Country Superior Court, Ramus sold the Chase painting again for $151,500. This time he didn't pay Cousins. Irked that Ramus had profited twice from his art, Guillaume bombarded local prosecutors with documents, depositions, allegations. "I've got to prove that the justice system works," he says. "It is one of the reasons I came to America."  <p> Ramus frets that Guillaume, who saw combat as a paratrooper in Algeria, might be passionate enough to take justice into his own hands. The bearded, 60-year-old Frenchman seems loath to reassure him. He shrugs when asked whether he has ever followed Ramus around Atlanta in his Land Rover. "I am not in that business anymore," he says jokingly.  <p> Such fears, lawsuits, and judgments are piled like snowdrifts over Ramus's life. According to bankruptcy papers, he owes at least $3.6 million to private creditors and another $357,000 in taxes. His rich southern investors are on the hook for his $1 million credit line. Ramus even owes his boyhood friend, Reed Galin, who says he lost $125,000 when an Andrew Wyeth painting vanished.  <p> Although he can't quite explain where all the money and paintings went, Ramus swears he'll pay his debts eventually. Remorse, however, is a different matter. Playing back events in his mind, he says, he's not sure he'd do anything differently.  <p> "I couldn't bear being a failure," he says.  <p> "This is how I live now," says Ramus with  a sigh. He's conducting an Architectural Digest tour in reverse, pointing to a crack in the ceiling. "This bathroom leaks. We can't use it." He scurries past a set of glass doors, not wanting to draw attention to the swimming pool.  <p> "We sold the stereo to buy groceries," he claims. "And I almost got $800 for that couch from a pregnant woman. I told her velvet would feel so good when the baby was born. I had her this close. "Ramus plops himself forlornly onto the couch. "Please keep in mind," he says, "that the only person whose lifestyle changed because of all this has been me."  <p> But in fact, Ramus has been doing fine lately, especially considering that, according to his bankruptcy filing, he has no income. True, his Japanese jet-setting has been scaled back to sushi on Wednesday nights. But Cathy Ramus just got a new BMW. And Ramus himself enjoys an occasional stay at the Ritz Carlton Hotel in Palm Beach "for research." For this return to luxe, the couple must thank Ramus's production of one of 1995's most eagerly awaited novels. <p> Ramus wrote Thief of Light in ten months, starting in October1993. His preparation included two days in jail, the arrest was engineered by Guillaume, a few beers with local novelist Charles McNair, an evening writing course at Emory University, and the unshakable notion of "a guy in a box with no way out." The book was pecked out on a borrowed word processor as Cathy acted out many of the scenes for him. Says Ramus: "It felt as natural to me as a boxer stepping into a ring."  <p> McNair's own first novel, Land o' Goshen, had taken 14 years to write, so he was dubious about his protg's chances. "On a hot summer day, he brought the manuscript to my front steps," says the writer. "He was so scruffy-looking I didn't even let him in the house. I took it and sat on the porch, thinking I'd read a few pages and send him the obligatory Hang in there' note. But soon I was consumed."  <p> McNair gave Ramus the name of a New York editor, and within days the publishing world was a buzz over a thriller that read like a freight train. Soon Harper Collins executive editor Larry Ashmead, who'd read the manuscript himself, made an offer: $500,000. At the time, Ramus was unemployed and Cathy was cooking for $7 an hour. Ramus's agent turned him down anyway. Ashmead doubled his bid, and Ramus had a new career.  <p> "It was hilarious," says art dealer Vance Jordan, who had spent two years and a small fortune to collect $200,000 Ramus owed him. "I figured the news stories were a plant. I never thought the guy was literate."   <p> Next came a race to see who'd get dibs on this bonanza. Ramus set up JJN, a limited-liability company named for his three daughters, with his wife as sole shareholder. JJN received the first payment from Harper Collins and quickly paid $51,000 to Ramus's creditors, a move that did little to assuage them, especially when they heard about Cathy's new BMW.  <p> In November, Guillaume and others tried to establish that their fraud claims took precedence over any other losses. But a month later six of Ramus's major creditors, the southern art collectors, forced the newly hot author into Chapter 11, putting all other legal maneuvers on hold.  <p> In the resulting bankruptcy filing, Ramus listed assets of just $1,500.  <p> Which leaves us, as they say, in medias res. Ramus has earned another $700,000 selling the foreign rights to Thief of Light. He's working on a second novel, keeping a weather eye out for FBI agents and unhappy Frenchmen. And he's coaching his daughter Juliana's soccer team. After he was indicted on criminal charges in May, he went out and treated himself to a thick steak covered in barnaise sauce at Chops, one of Atlanta's top restaurants. <p> The novelist's trial will likely get underway around the time Thief hits bookstores this fall. A huge promotional campaign in September will feature his sensitive face, full-page ad in The New York Times, national tours, television and radio commercials. Ramus will squeeze in court dates between the interviews. Meanwhile, the whole affair is already fading from memory in New York's art world, pushed into the background by a market that's once again attracting "fresh meat," to use the Thief term.   <p> "Believe me," says dealer Vance Jordan, "David Ramus is no longer the most wanted man on Madison Avenue. The most wanted man right now is a new client."  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Small Business Ownership, Art Industry

