	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Sonny Bloch Faces the Music</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						America's top financial talk-radio host is smooth, all right--so smooth he could take the Mafia's money as a kid and still have a million people listen to his advice. It'll be harder to talk his way out of links to investment swindlers and a sex scandal. <p>By Christopher Byron<p>Sonny Bloch settles behind a microphone in his little studio in Tampa, Florida, flips some switches and spins some knobs, and begins his nightly ritual of seduction. Over the airwaves his voice spreads like a balm, soothing an AM dial that's more often inflamed by hate and fear. Bloch, by contrast, seeks to reassure. His subject is personal finance; his mission is to ease the frustration of everyone who's ever been confused by fine print and fast talk.<p>Bloch listens to problems and he gives back plain truths. He charms the young lovers who want to buy a new home together. He comforts the retiree who wants to withdraw money from a Keogh account without penalties. He bonds with the bus driver who is refinancing a second mortgage. For more than a million listeners in 41 states, he is shrink and accountant in one. People lay bare their lives and their bank accounts for him. In return, he gives them straight talk for an age in which money provokes more anxiety than even sex.<p>Like all talk-radio stars, the 58-year-old Bloch builds his business on intimacy--or rather, the illusion of it. Since Franklin Roosevelt we have invited these disembodied voices into our homes, and over time we have come to trust them. Rush Limbaugh tells us how to think; Dr. Ruth how to make love. And in the 1990s, ever-growing numbers of people tell us how to mind our money. Perhaps a half-dozen personal-finance experts now dispense advice nationally over the AM airwaves; many more operate locally. Some of the names are familiar: Ken and Daria Dolan, Adriane Berg, Bill Bresnan. Bloch stands above them all in his easy rapport with listeners. People feel they know Sonny Bloch. When they stop his Cadillac to thank him for his help--and they do--it's as if he himself had talked the bank into approving their loans.<p>Perhaps as a result of such devotion, Bloch's show is the longest-running of its type in the country. He attracts gilt-edged advertisers such as <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a>, Lincoln Mercury, and The Wall Street Journal, and welcomes guests such as Gerald Ford, Louis Rukeyser, and W. Randall Jones, founder of Worth. Bloch is heard nightly on stations including powerful WOR-AM in New York. Yet beneath it all, The Sonny Bloch Show is just that--a show. And Sonny himself is its velvet voice for hire. Despite his listeners' loyalty, he's not always looking out for them. As with many of radio's financial talkers, Bloch is also interested in making money for himself. And his on-air expertise, it turns out, is a shtick that's for sale to just about anyone.<p>Demand for financially oriented talk radio is higher than ever, but there's little policing of what goes out over the airwaves. As a result, radio-based swindles are proliferating, often targeting credulous advice-show listeners as their victims. From Dallas to Buffalo to Miami, schemes involving everything from pesos to stamps to trivia quizzes have been shut down. And shockingly, several of the deals under investigation have been pitched by Sonny Bloch himself. If talk radio is the 1990s equivalent of 1980s televangelism, then Bloch may become its first Jim Bakker--a star struck low by scandal. Three grand juries are investigating Bloch's promotion of various soured investments, while the Securities and Exchange Commission is also probing his conduct. There may even be a sex controversy brewing: When the Feds raided Bloch's condominium on Tampa Bay earlier this year, they found what court papers describe as videotapes showing Bloch in sex acts with apparently underage females.<p>Bloch says he's been an innocent dupe in some financial shenanigans--and he dismisses the sex tapes as products of his own youth, so dated as to be "almost laughable." He will look you full in the face as he makes his defenses, and his voice will never waver. For a moment, you may even believe him. But then you'll discover that Sonny Bloch's tales seldom add up to the whole story. There's a pattern of half-truths here that makes the very idea of Bloch being Middle America's financial advisor seem laughable.<p>In fact, Bloch's life story is a saga almost Runyonesque in its color and bathos. Ever since he spent one heady year as a lounge singer, it seems, Sonny has hungered for fame and fortune. And he has followed that dream the only way he knows how: He takes the money, he asks few questions, and he makes sure the show goes on.<p>It's a lesson he learned young, on the payroll of none other than Mafia boss Meyer Lansky.<p>
In the summer of 1958, rock 'n' roll was sweeping the country, and young Sonny Bloch, who had a knack for music and was in his fourth year at the University of Miami, wanted to be part of it. He was already a big man on campus: president of his fraternity and the pep club, dating the most beautiful coeds. But the action--the adulation--was in music, so it was toward music that Bloch turned.<p>A born salesman and charmer, Bloch formed his own group. He called it the Coralairs, and it featured himself as lead singer, with four classmates as backup: Sal, Tony, Dave, and Arnie. But the group needed a single to take to the radio stations, and no Miami recording label was interested. So Sonny asked his father, a successful real estate developer in Detroit, to set up a vanity label. Bee Records was born and quickly produced a 45 with Sonny's own "A Lover Is a Fool" on the A side and, on the flip, an up-tempo jingle called "Baby Blue Eyes."<p>It'd be nice to think that Miami immediately went mad for the record, and there's a side of Sonny that remembers it that way. But Sal Ronci, the group's arranger and trumpet player, tells a different story. Tracked down in Daytona Beach, Florida, he strokes a graying mustache and talks of payola: "We had to give a local DJ 10 percent of the business" to get the record airplay. The tactic worked: Soon everyone in Miami was toe-tapping to the Coralairs, and the group was booked at local nightspots like The Rockin' M.B. Sonny became a local celebrity. Wherever he went, teenage girls would begin squealing. It was great.<p>One night toward the end of spring semester, an agent approached the band. Would they come to Havana and play a place called El Comodoro? Four thousand for the week? Free room and board? Cuba then was America's fantasy island, shimmering like a forbidden city in the Caribbean sun. "Of course we were interested," says Sonny. "Wouldn't you have been?" It was all too exciting. Havana! Guys and Dolls, Sky Masterson. They were headed for adventure, five clean-cut guys in their chinos and a dinged-up Ford station wagon with "Sonny Bloch & The Coralairs" painted along the side.<p>In those days you could still catch a ferry from Key West to Cuba, just 90 miles away. The trip lasted maybe eight hours and deposited Bloch just minutes from Malecon Boulevard, Havana's answer to the Cannes Croisette. A man was waiting on the pier. He was short, thin, impeccably dressed. But there was something about him that Sonny and his band mates remember vividly even now--something cold and unblinking. "Welcome to Havana," said the stranger in perfect English. "My name is Santo Trafficante. You will be my guests on the island."<p>The boys were stunned by the scene in Havana. They were normal American youths, half-mad from testosterone poisoning even in the best of times. Now they had landed in a world where the smells, sights, and sounds of sex were everywhere. Fifteen-year-old putas stood on every street corner, while beautiful showgirls scampered naked between dressing rooms. The lads explored with gusto--and so it was not until a few nights later that Arnie sat bolt upright from a book he was reading about Cuba.<p>"Listen to this!" he announced, white as a sheet. "Do you know who this Trafficante guy really is?" The band members blanched in turn at the news: Santo Trafficante of Tampa, Florida, was a mob kingpin and drug smuggler who controlled every brothel and nightspot in Havana. "I was a nice Jewish kid from Detroit," says Sonny now. "What did I know from the Mafia?"<p>Maybe they should have taken the next ferry home, but they didn't. And within two weeks the Coralairs were the rage of Havana--it was good for Trafficante's business. The group played the Deuville and the Teatro National, then began appearing weekly on El Show Des Shows, Cuba's answer to Ed Sullivan. The high point came when they opened the Sans-Souci, Trafficante's attempt to outdo the Tropicana as the gaudiest, swankiest nightclub ever. Before they knew it, they were even playing private parties for Trafficante himself.<p>If you were a friend, or if he wanted to cultivate your favor, Trafficante would empty the room out, close the place down, and have the Coralairs play for just a handful of people, says Bloch, echoing the accounts of other band members. Then in would come the prostitutes, and the men would take their pick and go upstairs while the band kept playing. One rainy weekend, says Bloch, John and Bobby Kennedy came over from Palm Beach; Trafficante closed down the Sans-Souci for them.<p>Once a week, a man even more cold-eyed than Trafficante would pay the boys for their efforts. "It was Meyer Lansky," says Bloch. "He paid me cash money--$4,000 a week." Bloch pauses a moment, perhaps realizing it's unseemly for radio's favorite financial advisor to admit he was once on a Mafia payroll. "I mean, we were just kids," he adds hastily. "What did we know?"<p>Actually, Bloch loved his days in Havana. The delirious times ended only when Fidel Castro's revolution drove the Coralairs from the city. The Batista regime had but three months to survive, and the dictator's troops were so jumpy they would machine-gun anyone who looked at them cross-eyed. One morning Sonny heard shooting outside and got up to look into the street. Bodies hung out of cars; blood pooled in the gutters. We've got to get out of here, he thought. <p>But back in Florida, Bloch couldn't get Cuba out of his mind. He went back by himself a half-dozen times that winter, then reassembled most of the group for a last glorious tour the following summer.<p>
Still, the Coralairs were never destined for real show-business success. They broke up soon after the second summer, and most band members went on to quieter lives. Only Bloch couldn't give up the glitz--not realizing he didn't have the talent to become more than a B-list lounge singer. As the vogue swung away from club acts, Bloch's gigs became increasingly low-rent. He remembers playing a mob-owned joint in New Orleans and some spots in Chicago and Kansas City. And although Castro had driven Trafficante back to the U.S., Bloch says he met his mob sponsor one more time--presiding at a Sinatra concert a year or two before the murder of John Kennedy, in which Trafficante was rumored to have played a part.<p>Eventually Bloch succumbed to pressure and went into real estate, the family business. His father put up some money, and Bloch built a boring but healthy business developing real estate near <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Walt Disney</b></a> World in central Florida. For years the money came easily--but to Bloch it all seemed empty somehow. Where was the applause? Where were the dancing girls? In 1977, his desire for a life in the spotlight reached crisis level. He sold off his real estate business, bought a condo in Palm Beach, and sought to make a name for himself as a playboy among Florida's nouveaux riches. One photo from the era shows him sitting rather ridiculously atop a polo pony, mallet at the ready. Another shows him as a runway model for Gucci clothing, looking like Tom Jones's cheesier cousin.<p>Then, one day in September 1979, Bloch finally stumbled on the calling that could replace music. He was motoring along Ocean Drive in Palm Beach when a man came on the radio and started answering callers' questions about real estate. Bloch turned up the volume; it was a subject he knew well. But the guy didn't have a clue! He called the radio station himself.<p>"That guy you've got on doesn't know what he's talking about," he remembers saying to the station manager.<p>"Oh, yeah? Then maybe you'd like to come in and do it."<p>"Well, maybe I will."<p>A month later, he was on the air.<p>In talk radio, Bloch found a stage on which he could shine as brightly as he ever did in Havana. His financial advice wasn't what made him a hit--it was his voice and his personality. Bloch seemed able to talk with authority about virtually anything. Within three months, the Associated Press had signed him up to do a syndicated show.<p>Bloch easily gained the trust of his listeners. But either he didn't know about the responsibilities that went with that trust--or he didn't care. He aggressively blurred the line between his own opinions and on-air plugs for his advertisers. In the process, Bloch became a sort of financial rent boy, doing television infomercials and offering his credibility for hire on the radio. And the advertisers loved it. Bloch's shows began with a by-the-book disclaimer. But then for two hours a night the host would slide seamlessly between advice to his listeners and enthusiastic testimonials for his sponsors.<p>And what sponsors! Bloch was as picky about them as he had been about the Coralairs' patrons--which is to say, he took the money and asked few questions. Penny stocks? "Ride with them and take the profit," said Sonny. A travel agent discount card? "It was incredible--I made up the cost in one trip," said Sonny. Advertisers lined up to profit from the unsophisticated investors who would take Bloch at his word.<p>But that was not the worst of it. Behind the scenes, Bloch had undisclosed business links with the promoters of some of the lousiest investments he hawked.<p>
Unlike his flirtation with Santo Trafficante and Meyer Lansky, Bloch's ties with convicted swindlers can't be explained away as a youthful indiscretion. Indeed, prosecutors hope to put the radio talker in prison because of his promotion of various felons' schemes. At the top of their hit list: Bloch's links with the DeAngelis brothers of Brooklyn, New York.<p>Bloch says he first got involved with the DeAngelises in 1992, when the eldest brother, Jack, told Bloch they were starting a gold- and silver-coin investment firm to be based in Pennsylvania's Pocono Mountains. Naturally, they wanted to advertise on The Sonny Bloch Show. Bloch remembers the three siblings as respectable enough and says he accepted them as sponsors after having them "checked out."<p>He couldn't have checked very deeply. At the time, Jack DeAngelis was on probation from a 1986 conviction for conspiracy and fraud. The coin firm, prosecutors have charged, was just another swindle: The brothers were willing to take money from Bloch's listeners but not so eager to provide gold in return. (Jack wasn't charged, but his brothers pleaded guilty to several charges in the scheme.) When the coin company began to unravel, Bloch insisted he had been duped too--that he had no business with the DeAngelises except for the spots on his radio show. This wasn't true.<p>In fact, Bloch had numerous links with the brothers. Jack DeAngelis had his own radio show, for example, Collector's Corner; Bloch-controlled Independent Broadcasters Network distributed it to radio stations around the country. Bloch also appeared as a host for seminars sponsored by the DeAngelises. A column by Jack DeAngelis appeared in Sonny Bloch's Action Line, a newsletter published by Bloch; the DeAngelises plugged Bloch in their own newsletter. And Federal Communications Commission filings show that the brothers were involved in Bloch's efforts to raise millions of dollars by selling investments to his own listeners. The aim: To build a network of small AM radio stations that would buy Bloch's programming.<p>Even without the DeAngelises' involvement, these "limited liability company" deals reflect poorly on Bloch. In his on-air spiels, he invited listeners to invest in at least two stations. Each pitch closed with a toll-free number listeners could call for a packet of financial literature. One packet featured a small radio station in Middletown, Connecticut, while another featured a station in Gainesville, Florida. Remarkably, the prospectuses in both packets were essentially the same--it was as if a single document had been prepared on a word processor, then modified with a few search-and-replace commands.<p>For the Middletown promotion, according to The New York Times, Bloch solicited 200 memberships at $5,000 per unit, a total of $1 million. But for their money--nearly four times the station's eventual purchase price--investors got only a 25 percent interest. Meanwhile, Bloch-controlled Broadcast Radio Group put no money down and received 75 percent ownership. What happened to the surplus $720,000 invested by listeners? Bloch has said most will be spent on "future improvements, promotion, and programming," including shows from his own syndicate.<p>Bloch displayed other links with felons by plugging a "wireless cable" deal on his show. Many wireless-cable investment companies--which raise money to distribute cable-TV programming via radio waves instead of wires--are scams. Both the Federal Trade Commission and the SEC have issued alerts on the topic since 1992, and Bloch should have been wary of anyone pushing such a deal. But in late 1993 or early 1994 he accepted a wireless-cable promoter as a sponsor anyway.<p>Bloch says the deal came to him when a man named Alan Herr approached him to buy time on the show. Again, Bloch says he checked the deal out--but again, he couldn't have checked very closely. Herr was a felon who had been sentenced to 18 months in prison for commodities fraud. His father, Herbert Herr, was sentenced to two and a half years for the same scheme. Bloch knew both men. Alan Herr was associated with a New York art gallery for which Bloch had taped an infomercial; Alan's name and signature also appear on offering documents for some of Bloch's radio deals. Herbert Herr worked for the Bloch operation, fielding telephone calls that resulted from the host's on-air promotions.<p>No one knows how long Bloch has had such links to some of the people pushing deals on his show--or whether he could be as big a dupe as his listeners, as he now maintains. Either way, his cozy world began to fall apart last year when federal regulators received a flood of complaints involving his show. There were gripes about the Herrs' wireless-cable deal, gripes about Bloch's own radio deals, and gripes galore about the DeAngelis brothers and their gold-coin scheme. "We want to work with you on this," the brothers had allegedly told some ripped-off customers. "How about half your money back?"<p>
"Here--listen to this."<p>Sonny Bloch is breezing through downtown Tampa, top down on his Caddy convertible. He takes a cassette from his shirt pocket and pops it into the tape deck. Out comes a shrieking, banshee-like voice. Sonny had better be careful, the tape goes, because he never can be sure if he might be coming out the door one day when a bullet is coming in. Or words to that effect. Bloch carries the tape around like it's a Medic Alert bracelet. "I wanted you to hear it," he says. "This way, if something happens..."<p>Bloch's paranoia may be justified: He's certainly being assaulted from all sides these days. In February, federal agents raided his offices here, seizing tax records as well as tapes of his radio show. They came back a week later and searched his home for a suitcase with $1 million in cash. They didn't find it--but they did come up with those compromising sex tapes. "See, I told you," says Bloch in a show of unconvincing bravado just hours after the raid. "This is a witch hunt."<p>Radio stations that carry Bloch's show have also begun to feel the heat. In February the FBI arrived at New York's WOR-AM, one of the largest talk-radio stations in the country, to cart away more than 700 hours of tapes. "I think WOR could lose its license because of Bloch," says a former top official at the station. Yet WOR remains supportive of Bloch, who is a huge money-spinner for it.<p>In his high-rise digs on Tampa's Harbour Island, where he lives with his second wife, Hilda, Bloch now seems genuinely frightened by what lies ahead. A lifetime of self-promotion is crumbling; the spotlight isn't so warm anymore. "I haven't slept in three days," he confides. Still, he says, no one can get his money--how much, he's not telling. Perhaps sensing storms ahead, Bloch started shedding his wealth into trusts more than 15 years ago. He says he has no assets.<p>The sole extravagance in his apartment also helps keep Bloch sane these days: his one-man broadcast studio, umbilical cord to what's left of all the fame and adulation. Bloch may spend his days in a cold sweat, but he has yet to disclose this fact to his fans, to whom he still broadcasts every weekday. Why should they know? When the evening newsbreak is over and AM stations nationwide patch into Tampa, those listeners want a voice that's smooth and trouble free.<p>And that's what Sonny gives them.<p>"Welcome to The Sonny Bloch Show," he purrs, as he has every weeknight for the last 14 years. "We're here to talk about money, business, real estate--and life."<p>Then he does exactly that. Sonny Bloch has taken the money, and he has asked few questions. Now the show must go on. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
