	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Irreversible Damage</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Irreversible Damage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						A financial scandal at Harvard says much about the medical
industry's lax controls. It says more about a flawed genius 
who tackledand embodiedthe riddle of the human heart.<p>By William Green<p>Before Bernardo Nadal-Ginard arrived at his Boston office on a brisk Monday morning in October 1993, the Spanish native was a figure of immense stature in the medical world. He was cardiologist-in-chief at Children's Hospital, a prestigious teaching institution affiliated with Harvard Medical School. He was a tenured Harvard professor in both pediatrics and cellular biology. And his research into heart disease was so acclaimed that he was talked of as a potential Nobel Prize winner.<p>Nadal-Ginard was driven and intense, known not just for his medical triumphs but also for his superb aesthetic sense. Christie's valued his art collection at $6.75 million. He had few close friends and often clashed with his peers. But his professional admirers were legion. Says Edmund Sonnenblick, the chief of cardiology at New York's Albert Einstein College of Medicine, "He was probably the most important figure in cardiovascular research in the country."<p>But on this autumn day, Nadal-Ginard's towering reputation was about to implode. The doctor had been accused a few days earlier of stealing some checks. Now, when he tried to unlock the door to his office, he found that his key didn't work. Bewildered, he turned to his assistant, Maureen Piccolo, who tried her own key. That failed too.<p>Piccolo called the hospital's vice president, who told her Nadal-Ginard was no longer in good standing at Children's.  His office had been "secured" the night before, and he wouldn't be allowed in without an escort.<p>As a throng of colleagues gathered to witness his humiliation, Nadal-Ginard fled to a nearby lounge. He was usually a man of icy demeanor, but he was shaking now and his voice was slurred. Maureen Piccolo held his hand and hugged him as if he were a frightened child. Despite taking sleeping pills and Prozac, her boss hadn't slept properly in days.<p>Within a week, Nadal-Ginard had checked himself into McLean Hospital, a mental institution in Boston. The psychiatrists there diagnosed him as acutely suicidal. Two months later his troubles became even deeper, as auditors accused him of stealing $7.6 million from the medical foundation he had headed.<p>Nadal-Ginard's case received scant coverage in the press, even though a federal judge found late last year that he had committed fraud. Nadal-Ginard was ordered to repay $6.56 million; he faces a criminal trial this spring. Yet the famed doctor's story is tragedy of the highest order. After escaping poverty and fascism, Nadal-Ginard achieved astonishing success in the U.S., only to be destroyed by his pursuit of status and money. His downfall decimated the legendary research program he created and ended his search for a scientific Holy Graila way to use genetics to make damaged hearts repair themselves.<p>
Bernardo Nadal-Ginard sits in the living room of his duplex in Boston, surrounded by the trappings of a life he is trying to salvagetrappings by which he seems to have measured his own worth. This apartment is less stately than the townhouse he and his wife own just a few blocks away, but it bears ample testimony to his wealth and refined taste. There are books by Erasmus, Euripides, Sophocles, Gide, and Derrida; compact discs of operas by Verdi, Puccini, and Mozart. In the middle of the living room, which overlooks the Charles River, lies a sculpture of an overturned flask spilling liquid. Above the dining-room table hangs a massive aluminum sculpture of a hound in pursuit of a stag. The contemporary art contrasts exquisitely with beamed ceilings, carved mahogany panels, and grand fireplaces.<p>Amid the luxury, though, Nadal-Ginard looks pale and haunted. His face is deeply lined, and there is an overwhelming sadness in his eyes. When he speaks, he covers his face with his hands, as if to prevent anyone from peering beneath his composed exterior. He occasionally breaks into a chuckle or exercises his dry wit, but his manner is more often imperious. "I get things done that need to be done," he says tersely. "I don't do it by kissing asses." It isn't hard to see how he acquired a reputation for arrogance.<p>Though he has already been defeated in one court of law, Nadal-Ginard seems convinced that he can still vindicate himselfas if his career were just one more damaged muscle to be repaired. He spins a web of conspiracy theories to explain his fall. He attacks everyone from the dean of Harvard Medical School to the judge in his civil case, the result of which he is appealing. He has sued the trustees of Children's Hospital, the hospital's acting chief of cardiology, and his former foundation. Claiming they have all tried to "discredit and destroy" him, he demands reinstatement.<p>But the bravado is unconvincing and sadthe more so because Nadal-Ginard's earlier accomplishments were so extraordinary. Indeed, some of his old colleagues now talk as if the man they knew were dead. "We've lost a great scientist and a good friend," says Russell Medford, a former laboratory partner. "We've lost someone who was still in the prime of his scientific life."<p>Born on the island of Majorca on March 14, 1942, Bernardo Nadal-Ginard grew up knowing that others expected him to remain in poverty, to fail like his father. His parents had worked a tiny parcel of land from which they barely scraped enough to survive. General Francisco Franco's fascist government made matters harder, lowering the price of crops and limiting the quantities farmers could produce. Secretly, Nadal-Ginard's family would make surplus flour at night. Young Bernardo hid the extra wheat underground.<p>From the age of four he attended a one-room school. Though he excelled in class, he was dragged home when he was 11 because his parentswho were barely literate themselvescould no longer afford to educate him. He worked with his father, who had by now abandoned farming to make charcoal. A year or so later, Nadal-Ginard gave up this miserable and grimy job and returned to school on a scholarship arranged by his old teacher. If it weren't for this ally, he says gratefully, "I would be a manual worker."<p>When Nadal-Ginard was 14, his father developed such bad emphysema that he could hardly walk 100 yards. Taking over as head of the family, Nadal-Ginard decided they would fare better by raising chickens. "I went to ask for credit at the bank," he says. "They laughed me out." Refusing to give up, he arranged loans from neighbors and set up a primitive poultry farm that enabled his parents to live in relative comfort.<p>Having completed secondary school in two years instead of four, he trained to become a teacher. Again, people told him he would fail. But only two years later he was teaching at his old school. At 18 he married a local girl, Margarita Vicens. Proud of their noble lineage, her parents opposed the match; for a while they even refused to allow the impoverished teacher into their house. The slight just intensified Nadal-Ginard's hunger for success. Before long, he had earned a place in the medical school at the University of Barcelona. He graduated in only four years to become one of the youngest physicians in Spain.<p>After a stint of compulsory service in Franco's army, Nadal-Ginard trained at the National Institute of Cardiology in Mexico, a hotbed of medical innovation during the 1960s. In those days, cardiologistsheart specialistswere expected either to do clinical work, which involves treating patients, or to become researchers. Characteristically, Nadal-Ginard became proficient in both areas. But his inquisitive mind drew him irresistibly to the lab. "I wanted to know more about why things were happening," he recalls. "Why some people had degenerative diseases. Why some people were born with heart diseases."<p>Though his English was only rudimentary, Nadal-Ginard applied to Yale University as a Ph.D. student in developmental biology. In 1972, he moved to America with Margarita and their children, Mireya and Tania. He would never again live in insular, class-ridden Majorca. Just three years later, Bernardo Nadal-Ginard, M.D., Ph.D., landed a job as an assistant professor at the Albert Einstein College of Medicine, in the Bronx section of New York City. He settled into a tiny laboratory and embarked on a research career. For the first time, he felt he would be judged solely by his intellect.<p>A graduate student, Russell Medford, worked alongside Nadal-Ginard for several years at Albert Einstein, usually from early morning until late at night. The Spaniard was "open, warm, and supportive," says Medford, now an associate professor at Emory University's medical school in Atlanta. "He's a person you have to get to know. He's a very shy man." Nadal-Ginard was happiest in the lab. If an experiment yielded crucial information, Medford recalls, he "would run around the room going, That's fantastic! That's amazing! That's wonderful!' The mask of being a distant person would come off."<p>Nadal-Ginard quickly made his mark as a molecular biologist, using genetic techniques to explain how muscle cells function. Again he focused mainly on the heart, a peculiar organ in that it stops producing muscle cells at birth. This characteristic poses a grave problem that would preoccupy Nadal-Ginard for two decades. If muscle cells are destroyed in the womb, say, or by a heart attack, the damage is permanent. Nadal-Ginard searched for a way to reverse this processto induce the birth of new muscle cells so that damaged hearts could become healthy again.<p>Nadal-Ginard was almost alone in using molecular biology to tackle heart problems, an approach that has since become widespread. "He was the father of this field," says Medford. Inspired by his work and by his formidable personality, a string of gifted researchers became his disciples. They were often foreigners with unorthodox rsums, people who needed a chance. Among those he nurtured were Seigo Izumo, currently chief of cardiology at the University of Michigan, and Jeffrey Rottman, now head of arrhythmic cardiology at Washington University in St. Louis. "Everyone looked up to Bernardo," says Medford. "He was a standard to meet."<p>But Nadal-Ginard's obsessive focus on work caused tensions at home. In 1979, he and Margarita divorced, and she returned to Spain with Mireya and Tania. According to Mireya, Margaritanow a nurse in Spainnever understood Nadal-Ginard's "anxiety to keep doing things. She wanted someone who could stay around at home more."<p>In January 1981, Nadal-Ginard received a telephone call from Cliff Barger, a Harvard physiologist he knew only by reputation. Barger told him that the chief of cardiology at Children's Hospitala Harvard affiliatewas about to retire. Barger asked Nadal-Ginard to apply for the prestigious position, which involved overseeing all the hospital's heart programs, including research and cardiac surgery.<p>At the time, chairmen of cardiology invariably specialized in treating patientsnot in research. So Nadal-Ginard, who didn't even have a license to practice medicine in the U.S., guessed Barger had made a mistake. "I said perhaps someone gave him the wrong name or number," he says. "I hadn't seen a patient in about seven years."<p>But Barger was serious. Children's had decided to hire someone in the vanguard of the molecular biology and genetics revolution; Nadal-Ginard would be the first cardiology chief in the U.S. who had learned to use these new techniques. The hospital didn't care that he would not treat patients. "We contacted everybody who'd ever had anything to do with him," says Barger. "Everyone agreed that this was a very unusual man, and one who could lead Children's cardiology into the next century."<p>Children's Hospital, which celebrated its 125th birthday last year, has an unsurpassed reputation for pediatric care. In 1938, the hospital won international renown when one of its surgeons performed the first-ever successful repair of a congenital heart defect. A decade later, a Hungarian named Alexander Nadas began a remarkable 33-year reign as chief of cardiology, turning Children's into the preeminent center in the U.S. for the treatment of pediatric heart disease. At only 39, Nadal-Ginard would become Nadas's successor. Russell Medford loaded his friend's lab equipment into a moving van in the Bronx and drove it to Boston. "It was a wonderful time," he says.<p>Adding to the excitement, Nadal-Ginard got remarried that year to a woman he had met in New York. Vijak Mahdavi, a dedicated researcher with a Ph.D. in biology, was extroverted and aggressive. Her background couldn't have been more different from Nadal-Ginard's: Her family had made a fortune in Iran's electrical industry and now lived in Switzerland. Nonetheless, she and Nadal-Ginard got along well. And with a cultured and elegant woman by his side, the doctor became so sophisticated that a stranger might easily mistake him for a European aristocrat. "She taught my father a lot," says Mireya Nadal-Vicens. "She often convinced him of her opinions, and very few people have been able to do that. He loved that."<p>Mahdavi also understood Nadal-Ginard's obsession with science. Indeed, she became an integral player in his new research programa role for which she was well qualified. She soon became an associate professor at Harvard and was honored for her research by the American Heart Association.<p>Although he had little administrative experience, Nadal-Ginard proved remarkably successful as chief of cardiology at Children's. He hired some outstanding clinical cardiologists to take care of patients and simultaneously built a brilliant research program. In 1986, Daniel Tosteson, the dean of Harvard Medical School, wrote to congratulate him on his "inspired leadership." Under Nadal-Ginard, says Cliff Barger, Children's cardiology department "was probably the best in the world."<p>And Nadal-Ginard's own research continued to dazzle other cardiologists. One of his first projects at Children's had a profound impact on the treatment of a disease in which the aorta and pulmonary artery are attached to the wrong heart chambers. Skillful surgeons could switch the arteries around, but the left ventricle often remained dangerously weak. Experimenting on animals, Nadal-Ginard found a simple solution: By tightening a cord around the pulmonary artery, he could make the sickly ventricle triple in strength in about four days. Aldo Castaneda, then Children's chief of cardiac surgery, tried the technique on babies with great success.<p>At the same time, Nadal-Ginard kept looking for ways to make damaged hearts revitalize themselves. Under his guidance, Children's molecular biologists discovered why muscle cells in the heart aren't produced after birth. They identified genes that, if manipulated correctly, might make new cells form. And they laid the groundwork for a future therapy by introducing these genes into the hearts of animals.<p>Nadal-Ginard's work brought him accolades from every quarter. He snagged research grants from the American Heart Association and the National Institutes of Health; he won prizes from the International Society for Heart Research and the American Cancer Society. He became director of a renowned M.D./Ph.D. program run by Harvard and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and he became chair of the senior appointments committee at Children's Hospital.<p>The child of Spanish peasants had become as bright a star as any in the Harvard firmament. "I could do no wrong," he recalls. "I was walking on water."<p>Yet he also felt he was not getting his due.<p>Doctors earn widely differing sums of money, and they earn it in a wide variety of ways. Some surgeons, for example, may receive huge fees directly for their services; a top surgeon can rake in more than $1 million a year. At the elite teaching hospitals affiliated with Harvard, however, salary guidelines peg doctors' earnings at more modest levels. In 1986, for example, Harvard decreed that a full professora category that includes many of Boston's finest doctorsshould earn a salary of no more than $246,888. Nadal-Ginard easily fell within the prescribed range: Despite all the kudos, his official paycheck that year was $123,000.<p>Such guidelines may give the impression that teaching hospitals keep strict control over the earnings of their doctors. But this is a fiction. Until September 1994, Harvard did not require doctors to reveal their full income. And for those doing cutting-edge research, it was especially easy to undermine the spirit of the guidelines. In addition to their salaries, researchers can earn money through consulting fees, speaking fees, book royalties, and patent royalties and by forming biotechnology companies to commercialize their advances. In the last decade, venture capitalists have staked billions of dollars on research in molecular biology.<p>This flood of cash has created an environment in which talented scientists like Nadal-Ginard often expect to get rich. "Money has emerged in larger sums than we ever imagined was possible," says Donald Fredrickson, a former director of the National Institutes of Health. "It makes the system closer to the devil than it was in the pristine days."<p>Besides the temptations of commerce, Nadal-Ginard could also watch his colleagues making millions from deferred-compensation packages, another popular way to sidestep salary guidelines. To understand the income boost possible under such a deal, consider the case of Hardy Hendren, a top Children's surgeon who received an official salary of $344,418 in 1993, the latest year for which records are available. Hendren's paycheck fit within Harvard's guidelines, which specified a top salary of $355,422 in 1993. But Hendron received a bonus of $2.44 million that year by cashing out of a ten-year-old delayed-benefit plan.<p>Compared with peers like Hendren, Nadal-Ginard was in a frustrating position. In 1986, he had received a much-coveted award from the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, a huge philanthropy in Maryland. The institute hands out grants to ensure that top scientists like Nadal-Ginard have the financial freedom to pursue their work. The HHMI agreed to sponsor some of his research and pay his salary, which would rise to $237,235 in 1993, when his grant was to come up for renewal.<p>But the institute also sent Nadal-Ginard a letter explaining that, with the exception of a limited amount of consulting, he "should not receive any other compensation" from his "university, clinics, or hospitals." Ironically, the prestigious appointment threatened to deprive Nadal-Ginard of the wealth that any other star doctor could attain by skirting Harvard's salary guidelines.<p>In Nadal-Ginard's mind, money may have been a way of keeping scoreof proving how far he had come since his days of penury in Majorca. Certainly he felt entitled to more money than he was getting from the HHMI. And he was in a position to address the problem, for in 1983 he had set up a not-for-profit foundation known as a physician practice group.<p>Physician practice groups give doctors independence from the hospitals where they work. Technically, the doctors are employed by their foundation, not the hospital. This arrangement allows doctors to make their own decisions on matters such as hiring personnel and arranging benefit plans. The IRS estimates there are well over 200 such groups scattered across the U.S., associated mostly with top teaching hospitals. Hundreds of millions of dollarsperhaps billionssluice through them each year with minimal oversight.<p>Nadal-Ginard's physician practice group, the Boston Children's Heart Foundation, was typical of the breed. It had tax-exempt status because its membersall of whom belonged to his cardiology departmenttaught medicine and conducted research. Nadal-Ginard was the group's president and treasurer and one of its three directors. He controlled revenue of up to $8 million a year but received virtually no guidance from the foundation's directors or from his hospital.<p>In fact, as with many such groups, no one paid any attention at all. The IRS says that directors of tax-exempt groups must ensure that employees receive only "reasonable" compensation. But Michael Freed, one of Nadal-Ginard's fellow directors, has testified that he never read the group's by-laws, that he had no idea what any foundation member was paid, that he cannot remember a formal meeting of the board of directors, and that no senior official saw reports about the foundation's expenses.<p>This surprises no one who is familiar with tax-exempt physician practice groups. Lawyers and accountants say many foundations don't undergo scrutiny by outside auditors and that directors often fail to monitor their groups' financial dealings. It's the hallmark of an industry that has suddenly become big businessbut thinks it can keep operating under medicine's old collegial rules.<p>It was easy, then, for Nadal-Ginard to award himself a supplementary income to reflect what he felt was his due. He gradually increased the sum until, in 1992, the nonprofit foundation paid him a salary of $229,194not bad, given that he provided no patient care, the source of the foundation's revenue. That year, the foundation also paid him more than $500,000 in various benefits. Nadal-Ginard claims these arrangements were approved by various people, including David Weiner, the president of Children's Hospital. But a U.S. district court judge has ruled otherwise, calling the deals improper.<p>Although Nadal-Ginard may have felt he deserved the extra money, he also needed it to fund an increasingly glamorous lifestyle. In 1985, he and his wife began to collect art, focusing on conceptual artists who presented complex ideas in simple but striking ways. He approached his new obsession with the same intensity he brought to science. "He has a mind that's phenomenally investigative," says Barbara Krakow, a gallery owner and friend. "He began to understand very deeply what each artist was doing."<p>Indeed, art consumed almost all of Nadal-Ginard's spare time. He became a fixture at exhibitions and auctions from New York to Zurich, Paris to Madrid, Basel to Venice. He joined the board of the Institute of Contemporary Art in Boston. He befriended artists, gallery owners, and eminent museum curators such as Kathy Halbreich, director of the Walker Art Center in Minneapolis. His daughters worried that the hobby had become another full-time job. Mireya Nadal-Vicens recalls, "We had conversations about how sad it was that he couldn't relax."<p>Nadal-Ginard says he and Mahdavi recognized many lesser-known artists who subsequently won broader acclaim, including Cindy Sherman, Matthew Barney, and Gabriel Orozco. They also bought works by more established artists such as Bruce Nauman, Kiki Smith, and Bryce Marden. The couple had such confidence in their artistic judgment that they took out a bank loan of $467,000 so they would have more to spend on art. Nadal-Ginard says he regarded this as a sound investment.<p>
Meanwhile, at Children's Hospital, things were turning sour. Despite his many successes, Nadal-Ginard seemed ill-suited to the administrative side of his job. He loathed bureaucracy and was incapable of hiding his contempt for incompetent colleagues. He tended to fight with anyone who would get in his wayespecially with superiors. "If I believe in something," Nadal-Ginard says, "I don't budge."<p>At times he acted like a despot. He had a furious argument with the hospital's chairman of pediatrics, David Nathan, who had objected to Nadal-Ginard's grabbing more lab space for his department's research. Afterward, Nathanthe hospital's physician-in-chief and a member of its board of trusteeswrote Nadal-Ginard: "You are a brilliant Chief in many ways.... But your tremendous determination to get what you want leads you to ride roughshod over perceived opponents and further, you have a one-way mind. You have great difficulty in seeing the needs of other colleagues."<p>Nadal-Ginard hated the fact that such distractions tore him away from the laboratory. "I thought I was squandering significant amounts of my intellectual resources," he says. A further source of distress may have been the state of his finances. Besides art, Nadal-Ginard and Mahdavi had been amassing property. They had bought a batch of condominiums as an investment in 1986 and still owed a hefty sum on the mortgages. They also had mortgages on their apartment on the Charles River and their Boston townhouse. Despite Nadal-Ginard's illicit income from the foundation, the couple would owe almost $2.7 million by 1993.<p>Nadal-Ginard started having bouts of depression throughout the late 1980s and early 1990s. "He slouched a lot," says daughter Mireya. "He was chronically tired." Because he had little faith in psychiatry, he sought no help. Instead, he escaped by thowing himself ever more manically into his twin obsessions, art and science. He often woke up at 5 a.m. to start working.<p>And despite everything, his research was going better than ever. In 1993, rumors circulated that Nadal-Ginard was a finalist for the Nobel Prize for medicine. He had discovered that one gene in the heart can produce many different proteins by a process called alternative splicinga revelation that changed assumptions about the way genes work. "The whole thing was falling into place," he says. "I was at the threshold of really getting the answers. For the first time in my life I was starting to feel satisfied."<p>But he couldn't live at this pace indefinitely. His insomnia got so bad that he sometimes went three or four days without sleeping. When he came home in the evenings, he would collapse. Mahdavi understood him better than anyone, but she began fighting with him over his self-destructive lifestyle. "When you're here," she would wail, "you're dead."<p>
The third director at the Boston Children's Heart Foundation was a cardiologist named James Lock. Nadal-Ginard had hired him back in 1984 to head the cardiac catheterization laboratory at Children's Hospital. Ambitious, headstrong, and willing to take risks, Lock soon earned a reputation as an innovative surgeon. One of his most notable achievements was to perform the first successful operation in which a cathetera tube threaded through veins and into the heartwas used to close an abnormal hole between the heart's upper chambers.<p>Under Lock, now 45, the catheterization lab expanded to a point where it handled more than 1,300 procedures a year. By 1989, the Stanford University graduate had risen to become the hospital's chief of clinical cardiologyhe was in charge of all patient-treatment programs. Lock has testified that he paid little attention to money matters for most of his tenure at the Boston Children's Heart Foundation. But it would be he who first suspected Nadal-Ginard of wrongdoing.<p>Nadal-Ginard admired Lock's skill as a surgeon but suspected him of craving power. For his part, Lock thought Nadal-Ginard neglected the needs of doctors who actually treated patients at Children's. Their conflict escalated in 1993, largely because Lock had to cut spending in the clinical program but couldn't get the financial data he needed from Nadal-Ginard.<p>That summer, Nadal-Ginard finally allowed Lock to peruse expense reports from both the cardiology department and the foundation. Scanning the documents for the first time, Lock noticed that his boss had issued himself a foundation credit card. "When I found out he was spending $70,000 or $60,000 or $80,000 a year on travel and entertainment," Lock later testified, "I became very concerned about my duties as a foundation director."<p>Lock challenged Nadal-Ginard but says he was told "it was none of my business." However, the younger man had just read about a scandal at the House of Morgan in the 1920s that led to a crackdown on the entire banking industry. "I told [Nadal-Ginard] I was worried that the medical profession was going to come under the same scrutiny," Lock has testified. "And when that scrutiny occurred, they were going to go after Harvard."<p>Shortly afterward, Robert Gold, the foundation's accountant, conducted a routine audit and found that several checks had gone astray. One was for $25,000 and had been made payable to Shearson Lehman Brothers, which handled some of the foundation's assets. Gold showed the canceled check to Martin Stocklan, a Shearson executive who had apparently endorsed it. According to foundation documents, Stocklan said the endorsement was a clumsy forgery: His name had even been misspelled. State Street Bank in Boston, which had cleared the check, then revealed that the missing money had been deposited in Nadal-Ginard's personal account. In the following weeks, four more improperly endorsed checks would be found .<p>These discoveries led to Nadal-Ginard's humiliating lockout at his office in Children's Hospital. They also caused the foundation to retain accountants Ernst & Young to dissect the doctor's other financial dealings. The ensuing investigation, as detailed in court documents, revealed an array of further irregularities. Most startling, perhaps, was the discovery that Nadal-Ginard had dramatically altered his own deferred-compensation plan as far back as 1988.<p>Nadal-Ginard's original plandrawn up in 1985allowed him annually to accrue a sum equal to 15 percent of his foundation salary. But three years later, Nadal-Ginard claimed that all copies of that document had been lost. He had an attorney draw up a replacement plan that increased his benefits enormouslywithout notifying his fellow directors. When Nadal-Ginard terminated the plan on December 31, 1992, he received a jackpot of more than $4 million.<p>Questions also arose over an escrow account Nadal-Ginard used to pay for his life insurance and income taxes. In 1992 and 1993, a judge has ruled, Nadal-Ginard improperly deposited nearly $750,000 of the foundation's money in this account. Another dubious deal involved a biotechnology company called Myogenics Inc., which Nadal-Ginard founded with a colleague in 1992. Myogenics attracted $7 million from venture-capital money, but Nadal-Ginard was found to have paid its first employee, Richard Odessy, with the foundation's money. Myogenics' president now calls Nadal-Ginard "untrustworthy."<p>In Nadal-Ginard's civil trial, the judge agreed with most of Ernst & Young's findings. Nadal-Ginard was ordered to return more than $6.5 million to the foundation; he had already paid back Odessy's $72,000 and $145,000 for the missing checks. Ironically, the judge found nothing wrong with Nadal-Ginard's credit card expenses, which had first convinced James Lock that something was amiss.<p>Nadal-Ginard's upcoming trial in the criminal division of Suffolk County Superior Court will focus on the same allegations. If the doctor loses this time, he faces up to five years in prison.<p>
Despite the array of damning evidence, Nadal-Ginard still claims he is "totally innocent of any misdoing." Perhaps the only people who believe him are his daughters and his wife. In a telephone interview, Vijak Mahdavi supports Nadal-Ginard's theory that his downfall was orchestrated by James Lock and David Nathan, the superior with whom he quarreled over lab space. "This is a political coup that was mounted," she says bitterly. "A lot of people were jealous. I always compare my husband to Mozart being kicked out of the royal court by Salieri."<p>The last year has had a crushing impact on Mahdavi. Before her husband's fall, she had her own research grants and seemed poised to become a full professor at Harvard Medical School. Now she claims Nadal-Ginard's enemies at Children's Hospital have dismantled her lab. A hospital spokeswoman denies this.<p>On his last day of testimony in the civil trial, Nadal-Ginard witnessed the full extent of Mahdavi's suffering. When he arrived at his lawyer's office that day in November 1994, he was handed a phone message from his wife's psychiatrist: Mahdavi hadn't shown for her appointment. Nadal-Ginard rushed home and found his wife lying unconscious on the living room floor. She had taken an overdose of Valium. Afraid she would fall into an irreversible coma, he slapped her so she would stay awake until the ambulance arrived. Mahdavi's stomach was pumped, and she has remained in a mental institution in Switzerland ever since. She is receiving treatment there for suicidal depression.<p>As he discusses his wife's breakdown, Nadal-Ginard's voice drops and he closes his bleary eyes. He walks across the room to find some documents, desperate not to let his misery show. Since being locked out of his office, Nadal-Ginard has been seeing psychiatrists himself. While visiting Mahdavi last December, his condition deteriorated and he too was briefly institutionalized.<p>It's little wonder Nadal-Ginard is depressed. In a matter of months in 1993, he was fired as chief of cardiology at Children's Hospital, president of the Boston Children's Heart Foundation, and an HHMI researcher. He lost his research grants and his income. He saw his life's achievements overshadowed by shame. One of the worst tortures, he says, was to watch helplessly as the research operation he had built up over a decade was dismembered. On one afternoon last year, James Lock met with several of Nadal-Ginard's protgs and told them the hospital could not afford to employ them.<p>Lately Nadal-Ginard has faced new humiliations. On January 6, he lost the right to travel abroad: The Massachusetts attorney general's office argued successfully that he should surrender his passport because he might flee the country. Four days later he received a notice informing him that all "right, title, and interest" in his Boston duplex and townhouse had been seized. The properties will be held as collateral for the millions he owes to his former foundation. And to prevent him from absconding with his art collection, he is tailed day and night by private investigators.<p>It's a sad fate for a man who, just two years ago, served as an inspiration to medical researchers around the world. Today, Nadal-Ginard appears in a tragically different lightas a genius who never believed his achievements were enough. In a way, perhaps, his own heart was bruised forever by the slights he endured as an ambitious child in Spain.<p>And despite Nadal-Ginard's best efforts, a damaged heart can't yet be healed.  <p><p>

