		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Battle Over Broadway</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Battle Over Broadway</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Feature  <p> BATTLE OVER BROADWAY <p>Tense drama will play out around a bargaining table this summer as upstart producers try to remake theater without dimming the lights  <p> By Paul Alexander  <p> From the windows of his corner office on the 19th floor of 1501 Broadway, John Hart can look down and see, amid Times Square's chaos and boarded-up stores and porno houses, the theaters he fills for a living. Urbane and at times savagely witty, Hart--the model of a take-charge producer--works the phone, looking for investors. He has joined with a team of fellow producers known as the Dodgers to bring another musical to Broadway and fill one of the theaters far below.  <p> Hart, whose gray hair and beard belie his age, 42, has a good story to tell prospective investors. His previous two efforts with the Dodgers were Guys and Dolls, the longest-running revival in Broadway history, and Tommy, a highly successful adaptation of the Who's classic rock opera.   <p> Hart and the Dodgers are producing what seems to be another sure thing: a high-tech revival of How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying. The satire by Frank Loesser and Abe Burrows, winner of both the Pulitzer Prize and the Tony for Best Musical, made a star of Robert Morse in1961.  <p> So far, How to Succeed looks like it has a good chance of turning a profit--unlike most Broadway shows these days. With a $5.2 million start-up budget, it's inexpensive by Broadway standards.What's more, it got rave reviews during tryouts late last year at the La Jolla Playhouse near San Diego, and it will feature Matthew Broderick, the Hollywood star and Tony Awardwinning veteran of Neil Simon comedies. Sure enough, the sales job has been easy for Hart. On this winter day, he's almost finished raising his half of the $5.2 million.  <p> "I talked to your wife on the phone last week," Hart tells a potential investor. Dressed in chinos and an oxford shirt, he sits at an antique wooden desk, his Tony for Guys and Dolls ona shelf behind him. "She was very interested. I'm telling you, you can't lose. So why don't you just go out in the backyard, dig up some of that money I know you have buried there, and get in while you can. You'll thank me."  <p> Maybe. But privately, Hart admits that investing in theater has become more and more risky. Guys and Dolls recouped its capitalization in a respectable 48 weeks from its debut in April 1992. Tommy,which opened in April 1993, took 78 weeks. Both shows will make a profit. Still, because of Broadway's rising costs, many productions now lose money--and even successful shows can take forever to turn a profit. That's why Hart and the Dodgers, along with a small clique of other producers, are working to ensure that How to Succeed will be among the last shows produced under the stifling restrictions of this $650 million industry.  <p> To do so, the producers may force a showdown this summer with theater owners and the entertainment unions that could result in a strike when a key contract expires on July 31. Even a shortwork stoppage--there hasn't been one since 1973--could hurt many shows, including How to Succeed. "We don't have any choice," Hart says, "if we're going to continue to produce Broadway shows." <p>  <p>Michael David sits at the desk in a small corner office that is, quite literally, crammed with furniture, mementos from his plays, personal effects, and a vast array of kitsch that includes an antique harp, a dime store display of Brooklyn Dodgers chewing gum, plastic miniatures of the Seven Dwarfs lined up on one window ledge, and a huge yellow sign that reads tommy. A pleasantly manic man who was once described by The Wall Street Journal as the "guru" of the Dodgers--no doubt because he affects a bohemian image with his blue jeans, ponytail, and beard--David, 51, is returning a few phone calls before his next meeting. On each call he speaks in a rapid, clipped cadence, as if he can hardly wait to say what's on his mind.  <p> Before long, David is joined in his office by Ed Strong, 46, a fellow Dodger whose understated style and reserved demeanor are in opposition to David's animated ways. Strong has come in with John Haber, the director of King Mackerel and the Blues Are Running, a modest off-Broadway musical revue the Dodgers are producing this spring. The two men sit on a small sofa. Soon David gets off the phone and focuses on the reason for this meeting: Haber's budget for his show.  <p> David and Strong study copies of the document.  <p> "What about these headphones?" Strong asks, pointing to a line item that might cost $1,500.  <p> "I noticed that, too," David says.  <p> Haber explains why he wants the headphones--to communicate with technicians during the show--but he soon seems ready to scrap the expense. David and Strong move on, but the exchange is telling. The Dodgers are putting only $20,000 into this revue, a paltry sum compared to the millions they'll spend on How to Succeed. Yet both David and Strong question every expense. They do this because they have to. Today theatrical producers must be maniacal in their determination to hold the bottom line. The Dodgers' ability to do that--relentlessly--is the reason they're the only American producers who can boast of having less than eight months of dark nights on Broadway during the past 12 years, an accomplishment that puts them in a league with Andrew Lloyd Webber, the composer-producer of Cats, The Phantom of the Opera, and Sunset Boulevard.  <p> Though they have produced some of Broadway's biggest recent hits, the Dodgers go out of their way to deflect publicity from themselves and toward their shows. In fact, they routinely avoid giving interviews, so the early history of the group has been unusually sketchy. "The Dodgers is an amalgam of six guys who met 15 to 18 years ago and have been together ever since," says David--who, along with Strong and Sherman Warner, constitutes a core corporation within the larger Dodger partnership. From offices high above Times Square, now remodeled to link with those of Kardana Productions, Hart's company, the three men manage the daily operations of all Dodger shows.  <p> The other three Dodgers work on particular projects for the group, but they also have careers of their own. Des McAnuff, the former director of La Jolla Playhouse, is a Tony Awardwinning director. Rocco Landesman heads Jujamcyn Theaters, which owns five Broadway houses. Doug Johnson is an illustrator; he often designs the Dodgers' graphically bold posters. The group's name "came out of the birthplace of our organization--Brooklyn," says Warner, who is 50. Studious, almost reticent, Warner oversees the number-crunching end of the Dodger operation. "Dodger' was sort of a generic name for people from Brooklyn," he says. "Short for trolley dodgers. But it also conjures up Dickens's Artful Dodger." There's also the obvious reference to the legendary Brooklyn Dodgers baseball team.  <p> In 1981, after working in not-for-profit theater for some years, the Dodgers got their break when they raised money to move Pump Boys and Dinettes to Broadway from a small theater where it was playing off-off-Broadway. It was a brilliant decision. The show ran for 21 months, spawned a national touring company, and ended up making its investors $1.75 on the dollar.  <p> The Dodgers followed this success in 1985 with Big River, the Roger Miller musical based on Mark Twain's Huckleberry Finn and directed by McAnuff. The show won seven Tony Awards, ran two years on Broadway, and toured nationally. Curiously, it didn't make much profit for its investors--although as managers of the show, the Dodgers did well. Over the next several years Dodger Productions went on to manage or stage Into the Woods, a Stephen Sondheim musical; The Secret Garden, Lucy Simon and Marsha Norman's children's musical; Prelude to a Kiss, Craig Lucas's romantic comedy; and Jelly's Last Jam, for which the Dodgers served as executive producers. All enjoyed long runs, but none was a financial blockbuster. "We're most proud of making things into hits that have been declared in lots of places not hits," says David. "That applies to Big River, The Secret Garden, and Into the Woods, all of which The New York Times critic dismissed, and all of which ran for two years or more."  <p> The one production the Dodgers couldn't save was The Gospelat Colonus, a weird concept of a show that set the tragedy of Oedipus to black gospel music. It opened in 1988 and closed after just 12 weeks of previews and performances, losing its entire $1.4 million capitalization budget. "It almost closed us forever," says David about the show, which Warner fondly describes as "tremendously creative" but not right for Broadway. Despite the disaster, the Dodgers learned this from Gospel: In the future, they would gamble only on popular works that didn't need help from the critics. <p> For the Dodgers, the early 1990s have been a vindication of this philosophy. With Hart they produced Guys and Dolls and Tommy; How to Succeed, which opens at the end of this month, is next. The Dodgers are managing <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney's</b></a> Beauty and the Beast; with Madison Square Garden they produced Alan Menken's musical adaptation of A Christmas Carol, which will run each Christmas season at the Paramount Theater for years to come. The Dodgers are also bringing Hamlet to Broadway for a limited run this spring. The play will star Ralph Fiennes, now a bankable name as a result of his Academy Award nomination last year for Schindler's List. <p> Still, even for a team as successful as the Dodgers, a question now looms. When will rising costs make any Broadway show, no matter how cannily it's constructed, economically unviable? <p>  <p>It seemed calculated to incite reaction--calculated even for Frank Rich, a man who angered so many people during his 11-years tint as chief theater critic for The New York Times. In a Times op-ed column titled "Panic on Broadway," Rich called the December 4 closing of Angels in America, the only new American drama then running on Broadway, "the most resounding final curtain in the history of the Broadway theater." Then he went on to declare, in his usual no-holds-barred style, that Broadway hovered at "the edge of doom."  <p> Indeed, the fall of 1994 was not a good season. In October, Neil Simon, so associated with Broadway he has a theater named for him, caused a stir by announcing he would stage his next play off Broadway, citing Broadway's limiting economic structure. Besides Lloyd Webber's Sunset Boulevard, which earned $38 million in advance sales but tepid reviews, few shows opened. Most notable was Show Boat, a revival of the classic 1927 musical produced by Garth Drabinsky, a Canadian entrepreneur. In fact, so few new productions opened that, in moves that elicited both laughter and ridicule from Broadway circles, the Tony Award committee hinted publicly that it might have to start recognizing off-Broadway shows just to fill its categories. That behavior angered Pulitzer Prizewinning playwright Edward Albee, who charged that the committee's we-don't-have-anything-else attitude was insulting to theater people who worked off-Broadway, himself included.  <p> Where had all the new shows gone? The problem was simple enough.With ticket prices so high--$70 orchestra seats are common--audiences now expect to be dazzled by nothing less than an enormous falling chandelier or a helicopter rising from the stage. No quiet dramas or romantic comedies for today's audiences; they can watch those at home on television for free. And why are ticket prices so high? The $70 tag is vital if producers are to have any hope of offsetting, using their limited number of seats, both a show's start-up costs and the weekly "nut" needed to run it. Capitalization costs for musicals now vary from the $3 million to $6 million range (Guys and Dolls, Damn Yankees) all the way to the $13 million to $14 million range (Sunset Boulevard, Show Boat). Even a simple one-set drama requires more than $1 million in start-up money. Weekly nuts can also be staggering, varying anywhere from $350,000 (Guys and Dolls) to $600,000 (Show Boat). Regular expenses include rent, all labor costs including actors' wages, a producer's fee, and a royalty pool for the creative team.  <p> It is the money a show earns each week over its nut that producers use to repay gradually the investors who put up capitalization money. Once the investors have been made whole, the show goes into profit, which is divided between the producers and investors. Unfortunately, as rents and labor costs drive up weekly nuts, only megamusicals such as Cats and Les Miserables can consistently rack up sales higher than their nut--meaning that many Broadway shows never recoup their initial investment. In 1989, for example, investors put up $8.7 million to finance Jerome Robbins' Broadway, a compilation of musical numbers from Robbins's previous shows. The Shubert Organization, as both the show's producer and a major investor, provided the theater at reasonable rates. The show's weekly nut was about $425,000; at capacity, it would generate about $550,000 in sales. With excellent reviews and a Tony Award for Best Musical, the show did sell out business--but only for a time. Then business fell off until it only barely covered the nut.  <p> Jerome Robbins' Broadway ran for 86 weeks, far longer than any of the original works from which its songs came, classic productions such as Peter Pan, West Side Story, and Gypsy. Even so, the show returned only 55 percent of its capitalization, making it a financial flop. A flop, that is, for investors. The Shuberts did better. While they lost about $1 million on their initial investment, they took in more than $2 million in rent alone. Such economics likely helped the organization decide to stop producing shows and concentrate on making money as Broadway's landlord.  <p>  <p>Anyone who raises enough money can produce a Broadway show; producers need deal only with their investors and a theater's owner. Some producers open a show or two, get burned, and flee. Even those who end up with a hit may leave, usually after they learn just how perverse the business is. Because of these short half-lives, producers traditionally have had little clout on Broadway. Instead, the vital functions of this industry--including labor negotiations--have been controlled for years by the theater owners, who stay in place as producers come and go.  <p> These days, the main theater owners are the Shubert Organization, Nederlander Theaters, and Rocco Landesman's Jujamcyn Theaters. Of the three, the Shuberts are the most powerful by far--not just because they own the most houses, 16 plus one co-owned theater from a total of 28, but because they rent to some of Broadway's biggest cash cows: Cats, The Phantom of the Opera, Les Miserables, and Miss Saigon, to name four. Shows such as these provide a rich and predictable cash flow, a rarity on Broadway. So from their offices atop the Shubert Theater on 44th Street, Bernard B. Jacobs, 78, and Gerald Schoenfeld, 69, have run much more than just the Shubert Organization. Crusty and old-worldly, these two men have run the very business of Broadway. Over time, they have also found themselves at odds with the industry's younger producers.  <p> John Hart sees the conflict as partially generational. "The Dodgers and I are younger," he says. "We've been saying for years that costs have been getting out of control, and the Shuberts did everything they could to silence us. We ran our shows and they ran the [labor] negotiations. The Shuberts would dismiss me in meetings. It's intimidating when the largest theater owner tells you to sit down."  <p> The unions are the third key player on Broadway. For years, theater owners have given in to their demands, since extra costs could be passed right along to the producers. The owners, led in negotiations by the Shuberts, cared mostly about keeping the labor unions on the job: After all, a strike would stop the steady flow of rent. As a result, labor costs have ballooned ever since the late 1970s, when generous cost-of-living provisions combined with rampant inflation.  <p> But the balance of power on Broadway is shifting. Today, because they control all but a handful of shows, established producers such as the Dodgers, Cameron Mackintosh (Miss Saigon, Les Miserables), and Lloyd Webber's Really Useful Co. have as much clout as--maybe even more than--the theater owners. After a decade of success, these few producers now have the cash and the determination to fight for a bigger say in Broadway's future.  <p> "The Shuberts have always held the upper hand," says Frank Richfrom his office at The New York Times. "But now there's not so much product, and the Shuberts have gotten out of the producing business. So who holds most of the cards? The producers producing the big, money-churning musicals have more power than they have had in decades. Now the theater owners depend on them. Finally the producers can take over the various labor negotiations." <p> When it happens, the showdown will center on some of the most curious and expensive work rules in any major American business. Some are profoundly lacking in logic. For example, under union rules, producers must hire a set number of musicians for a musical, no matter how many they actually need. For Tommy, the Dodgers had to hire 24 musicians, though they needed just 16. For months, eight people showed up each week just to collect their paychecks. During lengthy negotiations, the Dodgers tried to convince the union to drop the requirement. The union finally agreed that as musicians quit, they wouldn't be replaced--but just for Tommy. Legendary producer David Merrick (42nd Street, Gypsy, Hello Dolly!) had a different approach: He would force all unused musicians to show up for each performance and play their instruments in the rest room.  <p> Other rules are arcane or outdated. A show must have a curtainman, for instance, even if the theater doesn't have a curtain. Many shows must keep a carpenter on hand for most rehearsals, though there's rarely work to be done. The salaries of theater workers are not insignificant, either. Stagehands, to name one group, make a minimum of $804 a week, plus another 58 percent in pension and other benefits. Factoring in holidays and overtime, a busy stagehand can make $100,000 or more a year--and work only a few hours a night.  <p> Bizarre work rules may infuriate producers, but the Shubert Organization doesn't seem too upset by current Broadway economics."The gloom and doom is overstated," says Lee Silver, a spokesman for the company. "This talk has gone on for generations. It started before World War II." Indeed, Silver, an older man who often speaks with a sharp, dismissive tone, has a quick answer for almost all the issues now affecting Broadway theater.  <p> On theater owners' role in the skyrocketing costs of Broadway shows: "All of this is not an accurate assessment of the theater as it has evolved over the years." On why the audience for Broadway has stagnated: "We don't get much coverage [on TV]." On why there are so few emerging playwrights: "A writer of a stage play decide she doesn't want to be bludgeoned by the critics. Many playwrights have gone to Hollywood and television to write drama." On Neil Simon's decision to take his next play off Broadway for economic reasons: "Neil Simon is not a good example of anything. [But] since he's such an icon of Broadway, it becomes a horror story." On Frank Rich's criticism of theater owners: "People believe that what appears in the Times is cut in granite. It's not." <p> Bill Moriarity, president of Local 802, the musicians' union, believes that the current salaries are justified for workers in a business as unpredictable as Broadway. Like Silver, he believes Rich's doom saying is disturbing and biased. "It was driven by a small number of producers," he says. "Those named in the column: Cameron Mackintosh, the Dodgers. They are younger people with a different type of background with unions." This is true, of course, which is why a strike may result when the current contract with Local 1, the stagehands' union, expires this summer. Producers are determined to lower the cost of their shows by tackling their biggest expense, labor, even if it means a work stoppage. "That's what has to happen," says Michael Riedel, theater critic for the New York Daily News, "or Broadway is going to stay what it is--an airport hangar for big musicals by Andrew Lloyd Webber." <p>  <p>Back at 1501 Broadway, it's another day and another blur of telephone calls for John Hart. He's currently producing his second film, Drunks, which will star Faye Dunaway. He's planning a week long sailing trip with Pete Townshend, the author of Tommy, with whom Hart has become close friends. And How to Succeed is making steady progress. It starts a run at the Kennedy Center in Washington,D.C., in February before moving to Broadway in March.  <p> Business hasn't always been so good for Hart, whose first Broadway production was Eubie, a 1978 revue based around ragtime pianist Eubie Blake, whom Hart had met at Dartmouth College when Blake came to accept an honorary doctorate. Hart followed Eubie with Onward Victoria, a show based on the life of Victoria Woodhull, who in 1872 became the first woman to run for U.S. president. It got such devastating reviews that it closed the night it opened, losing its entire $1.4 million startup budget. Modest success ensued--How I Got That Story, Smart Aleck, The Common Pursuit, The Leader of the Pack--until Hart had a chat in the fall of1991 with Dodger Ed Strong.  <p> The Dodgers had secured the rights to Guys and Dolls from the estates of Loesser and Burrows, but they wanted help raising the more than $5 million it would take to put the show on. "Can you raise money?" Strong asked Hart. Indeed he could--a little over $2 million from 50 different investors. When Guys and Dolls opened in 1992, it was an immediate sensation, and another project for Hart and the Dodgers became inevitable. That was Tommy. Now established as a team, Hart and the Dodgers are hoping for their biggest hit yet with How to Succeed.  <p> A key element in the new show will be Matthew Broderick, who can make How to Succeed into the star vehicle Guys and Dolls and Tommy were never conceived to be. Hart was instrumental in getting Broderick to commit. The actor became seriously interested in the project after he and Hart began to socialize together, often playing squash in New York City at the Yale Club, where Hart is a member.  <p> On an afternoon in early December, Broderick explains his involvement in the show over a late lunch at a La Jolla restaurant high upon a cliff overlooking the Pacific Ocean. At 32, Broderick no longer has about him the fresh innocence that defined him when he broke onto the scene years ago. Still, for someone so young he's had a prolific career, appearing on Broadway in Neil Simon's Brighton Beach Memoirs (for which he won a Tony) and Biloxi Blues and in motion pictures such as Ferris Bueller's Day Off, The Freshman, and Glory.  <p> At first, Broderick says, he was uneasy about doing How to Succeed, despite his friendship with Hart. He felt the play's lead character was too closely associated with Robert Morse. What persuaded him to do the show was the addition to the project of Dodger Des McAnuff, the winner of Tony Awards for directing Big River and Tommy. With McAnuff attached, the project promised to be innovative, for McAnuff has dedicated himself to revitalizing the theater by using new technology and cinematic techniques. <p> Even with McAnuff signed on, however, there was the problem of the script for How to Succeed, a piece rooted in the corporate world of the early 1960s. "Some people thought of the play as sexist because it's about women being secretaries and men being businessmen," Broderick says as he eats his meal. "But it's a satire. In the play, the women actually run the company." To prepare for playing J. Pierpont Finch, the ultimate corporate man, Broderick drew on his experiences with Hart at the Yale Club. "I could see all those old men with their towels and their wooden lockers with no locks, and all of their hair tonics, and their really good shower heads. It's the way WASPs live, you know."  <p> To modernize the show without destroying its lyrics, McAnuff uses a never-ending flow of characters on stage, countless backdrops that come and go, and a mammoth video wall that flashes an endless assortment of images, giving the production a high-tech, corporate feel. A few hours after lunch, when Broderick takes the stage in one of the show's last California tryouts, he brings Finch to life, reinventing the character who climbs the ladder at WorldwideWicket Co. with enviable ease. Near the end of the play, Broderick's Finch sings--to himself--"I Believe in You," the show's signature song, following it up with a breath takingly spirited version of "Brotherhood of Man," performed with the men of the cast and the astonishing Lillias White as Miss Jones.  <p> In this moment, How to Succeed achieves Broadway's loftiest goal: It moves its audience in a profound and memorable way. <p>  <p>On a wintry day in January, a passerby walking down 42nd Street in New York can look into the New Amsterdam Theater, a dilapidated building that was once the home of the Ziegfeld Follies, and see workmen and engineers planning the renovation of the historic theater. This is one of several developments that will help upgrade Times Square, too long a seedy, even dangerous section of the city. In 1993, David Letterman moved his television show to the Ed Sullivan Theater, prompting a major renovation of the Broadway landmark. <a name="AMEX:VIA"></a><b>Viacom's</b> MTV plans to convert another theater for concerts and special events. And there are rumors that a massive redevelopment project may finally start soon. Yet amid all this activity, the event that has drawn the most interest among theater insiders is the arrival on Broadway of the Walt Disney Company.  <p> After flirting with theater by opening Beauty and the Beast at the Palace last year--the show consistently plays to standing-room-onlyaudiences--Disney made a more substantial commitment by agreeing to sign a long-term lease for the New Amsterdam, which it will renovate with loans from the city and the state. The powerful media conglomerate will be watched closely. Some believe Disney productions will project a theme-park mentality on Broadway. But others are thrilled to see any major new presence here. "Disney brings in an audience that is different from the traditional Broadway audience," says Dodger Sherman Warner. "And they're serious about this. They're not carpetbaggers. They're going to make an investment in the community and stay."  <p> A few blocks away, Michael David walks hurriedly through Times Square. He's headed for the Richard Rodgers, where How to Succeed first opened in 1961 and will open again in only a few weeks. "You know," he says, "we--the Dodgers--have a continuity on Broadway now. As do Lloyd Webber and Mackintosh. We've all been around enough to learn from our mistakes. We know the business can't continue like this."  <p> He goes on in a subdued manner. "We're talking with the unions to try to resolve the situation," he says, "but if we can't resolve the situation, then we'll just have to endure a walkout." From his resigned tone, it's clear what he expects to happen.  <p> Before long, David is inside the theater, standing on the stage where yet another of his productions will soon be playing. As he lingers there, he is dwarfed by the vast expanse of stage. He looks out into the auditorium, row upon row of plush red seats, all of them empty. In a few months, this tableau may be heartbreaking. But today, while there's still hope, it inspires.  <p> "What a beautiful sight," David whispers. "A beautiful sight." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

