	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-"Anyone Can Be a Broker"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-"Anyone Can Be a Broker"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Dan Montano said he was rewriting the rules of Wall Street. Instead he became the central character in a rare financial drama, one in which the brokers are the victims.    <p> By Jesse Kornbluth  <p> On a pleasant morning a few weeks before Orange County discovered it had lost $2 billion investing in derivatives, Dan Montano drove his 1989 Lincoln Continental down from his home in the California hills to an office near Disneyland. His wife was by his side and he was feeling grandiose. It didn't matter that he wore suits with J.C. Penney labels or that Taco Bell was his favorite restaurant. What mattered was that he was founder and chief executive of a rapidly expanding brokerage firm that bore his name: Montano Securities. And in just two years, it had grown from a whistle-stop with seven brokers to a burgeoning operation with 10 offices employing 250 full-time and 650 part-time brokers. Before the end of 1995, he believed, Montano Securities would double or triple in size and go public. He would be acclaimed as the next <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab.</b></a>  <p> Montano's strategy for growth was poster-simple. In 25 cities, he ran newspaper ads and radio commercials aimed at retired white-collar professionals, women whose children had left the nest, immigrant cab drivers and shopkeepers. "You can be a stockbroker," the promotions declared. They offered a free seminar for further explanation. During these sessions, regularly held in overlit hotel meeting rooms, Montano would launch into a sales pitch that usually struck a chord with his audience. It went something like this:  <p> The brokerage system in the U.S. is rigged. A sham. Why? Because no one can take the Series 7 examination to become a broker without first having a job offer from an established firm. For people like you and me, it's a catch-22, a rule designed to keep us from selling stocks. The big firms don't want us. They only want to hire young white males to sell stocks to other white males. <p> Montano Securities can help. We offer jobs, training, and away to take the Series 7 exam. Join Montano, and see why the securities business can be the greatest business in the world. <p> The crowds listened to Dan Montano's story and concluded that he talked their language. They read his self-published 1992 paperback, The 21st Century Stockbroker. Then they signed up for his ten-session, $495 evening course and joined his flock.  <p>
On that october morning, Montano had planned to preach his populist vision to a magazine writer. He wanted to explain how he had enrolled 5,300 people in his course. And he wanted to add that this was just the beginning--the start of a revolution that would one day make Wall Street truly accessible to the full spectrum of the American middle class. Never mind that his firm provided its brokers with no actual training in selling, no lists of client leads, and little in the way of research. Montano Securities had already become the 30th biggest securities firm in the nation. <p> The evangelizing, however, would have to wait. Montano had some unexpected visitors. Stone-faced representatives of the National Association of Securities Dealers had dropped in for an unannounced, closed-door grilling. The regulators had no interest in Montano's visions or ideals. Their concern was the bottom line. Having noticed that a company with the unlikely name of California Quartz had just announced an investment of up to $4 million in Montano's enterprise, they wanted to know how badly he had been strapped for cash. Had his company been--not to put too fine a point on it--illiquid?  <p> The regulators left without taking action against Montano or Montano Securities. But all was not well at the company--far from it. On the very day the NASD came to visit, a conflagration was already brewing among Montano, California Quartz, and a number of familiar characters from the darker side of the brokerage industry--in particular, Pat Rooney, the former head of Rooney, Pace, a firm that itself was the subject of a two-year investigation by the NASD in the late 1980s.  <p> The prize in this battle: Montano Securities and its newly assembled sales force--a group of middle-class people with honest ambitions, clean records, and no previous connection to the shady world of bucket shops. A fusillade of puzzling financial statements and corporate shell games ensued. It lasted into the week before Christmas, when the commission checks of Montano brokers bounced and Dan Montano was finally ousted.  <p>
In the months before its founder lost control, the most remarkablething about Montano Securities--at least to an outsider--was the company's network of brokers. I talked with a number of them before the firm disappeared from beneath them--all smart, decent types. Like Jerry Markowski, one of Montano's part-time brokers,who is more like the lead in a Frank Capra film than a character from the movie Wall Street.  <p> Markowski, an immigrant from Poland, arrived in Chicago in 1981 as a 19-year-old with only a dollar in his pocket. Three years later, he had mastered English and was building electronic equipment as an employee of <a name="NYSE:ITT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10773"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ITT Corp.</b></a> But Markowski dreamed of making a fortune, and for that he had to break with tradition. "In Chicago, Polish people invest in single-family houses--it's the only way they know to make money," he said. "I bought stocks. After I made enough money in <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a> for a 25 percent down payment on a $150,000 town house, I started telling people what stocks I liked. I called a few places about becoming a broker, but when they heard my accent, they weren't interested."  <p> Markowski, now 32, married, and a father, heard Montano's radio commercial while he was driving to work and promptly enrolled at his school. Soon he was wearing a pager and carrying a cellular phone at ITT, then driving to the Montano office to service his clients and prepare a daily market report--in Polish--for a community newspaper. "There are 800,000 Polish-speaking people in Chicago and only two other Polish-speaking investment counselors I'm aware of," he told me in a ringing affirmation of his Montano affiliation.  <p> Other Montano brokers fitted the same mold: self-starters who wanted little more than a chance to succeed. Dick Schwaucker of St. Louis wore his TWA copilot wings in Montano's Chicago office when he checked prices and conferred with clients during layovers. In Washington, D.C., Jimmy Bian met with owners of Indian restaurants and groceries in the hope of redirecting the flow of investments of the Indian community to accounts at Montano. From a small desk in the Orange County office, 33-year-old Brian Chin made investment-banking connections in Korea. And Doc Norden, who would be designing particle-beam weapons at Grumman today if only the Cold War hadn't ended, called fellow members of the American Physical Society from his desk at Montano's New York office to announce, "I've switched to Wall Street."  <p> In their ignorance of the ways of the Street, many of the Montano brokers came up with good ideas about how to sell securities. "I won't let a customer invest with me until I've spent an hour in the same room with him," New York's Cy Yaranelli told me."That's a slow process--it will take me two to four years to make what I used to earn in the printing business--but I know my customers. And I smile more." There were other reasons for Yaranelli's happiness than good customer relationships. At Montano, most managers discouraged cold calling. Nor were brokers required to push stocks from the firm's inventory.  <p> "So how do they get clients?" a former <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> broker asked after being told about Montano's operating methods. "Look, when you start at Merrill, they give you a sheet each morning with numbers from one to 100. You start calling, and you keep moving. You sell funds that are brokers' dreams--no up-front costs, only costs at the end the customers don't think about.You're told to push things, and you get bonus points if you sell them on certain nights. That's the Merrill system, and it's the best on the Street."  <p> The Montano crew believed this traditionally effective system was on the verge of extinction. "Cold calling is dead," said Joan Coullahan, who signed on in Washington, D.C., so that she could work and still put her child on the school bus and take her off everyday. "Within five years, if you call people and their phone isn't programmed to accept your number, the technology will ring it busy and switch you to an answering machine. But we go to the mountain. We sit with people we know, look them in the eye, and say, I need to tell you about an infallible financial-planning concept: wealth over time.' "  <p> By and large, these recruits were extraordinarily loyal. "If the ship goes down, you'll see bubbles out of my mouth," said Chicago branch manager Nick Tscouris. Montano Securities counted on such fierce loyalty to keep it out of trouble. Montano knew that the firm would be on the hook if a broker got into legal hot water by selling an inappropriate product to a client or churning an account, but the company's systems for preventing violations of securities law were primitive by the standards of big firms on Wall Street. "Every trade funnels to this office," said Montano's son, Alex, who served as chief of compliance at the firm. "We can't stop a broker from doing something wrong, but we can catch it."  <p> "We've had to unwind a few trades, but we've had no formal customer complaints in 15 years," Dan Montano exulted back in October. <p>
Dan Montano isn't always the most credible source, either about himself or about his company. More than once, he has shown a willingness to resort to deception as a means to an end. Even his own children recount a story of how he once packed them into a car as youngsters and began driving toward Tijuana. He told them he was angry at them for not appreciating him more and that once they arrived in Mexico, he was going to trade them for children who would show more gratitude. The kids panicked and begged for another chance. His point made, Montano turned the car around. And soon they were waking up before dawn to wave goodbye as Dad drove off to work, and lining up at the door to greet him when he returned.  <p> Even Montano's outward appearance is misleading. Meeting him, you would never guess that Montano spent much of his childhood rumbling on the streets of East Los Angeles. Behind his glasses, he has the mildly pneumatic appearance of a 46-year-old man whose idea of exercise is to carry his briefcase to his car. With his short wavy hair swept straight back, he hardly looks the part of a slick, aggressive salesman.  <p> But Montano recalls that his father, "the only dark face in his unit of the Army Air Corps," became a boxer by necessity; family legend has it that he was heavyweight champion of the corps in 1945. Later, he turned professional. "If he won, we had meat," Montano says. "If not, beans."  <p> As a child, Montano claims, he was given boxing gloves before he got his first pair of shoes. He spent much of his childhood in fights, mostly winning. "People would ask: He's weak, skinny, and has bad eyes.' " Montano recalls. "My dad would explain, He knows the secret: The last guy standing wins.' " Montano didn't apply that same tenacity to his studies. "I spent half my time in gangs, half running away," he says. "In tenth grade, I got four Fs and two Ds. People thought I would die in the gas chamber."  <p> But at 14, he read a book about J.P. Morgan and decided he was destined for Wall Street. At 18, already married, he filled out applications at five New York brokerage companies with Los Angeles offices. "No one wanted me. At a Los Angeles firm called Noble,Cooke, I said I'd work for free, so they took me on."  <p> In the early 1970s, Montano worked at a firm that raised money for companies in the emerging field of computers. Some of these businesses soured; one, a small firm called Datatron, asked him to be chairman of its board. Soon, he fired the CEO and tookover as CEO himself. He was just 26. "At the next board meeting, everyone resigned," he remembers. "I knew the buzzwords, but I had no idea what a semiconductor really was." When Montano joined Datatron, he bought its stock at 25 cents. Eighteen months later, he says, it was $4.50.  <p> He started Montano Securities in 1979 with the idea of serving as an investment bank for small companies. But the firm, too under capitalized to go after the best deals, languished. Other business efforts--a trading desk in London, a plan to build a retirement community in the Philippines, and an attempt to revive a neglected gold mine--also failed.  <p> His history also includes a run-in with federal regulators. In 1992, the Securities and Exchange Commission ruled that the gold mine Montano tried to rescue hadn't been tested sufficiently to support his optimistic claims. It formally ordered him to cease and desist. In another action related to the gold mine, Massachusetts also barred Montano from conducting any private placements in that state for a year.  <p> As he weaves his tale of ambition and disappointment, Montano points to a painting hanging in his office of a sailing ship fighting its way through a severe storm. In the picture, there are just a few sailors courageous enough to remain on deck, and only one gutsy enough to climb the rigging. "That's me," Montano says. "I'm lashed to the mast."  <p>
Montano's plan to become the next Charles Schwab began in 1991 while he was serving as the president of a brokerage firm called Baraban Securities. When Montano became interested in Baraban, the firm was operating under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy act, which allows a company protection from creditors while it works out a repayment plan. Montano proposed that Montano Securities--still only a tiny outfit, but one he claimed was profitable--take over Baraban without any immediate compensation. He also offered to work for free, help cut costs, and even pick up the tab for the services that he, his son Alex, and several others would provide. Baraban accepted.  <p> What Baraban's management didn't know was that Montano Securities actually had a $1 million cumulative operating deficit, according to court documents. After taking control, Montano quickly began shifting his own payroll to Baraban's. This included Ann-Marie Montano, who at 18 was paid $21,000 a year to answer phones; 23-year-old Amy Montano, paid $36,000 annually as Baraban's executive vice president; and 20-year-old Alex Montano, who earned $40,000 as chief of the research department. Heading the new Baraban "Network Service Center" to assist the brokers was a Montano family friend who had failed the Series 7 exam. The new chief financial officer, who earned $78,000 a year at Baraban, wasn't a certified public accountant.  <p> Bankruptcy judge Barry Russell later concluded that Montano's tenure at Baraban was essentially "an attempted hostile takeover from within." This would-be coup, according to the judge's findings of fact, was thwarted in August of 1992 by both the appointment of a new bankruptcy trustee and an offer from Jacinto Development Corp. to buy the company. Montano directed a Baraban employee to deposit $350,000 of the firm's fast-diminishing capital into a margin account he controlled. The bankruptcy trustee countermanded that payment. Montano told his employees to ignore the trustee. With that, the trustee fired Montano.  <p> In May 1994, the bankruptcy judge ordered Montano and the former chief financial officer for the firm to repay Baraban $595,380, with Montano individually fined an additional $500,000 for interfering with the sale of the firm--judgments that Montano is appealing. <p> Two days after the trustee fired Montano, all Baraban offices received faxes announcing that Montano Securities was going national and would welcome applications from brokers. Montano began to place newspaper ads that were nearly identical to Baraban's. And then, appropriating Baraban's business strategy, he began to recruit people who wanted to be brokers, trained them to take the Series 7 examination, and then gave them jobs selling securities. <p> From the beginning, though, Montano operated the company as though selling securities was a sideline. The cash cow was the school. Each new broker initially brought $500 into the firm, but few could generate any significant business off the bat. Without another revenue source, Montano had little choice but to continue his ads and grow his school; he churned out brokers at a rapid clip until the school took on some of the characteristics of reckless expansion.  <p> In mid-1994, the firm almost went broke, and Montano slashed its expenses. New brokers couldn't get business cards printed. In the New York City office, letters to clients were never mailed, and coffee had to be imported from a cart on the street. Some regional office chiefs dipped into their pockets to buy supplies and made a joke of the crisis.   <p> In September, Montano placed a barrage of phone calls to prospective investors: "First one with money owns the firm." In mid-October, California Quartz stepped up to invest in Montano. That firm,which originally produced quartz material for semiconductors, also owns the Focus Institute, a high-level vocational institute that retrains people from the aerospace and defense industries to work with computers. Why not follow Montano's lead and trainthose engineers to be brokers?   <p> "The synergy is very good," California Quartz CEO David Lopes told me in October. "The cost of our training is underwritten100 percent by the government. Now, what Dan does in his broker-education program is the bare minimum. We want to add to it, so his people can hit the ground running. They'd be trained to sell, they'll have computer skills, they'll be expert in spread-sheet analysis. "This specialized training doesn't come cheap--Lopes estimated that his proposed five-month program would cost $7,000 to $9,000 per person. Who would pay for it? "The government," Lopes said, with a self-confidence that made Montano seem ambivalent by comparison."We're making the applications now."  <p> The terms seemed clear: Cal Quartz would purchase a minority equity interest in the firm, but Dan Montano and his wife, Vicky, also signed an irrevocable proxy that would give Cal Quartz effective control of a majority of the voting shares. But nothing was exactly what it seemed--on either side. On December 16, Montano filed for protection under federal bankruptcy laws to save it from the clutches of Wall Street operators who, he claimed, wanted to turn the firm into a bucket shop. A few days before, California Quartz had replaced Montano's board of directors with its own slate. These new directors had then tried to fire Dan Montano. <p> A shadowy figure runs through these maneuvers: California Quartz's advisor, Pat Rooney. In 1988, the NASD expelled the firm of Rooney,Pace, suspended its president, and punished five former brokers for stock manipulation. Rooney, who had left the firm in 1985, was banned from the securities business in the U.S. in early1989. He now lives in Bermuda and London, where he describes himself as a financial consultant.  <p> An October 17, 1994, letter from Pat Rooney to Montano makes it clear that Rooney envisioned aggressive sales practices for Montano Securities. In the letter, Rooney suggested, "The short-term strategy for Montano should be to get as many prospectuses as is practical on the street immediately. Product quality, of course, must be kept under control and our research concept must not be violated (too much)."   <p> Roney also suggested that Montano's brokers repackage small-capitalization penny stocks into something called PRAWNS, an instrument Rooney had invented. His influence with California Quartz apparently carried a bit more weight than it might have from some other advisor--the new Montano board put in place included Pat Rooney's son, John.  <p> Dan Montano says he was outraged upon "discovering" these plans. But this doesn't ring true. Montano knew all about Rooney before he signed the deal with California Quartz. He acknowledges taking Rooney's calls for almost a year. He even said Rooney was one of the people he talked to when he went looking for cash to save his firm.  <p> There's also confusion about the financial condition of Montano Securities. "In our due diligence, we saw a lot of disconcerting things," says David Lopes.  <p> Montano's numbers apparently didn't hold up to an audit conducted by his own accountant. Although Montano told Lopes that Montano Securities had made $953,000 in management fees in 1994, the auditor could find only $102,000. Montano claimed $1.9 million in revenue from trading and other sources, but the auditor could verify only $259,000. "They're wrong," Montano says in rejoinder. <p> When NASD demanded that the deal's structure be changed in light of Montano Securities' need for extra capital, Montano attempted to revoke the irrevocable proxy he and Vicky had signed. That part of the deal was void, he claimed. Now, he said, California Quartz owned no more than 16 percent of Montano. "I looked at him as he told me this and couldn't believe it," Lopes says."We were talking about an investment of $1.5 million!"  <p> That led to California Quartz's first attempt to fire Montano. But in a replay of the Baraban scenario, Montano refused to leave. Instead, he went out looking for an investor who would rid him of Cal Quartz.   <p> Montano's near-religious fervor to rescue the firm may have been something more than mere showmanship. Lopes insists that he's not Rooney's pawn and that Montano has used Rooney's involvement as a smoke screen. "Dan had a real-people concept, and with support at the corporate level and ongoing training, the brokers who are already there can make a living for themselves and a viable business for us," Lopes says.  <p> Nevertheless, according to a draft agreement, dated December12, 1994, California Quartz proposed to sell its 51 percent of Montano Securities--for $1--to R.G. Dickinson, a securities firm that, since 1987, has been involved in 28 arbitration hearings with investors and has received three NASD censures and fines. The NASD suspended the firm in 1987. The days of common folk as brokers and trusting customers may be over at Montano.  <p>
Financial magazines often publish stories about brokers who fleece their customers. This one turns out to be a story where the only real victims are the brokers--in this instance, the people who went to work for Dan Montano. Their original enthusiasm for a high-minded idea has only deepened their recent disillusionment. <p> "Dan has told us several things that were supposed to happen, and all he's done is leave us high and dry," Mike Nixon, the manager of Montano's Washington office, told me the week after the bankruptcy, "I've heard Dan wants us to move as a group. But if Dan, Amy, and Alex Montano are involved, forget it." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing
					</font>
