	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Part 2, Market Movers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Ted C. Fishman and the Editors<p>--------------------<br><p>26. DENNIS J. KEEGAN<br>
Managing director, Salomon Brothers<p>PROFILE: In the bond market (the world's second largest financial market, after currencies), Salomon is the 800-pound gorilla, and Keegan is its keeper. Keegan's job is to trade on the differences in yields among fixed-income securities: He makes money if he correctly guesses whether the differences will converge or widen. A key component to Salomon's success is its ability to finesse the traders in the giant U.S. Treasury Bond pit at the Chicago Board of Trade, an infamously brutal market where traders who step in front of the Salomon freight train can get crushed. POWER MOVE: Keegan's trading earned Salomon $1 billion in the firm's year that ended in September 1994. That is not a typo. CAVEAT: Keegan's power stems from his position within the Salomon franchise; it accrues to whoever has the job. John Meriwether was the first to tame the markets by honing the arbitrage trading techniques Keegan has used to such good effect.<p><br>
27. DAN HERTZBERG<br>
National news editor of The Wall Street Journal<p>PROFILE: Maybe he doesn't tell the financial world what to think on the way to work, but he certainly tells it what to think about. For a serious investor or broker, beginning a day without The Wall Street Journal is like flying blind. In its pages are what your colleagues and competitors are talking about, and what they expect you to know. POWER MOVE: Hertzberg dictates the paper's news mix, deciding what is and isn't important. The Journal can boost companies or devastate them; most days it does a little of each. One study even found a correlation between headline size in the Journal and the stock prices of companies featured in the stories. CAVEAT: Shortly after the trading day begins, the Journal's impact has hit stocks. From then on, the paper is stale, and the breaking news and market forces take over. In that respect, electronic news sources have usurped much of the paper's clout: Today traders need CNN and Bloomberg as much as they need Dow Jones.<p><br>
28. E.E. "BUZZ" GEDULD<br>
President, Herzog, Heine, Geduld, Inc.<p>PROFILE: As head of market-making activities at one of the nation's top over-the-counter (Nasdaq) stock-trading firms, Geduld plays a hand in pricing over 4,500 stocks, from active stocks like Apple Computer to small new issues. Geduld forged his reputation in the 1980s by making markets in highly volatile new issues that few other traders would touch. His firm still makes markets in scores of thinly traded stocks, where as a skilled trader he can both move the stock and keep margins comfortably wide. POWER MOVE:  Herzog, Heine, Geduld makes markets in every new initial public offering, sometimes in 50 new stocks a week. The firm accounts for about 8 percent of the daily volume in Nasdaq stocks. CAVEAT: The current Justice Department probe into Nasdaq may hit Geduld's firm hard. The probe grew out of charges that market makers manipulate the spreads between buy and sell prices; the firm faced similar charges in the 1980s.<p><br>
29. FRED GRAUER<br>
Chief Executive Officer, Wells Fargo Nikko Investment Advisors<p>PROFILE: Grauer personally sells his investment approach to top officials at every pension fund of consequence in the country, and now internationally. He's done nothing less than change the way institutions invest their money: Plain-vanilla stock-and-bond portfolios are becoming a thing of the past. Grauer advocates a one-two punch of indexing (designing portfolios to mirror broad-based indexes like the S&P 500) and asset allocation (diversifying portfolios among different asset classes). Wells Fargo Nikko now controls $160 billion in assets, making it the largest institutional money manager in the country and one of the top five lenders of stock to short-sellers. POWER MOVE: To diversify his company's enormous pool, Grauer has pushed billions in pension dollars into new markets. CAVEAT: Don't try this at home. Grauer's success in indexing and allocation hinges on the firm's huge assets; individual investors can't duplicate it.<p><br>
30. RICHARD G. SHERLUND<br>
Partner, Goldman, Sachs & Co.<p>PROFILE: Investors looking to find the next Microsoft would do well to watch Sherlund. The computer-sector analyst has pushed and pulled the stock ever since his firm took it public. His power to move markets is tied mainly to his ability to pry information out of the software giant. More than anyone else, Sherlund is thought to have the inside dope on how new software is testing and where Bill Gates might focus next. He comments often in the weekly computer trade magazines, whose readers not only run the computer industry but speculate on it as well. POWER MOVE: In the face of widespread uncertainty, Sherlund predicted correctly last year that the Justice Department's actions against Microsoft would mean little to the company. Up went the company's stock--and his. CAVEAT: Sherlund has proved less prescient about Microsoft's competitors. He stayed positive for too long on Lotus Development--he liked it right up to the moment it lost half its value.<p><br>
31. ABBEY COHEN<br>
Co-chair of the Investment Policy Committee, Goldman, Sachs & Co.<p>PROFILE: An important economist and priceless stump speaker for Wall Street's premier investment firm, Cohen is a coveted guest at investment seminars and conferences. Under her direction, Goldman churns out reams of strategy reports that land on the desks of the firm's institutional customers. Her recommendations are wide-ranging, covering individual stocks on one hand and asset classes on the other. The directives cover all the financial markets and relate them to broad trends in politics, resource consumption, and finance. The underlying message, of course, is that Goldman covers the world and that clients are wise to stick with the firm that trades anything that moves. POWER MOVE: Cohen was a leading voice in Goldman's recent push to persuade clients to move major assets into commodities. Her research anticipated the big jumps in commodity prices over the last year. CAVEAT: Cohen's approach suits institutional investors best. Individual investors without access to Goldman's resources would be wise to follow her lead only in the areas of stocks and mutual fund portfolios.<p><br>
32. DAN DORFMAN<br>
Market writer and commentator<p>PROFILE: The most watched reporter on individual stocks--the man for tips and rumors. He predicts a takeover, and the stock price goes up. He murmurs about trouble, and the stock price goes down. Dorfman, who offers a "pick of the day" weekdays on CNBC, is responsible for more client phone calls to retail brokers than anyone else. SEC enforcers keep a file of Dorfman's USA Today commentaries. Why? People nabbed for insider trading use them as proof they traded on public information. POWER MOVE: In a Washington Post study of the 18-month period ended last May, 95 percent of the stocks Dorfman recommended jumped in price--by an average of 13 percent--in the minutes after his television commentary. CAVEAT: Only four in ten of the stocks Dorfman recommended in the same period remained winners in the following months. Dorfman is taking his written commentary to Money magazine, where he and his fans might be frustrated by his longer lead times. <p><br>
33. CHARLES SCHWAB<br>
Chairman, <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab & Co.</b></a>, Inc.<p>PROFILE: The brokerage industry's most restless innovator. Not satisfied with attracting $120 billion in assets to his discount brokerage--nearly half of all discount-brokerage business --Schwab has begun to move in on the mutual fund companies. His company leads in providing investors computerized tools to manage their own financial affairs: Today, clients with PCs can place orders, watch market news, and track their portfolios, all without ever having to hear a sales pitch. Power  move: Schwab's firm opened 800,000 new accounts in 1994 alone. Schwab OneSource, a one-stop-shopping service for more than 250 different mutual funds from various fund families, has attracted more than $13 billion in the past two years. Anointment by OneSource is a virtual guarantee that millions of dollars will flow into a fund. CAVEAT: While still a service leader among discounters, Schwab may lose some competitive edge to cheaper deep-discount brokerages.<p><br>
34. BORIS YELTSIN<br>
President, Russia<p>PROFILE: With billions of dollars of hedge-fund, merchant-bank, and mutual fund money flooding Russia, Western capitalists have a lot tied up in the fate of the former communist state. Under Yeltsin and Russian economic coordinator Anatoly Chubais, the state has struggled to put its economic affairs in order with monetary and fiscal controls, efforts international investors have found encouraging. So far, 14,000 large and midsize companies have been privatized; all need to attract investors. To stay on track, Yeltsin must keep ultra-nationalists and die-hard communists at bay--increasingly difficult as the political culture of the country fragments. POWER MOVE: The U.S. stock market rises and falls with Yeltsin's fortunes. It slid when he faced impeachment in 1993, then rebounded when he beat back his challengers. CAVEAT: If right-wing zealot Vladimir Zhirinovsky pushes Yeltsin aside, today's U.S. investments may become tomorrow's donations to nationalist bloodlust.<p><br>
35. EDWARD HYMAN JR.<br>
Chairman, International Strategy and Investment Group<p>PROFILE: Perhaps the most respected economist on Wall Street, Hyman has topped Institutional Investor's poll every year since 1980. Hyman does not recommend specific investments but does describe the economic environment in which they will operate. His output of reports and analyses is Promethean: Every morning his office faxes clients a four-page missive filled with facts and figures, and on Mondays it ships a 20-page newsletter. Hyman has two appeals: an outstanding track record and an ability to condense masses of data into something quickly read and easily digested. It would take some looking to find a major bank, money manager, or other big investor who didn't get Hyman's service. POWER MOVE: Hyman's regular surveys and comments on the auto industry, retail chains, and the bond market rival government statistics as market movers. CAVEAT: Hyman showed fallibility in 1994 when he was slow in seeing interest rate rises.<p><br>
36. WILLIAM GROSS<br>
Managing director, PIMCO Advisors L.P.<p>PROFILE: Manages the largest bond portfolio in the country, PIMCO's $56 billion behemoth. Don Phillips of Morningstar Mutual Funds once said Gross was "kind of like the Peter Lynch of bonds," and the description stuck. It fits Gross because his performance is exceptional and his investment choices are copied by other multibillion-dollar managers. Ten years ago, when he was still just the William Gross of the bond market, reeling traders in the Chicago Board of Trades bond pit waved handkerchiefs at Gross's brokers after a series of trades that netted millions for his clients. POWER MOVE: Gross was an early, successful U.S. entrant in the bond futures and international bond markets, helping blaze a trail into markets where daily dollar volume is counted in the trillions. CAVEAT: Gross struggled through the volatile bond market in 1994 and reshaped his strategies to maximize yields. Whether the retooling will keep him at the top of the heap remains to be seen.<p><br>
37. C. FRED BERGSTEN<br>
Director, Institute for International Economics<p>PROFILE: Regarded by currency traders as the voice of the Clinton administration on economic matters--despite disclaimers from the administration itself. When Lloyd Bentsen traveled to Tokyo in 1993, he reminded his audience that he, not Bergsten, was the secretary of the treasury. Bergsten's pronouncements are taken especially seriously in Japan. His reputation there rests on his consistent prediction, made first in the early '80s, that the yen would strengthen to correct the country's balance-of-payments surplus with the U.S.; he was, to say the least, on the money. POWER MOVE: In July, Bergsten caused a strong dollar rally when he predicted that the yen had topped out. Bergsten's suggestion was seen as a sign that the U.S. would soon complete its bilateral trade negotiations with Japan. As was the case. CAVEAT: It's possible that Robert Rubin won't like having a shadow secretary and will move to minimize Bergsten's influence.<p><br>
38. LEON BLACK<br>
Founder,  Apollo Advisors L.P.<p>PROFILE: Wall Street's most successful "vulture investor," a master at buying distressed securities on the cheap and selling them later for a huge profit. Black was formerly co-head of Drexel Burnham Lambert's mergers and acquisitions department: Michael Milken worked in Beverly Hills, Black in New York. Both put together junk bond packages and helped create the distress Black now feeds on. Black is said to have big interests in up to 100 companies. He has played the junk bond market brilliantly and now has a $5 billion war chest. POWER MOVE: Black sometimes builds clout by buying blocks of securities just large enough to let him prevent restructurings that don't suit him. It's been called the "1990s equivalent of greenmail." CAVEAT: Black's business is all about taking chances, and he can misstep--as in 1992 when he offered to help New York developer Peter Kalikow prop up his financial house of cards and bid for the New York Daily News.<p><br>
39. ANNE BINGAMAN<br>
Assistant Attorney General, Antitrust Division<p>PROFILE: Has broad powers to review the competitive practices of U.S. companies. Can bring suit to force companies to compete more fairly or split them up, and her approval is necessary for corporate mergers. Bingaman can also exert influence on the securities industry directly, challenging trading practices on and off exchanges. POWER MOVE: Bingaman is scrutinizing Microsoft's intended purchase of Intuit, on the grounds that Microsoft could dominate the future online market for financial services. She is also aggressively investigating anticompetitive collusion by over-the-counter market makers, an effort that could put a lot of quarters and halves into the pockets of people who trade Nasdaq stocks. CAVEAT: Bingaman's fight against corporate consolidation is not always welcome in the Clinton administration. Laura Tyson, chief economic advisor to the president, believes many U.S. companies need to group to compete against other global giants. Bingaman may have also stumbled badly in previous fights with Microsoft, where efforts to rein in the company have had no real effect.<p><br>
40. NEIL PERRY<br>
Head of Latin American research, Baring Securities<p>PROFILE: Helps U.S. and European money managers get comfortable in the exploding (and occasionally imploding) Latin American equity markets. Perry runs Baring Securities' team of Latin American market analysts. His influence extends throughout the parent company, Baring PLC, the world's oldest merchant bank and itself one of the ten largest managers of international assets. According to Institutional Investor, Perry is the No. 1 analyst in his field. POWER MOVE: Perry influences the stock picks of a number of big, internationally oriented mutual funds, including those run by Fidelity and Templeton. Last year, his 100-page argument that Mexican conglomerate Desc Sociedad de Fomento Industrial was undervalued helped nearly triple the price of the stock. CAVEAT: American firms, particularly Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch, are fortifying their teams of foreign-market analysts, which may dilute the influence of Perry and Baring.<p><br>
41. ALAN BLINDER<br>
Vice chairman, Federal Reserve Board<p>PROFILE: The No. 2 policy maker at the U.S. central bank since last June. Blinder is the most dovish and talkative Fed Board member on inflation, particularly when rate tightenings threaten progress on employment. Philosophically close to Clinton, for whom he served on the Council of Economic Advisers, Blinder is regarded as the one high official at the Fed who really understands employment as an issue. Blinder, who supported last November's rate hikes, is closely watched for potential dissent. Alan Greenspan can't distance himself too far from Blinder if he hopes to get the nod from the president for another term as Fed chairman in 1996. POWER MOVE: Blinder's general endorsement of rate hikes before the Fed acted in November triggered anticipatory slumps in the bond and stock markets. CAVEAT: Six months ago, when it seemed he might regularly challenge Greenspan, Blinder would have rated higher on this list. Lately, he's been going along to get along.<p><br>
42. WILLIAM T. ALLEN<br>
Chancellor, Court of Chancery of Delaware<p>PROFILE: Nearly half the companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange (and some 214,000 in all) are incorporated in Delaware. The state's court system is a prime reason. Allen presides over Delaware's specialized business courts, which probably hear more major corporate-governance cases than courts in any other state. They certainly hear the big ones. In the last decade, Delaware courts heard cases related to many billion-dollar merger battles, including those over Paramount, insurer American General, and, most recently, Santa Fe and Snapple. Companies' fortunes often hinge on the rulings of the chancery judges. POWER MOVE: Allen himself presided over 1994's Paramount/Viacom/QVC battle, during which the stocks and options put in play in the merger gyrated wildly. CAVEAT: Other states would also like a piece of the incorporation action; a number of them are amending their business laws and courts to compete with Delaware.<p><br>
43. RICHARD SCOTT<br>
President and CEO, Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corporation<p>PROFILE: Richard Scott wants to own your hospital, or at least buy it and close it. He is the force behind the consolidation of much of the nation's health care business; his seven-year buying spree has netted him at least 4 percent of all the private hospitals in the country. (Columbia/HCA has 134,000 employees and more than 42,000 hospital beds.) Scott influences the entire health care sector by forcing economies of scale. He bargains hard with the likes of Baxter, the nation's largest supplier of medical goods; recently he said that he could "give them $800 million [worth of business] or nothing." POWER MOVE: Last October, Scott moved to snap up another giant piece of the hospital market, HealthTrust, the second-largest investor-owned chain, in a deal worth $3.6 billion in stock. CAVEAT: Attorneys general in Florida, Tennesse, Texas, and Utah think Scott is growing too fast and are acting nervous about the HealthTrust deal.<p><br>
44. PAUL TUDOR JONES<br>
Chairman, Tudor Investment Corp.<p>PROFILE: The most successful operator of futures funds. Though his recent results haven't approached his 500 percent return in 1984 or his 136 percent return the next year, he is one of only a few futures players who consistently wins for other people. In the last three years, futures funds have averaged returns in the low single digits, some of them to the left of zero; Jones's funds (for private clients only, by the way) have been up 18 to 25 percent. Jones trades in both agricultural and financial futures with a pot of $1.5 billion. POWER MOVE: Pit traders think Jones is consistently smarter than they are (they're probably right) and rush to follow him into a trade. Last year he correctly predicted that interest rates had bottomed out, thus skirting the disasters that hit much of the rest of the financial world. CAVEAT: As its assets and trading field expand, Jones's funds have begun to resemble the huge hedge funds. In the biggest league, Jones will have to be even more of an overachiever.<p><br>
45. TOMIICHI MURAYAMA<br>
Prime Minister, Japan<p>PROFILE: The socialist at the helm of the world's second-largest economy. Shakily. After a revolving-door series of leaders (four prime ministers in a year), Murayama took office last June amid grave doubts about his future. Apparently he means to stay. Murayama abandoned the Socialist party platform and transformed himself into something like a Liberal Democrat, the kind that has long led Japan. POWER MOVE: Keeping his job this long has been no mean feat. But if Murayama is going to have any real influence on financial markets, he must show that he's willing to push for the deregulation of Japanese industry. That means dealing with the Ministry of Finance, a bureaucracy that so far has proved impervious to change. The governing coalition's slogans, touting reform and deregulation, offer some hope. CAVEAT: Murayama's allies are his biggest threat. Prominent in his coalition is the most antireformist element in Japan--the public-sector labor unions.<p><br>
46. MARTIN ZWEIG<br>
Newsletter publisher and investor<p>PROFILE: Dr.Zweig--as his ads call him--runs the most prescient and widely followed of all stock market newsletters. He has long been a popular and frequent guest on PBS's Wall Street Week With Louis Rukeyser. Retail brokers expect calls on the stocks Zweig mentions and bone up on them. Often it's to stave off selling, for Zweig is known for his bearish sentiments (and, his marketers won't let you forget, for calling the 1987 crash). Of the several newsletters Zweig produces, Zweig Forecast is the most widely followed, not so much for the individual picks as for advice on timing the market. Indeed, of all the famous timers, Zweig is the only one left with his reputation intact. Zweig also runs a number of mutual funds, though others in his organization manage them. POWER MOVE: Since he began publishing it in 1971, Zweig's Forecast portfolio has never had a down year. CAVEAT: As with any investment letter, the Forecast's returns are reported without consideration of transaction costs, which are highest for individual investors.<p><br>
47. LEO O'NEILL<br>
Chief ratings officer, Standard & Poor's<p>PROFILE: Standard and Poor's is one of two agencies (Moody's is the other) that grade the creditworthiness of corporations and municipalities. The agencies are almost interchangeable and by design are lacking in stars. But O'Neill's work in corporate debt means a lot of CFOs know his name. Hiring the services of one of the debt raters is often a prerequisite for corporate borrowing. The rating directly affects the cost of money, and thus bottom lines. POWER MOVE: Though statistical upgrades of corporate debt ratings have little impact on companies' stock, downgrades can sink them. Last September, when Greyhound Lines ' junk bond debt was downgraded, the companies' bond and stock prices fell 15 percent. CAVEAT: Corporate bond ratings digest information that is already available in the public domain; more and more, they only codify old news. Big changes in corporate debt always hit the markets before debt-rating agencies have a chance to examine them.<p><br>
48. RUPERT MURDOCH<br>
Chairman and CEO, NewsCorp, Ltd.<p>PROFILE: The world's most acquisitive media mogul. Murdoch has spent some $3 billion over the last two years expanding his far-flung print and television empire. He began building in the 1980s, leveraging tabloids in his native Australia to buy newspapers in the U.S. and U.K. Murdoch rarely has trouble putting together new deals or finding the money to finance them. POWER MOVE: Last May, when Murdoch's Fox network snatched eight affiliates from CBS (as well as three from ABC and one from NBC), CBS stock got hit hard, dropping from $302 to $270 in a week of frenzied trading. One NBC executive purportedly told Murdoch that the deal would cost the peacock network $100 million. CAVEAT: Murdoch is constrained by laws that limit foreign ownership of U.S. television stations. And who can say with certainty that a different media mogul won't be even hungrier in 1995? It could be John Malone. Or Barry Diller. Or Sumner Redstone. . . . <p><br>
49. MARYANN KELLER<br>
Managing director and automotive analyst, Furman Selz Inc.<p>PROFILE: The dean of auto analysts, Keller covers the business that is the heart and soul of American industry. More than a number cruncher, Keller visits plants around the globe, looking under hoods and into corporate psyches. At a time when GM seemed indomitable, Keller predicted the Japanese ascendancy in the American market in the '80s. She understood the importance of Nissan's and Toyota's commitment to customer service. POWER MOVE: Keller's late-1993 book, Collision: General Motors, Toyota and Volkswagen and the Race to Own the 21st Century, is widely cited in industry press coverage. Her monthly column in Automotive Industries is closely watched for news of trouble brewing at car companies and their suppliers. CAVEAT: Despite Keller's reputation, her post at smallish Furman Selz means she has less of an immediate impact on institutional and retail customers than do auto analysts at Wall Street's powerhouse firms.<p><br>
50. SADDAM HUSSEIN<br>
President, Iraq<p>PROFILE: What's a market-movers list without a maniacal despot? Hussein carries the banner for a host of leaders in the Middle East, Asia (North Korea), and former communist states whose belligerence makes financial markets nervous. Hussein's strongest financial influence, of course, is over energy prices, but before and during the Gulf War, his behavior affected prices in everything from bonds to pork bellies. Last year, Hussein mobilized troops along the Kuwaiti border and continued to punish domestic refugees. Indirectly, Hussein's presence contains oil prices; it reminds the Saudis of the need for U.S. protection. POWER MOVE: When Hussein directed troops toward Kuwait last October, crude prices and oil stocks spiked. When tensions subsided, prices slid back. CAVEAT: Hussein rankles Americans, but he's ultimately a lesser threat than the militant Islamic fundamentalists who intend nothing less than to change the nature of government and society throughout the Middle East.<p><p>YOU SAID SOMETHING, SIR?<p>By Josephn Nocera<p>The great delusion of all incoming presidents, dreaming their dreams of glory, is that they will be able to control events. The great, harsh reality is that events almost always control them. Eisenhower, Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon, Ford, Carter, Reagan, Bush, Clinton--these are the presidents in my lifetime, and though their ideas and styles and philosophies span an enormous spectrum, they do hold one thing in common: They all had to learn, usually painfully, that they have far less control of their own destinies than they had imagined. Except maybe for Eisenhower, who seemed to know it all along.<p>You know the drill by now: The president who vows to balance the budget sees it balloon on his watch. The president who wants to shrink government finds himself tied up in knots by the bureaucracy. The president who hopes to focus on domestic affairs gets consumed by nasty little wars abroad. "When you first get to the White House," a former aide to Jimmy Carter once wistfully told me, "you have a tendency to hope that things will work out the way you want them to." But they never do. So why, oh why, would anyone think it's different when it comes to the market? Markets are fiendish creatures, immune to cajoling. If I were putting together a list of market movers--which, alas, I'm not--I don't know that I'd have room for a president anywhere on it. <p>It is often said that Wall Street prefers Republican presidents because it is such a fundamentally Republican place--and because Republicans supposedly care more about Wall Street's concerns. The only problem with this theory is that it doesn't hold up. Yes, it's true that the two sustained bull markets of the postwar era, those of the 1950s and the 1980s, were presided over by Republican presidents. But there is much less to that fact than meets the eye. The bull market of the 1950s was triggered by the obvious fact that America was the world's only economic superpower--a country whose companies got bigger and more profitable every year and whose workers had more money to spend each year. Eisenhower's main task during this wonderful boom time was to get out of the way, which, to his everlasting credit, he did.<p>As for the 1980s, that bull market didn't begin until Reagan had been in office nearly two years, and while the propagandists at The Wall Street Journal would give his supply-side program the bulk of the credit, it seems far more likely that the real credit belongs to Paul Volcker, whose tight money policy succeeded in squeezing inflation out of the economy. Unlike presidents, Federal Reserve chairmen really do have the power to move markets. Remember that another Republican president, Richard Nixon, presided helplessly over the most sustained bear market since the Great Depression. The only bounce Nixon ever got took place on the day he resigned.<p>The big problem for any president comes in trying to discern what exactly the markets want. For a long time, the conventional wisdom held that the single most important thing a president could do to make Wall Street happy was to balance the budget. Yet in 1980, when Carter momentarily succeeded in producing a balanced budget--the last president to even attempt such a feat--the markets tanked on him. He was then forced to unbalance the budget to revive the economy. In came Ronald Reagan, who blithely allowed the budget deficit to double while he was president, only to have the stock market triple during that time. So much for that theory.<p>What the markets usually respond to, of course, is a strong economy. And the truth is that presidents simply don't have much effect on the larger economy; if they did, we'd never have a recession, since no president would allow it. In a multitrillion-dollar economy like ours, even the biggest stimulus package is akin to throwing a pebble into the ocean.<p>Indeed, if anything has changed over the years, it is that the situation has become gradually impossible. The economy has become much larger and more complex, so much so that by the late 1970s, when it was clear that productivity had essentially stopped growing, Carter's economic advisors could not even figure out what the cause was, much less what to do about it. The Keynesian consensus, which guided policy makers for so long and offered a measure of comfort, no longer exists.<p>But worst of all, after all this time, a president's only real weapon in managing the economy remains his handling of fiscal policy. In addition to being a pathetically small weapon--more pocketknife than bazooka--it doesn't even offer any palatable choices anymore. If a president decides to lower taxes, which can stimulate the economy, the deficit will get ever more out of control--causing the government to spend ever larger sums on interest payments to its bondholders. If he raises taxes, he'll get booted out of office by those angry, overtaxed citizens who populate the land these days. Either way, the fickle markets probably won't be satisfied. This pretty well defines the condition of being between a rock and a hard place.<p>Which is another way of saying: Good luck, Mr. Clinton. When it comes to the markets, luck is what you'll need.<p><br>
"GENTLEMEN: I'LL RUIN YOU"<p>By Fredric Smoler<p>Men with the power to move markets have stalked Wall Street for a good, long time: The pirate Captain Kidd, who had considerable power to move the marine insurance markets, took up residence at 56 Wall Street in the late 17th century. At least until our own century, Captain Kidd's moral tone predominated in the area.<p>Jacob Little, known in the middle third of the 18th century as the Great Bear of Wall Street, specialized in the "manipulated short sale": He would sell shares he didn't have for delivery in 60 days, then dump the stock all over town and spread rumors about the target's insolvency. After buying the shares back at rock-bottom prices, he'd sometimes short the company again. Little was probably the first important full-time stock "operator." Several times blackballed before being admitted to the Board of the Exchange, he died broke but with his portrait on the wall above the vice-president's seat on the exchange.<p>Daniel Drew, a contemporary of Little's, learned the necessities of his future trade as a carnival barker. He began his financial career by trading cattle, buying them in Putnam County, New York, and selling them on the Bowery, and allegedly scored his first big hit by feeding his herd salt on the final night of the drive and then denying them water. The next morning he let them gorge at a stream in upper Manhattan and within a few hours sold them by the pound. <p>Drew formed a brokerage house in 1836. Soon one of the most powerful men on the Street, he dressed in old and sometimes threadbare clothing and cackled like a hen--usually, it was believed, at someone else's ruin. Drew was nearly illiterate. He was also a fantastically efficient predator. In one famous scam, he entered the Union Club in a state of quiet agitation, sweating profusely and apparently searching for someone. Invited to stay, he instead rushed out, mopping his brow with a handkerchief and in his rush dislodging from his pocket a slip of paper, which a nearby broker quickly snared. The note said, "Buy all the Oshkosh stock you can get at any price below par." The brokers present pooled to buy 30,000 shares; Drew immediately dumped Oshkosh, and it fell 12 points a day.<p>Drew, too, died broke, having several times crossed Cornelius Vanderbilt. Vanderbilt had markedly higher business ethics than most of his contemporaries, let alone Drew, but he was not one to turn the other cheek. In a telegram to some former associates, Vanderbilt announced, "Gentlemen: You have undertaken to cheat me. I won't sue you, for the law is too slow. I'll ruin you. Yours truly, Cornelius Vanderbilt." In 1863, a number of bears, including Drew, bribed the New York City Council to rescind a grant to Vanderbilt's Harlem Railroad. The councilors themselves apparently shorted Harlem stock as well, and it fell from 1165/8 to 72. Vanderbilt, however, had deep enough pockets to secure a corner and drove the stock to 180.<p>Jay Gould and Jim Fisk, however, attempted the most notorious corner in Wall Street history in 1869, when they tried to monopolize the gold market, driving it from 130 to 160, and produced the panic known as Black Friday. It's not clear that Gould and Fisk made money on the deal, but they achieved an imperishable sort of glory: "Nothing could be lost save honor," as Fisk remarked before the event, a line equaled only by his later response to a congressional inquiry as to where some investors' money was: "Gone where the woodbine twineth," answered Fisk. The aromatic woodbine, or honeysuckle, was grown around outhouses to mask the smell. Now that was a politer age than ours, if not a more scrupulous one. <p><br>
DELISTED<p>Sometimes you move the market, and sometimes you move aside, voluntarily or otherwise. Here are four people who would have made a Market Movers list as recently as a year ago:<p>* Elaine Garzarelli: In 1987 she was one of a few people to call the crash, and immediately individual investors began to follow her. But her bosses at Lehman Brothers let her go last fall; they purportedly found her too independent, especially at $2 million a year.<p>* Mario Gabelli: Another market guru with a formerly big following. Gabelli peddled advice in print and on TV, then became a money manager. His stature as seer hasn't withstood the real-life test. <p>* Worth Bruntjen: Last year, a bright star in government bond funds. His exceptional returns were built on ultra-high-risk derivatives, however, and by August, Bruntjen's funds at Piper Jaffray had lost nearly a quarter of their value.<p>* Steve Savage: As head of Value Line's new mutual fund publication, Savage's mission was to best Morningstar in the lucrative rating business. But Value Line lost momentum after reports that it lifted commentaries verbatim from Morningstar.<p><br>
EXPECT THE UNEXPECTED<p>By Jonathan Butler and Kevin Caliendo<p>It's not always about people. Something--emphasis on thing--could turn the market on its head at any given moment. We asked some pros what inanimate factors could move a market, and they pointed to four areas:<p>* Nature: Never mind hurricanes; how about everyday things like rain and sun? In Chicago, commodities traders hang on every word from Tom Skilling, weatherman for superstation WGN-TV. Not to check the forecast--traders have their own reports--but to know what farmers are being told. When the Mississippi flooded in 1993, says Paul Johnson Jr., senior vice president at ING Derivatives Clearing in Chicago, "Traders would look out the window. When the rain came down, so did bond prices."<p>* The Contract With America: Will Speaker Gingrich's Republican constitution be adopted, adapted, or dumped? The markets have begun guessing, reacting, and worrying. "Wall Street will think that the tax cuts are real but that the spending cuts are phony," predicts Donald Straszheim, chief economist at <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>. A capital-gains tax cut would create "an almost open-ended supply of stock that would effectively put a lid on the equity market," says Michael Metz, chief investment strategist at Oppenheimer. "It could create massive selling," agrees Todd Ehret, portfolio manager at Money Growth Institute in New York.<p>* Program Trading: Nearly every firm has a program that calculates the difference in value between the S&P 500 Index futures and the S&P 500 itself and then buys or sells accordingly, an arbitrage bet that can ravage the Dow in the final minutes of trading. Investors sometimes panic. "When clients see the market fell 42 points, they think 1987' and want to get out." says Ken South, a Smith Barney broker in Costa Mesa, California. Great, say Wall Street vets. "We can make a profit when a move is computer driven," says Sam Marchese, CEO of SIFE Trust Fund. "It'll correct itself the next day."<p>* Rumors: Remember hearing that cellular phones caused brain cancer? Nothing to it in the end, but that didn't stop investors from dumping their shares in Motorola and others. Playing a rumor, of course, is all in the timing. "When you buy on a rumor, you're anticipating someone else hearing it," says Metz. "I always figure I'm late and wrong."<br>
<br>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Government<br><p>

