	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Part 1, Market Movers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ted C. Fishman and the Editors<p>
Reporting assistance by Jonathan Butler and Kevin Caliendo. Additional research by Jack Bronis, Kazys Ozelis, and Liz Pawelko.<p>
Oddly enough, in the world's big financial markets, money buys little influence. The reason is that no fortune, personal or collective, matters much in light of the $2 trillion tide of money that changes hands every day in stocks, bonds, and currencies. But influence can be had, and some wield it mightily. They do so by getting other people to change the way they invest. Market movers can be innovators, investigators, or salesmen. Some have the might of governments behind them. They all command attention--either by example, like Warren Buffett; by offering information, like Peter Lynch or Dan Dorfman; or by exercising the power of their position, like Alan Greenspan. Our top 50 market movers are the men and women who set money in motion. They do so all over the world, but we looked in particular at how their maneuverings ultimately affect American investors. We offer them here as people to watch closely in the coming year. Professional market players make it their business to study them, and no one who hopes to understand or prosper in the markets can afford not to. <p>
1. ALAN GREENSPAN
Chairman of the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System
PROFILE: Greenspan has real power to regulate U.S. interest rates, which in this economy is the name of the game. Some say he bullies the other Fed governors on issues of money and credit; others say he has forged a grudging consensus. Jealously guards low inflation with aggressive interest-rate hikes. Less keen on full employment. Views cheap dollar as dangerously inflationary and pushes Fed to help prop it up. POWER MOVE: Reversed a long downward trend in interest rates with six hikes in short-term Fed rates in 1994. That in turn escalated bank and long-term debt, cost bond traders and bond mutual fund investors billions, spooked the stock market, doomed planned mergers, and offered a costly comeuppance to corporate treasurers who thought they understood exotic derivatives. CAVEAT: Clintonites griped about the Fed's latest and largest rate hike, in November 1994, and Greenspan must please the president to gain reappointment to his post in 1996. If anything's likely to get him interested in full employment, it might be the prospect of job hunting himself.<p>
2. HANS TIETMEYER
President of the Bundesbank, German Central Bank
PROFILE: Central bankers everywhere--and that includes our own Fed chairman--quake before Tietmeyer's power to set interest rates. World bond and currency markets quake, too. Relatively high rates for most of this decade lured investors into deutsche markdenominated assets and away from dollars--the main reason the DM is thumping the dollar. POWER MOVE: In May 1994, Tietmeyer began cutting interest rates. That didn't have the intended effect of halting the dollar's slide, but it did send the world bond markets into tumult. Generally, any time Tietmeyer persuades the Bundesbank council to reduce rates, similar cuts ensue across Europe. CAVEAT: Tietmeyer's power derives partly from his political ties to Chancellor Helmut Kohl. Recently the Bundesbank has been a responsible international citizen, but if Kohl needs his help, Tietmeyer may return the bank to its traditional role as guard dog of the German economy.<p>
3. BILL CLINTON
President of the United States of America
PROFILE: Despite Republican efforts to hobble the president, Clinton is no lame duck yet. He's still boss of all federal bureaucrats, commander in chief (i.e., the only American who can start a war), lord of the treasury, and steward of U.S. foreign and trade policies. He is also the nation's top opponent of supply-side redux and has a veto to prove it. POWER MOVE: Listen, we never said this was only about moving markets up. The specifics of Clinton's impact (such as the yo-yo-ing of health care stocks in reaction to the changing fortunes of the health care proposals) are less important than the fact that financial professionals hate going to work every day with Bill Clinton as their president. Only 1 percent of money pros polled gave his performance high marks, and 1994's lackluster markets reflected their lack of confidence. CAVEAT: Clinton's character isn't a market fundamental. As Wall Street realizes this, and looks with clearer eyes at the economy, the market could gain buoyancy. <p>
4. NEWT GINGRICH
Representative from Georgia; Speaker of the House
PROFILE: For now, the nation's leading Republican, friend of business and investors and enemy of regulation. Every newly elected Republican in the country owes him. So do the old-time GOPers to whom he delivered real power. Gingrich built his victories by lambasting President Clinton, but he also helped hand Clinton legislative wins on NAFTA, GATT, and the crime bill. In the coming two years, Gingrich faces a choice of whether to play politics with key legislation--like tax cuts--while biding time until 1996, or to play statesman and help build a concensus that may have the unwelcome effect of improving Clinton's prospects. POWER MOVE: In three words, Contract With America. It could genuinely change the direction and nature of the economy. CAVEAT: What to make of this Contract? The accounting on Gingrich's tax and spending cuts is more art than science. If taxes drop and the deficit pops back up, higher interest rates could weaken the market.<p>
5. JEFF VINIK
Manager, Fidelity <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Magellan Fund</b></a>
PROFILE: Runs the nation's largest mutual fund--$36 billion in assets and still counting. Since taking control of Magellan in 1992, Vinik has reshaped the fund that Peter Lynch built, spreading three times as much money across half as many stocks. POWER MOVE: Every move is a power move: Vinik cannot walk softly. Individual investors and fund managers watch him, and many piggyback on his choices. Corporations court his interest, and when they get it, they crow. Lately, Vinik is heavily committed to technology stocks; for example, he's tripled Magellan's holdings in Sun Microsystems and now owns 12 percent of the company. CAVEAT: Like we said, every move's a power move. Magellan can't make a quick exit from a company in which it has a huge stake--the fund, the company, and the market will all take hits. Magellan's prestige suffered at least a nick last year, when not only did it end the year in the red, but it also acknowledged an accounting gaffe.<p>
6. YASUO MATSUSHITA
Chairman, Bank of Japan
PROFILE: With Japanese stocks and real estate emerging from their nosedive, the Bank of Japan's new honcho has a relatively easy job for now: managing deflation. The bank also plays the international currency markets, most often in consort with the U.S. Federal Reserve, though Japan devotes billions more to fighting the yen's onerous rise than does the U.S. Matsushita must continue the deregulation of the Japanese securities industry, which should boost the fortunes of foreign stocks listed on the Tokyo exchange. POWER MOVE: Matsushita's term began last December 16. His predecessor showed how powerful the Bank of Japan is when he raised interest rates to bust the 1980s speculative bubble in stock and land prices. It worked, bringing crashes in both, a three-year recession, a sky-high yen, and a massive withdrawal of Japanese assets from U.S. markets. CAVEAT: Matsushita hails from the inner ranks of the politically powerful ministry of finance, a tie that may indicate a tendency to veer away from central bank independence and weaken his resolve for securities deregulation. <p>
7. WARREN BUFFETT
Chairman and CEO, <a name="NYSE:BRK.A"></a><b>Berkshire Hathaway, Inc.</b>
PROFILE: Not your average multibillionaire. Investors love Buffett because he amassed his $9 billion fortune by picking the right stocks, unlike those speculators whose fortunes stem from "percentage of profits" deals. Buffett's investment vehicle since 1969 has been Berkshire Hathaway, whose book value has grown at 23.3 percent a year and whose shares trade on the New York Stock Exchange at--gulp--about $20,000 a share. Two recent books on Buffett's strategies (neither by the master himself) have already become must-reads on Wall Street. Buffett details his own investment philosophy in Berkshire annual reports, quotes from which regularly fill analysts' newsletters. POWER MOVE: In December Buffett told a securities analyst that Berkshire Hathaway's $358 million investment in USAir had been a mistake. All major airlines tumbled. CAVEAT: There's still only one Warren Buffett. Analysts warn that he's a statistical anomaly.<p>
8. ROBERT RUBIN
Secretary designee of the U.S. Treasury
PROFILE: The most trusted voice in the Clinton administration on economic policy (true, incidentally, even when Lloyd Bentsen sat in the secretary's chair). Formerly a co-chairman of Goldman Sachs, Rubin champions deficit reduction, free trade, a strong dollar, and helping business do business. He is, however, lukewarm to a capital-gains tax cut and cold to other cuts. He's said to champion the urban poor, not the usual hallmark of a cost-cutter. POWER MOVE: Rubin framed Clinton's deficit-reduction strategy, which at least did the economic expansion no harm. His defining moments, however, will come as he begins work on the economic positions behind the reelection effort. Starting . . . yesterday. CAVEAT: While Rubin gets high marks for drawing parties in the administration together, he has not endeared himself to legislators, left or right. He must develop political skills at Treasury that the administration lost with Bentsen's departure.<p>
9. BARTON BIGGS
Chairman and CEO, <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley Asset Management Co.</b></a>
PROFILE: The biggest reason so much American institutional money goes overseas. Biggs advises Morgan Stanley's giant institutional investors on how to spread out their money; lately he's been suggesting they keep their billions "as far from Bill and Hillary" as possible. POWER MOVE: Biggs's cheerleading for stocks in China, India, and Southeast Asia has fueled a rush into those markets. When Biggs visited China in 1993 with an entourage of money managers, thousands of peasants greeted him in the streets. His report on the trip circulated widely among institutional investors and instigated what some have called the "Barton Biggs effect," a rush of money into a market he recommends. CAVEAT: Large institutional investors move in and out of markets conspicuously, which can be hazardous in the thinly traded markets of developing countries. Emerging markets are the most volatile of all; only investors committed to the long run should get cozy with Biggs.<p>
10. PETER LYNCH
Investor and author
PROFILE: The former manager of the Magellan Fund, and a genuine icon. Lynch is one of a small handful of legendary stock pickers and the only one whose name is well known outside financial circles. Now an oft-quoted source on sector trends and investment fundamentals. POWER MOVE: Any time Lynch mentions a stock, in the pages of Worth or elsewhere, retail brokers hear from their clients. It can get weird: In 1993 Lynch answered questions on the Prodigy online service, and some news services incorrectly interpreted Lynch's comments as indicating broad bearishness. The Dow fell 21 points the next day, and anecdotal evidence suggested that a lot of sellers believed they were just following Lynch. CAVEAT: Investors often miss the point of Lynch's advice. He famously wrote that culling investment ideas from "hanging out at the mall" beats listening to experts. That is no thumbs-up to betting hunches. The real message is, begin with what you know and dig deeper.<p>
11. BILL GATES
Chairman and CEO, <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft Corp.</b></a>
PROFILE: Gates's near hammerlock on the personal-computer industry comes from Microsoft's dominance in operating-system software and applications. Now Gates is tooling up Microsoft to expand into broadcast media and financial services. POWER MOVE: When Microsoft can't compete with an innovative product, it buys its competitor, as it did with Intuit, the maker of Quicken personal-finance software.Gates's clout is best seen in the behavior of others: The rest of the computer software industry continues to consolidate in order to defend itself from and do battle with Microsoft. Last year, Novell acquired WordPerfect, and Apple, IBM, and Motorola dragged one another into a pact to prevent Microsoft from dominating the industry completely. Microsoft is the main reason many once high-flying software stocks, like Lotus, have faltered. CAVEAT: The Justice Department recently settled an antitrust case with Microsoft on cushy terms, but that doesn't mean it isn't watching the company's moves closely. A new inquiry stalled the Intuit deal.<p>
12. CHARLES S. SANFORD JR.
Chief executive officer, Bankers Trust New York Corp.
PROFILE: Heads and molds the most aggressive proprietary bank trading operation in the world--one with a $54 billion war chest. Most top U.S. banks allocate 1 percent of total assets to their own trading; Bankers Trust, the nation's seventh-largest bank, devotes 50 percent and has been called the world's largest hedge fund. Bankers Trust is most famous, of course, as the cutting-edge house for derivatives, the No. 1 dirty word for 1994. POWER MOVE: Bankers' derivatives have changed the face of high finance. And no, Sanford isn't going to stop creating and pushing derivatives just because Bankers has taken heat for increasing market volatility. The firm has 300 derivatives specialists. CAVEAT: Last year, Gibson Greetings and Procter & Gamble claimed Bankers Trust didn't disclose derivatives risks that cost them some $180 million. The bad experience, together with government charges and lawsuits, have dampened the appetites of derivatives users. For now.<p>
13. GEORGE SOROS
Chief executive officer, Soros Fund Management
PROFILE: With $10 billion in assets--including the $3.7 billion Quantum Fund, the biggest and baddest of hedge funds--Soros is able to borrow and bet $100 million in markets ranging from gold to stocks to, most notoriously, currencies. POWER MOVE: Surely you remember 1992, when Soros pushed the fund's limits selling British pounds and Italian lira. The play netted Quantum $2 billion and sent tremors through European central banks. The British central bank devoted $15 billion, or half its foreign-currency reserves, to fighting Soros's gambit. More recently, news that Soros would acquire British real estate caused a rally on the London stock market. CAVEAT: Win big, lose big. Twice last year Quantum lost at least $400 million in the debt markets, wagering incorrectly that the dollar would rise against the yen. Soros bets so much money that Quantum can play only the biggest markets, currencies and bonds. Lately these markets have humbled even him.<p>
14. JOHN NEFF
Manager, <a name="FUND:VWNDX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VWNDX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard/Windsor Fund</b></a>
PROFILE: The only member of the triumvirate of legendary money managers (Peter Lynch and Sir John Templeton are the others) still running a fund on a day-to-day basis. For his Windsor Fund he favors what he calls "woebegone, misunderstood, and overlooked" issues. Over the last 30 years, his returns have doubled those of the yardstick S&P index. Neff is distinctly contrarian: He buys stocks on their way down and sells into rallies. His reputation and an $11 billion kitty give him clout. Neff invests in few stocks, but he buys big. Last year Windsor held a scant 72 stocks. POWER MOVE: Neff made Seagate Technology a darling among tech investors when he identified the company as a stellar performer in the cutthroat computer-parts business. Neff got in at $16; last year the stock rose to $28. CAVEAT: Neff has announced that he'll retire at the end of 1995. His successor will be Charles Freeman, who has spent 25 years with Neff and promises not to alter the course of the fund.<p>
15. MARK HOLOWESKO
Director of Global Equity Research
Templeton Worldwide, Inc.
PROFILE: Former apprentice, now heir, to the legendary Sir John Templeton, the 81-year-old mutual fund pioneer and market seer. Holowesko, 35, took over top duties at three Templeton funds in 1987, and today directly manages $16 billion worth of Templeton money dedicated to international investing. Templeton funds outshine most other international funds, and they do so, according to Morningstar, with less risk. Their success invites imitators. Holowesko didn't lead the charge into international investing; Templeton did. But Holowesko does seem to have absorbed all his master's wisdom. POWER MOVE: Holowesko anticipated the troubles that beset many international markets last year and quietly pulled back. He thus spared his shareholders the rout other international funds experienced. CAVEAT: The Holowesko/Templeton approach invests for the long end of the long run. Shorter-sighted investors ought to look elsewhere.<p>
16. JOHN MERIWETHER
Partner, Long Term Capital Management
PROFILE: Meriwether emerged as a formidable trader while running the bond desk at Salomon Brothers. There he assembled a brain trust that applied cutting-edge mathematical modeling to bond arbitrage. When he left Salomon in 1991 to start his own hedge-fund firm (taking some of his best people with him), he found backers who put $1.25 billion worth of faith in him. Meriwether's team is  finally kicking into gear (it entered the fray last February), and it may be even brainier than the one at Solly. Wall Street has a keen interest in Meriwether's fortunes. POWER MOVE: Meriwether is missed by Salomon, whose trading operations lost big in the first half of 1994. Meriwether's company, on the other hand, was reportedly up 15 percent in its first six months. CAVEAT: Firm traders who strike out on their own often learn they need the information and financial resources of a big firm to succeed. Meriwether may miss Salomon's fearsome reputation, as well as its capital. And Solly's bond desk could come to crowd him: It's headed by a former Meriwether disciple.<p>
17. JAMES BURTON
Chief executive officer, California Public Employees' Retirement System
PROFILE: Since October, the head of the nation's largest pension fund, with more than $80 billion in assets and more than a million members. CalPERS, more than any other pension fund, has made itself heard and feared by corporate boards. The fund is also the lead voice in the activist Council of Institutional Investors, which together represents $800 billion of uppity money. POWER MOVE: In recent years the fund has been instrumental in giving the boot to CEOs at Westinghouse Electric, Eastman Kodak, and IBM and has also pushed other Fortune 500s for more board accountability. You could do worse, by the way, than to put your money where CalPERS's is: A recent study showed that shares of companies that came under strong pressure from CalPERS have done more than twice as well as the S&P 500 since 1990. CAVEAT: Some CalPERS trustees want Burton to be less aggressive on corporate governance and spend more time on administration of the fund.<p>
18. KING FAHD
King of Saudi Arabia
PROFILE: Sits atop one quarter of the world's proven oil reserves, which gives him the most clout in OPEC. Saudi oil production is a key factor in the price of all the world's energy sources. Oil demand is expected to rise by 1.5 million barrels a day in 1995, while production holds about steady. That should send prices steadily upward. OPEC wants to raise oil prices gradually to $21 a barrel (the price is currently stagnant at about $17), and only Saudi Arabia has the will and the might to rein in production. POWER MOVE: Saudi Arabia spearheaded the November 1994 agreement to freeze OPEC output, the announcement of which immediately sent oil prices and energy stocks up. CAVEAT: OPEC agreements usually fail. Not only do cash-strapped member states cheat, non-OPEC-member oil producers are happy to rush into the breach. Cheap oil and Gulf War bills have left the Saudis cash strapped, and only a rise in price will restore their full clout.<p>
19. DAVID KESSLER
Commissioner, U.S. Food and Drug Administration
PROFILE: Some call him Lord of the Label. As Kessler himself points out, the FDA's jurisdiction covers "25 cents on every consumer dollar." Under Kessler, FDA injunctions have tripled and prosecutions have doubled. POWER MOVE: Approval of drugs and medical devices--and even such things as recommended changes in the national diet--can send stocks soaring. Approval denials or warnings of dangers in drugs and food can spell disaster. An arthritis medication from a hot, small company called Greenwich Pharmaceuticals failed review by the agency in September 1993, and shares in Greenwich now trade at less than a penny. In December 1994, U.S. Bioscience shares dropped 60 percent on news that the company's chemotherapy drug Ethyol didn't pass muster with the FDA. CAVEAT: Kessler was a Bush appointee, but Republicans are calling for his head. They bewail FDA overregulation and overreaching and have already moved to block new FDA regulations.<p>
20. DON PHILLIPS
Publisher, Morningstar Mutual Funds
PROFILE: Publisher of the most widely read and quoted mutual fund guide--the bible of financial planners and the publication most hotly in demand at public libraries. Morningstar's 60,000 subscribers hang their fund selection on its five-star rating system. Fund managers make pilgrimages to Morningstar's Chicago office to plead their case. In nearly 100 speeches a year, Phillips thrills investors and financial planners with mutual fund advice, and you can bet they act on it. Phillips is also the press's favorite source; a quote from him is found in virtually every mutual fund story. POWER MOVE: A critical word in Phillips's own Morningstar commentary can send a fund running for cover. Just ask the folks at the troubled Pilgrim Group. They sued (and lost) and later sold off most of their funds. CAVEAT: Five-star ratings don't predict the future, and the Morningstar system can't foresee which sectors are about to explode. It missed big swings in emerging-market funds.<p>
21. JESSE HELMS
Senator from North Carolina; chairman of Senate Foreign Relations Committee
PROFILE: Helms's new chairmanship makes him not just the most prominent politician to publicly menace the president, but also the most powerful American on foreign policy outside the executive branch. The markets are bound to be a little nervous about this. Resolve in foreign policy is one of their favorite measures of American stability, and if Helms keeps fussing with Clinton, it may give the impression the U.S. is a house hopelessly divided. An isolationist, a hawk, and a loner even among Republicans, Helms will keep on dividing even if the GOP gains the White House in '96. POWER MOVE: Following the midterm Republican victories, Helms declared to Secretary of State Warren Christopher that the U.S. must adjust the "broad focus of [its] foreign policies." CAVEAT: Helms is going to be Helms, but Richard Lugar, the last Republican chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee and a believer in bipartisanship, now ranks second on the committee. He may welcome dialogue with the Clinton administration and diffuse Helms's railing.<p>
22. JAMES DUGAN
Chief executive officer, Swiss Bank Corporation
PROFILE: Architect of one of the most sophisticated, well-rounded proprietary trading organizations in the world, a powerhouse in foreign exchange and interest rate derivatives. In 1992, Dugan merged his firm O'Connor & Associates, the most technologically adept player in Chicago's futures and options exchanges, into the huge Swiss Bank Corp. That brought the best of American trading culture to the staid but deep-pocketed banking giant. POWER MOVE: After acquiring O'Connor, Swiss Bank rose from tenth-largest among currency and option traders worldwide to first. (You were wondering who made the most money rendering pointless the Fed's latest attempt to prop up the dollar?) Says a competitor, "We only see a third of what Swiss Bank does. Even that makes us nervous." CAVEAT: The Swiss Bank/O'Connor union started a rush on Chicago-based trading firms. S.G. Warburg and NationsBank have acquired top-flight firms to compete.<p>
23. HERBERT ALLEN
Partner, Allen & Company
PROFILE: Investment banker to the stars, or at least to the star makers. Allen has helped orchestrate a great number of large media deals, including ones involving Sony, Time Warner, and Matsushita. Investment bankers don't usually play well in Hollywood, but Allen, once the head of Columbia Pictures, knows L.A.'s deal makers. Now his Rolodex is expanding with the rise in interest in multimedia. POWER MOVE: Allen throws an annual party/retreat for corporate leaders; last year's attracted the likes of Warren Buffett, Rupert Murdoch, and Bill Gates. Allen can assemble a giant or take it apart: He advised QVC in its failed bid for Paramount in 1993 and today is helping Viacom, which won the Paramount deal, shed Madison Square Garden and the New York Rangers and Knicks. CAVEAT: Watching the media sector is easy, because the media are self-obsessed. Don't rush in just because an entertainment deal makes the front page.<p>
24. CHARLES I. CLOUGH JR.
Chief investment strategist, <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.</b></a>
PROFILE: Twelve thousand Merrill Lynch retail brokers hear from him first thing every morning--just before they call you. Clough digests the best thinking of Merrill's army of analysts for the nation's biggest network of brokers. His insights come to Merrill's brokers--the firm calls them financial consultants, by the way--via frequent computer bulletins, bullhorn announcements, weekly newsletters, and Prism, Merrill's internal television network, which is broadcast directly to 500 offices in 31 countries. If you sell for Merrill, you know the man's face. POWER MOVE: Merrill Lynch holds $536 billion in client assets (about $20 billion more than the GNP of Canada), and Clough helps move a lot of it. Last year, he was keen on so-called deep cyclicals, such as stocks that rise with commodity prices. The sector performed well. CAVEAT: Clough's tips travel through the firm's large and diverse retail network; it might be old news by the time it gets to you. <p>
25. JIANG ZEMIN
President, People's Republic of China
PROFILE: Since March, Jiang has been the official leader of the world's most populous country and of an economy growing at warp speed. Though Jiang has more official titles than any Chinese official since Mao, he won't ascend to real power unless he can consolidate the powers now held by China's supreme ruler, the blind and aging Deng Xiaoping. So far, Jiang is the odds-on favorite to follow Deng. China's place as rising star in the world economy has been built on its prowess as a cheap manufacturer for export and as a magnet for foreign capital: China is currently a favorite destination for emerging-market mutual funds, whose managers expect the country to dominate the 21st century. POWER MOVE: Jiang has consolidated his power by placing allies in high government and party posts. CAVEAT: China's recent history has been tumultuous and brutal. An Institute of Strategic Studies report concluded that if Deng dies soon, the country could deteriorate into "warlordism." ------------------
See "Market Movers, Part Two" for completion of article.<p>

