				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-The Bear</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994 <p>Worth magazine/Feature  <p> THE BEAR <p>His intellectual and literary gifts are the envy of Wall Street.His track record is another story. Will the markets ever seethe world the way James Grant does?  <p> By Donald Katz  <p> At 6:36 on a midsummer morning, James Grant aims his donnishhalf-smile in the direction of the hosts of CNN's Business Morningshow. Each week the 48-year-old financial prognosticator andeditor of Grant's Interest Rate Observer arrives at the CNN studioswith every intention of adorning the morning's price quotes witha bit of the intellectual dazzle he thinks the study of marketsdeserves. But somehow the drill always turns out to be the same. <p> "Do you think long-term interest rates are going higher?" aCNN inquisitor with a British accent asks Grant when the redlight goes on.  <p> "I do," says Grant, who has said precisely this for all buta few weeks of a nearly 14-year decline in global interest rates. <p> "By how much?" the Brit bores in.  <p> "Yes," Grant says, trying to wrap his friendliest smile aroundhis long nose.  <p> Grant appears on CNN each Thursday, and each Wednesday a youngCNN producer will phone him at his Wall Street office. Grantwill suggest questions for the hosts to lob his way. Perhapsthey could ask him to expand on the larger meaning of surgingLondon futures prices for Baltic Freight Index contracts. Theycould ask about those Swedish government-debt instruments thatare so technically and morally corrupt that even Swedish CEOsrefuse to buy them. Or how about that American institution whoseleaders have so hollowed out the financial corpus that the companynow resembles some cavernous fiscal bedsore?  <p> Invariably, though, the on-air talk is reduced to Grant's viewson prices and money rates per se -- not about how these ratesand prices reflect as-yet-unidentified trends or offer a runningcalibration of the human folly that has characterized financialevents since the days of President Grover Cleveland, a memberof James Grant's short and quirky list of American heroes.  <p> Over 3,800 well-placed readers of the twice-monthly Grant'sInterest Rate Observer pay an annual $495 for access to JamesGrant's bloody-minded opinions, his particular view of history,his fluent prose, and for predictions about the direction ofprices and rates that have often -- quite often, in fact -- beenwrong. Grant is the quintessential bear of these times and financialmarkets.  <p> "My question, Mr. Grant, is this," said a man who approachedhim after an investment conference last year. "Have you everin your life been right about anything?"  <p> But Grant is that rare Wall Street presence whose appeal greatlytranscends his track record. His financial history, Money ofthe Mind: Borrowing and Lending in America From the Civil Warto Michael Milken, was reviewed by a Nobel laureate in economics.He is written about in contexts shared by Ivy League economists,World Bank leaders, and investment pros like Warren Buffett.Whenever "Who's the smartest guy on Wall Street?" discussionscommence, Grant's name is on the short list -- with an asterisktethered to a note about what a different sort of Wall Streetcharacter he is.  <p> There is currently a bull market in Grant's notoriety and inthe power of his opinions. Constantly rising interest rates during1994 and a bond market posting the worst total returns sincethe late 1960s have helped Grant -- however belatedly -- appearremarkably prescient of late. Grant turned bullish on the coffee-beanmarket in January, when the price hovered below 75 cents a pound,and by September coffee had touched $2.70 a pound. He similarlypredicted the escalation in wheat prices, and he suggested buyingsilver at $4 an ounce just before it moved to $5. The model portfolioGrant constructed for Wall Street Week With Louis Rukeyser (Grant'slist was full of short sales, stocks he was betting would declinein price) is outperforming those of the pack comprising the show'smany stellar guests.  <p> And yet, to the members of the virtual private club that surroundshim -- Wall Street intellectuals, fiscal curmudgeons, bearishromantics, dedicated short-sellers, and other "financial typeswith attitudes," as Grant describes the members of his circle-- it is only his crusade that truly matters.  <p> The work requires steadfast vigilance. In the pages of his "journalfor the age of monetary upset and volatility," as Grant calledthe Interest Rate Observer when he introduced it in 1983, helabors to uncover documents that indicate the presence of "overfedand overpampered" Wall Streeters who "think of themselves notas mere mortals, but as the people of . . . Morgan Stanley."On behalf of avid readers who inhabit the senior stations atinstitutions such as Morgan Stanley, he habitually smokes outmembers of "the banking classes" who would think themselves bettercapitalists than they truly are. ("Bankers Trust," Grant oncequipped, "is an oxymoron.") It was Grant who pointed out thatfinancial professionals of the late 1980s sent credit cards topet shar-pei puppies in Virginia and extended easy credit to11-year-old schoolboys in Maryland. He railed on elegantly aboutyoung "children of the bull market" on Wall Street whose absenceof memory allowed them to believe that the fat times would neverend, and he has persistently criticized federal governments hailingback to the Depression for subsidizing or "socializing" the risksinherent in lending money.  <p> In conversation, formal speeches, television interviews, andin print, Grant rarely fails to mention his favorite thesis:that over the course of a half century, an ever-expanding seaof easily accessed credit has undermined the financial superstructureof the economy, while more lately creating a genre of cowboycapitalist devoid of restraint or any hint of the honorable sobrietythat characterized the sorts of long-dead financiers Grant admires.The cowboys and the government have conspired to obscure financialjustice for years, Grant says, though this has never stoppedhim from predicting that law and order would eventually return,and that interest rates and the price of hard assets ("stuff,"as he puts it) would finally rise as the value of financial assetswould finally fall.  <p> Now Grant is on a roll, proclaiming in print and on the airthat the financial prosperity of the past dozen years is "notover, but is certainly in the process of being interrupted."He believes rates will continue to go up because of old-fashionedinflation, which he sees weighing heavily on the economy by theend of 1994 or in 1995.  <p> During his CNN appearance, Grant affably steers the conversationtoward recent developments that appear to support his generaltheme. The "pleasurable rhythms of the bull market" are now fadingaway, he observes. No longer is it axiomatic that interest rateswill go down and stocks will go up.  <p> "There's been a great financial epiphany," Grant tells the hosts."Everyone saw that rates would forever fall. Now those peopleare reappraising things. Aluminum is more expensive; copper,too. Look at the price of crude oil. The world is reflexively-- "  <p> "You actually watch these kinds of things," the British interviewercuts in. "I mean you watch aluminum. You even watch . . . what?. . . the market in paperboard . . . cah-tons!"  <p> "Well, yes," says Grant, who had indeed devoted the front pageof a recent Grant's Interest Rate Observer to a weirdly interestingpiece about the price of linerboard and pharmaceutical blisterpackaging. "Everyone has to do something."  <p> At this, the show's two presenters begin to guffaw.  <p> "There is news," Grant continues, "that does not fit into thestandard analytical grooves of Wall Street."  <p>   <p> In the spirit of skepticism of the "lumpen consensus opinionof the moment," as he once put it in his newsletter, Grant wrotein early 1984 that the future junk-bond king Michael Milken andthe whole financial junkyard of Drexel Burnham Lambert, Milken'semployer, were responsible for entertaining but very bad investmentproducts. Grant reiterated this supposition in no fewer than65 subsequent pieces of anti-Drexel investigative journalismand acerbic commentary over the next six years, supplementinghis lonely crusade with appearances on the MacNeil/Lehrer NewsHour and Nightline whenever he could wangle an invitation. Grantrode the wicked witch of Drexel like some sermonizing insecton the firm's mighty back, until the witch finally died.  <p> Grant turned out to be right about Drexel and about many ofthe company's junk bonds, but being right six years early inmoney and markets is very much like being wrong. And one of theabiding ironies of James Grant's life in light of his chosencalling and penchant for orthodoxy is that he can only barelystand being wrong. "If it all works out and I'm right, there'sa quiet sense of gratification," Grant admits after the CNN show."But the feeling is wholly out of proportion to the monstrous,gnawing feelings of inadequacy that go along with getting itwrong."  <p> Only Grant's colleagues at his newsletter and a few membersof Grant's inner circle of brilliant financial friends know thattheir otherwise jocular and easily self-effacing friend willsit alone in the middle of the night if he turns out to be wrong,twisting the proverbial knife himself. "You could not have morecomplex case material than Jim Grant," a senior Morgan Bank bondtrader says of his friend as Grant listens in on an extensionone afternoon in New York. "This is a man capable of seeing allthings from all sides at the time and yet doesn't have the wisdomto pronounce things that way."  <p> "It's true," Grant says softly, grinning away, the receivercovered by his fist. "This is true."  <p> Now and again, when he wrote the "Current Yield" column forBarron's in the late '70s and early '80s, Grant was notably rightabout securities that were unworthy of the term. He warned readersabout the quality of Washington Public Power Supply System municipalbonds -- the infamous "Whoops" bonds of the early 1980s -- before$2.25 billion worth of the issues went into default. Later, Grantwas right about the rolling real estate recessions that spreadfrom Texas in 1985 to Arizona in 1988 to New England in 1989and most recently to California. He was also right about DonaldTrump and the Reichmanns of Olympia & York -- though, as withMilken, he was early on those calls.  <p> Grant has also been right in innumerable microeconomic analysesof specific markets, companies, and securities. But none of thiswill erase the fact that his bearish predictions were systematicallytrampled under the hooves of the bulls for much of a decade.He augured inflation and the "low estate" of paper assets asthe rest of the world reveled in a lucrative frenzy of ever-lowerinterest rates and increasingly valuable paper. He has so oftensaid that the price of gold and interest rates are going up thatinterviewers like Rukeyser tend to chortle affectionately whenthey hear it. In 1991, after a year Grant calls his "genius phase"-- when all of the things he'd been predicting about economicgrowth, interest rates, and falling equity prices finally cameto pass -- he was whipsawed by a countervailing "moron phase,"a "predictive Waterloo" that ended up costing him a tremendousamount of his own money.  <p> Two years earlier, Grant had sold the home in Brooklyn thathoused his young family -- a wife and four children. He tookthe proceeds and in 1990 began to sell short some of the stocksthat he had been criticizing. He sold short International LeaseFinance Corp., an airplane-leasing firm built on financial air.He also shorted Chemical Bank, Citibank, First Executive Bank,and Columbia Savings (always being careful to disclose his personalfinancial moves to readers). And then he waited for his geniusperiod to set in.  <p> Just as Grant had forecast, the stock market went into verticaldecline. Television crews crowded into his office seeking furthernuggets of brilliant prophecy, and the Grant family, he recalls,"happily adjusted to a new level of liquidity."  <p> For much of a year Grant wrote essays that proved with technicalcertainty that the stock market could not go back up. The lastof them appeared just days before a six-week spike in the summerof 1991 that erased all his personal profits from the short positionsand the profits from the sale of his house, too.   <p> Grant says he entered a period of psychological decline thatincluded weeks of dedicated sulking broken by bouts of more severeself-immolation over having been wrong. His newsletter's subscriptiongrowth suddenly ceased, and there ensued a "great tailing offof returned phone calls from contacts and the diminished presenceof television crews waiting at the bottom of the elevator." <p> Throughout his moron phase and the bull run in 1992 and 1993,Grant tried to detail his analytical failings. It was evidenceof another characteristic of his that is unusual among thosein the business of understanding markets: He prefers to admithis mistakes.  <p> During the midsummer of 1991, the depths of the moron phase,Grant was considering desperate moves -- he thought about becominga money manager.  <p>   <p> Before getting to know Grant, I had long marveled from afarat the antique bearing of the man. With his red tie decoratedwith little bears, the hair invariably askew so that wisps surgeforward across his temple -- and with the stems of his glassesriding high above his ears -- Grant often looks like one of thoseOxbridge twits named Nigel or Jeremy who haunt the eating clubsof British academe. Six feet five, lean, and with an aquilineface, Grant has at other times reminded me of a Dickensian chinafigurine in some old curiosity shop.   <p> The physical aspect, the older and elegant prose, the seemingintellectual imprisonment in an economic world formed by orthodoxiesforgotten by everyone else but him -- all of it had caused meto wonder if the whole persona wasn't somewhat contrived.  <p> Grant's heroes are men like George F. Baker, the hidebound turn-of-the-centurybanker who always got his loans repaid, and Grover Cleveland,champion of a minimalist government that suits Grant's own libertarianleanings. It was Cleveland who brought back the gold standard-- that most noble of monetary systems, according to Grant --and brought it back long enough to cause a harrowing recessionin 1893. Grant's paramount literary hero is the great WalterBagehot, the writer and editor of The Economist more than 100years ago, who believed that aspects of "mind and character"were just as essential as numbers to understanding business andfinance.   <p> "People don't cultivate memory because, by and large, it hasbeen proven unprofitable," Grant says. "I think that John Reedof Citibank would have been a much happier person in 1990 and1991 [when the bank lost a billion dollars, largely as a resultof ill-advised loans] if he had a clue what had gone on in Dallasreal estate as recently as 1985. And yet the fact is, if youare running a Wall Street trading desk during a bull market,you want traders who are young enough not to be intimidated overthe losses of 1974. Nineteen-year-olds, after all, make muchbetter infantrymen than soldiers who are 35."  <p> The Grant's Interest Rate Observer offices are located at 30Wall Street, a building that until recently housed a branch officeof the Chase Manhattan Bank. The street-level windows were filledwith signs: "Borrow at Prime ... Home Equity Line of Credit ...No Credit History? No Problem." Officers of the Chase branchonce asked Grant to deliver one of his provocative speeches atan executive conference, but the Chase head-office guys foundout they were about to issue an honorarium to a man who has consistentlypointed out that bankers who borrow money at 2 or 3 percent andinvest it at 4 percent are not necessarily talented or even halfsmart. The invitation was withdrawn.  <p> Grant and the publisher of his journal, Jeremy Diamond, sometimestake their mitts and a ball and descend six floors to Wall Street,there to play catch beneath the flags and austere cornices aspassersby look on with either curiosity or annoyance. Grant usedto box for exercise at a nearby gym. "It wasn't yet in vogueon Wall Street when I started," he says. "I eventually gave itup because it hurt." But he still works out every morning, andup close an aura of easy athleticism and high energy mutes thepotted-plant-from-Oxfordshire courtliness conjured by his mossbackpronouncements. ("Every debt is ultimately paid," begins oneoft-repeated axiom, "if not by the debtor, then eventually bythe creditor.")  <p> Copies of the Milwaukee Business Journal, Automotive News, SupermarketNews, Oil & Gas Journal, Journal of Commerce, French economicjournals, and dozens of other periodicals cover almost everysurface not occupied by a computer or a laser printer insideGrant's offices. Books about how to quantify risk, about bonds,about foreign banks, about central banks, about baseball, arestrewn everywhere. Near Grant's own desk in the back corner ofthe main room hangs a picture of the writer E.B. White and anotherphotograph of a racehorse that the ever-bearish investor SethKlarman named Money of the Mind, after Grant's book. On the floorin the main room sits a three-foot-high stuffed bear.  <p> Grant composes and incessantly recomposes and polishes all ofthe 7,000 words in a typical issue of his magazine (newsletterbeing a term proscribed inside the company as indicative of "theHulbert crowd" of stock pickers and market timers). He regularlywrites through entire weekends.   <p> "Paid-up subscribers," as Grant constantly refers to his favoritecontacts, are forever faxing Grant underlined prospectuses withnotes that say, "Have you seen this one?" or "Can you believethis?" They will call him up: "Listen to what this dumb kid onthe trading desk said to me today."   <p> Though the Grant's subscription list includes just about everyhedge-fund jockey in the race, most of the chief traders insideevery money house, and nearly every speculator described as an"investor" in newspaper articles -- from the Tisches to PaulTudor Jones to the Soros gang to Grant's first subscriber, theshort-seller and pundit Jim Rogers -- Grant draws a great dealof intellectual sustenance from individuals who are somewhatless well-known. He is always ascribing to his readers the mostskeptical and prescient views: "When Jack A. Sullivan, a paid-upsubscriber in San Francisco, mentioned that he was accumulatinga short position in some of the Eurobonds of the Reichmanns'flagship company, Olympia & York Developments Ltd, we pausedto reflect on the state of the world."  <p> Grant also enhances the clubby sensibility by occasionally writingprofiles of some of his favorite Wall Street rogues and geniuses.Early on, he wrote a piece about the late financial journalistMaxwell Newton, son of an Australian plumber, a Cambridge grad,and the dispenser of brilliant opinions even more tendentiousthan Grant's from the unlikely pulpit of the business sectionof the New York Post. Newton hated his Wall Street enemies. Grantwrote lovingly that Newton "calls the markets as he sees them."Newton was a Grant's kind of guy.  <p> Grant often writes about Joe Rosenberg, portfolio manager forthe Tisch family, who for years has tried to teach Grant to,as Grant interprets, "have opinions at extremes and wait forextreme moments." Rosenberg and Grant regularly talk on the phoneabout the state of the markets and the world.   <p> Grant schmoozes frequently with the "intellectual spectacle"that is Paul J. Isaac, formerly chief economist at Mabon Securities,a man who somehow reads $45,000 worth of financial periodicalsand newspaper subscriptions. Like many in Grant's circle, Isaacis a closet hyperintellectual and a dedicated dilettante. Grantwill send over a document like a legal firm's internal briefingon changes in bankruptcy law. Then they get on the phone to chortletogether at laws that skew the symmetry of financial processesand undermine economic justice.   <p> A tone of commiseration marks many of Grant's conversationsduring a day. The bears for whom Grant serves as den intellectualmoan about lofty markets. The kingpin nerds and in-house professorsof markets speak to him of absurdities only they are smart enoughto discern. And the paid-up subscribers phone in with news ladenwith irony: "Did you see that guy [Michael] Vranos, the Kiddermortgage-bond group chief quoted in the Journal? 'We're not tryingto outsmart the smart guys,' he said. 'We're trying to sell bondsto the dumb guys!'" And Grant, as he does so many times duringhis long workdays, will start to laugh.  <p> Grant used to walk down to the graveyard of Trinity Church atthe corner of Broadway and Wall to sit with the young Yalie short-sellerJim Chanos, or one of the other bears, wondering for hours whatwas holding the market up. One day he and Chanos wandered overto the office of Ed Levy, a wise money manager and paid-up subscriber."When will it go down, Ed?" they asked.  <p> "When you stop asking," came Levy's reply.  <p> "That the financial markets will ever stop going up is thismagazine's leading unfulfilled prophecy," Grant wrote as thebull market continued to explode. "But we live in hope."  <p> Ed Yardeni, chief economist at C.J. Lawrence/Deutsche Bank Securities.and an early Grant's subscriber, once noted to InstitutionalInvestor that Grant was possessed of "a tremendous sense of history,and he's done good work reminding us of historical precedence... . But there's zealotry in him too. In a world created by JimGrant, there would be no financial intermediaries, no debt." <p> "If there were financial intermediaries," Grant responds quicklyupon being reminded of the characterization, "they wouldn't hireMr. Ed Yardeni.... But then Ed's been right a lot more than I'vebeen right. He's been bullish for ten years. 'Buy stocks andbonds. Buy stocks and bonds. Buy stocks and bonds.' Way to gothere, Ed."  <p> Before he grabs his gym bag and baseball mitt and heads towardWall Street, the subway, and his home in Brooklyn Heights, Iask Grant if a certain loathing of those financial types whohave backed into success since the early 1980s serves to inspirehis crusades -- if his inspiration is, at heart, less cerebralthan emotional, the most prominent emotion perhaps being envy. <p> "I don't know if it's envy," Grant says without defensiveness."But whatever it is, I do feel the adrenaline stir when I reada Morgan Stanley prospectus. Unlike most people who take dealsapart on Wall Street, I am not beholden to them. In fact, I believeit is incumbent upon the Grant's organization to deny MorganStanley the benefit of the doubt precisely because they are MorganStanley. So they do get extra scrutiny. We expect more of them,and -- more or less -- they always fail to deliver.  <p> "Most of the work of Wall Street is simply getting business,"Grant continues. "The people in the research end and the thinkingand explaining end of the trade are subordinated to the underwritingand sales effort. They are out writing about companies that thehouse hopes to enlist for a future equity offer. It's not a conflictof interest at all. It's a unity of interest. There's no conflict.They all do the same thing. The Street is in the business oftrying to sell you something." With that, Grant grins and boundstoward the elevator and down to Wall Street.  <p>   <p> The son and grandson of musicians, Jim Grant was a particularlygifted French horn player as a young boy in suburban Long Island.In high school he was invited to play classical pieces with collegestudents, but issues having to do with competition, authority,and the hierarchies of middle-class suburban life led Grant toquit school and his music after only a semester at Ithaca College.  <p> Grant left his eyeglasses on long enough to memorize the visionchart before it was his turn at the navy induction center, andsoon he was a gunner's mate on the carrier Hornet. He spent 1964watching "LBGBs" ("Little bitty gook boats. . . You have to rememberwhat year it was") off the coast of Vietnam. Grant was not amalleable and, therefore, not a particularly successful sailor.The experience seems to have helped form Grant's determinationto swim against the tide.  <p> Grant went to Indiana University after his discharge, one ofthe best places for an accomplished young musician returningto his horn. But he discovered 20 other brilliant French hornplayers there who hadn't taken two years off from practicingthree hours a day. So he studied economics and went on to furtherwork in the social sciences at Columbia University in New Yorkinstead.  <p> Grant became a reporter at the Baltimore Sun after that, atfirst writing obits and police news. Eventually, drawing uponvocabulary learned as a clerk at a New York brokerage house beforecollege, he joined the business section.   <p> In 1975, Grant was hired by the arch-conservative Barron's editorialistRobert Bleiberg, who wanted someone to write his column whenhe was away. Bleiberg, now retired, recalls that it was not easyto find a man of Grant's age who agreed with his own reactionarypolitical views in 1975, but Grant had lately chosen to becomea traveler of the radical right wing as an antistatist libertarian-- "if not for intellectual reasons," he now says, "then forthose glandular and hormonal reasons that cause the need to mortifyone's parents." Grant recalls a few months when he was a liberalDemocrat -- he even voted for Eugene McCarthy in 1968 -- butsoon thereafter he "moved off into the counterrevolution."  <p> Grant eventually edited the Barron's Capital Markets section,which included the "Current Yield" column. He quit the weeklyamid an editorial schism that saw Alan Abelson emerge as thetop dog instead of Bleiberg in 1983, and he invested a portionof the $75,000 in his Dow Jones profit-sharing plan in the launchof the Interest Rate Observer.   <p> A few months later the $75,000 was gone. "And nobody calledme back either," Grant recalls. "I was no longer Grant of Barron's.I was just Grant." His first book, a biography of Bernard Baruch,the early 20th-century financier and friend-to-the-powerful,appeared and disappeared like "the figurative brick in a lake."Grant, already a vociferous critic of easy credit, was soon runninghis business on his Visa card.  <p> As Grant's prose became sharper and more entertaining by themonth, he brilliantly seized the tips of innumerable financialicebergs, often impaling himself in the process. He saw earlierthan almost everyone else the folly in the new junk bonds floatedby companies that admitted they couldn't pay interest unlessassets were sold off. But he didn't realize that the assets inquestion had often been priced and sales had been arranged beforehand."This is the top," Grant crowed after reading the prospectusfor one junk-bond flotation.   <p> But the top was years away.   <p> Several times in the late 1980s, Grant appeared on the MacNeil/LehrerNews Hour. He was ever erudite and charming, but he was therein some part because nobody else would publicly say that MikeMilken was selling bad goods, or that any minute the "tide ofdebt would go out," that inflation would return, and that thestock market tumble. Conservative though his politics were, Grantalso blasted away at Ronald Reagan and supply-siders who wouldbelieve, as Grant expressed it, that "human behavior is governedby the marginal tax rate."  <p> Twenty-five calls for interviews came in the day in 1990 thatDrexel finally fell. Trump faltered that same year. The geniusperiod was on. Institutional Investor called him the "interest-rateguru." Subscription orders poured in.   <p> Patricia Kavanagh, Grant's wife, began to notice frosty interchangeswith the spouses of the financial workers who populate BrooklynHeights. She was sure she saw a Drexel executive's wife avoidher one day by crossing to the other side of the street. Kavanaghwas the fashion editor at the Baltimore Sun when she met thevery tall guy from the business section. Since then, she hasbeen an investment banker at Lehman Brothers, the publisher ofher husband's newsletter, a full-time mother, and a pre-med student."And I'm married to someone who actually has a life's work --the study of markets," she says. "Not many people have a life'swork these days."  <p> During the brief genius phase, a man showed up at Grant's officeand said he was a detective with the NYPD. He showed Grant aphoto of a murder victim and reported that Grant's name had beenfound in the dead man's pocket. When Grant later tried to phonethe detective, he was told that no such cop served on the force,leaving Grant to wonder if this was meant as some kind of threator as a comment upon his Cassandra-like point of view.  <p> As a student of financial history, Grant understood that everycycle has its genius. He knew the stories of Henry "Dr. Doom"Kaufman, famous in the '70s as the foreseer of hyperinflationbut fallen from grace by the '80s ("He know the rate," the wagsat Salomon Brothers used to say. "But he don't know the date").He could tell you about Bob Prector, the now out-of-fashion technicalguru of the '80s. He knew all about forgotten seers like ColonelAyers, prognosticator for Cleveland Trust in the 1920s.   <p> And Grant knew about the hubris that can infect those who turnout to be correct about markets. Yet he was still blindsidedwhen his turn came. Shares in Citicorp, which he had denigratedbecause the institution was all but insolvent, levitated fromunder $10 in early 1991 to $17.50 later in the year -- and toover $40 in 1993. Grant's net worth took a mighty hit in theprocess.  <p> Now Grant is writing a book that is essentially an analysisof the bond- and equity-market surge of 1991 to 1993. He writeslate into many nights to find out how it was that the bankerswon. He writes in search of the key to a recession that shouldhave been longer and heavier than it was. The answer, he believes,lies in the intervention of the Fed and in government policiesthat deemed certain institutions too big to fail.   <p> The romantic side of James Grant believes banks should act asthe banks of the days before protective mechanisms muted theirrisk. The capitalist shareholders of banks in pre-Depressiondays were personally responsible to depositors for their losses."There was a certain nobility there," Grant will muse. "And thoseof a romantic temperament want a similar justice today. ShouldCiticorp go from 8 to 40 because the Fed, in conjunction withwhatever fates are operating, gave us a lushly sloped yield curvethat allowed the bank to reliquefy?"  <p> When discussing the democratization of credit, Grant shiftsto something of a high Tory tone. He knows that easy credit hasa great deal to do with the rising standard of living enjoyedby Americans during the middle of the 20th century, and thatcredit extended to working people had a great deal to do withthe rise of the middle class, too. That same democratizationof borrowing led to a popularization of investment opportunitiesduring the 1970s, when previously elite instruments like large-denominationmoney-market instruments were broken down as dollar-a-share moneyfunds for the average investor. And yet he incessantly railsagainst the money pros who created these financial opportunities. <p> "I stand guilty of that," Grant acknowledges. "In part I reactto the trifle of 'democratization.' These latter-day democratizingcapitalists were not like the early people who believed the workingman should get a fair shake with credit. The modern guys crossedthe line of basic prudence. The result was the real estate crack-up.They often landed in the soup, and the taxpayer had to bail themout."  <p> Grant thinks Bill Clinton is a "collectivist" out of envy ofthe rich, and he recently wrote that "unlike greed, which promotesstriving, envy thwarts hard work and is bad for the stomach lining." <p> I ask Grant for a second time if he isn't himself susceptibleto envy -- in particular of his close friends. It's clear thatalmost every member of the Grant's club is much better off thantheir favorite intellectual.  <p> "Well," says Grant considering the idea uncomfortably, "oneis most vulnerable to envy when one is illiquid and needy. Myown low ebb, the summer of 1991, when the liquidity I'd builtfor myself in the sky vanished. . . well. . . "   <p> But the energy returns. "Other than then," he says, "I tendto think the fact that most of the people I associate with havea lot more money is fine. I've made my choice. Being of the well-to-domiddle class means you haven't solved the economic problem. Peopleon Wall Street have solved the economic problem, but I'm notsure they're happier for it. They can't walk into a library andshow their children what they've done."  <p>   <p> Finding someone in the professional world of money who knowsbut does not like and respect James Grant is all but impossible.Noting my frustration with the quest, Grant offered several namesof individuals who might just "hate me or at least think I'man asshole," but they all failed to pan out.   <p> Since Grant's close friends universally hate the way Louis Rukeyserreduces his smartest guest to the role of dancing bear duringGrant's half-dozen annual appearances on Wall Street Week, Ithought the compulsively bullish Rukeyser would offer some jibes."And here he is, Jim Grant," Rukeyser will say with a wink. "Hereto tell you why the world is finally about to come to its sensesand go straight down the tube. Jim, can we at least survive tillFather's Day?"  <p> But Rukeyser likes Grant quite a lot. "Jim has one of the rarestof gifts on Wall Street," he says, "the gift of literacy. Beyondthat, he is a genuine scholar, and beyond that he is a very,very good guy. I would like him just as much if he turned bullish.It would be such a striking event that we would have to declarea half holiday and celebrate."  <p> "There exists a market for bearishness," Grant said one Sundayevening after finishing his day's work. "At times I'm afraidI've filled that niche. As a writer you can get into a rut, andyou can get into a rut of foreboding. It's easy to fall into,and once you've mastered it, it's hard to shake. The truth is,I love blizzards. When promised hurricanes don't materialize,I am very disappointed. I hate ordeals by sunshine, and I preferstorms. I love 95 percent humidity in the summer time, verdantsprings and deep autumns and all sorts of other romantic impulses-- and I don't like it when they take the risk out the marketplace,because that's like living in Florida."  <p> "You're like the German Expressionist of market-watching," Iventured.  <p> "Guess so."  <p> Grant sometimes wakes up in the dead of night to engage in one-manacts of contrition. At 4:15 on a recent morning, he allowed himselfan hour of castigating reflection upon how much more productiveof good prose he must be. He was well into his fourth book aboutfinance, and he was still knocking out his many hundreds of wordsper day. But nevertheless, he sat alone in the predawn quietof his Brooklyn brownstone, pondering the twin tortures of writingfluent prose every day and trying to accurately "recognize change." <p> "There are many ways to be wrong," Grant said. "And one is toimpute one's own idea of rationality into an arena in which theheart and glands have more to say about the outcome than thehead."  <p> Though I once wondered if the provocative presence struck byGrant was an act, it becomes clear up close that the complexpackage of the man is much less the result of an act than ofa set of overpowering impulses connected to ideas and the past.Grant would undoubtedly thrive via a bit more of an act and abit less of the passionately thundering real thing. This is ironic,because though he is a bear and a doubter and a Main Street mistrusterof Wall Street ways, Grant has also brought four children intothe world. He owns a house in New York, the city "of life's finalists,"as he puts it. He tortures himself in the act of writing gorgeoussentences because he believes, in the long run, such things matter.He sits up stewing at night because he thinks that but for abit more concentration and hard work, he will get it absolutelyright.  <p> "What I do think I understand now is that the most powerfulforce in markets is paradox," Grant claimed in triumphant tones."The last shall be first and the first shall be last. Last year'swinners will be this year's losers. The genius shall be the moron.What is seemingly obvious is in fact misunderstood, and whatis hopelessly obscure and improbable will be the next idea thatreally works."   <p> Then he paused. "I also know," he said, "that it's simply notgood enough to be the perennial Jeremiah. At least it will neverbe good enough for me." <p>--------------- <p>Donald Katz is a contributing editor of Worth. His books includeJust Do It and The Big Store.  <p>  <hr>  <p>Copyright 1994 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved.  <p>   <p> 
					</font>
