<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Windfalls</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Windfalls</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
For these eight people, the money came out of nowhere. Now what?<p>By Carla Koehl<p>Easy money. Pennies from heaven. A free lunch. Dumb luck.<p>Whatever you call it, the lure of the windfall is undeniable: A windfall is the stuff of daydreams -- a winning lottery ticket, a flukey business success, a fantastically large legal settlement. It's unearned but, we'd like to think, not undeserved. It's the unexpected payoff for the task of simply being ourselves. <p>Money that is earned, or even desired too strongly, seems scuffed with moral grass stains. We can thank our Puritan heritage for that. Found money, on the other hand, is clean. Consider the word itself. Windfall. It implies a gift from above, brought to earth as if by nature. <p>But money doesn't operate quite the same way in the real world as in the ideal one. What follow are the stories of a nun who won a million dollars and gave it away; a 17-year-old who suddenly finds herself set for life; a couple who say they don't want their $950,000 and never will; and five more. In all, eight portraits of outrageous, improbable, and sometimes confounding good fortune. <p><p>C. JACK DOWDEN, San Diego
Windfall: $21 million<p>In 1991, Dowden, a sales manager for MetWest medical labs, blew the whistle on MetWest; its owner, MetPath; and National Health Laboratories, claiming the labs were charging Medicare and Medicaid millions for unneeded blood tests. When the labs settled with the federal government for $140 million, he got 15 percent.<p>Dowden: "There are a lot of people who'd like to see me gone, out of town. So if I join, like, a country club, I don't like my name to go down on the new members list. And if I make a donation, I do it anonymously. I'm not living my life in order to brag or show off or anything. But I'm definitely living a good life. No, I don't see why I should have any hang-ups about the money. We beat 'em fair and square. <p>"When I first went to the president of the company with this information, he told my boss to make me shut up and do my job. Then I was demoted, and then I quit. I was making around $70,000 a year. Then I made $18,000 a year selling cars for two years. We nearly went broke seeing this thing through. <p>"Now things are a little different: $21 million will do that. I still get up early every morning -- only now, it's to go fishing. I've bought myself a $100,000 fishing boat. I have bought a house that's four times the size of the old one. My wife and I have given most of our clothes and furniture to Goodwill. We're buying all new things. Every time a broker says, 'Why don't you buy $100,000 of this stock?' I say, 'Why? Give me one good reason. Like I need to make more money?' "<p><p>VERONICA BLUME, Barcelona, Spain
Windfall: $275,000<p>Blume, 17, was the 1993 winner of the Ford Models annual Supermodel of the World search. She entered the contest after answering a magazine ad and won a three-year contract with Ford. Since then, she's appeared in Cosmopolitan, Allure, Sports Illustrated's 1994 swimsuit issue, and on the cover of Spanish Elle.<p>Blume: "I used to be monobrow. Monobrow, monobrow. No more monobrow for me. I've been plucked! Totally plucked. But I like it this way. You like it? I like it. My mother is from Uruguay, and she's very dark. People see me with my whole family, they think I'm adopted. Really.<p>"Sometimes, I feel like I'm living in a dream. I'm living with Eileen Ford whenever I'm in New York. She reminds me to sit straight and which fork to use. I open the fridge at her house, and every day there's chicken with no skin and gallons and gallons of water. There are cakes too. That's strange to see, but they're there. You order orange juice at a restaurant, and she says -- very nicely -- 'No, I think you want water.' <p>"The work that I'm doing now -- it doesn't have to take on such a high importance. I mean, I don't have to worry so much about money or the future as a lot of other models do because, I hope, this is just the beginning for me. And it's a great way to begin. Most models finish their careers without ever getting a contract like this, and they don't have much money. <p>"When I was at home, I was always out of money. But now it's different. Now I like running out of money, because I know there's more."<p><p>MARVIN & MATTIE ADAY, Ellis County, Texas
Windfall: $950,000<p>In 1989, Congress designated nearly 17,000 acres of Ellis County, Texas, as the site for the $8.3 billion superconducting supercollider. The Adays were among 166 families forced to relocate. They had to sell nearly half their 750-acre farm to the Department of Energy. The supercollider was canceled last fall.<p>The Adays: "We didn't want the money, we just wanted to keep our home. What do we want with money? Got no grandchildren. Our daughters are full grown. We just wanted to spend the rest of our lives on our farm. <p>"You got to understand. That's my home. I built it, I farmed it, and I raised a family on it. We were very frugal. We had good food, a good house. Mattie, she never had to go out in the field to work or nothing. She kept the house. And now? Now the place is just half torn down. All the bricks is torn off, and the thing is standing out there like a skeleton. I wish they'd just tear it all down. Driving by, it's almost like going past a graveyard. <p>"That land's been in our family more than 100 years, from my grandfather to my father to me. The first 40 acres I bought myself was just $75 an acre. Two years later I bought 50 acres right by it. After World War II, I came back and bought more. You can't go and build a lab on that kind of history ... And look, they didn't after all.<p>"We was mad as H when it happened. I cussed and I prayed and I cussed some more. Now we got the money, we're still mad. Mad and tired. And we still don't want the money."<p><p>SISTER JOSEPHINE CONTRIS, Santa Maria, California
Windfall: $1 million<p>Sister Josephine took the Franciscan Order's vows of poverty when she was 17. In 1992, at age 72, she won the California State Lottery's "Big Spin" game.<p>Contris: "So many people said, 'Why don't you take the money and run?' I said, 'What do I want to run for? For that matter, where would I run to?'<p>"I became a nun more than 50 years ago. That means money, possessions, everything belongs to the community. So that's where the lottery winnings went. I turned the money over to our superior. <p>"You think I'm crazy. But I'm not. I learned that the money from people buying lottery tickets went to help the school system, so I thought, great, I can do that. Have a little fun gambling and have it go to a good cause: the schools. <p>"We were very poor growing up. During the Depression we were nine children. My father and my oldest brother worked in a lumber mill. We didn't have anything. We barely had full meals. Then, I would have been happy to get some money. But now that I've got it, all I want to do is give it away. I wouldn't know what to do with it for myself ... Well, I did always want to go on a cruise before I die. I got to go, too, and it was wonderful: Cabo San Lucas, Puerto Vallarta, and Mazatlan. These people who keep hounding me, wondering when I'm going to run off and join the circus now that I've won all this money, well ... They just don't get it, do they? Some never do."<p><p>DON CALHOUN, Bloomington, Illinois
Windfall: $1 million<p>In April 1993, as he entered Chicago Stadium for a Bulls game, Calhoun, a 24-year-old office-supplies salesman, was randomly chosen for a promotional contest. To win $1 million, he had to sink a 75-foot shot. Calhoun made the shot. He is now a Harlem Globetrotter. The contest was discontinued.<p>Calhoun: "I was always good with throwing paper in the garbage across the room in school. It's instinct as much as intensity. That night at the Bulls game? The basket looked close. I just let it go. And it went. <p>"Since then I haven't even taken a vacation. I haven't bought a plane ticket on my own yet. I don't feel like I can afford a vacation right now -- like, now is a very important time, and if I blow it, I blow a lot more than a career. <p>"Suddenly having $50,000 a year is kind of strange. I mean, I rent an apartment for $340 a month. I've got some government bonds and CDs, and I've been learning the stock market, but I don't understand it yet, and I'm not in a hurry. Before this happened, I was kind of going along, doing my thing -- my life was taking me more places than I was taking it.<p>"To me, this is an opportunity to do my short-story writing, play pro ball, and give something to kids who grew up the way I did. The Million Dollar Man Basketball Clinic I've started for underprivileged kids is real important to me. I wanted to play ball so bad when I was a kid, and these kids want the same thing. Now I have a whole lot to give that in my former life I wasn't in a position to give."<p><p>DOV JACOBSON, Atlanta
Windfall: $1.2 million<p>During the '80s, Jacobson worked at Time Inc. and spent nights creating software tools for computer animators. In 1987, he and his partner sold their company, West End Film, for $6 million. Jacobson is now creative director at Turner Interactive, a software division of Turner Broadcasting System.<p>Jacobson: "I've been lucky enough to make some really good decisions about my work -- because I didn't give a damn about money. <p>"Here I was, back in the late '70s, almost 30, stone broke, bringing my pregnant bride back from a $600 trip around the world to live at my parents' house in New Jersey -- and working nights on an experimental software project at Time magazine: Their art department let me use their equipment to teach myself computer animation. Then Time hired me in 1981 and gave me $29,000 a year. It was an incredible amount of money to me at the time. <p>"Seven years later, I was handed a check for $1.2 million -- one check with two commas on it. My share of the company. Really. I held the check, and still I couldn't believe it. Like they'd gotten the wrong guy. <p>"What the money's given us is the ability to say 'screw you' to everybody -- and especially to bogus computer jobs. I mean, if I lose this job tomorrow at Turner, it's really okay. I don't want to leave, but I have the freedom to. That's the greatest kind of wealth. That and the fact that my wife, if she's losing money on our investments, she's not telling me about it. So at least I have the illusion that we're rich."<p><p>ERIN MERCER, Jackson, Tennessee
Windfall: $10,000<p>Last spring Nickelodeon, "the cable channel just for kids," held a contest. The child whose postcard was chosen at random would win the grand prize: a $10,000 bedroom redecoration. Out of 250,000 entries, the winner was Mercer, now a seventh grader at Jackson Middle School.<p>Mercer: "I can't even believe it -- they're sending an interior decorator. They just told us. I can't believe it. <p>"My teachers are trying to give me hints on what to do. The worst idea I've heard so far is a boy in my homeroom class told me to get a whole bunch of motor scooters and line them up against the wall. So dumb. All different color motor scooters. Boys can be so dumb.<p>"Right now the only color I can think of is blue or pink. It all has to match. And I want some wallpaper and paint and posters and stuff. And a stereo with a CD player. And a VCR and Sega and lots of electronic stuff. I mean, I don't really need all this stuff, so it feels weird to want it now. But this is sort of like a fantasy thing, this Nickelodeon room I get. My room is sort of like a lemon yellow paint. I've got yellow curtains and a yellow bedspread. As long as I can remember, it's looked like this. Pretty much since I was born. But I don't remember that. Yeah, yellow is fine, I guess.<p>"When Nickelodeon called, my mom answered the phone. She told me, and I think I screamed. In a good way, though. It's the first time I've ever sent in to a contest in my whole life. <p>"Twelve years is a long time with just one color."<p><p>BOB CASTLEBERRY, Denton, Texas
Windfall: $10 million<p>In 1989, Castleberry won $10 million in the Publishers Clearing House Sweepstakes. Nine months later, he retired from his job as an account executive of a business-forms company and ran for mayor of his hometown, Denton, Texas. He's now in his third term. The job pays no salary.<p>Castleberry: "I can't say I've had any direct marriage proposals, but let me tell you something: Women sure can drop some big hints.<p>"I mean, I'm the kinda guy who's got a dozen pair of cowboy boots and around 150 ties. I just counted, so I'm not pullin' this outta thin air. First thing I did when I won, I promised myself I wouldn't do anything with the money for two months. Two months later to the day, I picked up the phone and bought myself a brand-new Cadillac. I mean, I negotiated for it like I always would, but I didn't even have to leave my chair. What a great, great country. Red leather interior. <p>"Pretty quick, though, I learned how to say no. If you don't, you can get in real trouble. Especially with all those people who write you all those mournful requests for money. I got to the point where I could detect which ones were real. And most of 'em -- I don't need to tell you -- most of 'em weren't. I made up my mind I wasn't going to loan anybody any money, either. If you're good for it, a bank'll help you. <p>"Yes, I know how lucky I am. I mean, I don't know too many other folks who've got a white Rolls Royce. Or any Rolls Royce, for that matter. Not any who still get elected mayor. Nope. Don't think I don't know it: Around here, every day is Christmas. I'm living everyone's dream."
---------------
Carla Koehl is a reporter at Worth.<p><p>

