<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-The Prince of Tithes</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-The Prince of Tithes</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Reach into your pocket and reward people for helping you, says James Redfield, author of "The Celestine Prophecy."  It will make you rich.<p>By Jesse Kornbluth<p>Those who shun new age best-sellers may not quite understand all the fuss over 44-year-old James Redfield, author of "The Celestine Prophecy", a slim volume that has been described as a combination of "Raiders of the Lost Ark" and "Jonathan Livingston Seagull."<p>But forget for a moment the flaky story, a spiritual adventure that takes an unnamed American narrator to the mountains of Peru, where he finds an endangered manuscript containing nine insights that could transform the world. Instead, consider the insights themselves -- for it's clearly Redfield's ideas, not his prose, that have sold more than a million copies of this book.<p>Here, at no extra charge, are a few of the biggies: Restlessness is a sign you're hungry for meaning in your life. Pay attention to coincidences and explore their possibilities. Stop fighting others for energy. Make eye contact with strangers and talk to them; they have messages for you.<p>Okay -- so far, so harmless. It's the final insight that stops many readers cold. Redfield predicts a time when automation will do most of our work. Our incomes will remain stable, however, because people will voluntarily pay us for the advice we give them. And we'll do the same for them, allowing everyone to do well by doing good. A spacey pipe dream or a radical vision? Jesse Kornbluth called Redfield at his Alabama home to learn more.<p>
Q: It amazes me that your endorsement of voluntarily giving money away has found any resonance in a society obsessed with accumulating wealth.<p>A: Our view of money is evolving. Money is only energy, a tool for creativity. The more you see money as a scarce resource and hold on to it tightly, the more you're locked into scarcity. No matter how tight money is for you, if you don't open your hand and make it available, it'll be harder for you to get more. When you give, you create a void that is filled again. And you always receive much more. Sounds too easy -- you give, you get -- but test it out.<p>Q: The huge success of your book shows that a lot of people are open to your ideas. But why should we believe your economic theories? Until recently, you were a therapist who worked with disturbed adolescents and their parents -- hardly a profession that spawns new ideas about money. Where does this stuff come from?<p>A: It's partly intuitive, and partly based on my investigation of many different religious offshoots, like theosophy and Religious Science, that promote tithing. These groups didn't talk about tithing just as charitable giving, but as something you do to achieve prosperity: Whatever you do, it comes back many times over. John D. Rockefeller and Andrew Carnegie were strong believers in giving money away. By the time I wrote the book, I'd been practicing it for three or four years.<p>Q: Practicing what, exactly? You're not talking about giving to churches and charity, which is what Rockefeller and Carnegie did. <p>A: People often happen to show up with information I've been waiting for. On those occasions I've given money, from a budget of roughly 10 percent of my income. People would say "What for?" I'd tell them, "It's a gift because you helped."<p>Q: You'd actually put cash in their hands?<p>A: Yes. They didn't understand, and I didn't try to explain. But what happened is that my income began to rise dramatically. I'd get a new opportunity, and things would work out. Once I began the process, for instance, I got several offers to leave the public agency where I was working and join an established therapeutic practice.<p>Q: You originally published "Celestine Prophecy" yourself. Did you also see that as a chance to test your theory about money?<p>A: Absolutely. I invested $15,000 and printed 3,000 copies. Then I phased out my therapy practice, and my wife, Salle, and I spent a few months crisscrossing the Southeast, giving the book away.<p>Q: Just giving it away?<p>A: Well, we left most of the copies at bookstores, mailed a few hundred, and handed the rest to people we met by chance. People embraced the book, sent it to friends, and orders started coming in. After three months we didn't have to do anything. We ended up selling 150,000 copies that way before we made a deal with Warner Books.<p>Q: Now that you're more solvent, are you any less willing to open your wallet?<p>A: I didn't write the book so I could become a philanthropist, but I've continued to give money away. The only thing that's different now is that I've set up a foundation.<p>Q: How about just reaching into your pocket and handing money to a person?<p>A: I still do that. Just recently, for example, I had a bunch of movie offers for the book, and I was feeling very unqualified to assess all the deals. A person came along and introduced me to an attorney who could help me understand my alternatives. I responded.<p>Q: And when you gave that person money, how did the two of you agree on the value of his advice?<p>A: As I see it, the value is entirely in the hands of the giver.<p>Q: Why not mutually agree on a dollar amount?<p>A: For one thing, if you have a sign on the door that says a service costs $20, that limits the high end of the scale. But more than that, to talk about what a personal service is worth is to create a caricature of the existing economy. We're talking about spiritual economics here.<p>Q: Still, you've got 5,000 subscribers to the "Celestine Journal," a newsletter that costs a fixed $29.95 a year. And you've sold 2,000 copies of an audiotape that you market at a fixed $30. How does that work? Should buyers who find value send you a gift as well?<p>A: Not at all. Tithing is about unexpected giving, not about being paid for a service. I don't want anyone sending me tithes.<p>Q: On the flip side of that, do people ask you for money now? Once you start paying folks unexpectedly, word must get around.<p>A: I'm careful how I talk about this, so people don't see me as someone who just gives cash away. That circumvents the principle.<p>Q: Speaking of circumventing a principle, one reviewer recently criticized you for identifying spirituality in terms of money. She said this could be "vastly misunderstood."<p>A: She's worried about charlatans who seek money by posing as spiritual teachers. She seems to miss the fact that "Celestine Prophecy" precisely deals with how to avoid being controlled by others. It's an anticult book.<p>Q: No danger, then, that you'll become just another spiritual leader asking us for money?<p>A: None. If this book continues to sell, I'll be harder and harder to find. In fact, here's a warning: People will take the ideas in the book and do strange things. There will be pyramid schemes based on tithing. There will be "Celestine Prophecy" study groups led by people more interested in money than in study. The buyer should beware.<p>Q: Would you feel vindicated if some big academic or economist endorsed your vision of economics?<p>A: Academics will be the last to get it. They gain their power from describing old information, and they don't want to lose that power. I wish I could say that my ideas are based on those of some great economist. But spiritual economics won't play out that way. If this vision is to happen, it has to be a grassroots phenomenon. The shift has to be made by individuals interpreting these ideas -- and then coming up with their own.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Publishing Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

