<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Call it Death Benefit Penalty</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Call it Death Benefit Penalty</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The real winners with these guarantees are the insurers.<p>By Alan Lavine<p>Sales of variable annuities hit a record $43 billion last year, and juiced-up death-benefit guarantees have emerged as one of their hottest draws. Here's how they work: A lump-sum or regular investment placed in a variable annuity earns a variable rate of return that is tax-deferred. The insurance company underwriting the annuity guarantees to pay your heirs the principal or the market value of your investment -- whichever is greater -- when you die.<p>Most of the top 25 companies selling variable annuities offer enhanced death-benefit guarantees. Some reset the amount they will guarantee every seven years, based on the policy's accumulated value. Others pay guaranteed rates of 4 percent to 7 percent and up to twice the principal upon the death of the annuitant if he or she dies before a certain age -- typically 80 or 90. <p>The death-benefit guarantee is a source of comfort to older investors who roll their maturing federally insured CDs into variable annuities. But an analysis of the numbers shows that this feature may in fact benefit the insurance company more than the annuitant.<p>"The death-benefit guarantee encourages people to take more risk and invest in more funds," says Roger Blease, a life- and health-insurance analyst at A.M. Best, an insurance-rating concern. "That generates more profits [to the insurer]. The death-benefit guarantee also keeps people from cashing out their annuities." <p>Death-benefit guarantees don't come cheap. For starters, annuitants are charged 1.25 percent of their investment annually in so-called mortality and expense fees. Tack on additional charges to help pay agent commissions and other expenses, and you get annual expenses as high as 1.77 percent, according to the Morningstar Variable Annuity/Life Performance Report.<p>John Snyder, an actuary with Milliman & Robertson in Milwaukee, says the cost to insurers of offering death-benefit guarantees runs between 0.03 percent and 0.08 percent of the variable annuity's assets annually. The lion's share of the fee -- 0.8 percent of total annuity assets -- represents the insurance company's profit. The reason for these enviable profits, Snyder says, is that the probability of exercising a claim is small -- on the order of 1 to 3 out of 1,000 deaths. <p>One potential risk to annuity holders is that the insurance company may fail. Fourteen states have life and health guaranty associations that cover the principal value of an insurer's death-benefit guarantee for company retirement plans, which are called unallocated annuity contracts. Individuals who buy annuities outside of their company plan are not covered at all. Even in those states that do provide coverage, combined benefits for the company that owns the contract are typically limited to less than $5 million. <p>The states with guaranty associations are Alabama, Arizona, Florida, Georgia, Idaho, Louisiana, Maine, Missouri, Oklahoma, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Texas, and Washington.<p>John Del Campo, counsel for the National Organization of Life and Health Insurance Guaranty Associations, a Virginia-based organization that represents state insurance funds, says state insurance funds would decide on a case-by-case basis whether they would cover nonqualified variable-annuity death-benefit guarantees. And even with coverage, state laws generally set a limit of up to $100,000 in annuity principal and up to $300,000 for all insurance benefits combined per policyholder. "It's a gray area whether the coverage is eligible," says Del Campo. "People are putting a large amount of money into these products, but they don't know if the guaranty associations will cover it."<p>Life and health guaranty associations are pools created by state law to cover insurance policies, including annuities. Guaranty associations are funded by insurance companies that pay 1 percent to 4 percent of premiums annually in the states in which they do business. Associations limit protection to residents of their states, but it doesn't matter where annuitants' beneficiaries live.<p>A top-selling variable annuity, Franklin Value Mark, which sports a death-benefit guarantee, pulled in $3.13 billion sales in 1993. The death-benefit guarantee is based on a 5 percent annual compound rate up to age 80; if the annuitant dies before that, the benefit received is the greater of the contract's cash surrender value or the amount invested multiplied by 5 percent for every year the contract has been in force.<p>Golden American Life Insurance's GoldenSelect policy guarantees a 7 percent rate and up to twice the principal when the annuitant dies. Merrill Lynch Fund's Retirement Plus annuity pays 5 percent until the annuitant's death. <p>Insurers contend that investors are willing to pay for a death-benefit guarantee even though it may never apply to them. "It's been a chief selling point for us," says Bob Langel, executive vice president at Golden American Life Insurance in New York City. "People know they can take on more risk and invest in stock funds without having to worry about their principal." Once in, policyholders are apt to stay with a variable annuity for the security it provides.<p>In fact, in stable markets few insurers ever have to pay on their guarantees. Brian Kroll, an annuity-product officer with Sun Life's MFS Regatta Gold in Wellesley, Massachusetts, says that since 1990, Sun Life has paid out an average of 10 to 15 claims per year in which the minimum death-benefit guarantee has exceeded the account value, each averaging $40,000. "Death-benefit claims are far and few between," says Kroll. "We set aside $500,000 a year on the Regatta product to pay for potential claims." <p>Jennifer Strickland, editor of the Morningstar Variable Annuity/Life Performance Report, says a death-benefit guarantee is similar to fire insurance -- you may never use it, but it may be good to have. However, Strickland advises investors to shop around and compare annuity expenses. "Many people don't realize they have to die to collect the death-benefit guarantee," Strickland says. "They think they can earn a 5 percent annual rate on a stock fund and won't lose any money. They may not use it, and the high cost of the insurance charges can eat into your total return." <p>If you think a variable annuity is for you, read the policy's prospectus carefully to determine if the insurance company is indeed reserving for its death-benefit claims. In general, experts advise that investors buy from companies rated A or better by A.M. Best and B+ by Weiss Research. Claims-paying ratings should be at least AA by Standard & Poor's, Moody's, and Duff & Phelps. If your insurer is using another insurance company to cover the claims, it is a good idea to check the safety ratings of both companies.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

