<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-The Tip</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-The Tip</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Can you be an insider without knowing it? Robert Sacks thought he was just getting a little free advice. Instead he got caught in the government's broadest insider-trading case ever.<p>By Ted C. Fishman<p>Robert Sacks enjoyed talking to other parents at his son's soccer games. Chatting with neighbors came naturally to him, but friendliness was also something of a professional responsibility: As the property manager for two residential developments in Calabasas, California, a well-to-do suburb on the northern rim of Los Angeles County, it was his job to know everyone around town. In the spring of 1990, Sacks was a regular at the Saturday-afternoon games. He would come out to root for his five-year-old son, Brandon, and to catch up on local gossip. He was well-liked -- "a helluva guy," in the words of one homeowner -- and he always seemed to have time for people. Sacks also got a kick out of watching the kids charge around on the grassy field. Too young to know how to play positions, they would swarm around the ball in a pack as they tried to boot it toward the opposing goal. <p>It was during these games that Sacks got to know another parent, Michael Newman. Newman was a speculator who played the stock, commodity, and rare-coin markets -- apparently with great success. "He drove a Mercedes and had a beautiful house with a tennis court," Sacks says. "Color me impressed." <p>The two new friends started talking about the market, and Newman suggested a pair of stocks he thought Sacks should buy. Sacks took the advice, but both of the investments wound up losers. Still, they remained friendly. Their children attended the same preschool classes at the local synagogue. Sacks regarded Newman as a well-meaning person who was "always very friendly." The two exchanged hellos at children's birthday parties and holiday carnivals. Newman, a friendly and gregarious schmoozer, took to calling Sacks "boychick," a Yiddish term of endearment.<p>In early June of 1990, Newman gave Sacks another tip. This time, he urged him to buy shares of Motel 6, the budget-motel chain. Apologizing for the performance of his other two recommendations, Newman practically guaranteed a winner. "This one looks real good," Sacks recalls Newman saying. "I think (the company) is going to get acquired." Despite the earlier losses, Sacks felt he still had every reason to trust his new friend, whose manner and lifestyle suggested a knack for hitting it big in the market. Plus, there was something else -- an air of certainty he heard in Newman's voice. Excited, Sacks decided that rather than purchasing Motel 6 common shares, he would buy call options. Because of greater leverage, the options would give Sacks a bigger score if the stock moved upward. He bought 70, giving him control of 7,000 shares of the stock.<p>To this day, Sacks maintains that he never knew the tip Newman gave him was anything more than just that: a friendly piece of advice, one he assumed was intended to make up for the two previous flops. Sacks also swears that he had no idea where Newman got the information -- or that Newman was in contact with a group of people who were illegally peddling inside information about Motel 6.<p>Yet that is exactly what the government would later charge. According to the Securities and Exchange Commission, the stock tip Sacks traded on had made its way through a complicated and disorganized web that started with a Motel 6 executive in Texas. It stretched through a chain of California tanning salons and even included an actor who, ironically, had had a bit part in the movie Wall Street, Oliver Stone's morality tale about insider trading. (See sidebar "Don't Ask, Don't Tell, Don't Listen" following the end of this story.)<p>The investigation of the Motel 6 insider-trading case became the broadest of its kind ever mounted by the U.S. government. To date, the SEC, working in tandem with the U.S. Justice Department, has targeted at least 23 defendants, including people four or five steps removed from the Motel 6 executive implicated as the source of the original leak -- and others may yet be named. This is the first time the government has ever pursued people so far down the information ladder in an insider-trading investigation. The case is so complex that when SEC lawyers discuss it, they draw themselves pictures in the air just to see where everyone fits.<p>The Motel 6 probe "is a classic insider-trading case involving the breach of fiduciary duty of a high-level corporate insider," says Richard Walker, the regional administrator of the SEC in New York. If the case is a classic, though, it is also the sort of classic that pushes the boundaries of the work that preceded it. Walker isn't shy about the example he hopes the Motel 6 case will set. He wants to send a message to the public that the agency will go after anyone if "they yield to the temptation of trading on insider information." <p>Robert Sacks didn't find out the SEC was looking at his trades until more than a year after he took Newman's advice. The news arrived when a Justice Department investigator knocked on his door. It was just an informal interview, the agent said. He asked Sacks a few questions and left. A few weeks later, in November 1991, another knock on Sacks's door brought a formal subpoena and summons to New York for questioning by the SEC. <p>Even now, Sacks says he cannot comprehend why he was singled out. "I don't know what the SEC was after," he says. Though he has for the most part kept his troubles to himself, he agreed to speak to Worth, even though his friends and attorney advised him to remain silent. "The truth is the truth," he says. "I did nothing wrong." <p><p>On the New York Stock Exchange, where Motel 6 was listed, some 280 million shares change hands daily. People and institutions trade stock for any number of reasons, but a general principle underlying public securities trading is that in order for the trading to be fair, investors should all have access to the same information. <p>Theoretically, no one has an edge. But of course, everyone wants an angle. Information the general public does not have access to is the stuff that makes hot tips glow and sends those that have it -- like the Motel 6 insiders -- aggressively into the market. To enforce the law, the SEC routinely monitors trading on the nation's securities exchanges. When companies make major announcements that affect the price of their stock, the agency often will look back at the activity in the period preceding the public dissemination of the news. Most major events will trigger a commission inquiry of some kind. "We have computers that can sort massive amounts of data in a nanosecond," says Walker, describing the agency's first line of defense against inside trading. <p>The computers look for aberrations in a stock's trading volume and price movement. They also search for overheated activity in options, the instrument insiders often use to maximize returns. An analysis of Motel 6 trading on July 12, 1990, would have left the commission's computers smoking. That was the day Accor S.A., a French-owned hotel concern, announced it would pay $1.3 billion, or $22.50 a share, for Motel 6. Even though the deal wasn't made public until after the market had closed, trading activity in the stock had been furious all day. In the previous month, between 50,000 and 100,000 shares of Motel 6 stock traded daily. On July 12, 1.5 million shares changed hands. Option volume had a similar bump. The traders who jumped the gun were easy marks.<p>Once the SEC's computers have flagged suspicious activity, the commission works backward to root out its quarry, looking for possible connections between people who bought and sold stock. If any connections are found, a fusillade of subpoenas comes next. These could be sent to lawyers, bankers, investment bankers, accountants, public relations people, even spouses, sons, daughters, friends, or neighbors. "If we're told the information was disseminated at a party, we get the guest list," says Henry Klehm, the assistant director for enforcement in the SEC's New York office. "We turn (suspects) upside-down and shake them."<p>Accor's 1990 takeover of Motel 6 came in the midst of a broad crackdown on Wall Street insiders. Investors were on notice: It was open season on cheaters. In fiscal 1991, the SEC filed 34 insider-trading complaints. Only months before, Michael Milken had paid the U.S. government $600 million and pleaded guilty to six felonies, and Ivan Boesky had been forced to pay $100 million. In both cases, the SEC linked forces with the Department of Justice, and both men received prison terms.<p>Due to the sheer volume of trading that takes place on the nation's stock exchanges, however, the SEC must be selective. It can't possibly run down every suspicious trade. This, however, doesn't mean that it pursues only big money. The agency wants the small-timers to think it is keeping an eye on them as well.<p>"The SEC is trying to create the illusion it is everywhere, and that if someone trades on inside information, the odds are strong of getting caught," says Harvey Pitt, a former general counsel to the SEC who, as a private attorney, defended Boesky. Pitt asserts that because of this strategy, more and more cases involve "people who are not stealing, bribing and cheating, but who just don't get the law, make mistakes, or who have a differing view on the law."<p>According to Walker, the SEC's new tack is working. "One indication that people are more aware of our enforcement," he says, "is that in current deals and transactions there is less of a tendency to see run-ups in advance of important announcements."<p><p>In 1990, at the age of 41, Robert Sacks had already seen his financial fortunes rise and fall. Money, however, was something he was usually able to keep in perspective. In 1983, he and his brother had sold a business they jointly owned -- a computerized billing service for dentists -- and Sacks invested his share in local real estate. He lived comfortably in a large home in the hills of Calabasas. In 1986, when a near tragedy struck his family, he was able to step away from his business and devote the next two and a half years to a public-service project. <p>His son Brandon, then two years old, had stuck a nail in an electric socket and almost died. In the aftermath, Sacks started an organization called the National Institute of Children's Environments. Among other things, he convinced a local builder to erect custom child-safe homes. NICE's work garnered press nationwide and was recognized in a personal letter from then-first lady Barbara Bush. "If God were to ask me what good I had done with my life, I would say this," Sacks says. NICE eventually was absorbed by the National Child Safety Council in Jackson, Michigan. <p>In the wake of the stock market crash in 1987, California real estate prices crashed, too. Over the next few years, Sacks's properties lost 40 percent of their value. This landed him in a reduced -- though still comfortable -- financial situation. On a brokerage application in 1990, he listed his net worth at $3 million. By the time the SEC deposed him in 1991, he pegged his net worth at $1.5 million. "The real estate market just killed me," he says. <p>Seeing his net worth fall by half scared Sacks. But he still had a steady income, earned as a manager for two private communities -- overseeing landscaping, coordinating street repair, and managing the private police force hired to protect the homeowners. During earthquakes, mud slides, and fires he never left the phone. He managed maintenance budgets so well that he never had to ask residents to pay extra for repairs in the wake of L.A.'s many disasters, something he's frequently thanked for. "He gives a damn about the community," says Joel Smulson, president of the Calabasas Park Estates residents association. "More than you'd expect."<p>Sacks also liked to play the stock market, and after his heavy real estate losses, he was eager to turn his fortunes around. When he first started talking to Newman about stocks in early 1990, he found his new friend more vocal than prescient. Newman suggested two stocks he thought were worth buying and sent Sacks to Ira Gorman, a friend of Newman's who ran a bare-bones discount brokerage. The two stocks declined in price after Sacks bought them. One of the picks, Caesars World, a casino operator, lost a third of its value. Sacks didn't blame Newman, but he was unhappy with Gorman. "I'm used to calling a stockbroker who'd give me the time of day," he told the SEC. "(Gorman) was very abrasive, uncaring." Newman promised to make up for these losses. His first gesture was to introduce Sacks to another broker, Rami Yahalom, of First Affiliated Securities in Encino, California, who insisted on meeting Sacks in person before taking the account. This put Sacks at ease immediately.<p>Then, Newman suggested a third stock: Motel 6. Sacks's hopes soared. "I probably was a little bit more excited about this one," he later told SEC lawyers during a deposition, "because I was a little bit more vulnerable.... I wanted to believe more than anything else that I could recover some of my losses (in real estate) by making some money in the stock market."<p>Had Sacks been on more solid financial ground, he might have scrutinized Newman's recommendation more closely. His one attempt at due diligence later became a critical point in his dealings with the SEC. Upon hearing the Motel 6 tip, he asked Newman, "How do you know this?" <p>Sacks later told the SEC in a deposition that Newman responded to this question by putting him off. Sacks quoted Newman as saying, "Boychick, don't worry. Don't ask, boychick." He also told the SEC that he quizzed Newman several more times, but Newman never offered more information. Sacks says it crossed his mind that Newman may have known more than he was admitting, but he had no way of knowing one way or the other. "For all I knew, he read it in The Wall Street Journal," Sacks says. (In fact, there had been speculation in the press about Motel 6 as a potential takeover candidate.)<p>In his deposition with the SEC, Sacks recalled that Newman also said, "Don't go telling anybody." This was advice Sacks didn't follow. He told at least two people, including a family member and a coworker. "There isn't a day that goes by that (I don't talk to) people," he told the SEC. "I don't keep anything I do confidential."<p>Sacks initially bought the Motel 6 call options through Yahalom, who he thought was "very sharp," and with whom he had begun speaking almost every day. Nevertheless, in the weeks that followed, the Motel 6 investment began looking like yet another lousy lead, just like Caesars World. Sacks called Newman several times at home to follow up on the progress of Motel 6. Each time, Newman apologized for the losses but said again he thought something would happen soon. (Newman would not comment for this story. Repeated attempts to reach him by phone and in person proved unsuccessful.)<p>Then, on June 20, Newman called Sacks to tell him the Motel 6 deal had fallen through and that he should get out of his options. Sacks took the advice. He liquidated the Motel 6 position. Sacks says he can't remember if he made or lost money: All he remembers is that it wasn't a "windfall." His faith in Newman plummeted. He thought Newman "didn't know what the heck he was talking about." Later, he told the SEC that at the time he thought Newman was a "schmuck." He resolved not to take any more tips from Newman. <p>"I called Rami," Sacks remembers of the time he was told the deal had collapsed, "and said that Newman was probably a flake." At this point, Sacks had dumped his position in Motel 6. But he had one other request for Yahalom: Would he continue to keep an eye on Motel 6's stock? The broker promised that he would.<p><p>In the meantime, the unseemly and fiendishly complicated tale of the Motel 6 insider-trading case had been unfolding in a vastly different world from Robert Sacks's comfortable suburb -- a world of Beverly Hills nightclubs and posh tanning salons.<p>In a 43-page complaint the SEC filed on March 4, 1993, the agency portrays a scheme that grew into a morass of intrigue, greed, and petty chiseling. Paradoxically, the man the SEC has tagged the insider at the top of the ladder, Hugh Thrasher, then executive vice-president of marketing at Motel 6, never made a dime from the information. Thrasher was a family man from Dallas who had joined Motel 6 in 1986, shortly after the chain was acquired by Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Co., the leveraged-buyout powerhouse most famous for its 1989 purchase of R.J. Reynolds. <p>Without Thrasher, Motel 6 might never have been such an attractive takeover target (Accor's acquisition price worked out to $37,000 per room). He inaugurated the first ad campaign in Motel 6 history. The ads, still going strong, feature Tom Bodett, the wryly homespun radio commentator from Homer, Alaska, who concludes the spots with the instantly recognizable tag line "We'll leave the light on for you." <p>Thrasher appears to have been rewarded for his efforts on behalf of Motel 6. He traveled frequently and had a home in Dallas, a yacht moored in Boca Raton, Florida, and a habit of giving expensive gifts. <p>According to the SEC's complaint, Thrasher had a "very close friendship" with a man named Carl Harris. Though unemployed, Harris lived in Beverly Hills with two roommates. The SEC says Thrasher bought Harris clothes and jewelry valued at more than $75,000. He also helped Harris buy a BMW convertible by arranging a $26,600 loan from a trust fund that belonged to Thrasher's children. The SEC says Thrasher also helped pay for Harris's rapidly mounting medical bills; Harris had AIDS.<p>In January 1990, when KKR and Motel 6 executives began to discuss a buyout with representatives of Accor, Thrasher was an active participant. His role put him a position to know intimate details about the confidential negotiations -- information that would obviously have a significant impact on the price of Motel 6 stock once it was publicly known.<p>Though the SEC never accused Thrasher of trading on this information for his own financial gain, its complaint does assert that he shared the news with Harris. The agency describes this action as "a gift of illegal profits." It also maintains that Thrasher himself "benefited directly" because the profits from his tip were "a means of providing Harris with additional financial support."<p>The details of how Harris acquired the takeover tip from Thrasher may remain forever unknown. Because he was gravely ill when the legal proceeding started, Harris's lawyer kept his client from being deposed. Harris died in April 1992. <p>Motel 6 suspended Hugh Thrasher when the government's insider-trading investigation came to light. Eventually, he was fired. His case is awaiting trial in New York State's Southern District. Thrasher's lawyer, Charles Stillman, who gained national attention for defending former Secretary of Defense Clark Clifford in the BCCI case, says he intends to fight the SEC's version of Thrasher's role in the Motel 6 case. Most likely, he says, Thrasher's defense will be that Harris somehow stole or misappropriated the information. <p>However Harris found out about the pending acquisition of Motel 6, he knew exactly what he wanted to do with the tip: sell the information to others and use the proceeds to buy options on the stock. To carry this scheme out, he first consulted one of his friends, William Gomez. Gomez, in turn, introduced Harris to Gregg Shawzin, who owned Future-Link, a brokerage firm in Beverly Hills. Shawzin also owned a share of a company called Lads and Lions, which operated a chain of tanning salons. As the information spread, its actual source was concealed. Either to protect Thrasher or to make his own story more credible, Harris said the tip came from his father, whom he said was on the Motel 6 board of directors. Of course, a call to the company switchboard would have revealed that Harris was lying.<p>At this level, according to the SEC, a classic insider-trading case took shape. For his part, Shawzin bought enough stock and call options to control 181,500 shares of Motel 6 (and would later split a $566,000 profit three ways, then pay Harris a $30,000 fee for the information). According to the SEC, Shawzin's friends also made side deals they didn't tell each other about.<p>Meanwhile, the Motel 6 tip spread far and wide. Tippers were demanding cuts of their tippees' profits, and tippees were striking deals to recoup their fees by selling the information yet again. The SEC believes that Michael Newman was brought into the ring by Shawzin. The two had a business relationship -- Newman had a desk at Future-Link, where he traded commodities -- and a social one too; Shawzin played tennis at Newman's house. <p>Shawzin turned to Newman as a way of helping Harris get money to invest in Motel 6, according to a deposition given to the SEC by Ronald Kuznetsky, one of Newman's closest friends (and, at Newman's urging, a Motel 6 investor). Harris had a gold jewelry box brimming with expensive items that he was willing to put up as collateral on a loan. The box had an amethyst on its face and contained a one-and-a-half-carat emerald and two wristwatches, one a gold Rolex. Newman, according to Kuznetsky's deposition, agreed to lend Harris $5,000. Despite the loan Newman made to Harris, Shawzin almost immediately regretted bringing him into the web. The problem, says the SEC, was that Newman started to peddle the tip too freely. Shawzin got nervous and tried to cut Newman out of the deal, calling him on June 20 to tell him that the takeover talks had collapsed. <p>Newman quickly liquidated the Motel 6 options he'd bought for himself. He also called his tippees and told them to unload their Motel 6 positions. One of the people to get such a call from Newman was Robert Sacks. Though Shawzin's lie cast Michael Newman out of the deal, Harris later reeled him back in. Three weeks later, on July 11, Harris ran an end-around on Shawzin and called Newman at home to tell him he had news about Motel 6. According to Kuznetsky's deposition, Harris told Newman he wanted 20 percent of his take. When Newman agreed, Harris told him the buyout would be announced the next day. Kuznetsky told the SEC that Newman planned to use the money he collected from his tippees, Sacks included, to pay Harris for the information. Newman assumed that Sacks was wealthy. He was going to ask for 25 percent of Sacks's take.<p><p>Robert Sacks starts his day at 6:15 each morning, so he was wide awake at 7:05 on the morning of July 12, 1990, when the telephone rang. It was Rami Yahalom, sounding excited. Yahalom had continued to keep an eye on Motel 6 stock, just as Sacks had asked, and guess what: That morning, trading in Motel 6 had opened on the NYSE with a frenzy of activity.<p>"I went crazy," Sacks says, his eyes widening, "I got stock fever. I bought and bought." In the course of the day, he placed some 30 telephone calls to Yahalom and poured about $80,000 into a combination of Motel 6 common stock and options. By his own account, he also discussed his moves with friends and relatives. (Some of them traded, he says, but the SEC didn't cite them as insider traders.) By the end of the day, Motel 6's common shares had closed at $19.25, up about $3. After the close, the news got even better. Accor S.A. announced it would take over the whole company at $22.50 a share. Sacks was $40,000 richer.<p>Newman had also telephoned Sacks that morning, this time to advise him that the Motel 6 deal was back on. Sacks said thank you, but he had already made his move to bet on the stock. In his deposition to the SEC, Sacks repeatedly insisted that his decision to get back into Motel 6 was based on the telephone call from Yahalom and not on the later call from Newman. Yahalom's testimony to the SEC corroborated Sacks's contention.<p>Two days later, Newman phoned Sacks again to congratulate him. But he also had something else on his mind. According to Sacks' deposition, Newman asked, "Well, boychick, how'd you do? How much money did you make?" When Sacks told him, Newman said, "I'm happy for you." Then Newman requested a 25 percent cut of Sacks's profits -- some $10,000 -- in cash. In his deposition, Sacks remembers Newman saying he had "expenses" to cover; the demand was made in a very friendly, matter-of-fact way. Nevertheless, Sacks says, he was shocked. "Wait a minute, let me get this straight," Sacks asked. "You expect me to pay this kind of money?" <p>"Yes, that's the way it is" was the reply, according to Sacks.<p>Later that day, Sacks brought a check for $2,000 to Newman's house. Newman again asked for cash but ended up taking the check, and asked Sacks to write "Art" on the bottom. He also told Sacks he wanted more money. "I believe I gave him another six to eight hundred," Sacks later told the SEC.<p>Though Sacks says he was taken aback by all this, he told the SEC that even before Newman asked him for money, he planned to give him "a little something" if the stock turned out to be a winner. At one point, before Newman ever demanded payment, Sacks recalls asking Newman, "Why are you doing this for me? What do you want?" <p>"Don't worry boychick, we'll work it out," Newman had replied lightly. <p>In the eyes of the SEC, Sacks's payment to Newman was highly incriminating -- an admission he had received information so valuable that he was willing to cough up serious money for it. Sacks, however, contends that just because he was grateful to Newman for putting him on to Motel 6 in the first place, that doesn't prove he ever knew that he was the recipient of inside information.<p>At first, when the Justice Department agent knocked on his door in late 1991, Sacks didn't imagine he was in trouble. "The Justice Department people were very nice," he remembers. "They treated me like a witness and told me what it was all about. I sat and had a very nice conversation." Shortly afterward, the SEC subpoena arrived, along with notification that Sacks would be named in the suit. <p>"I became a basket case," Sacks says. "They told me I had 24 hours to send them all my records. My attorney called for an extension, and it was denied. I didn't even have time to copy all of them. I sent them originals." Deeply rattled by the suddenness with which he'd become embroiled in the case, Sacks called Newman, who refused to talk. He then called Newman's friend Kuznetsky. "Would you please talk to me, no one wants to talk to me about this," Kuznetsky remembered Sacks pleading. <p>Sacks told Kuznetsky he was planning to testify that Rami Yahalom had recommended the stock, which was true. But this worried Kuznetsky. According to his deposition, he was not aware that Sacks had a different version of the story. Kuznetsky worried that Sacks's account might sound like a cover-up plot. He called Newman.<p>Newman then decided to call Sacks back. He urged Sacks to tell what Newman considered the truth; that is, that Sacks had bought the stock on Newman's tip. Sacks, however, says he found this advice strange and suspected Newman might be setting him up for something. "I said, 'Why are you calling me?'" Sacks told the SEC. "'Are you recording this call? What's going on here?'" <p>Newman said he wasn't recording the call. "I'm concerned for you," Sacks remembers him answering. "I'm concerned for my friends." <p>"You can't discuss it, I can't discuss it -- why are you calling me?" Sacks asked again. Newman apologized for putting him in a difficult situation but stressed that he should tell investigators he had traded on the information given him by Newman. By the end of the conversation, Newman too was emotional. Sacks remembers that Newman seemed on the verge of tears.<p>But Sacks wasn't going to change his story. He says he was not aware that Newman had offered the tip to anyone else. (The SEC fingered Newman for tipping four people in all.) Newman's call did little to ease his mind. In his deposition, he told the SEC he was "paranoid" about it. "I assumed the worst," he said. He remembers telling a family friend that getting subpoenaed was "one of the most frightening experiences that I've ever been through." <p>By this time, news of the case had spread throughout Calabasas. Sacks told a fellow congregant at the synagogue not to expect to see him at a soccer practice. "I'm going to New York for an investigation," he said, hinting at the matter. "Oh, is this the Newman thing?" the congregant answered. Sacks feared it was all over the temple.<p>Sacks flew to New York for the deposition, deciding not to bring an attorney with him. "I couldn't justify paying a lawyer $350 an hour for two full days," he says. "I thought I'd tell them what I knew, and they'd let me off the hook." Sacks says he did discuss his decision to go alone with his lawyer, who suggested that it would be better to go represented but felt there was little risk if Sacks stuck to the truth. (Many of the other figures in the case, Newman and Shawzin among them, refused to give depositions, exercising their Fifth Amendment right to avoid self-incrimination.)<p>At the SEC offices in lower Manhattan, Sacks was ushered into a room with three attorneys and a battery of microphones. "I got nervous because they were so accusatory," he says, "and I never thought in a million years it would end up like that." <p>Sacks was interviewed for a full day. In retrospect, he has few complaints about the way his interrogators treated him, except that he felt badgered by having to answer the same questions over and over. The transcript of his testimony shows that the government lawyers, led by Audrey Weintrob, a SEC staff attorney, pressed him hard, asking him to recall not just the facts of his case but also his mental state at every stage, his impressions of the people he talked to, of himself, of his doubts and hopes and suspicions.<p>When the interviewers started probing into Sacks's personal life, he had the sickening realization that he was in trouble for keeps: "They asked me every detail of my relationship with Newman, about the other people in the soccer league, about Newman's other tippees, his world." Nevertheless, he says, he stuck to his version of the events. The transcripts show Weintrob was especially interested in why Sacks had paid Newman money, which to them looked like a kickback. "The SEC made a big deal of that," he says of how the transaction is portrayed in the court papers, "but if I felt I was doing something wrong, I would have paid him in cash. I felt indebted."<p>Sacks relaxed once over the course of his interrogation, at lunchtime, when he approached one of the SEC attorneys. "Am I in trouble?" Sacks asked. "An Ivan Boesky you're not," the lawyer answered. <p>By itself, evidence that Sacks paid Newman only linked Sacks to the scheme, but it didn't prove that he had acted on inside information. To make a case against him stick, the SEC needed to show that Sacks at least suspected that he possessed material nonpublic information, an inside tip. <p>So the investigators zeroed in on what they regarded as the most vulnerable part of Sacks's testimony -- his acknowledgment that he had asked Newman, "How do you know this?"  During the interview, the following exchange took place:<p>Sacks: (Newman) basically said (Motel 6) was a good candidate for an acquisition, he liked the stock, he thought there was going to be a buyout. I had asked him repeatedly, "Where are you getting your information?" and he would repeatedly answer me, "Don't ask me." Those kinds of questions. I never knew, and I was impressed.<p>SEC investigator: What do you mean, you were impressed?<p>Sacks: I was impressed with his demeanor. I was impressed by the fact that he was obviously very successful and that he could make a living dealing in the stock market, and I guess my human nature was, I want to believe that he was giving me a tip.<p>SEC: What do you mean, giving you a tip?<p>Sacks: Just what I said. Giving me a tip like maybe a thousand other tips you get in life.<p>SEC: Did this appear to you like any other tip you've ever gotten?<p>Sacks: Absolutely.<p>SEC: What other tips have you gotten from what other people, for example?<p>Sacks: I am not going to sit here and go back on my life and remember a thousand tips, you know. Don't fly in airplanes, what stocks to buy. I hear it all the time.<p>To the SEC, the mere fact that Sacks had thought to ask Newman the source of his information demonstrated that he was aware of Newman's being privy to something inside and hot. And Newman's refusal to say where the recommendation came from offered Sacks no quarter. "As soon as you ask, it shows you are thinking about it," says the SEC's Henry Klehm. "Even if someone says, 'I don't want to know,' it shows a conscious avoidance of knowledge."<p><p>Insider-trading investigations usually conjure images of financiers, arbitrageurs, brokers, and lawyers -- the sharks in expensive suits who get early wind of big deals -- not small-timers in the suburbs. Among the 23 people the SEC has so far named in its suits, the government estimates total illegal profits of somewhere around $10 million. This is a substantial amount of money, but it is a pittance compared to the other classic securities-fraud cases. Dennis Levine, one of the inside traders who came to symbolize the 1980s, confessed to receiving $12.6 million in illegal profits. One of the individuals the SEC caught in its Motel 6 dragnet was Julian Schor, a corporate headhunter and one of Michael Newman's other tippees, for a $11,125 profit.<p>In the Motel 6 case, the SEC investigation unfolded with few obstructions. Thanks to the relative lack of sophistication of those involved, the commission was able to uncover reams of two of the most sought-after kinds of evidence: that tippees said to other people, "I have a hot confidential tip," and that those who traded on the information kicked back money to those higher on the chain.<p>When the SEC can prove strong links between tiers in a scheme, tippers can be held liable to pay for all the trading gains and penalties -- usually equal to the trading profits -- of anyone on the tiers below them. Sacks's settlement with the SEC totaled $469,000, which covered his profits and penalties as well as the profits and penalties of the people Sacks encouraged to trade in Motel 6, plus interest. "I could have fought on principle and put up $300,000 to $400,000 in attorneys' fees, or settled and gotten on with my life," Sacks says.<p>Was Robert Sacks unfairly persecuted? The crime of insider trading exists only within the arcana of SEC regulations and some narrowly defined court rulings. In Sacks's case, the SEC reached beyond even these gauzy definitions of the crime. Going after an insider four times removed from the source of the information has never been tested in court. <p>So far, Sacks has not been charged by the Justice Department. The chances that he will be charged are somewhat diminished by the demands in a criminal proceeding that guilt be established beyond a reasonable doubt; in SEC investigations, only a preponderance of evidence is necessary. But even if the government has closed the book on Sacks, he's not off the hook. A class-action lawsuit brought last July by four law firms in New York and Chicago threatens to churn up new troubles. The suit, drafted almost directly from the SEC court complaint, apes nearly every aspect of the SEC action except that it seeks to return money to private investors who lost as a result of the insider trading. <p>Sacks says he went through a period of deep bitterness. "At first I blamed Newman for everything, but later I thought it was unfair to make him the source of my anger," he says. "He had no ill will or intentions to do me harm. He did what he did because he has a big heart and is a very caring person." Sacks is also at peace about his settlement, feeling it helped him refocus on what is important. This year he and his wife and three children are leaving Calabasas to make a new start in Utah. The insider case was the final factor that made up their minds. "What are the three dirtiest letters in the stock market today?" he asks. "T-I-P. Yet that is just what everyone asks their brokers for every time they call." 
---------------
Ted C. Fishman is a contributing writer for Worth.<p>
---------------<p>SIDEBAR: 
Don't Ask, Don't Tell, Don't Listen <p>If the case of Bob Sacks warns investors not to ask "What's hot?," the case of Darrell Sandy Marsh warns that you're probably better off not even listening. Like Sacks, Marsh was four steps removed from the alleged source of information, but he was also following Motel 6 stock on his own, well before he was tipped off.<p>Marsh was drawn into the web by John Anderson -- a busy  tipper and later a cooperative government witness. He and Marsh know each other from the tanning-salon business. Marsh, Anderson, and Gregg and Mark Shawzin were all associated with the Sun Days chain of tanning salons operated by Lads and Lions. Marsh is also a former movie actor, having appeared in bit parts in the movies Wall Street, Road House, and the remake of The Blob.<p>Before his acting career, Marsh, who graduated with honors with a degree in finance from Boston University, made a living trading stock options. He and his 74-year-old father, Jack, regularly trolled the market for takeover candidates. Marsh says brokerage statements even show that his father put in an unsuccessful bid for Motel 6 stock in April 1990; the elder Marsh reasoned that owner Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Company might sell the chain to help retire the massive debt it carried from its acquisition of R.J. Reynolds. Jack Marsh held over $100,000 in Reynolds bonds and so had been watching KKR's plans for Motel 6 closely. He wasn't alone. Dan Dorfman had reported takeover rumors in three separate USA Today columns, beginning in August 1989. In April, three months before the announcement, both Reuters and Investor's Daily reported on speculation that a "Japanese or French concern" was interested in the company. (Accor S.A., the hotel conglomerate that eventually purchased the chain, is French.)<p>When, as the SEC alleges, Anderson offered Marsh the tip, Marsh considered it cautiously and weighed the information against what he already knew about the stock. When he entered the market in early June, he did so gingerly, putting on hedged options positions, a strategy that let him bet the direction of the stock without betting the farm. Because he claims he was nervous about the information, he was in and out of Motel 6 securities numerous times in the month before the takeover. All along, he discussed the deal with his father, who was also holding a sizable position.<p>According to the SEC, Marsh made $152,000 on the Motel 6 takeover; his father made twice that. In his initial answer to the SEC's charges, Marsh maintained that he never relied on Anderson's tip. The SEC didn't buy it. The fact that the Marshes were already closely following Motel 6 stock did not help their defense. To regulators, Anderson's tip, even if it weighed minimally in their investing, was still the most important information they received. As long as inside information played any role at all in their decisions, the SEC said, the investors were insiders. That view has been supported by federal courts, which, in insider cases, have refused to play mind reader and divine which parts of an investment were made based on public and which on nonpublic information.<p>Marsh, who now runs a tanning salon in Los Angeles, is also named in a class-action suit. He will most likely be charged with securities fraud by the Justice Department.
-- T.C.F.<p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

