	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-The Prophet of Pain</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Michael Hammer is the best-selling author behind much of the job cutting in corporate America. Watch out: He's not finished yet, as this conversation with Jesse Kornbluth indicates.<p>By Jesse Kornbluth<p>Only yesterday, it seems, reengineering wasn't even a word. Now it's fodder for anxious cocktail-party chatter everywhere -- a sign that Michael Hammer, prophet of reengineering, is far more than just another best-selling author. He's the business guru responsible for a wrenching new doctrine that has even successful companies slashing jobs. Hammer burst onto the scene with a 1990 Harvard Business Review piece that blasted ossified U.S. corporations. His prescription? Businesses should obliterate old structures and start over from the ground up -- reengineer, in his terminology.<p>A onetime professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Hammer recommended using computers to replace outdated processes. Figure out what needs to be done, he said, then arm a professional with the technology to do it. The result would be reduced costs, nimbler companies, and empowered employees. Last year, Hammer and James Champy expanded this argument in Reengineering the Corporation, which stayed on the New York Times best-seller list for 36 weeks.<p>As the paperback version now climbs the charts, Hammer is giving pricey seminars and working on a follow-up, Beyond Reengineering. His thoughts are parroted by corporate titans; observers compare him to a televangelist. Yet the 46-year-old Hammer insists he's not satisfied. Few people have heard his message whole, he says. Companies say they've reengineered when all they've done is dispense pink slips. Such half-measures, he fears, may doom reengineering to becoming little more than the latest buzzword.<p>In a characteristically blunt talk with Jesse Kornbluth, Hammer reaches as high as the White House to chastise the weakhearted.<p>
Q: Americans like their sermons upbeat and poster-simple. In that kind of culture, can you really be surprised that your hard words haven't sunk in?<p>A: One of the biggest challenges for me in the past year has been that the term reengineering is so accessible. People who have no clue actually think they're doing it -- reengineering has become a generic term for good. At every company I know, management goes off for a week and comes back with high-sounding platitudes printed on laminated cards. They're all the same. They're all pompous drivel.<p>Q: That's not shocking; you're asking us to take a huge leap of faith. Reinventing a business from scratch often costs jobs and always causes pain.<p>A: I don't say "reengineer or die" because I think it's interesting or attractive or fun or because I like hype. American companies are living in a fantasy world. We've survived this long only because the post-World War II period was a unique time -- the rest of the world was either undeveloped or destroyed. American companies thought they were smart; in fact, they were lucky. Now the world has changed, and the old way isn't nearly good enough.<p>Q: And the new way? After a brutal reengineering, survivors are somehow supposed to work together better than ever. I can see why people might be grateful to have jobs, but I can't imagine they'd have enough trust left to buy into team play.<p>A: It's a real conundrum. Reengineering produces an environment of autonomous professionals. But the experience itself is top-down authoritarian. It's like the Bible: You have to go through the desert to get to the promised land.<p>Q: It's interesting to hear you mention the Bible. You were raised in a traditional Jewish family and attended a yeshiva -- your training was to cherish values that last. Does the Bible support your new position as the apostle of radical change?<p>A: I say this with a straight face: The story of the Exodus is one of the most insightful examples of change management I've ever encountered. What's required for change? A wedge and a magnet: A wedge to get you off your chair, a magnet to lure you somewhere else. The wedge was the pharaoh and his army; the magnet was Moses and his vision.<p>Q: Any other lessons?<p>A: The leader can't take his eye off the ball. As soon as Moses goes up Mount Sinai to get the Ten Commandments, orgy and debauchery begin in the base camp. And look at how the Israelites change their view of manna. At first, they're thrilled that God has given them this food. Later they tell Moses, "We're tired of manna. We remember the fleshpots of Egypt, the fish, the cabbage, the onions. We want to go back." People focus on the pain of the present and the joy of the past. They forget about the pain of the past and the joy of the present.<p>Q: But I have trouble locating the joy in the present -- or at the end -- for many people touched by reengineering. What middle manager wants to lead the way to a promised land he won't reach himself?<p>A:This is where the analogy breaks down. Reengineering is a revolution of the top and bottom against the middle. Those who lose are administrators who no longer have professional skills or the talent to be leaders.<p>Q: And what do you say to such people, who will be vaporized by reengineering?<p>A: Get back in touch with the work you did that got you promoted. Or become an entrepreneur, although managers have abysmal records as entrepreneurs.<p>Q: So much of this depends on technology. Is anything coming that'll speed reengineering even more?<p>A: The most important technology has been around for a while -- electronic data interchange. EDI allows data to flow in an organized way from one computer system to another. Procter & Gamble can dial up Wal-Mart, for example, see what's been sold, and adjust production accordingly.<p>Q: That's a vision based on a profoundly un-American idea: sharing.<p>A: Sharing and trust are absolutely required. But I'm preaching enlightened self-interest -- not affection and mutual regard.<p>Q: Speaking of mutual regard, or lack of it, what induced the Clinton people to call you? The number-one priority in Washington is job preservation.<p>A: I was asked to give some input to Al Gore on the "reinventing government" effort last year. I spent some time with his staff, and spoke at a summit last year where they were talking about reengineering the U.S. government. It was ... an interesting experience.<p>Q: That's usually a euphemism.<p>A: Yes and no. I suspect a lot of people at the summit were looking for jobs with the administration, which made them very sycophantic. I could be more blunt: I told the Gore people that following through on their initiative was the single most important thing they could do on the domestic front.<p>Q: How so?<p>A: The president doesn't really create jobs; Alan Greenspan has a lot more say there. But if a president could improve the government's performance it would cause a ripple effect -- private-sector companies are often constrained by the complexity of dealing with the government. And a reengineered government could reconnect to the culture. Americans treat government as a joke. But if government were seen as efficient, it would reduce our cynicism.<p>Q: So what's happened since that speech?<p>A: At the time I said the real test would be if the Gore initiative were still in the papers in six months. Well, six months have passed and it isn't. And that's troubling. This requires so much energy. I see some commitment, but it really must be pushed from the top.<p>Q: Some people would say you advocate violating the social contract between management and labor. In Europe, you gave a talk so blistering that some listeners described you as a terrorist bent on kneecapping workers. Given your increasingly high profile, do you ever worry that someone who's been reengineered out of a job will come looking for you?<p>A: My wife does. I don't. Look, I didn't invent reengineering. It was already happening. All I did was clarify and accelerate it.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Publishing Industry, Government, Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
