		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Kamsky Hoists a Red Flag</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Kamsky Hoists a Red Flag</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>Virginia Kamsky is one of the original Western entrepreneurs in China. Now 40, she's been running her own consulting company from Beijing and New York since 1980. Curious, then, that pioneer Kamsky is advising caution just as other investors pile into China -- and just as she launches her own China fund this summer.<p>But Kamsky's new venture, a joint effort with Oppenheimer and Odyssey Partners, isn't like most of the 60-plus funds playing this fashionable market. Big Zhonghua Investment Management Partners -- it'll likely have raised over $200 million by year-end -- will invest directly in the nonpublic Chinese companies that dominate China's infant consumer-products industry. For instance, ZIM already has a controlling interest in a Shanghai ink factory that has a 25 percent market share in China.<p>The soft-spoken Kamsky says she's wary of the publicly traded Chinese and Hong Kong companies favored by other China funds: She believes that market is still too hot, despite a recent 33 percent drop in many issues. Direct investment, she hopes, will more reliably match the stellar past returns of funds that are now hurting.<p>Does Kamsky, who stuck it out in China through the horrors of Tiananmen Square, feel vindicated by the recent flood of Western money into the country? Well, partly. But mostly it makes her nervous. "Investors are not looking at the underlying economics," she says. "They want to be in China at any cost."<p>Kamsky says her goal is to stay in China long term, "not expatriate out dollars on a short-term basis." It's an aim for which she has the perfect resume. At 26, Kamsky started to sell advice on China to U.S. companies. Kamsky Associates was among the first U.S. companies to open shop in China. During the Tiananmen Square crisis, her office stayed open round the clock -- but she saw Western money retreat anyway.<p>And return. "Until 18 months ago, the planes flying in and out of Beijing were virtually empty," says Kamsky. "Today, you can't get a ticket." So what's her pick for the next great opportunity in China? "A chocolate company. The Chinese are crazy about chocolate."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
