<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Death of a Broker</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Death of a Broker</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Michael Prozumenshikov was known as the Mad Russian - nothing would stand in the way of the success he dreamed about. Then he met a madder Russian.<p>By Jeffrey Taylor<p>If his murderer's account can be trusted, Michael Prozumenshikov, a top-producing stockbroker for Prudential-Bache Securities, died at night on the frozen surface of Lake Minnetonka, his screams muffled by howling northern winds. The cause of death, police suspect, was a gunshot wound to the head, though it was impossible to establish this conclusively. Prozumenshikov's head and hands were never found. The rest of his body was discovered at a Christmas-tree dump in the Minnesota countryside, hacked to pieces. <p>It was a brutal and unlikely end to an equally improbable career. Prozumenshikov had bootstrapped himself up from a destitute childhood in Russia to the pinnacle of the U.S. securities business. He was one of Prudential's top 90 brokers nationwide and a key man in the firm's expansion into the affluent bedroom communities west of Minneapolis. Before joining Prudential, he had distinguished himself at Merrill Lynch and Drexel Burnham Lambert. His client list contained nearly 500 names, including wealthy Minneapolis businessmen and such local celebrities as Minnesota Vikings stars Scott Studwell and Tommy Kramer.<p>But there was a dark side to his success. Known to many of his colleagues as the Mad Russian, a nickname he loathed, Prozumenshikov harbored an almost pathological drive to get rich. Nothing stood in his way - especially not ethics. Though he generated huge commissions throughout his career, he also gained a reputation for playing fast and loose: He churned accounts, traded on inside information, and pushed even elderly investors into risky, highly leveraged trades. He soon gained a reputation in the tightly knit Russian community as someone who would take advantage of his fellow immigrants if it meant getting ahead. <p>Prozumenshikov shrugged off the criticism; he'd say his old friends were jealous of his lavish lifestyle. He drove a Mercedes-Benz, regularly ate at expensive restaurants, and lived in a palatial home in one of Minneapolis's poshest suburbs. He seemed incapable of self-doubt. If he liked a stock at all, for instance, he loved it unconditionally - even if circumstances called for something less than unqualified endorsement. "Clients are looking for someone who is forceful, who is convincing and has strong opinions," says Dean Hutton, one of Prozumenshikov's early bosses. "That's the way Michael was. He was absolutely sure of everything."<p><p>The drive that made Michael Prozumenshikov a star resulted from a childhood of deprivation in Leningrad that his bosses could scarcely comprehend. In Russia, the Prozumenshikov family shared a six-bedroom apartment with 28 other people. Everyone used a single bathroom and prepared meals in the same small kitchen. There was no hot water, and the cold water that ran out of the taps looked like tea. Until he was 17, Michael, an only child, slept in the same bedroom as his parents.<p>In school, he was a hard worker. He also excelled at sports, and though he'd shown little aptitude for science, his athletic skills helped him win admission to the First Leningrad Medical Institute - the city's best - where he studied to become a dentist. After earning his degree, he took a position in a Leningrad clinic. In 1977, he and his wife, Ellen, whom he'd met at dental school, decided to leave for the U.S.; this was made possible by the Helsinki Accords, which liberalized emigration policies for Soviet Jews. The couple decided to settle in Minneapolis, near Ellen's older brother.<p>For seven years Prozumenshikov tried to win accreditation as a dentist in the U.S. while Ellen worked as a dental hygienist. By 1984, he quit in frustration and, at the urging of a friend, began to teach himself about the stock market. In 1984, he landed a job at a small local brokerage firm and, within a few months, parlayed that position into a job at <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, the nation's biggest brokerage firm. "One thing was obvious," says Dennis Kellner, the Merrill Lynch sales manager who hired him. "This was a guy who needed to succeed - a guy who had been successful in obtaining some goals while in Russia but had to give that up and really had a burning need to regain what he had lost." <p>Prozumenshikov had all the makings of a good broker. He was a natural salesman and a hard worker. Most importantly, the tough streets of Leningrad had fitted him with not only a strong belief in his own personal superiority, but also an intense desire to prove it every day. "This business beats you up so bad that if you have low self-esteem, you internalize it," says John Kelly, another sales manager for Merrill Lynch. "Once you internalize it, it eats up your gut and you start thinking it's your fault. People with high self-esteem let it bounce off. They'll just say: 'It's too bad. That guy's not going to have a chance to work with me.'"<p>No account was too small for Prozumenshikov. He networked tirelessly among the Russian community, but he didn't content himself with merely being a broker to his countrymen. His dream was to fill his client list with rich Americans. Despite his limited command of English, he wasn't afraid to phone prospective clients, whose names he got from lists of known stock market investors, internal corporate directories, or just out of the phone book. "Other brokers would say, 'Gee, I couldn't call that guy. He's the chairman of <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>,'" a former colleague says. "But it didn't bother Michael." <p>Prozumenshikov routinely worked weekends, when he could reach prospects at home. Another method was waiting until 5 p.m. to call a businessman at his office; by then the secretary would be gone and the man was likely to pick up the phone himself. Prozumenshikov's pitch when cold calling was simple and direct. "Hello," he would say. "This is Michael Prozumenshikov of the investment firm Merrill Lynch" - or, as he pronounced it, May-rill Leench - "I'm calling because I'd appreciate the opportunity to make more money for you." Few people flatly refused the offer.<p>When he made a sale, he told his friends, he felt an exhilaration like nothing he could name, a wave of wonder and excitement that he, a Russian, was becoming a successful capitalist. His ambition drove him toward a single, overriding goal: He wanted to be rich. He grossed $200,000 in commissions during his first full year at Merrill Lynch, taking for himself about $75,000 of that total. Midway through his second year, he was already among the top ranks of Merrill's brokers nationally. But his boss, Kellner, was growing worried. Most new brokers at Merrill Lynch generated annual commissions worth about 1.5 percent of the total assets their clients invested at the firm. In a broker's second year, the pace of trading was expected to slow. Prozumenshikov, by contrast, brought in commissions worth 5 percent of assets during his first year and continued to generate far more than the norm in his second year. He once told another broker that it was his habit to do $2,000 worth of stock transactions every morning, whether market conditions justified them or not. Merrill had computer programs that culled trading records and spit out warnings when a broker's trading became too active; to Kellner's dismay, Prozumenshikov was lighting up the warning system like a pinball machine.<p>Among his colleagues, Prozumenshikov's sales exploits inspired both admiration and envy; it was at Merrill that he was first nicknamed the Mad Russian. Some colleagues sniffed at his raw aggression, suggesting that his approach might be better suited to the used-car business. But Prozumenshikov's formidable sales skills were in high demand. In 1986, he received a generous offer from Drexel Burnham Lambert. Drexel, flush with profits from Michael Milken's junk-bond operation, was looking to put together a brokerage network to rival national firms such as Merrill Lynch. Drexel paid him a $100,000 signing bonus and a 50 percent cut of the gross commissions he brought in during his first year at the firm (35 percent to 40 percent is the norm).<p>The three years that Prozumenshikov spent at Drexel Burnham Lambert made his career. They coincided with the greatest bull market in Wall Street's history, a happy accident that would help Prozumenshikov reap material rewards beyond the wildest fantasies of his youth.<p><p>Zachary Persitz, one of Michael Prozumenshikov's many Russian clients, had always known that his heart held many secrets he couldn't share with others. Julia, his wife, understood, and she accepted it. "He would have this calm time sometimes, when he would be very quiet," she says. "It was his way." It was, perhaps, a purging process that relieved Persitz's daily pain and salved the many wounds left over from his unhappy childhood in Russia.<p>Many parallels ran between the Persitz and Prozumenshikov families. Both families had emigrated from Leningrad to Minneapolis in the late '70s. Both had two sons, and the eldest in each family was named Daniel. The two Daniels were best friends. Daniel Persitz, who was tall for his age, became known as Danny Big, and Daniel Prozumenshikov, thinner and shorter, was Danny Little.<p>When it came to finances, the parallels ended. As Prozumenshikov reaped a six-figure income, Zachary Persitz held a modestly paying state job as a hydroelectrical engineer. Prozumenshikov used the couples' friendship, and their affinity as fellow Russians, to persuade Persitz to turn over his family's savings. As Persitz remembers it, Prozumenshikov promised to make the Persitz family's money grow at a rate of 18 percent a year without any risk - a guarantee that, if it was offered, violated both Drexel's rules and Minnesota's fraud statute.<p>Before he turned over his savings to Prozumenshikov, his wife says, Persitz had never cared much about money. But he was a compulsive organizer and list maker. When he bought a dog for his kids, he spent weeks studying different breeds. On family vacations, he would carefully map out each day's schedule in advance. And so, once he turned over his family money to his friend, Prozumenshikov became the primary target of Persitz's obsessive streak. He had an annoying habit of phoning Mica Duncan, Prozumenshikov's sales assistant at Drexel Burnham, and demanding that she calculate the balance of his account to the penny. Although she was busy, Duncan would dutifully perform the necessary calculations and phone Persitz back. "Pretty close," he would say. "You're only off by three bucks."<p>Persitz invested $100,000 with Prozumenshikov - most of it from a legal settlement his wife won after a car crash, the rest his mother's money. Prozumenshikov sank $48,000 of it into stock in Texas Air, airline executive Frank Lorenzo's then-vibrant company. Almost immediately after Persitz bought it, the stock's price sank. Unperturbed, Prozumenshikov, who said he was acting on insider information, put $21,000 more of the Persitz family's money into Texas Air, a commitment that made Zachary Persitz uneasy. "I knew from the newspapers that Texas Air was experiencing problems between the owner, Frank Lorenzo, and the unions," Persitz says. "I told Michael I don't particularly like this kind of investment because I don't think it's conservative. He told me that it is conservative and that he has some kind of inside information that this stock would do real well soon."<p>Persitz began to hear stories about his friend that only added to his anxieties. There was talk that Prozumenshikov promised returns he couldn't deliver. It was being said that he had bilked elderly people out of their retirement savings. From time to time, Persitz asked Prozumenshikov about the rumors he was hearing from other immigrants. Prozumenshikov dismissed the talk as nonsense. "Don't worry," he would say. "These people don't understand the market." Rather than calm Persitz down, the airy disclaimers only made him worry that Prozumenshikov was as indifferent to the Persitz account as he seemed to be about the earnings of his other clients.<p>For his part, Prozumenshikov thought Persitz's obsessiveness was just an extreme example of a trait common among his Russian clients. Many of them, he concluded, naively believed that the stock market was a one-way elevator to riches. They wanted only gains, he groused to his colleagues, and they were too bitter about the losses. Then came Black Monday, the stock market crash of 1987. Persitz suffered huge losses. But it wasn't just the money that bothered him. When Persitz tried to reach his broker that day, Prozumenshikov was on the phone with someone else and waved off the call. The snub roused Persitz's suspicions. Busy indeed, Persitz thought - probably busy protecting his own stock holdings while allowing Persitz and other clients to hang.<p>After the crash, the already strained friendship between the two men effectively ended. Persitz's account, heavily leveraged because he had withdrawn cash to pay for a new house and car, was devastated. His $69,000 Texas Air investment was now worth only $22,500. And in a period of four months, Persitz would receive margin calls demanding $10,000, $8,900, $6,300, and $4,000 to avoid forced sales of Texas Air and other devalued stocks from his account.<p>Because of the close bond between their wives and sons, the two men couldn't simply wash their hands of each other. Nonetheless, their relationship was hardly cordial. They could be outwardly pleasant to each other, but as the months passed and Texas Air failed to rebound, Persitz's anger only deepened. Persitz constantly phoned the broker to challenge his judgment, to provoke and rebuke him, to hiss at him about his failings. "Their conversations," says Mica Duncan, "would get very hostile. Michael would get off the phone and say, 'Zachary is so irrational.' He constantly wanted an accounting of what was going on, because Texas Air was down."<p>At social events with the Prozumenshikovs, Persitz was uncommunicative. He brooded through dinners, hoping to make Prozumenshikov feel uncomfortable. Sometimes Prozumenshikov caught Persitz glaring at him as their wives talked. Prozumenshikov, not a man to be intimidated, was unimpressed. Indeed, he went out of his way to tease Persitz, as on the occasion he noted that Persitz's constant worrying was giving him gray hair. Persitz just glared until his wife stepped into the awkward lull, smiled at her husband, and said, "I like gray-haired men." Later that same night, in the driveway outside the Prozumenshikov home, Prozumenshikov jibed Persitz again: "That car is a piece of shit," he said cheerfully, gesturing toward Persitz's beat-up old Mazda. "Why don't you buy a new one?"<p>Persitz stared at Prozumenshikov in disbelief. He and Julia were swimming in debt as it was. Prozumenshikov had to know they couldn't afford a new car. "You're right," Persitz said, not wanting to give Prozumenshikov the pleasure of seeing him rise to the taunt. "I guess I should."<p>"You son of a bitch," he said under his breath.<p><p>Brokerage firms are always looking for established brokers with big client lists to boost their commission earnings. By the same token, many good brokers are always looking around for a better deal. So by 1989, Prozumenshikov was ready to leave Drexel. The company, which had once symbolized the optimism of the Reagan boom, was now on the ropes - debt-ridden and vilified by a federal investigation of insider trading. In April of that year, Prudential-Bache offered Prozumenshikov a $240,000 bonus to help the company in its plan to expand into Minneapolis's well-heeled western suburbs.<p>Under the leadership of its chairman, George L. Ball - a man known for quirky, rambling memos, including one comparing his daughter's acne to troubles in investment banking - Pru-Bache had embarked on a sweeping program to lure top investment bankers, analysts, and stockbrokers. Ball had spent the '80s attempting to revolutionize the brokerage business. In 1981, when Prudential Insurance bought the Bache Halsey Stuart Shields brokerage group for $385 million, it created the nation's first "financial supermarket," a huge operation that brought together stock and bond brokerage with insurance and other financial services. By the time Michael Prozumenshikov signed on, Pru-Bache had become the nation's fourth-largest brokerage firm, with more than 7,000 stockbrokers and 17,000 employees overall.<p>Despite the steady growth, Pru-Bache had lost money in two of the past three years. What's more, Pru-Bache didn't always seem capable of controlling its brokers. In 1986, the firm had reached a landmark settlement with the Securities and Exchange Commission in a case involving improper trading and fraud at two of its branch offices. The SEC, concluding that the abuses demonstrated "deficiencies in Prudential-Bache's supervisory procedures," ordered the firm to scrap its method of overseeing its 300 branch offices and come up with a new one. Despite this cleanup operation, newspapers continued to chronicle troubling examples of abuses by brokers at the firm. Among other things, Prudential's clients lost about $1 billion investing in ill-conceived oil and gas partnerships, which the firm marketed during the height of the 1980s oil-price bust. After the biggest multistate investigation of securities fraud in Wall Street's history, Prudential agreed to pay $371 million in restitution and fines in 1993.<p>Not surprisingly, Prozumenshikov shrugged off his new company's problems. In letters to his clients, Prozumenshikov was upbeat: "Prudential-Bache is part of the Prudential network, $185 billion strong in assets," he wrote. "You will want to be associated with this rock solid, market wise firm as our valued customer."<p>Prozumenshikov's Pru-Bache signing bonus became the down payment on his largely self-designed dream home, an ultramodern mansion nestled in a suburban enclave that had once been a forest. This palace in the woods was a 15-minute drive along country roads to the Prudential-Bache office in the suburb of Wayzata. The branch occupied the ground floor of a three-story building of red brick and black granite and commanded a sweeping view of Lake Minnetonka.<p>Wayzata is a town full of mansions and old money; the executives of Minneapolis's biggest companies - Pillsbury, General Mills, Honeywell, Northwest Airlines, 3M, and others - live in the area. The local grocery store is called the Country Club Market. Amid this opulence, Prozumenshikov was hardly shy about showing off the symbols of his own success. A 24-karat gold bracelet dangled from his right wrist. On the left one, he wore a Rolex. On one plump finger, a large diamond glittered in a gold setting.<p>when the letter from prozumenshikov arrived asking Zachary Persitz to acquiesce in the transfer of his family's depleted brokerage accounts to Prudential-Bache Securities, Persitz was incredulous. "Thank you for your continued support," Prozumenshikov's letter said, "and most of all, thank you for your confidence." <p>But by now, Persitz had lost all confidence in his broker. The bulk of Persitz's remaining money was tied up in his 1,500-share stake of Texas Air. As he examined the business section of his newspaper on New Year's Day, 1990, Persitz noted that the stock had sunk further still. Texas Air was now trading for a pitiful $11.75 a share, and Persitz's original $69,000 investment was worth $17,625.<p>The two men still saw each other occasionally - their wives remained close - but among most of the Russian community, Prozumenshikov was persona non grata. At parties Persitz attended, other immigrants stung by the stock market crash called Prozumenshikov Michael the Ripper and openly discussed their hope that he would meet with an accident of some kind. Once, someone asked Persitz why he remained friends with "that bastard." Having long anticipated the question, Persitz had his answer ready. It was impossible to avoid Prozumenshikov, he said. The two families lived near one another, and their children were friends.<p>But Persitz had other motives. Maintaining relations with Prozumenshikov was part of a secret strategy for recovering his lost savings.  Persitz decided that Prozumenshikov was consciously misleading Russian investors. In the old country, a man trusted his friends, and most immigrants, in Persitz's view, had brought that bias with them - they assumed that other Russians would look out for their interests. When Prozumenshikov lost their money, Persitz felt, they couldn't just shrug it off. Friends didn't treat one another that way. In 1988, four Russian investors had unsuccessfully sued Prozumenshikov for restitution of trading losses. Persitz believed that lack of documentation defeated the complaint; all he had to do was get Prozumenshikov to sign an agreement verifying his verbal pledge to produce 18 percent yearly returns on Persitz's account. Then he could sue his onetime friend. He believed he was owed $200,000. <p>The plan was naive, to be sure, but Persitz clung to it, even as he was consumed with anger toward Prozumenshikov. Persitz began to see Prozumenshikov as a demonic presence, "bleeding me like a leech... holding me by the throat like I was dangling and all he needed to do was to let me go." <p>Prozumenshikov, for his part, was exasperated with Persitz. Old agreements, to Prozumenshikov's way of thinking, were irrelevant in the post-crash world. Investors had weathered the worst market cataclysm in history. Prozumenshikov had done what he could to minimize the damage in the Persitz account and position it advantageously for the future. Now he wished Persitz would leave him alone.<p>Through the spring of 1990, Persitz's physical condition began to mirror his mental deterioration. He dropped 20 pounds and suffered from abdominal pains. Never a sound sleeper, he was plagued with chronic insomnia. Many nights Julia found him downstairs, reading or simply staring into space as dawn approached, his hand resting on the family dog for comfort.<p>Whenever Persitz visited the Prozumenshikovs, he noted that Michael entertained with conspicuous extravagance. Original art, including a Miro print, lined the wall of his new house. A live-in nanny took care of the children. Meanwhile, the Persitzes could hardly pay the bills. Zachary brought home about $550 a week, Julia about $200. Their mortgage payment was $1,500, plus roughly $400 a month in property taxes. And soon the payment on the adjustable-rate mortgage would rise by $200 a month. They were using credit cards to pay the family's bills. Unlike Prozumenshikov, with his company-sponsored perk trips to posh resorts, the Persitzes hadn't been able to afford even a modest vacation for the past two years. When people asked why they didn't take holidays, Persitz lied, saying his work schedule didn't allow it.<p>Persitz's self-image as a capable and devoted family man was in tatters. He felt like a failure, he says, "as a parent, as a spouse, and as a son." Lately, he had even taken to refusing to answer the phone when he was home alone; it might be his mother, asking for some of her money. For this, he said later, "I hated myself." To his eternal shame, he had even taken $1,000 from the money his elder son was saving to buy a computer. "It was getting real bad," he says. "I just didn't know what to do." With his family income likely to remain more or less constant until he and Julia retired, there seemed to be no prospect that things would ever improve.<p>In January of 1991, Zachary and Julia attended a birthday party at Prozumenshikov's house for his younger son, Ariel. The party was really for the adults, who celebrated the birthdays of their children together as a matter of Russian custom. Persitz watched as Prozumenshikov circulated among the guests. When he saw the chance, he drew Prozumenshikov aside. For what seemed like the hundredth time, he asked Prozumenshikov for an agreement formalizing his financial commitment to the Persitz family. "I said, 'Let's go to your office so that you can write it and give it to me. It will take us five minutes,'" Persitz says. "He said, 'No, I can't. I'm with my guests. I'll mail it to you in a couple of days.'"<p>At work the following week, Persitz did everything he could to avoid leaving his office, anticipating that Prozumenshikov might call about the agreement. Each day at 5 p.m., he hurried home to check his mail. By Friday, no agreement had arrived, and Persitz knew at last what he had to do. Cool reason replaced the confusion in his brain.<p>The following Monday, January 28, was gloomy and cold. A light snow fell all day. At the end of the day, Persitz drove to Wayzata and parked outside the Prudential-Bache office. He sat in his car until he saw Prozumenshikov's black Mercedes glide out of the underground parking lot at 6:30 p.m. He opened his car door and stepped out. With one foot in the car and one in the snow of the street, he hailed Prozumenshikov with a wave of his hand. Prozumenshikov stopped his car and rolled down his window. Persitz hollered out to him, asking whether they could talk. "Sure," Prozumenshikov said, looking a little confused.<p>Persitz climbed back into his car and drove across the street to a parking lot abutting the frozen surface of Lake Minnetonka. Prozumenshikov followed, parked his car there, and stepped into Persitz's beat-up Mazda, leaving his wallet in a briefcase on the front seat of his own car.<p><p>On each day of the murder trial of Zachary Persitz, the Prozumenshikov and Persitz families arrayed themselves on opposite sides of the spectators' gallery. To impartial observers, they resembled guests at a wedding, bride's side to the left and groom's side to the right. But despite the awkward intimacy of the 36-seat gallery, the two sides never spoke. And neither Ellen Prozumenshikov nor Julia Persitz so much as nodded at each other. Once the best of friends, they hadn't spoken to one another since Persitz was arrested over two years before.<p>Each day at 9:30 a.m., the jury of nine women and three men filed into the courtroom, followed by Judge Robert Schiefelbein. When everyone was settled, two guards led Persitz himself into the courtroom through a rear door to the table he shared with his defense attorneys, Joe Friedberg and Paul Engh.<p>Persitz was charged with the premeditated murder of Michael Prozumenshikov. The first week of the four-week trial featured a devastating presentation of the state's evidence against Persitz. For starters, three employees of a car wash in St. Paul had identified Persitz as having hired them to clean blood out of his car trunk on the morning after Prozumenshikov's murder. In Persitz's house, police had found records attesting to the sorry state of his family finances at the time of the murder. They also found a receipt for a pair of handcuffs, purchased a month before the murder at a police-supply store. Scrawled in the margins of  Persitz's appointment calendar were a number of notations about handguns.<p>Persitz's lawyers tried to get the charges against their client reduced to manslaughter. They put him on the stand and had him confess to the killing. Persitz claimed that he had never planned to kill Prozumenshikov. All he wanted was to force Prozumenshikov to sign the agreement pledging to repay the Persitz family's losses.<p>Persitz admitted driving Prozumenshikov onto the frozen surface of Lake Minnetonka and forcing him to put on a pair of handcuffs. The real trouble, Persitz said, began after Prozumenshikov asked to have the handcuffs removed because he couldn't sign an agreement while wearing them. And at that point, rather than signing the agreement Persitz had prepared, Prozumenshikov declared that he had to "take a piss," Persitz testified.<p>The two of them climbed out of the car and urinated, not far from one another, on the frozen lake, Persitz said. Suddenly, Persitz said, Prozumenshikov began walking quickly toward his car, which was parked on the shore, about 300 yards away. Persitz jumped back into his own car and wheeled around to intercept Prozumenshikov. Prozumenshikov couldn't run in his flat-soled leather shoes. "He was like a duck on the ice," Persitz said in a dull monotone.<p>Standing only a few yards apart, the two men began shouting at one another, Persitz went on. "I was calling him a crook, different names," he said. "He was calling me a dirty Russian immigrant, you know, the same like everybody else, something like that. And he was shouting at me that I am just jealous of his success and stuff. And I told him that this is all bullshit because I never was jealous of him, I never would want to work like him, to do to people what he does. Anyway, the arguments were getting hotter and hotter. I sent him to hell; he sent me to hell."<p>As Persitz spoke, the weeping of Michael Prozumenshikov's mother, Ida, became audible from the spectators' gallery. <p>"We were shouting for another few minutes," Persitz continued, "and then at the very end he shout at me in Russian. He shouted at me - " Here Persitz broke off his testimony and, much louder, spoke a phrase in Russian. "It means," he continued in English, "I fuck you and fuck your family.<p>"And then what happened is that I was looking at him, I saw his lips moving and he was close, but I couldn't hear what he was saying. Everything was very quiet around me, and then I was feeling that my head hurts from the cold.<p>"I looked around me, and I didn't see Michael. I looked down and he was laying on the snow. And I had gun in my right hand, so I couldn't believe it. I bent down on my knees, and his body was all limp. He didn't breathe."<p>To the horror of everyone in the courtroom, Persitz even described using a hatchet to dismember Prozumenshikov's dead body - because, he said, he was afraid Prozumenshikov's ghost would return to haunt him. Persitz threw the broker's head and hands into a river, he said, in an unsuccessful attempt to prevent identification of the body. He told of the days that followed the killing, of disbelief, of weeping when Prozumenshikov's son Daniel came to stay at his house after the killing.<p>The jury found Zachary Persitz guilty of first-degree murder. After a second, shorter stage of the trial, in which psychiatrists for the state and the defense presented contradictory accounts of Persitz's mental health, the jury found Persitz accountable for his actions despite a plea of insanity. Judge Schiefelbein sentenced him to life in prison. <p>In July 1993, Persitz entered Stillwater Prison on the St. Croix River, five miles from where he dismembered Michael Prozumenshikov's body. From there he was transferred to Oak Park Heights, a maximum-security prison built into a hillside in rural Minnesota. Authorities use the facility to house the most violent of all criminals as well as those who are considered escape or suicide risks. <br>
---------------<br>
This article is adapted from "The Pru-Bache Murder," published this month by HarperCollins.<p><p>

