	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Way To Surpass Ten-Grand Limit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Way To Surpass Ten-Grand Limit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Leave loved ones more than ever with Cristofani trusts<p>By Donald Jay Korn<p>Most people hate the notion that when they die, Uncle Sam may take more than half of the assets they leave behind. One of the best strategies for people to avoid draconian estate taxes (which can run as high as 55 percent) is to give assets to their heirs while they're alive. Taxpayers, however, are allowed to give away only $10,000 of assets per year to any one person. (Married couples can give away $20,000.) Above those limits gift taxes kick in, which can be as high as estate taxes.<p>In 1984, Maria Cristofani found a way to legally exceed the limits by more than 300 percent and pay no taxes. But taxpayers who want to use her strategy should act as soon as possible--the loophole probably won't stay open forever.<p>Cristofani, a widow with two children, Frank and Lillian, established a trust. She transferred real estate valued at $70,000 into it in 1984 and again in 1985. She did not file any gift-tax returns. The trust was set up with her children as the prime beneficiaries. At her death, the assets were to be split between the two children, who were twins. <p>Then Cristofani died. Her estate contended that there were seven trust beneficiaries--Frank, Lillian, and five grandchildren. The grandchildren, aged 2 through 11, were named secondary beneficiaries. If either Frank or Lillian failed to outlive Maria by 120 days, that child's children would split his or her share. Therefore, Maria was entitled to give $10,000 per year to each of them, and the $70,000 gifts incurred no gift tax.<p>The IRS demanded back taxes, arguing that the grandchildren were not bona fide gift recipients because their right to the trust fund was too contingent to be recognized. The IRS said that $20,000 could be excluded but the other $50,000 per year was subject to gift tax. <p>The tax court shot down the IRS argument. The court ruled that the grandchildren did have an interest in the trust; after each contribution, the trustees (Frank and Lillian) were required to give written notice to the beneficiaries (Frank, Lillian, and the five grandchildren). Then, each beneficiary had a 15-day period in which to withdraw up to $10,000 (called a Crummey power, after a landmark case). Thus, Maria Cristofani had been entitled to the $10,000 gift-tax exclusion for each grandchild and effectively transferred $140,000 in assets to her two children in two years, without owing gift tax.<p>This means that multiple-beneficiary trusts now can be used to expand the gift-tax exclusion. "Follow Cristofani as closely as possible," says David Rhine, tax partner and national director of estate planning for the accounting firm BDO Seidman. The key is that trust beneficiaries must have a real interest in the trust. "In Cristofani, there was a slim chance that the grandchildren could inherit the entire trust proceeds," says Rhine, "so there was a reason they would not exercise their Crummey power." <p>Future laws may limit use of the gift-tax exclusion or abolish Crummey powers. But gifts made before such a law is proposed or passed likely will be grandfathered.. So act soon if you want to make large, estate-reducing gifts. "The IRS has announced that it doesn't like the decision, but it won't appeal," says Gerald Morlitz, director of advanced estate planning for Cowan Financial Group in New York. "I use this technique to the greatest extent I can."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Taxation, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
