<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Balancing a Marital Ledger</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Balancing a Marital Ledger</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Postnuptial agreements can help resolve disputes<p>By Mary Rowland<p>It's hardly a secret that money differences are a frequent source of conflict between married couples. But even worse than fights over money are the consequences when partners fail to openly address or deal with the issues involved. Long-simmering resentments can build up and undermine the foundation of a relationship.<p>Resolving disputes can be painful, but better to do so before they cripple a relationship --or lead to the even more painful process of a messy divorce. That's one of the concepts behind postnuptial agreements. At their best, these legal pacts between husband and wife can relieve tension and improve a marriage. If the marriage does end, they can make divorce less painful. In contrast to prenuptial agreements, postnuptial agreements also offer the opportunity to negotiate at a more mature stage in a relationship, when a couple's understanding of each other is probably more realistic than it is prior to marriage.<p>Experts who handle such agreements say that the same people who consider the idea a waste of time are often the ones who feel unfairly dealt with in a divorce. Divorce courts look at all the property acquired by the couple. Often assets one spouse thought were his or hers become marital property and get handed over to the other partner. "The divorce laws work if you perceive that each of you contributed equally to the marriage," says Helene Brezinsky, a partner at the New York law firm of Rosenman & Colin. "But if you have a festering issue that you have not made equal contributions, a postnuptial agreement is the only way to deal with it." <p>Here are some situations that might merit a postnuptial agreement: <p>--One partner comes into a large amount of money from his or her family. "I've seen so many occasions where the wife inherits some money and the husband thinks it should be his, too," Brezinsky says. "It becomes a constant area of dispute unless it is settled in writing." <p>--The family of one spouse is reluctant to include that person in a business because they fear the other spouse could then lay claim to some of the assets. "We have a case in our office where the husband's family runs a small accounting firm," Brezinsky says. "They want to make the husband a partner, but they first want an agreement that the wife will never be able to look at the company." <p>--Money conflicts sap the energy of both partners, and neither can focus on the other aspects of the relationship. "If money is your principal area of dispute, an agreement can be quite constructive," Brezinsky says. "I have drawn up agreements for couples who could not continue in the marriage unless they resolved the money issue. Usually one is a spender and one is a saver, and the saver cannot sit and watch the partner dissipate everything he or she has saved." One of Brezinsky's clients was a serious art collector who poured much time and energy into her collection. She wanted an agreement detailing the artwork that she had collected and stating that it belonged to her. "It was her passion, and she was killing herself to acquire it," Brezinsky says. "She couldn't feel comfortable until she had this piece of paper acknowledging that it was hers." <p>--The relationship is poor--or over--but divorce is not the right solution at the moment. For example, Violet Woodhouse, a divorce lawyer and financial planner in Costa Mesa, California, represents a retired man in his 60s who is separated from his 40-year-old wife. They have a 10-year-old son. He came in for a divorce. But the potential financial impact caused them to reconsider. She earns $75,000; he earns $16,000 in pension income. She relies on his excellent medical plan. If they divorced, she would be forced to pay alimony. And she would lose access to the health plan. The two decided on a postnuptial agreement that retitled their rental properties so each controlled a portion of them, allow the wife to remain on her husband's insurance plan, and made financial arrangements for their son's college education.<p>--One or both partners have mixed assets together--or "commingled" them--when that was not their intention. "If you have separate property and you keep it separate and the spouse has no involvement in it, that's fine," says Renee Schwartz, a partner at Kronish, Lieb, Weiner & Hellman in New York. "But if you invest it in a condo with your spouse, without an agreement, that probably will turn it into joint property." Consider the case of a financial planner in California who received a large inheritance from her grandmother. She happily used a big chunk of it to make a down payment on the family home, assuming that her husband knew that "it was really my money." As she began to specialize in divorce work, she learned that money that is commingled becomes marital property. Assets that one spouse brings into the marriage--inheritances, family property, a home, apartment, or investments--may be deemed marital property and split in half at divorce. The key is whether the assets remained totally separate property, in a separate account, or were jointly owned. In this planner's case, it was clear that she had mingled her inheritance with her husband's money. The planner bit the bullet and told her husband she wanted a postnuptial agreement. "It wasn't easy, and I won't say that he was thrilled," she said. "We had been married for 15 years already. It was a difficult process." But they eventually transferred ownership of the house so that they held it as tenants in common. <p>The rules for writing a postnuptial agreement are much the same as those for a prenup. It should be prepared well in advance of signing; each partner must disclose all assets and liabilities; each should be represented by an attorney; the agreement should detail the property to be transferred; and the agreement should be notarized. "You have to make sure there is no coercion or duress and that it is not unconscionable," Brezinsky says. "You must have a fair document, not something scribbed on a napkin at midnight." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
