<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Wedding, No; Benefits, Yes</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Wedding, No; Benefits, Yes</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
But unwed-partner plans come with complications<p>By Mary Rowland<p>Although the plans remain controversial, at least 100 employers now offer some form of "domestic partner" benefit plan for unmarried employees. Such plans have an obvious appeal for nontraditional families that wouldn't otherwise receive health insurance and other benefits under their employer's plan. They also appeal to employers who advocate liberal human-rights policies.<p>Yet for those who sign up, there are important tax and legal consequences to consider. Often, these create complications that are serious enough to stop potential participants from enrolling. Employers have also taken flak for instituting the plans in the first place. In December, a Texas county effectively blocked <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a> from building an $80 million office complex. The reason: County residents objected to the morality of Apple's unwed-partner benefits plan. <p>Some companies offer benefits to both heterosexual and homosexual partners, while others include only homosexuals. "Employers who offer only same-sex coverage take the view that opposite-sex partners could get married if they chose," says Mark Wagoner, author of The Domestic Partner Sourcebook. <p>Employers normally require that partners show evidence that they have a permanent or ongoing relationship. A lease agreement, mortgage, or deed that the partners have cosigned might serve this purpose. So might auto- or life-insurance policies. "It might be as simple as having a joint checking or savings account," says Wagoner. Many employers also require domestic partners to sign an affidavit affirming the nature of their relationship. <p>Before enrolling, however, employees need to know two things. First, the benefits are taxable income to the employee because the Internal Revenue Service doesn't recognize such partners as dependents. Second, and perhaps more important, the signing of partnership affidavits that some employers require may have legal consequences, including giving partners rights to each other's property in the event the relationship ends. "One thing that has kept enrollments lower than anticipated is that once the partner has a signed affidavit in hand, he or she would have legal recourse if the relationship broke up," says Michael Bross, a consultant at the Wyatt Co., a benefits and compensation consulting firm. <p>How great are the risks? Each case should be decided on its own merits. Couples should assume that if they end the relationship, one partner may file a suit against the other, claiming a share of community assets. Some employees undoubtedly also worry about letting employers into their private lives, despite the fact that personnel information is required to be kept strictly confidential and discrimination is illegal, at least at larger companies.<p>Many employees who might qualify often decide not to participate. The University of Iowa has over 15,000 employees, but when it expanded benefits to cover nontraditional families, only 18 signed up. Of 3,300 U.S.-based workers at Lotus, only 15 or so have signed up. <p>A couple of domestic-partner plans have been in place since the early 1980s. But it wasn't until Lotus implemented such a plan in 1991, followed by Levi Strauss in 1992, that they began to receive serious attention. Today, a large percentage of domestic-partner benefit programs are at universities, city governments, and high-tech companies. Roughly half extend benefits only to gay partners; the other half include both gays and unmarried heterosexual partners.
 <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
