		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-...Almost</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-...Almost</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Darrell Zimmerman had a brilliant plan to beat the world's largest bond pit. It was a wild shot, and it worked...<p>
By Ted C. Fishman<p>
The ninth time Darrell Zimmerman went broke trading futures, he decided not to tell his wife. Lisa never took such news well. Once, she knocked him to the ground and pummeled his chest with her fists--right in front of other traders. Lisa also had been tense lately, ever since they'd had to sell their car to pay the rent. So Darrell was relieved that she'd been out that night and hadn't heard anything about his kamikaze trading. The next day, on his way to get the newspaper, he figured he'd just pull out the business section and maybe Lisa would never have to know. But there was his story on the front page, below a headline that bellowed: wild bond spree jolts chicago board of trade. <p>
That made two plans that week that didn't turn out the way Zimmerman had hoped. <p>
On October 22, 1992, he had walked onto the floor of the world's largest futures exchange with an incredibly bold plan, one he had spent most of the summer concocting. With only a bad check for $50,000 in his trading account, he would execute a rapid-fire series of trades in hopes of controlling the action in the huge Treasury-bond pit. His goal was to orchestrate a panic. But it was supposed to be a controlled panic. If the other traders played into his hands, he would become a very rich man. He needed only about 15 minutes.<p>
Zimmerman launched his attack at 7:25 a.m. For the first few minutes, the market went crazy, and just as he predicted, the momentum in the pit swung in his favor. At one point, he controlled enough contracts to leverage $3.6 billion in bonds. His profit climbed toward $5 million.<p>
But Zimmerman did not get rich that day. Instead, he lost control. By 7:40 a.m. security guards were hauling him off the trading floor, leaving mass confusion behind. By the time order returned to the pits, Zimmerman's actions had ruined an old-line trading firm, Lee B. Stern & Co., raised serious doubts about the Board of Trade's markets, and changed forever the way business at the nation's securities exchanges is done. The episode remains one of the most controversial--and least understood--to take place on the floor of a major U.S. exchange.<p>
Darrell Zimmerman is now on the lam. I found him in Vancouver, British Columbia, beyond the reach of the federal authorities who indicted him last summer. He still doesn't quite understand why the Board of Trade, the press, and the FBI made such a fuss over his trading. As he sees it, he was just doing what everyone in the pits dreams about--taking as much money from the next guy as possible. <p>
Every trader fantasizes about taking a wild shot and retiring. In Chicago, the dream is called the "O'Hare spread." The idea is to put on an insanely large position and head to the airport. If at the end of the day the position makes money, you head to Hawaii; if it loses, it's off to South America. Zimmerman's plan didn't work out quite that way.<p>
For seven years he shuttled back and forth between Chicago's two big trading floors--the Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange--convincing people to stake him and then losing ever-larger sums. One of his former bosses still has what he calls "Darrell Zimmerman nightmares." Yet, because trading firms do not have to pass information about their former traders to competitors, he was repeatedly able to resurface on the trading floors.<p>
Zimmerman had a gift for talking people into giving him money. He exuded the enthusiasm many salesmen spend lifetimes trying to perfect. He seemed manic and easygoing at the same time. Asked why so many people had a hard time saying no to her husband, Lisa says it's "because he's so good looking. That smile and those eyes had an effect on them." I traded against Zimmerman in the pits of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange for five years. He was a fascinating combination of skill, guts, and whim, a lightning-quick trader who refused to let the markets discipline him, a guy other traders bad-mouthed and envied. <p>
"I did in the bond pit what every trader dreams about," Zimmerman says. "You spend half of every day thinking about what would happen if you could trade large enough to move a market by yourself, to play like the big firms and banks do. I had everyone in the pit coming to me. I was the market. The exchanges just don't want to admit the market can be controlled by one guy, especially by someone like me, but I proved it can. Almost."<p>
The chicago board of trade is housed in a grand limestone building that sits like a huge armchair at the dead end of LaSalle Street, the epicenter of Chicago's financial district. The first contracts traded on the exchange 130 years ago allowed farmers, grain processors, and merchants to establish prices for commodities months in advance of their actual shipment, helping to insulate producers and commercial users from the risk of price swings and transferring much of that risk to professional speculators.<p>
In the 1970s, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange--the Board of Trade's longtime rival--began trading futures on foreign currencies. That stimulated an explosion in contracts on stock indexes, bonds, and other financial instruments. A decade later, the transformation was complete: Financial pits outnumbered agricultural pits in Chicago. For a few years inefficiencies in the markets made trading lucrative and not terribly difficult. Chicago became a magnet for traders, most of them young men, just out of school, accustomed to minimum-wage jobs. With a few thousand dollars anyone could leverage millions in the pits. Some became very wealthy; others arrived with big bank accounts and ran them dry.<p>
The lure of easy riches is what attracted Darrell Zimmerman. When he arrived in Chicago from Vancouver, where he grew up, Zimmerman was wearing the only suit he owned. He carried a change of clothes in his small bag and had $200 in his pocket. He'd moved to Chicago on the vague promise of a job from the CCJ Group, a retail trading firm with offices in the Board of Trade. Zimmerman thought a firm with a fancy-sounding name like that must be important, so he was dismayed when he actually visited CCJ's shabby, overcrowded offices. "I was greeted by one of the brokers, Jeff Sherman," Zimmerman says. "He cracked up. Me, my bag in hand, straight from the airport, was the funniest thing he'd ever seen." There was no job, but Sherman took pity on the greenhorn trader and invited Zimmerman to stay with him for a while.<p>
Sherman lived in DePaul, a recently gentrified neighborhood on Chicago's North Side. He was only 23, and Zimmerman, who had never been able to afford his own place, was awestruck. Sherman had all new furniture, a giant-screen TV, and a huge stereo. "He told me what he had was nothing compared to some of his friends with condos on the lake and sports cars," says Zimmerman. "I thought I died and went to heaven." <p>
Zimmerman stayed on Sherman's couch for two weeks before moving into a flophouse to make room for his host's girlfriend. But he had made inroads into the Chicago Board of Trade, landing there as a clerk, a mostly menial job that is most traders' entree to the floor. Zimmerman's clerkship lasted only two weeks. One night he met a young trader who was also a recruiter for a rapidly emerging firm, the Singer-Wenger Trading Co. He told Zimmerman to come by the next day to meet the boss. <p>
Norm Singer was closer to what Zimmerman had in mind when he thought of the romance of the trading floors. Singer, in his early 40s, was tall and tan, tailored, manicured, and pomaded. He wore a jeweled Rolex watch and ran his company from a large, marble-appointed office.<p>
Singer's success depended on keeping the expanding numbers of trading pits populated with his own people. He favored athletes. "He wanted people with stamina and an in-your-face attitude to make it in the pits," says Mitch Joseph, who started out at the firm when Zimmerman did and later became his best friend there. "Darrell was very good at tennis, skiing, and whatever else he tried. And he was very competitive."<p>
Singer told Zimmerman he would need $100,000 to trade on his own and then pledged to back him. All Zimmerman had to do first was perform well in the firm's mock-trading sessions. Up until then, Darrell Zimmerman had probably never struck anyone as particularly bright. He rarely sat still long enough to make an analysis of anything. That changed at the Singer-Wenger practice trading sessions, where he competed against others for fictitious trades and a job. The prices at the Board of Trade are quoted fractionally like stocks, and novices frequently bollix the fractional math. But Zimmerman could add, subtract, and multiply the fractions with unusual speed. He was hired to trade at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, known in the business as the Merc.<p>
"It was like Darrell was destined to trade," Joseph says.<p>
But Zimmerman was as much a born hustler as a born trader. For five years, he had worked the shady edges of the Vancouver futures business, but he concealed this fact from his new employers: Norm Singer liked his recruits to be green, figuring that people with trading experience would be resistant to his highly disciplined system. <p>
Singer-Wenger assigned Zimmerman to the enormous Standard and Poor's 500 Stock Price Index futures pit at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. The S&P contract is one of the world's most actively traded. It allows speculators and hedgers to take large positions on the stock market without actually buying common stock. Zimmerman was one of 300 traders wedged into a steep circle of stairs. In his novel Ghost Waves, James McManus describes such a pit as looking like "a brawl in a gumball machine, just one manic orgy of moxie." Brokers and speculators traded tens of billions of dollars' worth of contracts daily, but Singer-Wenger limited its newer traders to two contracts at a time. "Usually the small traders in a pit are invisible," says Mitch Joseph, "but somehow Darrell soon had a reputation as being a little off the wall, a little bit on edge." Zimmerman mouthed off to bigger traders and picked fights over small trades. He also had problems staying within the firm's trading limits. "We'd have group meetings where Darrell was told the firm needed him to scale back," Joseph says. "He'd agree, but then he would double up his position. He was always getting stuck with bigger positions and lots of risk." <p>
Zimmerman managed to do well enough for Singer-Wenger to keep him on. After a while, the firm moved him to one of the Merc's slower pits: live-cattle futures options. He was instructed to stay in the pit at all times and to update prices by continually calling them out to the pit. Like other Singer-Wenger traders, he had to carry pages and pages of computer "cheat sheets," printouts that priced all the options in a pit. The firm's idea was to enforce a kind of disciplined stupidity that would prevent traders from making their own calls on the markets. Other traders referred to them as "sheet monkeys." That was not the respect Zimmerman hoped for from a trading career.<p>
Zimmerman was increasingly driven by the intensity of life in the pits. He thrived on the competition, especially in the cattle-options pit, which tends to attract less-capitalized traders, many dependent on every trade for survival. Tensions were always high, bickering and name-calling common. On slow days tirades could erupt over $10 transactions. One trader in the pit described his fantasy of a great day as "showing up and finding that all the other traders had died and I got their money."<p>
A frequent distraction for Zimmerman was his future wife, Lisa Tatkus, a broker's clerk in the S&P pit. Smitten by his good looks and energetic charm, Tatkus quickly became Zimmerman's constant companion off the floor. Reflecting back on the first years of their relationship, neither Zimmerman nor Tatkus recalls discussing any significant issues with each other, and they rarely talked trading. "All Darrell ever wanted was to have fun, and he was very good at it." Tatkus says. They got married after a trip to Canada in June of 1987. They hadn't exactly planned on it, but when U.S. border officials refused to let Zimmerman back into the States because he didn't have a work permit, he asked Lisa to marry him. "I realize now," she said recently, "he married me so he could trade."<p>
The couple had a violent fight before work on October 19, 1987, Black Monday, the stock market crash.  Lisa says she was angry at her husband because she thought his highly leveraged positions were too risky. For most of the morning, the cattle pits were calm as Zimmerman watched the quote boards on the exchange's walls flashing huge losses in the equity markets. Finally the crash spilled onto every market--the meats, the currencies, and the bonds joined the frenzy. Bets that the markets would drop in the form of put orders flooded the pit, as hedgers scrambled to protect themselves against a meltdown. In the middle of the panic, Lisa walked by and gave him the finger. Between his quarrel with Lisa and the terror sweeping the pits, Zimmerman could stay still no longer. Too much money was changing hands without him. Impulsively--partly to spite his wife, partly to show he wasn't afraid--Zimmerman sold 250 puts. Not only was this trade more than ten times larger than his firm allowed on a normal day, but it represented a bet that the market would go up. He lost $60,000 and his job. Lisa got fired, too. And yet Darrell remembers feeling an odd sense of calm. He may have lost big, but didn't that prove he was a big trader?<p>
The course of Zimmerman's career at Singer-Wenger would play itself out again and again at different firms over the next five years. He would convince someone to stake him in exchange for a share of his trading profits. He would begin by trading well--sometimes very well--for a period of time and then accumulate a position that either lost money or carried so much risk that Zimmerman was turned out. "We led a very uncertain life," says Tatkus. "We were always moving in and out of different apartments. I just never knew what was going to happen." One of Zimmerman's backers, who asked to be spared attribution "because Zimmerman's name is poison,offered a reason why traders like Zimmerman do well, then fail. "Going through the markets is like going through psychoanalysis," he said. "If you have any self-destructive tendencies, the market is going to find them and hit you with them." <p>
By 1988, trading the newer futures and options instruments was considerably more difficult than it had been just three years before when Zimmerman came to Chicago. Traders and customers were more sophisticated, inefficiencies were more easily spotted, and making money required much more risk. The lone-wolf traders, those who traded their own money for their own accounts, became scarce. Trading now required the latest and fastest computer analyses, sophisticated risk management, and an organization that could simultaneously work related markets on different exchanges. Many of the lone wolves joined broker groups to share the expertise and expenses needed to survive the markets. For Zimmerman, who hated the hard work of analyzing positions, trading groups made business increasingly difficult and less fun.<p>
He eventually landed with Steve Klee. Klee still cannot fathom why he didn't fire Zimmerman a lot sooner than he did. He thinks it has something to do with pity, or maybe that, against all his instincts, he just liked Zimmerman. "I felt so sorry for this guy, and I really wanted to help him," Klee told Board of Trade investigators. "I kept making agreements, and he'd sign these things: 'I will never do this,' 'I will never do that,' 'I will always do this.'" At one point, Klee even sent Zimmerman for a psychiatric evaluation.<p>
In April of 1989, Zimmerman, tired of Klee's parameters, decided to get out. Before he left, though, Zimmerman decided to make one last big play with Klee's money. "Darrell was supposed to be trading 50 [contracts at a time]  but he sold 900 calls, something we just never, ever, ever do," says Klee. "He kept 300 of them a secret. I remember being left with the feeling that not only had he completely violated the trading and risk parameters that we established   but that he had committed fraud of a sort." Fearing the fate of his firm hung in the balance, Klee liquidated Zimmerman's position himself and lost $50,000. Yet he still felt sorry for Zimmerman when he fired him. Klee invited Zimmerman to visit his office with Lisa so he could explain. "In the middle of the conversation, his wife got up out of her chair and beat the living hell out of him," Klee says. "He obviously told her a story that bore no resemblance to the facts."<p>
Zimmerman's reckless trading with his various bosses' money provided a semiregular source of income--and a regular source of jokes--for the other traders in the cattle-options pit. "We loved it," says a trader who made money off of Zimmerman's fumbles. The other traders began to refer to such episodes as a Darrell Day.<p>
Zimmerman's next partnership was with a trader named Paul Leventhal. It was lucrative at first. In 1989 Zimmerman's account made $250,000. He bought two cars--including a Mercedes--and lived in a deluxe duplex in the DePaul neighborhood. But the firm responsible for guaranteeing Zimmerman's trades, called a clearing corporation, was not confident his fortunes would last.<p>
A clearing corporation is a trader's lifeline to the pits. It performs the banking and bookkeeping necessary for traders to conduct their business. A clearing firm also guarantees the trades of all its trader clients. In return, it collects commissions on trades and interest on the money it lends traders for margin. "The biggest red flag for that risk is when a trader sells high numbers of puts and calls," says an officer of Hammer Trading, the firm that cleared for Leventhal and Zimmerman. "And he sold way more than we allow. We told him to go, but I still have Darrell Zimmerman nightmares." <p>
Hammer, which had a long-term clearing relationship with Leventhal, told him to lose Zimmerman or find another clearing firm, On his own again, Zimmerman moved to First Commercial Financial Group and opened an account with his own money. It was his inaugural outing as an independent trader. For the first year and a half, Zimmerman traded well. By December 1990, First Commercial put enough faith in the relationship to lend Zimmerman $65,000, half the cost of an options membership, or seat, at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Zimmerman paid the other half in cash. "I always measured my success by the dollar value of my account listed on my daily statement," Zimmerman says. "When I took the money out to buy my seat, it felt like I lost it."So Zimmerman began to trade even more furiously, accumulating large options positions. Shortly afterward, the gulf war hit, the commodity markets became volatile, and prices exploded upward.<p>
First Commercial watched Zimmerman's position swell against him and, deciding he was putting the firm on the line, forced him to liquidate on thousands of contracts, leaving a $150,000 loss. Selling his seat just 20 days after he bought it, Zimmerman owed the firm $70,000 and was barred from trading at the Merc.<p>
Paul Leventhal also lost big during the gulf war, but he still had enough cash to begin again in the options pits of the Board of Trade, where it cost less to trade. He asked Zimmerman to rejoin him. Although the Board of Trade is within blocks of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, no one bothered calling the Merc to check either Zimmerman or Leventhal out. Their new clearing firm paid for its inattention. Leventhal lost $400,000 when soybean options exploded on drought fears. He was finished as a trader. Unless Zimmerman found a new backer, he was kaput too.<p>
Desperate, Zimmerman convinced his father to take a $20,000 second mortgage and lost half that in a week. First Commercial, aware that Zimmerman was trading again and still owed $70,000, put a lien on the rest. Zimmerman was shut down. He and Lisa moved to a smaller apartment tucked between a large bakery and an expressway far from the trader hangouts. In July 1992, Darrell stopped payments on Lisa's Chevy Blazer with only two installments left. At the end of the month, Zimmerman reported<p>
this okay way to say it--that he reported it stolen? funny thing, i have a friend in chicago who was a trader and reported his mercedes stolen for similar reasons. he went to jail for six months. the Blazer stolen. <p>
While he shopped for new backers, Zimmerman killed time at the International Trading Institute, a training school for firm and institutional traders. ITI's lead instructor, Charles Cottle, thought Zimmerman could make better use of his talents and offered Zimmerman a deal. He'd take him "apart piece by piece, like a car, and build him back up again" with better habits. In return, Zimmerman could earn some money teaching beginner classes. ITI pushed strategies that required hard analytical work. The successful traders and promising prospects filing through ITI reminded Zimmerman how much he missed trading and how hard it would be to build up again. He began to fray. To the ITI staff, he seemed like an odd addition. <p>
The grunt work at ITI was done by six months of work without pay in exchange for the chance to take ITI's full $15,000 trading course. One day while Zimmerman was in the office, twolab techs lab techs, Mark Mason and Anthony Catalfo, asked why he wasn't trading. Both were East Coast rich kids in Chicago to turn small fortunes into big ones. Zimmerman figured that maybe he'd found his new backers. "We made a good fit," Zimmerman says, "I had experience and awareness of the floor, but I didn't have money. These guys were looking for experience and someone to teach them, and money was no problem for them." Zimmerman was back in business, this time with carte blanche to trade any way he pleased. <p>
Mason and Catalfo found the work at ITI demeaning and the instruction too conservative. While Mason did his job, Catalfo caused problems. In one class, Catalfo, assigned to show slides, left the projection booth to call the instructor an idiot. Like Zimmerman, Catalfo had no use for ITI's structured approach. He had his own scheme for making money on the floor. He spent most of his time at ITI testing it on the institute's computer simulator, Trade$tar. His idea was to take a large position in futures, either long or short, and load up on options in the same direction. A big enough position, he believed, would cause a market panic and make him a killing. "He got on Trade$tar<p>
Callendo Kshould we put that little R thing here as well "registered"/i don't know, i don't think so NO/ml. the first day and said he made a million dollars," Mason recalls, "but it was all just fooling around with the machine." ITI staffers told Catalfo to quit his experiments before the paying students got the wrong impression that the institute sanctioned that kind of trading. When Shelly Brown, an ITI instructor, heard Catalfo's scheme, he\ warned him, "They'll carry you out, either on a stretcher or in handcuffs."<p>
Zimmerman had been contemplating a similar play since he lost his father's money. Catalfo and Mason backed Zimmerman with $30,000, enough to get him back on the floor and trading. Zimmerman persuaded yet another firm, TransMarket Group, to clear for him and promised to limit his trading to ten contracts at a time. On his first day of trading soybean options, Zimmerman lost track of his inventory of contracts, a mistake that happened to net $6,000 in profit from Darrell?. His young backers were impressed. Zimmerman suggested they move to the U.S. Treasury bond pit, where the big traders were.<p>
The Board of Trade's bond futures are the most actively traded contracts in the world. The pit is the most grueling in the industry. Trading firms send their quickest and toughest traders there. The bond-options pit, a few feet away, is not much calmer. Zimmerman lost $25,000 on his first trade. "We pissed away most of our money until we were down to ten grand," Zimmerman says. TransMarket vice president Ken Bosgraf warned him to scale back: "I talked to him because there was too much risk in his position. He seemed very cooperative [when I asked him to] reduce his position, [but] in fact he increased his position.  I told him to find somewhere else to place his trades."<p>
Catalfo suggested they take one more shot before Bosgraf shut them down. They sold 3,000 calls just before the release of the monthly government statistics on unemployment, gambling that the figure would send the bond market down. "The number came out and it was in our faces," Zimmerman recalls. "We lost 40 grand immediately." Catalfo panicked. Zimmerman, with nothing of his own to lose, said he didn't believe the number. He persuaded Catalfo to join him for breakfast at a nearby deli. Throughout the meal, Catalfo muttered glumly about getting his family to cover the loss. "When we got back to the board, the market had reversed; our loss was now a $75,000 winner," Zimmerman says. He rushed into the pit and took the profit. Catalfo thought Zimmerman was a genius. <p>
TransMarket immediately closed Zimmerman's account  Bosgraf also informed Mason and Catalfo that Zimmerman still owed $70,000 at the Merc. Mason, afraid that his earnings would be seized to cover Zimmerman's debt, exited the partnership. For Catalfo, however, it just raised Zimmerman's stock further.<p>
"Darrell had some kind of control over Tony," says Mason. "I don't know why. Anytime Darrell asked for anything, Tony gave it to him. He even talked Tony into renting a car for him for two months."<p>
Around this time, Zimmerman and Catalfo began plotting for "something really big." Catalfo applied for membership to the board, easily rented a seat, and opened an account for $30,000 at another clearing firm. Zimmerman also had no difficulty finding a seat or another clearing firm, Lee B. Stern & Co. Stern was a company whose traders worked the board's sleepier agricultural pits. Though Stern itself took surprisingly little initiative to check Zimmerman out, it did receive two unsolicited phone calls from Hammer officials at the Merc, both of whom warned that clearing Zimmerman could be disastrous. "Their response to us," says one of those who called, "was they could handle it. They had better risk management than we did." <p>
The stage was set for Zimmerman, aided by Catalfo, to make his biggest play yet. "Our game plan," says Zimmerman, "was to have a really aggressive opinion about the market and take as big a position as we could and freak out all the people who make their livelihoods down there." The best way to do that, he thought, was to buy options. This was a turnaround; Zimmerman's trading strategies usually revolved around selling options. <p>
Options are either puts or calls. A call is an option to buy a security at a given price by a determined date. A put, similarly, is an option to sell a security. People who buy put options are either hoping for or hedging against a market drop. Put-option sellers, on the other hand, bet that the market will not drop. As a put buyer, Zimmerman would get others to sell him options. In fact, he would get them to sell him far more puts than they actually owned, luring them into large "short put" positions and making the pit vulnerable to a massive short squeeze. Themselves hoping the market will rise; options sellers, on the other hand, bet that it will drop. As an option buyer, Zimmerman would force others to sell options to him or maybe even go short, that is, sell options they didn't own. Zimmerman planned to buy very big.     <p>
All options have a price--what an investor must pay to buy them--and a strike price, the price at which the option can be used to leverage the underlying security. Someone buying a call option on a $25 bond future, might buy an option with a strike price of $30. If, before the option expires, the underlying security rises to a point that exceeds the strike price of the option, it is said to be trading "in the money." An option trading "in the money" trades differently from one that is not, moving more closely in tandem with the underlying security it becomes more volatile, shows bigger price jumps, and rises. Immediately before expiration, "in the money" options move virtually dollar for dollar with the underlying security. When this happens, an option and the security are for all practical purposes the same.<p>
Zimmerman's plan was to make his fellow traders think bond futures were headed lower by flooding the futures market with sell orders and the put market with buy orders. Eventually, traders, panicked to get on board the trend, would push down the prices of the underlying securities--in this case, bond futures contracts. As the futures dropped in value, Zimmerman's put options would become more and more valuable. Zimmerman's heavy option buying would create a stampede pushing both bond and put prices his way. "Our plan," he said "was to load up the pit so much with short positions that the options would blow up in everyone's faces."<p>
The date that Zimmerman was to execute his plan was important too. Near an options expiration date, a big move in futures can make options prices explode."Darrell figured out how to cause a real panic by turning the options into futures," says Joseph, "and making people go to the futures market to hedge them." In effect, he bought options from everyone and caused the markets to go nuts himself. "In many ways, the plan was brilliant," says Joseph.<p>
"I saw the play as a way to plan my retirement, so it had to work just right," Zimmerman says. "Tony and I took the summer off, mostly on the golf course, plotting what we would do. First we thought about it in terms of trading maybe ten or a hundred times bigger than before. But then we thought, let's do it a thousand times bigger. Well, we couldn't spend months on the floor trading ten and twenty lots and then all of a sudden trade thousands. No one would believe us. We had to schmooze people. So we made appearances on the floor. We said we had some big positions off the floor and that we were working with our people in New York and overseas setting up this big trading thing.  Well, the big trading thing was all in our minds."<p>
Zimmerman figured his plan could only work if the traders thought the market movement was a general market panic. So he enlisted brokers to make trades for him from different parts of the bond pits. Most of the big, established brokers refused his business, but some smaller ones snapped it up. "All we would tell them was we 'had a situation.' People said we misled them, but 'a situation' can mean anything. They never even asked us what our situation was. They just wanted the business." <p>
Catalfo was approved for trading on October 19,1992, the fifth anniversary of the crash, the Monday before the Friday when bond options expired. On Wednesday, Zimmerman gave Lee B. Stern & Co., a check for $50,000 to get him on the floor. (It later bounced.) That night, Zimmerman and Catalfo were at Zimmerman's apartment. "Tony said, 'Let's do it tomorrow instead of Friday,'" Zimmerman says. "Thursday was better anyway; an unemployment number was coming out, and we could play off that." Catalfo had his own reason for changing the date: His little brother and a friend were coming to town. Says Zimmerman: "We were going to take down the world financial system, and the guy wants his brother there to see it."<p>
At 6:00 a.m. Thursday, Zimmerman and Catalfo took the guests to breakfast before the market opened. "We didn't tell them, 'Watch us--we're going to take this market by the balls.' We just said we were excited the market was going down and that we were pretty heavily invested in it," says Zimmerman. To explain options, he drew a simple graph on a napkin. Later in the day, the FBI seized that napkin.<p>
All four walked onto the floor early to get good spots, Zimmerman and Catalfo in the options pit, their guests just outside. Though it had not occurred to them, to other traders it appeared that Zimmerman and Catalfo had brought the backers they had been talking up. This wasn't implausible, because some of the biggest movers and shakers on the floor do, in fact, look like college kids at a frat party.<p>
When the markets opened at 7:25, Zimmerman and Catalfo started buying every put offered in the pit, 25,000 of them. Put prices soared, and the traders who sold scrambled to hedge by selling futures in the bond pit. Zimmerman, however, beat them to it. He was sending huge sell orders to nine different brokers in the pit, driving the bond prices down. At 7:30, the unemployment number came out, and it was bearish. The market got another kick downward. Catalfo liquidated his position, netting $1.5 million. <p>
Zimmerman looked at the trades in his hand, and saw between $3 million and $5 million in profits. He had built the whole pyramid in 15 minutes. "I knew by then that Tony was at least a millionaire, so no matter what happened I would have half of that," Zimmerman says. "I started to buy in a hundred here and a thousand there. It was pandemonium all over. People were coming up to me and saying, 'Excuse me sir, who are you doing these trades for?' People who saw me on the floor for two years and never gave me the time of day. I thought then, 'I'm a multimillionaire. I control the market now. How many times is that going to happen in your life?' I started selling again to bury everyone." In all, Zimmerman controlled 36,000 contracts, leveraging $3.6 billion in bonds. <p>
Two things happened that slowed his momentum. Word that he was behind the wild action in the bond pit reached the Stern office, which sent the firm's officials racing to the floor. They had no idea what Zimmerman's positions were, but they did know they were ludicrously beyond what his margin (represented by the $50,000 check) would support. Stern's word was all Board of Trade officials needed to yank him from the floor. The second factor was Zimmerman himself. He lost count of his contracts and stepped out of the pit to tally them. That allowed Board of Trade security guards to reach him. When the other traders realized what was happening, the market reversed with a vengeance. Stern employees wrestled Zimmerman's trading cards from him and started a frantic attempt to learn his position. The scuffle blew the charade. Soon everyone in the futures and options pits smelled blood. Zimmerman's positions, they knew, would be liquidated. Lee B. Stern & Co. was swallowed whole. The firm lost $8.5 million, $2 million more than its net worth. It was the biggest Darrell Day ever.<p>
The feeding frenzy continued even after Zimmerman was pulled from the floor. Because Stern did virtually no business in the financial markets, no one from the firm knew how to deal with the catastrophe. It took two hours before its officers had a handle on Zimmerman's position and could round up the brokers who could liquidate it. If they had acted faster or more discreetly, many floor traders believe, Stern could have reversed Zimmerman's trades with minor losses, perhaps even for a profit.<p>
Instead, the Board of Trade forced Lee B. Stern & Co. to cover Zimmerman's loss. Though Lee Stern, the retired founder of the firm, eventually covered the entire amount, his company lost its status as a clearing member of the Board of Trade, where it had done business for 25 years. Twenty employees lost their jobs<p>
The next day, when Anthony Catalfo asked for a check for the full $1.5 million, he was told that his funds had been frozen pending an exchange investigation. When Zimmerman tried to reach him, Catalfo refused to talk. The two have not spoken since. Mark Mason called Catalfo three days later: "Tony said, 'Oh, God, it was a horror show. I got suckered.'" The money Catalfo made was eventually ceded to Stern to cover Zimmerman's losses. He subsequently filed for bankruptcy. <p>
When Zimmerman was shut down, Lisa, who started trading on a seat the month before, was also forced from the floor. "The clearing firms told me I was barred because of guilt by association," she says bitterly. "I worked on the exchanges for seven years before I finally got a chance to trade, and when I did, I just did low-risk trading. That, though, was my dream."<p>
 In the months that followed, Zimmerman plied the halls of the shabbier buildings on the fringe of the financial district looking for a job. And despite continuing news reports of the CBOT debacle and imminent indictments, Zimmerman was able to land three jobs selling and recruiting for small brokerage firms in Chicago. Once at work, though, he was often in a daze. He lost each job in a matter of weeks. He bought a pair of Rollerblades and often skated through the night, rethinking how his plan went wrong. He did manage to open a few stock trading accounts over the phone, racking up $10,000 in losses at one firm.<p>
At the end of June 1993 he left a note for Lisa saying he was taking a vacation. He took money out of her piggy bank and bought a bus ticket to Canada. She has not begun divorce preceeding and will not testify against him because she is afraid of the catalfos (this is off the record. She is planning on getting a divorce but cannot aford one right now. "Darrell ruined the lives of lots of people," she says bitterly, "because he never thought of anyone but himself. He put money before humans." "He put money before humans." --Lisa <p>
Mitch Joseph has another theory about him: "I don't think there was ever anything really malicious in Darrell's trading.  He just did what he always wanted: He went big, and he went home."<p>
Over the last year, all the Chicago exchanges have instituted rules and penalties against trading over margin limits. One, unofficially labeled the Darrell Zimmerman Rule, entitles clearing firms to keep any profits traders make on positions that cannot be supported with margins.<p>
On July 21, a grand jury indicted Darrell Zimmerman and Anthony Catalfo on six counts of wire fraud, charges that carry maximum prison terms of 30 years and $16 million in fines. The indictment charges that both traders lied to their clearing firms about the limits they would place on their trades. No laws specifically forbid trading beyond one's margin (largely because the exchanges have long insisted on policing themselves), and the wire-fraud charges rely mainly on the fact that the bond prices Zimmerman and Catalfo traded at were quoted across state lines over financial-news services and they used phone lines to call New York from Chicago. That allows the FBI to get involved. Prosecutors may have difficulty convincing a jury that was a crime. Catalfo, through his court appointed lawyer, has pleaded not guilty <p>
Zimmerman, taking his chances on extradition is now selling penny gold stocks. "The funny thing," he says now, "is that no one I know said, 'Darrrell, you're an asshole.' They all say, 'Why the hell couldn't you tell me you were going to do that, so I could have done at least a five lot?'"<p>
Ted C. Fishman, a former trader on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, lives in Chicago.
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing
					</font>
