		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-The Lottery Winner</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-The Lottery Winner</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
There are sixteen million reasons why Bud Post's life has become a nightmare.  He won them all playing Pensylvania's Super Seven Game.<p>By John Marchese<p>In a late-February night in 1988, a night with snow coming in off Lake Erie, William J. Post III, whom nearly everyone calls Bud, sat in the front bedroom of his $250-a-month furnished apartment waiting for his luck to change.<p>It was a few minutes before seven, and Bud Post just had been awakened from a nap by Ann Karpik, his landlady and (she would later tell a judge) his girlfriend. Ann didn't want to stay long; she was on her way to play bingo. But she did have some business with Bud. That night was the weekly drawing for the Super 7 game of the Pennsylvania Lottery, and she held 20 tickets. Bud himself held 40; earlier that day he'd pawned his gold ring to buy them. The week before, he'd cleaned the last $100 out of his bank account to buy 100 Super 7 tickets.<p>Ann Karpik's house on 13th Street was in a decaying residential neighborhood on the east side of downtown Erie, Pennsylvania. It was really nothing more than a tenement with a backyard, and Post lived there on a $340-a-month Social Security disability pension.He didn't have much, but he always kept several televisions around. To see the lottery drawing tonight, he watched the one in his bedroom. Karpik watched in the kitchen.<p>Bud Post was confident that the white numbered Ping-Pong balls bouncing around in the clear plastic container would soon change his life. For the last three days and nights, he had been studying the winning numbers in past drawings, and he had come up with what he thought was a flawless probability theory. He couldn't lose. And so, just after 6:58 p.m., he puffed on a Pall Mall and waited calmly as each ball slid to its assigned slot. <p>The next thing you know, old Bud's a millionaire.<p>But if ever there is a cautionary case to be made about riches leading to ruin, it is the story of Bud Post. Since that wonderful night of February 24, 1988, when he won $16,183,487.84--became the "$16 Million Man," as he says now, bitterly--he has lost just about all of his friends. He did briefly reconcile with his three estranged siblings, but the accord quickly disintegrated into bizarre and intense feuding. This fall, his younger brother, Jeffrey, will be tried on charges of hiring a hit man to kill Bud Post and his postlottery wife, Connie. Meanwhile, his other brother, Ed, and his sister, Patty, have brought libel and slander suits against Bud. And Connie, who married Bud five months after he received his first big check, is soon to be his ex-wife. Over the last few years Bud Post has been arrested and sued enough to make up a whole season's worth of L.A. Law. <p>What's more, he has squandered more than $2.5 million, and is now as broke as he was on February 23, 1988. And he has bought for himself the kinds of problems he never could have afforded on $340 a month. <p>Bud Post now has a working title for his life story: The Nightmare.<p>Before the nightmare commenced five years ago, Bud Post's life had been at best a fitful dream, filled with the kind of bad luck and hardscrabble deprivations that drive a man to drink. At least it did with Bud. By the time he returned to Erie, his hometown, in 1986, he'd had five wives, ten children, numerous stepchildren, and more than two dozen grandchildren, but little else. <p>He had first left Erie as a kid, shipped out of town to live in a series of rural foster homes after his mother died and his father, a used-car dealer, decided he couldn't take care of three sons and a daughter. Though the Posts were reunited when their father remarried, all four kids would face big hurdles in life. Bud, in particular, seemed unable to clear them. He ran off to the army before he was 16 but then was discharged in Korea after drinking enough wood alcohol to nearly kill himself. With his dreams of a career in army intelligence dashed, Bud Post came home and worked at a variety of dead-end jobs--circus cook, carnival roustabout, truck driver. His last stint of steady employment was in 1987, when he worked spray painting aluminum siding. But that ended when complications from a hernia operation put him on a disability pension. <p>He wasn't even 50, but in many ways he already seemed like an old and broken man. His fourth wife had died recently. His social life was limited to a tight circle that extended to Wally's Bar, a few blocks from his apartment (where he drank), and to the nearby church-run soup kitchen called the Food Hamper (where he often ate). Sometimes Bud and his landlady, Ann Karpik, would play bingo at the local churches. Occasionally they played the lottery together. If they won at either, they'd share the pot--an arrangement that a judge would later decide was as good as contractual. But they never won much, and as their friendship grew, Ann Karpik would often let Post miss a rent payment. "He was basically living off of me," she says. "Before he got all the money, we got along pretty good."<p>Then he found out his small disability payment was being challenged. He got mad and decided to find a lawyer. But first he needed a way to pay for it. Years ago, when one of his wives sent him to a mental institution for evaluation, he'd been told by doctors that he had an IQ of 157. So maybe it was one of those mad leaps of borderline genius that led him to devise a way to get money to sue for his $340-a-month payment: He'd win the lottery.<p>Instant money has become America's postmodern Lourdes, a miracle cure for the ailing lower middle class (who, with the poor, buy most of the lottery tickets) and a long-term treatment for anemic state treasuries. Since 1964, when New Hampshire introduced its lottery, 35 states and the District of Columbia have come up with some kind of state-run numbers game. In all, citizens now spend nearly $12 billion a year on lottery tickets. "Lotteries are selling hope," says Eugene Christiansen, president of Christiansen/ Cummings, a consulting firm that works with lotteries. "It's the poor who hope the most."<p>Bud Post was poor and hopeful. years of struggle have marked him: a trim man, medium height, with scars crisscrossing his body from dozens of operations. He has thin hair and a lined face, sunken around the mouth because he rarely wears his false teeth. They worsen the headaches that have plagued him for years. <p>"I worked two jobs to feed my family," he says. "I had ten kids--how many people could make it today with ten kids?" (He did not feed them consistently; one of the first liens on Bud Post's new fortune came from Erie County child-welfare officials, to make up long-overdue child-support payments.) "I even wrote some bad checks once to buy groceries. And I went to jail for it," he says.<p>So you would think that becoming the $16 Million Man would have made him happy. "Nah," Post says. "Right from the beginning, I knew. Look at the photos they took of me when I was in Harrisburg," the state capital, where he officially claimed his prize. "Do you see me smiling? I knew the money would cause me a lot of problems."<p>But people who were around him in the first hours after he won say Bud Post spent at least a little time celebrating. Ann Karpik remembers him coming to her house at three o'clock that night after the drawing and banging on the door until he was let in. "I told you I was going to win," she says Bud told her. "You're going to have a new house and new cars." One of the first things Post did was get out of Karpik's low-rent apartment. He charged a hotel room for the two of them (onKarpik's credit card) at the Quality Inn in downtown Erie. <p>A few days later, Post hired a Cadillac limousine to bring him and Karpik to Harrisburg to meet with lottery officials. Post's brothers, Ed and Jeffrey, flew to Harrisburg from their homes in Florida. His sister, Patty, drove in from Erie. One of Bud's children showed up. The year before, no one had called or sent him a card on Father's Day. "His family never even answered his phone calls before," says Ann Karpik. "Now there they were."<p>Bud Post's fortune wouldn't arrive all at once. To lessen the winner's tax liabilities and to mitigate the danger of ruinous, heedless spending--and to save money itself--state lotteries don't pay their big winners directly.Instead, they buy them annuities; Bud's provided him $622,441.84 each year for 25 years. Under Pennsylvania law, no state or local taxes would be levied on the winnings, but 20 percent was withheld for federal income taxes, leaving Post's yearly take at $497,953.47.<p>"I spent about $10,000 that weekend just on hotel bills and food for everybody," Post remembers. He sent Ann Karpik on a clothes shopping spree. He bought her a used Cadillac and wrote her a $10,000 check for back rent and damages to her apartment. But he didn't do what she'd been hoping he'd do: share his winnings equally with her.<p>"I told him," Karpik says, "Bud, if you don't do what's right with this money, you're just going to have bad luck with it."<p>By late summer of 1990, Bud Post's brief good luck was starting to turn bad again. It was barely a year and a half since he'd become a millionaire, and Post was already short on funds, so he decided to hold a gigantic fire sale on the grounds of one of the two farms he'd bought in OilCity, Pennsylvania, about an hour southeast of Erie. <p>"He told me he was pressed for money and wanted to sell all his toys," says Charles Baker, an auctioneer in the area. "I wouldn't say he described them as toys--I described them as toys.<p>"We sold backhoes, limousines, motorcycles, bicycles, horse trailers," Baker says. "I could just go on and on."<p>The official auction notice did go on and on. Besides selling one of the farms, Post put on the block items that ranged from the limousines to an ultralight aircraft, from complete bathrooms (shower enclosures, sinks, and commodes) to living-room furniture, from an oak-barrel bumper-pool game table to stereo systems, an electronic organ, antique suits of armor, and train sets. Post had even thought of selling the 1,200 pairs of men's polyester pants he'd somehow acquired. "The pants are a long story," says Baker.<p>The short explanation is supplied by Bud Post himself: "I'd just collected too much stuff," he says. "Most of it was inexpensive stuff. The whole auction didn't get me more than $110,000. I just wanted to get rid of it because I couldn't even keep track of the stuff. How much stuff can you watch at one time?" <p>The auctioneer had never seen a larger turnout in his 33 years in business. "People came out just to see this guy who'd won $16 million," says Baker. "Around here that's like meeting Donald Trump."<p>He was no Donald Trump, but bud post had installed himself as chairman of Post Enterprises Inc., a Florida corporation whose officers included his two brothers, his sister, and his wife, Connie. He'd met Connie years before he won the money, when he was being treated in the psychiatric division of Northwest Medical Center in Oil City. Post says he proposed to Connie then, but she turned him down. Soon after he won the lottery, he looked her up again.<p>"At the time," Post says, "her boyfriend had just gone to jail." So he bought a house in Oil City to be near her. "I treated her like a queen," he says. "Anything she wanted. I mean, she's got clothes like you wouldn't believe. She's got jewelry, $1,300 and $1,400 dresses." To make sure she had plenty of time to wear those dresses, Post called Connie's employer and told him she didn't need a job anymore. <p>After they were married, Bud and Connie moved into a big brick house on Shady Oak Lane, an accurately named street near the top of a hill that rises out of downtown Oil City. Built by a man who made a fortune opening the first McDonald's franchises in the area, the house was lavish, even gaudy, by Oil City standards. Bud Post bought it for about $250,000 and decided to make it even more ostentatious.<p>"He obviously wanted a castle," says his banker, Robert Bablak Jr., assistant vice president at the local Northwest Savings Bank. "He just wanted to be somebody significant, and he was going to make himself significant with this money."<p>Post bought an old coat of arms at a thrift shop, painted it and hung it over the front door. He bought suits of armor and life-size religious statues, which he placed in the front yard. He hired the local Sears to put a mansard roof on the house and hired a contractor to build turrets. "We wish that house would disappear," said one of his neighbors recently. Another neighbor was the CEO of Quaker State Petroleum, Jack Corn. When Bud Post heard that Corn was ready to retire and move to Florida, he boasted to his nephew that he was going to buy Corn's quarter-million-dollar house, too.<p>"Why?" his nephew asked.<p>"Storage," Post said smugly.<p>While he built his Oil City Xanadu, Post Enterprises went into a variety of businesses. Bud Post says now that he only wanted the business to take care of his long-estranged siblings and "keep them away from me." His brothers and sister say he promised them money and then took it back. Connie Post believes that "when Bud won the money, he tried buying their love back." (He didn't try so hard with his children. Post's wife reports that when one daughter called and asked to borrow money for a new wooden leg, Bud hung up on her.)<p>So Bud bought his siblings a restaurant and bar near the Sarasota, Florida, airport called City Limits, which would be run by Jeffrey Post and Patty Post. Bud's older brother, Ed, would run a car dealership that would buy cars cheaply in the economically distressed regions around Erie and sell them high in booming Florida. For a short time, Bud Post, who had the urge to fly airplanes, had a scheme to ship Maine lobsters to Florida and shrimp back to Maine. Though he didn't have a pilot's license, he bought a small used Beechcraft twin-engine plane.<p>"I wanted to fly," Bud Post says. "And I figured if I live in Pennsylvania and I have a corporation in Florida, wouldn't it be nice to have an airplane to fly down and smoke in. You can't smoke on commercial airlines. That really pissed me off. So I bought myself an airplane. Why not? The corporation should have been making money. I should have been able to afford a $70,000 plane out of $16 million."<p>Why Post Enterprises never made money is a subject of dispute. Bud Post says his siblings took money meant for the business and spent it on lavish living. He had originally agreed to pay them $50,000 a year, and there was a less formal agreement that as the business prospered, so would the family.<p>Ed, Jeffrey, and Patty blame the company's problems on their brother's erratic behavior--characterized by such acts as depositing money into the company account and then quickly taking most of it back.<p>"It's really kind of simple," says Jeffrey Post. "After our mother passed away and we were sent to different places to live, Bud felt he got the short end of the deal. Somewhere along the line he decided to destroy his family."<p>Before their brother became a millionaire, the Posts never had much money, but they all owned homes and held down jobs and, for the most part, did what they could for their troubled middle brother. But they only had so much tolerance for Bud's drinking and his unreliability. In the years before February 24, 1988, Jeffrey had washed his hands of Bud. He wouldn't let his brother into his house. Ed sometimes gave Bud a place to sleep in Florida, but only on his office floor. Only Patty was unable to refuse Bud. For a time in the early '80s, she had let him live in a trailer behind the Oil City restaurant she ran with her husband.<p>"They sure took money from the black sheep," says Bud Post now. "They came to me. I didn't go to them. They thought they were going to become millionaires. My brothers and sister are just plain pure jealous.<p>"Generally, when money comes into a family," he continues, "it causes greed and revenge. In this case I believe greed was the seed that grew revenge."<p>Revenge against Bud Post would take many forms. Most extreme and self-defeating was the course followed by Jeffrey Post. According to the police in Sarasota, Jeffrey wanted to drown his brother on a boating trip. When that scheme failed, he allegedly sent a hit man up to Pennsylvania in the spring of 1993. Jeffrey will not talk about the murder plots, but Ed and Patty say that if Jeffrey planned to kill Bud, he did it for revenge, not greed. In any case, revenge would come first for Ann Karpik. <p>Karpik was less impetuous in her antagonism than Jeffrey.Rather than resort to violence to get what she thought should be hers, she hired legal counsel. Just about the time he was having his auction, Karpik sued Bud Post in Erie County, claiming that she was entitled to half his winnings. Her lawyers, a former Erie County judge and two partners at one of Erie's top firms, argued that the bingo partnership Ann and Bud had developed constituted a contract, which Post had violated by not sharing his winnings.<p>The case came to trial in August 1991 and took an unusual form. Erie County President Judge Jess Jiuliante would decide the case, though there would be an advisory jury that would vote on matters of fact. The matters of fact were hotly disputed.<p>Karpik claimed that she and Post had been lovers. Post denied it. Karpik claimed they'd gambled together often and always shared the winnings. Post said that wasn't really the case. Karpik claimed that on the night of the drawing Post hid the winning ticket from her. He said that was a lie. Karpik's attorneys said that because Bud Post had often treated her violently in the past, she was afraid to speak up before lottery officials to claim her share of the prize. Post's lawyers said the fact that Ann Karpik ran her own bar for years in a tough Erie neighborhood proved that she couldn't have been afraid of Bud. <p>Karpik's lawyers produced a prelottery handwritten will leaving everything to Karpik (which Post claimed was a forgery) and the testimony of Carl Smith, another of Karpik's tenants and, according to Karpik, Bud's rival for her affections. Smith testified that while hiding in a closet in Karpik's house in the early-morning hours of February 25, 1988, he'd heard Post promise Ann a half-share of his winnings.<p>In the end, Judge Jiuliante ruled for Karpik, though he thought she only deserved one third of the prize (the judge explained recently that he based the one-third award on the fact that on February 24, 1988, Bud had bought 40 tickets and Ann only 20). Jiuliante ordered Bud Post to pay Ann Karpik $5,333,333.33 (plus back interest) and to immediately sign over to her $300,000 from his 1992 annuity check. Post refused and was found in contempt of court. When it came time for the 1993 payment, Bud didn't even get a chance to refuse. Jiuliante ordered the money put straight into escrow. Post has appealed the decision to the state superior court, which has yet to hear the case. <p>By early 1993, Post's life officially became a nightmare, and no one had even tried to kill him yet. In one affidavit filed with the Erie court, he said, "I have incurred substantial indebtedness to various creditors in various amounts." In another filing, his lawyers said, "The defendant's long-standing and acutely exacerbated health problems, the stress attributable to the underlying controversy  as well as worsening domestic difficulties involving the defendant's wife and third parties" were impairing their client. <p>"Yes, I had wife troubles," Bud Post says now. In July of 1990, Connie filed for divorce, after a number of fights that were settled only when the cops were called in. Later that year, Connie obtained a protection order in Venango County Court.She told the judge that Bud was firing guns inside the house, had once shot her car, and had threatened to kill her if she ever tried to take his money. Despite the turmoil, she always came back to him. <p>Go to visit Bud Post for the first time in late August, not long after police in Sarasota have arrested his brother and charged him with hiring a hit man to kill Bud and his wife and make it look like a murder-suicide. It is dusk. The pile that had become Bud's castle, had held his dreams of significance, sits on the top of a steep lawn looking empty and forlorn. The turrets that Bud wants built are half-finished, covered in tar paper. An Oil City police dispatcher who gives me directions to Bud's place says, "I wouldn't tell him you were talking to us."  His neighbor, who is taking a walk, asks warily, "Does he know you're coming?" He doesn't. "I'll keep an eye on you," she says.<p>I ring the doorbell and wait. In the muggy summer heat bugs are making a racket. Bud Post comes to the door after a couple rings, looking worn out. He is 53 now and seems ten years older. He's wearing only jeans and white dress socks--he'd been sleeping--and as he talks for the next six hours he won't bother putting on a shirt or shoes. "You know what I've had as a sleeping companion?" Post asks at one point. "An M1 carbine with a banana clip in it." He pauses: "You're not nervous, are you?"<p>Bud Post has enough nerves for both of us. When he sits, he pumps his leg almost continuously. Often, he jumps up and paces the room, and he smokes one Pall Mall after another. Within 20 minutes of letting me into his house--where whole rooms are devoid of furniture and fixtures have been pulled from walls ("They stole my curtains," Bud says, never identifying "they")--he takes me into his bedroom so he can play a tune on his electronic piano.<p>The bedroom is dark but for a huge television image soundlessly projected onto the back wall. Two other small televisions on either side of his bed play the same movie (Outrageous Fortune, starring Bette Midler and Shelley Long), also with no sound. Another television glows near the heavily curtained window, which is barred and has been smashed. That television--a security monitor--holds a static image of Bud's driveway. When Bud Post stops talking for a moment, the sound of bugs and wind rustling leaves fills the room. He also has a listening device set up outside. "I could see you and hear you before you rang the bell," he says.<p>Then Bud Post drops to his knees on the floor and starts to play his piano. He pages through a book of simplified sheet music, with notes as big as quarters, and picks "I Fall to Pieces." The performance is so inept it is touching. Assured that he plays beautifully, Bud plays "Release Me" as an encore. "My wife loves this one," he says, staring hard at the big notes.<p>Had he only listened, Bud Post might have avoided this nightmare. The Pennsylvania Lottery Commission gives an information packet to its big winners that emphasizes two points: "Don't make any hasty decisions regarding your prize money," and "If you do not have professional legal and financial advisors, you should consider seeking such help." After that: "We believe they're adults and leave it up to them," says a lottery spokesman.<p>There was a crucial moment soon after he won the money when Bud Post could have let someone else run his affairs. His lawyer at the time, Robert McCullough, says he arranged for a banker to devise a financial plan for the new millionaire. "But Bud couldn't stand to have anyone tell him what to do," McCullough says. "He just won't let people help him."<p>"The banks wanted to deal with me like I was a little kid," says Bud Post. "I was going to control my own money.<p>"The problem was, I wasn't expecting them all to come for it at once. I knew Ann Karpik would, because of the way she was talking. But everybody I ever knew or talked to wanted money. I'm not the keeper of the world because I won the lottery."<p>Connie Post says that her husband has only come to this posture of world-weary philosophizing now that he's looking for sympathy. Before things got sour, she remembers him saying, "I've got more power than God."<p>Bud Post has not received a penny since February 1992. His siblings, he says, were out to get him from the beginning; he contends that the Erie County court system has systematically deprived him of his rights. These allegations sound like the ravings of a paranoid, except for the fact that the Sarasota police say that a man hired by Jeffrey Post did indeed stalk Bud at his castle last May. Months before, Jeffrey tried to get Bud to Florida for a sailing trip, where he allegedly planned to kill him and make it look like a suicide. Bud thinks his brother was after the money--the three Post siblings were listed as beneficiaries with the Pennsylvania Lottery Commission. Of course, Bud has changed that now. His most recent beneficiary statement leaves 90 percent of the money to his church, 10 percent to Connie.<p>"He blames everybody but himself," says Jeffrey Post, who is free on bail awaiting trial and who is dying of AIDS. "It should have been the greatest thing that ever happened. He could have retired his brothers and sister, handed each of us $50,000 a year, and there still would have been an awful lot of money. But the money just made everything miserable instead of wonderful."<p>It is tempting to think that Bud Post was simply unequipped to handle any amount of money, let alone a multimillion-dollar lottery jackpot. But there are so many horror stories attached to sudden wealth that his dilemma seems almost predictable. As he told his tale and as everyone around him complained of the damage the money had done, I kept thinking, could I have handled it any better? "I know I wouldn't trade places with him," says Post's banker, Robert Bablak. "His goals in life might have been different from yours or mine. But I really think he meant well." <p>I asked Bud Post if he didn't often wish his luck were different on that cold February night with snow in the air. He hadn't been sleeping much recently, and there were big, dark pouches under his eyes. He looked at me for a while.<p>"Do you ever think, 'I wish I hadn't been born?'" he asked. "What's the difference? I'm a survivor, and I'm still holding things together--as little as it may look. This is war, and when you have war you have damages.<p>"I'm still alive," Post said. "I don't know if that's lucky or not." <p>John Marchese has written for the New York Times, Esquire, GQ, and Philadelphia.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Business

