	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Uneasy Street?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Uneasy Street?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Is an income of $100,000 a year enough to buy the American Dream?<p>By Ilyce Glink<p>Earlier this year, when the federal government was busy trying to decide whom to hit up for higher taxes, the Senate Finance Committee, headed by Democratic Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine, offered a proposal: Boost rates for all households earning six-figure incomes or higher. The committee asserted that this was the cutoff for the middle class.<p>By the time Congress finally passed the Clinton budget package this summer, however, its authors had set the tax-hike threshold even higher. The new cutoff was $140,000--$40,000 more than the finance committee had recommended. In so doing, Washington acknowledged something that more and more Americans are gradually coming to realize:An income of $100,000 no longer can be considered rich.<p>Public perception has not fully caught up to this development. Most folks still accept $100,000 as a token of the good life, a magic number promising access to personal security and material well-being. Even with inflation, which has reduced the value of the dollar 41 percent since 1980, $100,000 is far more than most people earn in a year. Or even dream of earning. Only 4.3 percent of U.S. households pull down $100,000 or more annually. Last year, when pollsters at the Roper Organization asked people how large a household income they'd need to satisfy all of their wishes, the typical response averaged out to $82,100.<p>The people who actually make $100,000 or more, however, tell a different story. Many don't consider themselves anywhere close to being well-off, let alone wealthy. To them, rich is something that happens at a far higher income level--like $500,000 a year or $1 million. Between taxes, mortgage and tuition payments, and the general expenses of maintaining a household in the cities where high-income jobs are located, money sweeps out as fast as it comes in.<p>Easy Come, Easy Go
Jim Abeles is an executive with the magazine-publishing division of the Chicago Sun-Times; he makes about $80,000 a year. His wife, Jennifer, works part-time for Crate & Barrel, a furniture retailer, in Chicago. The money she brings in pushes them near six figures. They live in a brick colonial home covered with ivy in Highland Park, Illinois. They own two cars, a Saab and a Jeep Grand Cherokee. Money from Jim's family helped them buy the house, but they don't have anything left. And they worry about their finances.<p>"If I thought about how much we're spending relative to how much we're making, I wouldn't sleep well," says Jennifer. "We've been dipping into things that have always been earmarked for emergencies to pay the grocery and Visa bills." When she describes their life, it doesn't sound extravagant. With a newborn son, the Abeleses have cut out most of their indulgences--Jennifer says she used to spend $1,000 a month on herself, and Jim bought computer equipment, upgrading all the time--but life with a newborn is still expensive. When they go out to dinner now, it's usually to <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a>. Even so, she says: "We're living well beyond our means."<p>In fact, statistics show that the typical six-figure household is considerably less wealthy today than it was ten years ago--despite all of the talk about the go-go 1980s. According to a survey conducted by Payment Systems Inc., the average net worth of households with annual incomes between $100,000 and $200,000 declined 58 percent between 1983 and 1992, adjusted for inflation. Factoring out real estate values doesn't significantly alter the amount of the erosion. So it's likely that much of the drop is related to the arrival of more and more two-income couples to the group, with comparatively high earnings but little in the way of accumulated assets.<p>Peter Roth and Jennifer Freeman live in New York City and earn $100,000 between them, he as a manager of new business development for a small cable-TV company, she as a project supervisor for a construction company. After three years of marriage and with a baby on the way, they're finding that at a time when they expected to be getting ahead, they are still just trying to get a foothold. "We're not suffering at all in our lifestyle," Roth says. "But we're being forced to make some choices we didn't expect to be making at this point in our lives." <p>Recently Roth and Freeman went shopping for a home in the suburbs. And what they learned was that they couldn't afford one--at least not the kind of place they envision for themselves. So they'll keep their one-bedroom apartment in the city, and the baby's crib will go in the corner next to their bed. "It's kind of unbelievable that this kind of money--think about it: $100,000--doesn't go very far, or that we're even having this discussion," says Roth. He says they now know that when they do finally buy their first dream house, it's going to be "even less dreamy than our lowest expectations."<p>How It's Supposed to Work
It would be easy to dismiss such complaints as examples of the old proverb that riches enlarge rather than satisfy the appetite. Or they could be shrugged off as the whining of spoiled brats, a great temptation at a time when class tensions simmer just below the surface of society. Public sentiment, in fact, is so strong on this score that many people who make six-figure salaries feel that they are not entitled to their anxiety. A number of those interviewed for this story refused to disclose their names.<p>This doesn't mean we should all start feeling sorry for people who make six-figure incomes. That's not the point. What is important is that this isn't the way things are supposed to work. People in the upper 4 percent income bracket of a wealthy nation are not supposed to feel like they are under a lot of financial stress. They are supposed to be comfortable. And their success is supposed to reassure everyone else that, by applying themselves, they too can reach this level of comfort. It's the incentive that drives our economy.<p>So it's painful to admit that $100,000 isn't rich anymore, because it seems to put so much out of reach. And it's perplexing and frustrating for those who have arrived at that level only to discover that they still have further to go. Many feel as though they upheld their end of the bargain--studied hard in school, put in long hours at work, and climbed the ladder--only to discover that the payoff has been reduced. <p>Some refuse to accept it. According to Kathleen Gurney, founder of the Financial Psychology Corp. in Cincinnati, many people who make six-figure salaries spend themselves into debt simply because they want to believe they are rich. "I'm seeing more anxiety than usual," she says. "You see people getting themselves into trouble because they are saying to themselves, 'How could I possibly be in trouble if I'm earning $100,000 a year?'"<p>Moreover, technology and marketing whizzes are forever expanding the temptations offered in the marketplace. This constantly expands the gap between what society offers and what people can afford--leaving everyone feeling more deprived. Part of what concerns Jennifer Abeles and her husband is that they want their son to have everything they had as children. "Having a baby is expensive, even though everyone says it's not for the first year," Jennifer says. "None of our son Will's medical checkups are covered by insurance. And then there are those fun gadgets, marketed in such a spectacular way. It makes you feel your child can't live without that Barney sleeping bag." Susan Mayer, a professor of public policy at the University of Chicago, understands how families like the Abeleses let themselves be stepped on by an imaginary dinosaur. "One reason people feel pinched is that they're buying a whole lot more," she says. "They save less, spend more, and feel worse."<p>Location and Wealth
To be sure, not all households earning $100,000 a year are suffering. It makes a difference where people live, what they own, what they owe, whom they have to take care of, and how healthy they are. A six-figure income stretches pretty far in Manhattan, Kansas. Manhattan, New York, is another story. If there are no medical bills to pay, no alimony checks to sign, and no sick relatives to take care of, $100,000 also looks better. If the mortgage is already paid off, a $100,000 household might even start to feel rich.<p>On the other hand, the vast majority of $100,000 households do not live in small farm towns, and still have plenty of payments left on their mortgages. Four of ten, in fact, reside in just five U.S. cities: the New York, Washington, Chicago, San Francisco, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas,where prices are a space shot higher than in rural America. So is the cost of living in Boston, Minneapolis, Seattle, and a host of other places. In New York City, an income of $100,000--after federal, state, and city taxes are extracted--means a couple would practically have to forgo food altogether to buy anything bigger than a one-bedroom apartment to live in. And even then, it could be difficult. "You have to have a certain amount of money to be accepted by a co-op board," says Patricia Burnham, president of P.S. Burnham, a Manhattan real estate brokerage firm. Burnham suggests that a $100,000 couple accept the fact that they'll have to rent. Two thousand dollars a month should get them a nice one-bedroom place in a good neighborhood.<p>A lot of six-figure earners also feel poor because they don't have much in the way of assets, which is the true measure of wealth and the way it is accumulated over the long term. According to one study of affluent households, couples who earned between $100,000 and $150,000 a year but were less than 50 years old averaged a net worth of under $40,000, not including their residence. This describes about a third of the households who earn more than $100,000. Many also have watched their total net worth decline because of the collapse of the housing markets on both coasts. It's difficult to accumulate assets when you're living paycheck to paycheck. Says Susan Mayer: "If you look at the statistics, you can see that even in the highest decile, people spend most of their income." <p>It's no wonder, then, that bankruptcy lawyers and credit counselors report an upsurge in the number of six-figure households getting into financial trouble. "I don't know if a person making $100,000 is a high earner anymore," says David Askanase, a Houston bankruptcy attorney who has had several clients in that income range. Adds Catherine Williams, director of education for Consumer Credit Counseling Services in Chicago: "There are plenty of people who earn $100,000 a year who are truly a paycheck away from disaster. When you hear the credit balances, it will make your hair curl. One gentleman has a debt load of $183,000, but he only bought about $140,000 worth of stuff. It's the accumulating-interest snowball theory."<p>Dan and Chrissy Barr, who live in Loveland, Ohio, about 20 miles from Cincinnati, are certainly nowhere near that kind of trouble. They are both 34 years old and earn a combined $130,000. Their biggest expense is the $2,000 a month they pay for the mortgage on their red brick home. Their second biggest expense is the $7,000 tuition they pay to send their six-year-old son, Andy, to a private school.<p>Partly because the cost of living isn't astronomical in Loveland, they say they live a comfortable life. On the weekends, he plays tennis and she goes for two-hour bike rides. The private school is a luxury, but they both felt it was important after Andy scored extremely well on standardized tests.<p>Neither Dan nor Chrissy, however, feels anywhere near the brink of luxury. In fact, it is primarily for financial reasons that they've decided not to have any more children. "We wouldn't want to compromise the education factor," Chrissy says. In other words, they plan on keeping their family limited to one child so they don't ever have to skimp. "Andy's school clothes alone were $350 at <a name="NYSE:GPS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gap</b></a> Kids the other day--for some turtlenecks, pants, and sweaters," says Chrissy. "The money just goes."<p>Indeed, the most common complaint of people who earn $100,000 is how restricted their life choices are. For Mike and Cathy Marchesano, that means sacrificing Mike's time with the family. To be able to afford a nice suburban home, they chose to live in Nassau County, New York, about 50 miles away from Manhattan, where Mike works as a publishing executive. Their cedar-shingled Dutch colonial home is more than comfortable, with a large deck and beautiful landscaping. Yet Mike spends nearly three hours a day commuting on the Long Island Railroad. He rarely gets to see the house in the daylight. More important, he barely gets to see his two daughters except on weekends, and he often has to work Saturdays. "I think I have a very good life," he says. "But I wish I could spend more time with my children." <p>$2,368 for Harvard
One reason members of the $100,000 group may feel let down by what their income can buy is that perceptions about money rarely keep pace with inflation. It comes as a shock to a lot of people to hear that $100,000 in 1980 dollars is equal to $175,000 of today's dollars. And, of course, the further back in time one goes, the more pathetic the comparisons get.<p>In 1960, $100,000 purchased 42 years at Harvard ($2,368 a year) or 13.5 Eldorado Seville Biarritz Cadillacs ($7,401 each) or an 8,000-square-foot condo at one of Chicago's best Gold Coast addresses. Today, it will barely buy one four-year education at Harvard ($24,000 a year) or three 1993 Cadillac Sevilles ($33,200 each) or a small one-bedroom condo in Chicago.<p>But the psychology of inflation doesn't account for all of the disappointment. "These people legitimately feel like they are just scraping by," says Nobel-prize-winning economist Gary S. Becker. "They are just meeting their monthly bills and mortgage payments.. . .  Their complaints aren't just whining. They are real...even though others making $30,000 won't have much sympathy for them."<p>Social critic Barbara Ehrenreich writes in her book Fear of Falling: The Inner Life of the Middle Class, "It is hardly greed that impels a man to want the best education for his children or a comfortable home for them to grow up in.... Something is indeed 'terribly wrong,' when the once-modest expectations of the middle class can be met only with what is a far from middling income." David Drucker, a financial planner in Bethesda, Maryland, echoes her sentiment:"I don't think it's impossible for a $100,000 family to send a kid through private school and Harvard," he says. "But they would have to live a pretty meager lifestyle."<p>As evidence of the nation's wealth, many economists point to the rise in households earning more than $100,000 a year--which has occurred even in real dollars. Yet the largest percentage of this increase is accounted for by the jump in two-income households. And a two-income household making a combined $100,000 doesn't net nearly as much as a home with one breadwinner making $100,000. Taxes are one reason for that, since both husband and wife must pay Social Security, doubling the family contribution. The Social Security rate itself has also gone up. In 1980, two wage earners making $50,000 each would have paid $3,175.34 in Social Security taxes. Today, their bill would be $7,650, a 240 percent increase.<p>A two-income couple also may need to pay all of the expenses for two cars, instead of one. If the family has children, they'll need to foot the bill for day care. With two jobs, they also  buy more business clothes and are more likely to eat out or consume expensive prepared foods, since there's little time for cooking.<p>Other costs have risen for everyone, making it harder to live well at any income level. New York economist Ed Hyman's New Misery Index shows that in 1980 the average American spent about 37 percent of personal income on four things: taxes, health insurance, Social Security, and debt service. Today, we spend more than 44 percent on the same things. To a $100,000 family, that 7 percentage point rise is $7,000 spent for no gain. The average total tax bill--federal, state, and local--for a two-earner family with two children and a total income of $100,000 is about $25,000, according to Phil Ravid, a partner in Ravid & Bernstein, a general accounting practice in Chicago. He says: "I started accounting in 1964. People spend more today, but I get the impression that the ones making a buck back then were able to accumulate more wealth. Today, it seems tougher."<p>Although the Clinton tax plan appears to acknowledge the problems of the six-figure household, if only slightly, a lot of people think that the threshold for middle class should have been set even higher than $140,000. "Someone living on $140,000 a year in New York City is certainly not rich," says Paul Craig Roberts, a political economist with the Center for Strategic and International Studies. "Clinton's definitions of income are very arbitrary because most people with high incomes are living in densely populated cities." One result: Concerns and complaints of this group are largely ignored. They aren't poor enough to attract sympathy. And they aren't rich enough to fund powerful lobbies in Washington.<p>No One Else's Fault
Of course, there's a lot of self-inflicted pain, too. The breakup of a marriage is a far worse financial disaster than a tax increase or even a stock-market crash. And about 50 percent of marriages end in divorce. Clint Johnson, who works for an insurance company in Boston, brings home a little over $100,000 a year. But he's divorced, and child support siphons off about 25 percent of his take-home pay. On top of that, his two daughters live in Chicago: He spends an additional $500 per month flying there to see them.<p>Judith and Frank, who live in New England and asked that their last name not be used, say they at least don't feel alone in their struggles. "I know a lot of people who are poor on $100,000 a year," says Judith. "Our house has problems, and we don't have the cash to fix it up. We're carrying a mortgage that's too much for us. We're trying to get ready to sell. We thought we'd be able to meet the bills and be comfortable and take a vacation once a year, and we can't do it. We thought we'd be able to send our daughter to college and be comfortable. We had hoped for a modicum of comfort and spending power, and we have not even achieved that." Their problems stem from the loss of her job in the pharmaceutical industry. Even though he makes $150,000 a year working in the computer industry, it isn't enough to pay their bills. Recently, they found a way to save $92 a month: They canceled their eight-year-old daughter's piano lessons.<p>Increasing angst about job security is another reason why a lot of $100,000 households feel less than well-off. They know that income could disappear. Says Judith Lansky, president of Lansky Career Consultants: "An awful lot of people earning $100,000 a year spend every penny of it. Unfortunately, when you lose your $100,000-a-year job, it could easily take you more than a year to find another one. And if you are the sole support of a family with children, it's going to be a long year."<p>"It's a convergence of forces," says Kevin Phillips, a political analyst and author. "Not only has their income been undermined but also their jobs, pensions, and the whole sense of the American safe-living standard, which for people who wore white collars and graduated from college was bankable into the 1980s. After the crash of 1987, you began to see bank crises and employment slipping. The American Dream wasn't out there for Mr. and Mrs. Jones anymore. Politicians could tell them they were rich, but the voters couldn't feel it."<p>Bob and Kim Witwer of Phoenix describe earning $100,000 as a disappointment. Says Bob, who works as an engineering supervisor: "It's more of a general disappointment, because you have a gradual rise in income and a gradual decline in what you can do with it because your expenses are greater. We don't really look at ourselves as people who put an excess emphasis on material stuff. But it's surprising with having kids, both of us working, and all of the other things you pay for. There's a lot of people running around with $40,000 thinking if they made $100,000, they'd be living high on the hog. But they would be surprised."<p>As for Jim and Jennifer Abeles, they say they are mainly focused on adjusting to parenthood. Recently, however, Jim has been experimenting with a new financial strategy he hopes will finally end their worries: He's buying Illinois lottery tickets every couple of weeks.<p>
Ilyce Glink is a writer living in Chicago.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
