<DOCOLDNO>IA032-000664-B037-231</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.worth.com:80/articles/Z9309F06.html 204.141.48.165 19970209131526 text/html 25253
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 09 Feb 1997 13:16:14 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=2063848855494174237; path=/
</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Trapped in a Squeeze Play</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Trapped in a Squeeze Play</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
At 37, Jack Clark should be moving into the twilight of his career as a great home run hitter, a millionaire many times over. Instead he's bankrupt, out of baseball, and barely hanging on to a rented condo in California. Here's his story, Chapter 11 and verse.<p>By John Strahinich<p>From Ty Cobb to Yogi Berra, professional baseball players have long been known as tightwads. Berra, for one, would eat at the ballpark after games rather than risk getting stuck with the check at a restaurant. The advent of the million-dollar contract did little to change the image. Sportswriters joke that ballplayers are the cheapest millionaires on earth. <p>But Jack Clark was a different story. He had earned the nickname Jack the Ripper early in his big-league career as a power-hitting outfielder with the San Francisco Giants. Off the field, he acquired another name: Jack the Tipper. Clark would think nothing of handing a batboy a $100 bill for a sandwich and some odds and ends and telling the kid to keep the change. As he carried his high-priced bat from the Giants to the St. Louis Cardinals, the New York Yankees, the San Diego Padres, and, finally, the Boston Red Sox, he became known for his unfailing generosity with clubhouse managers, front-office secretaries, and public-relations flacks. In 1991, Clark was listed among the ten most generous ballplayers in a Sports Illustrated survey. When he signed his first million-dollar contract in 1982, one of the first things he did was buy his parents a house.<p>But there was a dark side to his largesse. Clark was spending much more than he was making. And he was making a lot. In the middle of the most lucrative contract of his career__a three-year, $8.7 million deal signed with the Red Sox in 1990__he was still nearly $7 million in debt. <p>Late in the 1992 season, Clark found himself in the training room at Yankee Stadium, trying to explain his predicament to a small group of baseball writers. It was hours before game time, and Clark was in no hurry to rejoin his Boston teammates in the locker room. The Red Sox, destined for their worst finish in 60 years, weren't going anywhere anyway. And Clark, the team's designated hitter, was slogging through the worst season of his 18-year professional career. <p>A few weeks earlier Clark had hinted to the Boston Globe that his shabby performance had something to do with off-the-field distractions: his mother's deteriorating health and some financial problems of his own. But he hadn't gone into much detail. Away from the hometown press, he was hoping that the story he was about to tell might be downplayed. With a pack of Marlboros rolled up in his sleeve '50s-style, he chain-smoked and talked about his financial woes. At the age of 36, he told the reporters, he was finally ready to kick his spending habit and open a new chapter in his life.<p>Chapter 7 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, to be exact.<p>
Going broke is supposed to be easy. Since the bankruptcy codes were revised 15 years ago, the United States has had the most liberal bankruptcy rules in the world. Consequently, in 1992 more than 900,000 bankruptcies were registered in federal courts across the country__the eighth straight year of record filings. But while the mechanics of the bankruptcy process have been streamlined, a typical filing is still fraught with angst, uncertainty, and humiliation. <p>Jack Clark thought filing would be painless, but he sooned learned otherwise. "Basically I had been ready for a lifestyle change," he says. "I got overextended, and the bills all kind of cropped up at the same time. And I never caught a break."<p>The full extent of Clark's compulsive spending was evident in the court papers he filed in Orange County, California, where he still lives. He listed assets of $4,781,780 and liabilities of $11,459,305.97. But, as in baseball, the numbers tell only part of the story. <p>Just before the filing, he had bought three top-of-the-line Mercedes-Benzes, bringing his fleet of luxury automobiles to 18, not including the four cars he was leasing for his family. He had bought a new $2.4 million house built near a golf course in a posh suburb of Oakland. He and his family would never move into that house, because Clark ordered $1 million worth of interior decorating changes once construction was complete. Credit cards had also proved a irresistible temptation. He owed <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a> $55,955.17, Nordstrom's $37,000, and Visa $19,820.78. Finally, there was the drag-racing team he had underwritten__it had drained another $1 million.<p>
Cars were always a great temptation to Jack Clark. Perhaps that was because some of his fondest childhood memories were of going with his father to the drag races in Pomona, a small city in suburban Los Angeles, not far from Asuza, where Clark grew up. Car racing was one of the few interests the elder Clark shared with his son. Most nights Ralph Clark would come home nauseated from inhaling fumes during a long day at the paint factory where he worked, eat dinner, and go straight to bed.<p>The younger Clark was determined to avoid such a fate. He raced hot rods in high school, but soon grew too big to consider doing it professionally. Fortunately, Clark was a gifted athlete. His six-foot-three-inch, 200-pound frame proved perfectly suited for smashing baseballs. He was scouted by the major leagues his senior year, during which he batted a staggering .517 at Gladstone High, and he signed with the Giants after graduating in 1973. Three years later, he was in the big leagues. His timing couldn't have been better. The modern era of free agency and million-dollar contracts had just begun.<p>Clark averaged 20 home runs and 80 runs batted in during his eight full seasons with the Giants. He regularly made the All-Star team, and in 1982 he struck pay dirt, signing a five-year pact worth $5.3 million. But he was often injured and criticized for spending too much time on the disabled list. He was constantly compared with the other great Giants sluggers, Hall of Famers Willie Mays and Willie McCovey. Jack the Ripper soon became Jack the Ripped, vilified by the fans, the press, even management. He responded in kind, taking his rips at the fans, the Giants' frigid ballpark, the press, and his coaches.<p>Off the field, Clark was faring better. He bought a house for his parents in Danville, California. He married, too, and started a family. In 1980, his wife Tamara gave birth to the first of their four children.<p>As Clark started making more money, he also attracted swarms of financial advisors who were eager to help a new millionaire handle his wealth. "Baseball players get approached by so many people, with so many ideas, from Arabian horses to restaurants," he says. "And we don't have the time to focus. And most of us aren't wizards to begin with."<p>Clark recalls getting burned by two such advisors. They had him investing in oil-and-gas leases in the Sunbelt, over-leveraged real estate in Atlantic City, and lithographs by unknown artists. When the IRS cracked down on tax shelters in the mid-'80s, Clark was hit with hefty penalties and forced to pay interest accrued on back taxes. As for the advisors, "One guy left the country, and the other guy ended up in jail," Clark says.<p>Clark decided that he'd had enough with financial advisors. He hired his father to keep his books and pay his bills. That left him free to concentrate on baseball, and in 1985 he led his new team, the St. Louis Cardinals, to the National League pennant.<p>
Buoyed by his play for the Cardinals, Clark drifted back to his first love__cars. He started collecting them as a hobby. His first acquisitions were '50s muscle cars__a $15,000 1957 Bel Air, an $80,000 '57 Thunderbird, a $42,000 '55 <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> Crown Victoria, a $36,000 '57 Plymouth Fury, a $39,000 '57 Lincoln Coupe, and a $63,000 '57 Lincoln Premiere convertible. <p>In 1988 he signed a two-year, $3 million deal with the New York Yankees. But the home runs didn't come, and after one season he was traded to the San Diego Padres, who agreed to pay the increasingly unproductive slugger $2 million per year. By this time, Clark's appetite for expensive automobiles had expanded. He was now buying Ferraris.<p>The market for Ferraris had traditionally been made up of rich collectors who were content to watch the value of their cars rise a steady 10 percent per year. But after Enzo Ferrari died in August 1988, the cars he'd designed started appreciating 10 percent a month, which attracted speculators and forced prices up even further. In 1989, Clark paid nearly $200,000 for a Ferrari Mondial. In 1990, he spent $717,000 on one of the 180 Ferrari F-40's shipped to the United States that year. Within months, the car's value shot up to more than $1.2 million. But the value fell just as fast. By the fall of 1990, Clark's Ferraris were worth less than half of what he had paid for them.<p>Clark remained oblivious. "Jack is a car guy," says Brandon Lawrence, sales manager at Walnut Creek Ferrari, in Walnut Creek, California, where Clark was a customer. "He never bought cars to make money on them. He just happened to buy when everything was going down."<p>Clark's "auto frenzy," as he calls it, was soon the talk of the major leagues. Stories circulated. One afternoon, according to one such story, Clark and San Diego teammate Mike Pagliarulo made plans to take their kids to the movies. Clark decided to run some errands during the film, and left his kids with Pagliarulo. When the movie let out, Clark drove up in another new Ferrari that he had just purchased. Another time, Clark grew tired of one of his BMWs a few days after buying it, and sold it to Pagliarulo for a fraction of the original price.<p>When the 1990 season ended, so did Clark's two-year, $4-million contract with the Padres. Clark was a free agent once again, and the market for sluggers, unlike that for Ferraris, was still rising. He caught on with the Red Sox, signing the three-year, $8.7 million deal. And, feeling flush, he decided that it was time to go from collecting cars to racing them. That fall he started the Jack Clark Racing Team, equipping the new venture with a high-priced dragster and driver. <p>It seemed like a good idea at the time. There was money to be made in racing and Clark wasn't going it alone. He had found a cosponsor, <a name="NYSE:MBL"></a><b>Mobil</b> One motor oil. But some people saw that he was on shaky ground. "Jack Clark," says one sports attorney, "was a train wreck waiting to happen."<p>
Clark's first inkling that he was in financial trouble came in early 1991, just before he joined the Red Sox. He was making more than ever, but beyond his rapidly depreciating auto collection, he had little to show for his millions.<p>Clark decided that what he needed was someone who could put him on a budget. Enter Mark Gillam, a 30-year-old financial manager with offices near Sacramento, California, who counts among his clients Clark's former Yankees teammate Steve Sax. Gillam's advice was simple. Forget real estate. Stop collecting cars. Invest conservatively, in blue-chip stocks, tax-free municipal bonds, and T-bills.<p>Clark's father had long argued along the same lines. But Clark found his father old-fashioned, out of step with the times, even embarrassing. Ralph was always expecting the worst, even in the best of times. "His dad is a put-your-money-in-the-mattress kind of guy," says Gillam. "You can listen to your folks, but when you're independent like Jack is, it doesn't always have an effect."<p>Gillam drew up a financial road map, and for a while Clark followed it. For a short while. In June of 1991 the ballplayer reverted to form, laying out close to $400,000 for a share in a seafood restaurant in San Ramon, California__an illiquid investment if ever there was one.<p>Clark can't really explain why he discounted Gillam's advice. "I wasn't trusting anybody 100 percent like I had before," he says. Gillam tries to remain philosophical about Clark's detour from the plan: "You can only give people road maps," he says. "Getting them there is a very different science that you have very little control over."<p>The racing team wasn't working out either. In the fall of 1991, Mobil One withdrew. Mobil's contribution had never been large, but now Clark was forced to pay all of the hefty expenses of keeping a dragster running. By the following spring, he was forced to fold__$1 million poorer. The experience with racing hardly chastened him, though; he kept on spending. Having just bought the new home in Danville, a rambling mission-style affair, he laid out $1 million for the post-construction redesign. ("Jack loves tiles," says Gillam by way of explanation.) <p>And he kept collecting cars. He'd given up on Ferraris. Instead, he bought Mercedes-Benzes. In 1992 he paid more than $100,000 each for a black 500SL coupe and a white 500SL sedan, and more than $140,000 for a black 600SL sedan. <p>Gillam was alarmed by his client's spending, but he was hardly surprised. He had seen the same pattern of reckless spending in other successful athletes. "Baseball is a surrealistic occupation," he says. "It's hard for players to come to terms with the fact that money isn't readily available in a neverending stream." <p>In the spring of 1992 Clark started falling behind on his car loans, mortgage payments, and interior-design bills. The banks and his other creditors started turning on the pressure. Clark was hounded by phone calls at home, on the road, even in the clubhouse at Fenway Park. Gillam met with the creditors throughout the summer, but they were unwilling to extend Clark's credit. They knew what the slugger was making__news of his contract had been in all the papers. They wanted their money. <p>In June, Clark's mother, Jennie, suffered a viral infection of the aorta and required open-heart surgery. After the operation she returned home, but her medical and nursing bills ran as high as $14,000 a month. He could hardly afford another obligation. He had already asked the Red Sox to alter his payment schedule to help him fend off his creditors, and he owed the IRS another $400,000 in taxes. When the Red Sox declined to help him out with a loan, Clark turned to his financial manager for help. This time, Gillam had a new map to show him__a bankruptcy filing.<p>Overnight, Clark became the symbol of the millionaire athlete run amok. "When some athlete asks to have his contract renegotiated because 'I have to do what's best for my family,' is he saying that his family is being forced to survive on a mere 15 or 16 sets of wheels?" wrote Sports Illustrated's Leigh Montville shortly afterward. <p>It seemed the only people offering any understanding were other ballplayers. "It's got to be very tough for him, this happening in a very public game like this," says Minnesota Twins designated hitter Dave Winfield, a former teammate of Clark's. "He's a rich baseball player, and people don't have much sympathy for someone in his situation." Even Tony Gwynn, the Padres star with whom Clark had a highly publicized feud during the 1990 season when the two were teammates, empathizes. Gwynn too has been through bankruptcy, and those memories cut deeper than his animosity toward Clark. "I feel sorry for him," Gwynn said.<p>
Chronic shoulder injuries ended Clark's 1992 season early. In late August he cleaned out his locker at Fenway Park for what would be the last time and joined his wife and children in the family's newly rented condominium in Newport Beach, California. Bankruptcy didn't seem so bad. He was hoping to put the whole mess behind him by spring training, and to find a way to protect the $2.4 million that the Red Sox owed him for the 1993 season. <p>That same month, he refiled his petition under Chapter 11 of the bankrutpcy code, in large part so that he could retain control of his remaining assets and future income. Under Chapter 7, he would have had to liquidate all of those assets in order to pay his debts. With the Chapter 11 filing he would be able to hold on to those assets, assuming he could come up with a reorganization plan to pay off his creditors.<p>The following month Clark's hopes for a clean getaway were dashed. His creditors accused him of hiding some of his assets, among them his '57 Bel Air. The U.S. bankruptcy trustee agreed with Clark's creditors and filed a motion to have Clark's reorganization plan seized__a highly unusual move in Chapter 11 proceedings. The court granted the motion. Clark and Gillam insist that they had been operating in good faith all along. "Some debtors don't want to pay back debts," Gillam says. "That wasn't Jack Clark's case. His intention was always to pay back his debts." But the creditors wouldn't cut him any slack. "I firmly believe that if Jack was Joe Jones," says Gillam, "they would been a lot more understanding. But because he was Jack Clark, the baseball player, they had no sympathy."<p>The court's decision meant that Clark had to surrender control of his finances to an independent trustee, Charles Daff, who had handled Clark's original Chapter 7 filing. Daff hired Rus, Miliband, Williams & Smith, a law firm based in Irvine, California, to take charge of Clark's money while a reorganization plan was drafted. Clark finally had a keeper. He was also broke.<p>To Clark, bankruptcy was both a blessing and a curse. "When you file," he says, "you get a tremendous amount of protection, but now you've got a trustee who's calling all the shots in your life. And if you cross him, watch out. He's like the IRS ... or God."<p>The following December brought more bad news for Clark. His creditors got wind of the estimated $1.6 million owed him as a result of a 1987 court suit brought by the players' union against the major-league owners for colluding to keep baseball salaries down by hindering the movement of free agents. None of the players were expected to collect on the settlement until 1994 at the earliest. But that didn't stop his creditors from filing a motion with the trustee. <p>Clark's attorneys tried to block the motion, arguing that his collusion money ought to be protected in much the same way that endowments and annuities are. Once again the court ruled against Clark. And once again he was left to wonder whether Chapter 11 offered any protection. "One day they were going after expensive pieces of steel," he says. "The next day they're going after money that isn't even there. It's a cold, cold deal."<p>In February 1993 Clark reported to the Red Sox training camp 20 pounds overweight and hobbled by a hip injury that had flared up during the off-season. Consumed by his financial woes, he was on the horn with Gillam and his attorneys every chance he could get. For the Red Sox, who were purging their problem players, Clark had become dead weight. He was released during the first week of training camp.<p>By March, Clark's outlook brightened, albeit briefly. He was back on the dragster circuit, thanks to Taco Bell, which put up $1 million in backing. A few weeks later, he was back in baseball as well, signed by the Montreal Expos, a pennant contender greatly in need of a right-handed slugger. Still overweight and still distracted, he joined the Expos in Florida, but his late start and lack of conditioning had put him too far behind the other players. When the team broke camp and traveled north for the new season, Clark agreed to stay in West Palm Beach and continue working out with the Expos' single-A team in the Florida State League, the lowest rung of the minor leagues.<p>April would be the cruelest month of Clark's financial ordeal. For the first time in 17 years, he wasn't in the dugout on opening day. Instead, he was in West Palm Beach, broke, alone, and still waiting for the first paycheck under the new budget plan that Gillam was negotiating with Rus, Miliband. He tried to concentrate on baseball, but he was too distracted. One night, his distraught wife called to tell him that the landlord was threatening to evict her and the kids from their condo. A few nights later, she called to tell him that the power had been turned off. Then his attorneys called, summoning him back to California: Four of his bank creditors had filed civil suits, seeking further protection in case the reorganization somehow went awry.<p>In the last week of April, Rus, Miliband finally submitted Clark's reorganization plan to the creditors for a vote. The plan called for 100 percent payback of all of Clark's unsecured debts over the next 12 months. That came to a little more than $2 million, a far cry from the original $11.5 million Clark had appeared to owe, but most of those claims had been canceled out when the various assets__his house, his cars, and so on__were returned to the secured creditors.<p>Clark had to agree to sell his parents' house. He would have to live on $23,700 a month during the baseball season and half that amount during the off-season__a large cut in pay from the $400,000 a month he had been pulling down at the time his bankruptcy was filed. As Gillam said to one of the Rus, Miliband lawyers, however, "This may be the best thing to happen to Jack. He's finally on a budget."<p>In a year's time, Clark's creditors would be collecting 100 cents on every dollar they had lent him__a payback that was virtually unheard of in Chapter 11 reorganizations. Clark, on the other hand, would be walking away with about $450,000 in total assets, which worked out to about a nickel on every dollar of the estimated $20 million he had earned in the big leagues.<p>That closed the books on Jack Clark the bankrupt. Jack Clark the ballplayer was cut by Montreal last June, but he still hopes to make a comeback next season. He's been spending the 1993 baseball season taking in his son's Little League games, catching his daughters' plays, and trying to enjoy his first summer off in two decades.<p>The worst of the ordeal is over, and though Clark clearly seems committed to reforming his reckless ways, it's not clear what he's learned. In one instant, he says, "Bankruptcy is like a big chess game that nobody wins." In the next: "It's not as bad as it seems." And a moment later: "It was a lot tougher than people think."<p>In the end, though, Jack Clark betrays a bitter wisdom: "There's no way to really understand this unless you go through it. You just have to be ready for a clusterf__ day in and day out until it's over."<p>
John Strahinich is a senior editor at Boston magazine.<p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Sports Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
