		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-Scott Turow's Chicago</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Carla Koehl<p>Ah, those Chicagoans. When they aren't slogging through another murder case, they're sitting back, slugging down beer in some Polish bar under the El tracks. As the lawyer-turned-novelist Scott Turow tells it, that's how things work in his brilliantly decaying fictional version of the Windy City. <p>Turow has set his newest murder-mystery, Pleading Guilty, against the relentlessly gray skies of a fictional Kindle County, a place that bears more than a passing resemblance to Turow's native Cook County. After witnessing Presumed Innocent and Burden of Proof unfold under the same somber skies, it's reassuring to find the author's own Chicago isn't the least bit grim.<p>Best business lunch: "The Berghoff [17 West Adams] is a great old Chicago institution where you never get a bad meal. Let's just call the service brusque and efficient__no one lingers trying to make you feel like they're your pal."<p>How to pass for a native: "If you do nothing else, pronounce the city right: It's 'Chicawwlgo.' Otherwise, you ain't from here. Also, you can't look too chi-chi here, or everyone'll think you're one of those film directors who's been swarming around lately. Right now, the definitive Chicago apparel has some kind of tie to the Bulls. Even Bears apparel, if worn elegantly, is very in__like maybe a $400 leather jacket with the Bears logo on it....Speak reverently of Michael Jordan; speak mournfully of the Cubs."<p>Where to stay: "The Four Seasons [120 East Delaware] is reliably exquisite, and the level of everything there is the best, including the food."<p>Best breakfast:"You've got to experience Lou Mitchell's [565 West Jackson]. What you love about Lou Mitchell's is Lou. He hands out Milk Duds at the door. I went in there once with Tillie Olsen, who's beautiful, and he regaled her with Milk Duds."<p>Best barber: "The classic spot is The Barber Shop at the Drake Hotel [140 E. Walton] complete with straight-razor shave." <p>If you have only one day in town: "Get seats right behind the Cubs dugout at Wrigley Field [1060 West Addison]....If you like contemporary art, take a look at the Jan Cicero Gallery [221 West Erie] and the Cortland Leyten Galleries [815 North Milwaukee]."<p>If you have only one night in town: "Go to the Green Mill on a Thursday night [4802 North Broadway]. It's rumored to be an old Al Capone hangout, with an escape hatch under the piano....Also, the theater is outstanding here__much less shtick than going in New York."<p>Where to sweat: "Without question, the Division Street Russian Baths [1916 West Division]." Writes Turow in Pleading Guilty, "'Seedy' is not the word for the Russian Bath; better 'prehistoric.'...Time would wear it down, but ne'er destroy it: the sort of atmosphere that the Irish perpetuate in every bar."<p> <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
