<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/01-Pots and Panache</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/01-Pots and Panache</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>
By John Loring<p>
In 1988, having apprenticed with couturiers Geoffrey Beene, Mary McFadden, and Todd Oldham, and having organized his own ready-to-wear clothing company, 24-year-old John Innes gave up the rag trade to study textiles. <p>
He describes his education at New York's Fashion Institute of Technology and London's Middlesex Polytechnic Institute as a rough mix: half Ballets Russes and half Bauhaus. "It was handy in my case," he says. "Textile design is one part Scheherazade to one part Walter Gropius."<p>
Everything in Innes's life is strictly by design. His Dalmatian has only a few stylishly placed black spots. A massive Corinthian column is strategically placed in his Manhattan penthouse. Overscaled friezes and moldings give his deep madder-colored living room more the look of an upper floor flat in London's Eaton Square than that of an Upper East Side apartment. Even the flowers in his roof garden have a color scheme: red one season, blue the next. <p>
Two years ago, Innes purchased an aggressively patterned 1920s ceramic lamp at New York's Sixth Avenue Flea Market and began collecting the highly designed art deco ceramics of Charles Catteau. Since then, a phalanx of Catteau vases and bowls has invaded practically every bookshelf, tabletop, and counter of his living room.<p>
Catteau's stylized plants, animals, and flowers made him a star of art deco and won him a first prize at the great Paris Exposition des Arts Decoratifs of 1925, the legendary show that influenced 20th century design.<p>
Innes loves the ceramicist's extreme, almost cartoon-like forms and Catteau's spirit of populism. "We're both for high-style design," he says, "with broad enough appeal that it can be mass produced. Catteau's best work was done for distribution through three Paris department stores: the Printemps, the Bon Marche, and the Galeries Lafayette."<p>
Good news for the collector: Catteau's work shows up all over. Innes has found vases at major dealers in London, Paris, and New York, but they also turn up in improbable places. "Recently I discovered a favorite at a summer antiques show at the Allegan County Fairgrounds in central Michigan." The find turned out to be an early Catteau, Innes recalls. The highly stylized red and yellow flowers and blue ribbons draped down the vase's sides "divide the piece into panels, or patterns, almost like fashion patterns. <p>
"Catteau's preferred way to design patterns was to study plants and flowers 'sandwiched' between two parallel mirrors, kaleidoscope fashion. Beyond that, I can see that he was just crazy about the old-fashioned, basic beauty of nature that he saw everywhere. And so am I."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
