<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Letters</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Letters</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The Wealth of Kings
Stephen King and his wife, Tabitha, are obviously well-grounded individuals who do not need all the materialistic trappings to lead a happy and fulfilled life (<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9701F02.html">King of Bangor</A>"," December/January). How refreshing it is to finally read about a successful couple who are giving something back by making their community a better place in which to live and by helping the less fortunate. Bill Gates and his ilk should take lessons from the Kings.
Karen Russo
Saddle River, New Jersey<p>
Right Angles?
Andrew Tobias seems quite taken by his "Amazing Math: Wine by the Case" ("<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9701U04.html">Money Angles</A>," December/January), but his analysis is just silly. While buying anything at a discount (when one would buy it anyhow) yields a saving, to call that saving a return on investment is a distortion of what investing entails. And Tobias doesn't consider the loss of interest on the money "borrowed" to buy a case, because one either draws on savings or actually takes a loan to make up the weekly cost of buying a single bottle. Using his view of investing, I propose a more lucrative scheme: Every day, do not buy several cases of wine. Then one would save nine dollars for each bottle not bought, yielding a huge return on investment. Since the cost of the investment is zero, the percent gain is infinite.
Gerald K. Schoenfeld
Baltimore, Maryland<p>
Anyone who takes Andrew Tobias's advice on buying airline tickets is in for an unpleasant surprise. True, tickets can be changed for a $50 fee, but only at the fare in effect at the time of the change. The cost is $50 plus the difference between the new fare and the original fare. Travelers would be well advised to consult a travel agent rather than a money manager when planning a trip.
Bonnie Williams
Clearwater, Florida<p>
Index We Trust
From your recommendations in "Our Favorite Equity Funds" ("<Mutual Fund Laboratory," December/January), I picked out for special attention the five large-company growth funds and the best-performing of the small-company growth funds. I compared the one-year performance of these six funds to the Vanguard Index Total Stock Market Portfolio. It turns out that only two of the six outperformed the index fund and that, on average, they underperformed by more than three percentage points. Do any of the four underperformers qualify as what you announce will be "consistent top performer[s], achieving superior returns"? For that matter, how much would you bet that the two superior performers will continue to beat the market? It's an old story but a true one: Expenses persist and performance does not. Most managed funds -- including many a favorite -- underperform the market. So why not go to an indexed fund? And if the case for this option makes sense, why not add to your selection a 21st fund: Vanguard Total Stock Market?
James Chalmers
Huntington Woods, Michigan<p>
The Drive to Excel
"<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9701F02.html">Selling the Dream</A>" (December/January) must have been written by Excel to help sell costlier long-distance service. Last year, an acquaintance asked me if I would like to save 30 to 50 percent on my long-distance telephone bill. I replied that I was looking for better rates, but that I already spent only 13.4 cents a minute, 24 hours a day, seven days a week with LDDS. He would not tell me his (Excel's) rates; he just wanted to tell me about this get-rich-quick scheme. His only interest was in signing me up, not saving me money. He never did give me his rates. I went around him and directly contacted Excel, which quoted a business rate of 17 cents a minute, 27 percent higher than what I was paying then and 56 percent higher than my current 10.9 cents a minute with Destiny Telecom International.
Scott Olson
Satellite Beach, Florida<p>
The Planning Business
The 11,000 members of the Institute of Certified Financial Planners are disappointed with contributing editor William P. Barrett's assessment of our professional association as a "marketing organization" in your October 1996 issue. If, by marketing, Barrett means that the institute vigorously promotes and represents the interests of its members, who have met the highest examination and education standards in the profession of financial planning; that the institute actively works to enhance public understanding of the importance of personal financial planning; and that the institute develops advanced-level educational programs to ensure that its members hone their knowledge and skills to better serve their clients, then this is an appropriate interpretation of our mission as an association.
John S. Longstaff
President, Institute of Certified Financial Planners
Denver, Colorado<p>
Follow-up
Isis Pharmaceuticals, our pick as the "<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9606C.html">Next Microsoft</A>" (June 1996), took a few steps toward achieving that goal in late November and early December, when the biotechnology company picked up another 11 patents, bringing its total to more than 80. Perhaps more important for investors, on December 3, German pharmaceutical maker Boehringer Ingelheim made a $10 million milestone payment to Isis to mark the completion of Phase IIa clinical trials for one of the company's antisense inhibitors used in the treatment of inflammatory diseases, such as rheumatoid arthritis. Isis, which had traded as high as $24.75 a share and as low as $10.38 in the previous 52 weeks, was at $18.75 in mid-December.<p>
KEYWORDS:mail, reader, Stephen King
