				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Fall Classic Springs Ahead</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						World Series broadcasts move into a computer age<p>
In the old days, people sneaked transistor radios into work to listen to the World Series. But in the days of personal CD players, who even has a transistor anymore? In the modern age, the way to sneak in some Series action is to tune in via computer.<p>
For the first time, this year's Series will be broadcast via baseball's site on the World Wide Web (<A HREF="http://www.majorleaguebaseball.com">http://www.majorleaguebaseball.com</A>). The site will also have downloadable photos and stories available while games are in progress, as well as 3-D virtual tours of the ballparks of the Series competitors.<p>
Fans will need a computer with multimedia capabilities and a modem with 14,400 baud speed to listen to the broadcast. The AudioNet home page (<A HREF="http://www.audionet.com">http://www.audionet.com</A>) provides software for downloading, as well as a schedule of other sporting events to tune in to, so fans can make a trial run.<p>
Of course, all the games this year will be at night, so even West Coasters won't be distracted during the heart of the workday. But these days, who's going home before 8 p.m. anyway?<p>

