	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-All Work, No Ethic</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>All Work, No Ethic</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-All Work, No Ethic</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> ALL WORK, NO ETHIC <p>A short history of the work ethic, from John Calvin to Cal Ripken, and why it has become one of the most popular and degrading cliches of our time.  <p> By Richard Todd  <p> I am a student of cliches--a dubious field of inquiry, I know.You, in your wisdom, reader, you doubtless just tune out when you hear somebody talking about the "work ethic"--which is the cliche currently inhabiting my ear. I am trying to figure out why suddenly people have seized on this phrase.  <p> Jesse Jackson, not Colin Powell's best friend, says that what the two men have in common is a "strong work ethic."  <p> Cal Ripken Jr. plays in 2,131 consecutive games, the stadium goes wild, and the President of the United States, in the stands, praises Ripken's "discipline, determination, and constancy. "Chris Wallace, the ABC interviewer, sums it all up: "He's a paragon of the work ethic."  <p> Newt Gingrich, in his book To Renew America, laments "pauperism, a condition of passive dependency in which the work ethic has been completely lost."  <p> Pete Du Pont, a man who could have eased his way through life without activating his work ethic, writes in the National Review that "[t]he work ethic is at the core of a healthy society, and the individual responsibility of doing a job, earning a living, and striving for improvement is crucial to restoring opportunity and self-respect to underclass Americans."  <p> Republicans love the work ethic, but so do Democrats. The president, an early champion of "workfare," has spoken of it often, and the White House Conference on Character Building for a Democratic, Civil Society, convened last year, puts "work ethic" on the listof those traits that need national encouragement.  <p> A survey of Colorado manufacturers concludes "poor employee work ethic" is the No. 1 problem facing businesses.  <p> If it sometimes seems we are developing the first culture in history united by the fact that it shares no beliefs, consider these voices. To listen to them, you might think that the one thing Americans will agree to defend in public is the sanctity of work. Of course, that's too simple a conclusion: All we know for sure is that for some reason it seems to give people a lot of pleasure to use the words. Since the first of the year, the phrase "work ethic" has appeared on average once every otherday in The New York Times. It seems a work ethic is something you want to have whether you're a political leader, a businessman, a sports hero, or a rock star. Did I hear Kato Kaelin murmur about his work ethic earlier in the year?  <p> Where is all this coming from? What people mean by the work ethic seems never to be specified--that's a nice thing about speaking in cliches; you don't have to explain what you mean. But the whole usage seems to be tinged with a not unpleasant sense of loss: Once we had the ethic and now it's ebbing away. To believe in it is to believe in a better past.  <p> It is indeed a phrase with a history, though not as ancient as some might think. It derives from Max Weber's great book The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Capitalism, published in 1904. ("Protestant ethic" became known as "Protestant work ethic," and finally euphemized into its present form.) I say in conscience that this is a "great book," because I have recently read it, though it slipped by me in my great-book days. It is in fact a beautiful piece of work--an odd way to describe a sociological study, perhaps, but true. The beauty comes from the book's imaginative power, the act of penetrating the mind of another era.  <p> Weber set out to explain how two seemingly opposite forces in Western history--one might say the forces in Western history, Christianity and capitalism--managed to reconcile their differences. He identified the 16th-century Protestant Reformation as the crucial event and the Calvinist vision of God as the crucial doctrine. Calvinism made it possible for Christians to continue their tradition of self-abnegation while succeeding in the material world.  <p> The old Catholic Church, Weber argued, thought the world an insubstantial place and held that the purpose of life was to achieve heaven. It imagined a God who could be propitiated through sacraments, prayer, confession, and self-denial. Calvin swept all that away: One could not curry favor with God; one could only labor in service of his plan. According to the Calvinist doctrine of predestination, one's eternal fate was sealed--you were either one of the elect, living in a state of grace, or you were damned, destined for hell. There was nothing you could do about it.   <p> At the same time, it was all important to demonstrate to yourself and others that you were probably among the elect, and this was done through work. "[I]t is held to be an absolute duty to consider oneself chosen, and to combat all doubts as temptations of the devil, since lack of self-confidence is the result of insufficient faith, hence of imperfect grace ... in order to attain that self-confidence intense worldly activity is recommended," Weber wrote.   <p> To Calvinists, work was an emblem of faith, and so ultimately was wealth--just as long as one acquired it but did not enjoy it. Here was a spiritual recipe for the accumulation of capital, the tradition of Christian abnegation made into a worldly virtue: "Not leisure and enjoyment, but only activity serves to increase the glory of God."  <p> The capitalist spirit Weber described was born in melancholy and fear. He evoked the distance people felt from God: "a feeling of unprecedented inner loneliness of the single individual. In what was for the man of the age of the Reformation the most important thing in life [salvation], he was forced to follow his path alone to meet a destiny which had been decreed for him from eternity. No one could help him." This was the desolation that drove people to toil and the accumulation of wealth.  <p> One might well ask: And this is what we're suddenly nostalgic for?   <p> Of course, the Protestant ethic is a theory, a construct. It never existed, not in pure form. And the point the new priests of the work ethic might remember: It was a diagnosis, not a prescription. It was Weber's attempt to describe a social phenomenon, and (some might argue) a rather neurotic phenomenon at that.  <p> Weber was inspired by the vestiges of a society he saw on a trip to the United States--the 19th-century economy created by descendants of America's Calvinists, the New England Puritans. But already their values were eroding, and the 20th century mounted a full-scale assault on the work ethic. The labor movement, Henry Ford's perception that workers had to spend as well as toil, and the New Deal's pump-priming all contributed to the development of an "ethic of consumption." Americans were enjoined as a matter of public policy to spend, enjoy, and fuel the economy. A lesson we learned well.   <p> Why then this fit of longing for the imagined puritanical past? It would be nice to think that the nostalgia is a matter of rigorous self-questioning, a rededication to a life of principle. But the thrust of most talk about the work ethic is hardly self-critical. On the contrary, even more important than having a work ethic of your own, it seems an excellent thing to be able to accuse other people of not having one.   <p> A man named Du Pont, no matter what he might think in private, could not, until very recently, say in public that the American poor needed to revive the work ethic. The ethic of simple politeness--there cognition of the gulf between a huge inherited fortune and the straitened circumstances of a welfare mother--would have prevented him.  <p> I don't know the answer to the "welfare mess" (if it is a mess) or what besides money would improve the morale of the underclass. But I don't think solving those problems is the point when our political leaders talk about the "work ethic." They may be talking about the poor, but they are talking to the rest of us. And they have found a language that tastes as good to them as a mouthful of Pomerol.  <p> Here is the argument for listening to cliches: not for their literal content, which tends, by the time they reach cliche status, to be nonexistent, but for what they say about the people whouse them, what they say about their era. A generation ago, people used to love a sentence that began "If we can put a man on the moon, then we can..." You could finish the sentence as you chose, but the nobler and more humanitarian the goal, the better: "...send our children to decent schools, eliminate poverty," etc. These formulaic constructions were enough to drive you crazy, but if you listened you got the idea, which was, unwittingly, the opposite of what was being said. We were just waking up to the realization--and simultaneously denying it--that technological achievement was easy compared to the more mundane, social work of society.  <p> Do we not hear a similar effort at sweet denial when the work ethic is invoked? I think those who would attempt to sway minds with this work-ethic talk are wittingly or unwittingly playing to certain apprehensions, even fears now abroad in our society.  <p> The past few months have seemed a strange time for our economy, if you were just a guy sort of listening to the news. Let's imagine such a fellow on the early train, 6:51 out of South Norwalk, Connecticut, commuting to his job and reading the paper. He's a middle-ranking financial officer at an international company with headquarters in Manhattan; his wife has a similar job in White Plains, New York, and they have a household income of about $230,000 (making him, what, among the best-off 2 or 3 percent of the country?).  <p> Over the space of a couple of weeks, while he's at work on asection of next year's corporate budget (a painful one since the way to make the numbers work is to fire 125 people), he has read of Michael Ovitz, a name he'd been dimly aware of, who has been hired to be president of <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a>. Salary undisclosed, but presumably a good one, since his previous asking price was about $300 million. The Disney takeover of Capital Cities/ABC was also of interest. That was the one in which Warren Buffett made $402 million on the afternoon's increase in his Capital Cities stock. <p> Here's another interesting item, about some people our friend happens to know: <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a> and <a name="NASD:CHFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12961"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chemical</b></a> banks are to merge, with the result that some 12,000 jobs will be lost, or saved, depending on where you sit. Then comes a front-page story in The New York Times, not hard news, just a trend suddenly articulated: Skilled Workers Watch Their Jobs Migrate Overseas. People in the computer business making $70,000 to $100,000 a year are waking up to discover that their jobs are gone--snapped up by engineers and programmers in India for a fraction of the cost. A final item: The year long run-up in <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> stock has added a few billion to Bill Gates's fortune; now he's worth $15 billion. <p> As he looks around him, the prosperous young man on the train has a feeling he can't quite name. He's doing very well, no complaints, really; frankly, he's doing better than he imagined he would. Yet he feels excluded from something important, and he feels vulnerable, as if his life were insubstantial, tenuous. There is a strange chill in his universe. Is he going to be okay? The answer isn't obvious to him. And if it's not obvious to him, what about the 97 percent of Americans less well off than he? <p> I have been reading a book lately called The End of Work, by Jeremy Rifkin, a Washington economist. Rifkin describes the plight of a displaced sheet-metal worker who, with his wife, now works four part-time jobs and makes less than half what he did before. The worker's assessment of job creation in the Clinton administration: "Sure, we've got four of them, so what?"  <p> Rifkin's argument has an apocalyptic tinge to it; he says that after decades of crying wolf about the dangers of technological unemployment, the crisis is now at hand. By his calculation, given currently foreseeable automation, some 90 million jobs out of a labor force of 124 million are vulnerable to elimination. <p> Of course one immediately musters the comforting rebuttals. The doomsday view of technology is the counterpart of Malthusianism; current trends projected into the future always spell disaster, but somehow disaster never arrives in its predicted form. Something happens, and what happens usually has to do with a phenomenon that can be predicted, though its form cannot--human inventiveness. <p> Still, you don't have to buy into the Rifkin thesis to feel that the pace of change seems to have accelerated noticeably, and with each new merger, each new downsizing, corporate indifference to the effects of change seems to take on the aspect of a new natural law. We suffer from an apprehension that something is terribly wrong: "presentiment" (as Emily Dickinson said) "that long Shadow--on the Lawn-- ... Notice to the startled Grass/That Darkness--is about to pass--."   <p> Our economic lives are supposed to be rational; we cannot prevent the human tragedies of life, but for the basically fortunate among us surely we can, with prudence, govern our economic fate. If we work hard enough, then we should achieve our goals, rise to success. Isn't that what the work ethic, as popularly understood, promises? The source of the anxiety is the suspicion that this article of faith, never entirely true, is in fact increasingly false. Just as a plane can crash or an artery can clog, so too can people who do the right thing with their careers be swept away by some force that is larger than their efforts. Has there ever been a moment in a prosperous, growing economy when so many well-paid people felt such fear for their jobs?  <p> That is one source of our anxiety. Another arises from the nagging relationship between work and reward. In my experience, people with jobs tend to work very hard these days. Yet they feel less certain that work represents a path to success. As Keynes said, nothing so demoralizes a society as to "cut the cord between effort and reward." The apt phrase was used recently in The New Republic by Thomas Geoghegan, who was lamenting the decline in wages for working people. The disparity between work and its financial rewards seems even more vivid if one looks in the other direction.  <p> The growing concentration of wealth at the top of society has been much remarked on lately, and the numbers are dazzling. On one hand, it's not that we think of ourselves as having a class of elite sybarites--people at the top work hard, too. But their money seems to accrete in amounts disproportionate to any conceivable human effort. I am sure Michael Eisner works hard, probably harder than a guard or a technician in the Magic Kingdom, though maybe not harder than a chambermaid in the Ramada Inn. Really, though, how hard should you have to work for a billion dollars? In 1974, the average CEO was paid 35 times more than his lowest-ranking employee; now the average compensation at the top is 150 times the wages on the factory floor.   <p> A recent article in Harper's laments the division of the country into two classes and cites the existence of an "elite" made up of about 20 percent of the citizenry, those blessed with the right education, manners, profession. But 20 percent! I think it is closer to the economic realities of life in the country now to say that one can belong to the top 20, 10, 5, or 2 percent of the country and still feel something of an outsider in the governing forces of the economy--still feel unsafe, insecure, even poor!  <p>    It would be ludicrous to claim much in the way of exalted suffering for these people--but their sentiments are interesting, not least because they are ones you and I are best able to understand. If so, they ought to provide something of a window, an imaginative purchase, on the world of the infinitely less fortunate. How must Ovitz's rejected deal, Gates's fortune, Buffett's stock seem to the famous welfare mother or the fellow who is making $5.75 an hour?  <p> It is at this peculiar moment in our history that the rhetoric of the "work ethic" becomes a part of our discourse.  <p> I sometimes think we give our political leaders too much credit for cynicism. This may be naive of me, but it seems that what they more often have is a kind of instinctual cunning (and we, for our part, have an interest in being misled). What else could explain the rightness of the "work ethic" as the perfect demagogic phrase for this moment in American life? It plays into our deep anxieties about the meaning of work, our work, all work. Whenused against others--the lazy poor--it invites us to deny our own worries.  <p> And yet, and yet... it may be that there is some eerie deeper truth to this language--it may be that the old Puritan impulse that Weber defined does linger on. As I look about, I see a number of people whose spiritual condition seems to answer to Weber'shaunting description of the Reformation man in his solitariness, "forced to follow his path alone to meet a destiny which had been decreed for him from eternity...." In what has recently been called "a winner-take-all society," we imagine in our self-blaming that there truly is an elect, people whose grace is money. And where does membership in the elect start? At the CEO level, about $1.2 million in income a year? At a net worth in impregnable-fortress assets of, say, $3.2 million? Or is the cut even higher than that? And you, reader, are you saved or damned?  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment, Economic Trends

					</font>
