	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Interview with the Burglar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Interview with the Burglar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Feature  <p> INTERVIEW WITH THE BURGLAR <p>If you're as well rewarded for your work as Jack Dillon is for his, he's definitely interested in you  <p> by Mike Mallowe  <p> "It all starts here."  <p> Testing for heft and size, Jack Dillon works his way along the bins in the screwdriver aisle at my local <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a>. He taps his index finger on the business end of a shiny slot head and smiles. <p> "You want a big screwdriver," he says. "A solid-steel shaft is best. Don't want that tip breaking off." Dillon holds the Craftsman tool at eye level, squinting like an expert watchmaker. <p> "Then, gloves, of course. Not just for fingerprints--you have to be prepared for some rough work. I've been known to go in through a roof, because the roof is not normally alarmed."  <p> Another aisle now; he's talking almost to himself.  <p> "Have to have a good, large crowbar, too. And a flat bar. That's for sliding up and under things. The flat bar and the big screwdriver I probably use more than anything else. And, let's see--a sledgehammer. Drills and a power source. A good assortment of bits. Chain cutters you need once in a while; maybe a burning bar, too, if you do a lot with metal or aluminum."  <p> He takes just the screwdriver and moves to the checkout. "And you want to pay cash--full price. Nothing that can be traced. You don't want to steal the tools; that's just stupid. Sears is fine. Nobody asks anything."  <p> Not once does Jack Dillon refer to himself as a burglar; the very word seems to him distasteful. He speaks of jobs done and orders filled, always careful to put distance between his work and its consequences. When he breaks into a home, the cops tell me, he immediately turns all the family photos face down--as if by doing so he makes the transaction more impersonal.  <p> Dillon is a very physical specimen, tall and strong. Shake his hand, and the pig-iron grip leaves a vaguely ominous twinge. He parts his hair in the middle, and it's really too long, almost like the shag on a Venice Beach slacker. But Dillon doesn't have the same vacant gaze. Instead he has a predatory, appraising look. It is hard and cold and it scares me.  <p> Some people may have better things to fear than Jack Dillon. Perhaps they live in the city: Urban burglaries often are smash-and-grab invasions born of junkie desperation, far more dangerous than Dillon's suburban jobs. But in small towns and in suburbs like mine, Dillon is the person you'll hear downstairs at 2 a.m.--and that's a frightening prospect. Burglars are white (67 percent) males (90 percent) under 25 years of age (63 percent). That's Dillon--except that, at almost 30, he's been at it for a while now.  <p> His accent has the flavor of New England. And though he's based in Massachusetts, he'll travel to ply his trade in most any Northeastern suburb: He's gotten more entrepreneurial and will even burgle businesses to order. He says he likes working the area near my home, just outside Philadelphia--and for the naked threat this presents to my family, he's unapologetic. It's just business."It's work I know," he says. "You answer to no one. Just seeing if you can get away with it, testing how good you are, that's as important as the money. If you're just in it for the money, you're a fool. But this--this is a challenge. It's a rush. Just you out there in the dark, looking up at this big house. How're you gonna get in? Get away? That's sweet. That's it."  <p> He laughs easily, but with no real mirth. His eyes are deep-set and private; his eyebrows knit and unfurl and sporadically twitch. He doesn't enjoy talking to me; he's just doing a favor for a cop he knows, earning an IOU to be claimed at a later date. His conditions are that I preserve his anonymity and that I forget about any follow-ups. I gladly agree to this one-and-done approach. <p> I don't enjoy talking with Jack Dillon, either. My own home was broken into a few years ago. I felt utterly violated and powerless, humiliated. They took only a camera and some other small stuff and, weirdly, moved the furniture to steal the rugs. But the entire time they were in the house, I never woke up. Neither did my wife. My three-year-old, though, wandered downstairs and ran right into them. I still have nightmares about it. They were in our home.  <p> As far as I know, Dillon had nothing to do with that crime. But in some weird way, I figure that by mastering him--capturing a burglar on paper--I can reclaim my status as family protector. Maybe I'm just kidding myself. Even in a public place like Sears, Dillon's utter detachment from humanity makes me jumpy. As unsuspecting shoppers around us go about their cheerful weekend business, the muscular young man in the Nike shirt and faded Levi's jeans coldly sizes each one up. And if someone lingers just a few beats too long over the home security devices, he zooms in.  <p> "When you see people spending time with locks and such," Dillon says in his broad, vowel-compressing twang, "it can only mean one of two things: They're afraid of something, or they have something to protect. This is where it becomes a challenge. Is there something of value--a family--or is it things, like jewelry or gold or a rare-coin collection? You gotta go by your gut, by the vibes they give off."  <p> He nods toward a middle-aged couple making small talk over the dead bolts. "If I had nothing better to do," he says, "that could be interesting. They're about the right age. No kids with them. You always look for an older couple who can afford to spend it on themselves. There's no trick to it. If you get the right feeling about people, you follow them through the mall, from a safe distance. Once they're outside, you jump in your car and follow them home." <p> It takes a second to hit me: He isn't kidding. This is how he actually finds his targets. In my absence he could easily be stalking this couple. "Casing a house, watching people," he says."It's all an investment. Your time, your gas, your trouble. See what happens. Pick your places in advance and know there's something there worth grabbing."  <p> As he leaves the hardware department, new screwdriver in hand, he looks back lingeringly. "Too bad," he says. "They look like they might be worth a ride." I'm stunned by his off hand menace."Hey, just kidding," he says. And laughs on just the right beat. <p> I am not reassured.  <p> Burglary, maybe more than any other serious crime, is passed down from father to son. "And the better the burglar, the surer you can be that it was learned in the family," says Michael Chitwood, chief of police in Portland, Maine.  <p> Chitwood knows Dillon's story well; his department was the last one to send the burglar to prison. He and his force have developed a peculiar respect for their opponent, regarding him as a scrupulously nonviolent professional with a curious code of honor.  <p> Dillon's father was a well-known burglar in New England. Unlike his son, however, he was often picked up for assault and other crimes. "He was a rough one," says Chitwood. "He was in jail so much he was out of the family picture a lot. I think that's how Jack stepped up." The Dillon household consisted of six kids living in only two bedrooms and a cellar. The family had always taken hard-nosed work in the building and construction trades: carpentry, steam fitting, and contracting. But there wasn't much money to be had in the depressed Northeast factory town. Jack was the second boy.  <p> "He's got very early arrests in here for theft of services," says Chitwood, looking at a nine-page-long "yellow sheet." "I'll tell you what that has to mean. Jack was feeding the younger kids. He probably took them to a restaurant, had a nice meal, knew he didn't have any money to pay, and tried to beat the bill. You're looking at Jack at 12, 13 years old."  <p> Chitwood shakes his head. "His first arrest came when he was age ten--criminal trespass. It sounds like Dad was teaching him the trade back then." For his part, Dillon won't discuss his childhood in any depth, or his family at all. But he traces his criminal history to the day he grabbed his first bundle of newspapers off a street corner at age 13. Later that day, he says, he sold them for dimes and quarters.  <p> "From there," he says, "I'd break into garages, steal powertools if I knew I could sell them, lawn mowers, whatever. Pretty soon, I'm eyeing the cars in the garages. So I start to steal them, just to see how good at it I could be. Then one day I come on all these house keys in a garage. So I walk in and take what I can. That made it burglary, my first solo burglary. I wasn't even 18."  <p> In fact, according to police, Dillon was arrested practically every three months when he was an adolescent--a classic case of a kid who never even imagined living straight. In the 11th grade he was finally sentenced as a repeat delinquent and thrown into a facility for young offenders. It was there he earned his high school equivalency diploma--and celebrated by breaking out to continue his criminal career as an adult.  <p> In my quiet suburb outside Philadelphia, the houses are mostly stone and the nannies are from Ireland and England. My neighbors tend to have two incomes and one Volvo wagon; their cocktail-party chatter is about the capital-gains tax. It is a long way from the down east docks.  <p> "Look at these houses," says Dillon with ill-hid envy. "I really like those old high ceilings. All the room you'd ever need in there. Sometimes, when I'm inside one of those places, I'll just stand there and look around before I touch a thing."  <p> We're casing a street, my street. Call it a controlled experiment, if Dillon can indeed be controlled. So: How does a professional burglar know when to hit a mark--and when to pass it by? Why did those guys choose my home? We park under a shade tree near my house.  <p> "Nobody spends more time checking out a target than I do," says Dillon. "And I've been wrong lots of times too. About all you can do is get to know a house as well as you can. Concentrate on a room or two, ignore everything else. That way when you're in there, in the dark, you'll be able to move around fast. Walk up to the front door and knock. Ask for directions or to use the phone. You want to see what's on the other side of that door. <p> "Your driveway is a definite maybe," says Dillon. "It goes pretty far down, so that's good, and that shrubbery provides a nice screen from the street. But I'd like it better if it curved or formed a semicircle. That's the problem--only one way in and out. A cop pulls up behind me and I lose my car."  <p> He turns a little sheepish. "Your car," he says, as gently as he can, "looks like a nice car. I mean, it's well preserved. But in a neighborhood like this ..." The car is a venerable Oldsmobile, worth about $2,000. "I look at that car and I see your big, old house and I'm thinking to myself, this guy is just about making his mortgage every month.  <p> "I also see kids' toys all over the place. So unless I really know something about you, I probably keep going. Old car; kid expenses; nothing fancy about the outside of the house. You'd never make my first cut. I hate to put it like that. But just on a quick once-over, the benefit may not be there with you. No offense."  <p> We wander down the street and come to a pocket mansion that dwarfs my house. The driveway is semicircular, and there's a new Lexus parked out front. I'm shocked to see three or four unread newspapers scattered in the driveway. "Now, this--this," says Dillon, "shows real promise. Nobody home, or nobody cares. See that little sign?"  <p> It's stuck in the lawn and has the letters ADT printed on it. <p> "That's one of the best burglar-alarm systems on the market," Dillon says. "Good on windows and doors. If you're going to put money into anything, put it into the outside. Because the goal is to keep me out--that's your first line of protection. Once I'm in, not much is going to stop me. The cops will have to be in that house for me to leave empty-handed. And if I've been inside once and I think it's worth it, I'll just lay low and come back in a few weeks. That's why systems like ADT are good--they keep people like me out. There's only one problem: I happen to know that system. I can install it, and I can take it apart. So, with me, it's not going to do much good."  <p> Dillon smiles. "I do like the looks of this setup. I'm sure an older couple lives here, right? You happen to know if they're away on vacation, or what?"  <p> I don't answer, and he shrugs.  <p> "Well, this is okay for a first run-through," he says. "We know enough about the layout of the street and the houses. Next thing we do is get lost and come back here around midnight, just about the time most police departments are changing shifts. Then we can catch a little privacy."  <p> When they first began to track his burglaries in an ever-widening circle around his home base, investigators found that Dillon had learned his trade well. He never ransacked a house or building. He'd break in, neatly and expertly, get what he was after, and leave. Without doing an inventory, you might not even know he had been there.  <p> Yet no matter how slick, every burglar leaves a signature. Not most burglars: Every burglar. In bucolic Bucks County, Pennsylvania, the great housebreaker Angel Calo was recently undone by his habit of using toothpicks to jam front-door locks so he couldn't be disturbed while he worked. He recently pleaded guilty to 17 burglaries--many of which were pinned on him because of the toothpicks. "Common scheme and design," prosecutors call this legal concept. It helps them put burglars away without needing witnesses.  <p> Dillon's trademark is that he can't stand to see his victims' faces. "Every job, he'd turn the pictures facedown," says Michael Chitwood. "He developed that pattern early, and it never varied. The pictures I mean are the family portraits most people have sitting on their mantelpieces or tables. He'd still steal their stuff--he was inside, why not? Jack does have a conscience, but he can turn it off. Still, he couldn't stand to see who he was hurting. In his mind, I don't think he could admit he was hurting anybody. Because physically, he never would."  <p> Indeed, Dillon's aversion to violence--he's never been charged with any gun-related offense--is a point of honor with him, perhaps a way of rejecting his father's violent legacy. "I'd never carry a weapon of any kind," Dillon says. "I'd never want to hurt anyone. The cops know that; I want them to know it. Once, in the middle of a job, I was trapped and the only way I could escape was to go out the front door, where two cops happened to be standing. So I just rammed them. One cop got knocked over, but I didn't do that on purpose. That's the only time.  <p> "On another job, a cop walks in on me and pulls out a gun, points it at my head. That was so uncalled for. Those cops knew me; that whole little town knew me. Fight me, sure, hold me, but don't go for a gun when you know I never carry anything."  <p> Dillon's last major run-in with the law was the Portland arrest in 1988. The Portland cops cleared over 100 burglaries with that single arrest, based partly on Dillon's signature photo-turning. His take for those crimes was estimated at between $300,000 and$400,000. (While in the custody of the Portland cops, Dillon talked at length about his trade. See "Your Home, Through a Burglar's Eyes" on page 95.)  <p> Dillon was sentenced to ten years as a habitual offender and served about four of the ten--an unusually long stretch for a burglar, but just part of the natural ebb and flow of his ingrained recidivism. He was released early for good behavior, and the only trouble he's had since then has been a couple traffic tickets. <p> These days Dillon has a family to take care of. He insists he does this without welfare, handouts, or risk of arrest. "I work now, work hard," he says. "It's better." But he's shy with specifics, and there's no conviction in his voice. The cops don't all believe him, and if you see him on the street, you know instinctively that there's little chance this guy is punching a time clock. <p> Besides, Dillon consistently tells me of his burglary exploits in the present tense, portraying himself as something like an addict of the thrill involved. "I'll hit five houses in one night," he says. "I can have $1,000 in my pocket, and I'll still see if I can break into a house that just looks right. It's about seeing how good I am."  <p> He has few other vices. He doesn't drink or do drugs, though he is a chain-smoker. He loves sports. He drives small, fast cars and lives in a nice apartment. He wears a real Rolex.  <p> "I do not get a good vibe here."  <p> Dillon says it gravely, like a concerned doctor delivering bad news. We've returned to my street, near midnight, to case my house up close. My wife and kids are inside. Dillon immediately tells me they are not safe. I'm grateful for his advisory--at first.  <p> We walk the perimeter of my house in darkness that's relieved only by the moon and my neighbors' lights. Mounting the steps to my back deck, we are completely hidden from the view of the street. We look into the family room, which has glass on everyside. I've always loved seeing the backyard trees through those windows. But in the darkness our television, stereo, and camcorder look absolutely naked.  <p> Dillon is thoughtful; concentration adds years to his looks. "I'm beginning to see why they broke into your place," he says."It's almost indefensible. Everything's open in the back. I punch through one of these little window panes--there must be 60 of'em back here--and I'm in."  <p> This isn't what I want to hear. In fact, all of a sudden, I don't even want to think about this stuff. In the daylight Dillon seemed cold and distant but controllable. Now I realize that bringing a career criminal within feet of my sleeping family wasn't such a good idea.  <p> "In your case," Dillon goes on, "I have free rein on the ground floor. You have wonderful hiding places for me, too, like the lattice work under this deck. I could be there all night, waiting until you and your wife leave for work. Then I could go upstairs, too. By the way, does your bedroom door have a lock?"  <p> I nod numbly: At least I'm on the score-board. I don't tell him that we never lock our bedroom.  <p> "You're really exposed here," Dillon says. "I could be in and out your place in ten minutes. If the rest of your neighbors are anything like you, I could do your whole side of the block in a couple hours."  <p> "What about the cops?" I ask feebly. "They come by pretty regularly." <p> He gives me a withering look. "You ever see them come up on your patio during the night and check your doors and windows? Or do they just drive by? I've had cops shine their searchlights directly in my eyes while I was carrying away a small safe. They waved and I waved back."  <p> Dillon seems a little irritated now, determined to prove he has it over me. He heads for the outside basement door, which is supposed to be kept locked at all times. The handle turns and he walks inside my house.  <p> "If I can't pop a box or a lock with the screwdriver, I move on. With a safe, the first thing you do is try combinations. I've had plenty open for me by just twisting the dial to zero. Alarms? I've done it enough times so I know that once I do trip an alarm, I'll still have three to four minutes before the cops come. If I can't get away, I'll be hiding someplace. Before I take cover, I try to count how many cops show up. Almost everytime, they all come inside--so if I get outside first, they'll never catch me. As soon as I know where they all are, I boogie right out of there. And by that time, I really know the layout of the place. Those cops are in my house, scared to death." <p> I slowly come to realize that all my interviews consist of Jack Dillon trying to warn me, subtly and not so subtly, about himself. He doesn't want me--or you--to trust him, because he is different from us. He can switch off his conscience, and that's when people start getting hurt. Maybe he doesn't want anyone to trust him. This could be why he seldom hooks up with accomplices. "It's best to work alone," he says gruffly. "There's no need to split the money, and there's nobody to give you up."  <p> In this, Dillon may be a little unusual--many suburban burglars work very closely with women. Says Lou Orlando, a private investigator who lives near me: "She might be the hairdresser, the maid, the cook, the woman in the restaurant. Whoever she is, she gets to know when Mrs. So-and-so has on the good jewelry and the not so good. The night she's out wearing the costume stuff, that's the night you hit the house. If she works in some capacity inside the house, it can even be worse. She'll know all the weak spots and all the hiding places."  <p> That's certainly not Dillon's style. He'll tell you plenty off acts, but the crucial information he shares with no one. "I'm even afraid of buying anything on credit," he says. "I know too many people who work in credit bureaus. You buy a new stereo, a new computer, and they have the transaction. You don't know how much money they make selling that information to people like me."  <p> He also avoids fences, the middlemen who buy stolen merchandise and sell it at about 20 cents on the dollar. With the exception of order jobs--where he breaks into businesses to steal specific items for someone else--he tries to fence all his own goods. But that has its risks, too. "You have to use your head about it," he says. "If you go in and the job is under $10,000, you begin to ask yourself is it really worth it?"  <p> We don't linger in my basement. I KNOW Dillon could easily walk upstairs to the kitchen, but I'm not interested in seeing him prove that point. I just want him out of my house.  <p> "No burglar alarms, right?" he asks as we walk back outside. <p> "I've nailed a few windows shut."  <p> Dillon reaches inside his shirt pocket and taps out a cigarette. He lights it and inhales. I see his vigilant eyes following the low roofline of my second story.  <p> "You ever think of moving?" he asks, exhaling. "That might be the best thing you could do."  <p> I feel a rush of tension. Until now, Dillon has never hesitated to look me directly in the eye. But suddenly his eyes are everywhere except on mine. Abruptly he changes the subject.  <p> "Let's go take a ride," he suggests.  <p> "Where?"  <p> "Up to that neighbor's house, where we were earlier. See if anything's open."  <p> I'm shocked and excited at the same time. He has suggested it casually enough, but I sense he's trying to make a real connection with me--to communicate the illicit thrill that drives him so I can be more like him, not a victim whose eyes he can't stand to see. He uncorks a smile at me, a nice one.  <p> Is this what I've been looking for all along? A rush of power that'll erase the impotence I felt when my own home was violated? If so, the price is too high. I make a lame excuse.  <p> Dillon puffs on his cigarette a couple more times. He looks down, leaning against my car in the dark.  <p> "That would be the real thing, you know," he says quietly. "Break and enter. See how it's done." There's that flicker between his eyebrows again.  <p> "Sorry. This'll have to be real enough."  <p> Another puff. Even by moonlight I can see I'm getting the prison-yard once-over. I know I'm not measuring up.  <p> "I think I was right the first time," Dillon says. "You got a real problem with this house. It isn't safe. Maybe you should move."  <p> He moves away from the car and flicks the half-smoked cigarette onto my lawn. It isn't a nice gesture. He could have just as easily aimed for the street. Or crushed it out with his shoe. In that moment, I believe I can see right inside his head. The image will not help me sleep.  <p> Dillon is picking up a photograph of me, and he's turning it face down.  <p>   <p> YOUR HOME, THROUGH A BURGLAR'S EYES  <p> After Jack Dillon's last burglary conviction, the police in Portland, Maine, persuaded him to let them pick his brain. Dillon also walked the cops through a tour of the sites of some of his crimes.  <p> Along the way, Dillon lectured on the best way to break into homes and businesses. "You slide a flat bar, which is like a crow bar only different, under the wood frame, then work it in along the sides where the door is set in. You peel it back like the skin on an orange and the whole door pops...." Detectives furiously scribbled notes as the expert held court.  <p> Much of the burglar's advice was deceptively simple. He recommended better police-car maintenance, for example: Squealing brakes often tip off a house breaker that he has tripped a silent alarm. Dillon claimed he could calculate the number and location of responding police without ever looking out a window.  <p> The Portland police took such observations seriously, and today they respond to burglary calls with far more stealth. They also bring along dogs to sniff out thieves who haven't yet left the house. And they make sure to leave two officers posted strategically outside: Dillon says he can always out run the cops once they enter the house.  <p> Dillon's advice for homeowners was similarly basic. Spend most of your money on preventing a burglar from targeting your house. That means concentrating on the outside of the building. Dillon's rules:   <p> DON'T PLANT SHRUBS that hide your home from the street, especially if you have a long driveway.  <p> KEEP THE OUTSIDE OF YOUR HOME WELL LIT, particularly in areas that can't be seen from the street.  <p> SECURELY LOCK AND ALARM all your external windows and doors. Use all the stickers and signs that come with your alarm system. <p> AVOID DOORS AND WINDOWS with numerous small, thin panes of glass. They can be broken with a minimum of noise.  <p> MAKE SURE VALUABLES--or anything else indicating wealth--can't be seen through windows.  <p> PLAY DOWN any external shows of age or wealth, such as a Cadillac in the driveway. Play up signs of family life, such as a basketball hoop.  <p> IF YOU'RE GOING ON VACATION, suspend your newspaper delivery and have a neighbor check your house every day.  <p> If you take these steps, a burglar likely won't pick your house. If the unthinkable does happen, your aim should be to send the intruder away quickly and with little of value. Keep the master bedroom locked at all times, Dillon said, even if you have kids. Never try to face down a burglar and never use a gun. Just press a panic button that sets off a cheap, loud siren. Then call the cops.  <p> What about watchdogs? "No big deal," said Dillon, who fears only police dogs. "If you can't handle dogs, you're in the wrong line of work."  <p>  Homeowners are most likely to be hit in December; burglaries are least likely in February. According to the FBI, you can count on losing more than $1,000 if your house is burgled. And even if they take all Dillon's advice, the police will never catch most criminals: Nationwide, only 13 percent of reported burglaries are solved.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowners

