		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>How to Save Social Security</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-How to Save Social Security</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> HOW TO SAVE SOCIAL SECURITY <p>First of all, it is worth saving. Second, it's an even bigger mess than most of us think it could go bust as early as 2016. The solution? Take the biggest government program of all private. <p> By Walter Mead  <p> It's time to think the unthinkable and mention the unmentionable. Social Security can't be saved unless we take at least part of the world's largest pool of investment dollars out of the hands of government bureaucrats and let those who will someday retire on these funds invest for themselves.   <p> We really have no other choice.  <p> Everyone knows the politicians are lying and that we are hip deep in the sheep dip.  In today's anything-goes atmosphere in Washington, the two parties compete to slash budgets and put sacred cows on the chopping block, but one subject seems truly taboo: Social Security. The Republican and Democratic leadership in both houses of Congress have sworn an oath of mickle might not to touch one hair on its hallowed head.  <p> Let's hope they were perjuring themselves, because Social Security is in bigger trouble than you think, and the longer Washington leaves it alone, the worse it will get. One scenario says that the system will start running in the red in 2020 and that by 2030 annual deficits will have eaten up the entire current surplus in the trust fund. Frighteningly enough, that's an optimistic view. The pessimists say the system starts running out of money in 2016. And this assessment comes a mere 12 years after the government hiked taxes and raised the retirement age so that the system would remain solvent forever.  <p> Not only did that fix not work, it's also now clear to just about everyone that we can't hike Social Security taxes high enough or cut benefits low enough to prevent a melt down. Ultimately, privatizing the system is the only possible answer and thatwon't be easy.  <p> What exactly would a privatized Social Security system look like? Let's take an example: John and Mary Worth, a couple who match the median demographic profile of this magazine's readers. Their total family income is $118,000 a year. John earns $61,000 and Mary makes $57,000; both turn 45 in 1995.  <p> By the time they retire (in 2016), the Worths will have paid (in constant 1995 dollars) $465,187 into Social Security. Actually, they will have paid twice that. Employers match workers' contributions dollar for dollar (self-employed people pay double). John and Mary's total lifetime contribution to the system will be $931,248, counting both employer and employee contributions.  <p> If John and Mary both reach 65 and then live 15.2 and 19 more years, respectively, as the actuarial tables predict, they can expect to get $480,631 out of the system (monthly payments of$1,416 for John and $1,385 for Mary while both are alive plus additional survivor's benefits for Mary during the years of her widowhood). Assuming the two have other sources of income in retirement, they can expect to be taxed on 85 percent of their Social Security benefits at a rate of 30 percent, reducing their $480,631 in benefits by $122,561. To sum up: They pay in $465,187, their employers ante up another $465,187, and they get, after taxes, benefits of $358,070. (All this in constant 1995 dollars, of course, to negate the effects of inflation.)  <p> But suppose that in 1972, the year John and Mary started working, Social Security had been privatized and replaced by a compulsory individual savings plan. Suppose that instead of paying payroll taxes to Social Security, John and Mary and their employers paid the same amount into a tax-deferred retirement fund that could be invested, as the Worths directed, into approved and regulated mutual funds, stocks, or bonds. If they put that money into a Standard and Poor's 500 Index fund beginning in 1972 and stocks were to provide a total return of 10 percent annually, by 2016 they would have a retirement nest egg of $1,730,227 (in constant1995 dollars, assuming 4 percent inflation). Assuming they turn a little more conservative after retirement and earn an 8 percent return on this money, reinvest half of that to stay even with inflation, and live off the other half (and that they pay taxes at an effective rate of 39.6 percent), they would have an after-tax monthly income of $3,484 about two thirds more than the $2,087 monthly after-tax benefit they'd receive under the current Social Security system. And, of course, John and Mary would also be able to leave their kids a $1.7 million estate (in 1995 dollars). <p> Let's see: On the one hand, $2,087 a month from Social Security; on the other, $3,484 a month plus a $1.7 million estate to leave behind (or spend) under a privatized system. So why is the American Association of Retired People opposed to the idea? And why are many unions and liberal politicians so hesitant to embrace it? To see why getting there from here will be so politically difficult perhaps impossible it's crucial to understand how the current Social Security system works.  <p> Social Security started during the New Deal, but its roots go back much further, to the social-insurance programs German chancellor Prince Otto von Bismarck introduced to keep German workers from voting for the socialists in the 1870s. Bismarck's program wasn't specifically directed at retirement. Instead, he designed a system of nonprofit government insurance for workers against certain life events old age, sickness, disability, unemployment. These programs, and later Social Security, were supposed to be self-funding. Contributions by workers and employers were to cover the costs of annual benefits.  <p> In the United States, Social Security was set up as a pay-as-you-go pool, where contributions from taxes on current workers were supposed to equal the benefits paid to retired workers. Surpluses, when there were any, were "invested" in special government obligations. By law they could not be invested in corporate bonds or in stocks. In effect, this created a giant offbalance sheet pool of savings, the Social Security Trust Fund, that current workers "lend" to the federal government.  <p> As insurance programs go, Social Security is managed relatively efficiently. The total administrative cost for the program last year was $2.7 billion, which represents only 0.8 percent of the benefits paid out. By comparison, a private-sector company suchas Prudential Insurance has an administrative cost of 13.3 percent of its total revenue.  <p> But it's as a political program that Social Security demonstrates its true genius. It is a transfer program that doesn't look like a transfer program. The benefit formulas are calculated to ensure that low-income workers qualify for a minimum benefit that is disproportionate to their earnings. For example, a worker who earned $50,000 would get a retirement benefit only twice as large as a worker who earned $10,000 not a benefit five times as big. Better yet, long periods of unemployment don't cut much in toretirement benefits.  <p> Social Security has never been an attractive investment for upper-income families, but Roosevelt's brain trust gave them something, too: the payment cap. Above a certain income level this year, it's $61,200 a worker no longer has to pay Social Security taxes. This ceiling is particularly hard on dual-income households in which both workers make something close to the cap but it keeps the rich from hating Social Security too much. For someone making $750,000 a year, Social Security benefits don't mean much in retirement, but the annual tax of $3,794 is only 0.05 percent of income, which is not really enough to bother about. <p>In some ways, Social Security works better now than it did when it started in 1936. In an era when many workers switch jobs sooften that traditional private pension programs don't help them, Social Security is portable. It also works for women who take time out of the workforce for their children. Under the current Social Security system, a woman can spend as many as ten years away from the workforce, return to a high-paid professional job, and still retire at 65 with a 1995 maximum monthly benefit of $1,199.  <p> But the financial foundations that support this edifice are giving way. How fast? Well, it's very hard to say. To figure out the financial status of Social Security in, say, 2020, we need to know how many retirees will be alive and what their level of benefits will be. Since benefits depend in large part on income, we need to predict what average incomes will be. That means predicting the rate of real wage increases (or decreases) and the unemployment rate. We need to estimate how long people will live and how many children they will have. With all these variables, the only thing we know is that our projections for Social Security will all be wrong and by how much we don't know.  <p> If the optimists are right, there isn't much of a problem. In this case, the system continues to roll up surpluses until 2070 and continues to pay out benefits as far as the eye can see. Unfortunately, the optimists are few in number.  <p> In the most likely projection, the system stops running surpluses in 2020, and by 2030 the trust fund has evaporated and annual payroll taxes can no longer fund benefits. Under more pessimistic assumptions, the system will be insolvent in just 21 years. Things get worse from there. In 2035: Income $642 billion (in 1995 dollars),expenditures $1.48 trillion, deficit $834 billion. By 2050, total expenditures are projected to hit $673 billion, and the expected deficit will be $1.03 trillion. For reference, the current U.S.gross domestic product is projected at $7.01 trillion for 1995.<p>  <p>We've already made one attempt to fix the problem. In 1983 the country woke up to discover that Social Security was headed for bankruptcy. After much moaning and groaning, a bipartisan commission headed by current Federal Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan came up with "reforms" actually, tax increases and benefit cuts.The retirement age was set to rise gradually from 65 to 67; payroll taxes rose from 10.8 percent to 12.4 percent; many recipients would have to pay income tax on their Social Security benefits; and more income was subject to the Social Security tax. All that was supposed to keep Social Security afloat for 75 years.  <p> It wasn't enough. Just 12 years later, it's time for another big fix. <p>This is, to put it mildly, unsettling. The meltdown of Social Security is speeding up. Three things have gone wrong: Americans are living too long, we are not having enough children, and we are not making enough money.   <p> In 1940, when the first Social Security old-age checks went out, men had an average life expectancy of 61.4 years, and women 65.7 years. With a normal retirement age of 65, it was easy to make the system work. Those who made it to 65 could expect to live longer; still, the average time between retirement and death was 11.9 years for men and 13.4 years for women.  <p> By 1994, life expectancy for men was up to 72.6 years, and for women it rose to 79. Furthermore, the average length of retirement had increased; men retiring at 65 in 1994 can look forward, on the average, to a retirement of 15.2 years, and women have 19 years of cashing their monthly checks.  <p> At the same time that we are living longer, we are also having fewer children. The average family size has dropped from 3.5 children per couple in the 1950s to 2.1 children today, meaning fewer wage earners to pay Social Security taxes in the future. <p> American wage growth collapsed as well. From 1959 to 1972, real wages grew an average of 1.7 percent a year. For reasons economists don't understand very well, from 1973 to 1994 real wages fell at an average rate of 1 percent a year.  <p> To keep the Social Security system in balance in the face of these demographic trends, payroll withholding taxes would have to rise from the current level of 12.4 percent on the first $61,200 of income to 14.7 percent or possibly even 17.3 percent. If Medicare is included with Social Security, by 2030 payroll taxes for those two "benefits" will reach 25.69 percent.  <p> The alternative is to cut benefits. One study suggests that to avoid tax increases, inflation-adjusted benefits to baby boomers would need to fall 40 percent by 2030.  <p> All those who want their payroll taxes doubled please raise their hands. Nobody? Okay. Then all those who want their benefits cut by 40 percent raise their hands. That, in a nutshell, is why politicians don't want to mess with Social Security.  <p> But the terrain is slowly shifting, and a few politicians havenoticed. A lot of retirees who vote like the system just fine as it is and will punish politicians who even hint at changing it, but a powerful coalition favoring change is slowly coming into being. As the Johns and Marys of the world notice that Social Security isn't a good deal for them, as Generation Xers increasingly doubt that Social Security will pay off, and as Social Security taxes inexorably increase, we can look for increasing political pressure for changes in the system.  <p> And don't discount the clout of the financial-services industry in this contest either. Here's a guess: When the politicians finally summon up the courage to take on the Social Security system, the financial-services industry will be there for them. Not long ago, I gave a luncheon talk at New York's "21" Club for pension-fund managers concerning a privatized Social Security system. Their eyes lit up as they fantasized about the effects of trillions of dollars moving into the stock market over the next generation. As they played with the possibilities the Dowat 20,000, billions in management fees it was clear that, from their perspective, this was a Big Idea.  <p> Already proposals for reform are wafting around the think tanks; a few politicians like senators Bob Kerrey and Alan Simpson areurging their colleagues to take a hard look at them. In general the proposals fall into one of two types.  <p> One, favored chiefly by political forces loyal to the old New Deal coalition, can be called the tinker approach. Raise a tax here, cut a benefit there, hike the retirement age, and hope that the system holds together. Better yet, take the current surplus in the system and invest it in equities. At least that way we will get a better rate of return on the money we are setting aside.  <p> The problems are probably too severe to be solved by tinkering,however. A 25 percent payroll tax would wreck the economy, but anything less would result in benefit cuts. Moreover, tinkering will infuriate those who like the current system without enlisting the enthusiasm of those who want a meaningful fix. It's political poison.  <p> More radical proposals calling for wholesale or partial privatization of the system may therefore actually have better political prospects. Conservatives like a system that sets up individually directed retirement accounts because it puts individuals in control of their financial future. Those who are skeptical about the future of Social Security like it because individuals would have legal title to their contributions. The financial-services industry likes it because administering these pension funds would be the source of huge and continuing profits.  <p> Although in general the idea of Social Security privatization remains the property of the political right, the system is too big and affects too many people for it to be reformed without political consensus. That's why glimmerings of support from moderate Democrats like Senator Kerrey and social activists such as Sam Beard are so interesting.  <p> Beard, who got his political start as a staff associate with Senator Robert Kennedy in 1965, is an unexpected voice arguing for privatization. Chairman of the nonprofit National Development Council and a descendant of railroad baron James J. Hill Beard believes that partial privatization of Social Security is a social-justice issue. "Working families in this country," he says, "don't have the chance to accumulate capital. I'd like to see this become a country with 100 million millionaires."  <p> As Beard sees it, by encouraging working families to accumulate capital in a mixed public-private Social Security system, we might be able to address some of the inequality in our society. That is another feature of a mixed Social Security system that could be attractive to liberals. Obviously, government regulation of these pension funds would be necessary.  <p> That's the situation in Chile, where something similar to this plan has actually been adopted. Facing a pension crisis of its own, the Pinochet government set up a privatized program in 1981. Participation in the program was voluntary, and workers were at first suspicious, but with the Chilean stock market soaring, over time virtually all have transferred from the old state system to the private program. In Chile, retirement funds are required to invest 90 percent of their funds in Chilean stocks and bonds. This keeps the money at home and creates new jobs in Chile. <p> There are, however, a few flies in the ointment that nobody, left or right, really wants to talk about. The biggest is what Social Security experts call the "transition problem." In a nutshell: If we abolish Social Security taxes and replace them with a private funding system, who puts in the money to pay the benefits for the people in the current system? Those who have already retired and those who have paid into the system for decades have legitimate moral claims to the benefits they have been promised. At present, Social Security pays out $317 billion in benefits annually. Over a 30-year transition period, we could be talking about $10 trillion to $12 trillion in unfunded pension liabilities. The total current surplus in the trust fund is just $436 billion. Any suggestions? <p> The Chilean example, unfortunately, isn't much help. Since previous governments had nationalized much of Chilean industry, the Pinochet government was able to use the proceeds from privatization to help fund the transition. Furthermore, as private-pension expert Jean de Fougerolles told me, at the time of pension reform, Chile had a significant budget surplus. This, too, could be devoted to filling the holes in the pension system. Finally, the vast inflow of capital from the new pension system transformed Chile's underdeveloped financial markets and ignited a period of rapid economic growth. Tax revenues shot up, and the pension obligations of the old system shrank as a percentage of Chile's gross domestic product. Even so, the transition has been difficult and costly 4 to 5 percent of Chilean GDP was devoted to paying off the old system's pensions for the first ten years.  <p> Beyond the funding problem are questions about how such a vast private pension could be effectively regulated and administered. If private pension funds went broke, the government would clearly be obligated to insure investors against complete destitution. This implies a certain amount of supervision of the management and operation of the licensed investment funds.  <p> A mixed system one that introduced partial privatization while keeping many features of the present system might be a solution to these problems. For example, a bill proposed by senators Kerrey and Simpson would allow individuals to place part of their Social Security contribution 2 percent of wages into private pension plans.   <p> A mixed or gradual plan combined with benefit reductions, extension of retirement age to 70, and other belt-tightening features could keep the present system more or less afloat while giving younger people more assurance that at least some of their contributions will be waiting for them at retirement. Benefits under the old system would gradually drop through the transition, but no age group would suffer disproportionately.  <p> The right mixed system could solve these and other problems but not without major expenditures. Although mixed plans shrink the costs of transition, they don't eliminate them. One study of a mixed plan suggests that without a payroll-tax increase, the cost of transition would be about $2.4 trillion. Raising payroll taxes from 6.4 to 8.4 percent during the transition period would help fill that gap.  <p> A mixed system could still disproportionately hurt some classes of Americans in fact, precisely those classes that the current Social Security system is designed to help. For example, blue-collar workers face falling incomes, making it more difficult for them to save for retirement. At the same time, layoffs and intermittent employment are increasingly common facts of blue-collar life. <p> People who temporarily drop out of the workforce in their 20s would also be hurt. These are the years when most women take time off from work to have children. Thanks to compound interest, missed contributions in the early years are hard to make up. At a 10 percent annual total return until she retires, every $100 a young mother misses contributing at age 21 reduces her retirement nest egg by $8,018. Unemployment has a similar effect.That flaw could be fixed. An insurance program working much like current disability insurance could ensure that contributions would be kept up during parental leave and unemployment.  <p> Low-income workers would take the biggest hit. The present system subsidizes retirement for low-income working people. They cannot afford benefit cuts, nor can they save enough to give them the kind of nest egg John and Mary Worth put away. But this too can be remedied. A government savings match could top up the contributions of low-income workers to the private investment fund. Since these contributions would compound over time, it would actually be cheaper for the government to subsidize the retirement of the working poor with a savings match rather than pay-as-you-go transfer programs.  <p> A mixed public-private Social Security system could work significantly better than the current system is projected to do. But that requires that we do not simply gut the current Social Security program and replace it with a privatized pension plan that works for the rich but for no one else. The present Social Security system protects most of the elderly against poverty. It is a cheap form of term insurance that provides generous benefits for the under-18 children of deceased workers. Unlike almost every other government program, Social Security provides economic recognition for the contribution that homemakers have made, providing women with survivors' benefits after the deaths of their bread winning husbands. <p> But that system looks increasingly unable to perform all the set asks. The delicate balance that has made Social Security work so well has been upset. It's time for a new system that pays attention to the goals of the old plan but that has a better chance of achieving them in a world that is demographically and economically far different than that of the New Deal.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Taxation, Retirement

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

