<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Die Broke</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Die Broke</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Die Broke</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover  <p> DIE BROKE <p>We are all being held hostage by a national obsession with inheritance. When will we realize that a good life beats a good death?  <p> By Stephen M. Pollan and Mark Levine  <p> Ever since 1993, when two Cornell University economists primed U.S. baby boomers to expect the largest collective inheritance in world history around $10 trillion Americans of every stripe have been infected by patrimony fever. The landmark study, by Robert Avery and Michael Rendall, told boomers to look forward to 115 million bequests with a mean value of more than $90,000. This avalanche of gifts, said the academics, would reach far deeper into society than any previous transfer of wealth. Once a prerequisite of high birth, inheritance was going middle class. <p> Until this study appeared, Americans had a far less grandiose vision of their patrimony. In a survey by Louis Harris & Associates, conducted the very same year, only 42 percent of people with living parents said they expected to be left anything at all. And only 24 percent of those thought they'd get more than $50,000. Still, Avery and Rendall's numbers were seized upon by trend-hungry media pundits, and soon it became common wisdom that a massive windfall was about to be passed from generation to generation. Financial-services companies started jockeying for a piece of the unprecedented transaction.  <p> Two years later, talk of inheritance is everywhere. Estate planning once an upper-crust business is being touted as something for the common man. Brokerage firms have launched or expanded trust subsidiaries that target the broad middle class: <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>'s unit now operates in 38 states. Mutual fund companies such as Fidelity Investments, which owns Worth's parent company, also are moving strongly into the trust business to meet the needs of boomers and their folks.  <p> Meanwhile, insurance companies are selling more policies designed to shelter estates. Purchases of secondtodie policies which pay off any estate taxes after the death of a spouse, among other benefits exploded in the late 1980s and are still climbing. Equitable Life's product in this category, for example, saw a 57 percent jump in sales last year. And well over 3 million Americans now hold long-term-care insurance, a number that has been rising an average of 27 percent a year since 1987, according to the Health Insurance Association of America.  <p> Rather morbidly, many of these products and services are being marketed to the likely recipients of bequests not to the givers. Financial advisors fashion themselves "inheritance counselors" and offer wisdom to boomers whose parents are about to die. Experts suggest taking a more active role in a parent's financial life to maximize a legacy. And attorneys tell people how to impoverish their parents artificially by taking legal ownership of their homes, for example so the oldsters will qualify for federal aid instead of squandering their kids' inheritance in a nursing home. <p> "I knew the whole thing had gotten out of hand," says investment advisor Gary Ambrose, "when a new client came into my office and I took a look at his net-worth statement. There was a line in the asset column titled 'Inheritance.' When I offered my condolences, he said, 'Oh, my parents aren't dead yet. That's just an estimate.'"  <p> It's understandable that baby boomers would grasp at inheritance as a cure-all. After all, they've felt squeezed for years by rising living costs, stagnant wages, college tuition, and the specter of huge health care expenses in old age. A Lotto-sized bequest from Mom and Dad seems like the magic bullet they fantasized about as they lay awake wondering how they'd ever afford to retire. But while millions are being encouraged to act as if such a bonanza is their due, we should keep a couple of important facts in mind. First, no one is entitled to his or her parents' money. And second, this supposed bonanza may not even be real (see "A Rather Uncertain Jackpot" below).  <p>  <p>What's more, counting on a big handout from your parents is hardly a, well, mature approach to personal finance. We think the more important insight here lies behind the hype, where an anti-inheritance backlash is taking root. It's too early to call this fledgling intellectual movement a trend. But it should prove of more significance than any onetime transfer of wealth no matter how large.  <p> In the vanguard of this new movement are a small number of upper-middle-class folks, boomers and parents alike, who could easily be building an estate for their kids. Instead, they plan to leave nothing behind when they die. Even a single dollar left on the table, they say, represents an opportunity for happiness either as spender or gift giver that has been lost forever. We believe these people's example contains the seed of a new, holistic view of personal finance, a healthier approach than the inheritance model now in vogue. <p>We call it "dying broke."  <p> Our corporeal lives are finite. Shouldn't financial life end at death, too? That's what 67-year-old Bill Brady figures. The former owner of his own security company, Brady is now busily spending every penny he earned over more than a half century of work. Between renovating his country home and fixing up his boat, he takes the time to explain his credo: "I intend to enjoy life with my wife and family, do the things I never got to do. I'll pass my money on to my eight children while I'm alive." <p> He's not alone in his resolve. Take the ebullient 48-year-old Dwight Tierney, vice president of <a name="AMEX:VIA.B"></a><b>Viacom</b>, the giant entertainment company. "I've explained to my three children that if I do things right, all that'll be left over will be enough to pay my debts and bury me." Or consider Allan and Lori Bahn, who'll pass along the same message when their kids are old enough to understand. Allan, the introspective 41-year-old inspector general of New York City's Department of Transportation, and Lori, a thoughtful 38-year-old exercise entrepreneur, have a 3-year-old daughter, Hallie, and a 2-year-old son, Jack. "Leaving lots of money to them upon my death would diminish their survival instincts," says Allan. "They wouldn't have to exercise the skills that make people stronger."  <p> Brady, Tierney, and the Bahns have all looked closely at the idea of inheritance. Like other die-brokers, they've come away with the conclusion that leaving money to one's kids is, at best, a mixed blessing. Their reasons are varied: Inheritance can be inefficient, harmful to relationships, destructive of the work ethic, even bad for society as a whole. But whatever the specific objection, these people are agreed on one thing: Money is bestused while its owner is alive to see the benefits.  <p> Dying broke doesn't mean not saving or not planning carefully for the future. In fact, it requires at least as much thought as any other financial philosophy (see "One Die-Broker's Experience" below). But it differs from traditional strategies by not putting off enjoyment until it's too late. Die-brokers use financialtools to allow them to live fully and securely up to their means. If they want to help their grand kids, for example, they won't leave behind a trust fund. Instead, they'll help pay off college loans or take the kids to Paris. If they want to help adult children, they won't leave a stock portfolio; they'll help buy a vacation home. The idea is to build a better sort of legacy: skills, memories, a sense of family. And, not incidentally, have some fun along the way.  <p> The downside of such a strategy, of course, is abandoning that most entrenched of financial traditions: inheritance. But as we'll see, that's neither much of a sacrifice nor for most people much of a change.  <p> Inheritance has been around for as long as humans have had something of value to pass along. Prior to the Industrial Age, property passed from one generation to the next mostly as fixed assets: a farm, some land, tools for a trade, a family business. These assets were the backbone of an unspoken contract between the generations. The oldest son of a farmer, for example, would slowly assume his father's work, knowing that the farm would eventually be his. When the father died, the son would take over the farm with the provision that he'd take care of his mother.  <p> A daughter, meanwhile, might receive valuable heirlooms, like silverware or furniture. A younger son might get tools or perhaps a library of books. Just as the oldest son assumed a responsibility along with his inheritance, so did the younger children. They were charged with making good use of their inheritances and passing them on to subsequent generations. In this admittedly simplified vision, inheritance was about family possessions rather than money. Except in the richest families, wealth was expected to come as the result of hard work, ambition, and virtue.  <p> With industrialization and the resulting shift to a more mobile, urban society, however, families had fewer assets such as land or small businesses to pass along and the Great Depression sopped up much of what remained. Many average Americans lost their tie to a family heritage and sharpened their reliance on themselves, looking especially to the skills and knowledge that came from education. The way to become rich in the modern U.S. was to train as a doctor or a lawyer. For middle-class folks, inheritance stopped being part of the family cycle and was transformed into an idle fantasy.  <p> The apotheosis of this attitude may have come with popular television shows such as The Millionaire, a popular drama on which everyweek some John or Jane Doe was handed a check for $1 million. From Little Lord Fauntleroy to Charles Foster Kane, inheriting great wealth was part of our collective unconscious. But it was all harmless day dreaming, having to do with surprise telephone calls and distant relatives and kindly strangers. Real people seldom died with much money to give away.  <p> By the Reagan era, things had begun to change once more. Extensive government support systems had helped many World War II vets and their younger siblings go to college, buy a home, and send their own kids to college on the cheap. Coupled with the economic boom of the post war years, that had freed up lots of money to be saved. Meanwhile, real estate values had gone through the roof. When the baby boom generation began buying houses in droves, older people reaped a considerable profit. In addition, these folks were the first and probably will be the only generation in American history to take advantage of generous private and public pensions. Suddenly, the U.S. had an older cohort with a lot more than Aunt Minnie's topaz pendant to pass along.  <p> The final piece dropped into place with Ronald Reagan's 1981 tax cuts. Reagan's program chopped by two thirds the number of estates subject to tax and sliced taxes for the rest, too. After1981, a savvy couple could leave $1.2 million tax free. By the end of the decade, twice as many families would have enough wealth to pass along big bequests as during the 1950s and 1960s. Boomers began talking wistfully about getting their parents' money but only among close friends and after a couple of bottles of Cabernet had been knocked back.  <p> Then Avery and Rendall released their figures, and the floodgates opened. Before long, it wasn't just okay to discuss a hoped-for inheritance; it was positively trendy. A generation that had venerated On the Road instead started acting out Martin Chuzzle wit. Precious few took the time to examine whether inheriting money was really such a good thing.  <p> The division of an estate has always been grounds for family fights worthy of a Eugene O'Neill play. And when a parent's estate is composed of investments as opposed to, say, a family farm society hasn't devised a customary way to divide the spoils. The two most common approaches are equal division and need-based division. But both methods can rile the recipients. As attorney Erwin Shustak, who has been involved in scores of estate battles, says: "It's rare that testamentary gifts turn out the way the giver intended. Some people are resentful they weren't left more. Some are resentful a sibling was left the same amount they were. I've seen it create more problems than it solves."  <p> Even if such conflicts can be avoided, receiving a monetary bequest can cause other dilemmas. "It's ironic, but a large inheritance is often detrimental," says financial advisor Gary Ambrose. "Sometimes people aren't able to handle it either financially or emotionally. They end up being worse off in both areas of their lives." That's particularly true when it comes to inheriting money: <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> shares or T-bills don't carry with them the moral road map that used to come with a gift of family property.  <p> It has long been theorized that inheriting money erodes an individual's work ethic. That's backed up by the results of a 1992 study by Douglas Holtz-Eakin of Syracuse University and David Joulfaian of the U.S. Treasury. Using IRS records, they showed that 4.5 percent of those who received an inheritance of less than $25,000 dropped out of the work force but almost one in five who got more than $150,000 packed up their work clothes. In fact, just expecting a bequest can damage a person's financial habits. A1994 study by economist David Weil of Brown University found that people who expect an inheritance spend more, and save less, than others in the same income bracket.  <p> Expecting an inheritance can also hurt the dynamic between elderly parents and their children. Every dollar the parent spends, whether on a rattan dining set or a two-week vacation in Italy, can be viewed as a dollar that's coming from the child's pocket. For those who'll leave a fortune either way, the calculation can be shrugged off. But for the merely well-off it has serious implications. Should you draw on principal to buy that perfect retirement home or settle for something less satisfying? The more eager people are to leave a healthy estate, the more likely they'll compromise. This amounts to choosing quality of death over quality of life. <p> A culture of inheritance also does little for U.S. society as a whole especially since tax revenue from after-death gifts has fallen since Reagan's tax cuts. (The Republican Party's Contract With America would slice in half again the number of bequests subject to tax, to just 0.5 percent of all estates.) It's often proposed that a boom in inherited wealth will speed the division of America into a society of haves and have-nots. There's certainly evidence for this view. In 1982, for example, parents with networths of between $1 million and $2.5 million left average bequests to each of their children of $238,567, according to an oft-cited study. Meanwhile, those kids already had incomes double the median family income.  <p> And of course, inheritance can be an inefficient way to pass along wealth. Even after the easing in 1981, estate taxes still are among the highest levied by the Internal Revenue Service, ranging up to 55 percent. And if an estate's assets are mostly in a qualified retirement plan an increasingly frequent occurrence the tax bite can be even harsher. Says financial planner Madeline Noveck: "It's conceivable that heirs could be left with only15 to 30 percent."  <p> Finally, consider the deadening effect on the psyche of a generation that's being encouraged to rely on inheritance as part of its financial plan. It's tough to wait for a loved one to die so you can come into your own.  <p> Just ask Prince Charles.  <p> What makes America's newfound obsession with inheritance so galling is that there's a better alternative one that makes more sense whether your children are 4, 14, or 40. And while it's not a complete cinch to execute, it's stunningly simple to understand: Use up your money while you can enjoy it; leave only enough to settle your affairs.  <p> In some ways, dying broke mirrors a conventional personal-finance plan. It advocates building wealth as early as possible. It uses conventional financial tools (see "How to Use It All Up Safely" on page 65). Where it diverges from tradition is in its treatment of assets. Traditional plans seek to preserve assets even beyond the life of the individual. Dying broke means exploiting these assets, though it'll lead to their depletion. Even with sucha distinction, however, die-brokers have no radical disagreement with traditional plans at least in the early stages.  <p> Those who choose to die broke begin their financial lives in the time-honored way: They try to grow wealth through sound equity investments, while protecting themselves and their family from disaster by insuring against early death, disability, serious illness, and the like. So far, so good. During the peakearning years of middle age, though, dying broke begins to veer slowly away from conventional practice.  <p> Middle-aged couples who want to die broke maintain their insurance and keep building their personal wealth to the extent possible but they no longer grow a nest egg at the expense of their own quality of life or that of their children. Savings may be spent on things like much-needed family vacations, renovations, or down payments on second homes. Meanwhile, long-term-care insurance should be bought while it's still affordable: A 40-year-old can take outa lifelong comprehensive policy, with a decent benefit of $250 a day, for an annual premium of less than $900.  <p> It's after age 60 that die-brokers break rank most firmly with their peers. Rather than view their life savings as capital from which to earn income either primary or supplemental, depending on a person's attitude toward retirement they regard assets as a storehouse from which it's time to start drawing. Outliving one's money is an obvious concern, so a big chunk of savings should go toward annuities that'll serve as longevity insurance, guaranteeing a decent income for life. Long-term care has been dealt with already, so that's not a problem.  <p> What's left over, then, is for enjoyment. Free of the burden of preserving an estate, die-brokers can use their money freely albeit on a long-term budget to help their families and improve their own lives in large and small ways. Now's the time to look into tools like a reverse mortgage, which can provide extra tax-free income while you maintain use of a property. Now's the time to start giving gifts to your kids and grandkids and reaping the tax advantages.  <p> The rewards are large. Strictly on the financial side, one person can give another up to $10,000 a year tax free. That means a couple can give each of their children or grandchildren $20,000 a year. Additional gifts can be made "presently tax free" if applied against your $600,000 estate exclusion. (In effect, youget the benefit instead of your estate.) And any money paid to educational institutions or medical facilities as a gift to pay for someone else's education or care is tax exempt, too. Even bequests to charities can be structured so they provide a stream of income while the donor is alive.  <p> There are other types of reward, too. Compared with leaving money in a will, giving gifts while you're alive is better for those on the receiving end. With life expectancy rising, inheritances will pass to people later and later in life. Parents who live well into their 80s will be leaving their money to 60-year-olds.While still in the prime of their lives, these recipients have already gone through the period when extra money would have made the most difference. Sure, it'll be nice for them to take that cruise but it would have been nicer to start the small business they once dreamed of.  <p> Die-brokers also help society. For over two centuries now, the engine of wealth has been shifting away from property land, say,or a set of tools and toward knowledge and skills. Well-chosen gifts can help kin acquire these 21st-century assets. That might mean helping a teen pay for college, giving a 30-year-old the freedom to get a professional degree, or helping a 40-year-old become an entrepreneur. It might even mean taking a family member to Mexico or buying a computer game like Myst. The way we see it, any expenditure of less than $1,000 that broadens a mind is worth more than an equivalent savings bond.  <p> And passing wealth along during life offers big emotional benefits to die-brokers themselves. The joy of seeing a young child learn, or getting the thanks of a young adult, can not be measured. "When you give a child something, you're saying to them, I'll be here when you need me,' " says Nancye Green, the 47yearold president of a design consulting firm and a mother of two who has decided to die broke. "It's the act of giving, not the money, that's really important."  <p> Of course, die-brokers shouldn't forget about themselves. Get yourself over to Ireland while you're still young enough to climb Croagh Patrick. Go out to dinner more often. Don't hang on to your money so your kids can blow it on a Mercedes you'll never see buy the darn car yourself. As Bill Brady, the energetic former security consultant, says, "I get to enjoy my life and see my children enjoy the fruits of all my labors."  <p> So why aren't more people doing this? Partly it's because little media attention has been given to the concept of dying broke especially compared with the recent wave of hype about inheritance. Partly it's because the idea is new enough that few financial advisors offer plans for it yet. These things are changing, though. Planner Gary Ambrose, for example, calls dying broke "a wonderful value system." Nick Morrow, an accountant who specializes in lifetime financial planning, calls it "probably the smartest thing you can do."  <p> There's also been some hesitation because of the nature of annuities the primary tool for dying broke. By buying an annuity, you hand over some of your wealth to an insurance company. In return for your cash, the insurer pays you a guaranteed stream of income in essence, betting that you'll die before you come out ahead. You're making an actuarial gamble too: You bet that you'll die before your insurance company does.  <p> "When you buy an annuity, you're often giving up control of your capital," says Jesse Gottlieb, senior vice president of Alexander & Alexander Services, an insurance consultancy. "People don't like that. Even though there are ways to mitigate the risk, they're afraid the insurer could go broke and leave them with nothing." Die-brokers will protect themselves in a couple of ways. They should buy annuities only from an insurer that has been rated AAA by both Standard & Poor's and Moody's for at least10 years running, for example. They may also buy annuities from more than one such company, diluting risk even further.  <p> Some people also worry about dying too soon and leaving money behind that'll go to their insurer instead of to their kids. Others are convinced they can generate a better income stream on their own. And still others fret about locking up their money in an illiquid investment. An emergency will arise, they imagine, requiring the lump sum they've irrevocably paid to the insurer. Such misgivings have led insurers to introduce new products that, for example, offer access to an annuity's cash value at a price, natch. But while such innovations may boost people's comfort with dying broke, it's really America's fixation on inheritance that must change for this concept to move forward.  <p> As long as inheritance was focused on property, it served a social purpose: promoting family continuity. But now that the mechanism is focused on money, its benefits are murkier and its drawbacks are clear. We think dying broke is shaping up as a worthy philosophical replacement. It lets us devote our energy to life, not death; to the present, not a future that never comes. People are human beings, not corporations that must be perpetuated. And money is best used for families not heirs.   <p>  <p>A RATHER UNCERTAIN JACKPOT  <p> Baby boomers may indeed receive the biggest intergenerational transfer of wealth in history but the payout won't be nearly as impressive as some believe. As economists Robert Avery and Michael Rendall admit in their 1993 study about boomers and inheritance, they took some shortcuts to arrive at that much-cited estimate of a $10.4 trillion bonanza.  <p> Take, for example, the rising cost of end-of-life care for boomers' parents hospitals, nursing homes, and such. Avery and Rendall didn't address it at all. Gifts to charity weren't taken into consideration either. And all inheritances were expressed in1989 dollars, without accounting for decades of likely inflation. Perhaps most problematic, though, were rosy assumptions about the habits and demographics of boomers' parents projected all the way through the year 2040. Avery and Rendall are up front about these problems, presenting their numbers as little more than hints about the future. But the media down played such caveats to focus on a sexy headline.  <p> What's a more realistic scenario for boomers, then? No one quite knows but trends suggest that the huge bequests now being predicted (an average of more than $90,000 per recipient) simply won't pan out. For one thing, boomers' parents are living ever longer and retiring ever earlier. That means they'll be spending far more on living expenses. And increasing health care costs at the end of life could have a big impact, as we've said.  <p> There's also evidence that older people's habits are changing: They're saving less and spending more than anyone previously expected. A study by economists Laurence Kotlikoff and Jagadeesh Gokhale, for instance, found that the average 80-year-old is spending $1.16 for every $1 spent by a 30-year-old. In the 1960s, by contrast, 80-year-olds spent just 65 cents for every 30-year-old's buck. Medical costs may account for much of this increase but consumption is up in every other category, too.  <p> Meanwhile, older Americans are beginning to pass along money while they're alive. We endorse this "die broke" attitude, of course, but it'll deplete inheritances. A couple of illustrations: A study by Richard Anderson of Columbia University found that 25 percent of college tuition prepayment plans and nearly all such plans for kids under 12 are now funded by grandparents. And according to the National Association of Realtors, more and more first-time home buyers are making down payments with help from family members.  <p> Finally, all this hype about an inheritance explosion may prove irresistible to the tax man. Republicans hate estate taxes, but the Congressional Budget Office has noted that a tantalizing windfall some economists say $80 billion by the year 2000 could come from enacting two changes in tax rules: cutting the personal estate exemption in half (to $300,000) and applying capital-gains tax to estates. Despite all the publicity, therefore, the true extent of boomers' patrimony is unclear. What is certain, though, is that few of us can count on getting rich this way. For most people, inheriting great wealth remains what it always has been: a fantasy.  <p> HOW TO USE IT ALL UP--SAFELY  <p> To die broke, you'll need some combination of these seven everyday financial tools. Talk to your advisor whether an accountant, financial planner, or attorney about a mix that makes sense for you: It'll vary according to your age and your current financial health. "The key to getting the maximum benefit from dying broke," says accountant Nick Morrow, "is to make sure you do nothing to jeopardize the lifestyle you've chosen while simultaneously using every tax and legal vehicle possible to make sure your wealth is used in the most efficient manner."   <p> Annuities. These are the instruments that make dying broke possible, by shifting the risk of outliving your savings to an insurer. An annuity offers lifelong income in exchange for a lump-sum payment. There are many variations, but most die-brokers will go for "immediate annuities," which offer income from the moment they're purchased usually in one's 60s. They're also the easiest annuities for comparison shopping. Look only at insurers with AAA ratings for the past 10 years, then compare the quoted monthly income per $1,000 investment.  <p> Long-term-care insurance. An invaluable tool for maximizing disposable income. In traditional financial plans, it's used to protect assets from being eaten up by nursing-home or home-care costs. For a die-broker, this insurance frees spending money that might otherwise be held in reserve. The best policies offer lifelong coverage and the savings from early purchase are substantial. <p> Disability insurance. Essential for anyone who relies on earned income, particularly in middle age. Since die-brokers are apt to devote more income to themselves and their children and less to long-term saving disability insurance is a crucial safety net. An employer's plan may not be enough: Benefits should last as long as you plan on working. Annually renewable disability income policies are a good option.  <p> Major medical insurance. As with disability coverage, it's vital not to skimp on this type of program. Die-brokers typically live for the moment, but they can't ignore the financial devastation that can be caused by a family member's illness.  <p> Term life insurance. For someone planning to die broke, term-life policies can serve an important role: They protect against the early loss of a spouse's income in youth or middle age. Once that need can be addressed through savings, however, the insurance can be allowed to lapse. In later years, more affordable whole-life policies will provide for burial expenses and after-death payment of debts.  <p> Reverse mortgages. So far, we've dealt with protective measures a big concern for die-brokers, and perhaps all that's needed if you're a good saver. But for those who want to squeeze every last dime from their wealth, reverse mortgages are indispensable. These loans are secured by the equity in a home, which would otherwise pass into your estate at death. No fixed amount is borrowed; rather, the lender offers a monthly payment for as long as the borrower lives in the home (until death, for our purposes). Fees are included in the loan, and interest isn't paid until the loan is settled (again, at death). The resulting income comes tax free, since it's actually a loan. And of course, you get to stay in the house. When the house is finally sold to settle accounts, the lender takes half the profit or, if you've lived long enough, swallows the loss.  <p> Charitable giving. Giving money to family members has big tax benefits. Donating to a charitable organization can accomplish the same result and many nonprofit bodies now offer gifting plans that provide a stream of income similar to that from an annuity or reverse mortgage. There's also the psychic reward of doing good. And there's public acclaim, too, if that matters to you. To put it bluntly, give while you're alive and you get to attend a testimonial dinner. <p>  <p>ONE DIE-BROKER'S EXPERIENCE  <p> Dwight Tierney remembers the instant he decided to die broke though he didn't think of it that way at the time. Back then, Tierney was looking for a philosophy by which to live, not a lifetime financial strategy. "It was around 25 years ago, when I first started working in New York City," says the 48yearold vice president of Viacom, the big entertainment company. "I was walking down 48th Street, where all the music stores are, when I fell in behind a father and son. The son looked to be around 12 or13 and was clutching a guitar case to his chest. As I passed them I overheard him say, Dad, I want to thank you so much for this guitar you have no idea how much it means to me.' And the father replied, You have no idea how much enjoyment I got in buying it for you.' "  <p> From that point on, Tierney resolved, he would strive to get the same pure joy from his money. And he's followed the stranger's example ever since. "I've gotten the pleasure of giving my daughter the down payment for a handyman's special that she and her husband have done wonders with," he says. "I've had the thrill of giving my son the down payment for a truck that would make it possible for him to launch his own business. And I've helped my youngest afford payments for a car."  <p> Tierney hasn't yet reached the stage of life when he'll begin spending his nest egg to zero. But as a die-broker, he's already treating his finances differently, paying extra for a strong safety net and not worrying  about long-term accumulation anymore. "I'm not looking at 10- or 20-year returns," he says of his current investment style. "I'm looking to exploit the cash I have now to maximize its productivity so I can do the things I want for my family. I don't want to wait till I'm 65 to enjoy myself. AndI don't need to be buried in the best casket in the best plot in the best cemetery."  <p> Now that Tierney's moving into a spending mode, he says he sometimes feels a bit guilty perhaps because, like other die-brokers, he's disbursing wealth in a culture that preaches piling it up. And while he's not living beyond his means, his lifestyle is more lush than he could have imagined when growing up in a lower-middle-class home. Tierney also grapples with balancing his needs against those of his wife and their three children. "There have been times when I realized that if we did something for one of the kids, we couldn't afford to do something else for ourselves," he says. "In those instances, we've compromised. Sometimes we give a portion of what they need; other times we just lower our own sights. And of course, if the kids are in danger, you throw your own wants out the window."  <p> Still, Tierney and his wife are adamant that their children will get no helping hand from inheritance. "We want our legacy to be that our kids got a good education, and that they got support spiritually and financially when they needed it," he says. "Life isn't a dress rehearsal. The best time to give love and money is now."  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Family Finance, Insurance Industry, Retirement, Taxation, Government, Legislation, Banking Industry<p>

