	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Homework With the Family</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Homework With the Family</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> HOMEWORK WITH THE FAMILY   <p> By Alvin Rosenbaum  <p> In 1989, having paid the rent on some pricey downtown Washington office space for nearly two decades, I decided to stop commuting and start seeing more of my family. So I hauled files and equipment to my basement rec room and turned myself into a telecommuter. <p> Somewhat to my surprise, not only did I achieve my original goals, the move also made me far more focused, productive, and self-reliant in my work a result that, it turns out, is hardly atypical. According to Charles Grantham at the Institute for the Study of Distributed Work, an Oakland, California, teleworking think tank, white-collar workers in a range of studies experienced an average 15 percent increase in productivity after they began working from home a few days a week. Among full-time home-office workers, particularly consultants and those operating their own businesses, productivity can double, says Jack Nilles, an early telecommuting advocate and consultant.   <p> Over 200 computer-literate teleworkers and their managers recently took part in a study of telework programs by Smart Valley, a Palo Alto, California based information-management trade organization. Those surveyed said the benefits of working at home, including enhanced quality of work and personal life, far exceeded expectations. <p> The problems included promotion worries, maintaining office relationships, and, significantly, integrating work and family life. Families may not adapt naturally, or easily, to having a working parent or spouse home during the weekday, much less one unavailable to do chores or play with children.  <p> After two years in the rec room, I built a space behind my house with its own approach and entry. Unfortunately, most houses mine included were not designed for office work. Historically, the homes of the well-to-do have contained a number of sanctum-like spaces, libraries, dens but not rooms fitted out as a home office, or, more important, separated from the rest of the house. Physical isolation may seem a luxury, until a prospective client traipses past the breakfast dishes and a food-throwing infant on the way to the spare-bedroom office.  <p> Of course, you can't turn your home into a Potemkin village every time a client drops in. Working from home takes the cooperation of everyone in the house, according to authors Paul and Sarah Edwards, who recommend a week's trial run to uncover issues that need to be resolved. Invariably they appear: Is the office computer shared or not? What bathroom should business visitors use?  <p> Clear boundaries between home and office are essential, beginning with a door between them. Is the workspace off-limits to the children? If not, when is it okay to come in? I once had to lock my office door to make the point to my small son that he couldn't wander in and play computer games whenever he wished.  <p> I discovered after several trial runs that I was not very good at sharing the office with a coworker or an assistant. But working alone was impractical and lonely. My solution has been to increase the size of the business through strategic alliances that keep me in constant communication with coworkers through visits and the full panoply of electronic aids: E-mail, fax, phone, and modem. I also joined a downtown club to have a comfortable place to hang my hat between appointments and to meet colleagues. <p> There is no one formula for making your telecommute successful. Each person wants something different from a home office. And that's the point: At home your environment is custom-built for your needs. For example, I'm surrounded by my library, have 80 square feet of counter top to use as project staging areas, and have technology best suited to me, not to a purchasing department.  <p>- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - -  <p>Alvin Rosenbaum's web-site address is http://www.al.net. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowners, Small Business Ownership, Family Business

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

