<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Building Better Town to Live In</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Building Better Town to Live In</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>
Worth magazine/Advisor  <p>
 BUILDING A BETTER TOWN TO LIVE IN  <p>
 By Russell Miller  <p>
 Three things stand out on the map of Abacoa, a new town under development in Palm Beach County, Florida. Smack in the center of town sits a 7,500-seat baseball stadium. A university campus with room for 4,900 students opens across from the town square. And one of the units on the map's scale is "five-minute walk." <p>
 Planned for 2,050 acres of native pine owned by the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation, Abacoa will be both the spring-training base for Ted Turner's Atlanta Braves and home to a branch of Florida Atlantic University. By 2000, some 5,000 Abacoans could be living there, a population that should triple by 2015. Abacoa is a prime example of New Urbanism, a planning philosophy designed to conquer sprawl, tame traffic, and recapture a sense of community. New Urbanist planners look to old-fashioned towns for inspiration. They argue that sociable residential streets within walking distance of shopping and work will be the American neighborhoods of the 21st century.  <p>
 Abacoa was laid out by a prestigious team of New Urbanist leaders. Two of the designers, Peter Calthorpe and Andres Duany, spoke recently with Worth.  <p>
 Calthorpe, based in San Francisco, has long advocated pockets of pro-pedestrian development linked by transit lines. In <a href="http://www.lagunawest.com/">LagunaWest</a href>, an 800-acre town near Sacramento, California, he planned in 1989, Calthorpe demonstrated his model for integrating home, retail, and public facilities with jobs through roadside office parks. <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a> was the first major recruit. An advisor to the Department of Housing and Urban Development, he also sits on President Clinton's Council for Sustainable Development. <p>
 Duany, together with his wife, Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk, is best known for Seaside, a Florida resort town in which building codes are written to control the proportions of streets and skyline. Architectural details like porches, windows, and fences make the houses pleasant places for socializing while also molding the shared space beyond. The Duany/Plater-Zyberk practice is based in Miami.  <p>
Worth: How does Abacoa differ from other projects you've designed? <p>
 Duany: It's unusually complete. It's large enough. It's going to be very well balanced in terms of the elements of workplace, office, and shopping. But also it will have a university, tremendous sports facilities, and elementary schools.  <p>
 Worth: How does that make such towns different?  <p>
 Duany: Most towns are not towns. They're suburban sprawl, a collection of statistics that don't have the physical bond that makes a town, how the elements are assembled in order to createpublic space.  <p>
 Worth: So in a place like Abacoa, retail mixes with houses and apartments?  <p>
 Duany: There's a declension. The corner store the equivalent of a convenience store is in the neighborhood. Then there's a main street, the dry cleaner, the small market, the bank, the video store, the restaurant, and so on. At a regional scale, there are entertainment centers, which have the cinemas and the restaurants. And then there are the big-box retailers, out on the highway.   <p>
 Worth: Doesn't the market demonstrate that Americans prefer subdivisions set apart by fences and even a gate?  <p>
 Duany: If you ask people, "Would you like to have a gated community or, for the same price, have a library nearby?" we know what the percentages are: It's overwhelmingly the library. Between a clubhouse and little shops nearby, it's overwhelmingly the little shops. If you ask if you want "retail" next to your house, what they're imagining is a 7-Eleven, and the answer is, of course, "No." But if you say "a corner store," especially if you show people a picture of what you mean, that answer's quite different. People say, "People don't live near where they work." But when you ask them, "Do you want your work to be near where you live?" they'll say yes.  <p>
 Worth: Who decides what building materials may be used?  <p>
 Duany: We decide in conjunction with the home builders and the master developer. The rules are fixed because the homeowners' association fixes them. The homeowners' association is more powerful than municipal codes because their rules are more difficult to change. And they can sustain lawsuits better because you contract into following the rules when you purchase your land.  <p>
 Worth: What makes you believe developers will embrace plans like yours?  <p>
 Duany: They're profitable. Lot for lot and square foot by square foot, Seaside and Kentlands [a development in suburban Maryland] outperform the competition. I can predict that by the turn of the century the model will have changed.  <p>
 Worth: Who do you expect will live in a town like Abacoa?  <p>
 Calthorpe: Our goal is always to have a diverse population base elderly, singles, families. We have double-income families now: Mom's not at home to take care of the kids. So what kind of a neighborhood works? A neighborhood with day care nearby, and parks and stores within walking distance so the parent doesn't have to be there to drive the kid everywhere. It works for the elderly, too. <p>
 Worth: Do people want neighbors with different levels of income? <p>
 Calthorpe: You know, supposedly people don't want to but LagunaWest is succeeding. It's got $300,000 to $400,000 homes and $100,000 homes. People are afraid of crime and poverty. I don't think they are afraid of social diversity. When you are talking about affordable housing, more often than not you are talking about the teacher in your school or the policeman or fireman in your community.  <p>
 Worth: Critics argue that Americans won't give up the freedom cars symbolize, that we prefer subdivision street plans with, for instance, culs-de-sac, to keep traffic off streets where we live.  <p>
 Calthorpe: People like culs-de-sac because through streets have too much traffic and people travel too fast on them. If you have multiple pathways, you don't have too much traffic. If you have narrow streets, people go slower. In solving one problem, you solve the other: It becomes a more walkable neighborhood simultaneously. <p>
 Worth: What about security? People pay more to live in gated communities.  <p>
 Calthorpe: You can try to achieve security through exclusion and gates and guards, or you can achieve security through community. I've had parents tell me, once again in Laguna West, that they feel safer about having their kids playing in the streets. They figure somewhere along the street, one out of 30 houses, someone's on their front porch. Whereas in the typical suburban pattern, where it's all garage doors, there's no reason for an adult to ever be out there.  <p>
 Worth: Will retailers abandon strip malls for a new version of Main Street?  <p>
 Calthorpe: Safeway's one of the biggest supermarket chains in the country. We're working with them on one of their typical sites only 12 acres, in Boulder, Colorado. We showed them a plan that included housing and offices and civic uses, a day care center and a library, as well as their store. They discovered that the land-use economics performed so much better than the standard strip center that they're now going after entitlements building permits for a mixed-use plan.   <p>
 Worth: That sounds like the sort of module you could slip into an existing city.  <p>
 Calthorpe: A lot of what we're doing has to work as infill. The thousand-acre freestanding town like [Abacoa] is not the wave of the future. The wave of the future is going back in and taking underutilized commercial parcels, industrial areas, skipped-overlands in existing suburban areas, and redeveloping them. In Portland, Oregon, we demonstrated that you could add another million people without expanding the growth boundary just by redeveloping parcels into more compact neighborhood centers.  <p>
 Worth: Does that create investment opportunities?  <p>
 Calthorpe: Huge. For example, we looked at a shopping mall [inPortland] just an object with a huge sea of parking around it. The owner said, "What if we put the downtown Portland grid into my parking lot?" It turned out that he had the equivalent of12 city blocks. If you develop those at only two- or three-story densities, he has tremendous land value. But for that to happen, you have to have an intelligent region that says, "We're not going to have development out in these farmlands. We're going to have redevelopment on these parking lots."  <p>
 Worth: How can a home buyer know if a community embodies New Urbanism principles? Isn't it just a subdivision with a few extra porches and sidewalks?  <p>
 Calthorpe: One way is to imagine yourself as a ten-year-old kid and see how many places you can get. Just draw a mental map: Can I get to the park? Can I get to the library? Can I get to school? Can I get to stores? The next question is, What's the quality of the path? Do I have to go out on a big arterial, with sound walls on either side, or am I on a tree-lined street? The other way is: How diverse is the community? Is this just for one age group or one income level? Or is it for a heterogenous community?  <p>
 Worth: Do you agree with Andres Duany that yours will be the do minant development model with in a decade?  <p>
 Calthorpe: I see the New Urbanism as expanding the realm of possibilities. I do believe it'll become the majority because it reflects more of the reality of our culture than the homogenous nuclear-family vision, the way the American Dream used to be.
KEYWORDS: Real Estate, Homeowner, Family Finance<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

