<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-"A Journey We Did Not Want to Take"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-"A Journey We Did Not Want to Take"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4>By Donald Katz</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>The Long Island Rail Road Massacre lasted three minutes; the passage to recovery continues. those directly touched were challenged to accept new lives, while society was called on to show the will and ability to help.
</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						"Out of it steps our future, through this door/Enigmas, executioners and rules..." -- W.H. Auden<p>
At the dark end of a memorably bright winter's day in December 1993, a young man wearing a tan windbreaker rose from his seat on the 5:33 train out of Manhattan's Pennsylvania Station and began shooting his fellow passengers in the back and in the head. With his semi-automatic pistol gripped in both hands, the man -- a deluded and incessant failure named Colin Ferguson -- fired a bullet into Maryanne Phillips, who was reading a newspaper in the next seat. The bullet burst through the chest of the 39-year-old Nynex employee, exploded out of her left breast, and continued on to shatter the bones inside her upper left arm as if they were made of glass.<p>
Ferguson turned and fired a bullet into the head of Dennis McCarthy, a husband and father and an assistant manager at the Manhattan headquarters of Prudential Securities; a garrulous fellow who loved early mornings, big breakfasts, cheap ties that looked expensive, black-diamond ski runs, and saloons full of strangers. Friends said that when Dennis McCarthy came into a room filled with 100 people he didn't know, he would invariably meet 75 of them, offending 25 and befriending half the others in the process.<p>
McCarthy was riding home from work alongside his 26-year-old son, Kevin, the big and often introverted only child of a clever and opinionated father and a quietly strong and all-providing mother. Kevin had joined his father as a Prudential employee in the mutual funds division just six weeks earlier, and because of the commute he had shared with Dennis since taking the job, Kevin sensed that he was finally getting to know and respect his father as a fellow adult, as someone he no longer needed to test and challenge.<p>
After Ferguson shot Dennis McCarthy, Kevin -- who loved video games, rock music, movies, and dancing in the aisles at "hooter bars" with his friends -- had just enough time to raise his right hand as a shield before Ferguson shot him, too. Among the 140 bullets Ferguson brought along the night he boarded the third car of the 5:33 to Hicksville, Long Island, were a few dozen "deep penetrator" Black Talon cartridges. These were designed so as to unfurl six razor-sharp prongs upon entering a live target. The bullet was intended to claw its way up to 11 inches into living tissue, tearing an ever-wider hole like some vicious copper-petaled flower in full bloom. It was a Black Talon that tore apart the hand Kevin raised, blew a gaping hole in his skull, and then seemed to detonate inside his brain. <p>
This, as Kevin's father died against his left arm.<p>
Ferguson then strolled backward from the rear of the train toward the front, filling the car with acrid clouds of gunsmoke and splattering blood over handbags, winter overcoats, newspapers, and bound appointment schedulers. <p>
After the first sharp cracks of the pistol, some of the suburbanites standing near a door of the car in anticipation of the train's arrival at Merillon Avenue, in the suburban retreat of Garden City, looked back and saw what was happening in the rear of the car. A stampede commenced, with women knocked to the floor and men leaping over them "like terrified deer in the forest," as one seated passenger would recall it. Passengers rammed into locked doors at the front of the car, and with that, the full car of 80 or more commuters realized they were trapped. The neatly dressed man was now leisurely turning from left to right as he fired, as the train coursed deeper into the nightmare, like some exitless, silver-coated abattoir rattling through the preholiday evening.<p>
Ferguson shot a 35-year-old CPA and triathlete five times. He shot a pregnant banker, a software specialist, three lawyers, and two financial analysts. He shot employees of Salomon Brothers, National Westminster Bank, Moody's, IBM, Viacom, Reuters, and Consolidated Edison, and then he moved along to shoot again. <p>
Almost all of the passengers locked inside the terror of the third car were middle-class Americans in the way of white-collar workers who leave the office at five to get the train. They weren't the high-profile, late-night Manhattan laborers featured in The Wall Street Journal. As with the vast majority of commuters who navigate the anonymous crush of Penn Station and board the 90 trains leaving for the suburbs of Long Island during rush hour every weekday, they were the kinds of people for whom the evening's train ride home defined the blandest of middle-class certitudes. <p>
For more than a century, the short ride home on a train -- away from the urgency and innumerable threats of the city -- has been essential to a shared vision of safety that in many ways defines the purpose of life in an American suburb. Everyone riding in the 5:33 that night must have realized that violence and crime had flowed out from the city in the wake of the postWorld War II suburban surge. Yet in all that time, only one passenger had been killed on a Long Island Rail Road train, when a kid with a rifle fired into a passing train in 1968. Commuting on the LIRR was statistically much safer than driving a car, crossing the street, or even breathing the New York air.<p>
One passenger sitting in the middle of the third car, a lawyer named Tom McDermott, had heard the sound of gunfire thousands of times during his combat days in Vietnam, but he still figured the first cracking sounds were rocks hitting the windows. A broad-shouldered man of 50, McDermott had been at the Securities and Exchange Commission office in Manhattan conducting research for an upcoming case. He would always remember, perhaps because of the bleak irony involved, that December 7 had seemed a very good day, because he'd found a parking place close to the tracks at the Mineola station and had then caught an early train home.<p>
As soon as McDermott saw the pack of terrorized passengers rush up the aisle past him, he realized he was hearing gunfire. The shots were repeating so rapidly that he thought a shootout had erupted beyond the partition defining the rearmost seating area in the car. The row in front of McDermott emptied out, and he stepped into the aisle to help some of the women who had been trampled by the rushing crowd. Then he looked up and saw Colin Ferguson standing in the vestibule a few feet away. Ferguson was sliding a new 15-round clip into his 9-millimeter P89 Ruger. McDermott heard the sibilant glide of the spring-loaded container and the affirmative click when the clip was in place.<p>
"My God," McDermott thought as Ferguson raised his gun, "he is going to shoot me."<p>
McDermott turned away as a bullet entered below his neck and traveled down through his shoulder. He remembers hitting the floor and sliding his head under a seat as Ferguson strolled up and stood over him. McDermott was sure that the man with the gun realized he wasn't dead, so he closed his eyes tightly and waited for the end, thinking hard about his three kids and all the things he should have told them about the possibility of a future in which their father was a memory.<p>
Two quick shots were fired. Then Colin Ferguson walked away to shoot others. McDermott stood up, covered with the blood of the two passengers seated above him. Both of them -- Jim Gorycki, a kind and easygoing 51-year-old father of four who didn't like commuting at all, and a pretty 27-year-old New Hyde Park woman named Mi Kyung Kim, a librarian at Columbia University -- had been killed. "And they were still just sitting there," McDermott would recall too often over the coming year. "They were leaning on one another, their heads softly touching."<p>
Everything around him -- the heavy clouds of smoke from the gun, the macabre and enormous silence of the event broken only by the report of the pistol, the contorted faces of those who'd been shot and those passed over -- all of it became emblazoned on Tom McDermott's memory. He would be able to recall tiny increments of a day begun with the most prosaic victory of a parking place and concluded with the sight of unceasing human slaughter. <p>
Strangely numb to his own wound, McDermott rushed to the back of the train in search of the emergency brake. He saw people bleeding on the floor and in their seats. He saw Dennis McCarthy lying in his son's lap. A woman sat bolt upright nearby, unhurt and yet unable to move. Her eyes blinked away tear after tear. "God help us," she said.<p>
Ferguson shot Amy Federici, a 27-year-old woman who worked for MTV, and a 30-year-old woman named Marita Theresa Magtoto, who had just passed the bar exam and joined a downtown firm. Lisa Combatti, seven-and-a-half-months pregnant and lying on the floor after a bullet passed directly through her sciatic nerve, looked up and stared at Marita Magtoto as the life vanished from her face.<p>
Frank Barker, next in Ferguson's path, looked up at him and said, "Please don't kill me, I have seven children." Ferguson -- who had begun to mutter, "You're gonna get it ... and you're gonna get it," as he fired -- proceeded to shoot Barker several times, one bullet coming into his mouth from beneath his tongue. <p>
Ferguson had stopped beside a bank VP to reload for the second time when he was suddenly tackled by a briefcase-wielding, 42-year-old Lehman Brothers bond trader named Kevin Blum. While Blum's wife and kids waited in their Volvo station wagon a few hundred feet away at the approaching station, the tall and balding trader had decided to charge. He believed he would be shot next. Blum was joined by another trader who worked for Goldman Sachs and then by a Merrill Lynch employee who piled on top of Ferguson too. The three held the now-passive killer down until the doors opened at the station. "In the morning," Ferguson said softly, "this will all be over."<p>
The three men who subdued the killer would become known as "the heroes." They would meet the president of the United States and the governor of New York, and locomotives would be named for them. All would find that the accolades only made it harder to shake loose of the cloying horror of the day, because they'd charged to save themselves.<p>
The police would find seven pages of scribbled notes in Ferguson's pockets, each line beneath the heading "Reasons for This" indicating his perception of a vast network of racists and vindictive, bureaucratic institutions that had conspired to destroy him. Since Ferguson had emigrated to the United States from Jamaica in 1982, he had battled with and sought administrative or legal redress from a long list of organizations that had employed him and fired him. He fought with two academic institutions that he believed had oppressed him. The focus of his complaints included "the racism of Adelphi University" and "the racism of the EEOC" -- the federal Equal Employment Opportunities Commission. He listed the racism of the New York Worker's Compensation Board, and of the staffs of the governor and lieutenant governor of New York, and the generalized "racism of Caucasians and Uncle Tom Negroes." His notes listed various lawyers he'd approached to handle his complaints, including two "black" -- Ferguson adorned the word with quotation marks -- civil-rights activists. It would turn out that Ferguson had experienced the institution of marriage for a short time and knew some of his neighbors, but those connections had also been broken by the conspiracy. He referred to his neighbors in the notes as "filthy swines" and wrote, "I hate them with a passion."<p>
So Colin Ferguson boarded a train and in three minutes shot 23 people he'd never met. Ferguson would forever rearrange the familial, psychological, physical, economic, social, and political lives of a group of strangers in ways that only the many tens of thousands of people who become victims of violent crime each year tend to understand. A crime of violence is the prelude to a labyrinthian process of violation that reaches out to involve and profoundly change people far beyond the immediate circle of those injured or killed.<p>
By force of some brutal, Manichaean symmetry emanating from Colin Ferguson's perceived injuries at the hands of society's organizations and systems, his brutality would launch his victims, their families, their friends, eyewitnesses, those who rushed to help the victims, and many others into a vast webwork of brand-new relationships with many of the same kinds of organizations and systems Ferguson loathed. An aura of infamy would immediately envelop the event known as the Long Island Rail Road Massacre of December 7, 1993, and during the many days of heavy news coverage, Americans of the least victimized classes could not avoid the claustrophobic vision of people not unlike themselves becoming trapped inside a tunnel through a weekday evening with a madman wielding an efficient gun. <p>
And yet when the members of families crippled by American murders and maimings get together -- as they do more often now, as public awareness and organized advocacy increase with the toll -- they tend to talk about how quickly people forget what happened, and how the unvictimized never quite realize that the crime is only the beginning. <p>
For all of the coming year, the victims of the shootings would experience the medical establishment, insurance bureaucracies, corporations, the media, the criminal-justice system, government agencies, political organizations, and other institutions in new and different ways. Several of the victims and survivors would become politicized by their experience, urged on to challenge the status quo by the eternal silence of people they had loved or by the terrible things they saw on that train. Some would perceive themselves as still ruined a year later, some would feel saved by strangers drawn to aid them, and not one of them would be the same.<p>
The shooting instantly undermined basic assumptions that allowed most of the people in the third car of the 5:33 to fall asleep at night or turn corners without fear of what they might find. Basic suppositions woven so deeply into the psyche that they are usually imperceptible -- that you get home at the end of the day, for instance -- were now absent from their calculations. Out of the public bloodletting and the pain, a bunch of people headed home one night on a commuter train were forced to reconsider everything about what it means to be alive.<p>
Carolyn McCarthy had never much enjoyed addressing three or four people at the same time, so an appearance before an auditorium full of reporters at a press conference would surely entail an act of will. Dennis, her husband of 27 years, was the talker in their small family, a real "love life" person, Carolyn would say. "He had a comeback for anything you had to offer." Carolyn always preferred to talk "one-on-one ... off to the side." When she had gone back to finish college at the age of 30, tests revealed that Carolyn's lifelong trouble with reading and selecting the word she wanted to say had all along been the result of a learning disability, a case of dyslexia that caused words like "dyslexia" or "mimosa" to come out as "dys-ah-lexia" or "the Moses." <p>
Up at the Vermont ski house she and Dennis shared with friends, Carolyn would occasionally raise her hand. "Wait a minute," she'd announce. "I'm gonna say something." And everyone would laugh and wait patiently while she got it out.<p>
The administrators who came into the intensive care unit at North Shore University Hospital the day after the shootings told Carolyn that the reporters downstairs wanted to know how Kevin was doing. Carolyn realized that the probability of what several headlines called a "double tragedy" in her case had concentrated public focus. A former intensive care nurse, Carolyn had listened carefully to the dire prognosis of Kevin's tough-talking neurosurgeon, Nancy Epstein, after Epstein came out of the operating room. Since then, as she sat up all night holding Kevin's hand, she had refused to talk about the arrangements surrounding Dennis's death, because she knew the funeral might include her only son.<p>
Five of the victims carried out of the train when it finally stopped in Garden City had been rushed to North Shore. Next to Kevin in the ICU was Helen Alexanderson, a 31-year-old woman who planned to marry in a few weeks and now had gunshot wounds in her chest, abdomen, and thigh. Maryanne Phillips, the first passenger shot, was also nearby. A 61-year-old man had chest wounds, as did a young electrician named Bob Giugliano, who had been clawing at the door leading to the next car when a bullet went through his arm and into his chest. <p>
The police would have trouble finding many of the bullets Colin Ferguson fired because of the way they shredded and broke apart inside the victims. There were many more bullet wounds than bullets fired because one powerful round sometimes injured two or three people.<p>
Five riders on the train were dead on the day after the event. Along with Dennis McCarthy, Jim Gorycki, young Mi Kyung Kim, and Marita Magtoto, a 34-year-old man named Richard Nettleton had died in his seat near a window. Seventeen others had been shot, and two people had been judged so severely traumatized by what they had experienced -- one man had a bullet part his hair and skim along his scalp -- that they were considered wounded, too. <p>
When Kevin McCarthy arrived at the hospital he exhibited no neurological functioning at all. Nancy Epstein, who rushed to the ER from a Christmas party just two minutes away, judged Kevin to be "as neurologically close to dead as you can be." "But with a kid," she said, "you try everything."<p>
Epstein, tall and with very thick black hair, was a notably gifted surgeon who had worked on the broken heads of people who'd walked into whirring helicopter blades and on the victims of machete attacks. She'd trained at Bellevue/NYU, the huge people's hospital on Manhattan's East Side, where she'd seen hundreds of gunshot wounds over the years. But Kevin McCarthy's head was opened up "like a big book." Brain and skull fragments were pouring from a wound at the level of the motor strip, which almost always means the victim will be paralyzed. Epstein and the other doctors spent hours removing hair, skin, and scalp embedded deep in Kevin's brain, discarding in the process a great deal of brain tissue cut off from vascular nourishment and therefore rendered useless. <p>
Epstein figured Kevin had a 10 percent chance of waking up after the operation, and she said as much to the sad-eyed blonde woman standing beside his bed. "Kevin and Dennis are my life," Carolyn said. "They're my reason to be."<p>
Epstein was impressed by Carolyn's even grace when the idea of attending the press conference was posed. The auditorium was jammed with cameras and lights. Carolyn sat beside her brothers and sister and the doctors. When Epstein started to speak, she reiterated that the odds were stacked against Kevin McCarthy. Then she went on to list the many deficiencies of movement and mind that would probably be the result of such a devastating injury if he survived.<p>
Carolyn listened with her head bowed, but she could feel a strangely powerful, almost emergent sensation overtaking her. Carolyn's best friend, an effusive blonde woman named Carol Neary, was at the press conference, and Neary -- who'd been there for the rare soliloquies Carolyn offered at the table in Vermont -- was bowled over by the transformation evident from the moment Carolyn began to speak. <p>
" -- I'm sorry," McCarthy interrupted as Epstein was speaking. "But you're wrong. My son is going to get better."<p>
Kevin had opened his eyes during the night. He squeezed his mother's hand in a way that made her know how terrified he was. Carolyn stared hard into her son's eyes, and she could see him knowing her. <p>
"He's still there," Carolyn continued at the press conference, turning to Epstein.<p>
Carol Neary couldn't believe how her friend sounded as she went on to talk about her own experience with rehabilitation as a nurse and of the power of "positive energy" to heal. Tearful reporters asked questions, and Carolyn responded with eloquent resolve.<p>
Epstein listened, and as the cameras chattered noisily around her, she leaned toward the microphone. "All I hope for," she said, "is to be proven wrong."<p>
 Joyce Gorycki was unable to remember eating or sleeping at all before her husband's funeral, four days after the shooting. Everything about Jim Gorycki's violent death was so much different from her transitory fantasies of losing him. Everything about the experience was so much bigger than she'd pictured it, so wayward and skewed and unreal. Reporters were still camped outside the apartment as if laying siege. Every so often one would ring the buzzer and ask Joyce questions through the intercom. <p>
Joyce said she had a premonition that something was going to happen to Jim. She and Jim were so strangely attuned to one another -- "like soul mates who knew the other's feelings without talking" -- that they used to joke that they must have been married before in an earlier life. When Joyce sent out the annual Gorycki Christmas letter on the morning of December 7 -- including the news that a corporate downsizing program at Moore Business Forms meant that Jim now had to commute to Manhattan for the first time in 24 years -- she felt something was seriously wrong.<p>
Joyce and her 10-year-old daughter, Karen, had to wait more than four hours after the train was due to find out why Jim hadn't come home. Joyce called all the hospitals in the area, so she knew he wasn't among the injured. It was 10:30 when two policemen finally arrived. Karen started screaming as soon as the door opened, and Joyce collapsed on the foyer floor.<p>
Five hundred people variously traumatized by what had happened on the train had by now phoned the counseling hot line set up by the LIRR. Other hot lines, mental-health associations, and victim-assistance programs had received innumerable other calls and visits. Among the many people who came to the train station in Garden City each night bearing wreaths and flowers, reporters and police officers found survivors of the massacre wandering around the platform looking for someone to talk to. Several said they couldn't stop seeing the shooting over and over when they closed their eyes.<p>
Through a haze of shock, Joyce still managed to worry about life insurance, funeral expenses, and the improbability of supporting the family alone on her back-office job with a publishing house. Joyce's brother said he would take her to the Social Security office to deliver the required forms, but she feared the cold bureaucratic experience would put her over the edge.<p>
"We had the simplest life," Joyce said to friends at the funeral. "Now nothing will be simple again. All that time we sacrificed, and we never got a house."<p>
Joyce received letters from the president and the governor. One of her friends regarded all the reporters staked out at the apartment, and when she got inside she said, "Joyce, you're like Jackie Kennedy."<p>
Joyce took tranquilizers after the funeral, but still she couldn't sleep. She lay awake crying over premonitions she hadn't accurately understood and cursing the injustice of her loss.<p>
On the morning of December 12, five days after he was shot, Tom McDermott turned on a television set to watch himself on This Week With David Brinkley. Tom's wife, Rosemary, was usually polite when she turned down requests for interviews with Tom. But sometimes, from his bed, Tom could hear her raise her voice: "Have you no sensitivity at all?" A producer at the Brinkley show turned out to be a friend of a friend, however, and Tom said he'd grown up watching Huntley and Brinkley read the news.<p>
McDermott was wearing bandages and a sling for his left arm. The bullet had passed within a centimeter of an essential artery on one side and delicate nerve bundles and bones inside his shoulder on the other. For some reason, the bullet never opened or frayed, and a doctor had told Tom that he hadn't seen a cleaner entrance and exit wound in nine years of treating gunshots.<p>
So McDermott was quickly sent home with gauze taped to his front and back. He firmly believed his life had been touched by a miracle. McDermott had felt himself fundamentally changed from the moment he got up from under that seat, drenched with other people's blood. As he stood up, he realized he no longer feared death. <p>
He tried to make it through Jim Gorycki's big funeral but had to flee halfway through. "Jim was only a few years older than I," he said, "and he had teenaged children like me. I realized I didn't know what was going on around me. 'What's going on here?' I kept thinking. 'This is not fair.' Nobody on the train was more important than anyone else. Why was I spared? Why did I turn left when I came inside the car to find my seat instead of right? Why didn't my bullet explode?"<p>
Many of the survivors of the shooting -- there was one fewer as of the morning before McDermott appeared on television, with the death of Amy Federici, the young designer who worked for MTV -- were variously wondering why they had been spared. <p>
On the Brinkley show, Tom McDermott shakily said he was grateful he had been "spared by God." He said he now looked at life from "a different perspective," though he'd spent four days asking himself what that perspective called for him to do. <p>
The show had opened with gory film clips of the aftermath of the LIRR shootings, and included others depicting child-killings in St. Louis and other tragedies that were part of a wave of holiday-season violence. <p>
The last part of the show featured Brooklyn congressman and gun-control advocate Charles Schumer and Wyoming senator Alan Simpson, a vocal opponent of restrictive gun legislation. Schumer argued that 20 years earlier Colin Ferguson might have gotten on the train and simply started ranting: "Now he gets a gun and he shoots." Schumer said that since the states had shown themselves unable to handle the escalation of gun violence, he had authored legislation that called for the federal government to intervene. Schumer declared that even New York City's tough gun-control laws were ineffectual, for recent research indicated that 98 percent of the weapons used for crime in the city were purchased out of state -- as was Colin Ferguson's gun.<p>
Simpson, ever affable of style, acknowledged voting against the relatively mild weapons restrictions included in the Brady bill. "I come from Wyoming," Simpson said with a slight smirk wedged into his long face, "a place where gun control is how steady you hold your rifle."<p>
The words catapulted Tom McDermott to his feet. He heard himself yelling at the television in rage.<p>
"What?" his wife kept saying. "What?"<p>
Tom raced to the phone to call the television studio in Washington, but the segment had been taped and Simpson had left. "Did you hear the sarcasm!" McDermott yelled. "Did you hear the complete disregard ... how steady you hold your rifle!"<p>
And from that moment Tom McDermott knew what he was supposed to do. He had been chosen to survive the tragedy to make sure that others wouldn't have to see what he had seen or die because of a gun. "I'm a radical now," McDermott would begin to tell people wherever he went. "I'm a radical for the safety of us all."<p>
The first word Kevin McCarthy spoke after his first operation was "Dad." When he began to speak in phrases, he said he remembered only the sound of one shot being fired. That and his father lying on his lap. <p>
"We can't handle this pain right now," Carolyn would say when they both began to cry. "So let's kind of push it away." <p>
Kevin's friends came to his room as his miraculous recovery progressed and would often talk to him, though he didn't respond. Doctors hailing from innumerable specialties came and went -- some 200 North Shore employees became involved in his case -- and at first Carolyn watched them carefully and as quietly as she could force herself to be. "Kev," she'd whispered when her son first woke up, "you're gonna hear doctors talking over you. Talking about what's wrong. Do not listen. Listen to no one." <p>
But over the next few weeks Carolyn came to trust, and then to admire, some of the medical specialists. She was particularly drawn to Nancy Epstein. Doctors and nurses who worked with the brilliant and notably impatient surgeon were used to seeing Epstein race through hallways and wards, refusing to physically or intellectually slow down for those not quick enough to handle the pace. Colleagues were surprised by Epstein's habit of stopping to spend time chatting with Carolyn McCarthy.<p>
"She's there every goddamned morning at 6 a.m.," Epstein would say later. "Every morning she's there making sure he goes through the range-of-motion exercises, or she's just sitting there with him around the clock. Carolyn McCarthy's one tough, no-bullshit babe."<p>
On the 12th day of the new year, 36 days after he was given the slimmest of chances to survive and three months earlier than his doctors had said he might be freed of wires and tubes and machines, Kevin was transferred from North Shore's big central facility in Manhasset to the hospital's physical medicine and rehabilitation wing in Glen Cove. A phalanx of photographers awaited the arrival of the ambulance, because nobody had yet gotten a picture of the high-profile massacre victim who'd defied the odds. Kevin was wearing a helmet, and metal dowels and hinges protruded from his reconstructed right hand. His left side was paralyzed, and his cognitive abilities appeared to be severely impaired. He had almost died on Christmas Eve, when a blood clot lodged in his lungs. A filtration system had been inserted inside his lower abdomen on Christmas Day to make sure the same thing didn't happen again.<p>
Nevertheless, Carolyn's days were buoyed by the most transitory display of the old Kevin peering back at her through his private fog. Every so often, her spirits would soar at a demonstration of Kevin's -- and Dennis's -- ironic sense of humor. Even in the ICU, Kevin would sometimes punch at his heart monitor to simulate heart arrhythmias and then smile when the nurses ran in. During one of the early, painful days in rehab, Kevin told Carolyn he didn't want to get better. He wanted to be disabled. After a pause long enough for his mother to appear horrified, he said, "Better parking."<p>
One day he opened his eyes and asked his mother to get back the suit he had been wearing on the train ... "and a refund for the ticket," Kevin managed.<p>
The refund arrived soon thereafter, along with silk flowers, since real plants weren't allowed in his room.<p>
Carolyn put the check in front of Kevin. "Now Dad's refund too," he said softly.<p>
At the Glen Cove rehab unit, Kevin began a rehabilitation regimen under the direction of Pat Corcoran, a specialist in physical medicine. But none of the "ADLs," as they call them in the world of rehab -- the activities of daily life -- came back easily. His memory would come and go, and his emotional state would change radically in an instant. After a few weeks, he began to try computer puzzles and other cognitive exercises to retrain his mind. Kevin's left hand wouldn't move at all, and he moved his reconstructed right hand with extreme difficulty and pain. The physical exercises often caused him so much pain that he would scream out loud.<p>
Nancy Epstein was worried about Kevin's lack of emotional affect, but then she also had to wonder if having women like her and Carolyn McCarthy hovering around, always telling him what to do, wasn't causing him to clam up. Carolyn had asked a psychologist named Mark Lerner to treat Kevin for the combination of profound grief, post-traumatic stress, and neurological damage he'd suffered, but Kevin soon told his mother that he didn't want to see the psychotherapist anymore. "There's nothing more to talk about," he said. <p>
One day during the very cold winter of 1994, Kevin was sitting at a table doing exercises when Pat Corcoran noticed tears in the big kid's eyes. Corcoran glanced up at the television suspended overhead and saw Colin Ferguson on the screen. <p>
He jumped up and reached to turn it off.
"No," Kevin said.<p>
In articulate, weirdly haughty phrases, the man who'd killed Kevin's father stood in court enumerating a long list of urological, orthopedic, and circulatory complaints. Ferguson also averred that in "the facility in which I am housed" he received "no sympathy."<p>
"Come on, Kev, I'm gonna turn it off,"  Corcoran said again.<p>
"No," Kevin said haltingly, the tears falling down his cheeks. "I want to see."<p>
On March 23, Ferguson addressed members of the local press corps at the Nassau County Jail. He wore leg irons and handcuffs, and his face was swollen and discolored from a recent beating at the hands of four fellow inmates.<p>
Ferguson said that upon being approached by four attackers wrapping strips of cloth around their knuckles, he had declared, "Let there be no violence." He added later if he ever became a wealthy man, he planned to "volunteer my services to those who are internationally subjected to poverty."<p>
It was now becoming clear that Colin Ferguson's own Caribbean boyhood was spent in anything but poverty. He had in fact grown up amid servants and cricket fields, a child of privilege in Kingston, Jamaica. He'd attended the best private schools, and he and his four brothers had cars and motorcycles while still in their teens. But his father, a senior executive with a large pharmaceutical firm, was killed in a car crash when Ferguson was 20. His mother died shortly thereafter, and everything about the family and its fortunes changed.<p>
Ferguson left Jamaica in 1982 and spent the following three years in Southern California. He held retail and low-level administrative jobs he considered well beneath his background and abilities. Fellow employees would later tell members of a reportorial team working for Newsday that Ferguson believed racism held him back.<p>
Ferguson moved to New York in 1985 and began his serial wars against institution after institution. He fell off a stool at work in 1989 and, despite a $26,000 settlement, spent years pursuing and repursuing a workman's compensation claim. He would hire lawyers to sue the state and the employers who had wronged him. Then he would hate the lawyers for betraying him in one way or another. He studied at two Long Island colleges and was invariably at odds with fellow students, administrators, and teachers. He said his professors wouldn't call on him in class. <p>
Ferguson was accused of harassing a woman on a New York City subway in 1992 and spent months thereafter placing phone calls to officials and seeking out lawyers who would pursue his claim that a "racist and vicious" motive had inspired the charge against him.<p>
Born so high and fallen so low and alone at the age of 35, Colin Ferguson was renting a little room in Brooklyn at the time of the shooting. He apparently chanted and talked about and to God long into the night. He had no job, money, or friends. But he did have the gun and the bullets he'd obtained legally during a trip to California.<p>
Radical trial lawyer William Kunstler said he was drawn to Ferguson's case because Ferguson was a pariah. Since garnering fame 
in the 1960s for his defense of civil-rights activists and antiwar protesters, Kunstler had defended more than a few pariahs -- among them a mob boss, a drug dealer accused of shooting six policemen, and a man accused of raping a young investment banker in Central Park.<p>
In March, Kunstler and his partner, Ronald Kuby, announced they would not only defend Ferguson but would pursue a groundbreaking defense predicated on the assertion that Colin Ferguson was an insane man who hailed from a nation all but devoid of the venomous racism he would find in America. Ferguson's experience of that racism, the lawyers planned to argue, had turned him from a madman into a mad killer. <p>
Kunstler said he waited for years for the chance to do "an education job" such as the one that presented itself with the Ferguson case. Kunstler didn't plan to touch the particulars of Ferguson's problems with the Workman's Compensation Board or Adelphi University; rather, he would call forth testimony from social scientists and social psychologists that would delineate the "strength and venom of American racism and the black rage that is its result."<p>
Ferguson's incarceration was costing the state more than $1,000 a day, and each day of trial would probably cost $3,000 more. Aside from his treatment after the jailhouse beating, Ferguson's other medical complaints led to doctors' visits every few days. He complained regularly about the quality of the reading material in jail, and he said he was positive that an assassin sent to get him by conspirators was just biding his time.<p>
It was one of the many jobs of a Nassau County homicide detective named Brian Parpan, a 20-year veteran of the force, to inform all the victims of the LIRR shooting about the existence of the New York State Crime Victims Board. Since the first government-sponsored victim-assistance system was constructed in California nearly 30 years ago, every state has established programs designed to compensate crime victims for uncovered insurance expenses, lost wages, and other out-of-pocket expenses. New York victims or their heirs are allowed to claim up to $2,000 for funeral expenses, up to $20,000 for lost wages, and unlimited medical expenses. But Carolyn McCarthy and most of the other LIRR victims found that the process of application and reapplication was overwhelming. The New York board fields some 30,000 applications from victims each year, and it labors under an immobilizing backlog. McCarthy gave up on the Crime Victims Board, though she did struggle for six hours with the paperwork from the Social Security Administration. <p>
Brian Parpan was also in charge of the ongoing investigation of the shootings and of organizing the victims and witnesses to appear before a grand jury. Few of the victims or eyewitnesses made it through a description of events before the grand jury without breaking down. As they spoke, Parpan could see various members of the jury crying too, and then cops and others in the room started to cry.<p>
By the time a 93-count indictment against Colin Ferguson was handed down in January, most of the people who'd witnessed the massacre had partaken of some form of therapy or psychological counseling. <p>
Tom McDermott spent time with one group composed entirely of men and women from the train who had not been shot. He was quickly struck by the seriousness of the psychic wounds suffered by those who were passed over. One young lawyer told of being chased up and down the aisle by Ferguson; with huge emotion he talked of the bullet holes he later found in his suit. During another meeting, all the men in the room realized that they shared guilt over the fact that as Ferguson came near, they had each thought exclusively about their children. "Not one of us thought about our wives," McDermott said later. "However unacceptable that may have seemed when we first said it, we realized that all of us thought about never being able to say goodbye to our children, to never have the chance to assure them that they would be all right."<p>
McDermott joined another group composed of people who had been shot. He would look around at the crutches and canes and wheelchairs and hear about all the metal plates and surgical pins that often seemed to be the only things holding some of the people in the group together, and he felt a mixture of wonder and rage. Hardly any of the victims had returned to work, and most of them faced subsequent surgical procedures. <p>
After a session with other victims, a young banker named Debra Weber, who was shot in the buttock and leg, was able to phone Joyce Gorycki. Joyce had been unable to consider going to therapy, because in truth she was still unable to consider accomplishing anything at all but waking up in the morning. When Weber haltingly began to speak on the phone, Joyce wondered if she'd been sitting close to her husband on the train. Maybe she'd seen it. For some reason this thought made Joyce feel a little better, and when she eventually met Weber at a gathering of victims in March, she felt better still.<p>
Carolyn McCarthy said she had no time for counseling sessions. Her life was dedicated to Kevin, her days ordered by the tiniest progressive indications that he was healing.<p>
Mark Lerner, the psychologist Carolyn had asked to treat Kevin, told her she had better start talking about things.<p>
"I know the facts," Carolyn said, staring at the shrink with her clear blue eyes. "And I'm talking all the time; I'm talking all day."<p>
"But you're putting things into little boxes to get by," Lerner said. <p>
"Can you change anything, Dr. Lerner?" Carolyn asked.<p>
Lerner shook his head.<p>
"There's my point," she said. "And those little boxes? That's the way I handle life."<p>
Late at night, Carolyn McCarthy would try to read some of the hundreds of letters that arrived each week. She could handle only a few, so her sister picked them out during the day. Every so often, the letters would help her cry.<p>
She had been able to cry at Dennis's funeral, held the day after Jim Gorycki's in the same church. She also cried with Kevin whenever they tried to talk about what happened. But one night during the winter Carolyn began to sob so powerfully that she wondered how she would ever stop. She would always remember that it was money she cried so hard about -- money and the way it insistently connected her to so much pain and anger and fear.<p>
But then worrying about money had always been Carolyn's task in the family. Every year she and Dennis reviewed their finances, and not long before he died, Carolyn had asked Dennis why he had so little life insurance and why he'd decided not to pay for double-indemnity protection. Dennis, in Carolyn's estimation, was a "spender." He thought nothing of getting a new pair of skis every year. He didn't think about saving money, because enjoying life was far more important. Kevin was the same way: He'd gone out and bought two $500 suits before starting his new job.<p>
Carolyn knew that medical-insurance contracts were filled with booby traps, so one night after Kevin was ensconced at the rehab hospital, she tried to spread out all the medical bills and letters from Dennis's employers at Prudential to see where she stood. She sat on the living room floor, surrounded by pictures of Dennis and Kevin and a sea of bills that covered the carpet.<p>
Carolyn crawled around trying to match up all the reference numbers to see what charges Pru-Care, the Prudential insurance wing, had received and covered. Nancy Epstein had recently become irritated with Prudential's handling of Kevin's case. At a party, Epstein had approached Burton Malkiel, a member of the Prudential board of directors (and the author of A Random Walk Down Wall Street), and said, "Your guys are sure blowing it with Kevin McCarthy."<p>
Kevin's nearly $200,000 worth of treatment through North Shore hospital had already exceeded by a substantial sum the McCarthy family's net worth. Dennis's funeral costs had run close to $9,000, $5,000 of which was covered by disbursements from a fund set up for victims by the Long Island Rail Road -- but it was unclear how much more money the fund would pay out.<p>
As she sat on the living room floor, Carolyn felt herself slipping underwater. The next thing she knew she was sobbing and she couldn't stop.<p>
Something about all those pieces of paper on her living room floor was impossible for Carolyn to fit into a box. As she sat weeping into the evening, the phone rang and Carolyn answered. A man identified himself as Joe Tierney and said, "I'm calling from the Prudential employee-benefits department, Mrs. McCarthy. If you have any problems from now on, just call and ask for me. If you have any bills or paperwork there, just pack it all up and send them to my attention."<p>
To Tierney's embarrassment, Carolyn would refer to him after that as her angel.<p>
"I knew someone told him to do it," she would say. "But something about the timing of it ... you know, like a call from heaven."<p>
Joe Tierney would join a long list of new connections, alongside doctors and cops and so many others. Kevin and Carolyn would from that point be dependent on Prudential, as they were on other organizations and institutions, as they attempted to steer a course back toward a semblance of what was home.<p>
During the spring, Tom McDermott appeared with William Kunstler, Harvard law professor Alan Dershowitz, and several others on Geraldo Rivera's cable talk show on CNBC. The show was one of dozens refocused on the Long Island Rail Road massacre by Kunstler's controversial "black rage" defense. McDermott was seated next to a convicted felon named Paul.<p>
After Kunstler and Dershowitz argued about the black-rage defense, McDermott commented that nobody who had survived the events of December 7 envisaged the shootings as anything but the "venture" of a lone gunman. "None of us saw it as a matter of black against white," McDermott said.<p>
When it was Paul's turn to speak, the convict said that he, for one, understood black rage. In fact, he continued, wagging his finger in McDermott's face, he could even understand getting a gun and dispensing rage -- he turned now to fully face McDermott -- "starting with this cracker right here."<p>
McDermott just stared back at the man.<p>
Since being reborn as a crusader, McDermott had spent the better part of every evening and weekend talking about guns. He attended meetings of activists, lobbied politicians, and tried to gently rally fellow victims to the cause. He now knew that more people died from gunshot wounds over two years in America than had died in all the years of the Vietnam War. He'd discovered that so few American soldiers are shot by guns nowadays that military medical personnel are sent to train at Jamaica Hospital, an institution not far from a Long Island Rail Road stop, because gunshot trauma is addressed there throughout the day. He knew that there were 70 million handguns in the United States and more gun dealerships than grocery stores.<p>
McDermott had established contact with most of the LIRR victims by now, and he asked each of them to get involved in efforts that might someday assure that such a thing would never happen again. Amy Federici's parents, Arlene and Jacob Locicero, were early conscripts, as was the young triathlete John Forni, who'd made an astounding recovery from his many bullet wounds to the chest, arm, face, and hand. Tom approached Joyce Gorycki at a candlelight vigil held in memory of Amy Federici, and Joyce said she wanted to help when she felt that she could. Tom had talked to Carolyn McCarthy about lending her voice to the cause in February, but she said her duties with Kevin sucked up all her time.<p>
During a January trip to Albany to urge the New York legislature to adopt a ban on assault weapons, McDermott and the Lociceros worked with Tina Johnstone of New Yorkers for Gun Control. Johnstone, a Staten Island mother of two whose husband, a New York editor, had been shot and killed a year earlier by a 16-year-old boy, had become an ever more tireless and articulate advocate. During the January trip, Johnstone's own state assemblyman told her he would not support a ban because people ought to own 9-millimeter guns for self-protection. Her state senator, Robert DiCarlo, had told her that most people who die from gun wounds are drug dealers anyway.<p>
Carolyn McCarthy phoned McDermott during the spring to say she was ready to take the plunge. She joined McDermott for a lobbying trip to Albany, where she immediately noticed that several legislators were unable to look her in the eye. She listened closely during a meeting with leading Republicans that included Ralph Marino, then the leader of the state's Republicans and a representative from Long Island. <p>
Marino said that he thought federal legislation should address the licensing and banning of guns. He had problems with certain items in a bill before the state senate, one that would ban 51 different assault weapons. For instance, he thought the limit on the legal size of bullet clips should be held at 15 and not reduced to 10.<p>
"The last five bullets in Colin Ferguson's second clip killed at least three people," Tom McDermott pointed out, his voice even and restrained.<p>
Marino began to speak of the importance of budget discussions and other items clogging the agenda. Someone asked Marino why the Republicans had demanded that the return of the death penalty be inserted into the bill. Everyone knew that Mario Cuomo, then New York's governor, would not sign a bill that reestablished the death penalty.<p>
Marino just smiled and in his soft voice said the two issues could not be separated.<p>
At this, Carolyn McCarthy, who was sitting directly across from Marino, leaned forward and stared hard in Marino's eyes. "That's not a good enough answer, Mr. Marino," she said loudly and deliberately. "Vote on the death penalty in the morning and the assault-weapon ban in the afternoon. Get me a scissors and I'll cut the bill in half for you, because I do not want to have to come up here ever again!"<p>
"Guess I kind of lost it there," Carolyn said to Tom on the way home. "A display of Irish temper, I guess. Now I see what we're up against."<p>
During the summer Kevin McCarthy would finally sense that the thick shroud that had enveloped his thoughts for so many months was beginning to peel away. Events slowly came into sharper focus. <p>
Carolyn was reminded too often of the many differences between the old Kevin and the son she helped dress, shower, and organize every day. But she forced herself to step back and consider how far they'd come.<p>
Two Garden City cops who'd entered the McCarthys' far-flung constellation of new friends, John Hoffman and Neal Sullivan, organized a fund-raiser for Kevin and other victims at the Garden City Hotel. When Kevin heard about their plans, he'd enunciated the unlikely goal of walking into the event.<p>
It was Hoffman and Sullivan who had waded back past other victims to pull Kevin out of the railroad car -- a young paramedic had told them she was sure she'd seen his hand move. Kevin had ballooned to 260 pounds before the shooting, so Hoffman and Sullivan had trouble lifting the stretcher. The two policemen kept checking in at the hospital to see how Kevin was doing. Carolyn had also gotten to know the deeply traumatized young paramedic who'd seen Kevin move his bloody hand, and she kept up with the the stunned ambulance driver who had driven Kevin to North Shore University Hospital and the crack neurosurgery team that, just by chance, was close at hand.<p>
When Carolyn realized that her old house had narrow doorways and other impediments to a wheelchair -- Kevin's probable means of getting around, it seemed at that point -- a mustachioed LIRR cop named Terry Culhane came over to measure doors and do carpentry work. Culhane was another who had boarded the third car early on December 7. When Carolyn told Culhane she couldn't face taking the train into the city to give her speeches and meet with politicians, he began to give her rides as often as he could.<p>
The special fund for victims established by the LIRR had swelled beyond all expectations. Contributions came from sources such as the Citibank VP who set up a stand in Penn Station two days after the shooting to collect money to help the victims. The New York Islanders hockey club donated over $70,000 to the fund, and Long Islandborn pop singer Mariah Carey, who had called the hospital to see if she could help Kevin, pitched in more than $200,000. The LIRR would eventually dispense more than $500,000 to the victims over the course of the year, and though several of the victims had already announced their intention to launch a variety of suits against the railroad -- and some felt that disbursements from the huge kitty arrived too slowly -- most privately acknowledged the LIRR and its employees had done pretty well.<p>
Carolyn's fears for her financial future were further allayed when Prudential pledged to match all contributions employees made in the name of her husband and son. Eventually $245,000 would be paid to a trust set up in Kevin's name -- a sum separate from the $320,000 Prudential's insurance wing would pay out for Kevin's medical care over the course of the year.<p>
Even veteran benefits workers had become intimate listeners. In July, Carolyn McCarthy was informed that the Social Security Administration had lost all the paperwork pursuant to her claims, so she made an appointment to go to the nearest office. She saw a sign that said that people with an appointment should proceed to Window 2, which was next to a line where 75 people waited. "Who do you think you are!" "Get in line!" people began to yell at her. One man came over and tried to push her to the back of the line. After the appointment, Social Security officials helped Carolyn leave through a side door. Months later she still referred to the incident as "the riot."<p>
Each victim of the LIRR shooting had horror stories about the loss of independence that marks the bureaucratic aftermath of victimization, but for the most part, long lists of systems renowned for a lack of sympathy had become humanized in the face of so much concentrated pain. "What Prudential did for us," Kevin McCarthy said, "was show that they can care about the little guy."<p>
"Well, of course they can," William Kunstler observed when told of Kevin's observation. "Of course! Those who control the nation's life mold laws and organizations in their own image. These institutions were designed to perpetuate the kinds of people who run the society."<p>
And yet none of the people riding the 5:33 served on corporate or hospital boards. The victims were more privileged than many Americans -- certainly more privileged than Colin Ferguson at low ebb -- and much less than others. Most of them were people who lived in unspectacular houses or apartments and went to work every day.<p>
Joyce Gorycki had become friends with some of Jim's fellow employees at Moore Business Forms whom even he had never met. From the middle ranks of the Chicago and San Mateo, California, offices of the company, people wrote her letters and called her on the phone. Around the time Joyce sat down and realized that it would be impossible to continue on her salary alone, Jim's boss had called to say that her husband's benefits were forthcoming, and that employees in the New York office had already established a support fund.<p>
Joyce talked regularly to her church pastor, Robert Mursch, who had quickly come to her aid when he heard what had happened on the train. She also consulted regularly with her daughter Karen's guidance counselors at school, but Joyce's brother kept insisting that she talk about the tragedy in a therapeutic setting. In June, Joyce finally felt ready to join a bereavement group.<p>
Carolyn McCarthy now realized that she was the only survivor or victim of the LIRR massacre who'd avoided some kind of counseling during the year. She said that one of these days she'd get around to it. "But I can't slow down now," she explained before leaving to give a speech in New York City one afternoon. "I've seen how others whose tragedies are less famous and farther in the past than mine have politicians' doors closed in their faces. Having Tom and me along has opened up certain doors that were closed. We only have so much time before all of this is just another crime."<p>
The Garden City Police event at the Garden City Hotel drew some 540 people. There had been other smaller and much less opulent events thrown by some of Kevin's friends in local bars, and there was a memorial road race run in memory of Dennis, with everyone wearing buttons bearing a picture of Dennis in a ski jacket, sunlight reflecting off the top of his head. But the Garden City gala drew politicians, business leaders, victims, and all sorts of friends.<p>
The huge crowd was already seated in the ballroom when Carolyn pushed Kevin's wheelchair to the doorway of the ballroom. Kevin had managed to take steps twice in therapy before the event, but he hadn't told his mother. So Carolyn stood back in surprise with the others as Kevin stood up and began to lurch into the ballroom, throwing his left leg out in front of him in a circular motion that required a great deal of balance. <p>
After a moment of hushed silence, someone in the crowd started to clap and everyone rose. Kevin turned bright red with embarrassment when the band struck up the theme song from Rocky, while Carolyn stood at the doorway and wept.<p>
In September, Colin Ferguson informed the judge overseeing his case, a thoughtful, round-faced man named Donald Belfi, that the state was plotting with his attorneys to blind him. After Ferguson refused to be examined by a retinal specialist -- which would have been his 59th visit by a medical professional -- he demanded to be seen by another retinal specialist, claiming that the conspiracy to render him sightless was designed to make him unable to identify the "Caucasian shooter" who had really been aboard the train on December 7. <p>
Ferguson refused, after a few visits, to see the psychiatrists his defense team had drafted and refused to cooperate with the psychiatrists hired by the prosecution. Ferguson had also decided to reject William Kunstler and Ron Kuby, in large part because of their supposed complicity in a plot to kill him. He also rejected the "black rage" insanity defense, because he was not in the least bit insane and was not the man who pulled the trigger. <p>
Kunstler and Kuby responded by asking the court to declare Ferguson psychologically incompetent and unfit to stand trial. <p>
On December 6, 1994, one day before the anniversary of the LIRR shootings, Ferguson shuffled into the dim and high-ceilinged courtroom in front of a class of unsettled-looking high school students who'd come to the trial to learn about the American legal system.<p>
Ferguson now wanted to be his own lawyer, which would mean that he would be able to put the people he'd shot on the stand and grill them personally. If those close to the victims imagined this as a process of further victimization, it was clear that to Ferguson the public display would be a chance to exercise his intellect and gifts of expression in ways previously proscribed by a racist system.<p>
Dressed in khaki trousers, a bright tie, and a white shirt made bulky by the bulletproof vest under his tweed jacket, Ferguson asked to sit along one wall of the courtroom so as not to be associated with Kunstler and Kuby, still his attorneys of record despite his desire to fire them. When he'd moved to a chair along one wall, Ferguson smiled at the leonine figure of Kunstler and said, "May the best man win."<p>
Kunstler walked away shaking his head.<p>
Ferguson rose to state that he considered the proceedings about his sanity a "kind of mock trial" that might preclude his later access to an untainted pool of jurors. Then he sat back down and listened, his eyebrows often raised in bemusement or irritation. His face had thinned over the course of the year in a way that highlighted the aristocratic nose he now held high in the air. <p>
A defense psychiatrist, Richard Dudley, testified that Ferguson suffered from an "encapsulated delusional disorder of a persecutory type." Dudley said that Ferguson irrationally believed people were out to destroy him. He therefore couldn't work with lawyers and couldn't defend himself.<p>
Ferguson rose to his feet. "I object," he said.<p>
Donald Belfi would eventually rule that Ferguson was competent to stand trial and therefore able, by right, to represent himself. As his own attorney, Ferguson said he would subpoena both Bill Clinton and Mario Cuomo. The court would allow the defendant to be served specially packaged food in response to his contention that enemies at the jail were trying to poison him, and the state would pay for a private investigator to hunt down the illusory gunman Ferguson claimed he saw on the train.<p>
Ferguson would appear often in court over the coming weeks, his demeanor at one moment lofty and then suddenly bewildered and weak. His eyes would look dead, then flare strangely bright. And nothing about his obvious madness appeared in the least poetic or instructive. Ferguson looked like nothing but what he had become, a living symbol of other people's fears.<p>
On the morning of the first anniversary of the shootings, Kevin and Carolyn McCarthy traveled to the Church of Holy Innocents in Manhattan, where a memorial mass for Dennis was scheduled. Though only Carolyn and Kevin knew it, the perennially irreverent Dennis McCarthy had stopped in daily at the church before going around the corner to his office.<p>
Carolyn held the arm of Kevin's black suit as he walked slowly to a forward pew near an altar dedicated to Dennis's memory. "I'm starting to fall apart," Carolyn had reported a day earlier. "I feel like I never had time to really mourn Dennis, and now I find myself going into my bedroom a lot to cry. I'm not used to this, and I'm really mad at myself. The other day the psychologist who said I survived by putting things in little boxes called and asked which box I'm in now. I told him I might be inside the last of them. I feel like I'm nearing some kind of end."<p>
Dozens of Dennis's friends and colleagues from Prudential sat together in one section of the big church. Carolyn inventoried the Prudential officials on the way in, and she noted the presence of a group of senior LIRR officials that included the president of the organization. <p>
A hymn was sung. Paul Keenan, a priest who had gotten to know Dennis during his regular visits, observed that Dennis McCarthy had leaned up against "the veil that separates this world from the Kingdom of God" and had gone over to the other side. Keenan noted that Dennis's widow seemed to harbor no malice or hatred for the man who killed her husband. "She was able to transform her hurt and anger into something else," he said. Kevin, who hadn't attended his father's funeral, sat bolt upright, blinking tears away from his eyes.<p>
Later that day would come a candlelight memorial at the Merillon Avenue station. Carolyn had recently referred to the station in the present tense, as the one "where Kevin and Dennis get off."<p>
Before the vigil, family and friends gathered in the kitchen of the McCarthy house. While Kevin's uncle, Tommy, buttoned Kevin's shirt and tied his necktie, some of the old friends -- skiing and drinking buddies who remembered Dennis from when he was a stick-thin kid known around the neighborhood as "Whitey" -- began to talk about Dennis McCarthy. "Well you know that the reason he liked to get up so early was so he'd have more time to bust everyone's balls before bed," declared Budd Salerno, Dennis's best friend, and everyone holding beers in the kitchen laughed.<p>
"I'm lucky because of these stories," Carolyn said, a smile below her sad eyes as she handed out candles. "For the rest of my life I'll be able to hear stories about my jolly Irishman. These stories give me strength."<p>
Below the train platform, hundreds of people drawn from the myriad circles of pain and support milled around in the damp evening waiting to meet the 5:33. A small stage had been constructed on a stretch of grass below the platform. Joyce Gorycki, looking very pale under the intense lights held by camera crews, stood near the stage holding up a large picture of Jim and a lighted candle. Two women nearby passed out flyers that offered free counseling at the high school when the memorial was over. High school students sat in circles on blankets, singing songs, and groups of nuns stood by chatting softly. Politicians moved through the crowd shaking hands, and cops eyed the growing crowd uneasily. Doctors like Pat Corcoran from Kevin's rehab days mingled with emergency-services workers who hadn't been back to the train station for a year. Carolyn McCarthy hugged the paramedic who'd discovered that Kevin was alive, and the woman told her that she was still in need of constant therapy because she just couldn't shake the effects of walking into the third car of the train. "But my therapist told me I had to come," she said. "So here I am."<p>
"If you look at the pictures," a young paramedic said to Tom McDermott, "I'm the one next to you wearing a stethoscope when they carried you out of the train. You squeezed my hand."<p>
Tom McDermott looked overwhelmed. "Thank you," he said. "I'm so glad you came ... to tell me. Thanks."<p>
Tom then moved back through the damp night in search of fellow victims. He knew that Lisa Combatti had a healthy baby girl named Kimberley Ann, and that Minoru Saito, the Japanese businessman shot in the leg during the rampage, was back at work, though his Japanese company had asked him not to become involved as an advocate. Frank Barker, the father of seven, could still not move his left thumb, but he was back at work and could hold his kids in his arms. Brendan Doyle, who still carried a bullet in his abdomen, had left Long Island that summer to join UN peacekeeping forces in Croatia. <p>
Carolyn McCarthy and Joyce Gorycki had worked the phones constantly for a week trying to get the victims who still lived in the area to come out for the vigil. The two widows talked often now. Jim used to tell Joyce about the McCarthys, the garrulous father and softspoken son who often rode with him in the third car. Joyce had recently told Carolyn that she planned to move to Phoenix after Colin Ferguson's trial. She and Jim had always planned to move there together.<p>
"It's like a reunion," Joyce said, surveying the large crowd at the vigil. Even the Kims, the devastated parents of Mi Kyung Kim, who died at 27 in the seat next to Jim Gorycki, stood huddled together in the wind, their candles protected by folded pieces of paper. Mrs. Kim sobbed beneath a big pair of sunglasses throughout the proceedings.<p>
Near the platform, Debra Weber hugged Helen Alexanderson and showed her that she was walking. Alexanderson, who had been married in January next to crutches trimmed with lace, said she was planning another ceremony so she could walk down the aisle. John Aspel, for whom a bullet in the belly had set off a long year of related traumas and personal setbacks, came up to Carolyn McCarthy. After he walked away, Carolyn said, "There's still so much horror in that poor man's eyes."<p>
Frank Barker stood beside his wife and children, shaking his head as he told another victim that while trimming the hedges he'd managed to cut off the end of a finger on the same hand shot on the train. He abruptly stopped talking when he heard a train whistle. "Here it comes," he said, staring up at the platform. "Here comes the train."<p>
The silver railway cars glided in alongside clouds of steam turned silver in reflection. "They've platformed it the wrong way again," Frank said, pointing to the two cars left short of the platform, as two cars were a year earlier at precisely the same time.<p>
The crowd remained very quiet until the train had disappeared. Joyce Gorycki stepped up to the stage and stood before a line of television cameras 50 feet long. "I'm positive that all the victims who didn't survive are looking down at us to see all of the people who've come," Joyce said. Then she began to thank the many people who'd helped her make it through the past year.<p>
Arlene Locicero, Amy Federici's mother, also thanked all the people hailing from corporations and government agencies who had responded to her daughter's death. "The children of this nation must be protected ... this violence must end," she managed before breaking down. Arlene turned to a young woman standing nearby. She drew the healthy-looking woman, who had received her daughter's heart in a transplant procedure, to her side. "This is Theresa Caravella," Arlene said. "She is Amy's heart."<p>
With Kevin towering above her a few inches away, Carolyn McCarthy looked out at the crowd. "Through the prayers and strength of family, friends, and the community, Kevin and I have survived," she said. "A year ago we all began a journey we did not want to take. For some, this day means closure, and I guess that's the way it should be. For others, this day is just the beginning."<p>
For several weeks during the winter of 1995, Colin Ferguson once again strolled back and forth in front of people he'd shot aboard the 5:33 to Hicksville. Drawing on a courtroom vocabulary he'd gleaned from the classic tome Fundamentals of Trial Technique and deploying stage movements and body language lawyers use only on TV, Ferguson argued that "Mr. Ferguson," as he referred to himself, had been sleeping innocently in the third car of the train when a stranger stole a gun he was transporting to "safe haven." After the smoke had cleared, Ferguson averred, the victims of the shooting had joined agencies of the state in an elaborate conspiracy to blame him and thereby destroy "yet another life."<p>
Ferguson questioned 15 eyewitnesses, all of whom refused to refer to him in the distant third person he preferred.<p>
"You shot me," Maryanne Phillips said to Ferguson, staring hard into his eyes.<p>
Tom McDermott took the stand and once again rolled the lurid tape of human slaughter he seemed doomed to forever carry inside his head. Many of the victims would soon join Tom in bringing a lawsuit designed to establish a legal chain of responsibility connecting murderers with the makers of the weapons and bullets that are their tools. In support of the suit and his constant lobbying efforts, McDermott could eloquently recall the horror of the train ride several times in a day. But up on the witness stand, with Colin Ferguson once again squared off at ten paces, McDermott seemed suddenly unnerved. He seemed to flail inside the nightmare in search of words. "The pushing," he said slowly, his voice weaker with each phrase. "The falling down ... no screams ... blood all over ... like a battlefield."<p>
Carolyn McCarthy and Joyce Gorycki sat in the audience, the two widows having decided that they would be in Colin Ferguson's sight whenever he turned around. Carolyn had been surprised at how shaken she was by the photographs of Dennis lying on the seat and the constant echoing of his name during the proceedings, and now the sight of Tom groping for expression moved her deeply.<p>
Ferguson eventually rose for cross-examination, and as soon as he began to speak -- "Mr. McDermott, is it your testimony..." -- McDermott's shoulders squared, and he again showed the mixture of dignity and profound sorrow that lent so much power to his words. "You were absorbed in details," Ferguson said, "...all these details, Mr. McDermott. It is your testimony that you could still identify the shooter?"<p>
"You walked past me," McDermott said, much louder than before. "You fired from your right to your left, from your right to your left, down into the seats." Because he was afraid Ferguson would come back, find him alive, and pump another bullet into him, McDermott said, he got up and went to the back of the train in search of the emergency brake. And still, McDermott continued, leaning toward Ferguson, "I was concerned that you would shoot me in the back."<p>
On the night of the 17th of February, 437 days after he'd shot his way into the middle of so many strangers' lives, Colin Ferguson was convicted of six murders and 19 attempted murders. As he was handcuffed and led from the courtroom, spectators began to clap and cheer.<p>
Outside the courtroom, the new extended family of victims gathered beside Tom McDermott, Carolyn McCarthy, and Joyce Gorycki as Tom told reporters that it was time to direct public focus away from Colin Ferguson and back to the safety of innocents. The others then came forward to take a turn addressing a public now aware of their plight more because of Ferguson's twisted legal performance than because of the pain he had caused. Most of the victims had decided that their tragedy and healing implied a certain responsibility to convey the truth of their ordeals -- or at least that part of the agony an outsider could begin to understand.<p>
"I know that there will always be aspects of those three minutes inside the devil's paradise that none of us will ever be able to express," Tom McDermott said. "There is a kind of chaos beyond anything that happens in a war, a vision of cruelty that can overwhelm the mind. And I know that I will never forget the words I heard myself say as the shooting and killing continued that night. 'This can't be,' I kept saying. 'This cannot be.' "<p>

