	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bombs Away</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Bombs Away</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Feature  <p> BOMBS AWAY <p>The bond salespeople worked in the Juice-O-Matic of the new economy. It was a machine with only two settings, hectic and burnout. A short story adapted from the upcoming novel Bombardiers.  <p> By Po Bronson  <p> The time had come. The bond salespeople double-timed out of their predawn mission briefing and marched down the aisles of the Atlantic Pacific Corporation to take their places in the bunkers. They were soldiers in their 20s and early 30s. Mercenaries. Professionals. Shock troops in the trenches of information warfare.  <p> They eyed the clock. It was two minutes to five in the morning, San Francisco time. They rehearsed the research department's sales pitches. Coyote Jack, their sales managerbosstyrant, paced back and forth in his fishbowl office, trying to look brutish and mean. It was his signal that there would be hell to pay for anything less than a 110 percent effort. Sidney Greeder refilled his coffee thermos. Sue Marino scanned the Post-It crib notes pasted down the side of her phone. Nickel Sansome set a tiny American flag and flagpole above his turret. Nelson Dickey turnedall seven framed pictures of his children toward Sansome's flagpole in mock allegiance. Eggs Igino reprogrammed his Quotron to constantly display the live prices of bond futures, gold futures, oil futures,and dollar futures down the left column of his screen. Lisa Lisaused the reflection of her face in the green monochrome monitors to lengthen her eyelashes, which she then batted in Eggs Igino's direction.  <p> They turned up the volume on their squawk boxes until the hoarse feedback made the worn-out speakers hiss and pop. They all gazed into the dark night clouds that rattled and bowed the enormous, wall-high window panes. Some of them jumped when the air-filtering vents overhead clicked on with a churning grumble. The heating element on the monster photocopier in the back room sucked ina rush of electricity that made the fluorescent bulbs above momentarily dim. Then the phone banks went red.  <p> "Incoming!" screamed Nickel Sansome.  <p> "Sell the Aussies!" screamed Eggs Igino.  <p> "More yield than Treasurys . . . !" screamed Nelson Dickey. <p> "It's patriotic!" screamed Sue Marino.  <p> "Of course we'll buy them back!" Sidney Greeder screamed.  <p> "Syndicate! Syndicate!" Lisa screamed.  <p> In a single day, the 37 salespeople in Atlantic Pacific's San Francisco office could move $1 billion in bonds, mostly new issues. Their customers were big pension funds, corporate treasurers,and state, county, and local governments. It was a filthy profession, but the money was addicting. The phone rang constantly, and everyone suffered cauliflower ears, neck rashes, and cervical pain, and when the sun came up and they had already been at their desks two, three hours, they went to the 41st floor window and imagined what it would be like to have to ride a bus or find a parking place. On days when the sun didn't come up and instead their tower was socked in by clouds and fog, the other world existed even less than usual; they could not see the streets below or most of the shorter buildings, and they were one of the few spaceships in the sky.   <p> Sidney Greeder's stomach soured and his back stiffened and he began to worry that he was going to develop an ear infection from all the germs that bred unrestrained in the receiver ofhis phone.  <p> "Do you see anything in there?" he asked Lisa Lisa, having unscrewed the receiver cap, exposing the resonator drum.  <p> "I don't see anything," she said, scrutinizing the cap. She poked the end of a paper clip through the holes in the hard plastic. <p> "I'm thinking of microwaving it," he said. "Kill 'em off." <p> "Would that do anything?"  <p> "It couldn't hurt."  <p> From his small outpost in the middle of the sales pit, Eggs Igino enjoyed the daily spectacle. He didn't see the harm of it. He didn't think there was any harm because the whole world was trending toward disorder anyway. He was an intellectual, and he knew how to maintain a certain scientific distance from his surroundings. His superiors were no more threatening than mitochondria in a petri dish; his colleagues, mice in a maze. <p> Igino had been selling bonds for Atlantic Pacific for less than a year, but he already had become the office's number-two producer. He was closing in fast on Sidney Greeder. Greeder, the reigning King of Mortgages, had been on the job for five years and had succeeded by learning to channel his anger into sales efforts.The King hated his customers, and he made them pay by selling them bonds. In contrast, Igino was a success because he had no anger--or fear--to channel in the first place. Selling was a game to him and he knew just how to play. Igino was quirky and jovial, a smart aleck with bad taste in ties. He had a freckled face and an athlete's casual slouch and globular, walnut-sized, muscular jowls that stirred as he spoke.  <p> Later that morning, Coyote Jack bolted upright when John White, managing director of the San Francisco office, buzzed the salesmanagerbosstyrant on the intercom. "He wants to see a what?" Coyote Jack shouted increduously.  <p> "A bond. Any kind of bond. Eggs says he can't sell bonds anymore if he's never seen one."  <p> "You want to what!?" Coyote Jack rasped, suddenly poking his head into John White's plush office, where Eggs was reclining leisurely on John White's sofa and John White was digging through his desk, dumping out the contents.  <p> "I want to see a bond," Eggs Igino remarked flatly. Coyote Jack's shoulders dropped.   <p> "What the heck for? J.W.--he's bullshitting us, right?"  <p> "I thought I had one in my desk somewhere here," John White mumbled as he dug into a drawer.  <p> Eggs looked down and picked under a fingernail on one hand with the other. "I've sold billions of dollars of bonds. I think it's time I got to know what I was selling."  <p> "You're selling them just fine without ever having seen one!" Coyote Jack blurted in frustration. Coyote Jack was a fat man with thin skin who wore garish watches and pointed shoes and starch-hardened shirt collars that caused a rash.   <p> John White sighed. "It's just a piece of paper with a bunch of colors and words printed on it. It's like a Publishers Clearinghouse Sweepstakes coupon."  <p> "I'd still like to see one. I would sleep better at night knowingI wasn't part of some big hoax. They're really just on the Fed's computer, aren't they? I'd like to know they really exist." <p> "We used to use the pieces of paper," John White said. "Hell, that was a long time ago. When you sold a bond, little old menon Wall Street would go pick it up, sign for it, and place it in a leather satchel. They would walk across the street and deliver it. We used to take lunches back then, walk out on the street. I saw a bunch of bonds once, when one of these little old men tripped on the curb and fell on the pavement and his leather satchel flew open, spilling millions of dollars into the gutter." <p> "This is stupid," Coyote Jack gasped. "It's idiotic. I ought to fire you, Igino. I ought to bust your ass right back down to vice salesman." This was far from an exaggerated threat; Coyote Jack had fired three salespeople in the past month alone, one simply because he had the gall to floss his teeth during one of Coyote's sales briefings.  <p> But Eggs Igino only laughed. He was the most promising young salesman in the firm. They would sooner shoot their foot off than fire him.  <p> "Why don't you just go over to the window at the Federal Reserve branch across the street and buy one," Eggs Igino suggested." Just get me a little $1,000 face-value T note. I just want to see one."  <p> Coyote Jack and John White stared at each other, realizing they had no choice. All the firm's money was handled out of New York, so Coyote Jack had to go to the downtown branch of his bank and withdraw a money order for $1,000, which he carried across the street to the Federal Reserve bank. He found the window, set down the money order, and asked for the current ten-year note. The teller requested his checking-account number so that the bond could be credited to his account. But Coyote Jack didn't want it credited; he wanted to walk out with it. The teller stared at him curiously. He told her he wanted to stuff it inside his mattress. She said that such a thing was no longer possible--the bank had to have an account to wire interest payments to. He asked for them to be mailed, by check. Such a thing was not anoption.   <p> Finally, Coyote Jack admitted that all he really needed was something that looked official, something that would serve as proof of ownership, even if it wasn't the bond itself. She gave him a receipt, stamped with the embossed seal of the Fed and a printed signature of Alan Greenspan. But it was no bigger than a credit card carbon, and it came in black ink on greenish paper. It could have been Monopoly money. For $1,000, he really though the was getting ripped off. Coyote Jack marched back to the sales floor and threw it down on Eggs Igino's desk with a show of resentment. <p> "What do you got there?" Sidney Greeder inquired.  <p> Eggs Igino removed the receipt from its brown envelope. "It's a bond," he said happily, though he was dissatisfied with its unassuming appearance.  <p> "No kidding. A real bond? Can I see it?"  <p> Eggs held the bond up to the light to see if it had some hologramon it or colored thread--something to be sure it was real. "Haven't you seen one before?" he asked Greeder.  <p> "Me? Naw. When would I have seen one?"  <p> "I just thought you've been selling them for almost five years, you might have seen one before." Eggs put it down on the desk and scratched at the black type with the point of a paper clip to see how it was printed.  <p> "Hey," Lisa Lisa saluted, crossing over behind Eggs. "What's everyone looking at?"  <p> Nickel Sansome rubbed his bald head and snickered. "Boy, Lisa Lisa--haven't you ever seen a bond before?"  <p> "That's a bond?" Lisa Lisa asked with chagrin. "It's not very impressive."  <p> "Well what did you expect?" Sidney scoffed. "A brick of gold?" <p> "I thought it would be bigger, at least," she answered, leaning over Eggs Igino's shoulder. "Can I feel it?"  <p> "Get your own," Sidney Greeder jeered.  <p> "I'll buy it from you," Lisa Lisa said. She looked at the Teleratescreen for the ten-year note, which was trading 98-2 bid. "I'll give you 2+ for it."  <p> "98-4," Nickel Sansome bid, in a plain, poker-faced grunt. <p> "It's Coyote Jack's," Eggs said. "I can't sell it to you. Besides, I wouldn't sell a real bond for less than 99. There's an authenticity factor you've got to add in."  <p> "I'll give you 99," Lisa Lisa put in. "It had better be real,though."  <p> "99-4," Nickel Sansome bid, standing behind her.  <p> "I could just go across the street and buy one," Lisa Lisa responded. <p> Eggs shrugged his shoulders.  <p> "99-8," Nickel proffered excitedly.  <p> "Done!" Eggs pronounced. "Sold to the man in the flesh-colored skullcap." His hands flew out to his calculator and tapped the keys, figuring the number of days between interest payments and how much was owed. "Make a check out to Coyote for $1,082.46," he said, handing over the piece of paper.  <p> Nickel Sansome beamed proudly, examining the snippet of paper carefully. He wrote the check out for Eggs, who took it into Coyote Jack's office and handed it over.  <p> "What's this?" Coyote Jack inquired, staring at the check. <p> "I made you a little profit," Eggs said.  <p> "How did you do that?"  <p> Eggs shrugged his shoulders. "I really just wanted to see a bond."  <p> "Sure you did," Coyote Jack said. "You know what you are? You're a damn genius, Igino. You could sell venom to a snake."  <p> "Yeah, right."  <p> "Hey, I'm paying you a compliment! You're the A-team, a regular Green Beret. You're the genius who sold Modesto County those Freddie Mac adjustables. <p> Eggs pulled a loose thread on the sleeve of his shirt. "They don't need money to buy a CMO when our repo desk is more than happy to loan them the money to buy it with. It's not that different from <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> loaning someone the money to buy a car." <p> Coyote Jack laughed with delight. "Heck, kid, we ought to have you out there talking to the press. You make it sound so simple." <p> "That's because it is simple," Eggs answered.  <p> "You wouldn't believe the flak this firm took after that Orange County fiasco."  <p> Eggs was nonchalant. "Yeah, well, there's a big difference between a principal-only strip and an adjustable-rate CMO, isn't there?" <p> Coyote Jack looked at the kid. He had a bright ruddy aura about him, a good-hearted glow that made Coyote Jack's stomach shoot with pain. Coyote Jack couldn't help but imagine what it would be like to have the most promising young salesman in the firm not show up for work one day. He knew why everyone else would show up for work tomorrow. For instance, Sidney Greeder was waiting to be fully vested in the pension. Nickel Sansome needed his money because being rich was what was expected of a man in his family. Lisa Lisa needed to prove she was as strong and smartas any man on the floor. They all needed their jobs, no matter how much they bitched and moaned. They all had their reasons, except Eggs Igino. He was too young to have suffered, and he was too innocent to be corrupted. Coyote Jack knew almost nothing about the kid, but corporate surveillance had dug up the fact that he didn't eat meat. It bothered Coyote Jack to no end that the future of the firm was a vegetarian. The only other story they could come up with was that when Eggs Igino was about to begin his all-Pac-Ten senior season for the Stanford Cardinal soccer team, the top goal scorer of the previous year met a woman named Katie, fell in love, and quit the team. A few years later,when something went wrong, the kid took off for Mexico. Coyote Jack understood the pattern: The kid had a soft heart, and he could quit again.  <p> So Coyote Jack had no choice but to invent a reason for the kid to keep coming to work. "Relax," he said to Eggs. "Hey, let me ask you something. I've been thinking. Can I ask you something?" <p> "I guess." Eggs looked away.  <p> "Don't get so defensive. I'm just talking. You used to live down in Mexico, right? You liked it there, spent your days on the beaches, climbed palm trees, etcetera. Am I right? You think about it, don't you? You look at all this stuff, all these buildings, and your mind starts wandering to the surf-and-sand landscape, right?"  <p> "Sure. What's your point?"  <p> "My point is, there's talk about a Honolulu office."  <p> "There is?"  <p> "Hawaii. You and me, kiddo. Luaus, volcanoes, Polynesian girls. There's a lot of mortgages coming out of Hawaii. Lot of money from Japan and Hong Kong."  <p> Coyote Jack reached into his desk and brought out an envelope, which he threw into Igino's lap. "Tickets to Hawaii. First class. They're open-ended--you can use 'em anytime. Go take a look-see, get acquainted with the island. I've got this saying, If you're going to go to hell, you might as well go to hell in Hawaii." <p> "Let Lisa Lisa use them. She covers the Hawaii accounts, and she needs a break more than me."  <p> "Lisa Lisa goes all the time. You keep them, use them when you like. Think about it, Igino. That's all I'm asking. Right now, we're just talking. We're studying the numbers."  <p> When Eggs Igino left his office, Coyote Jack began to wonder why he didn't just fire Lisa Lisa and give her accounts to Eggs Igino. If Eggs Igino had done well selling bonds to rural Modesto, he didn't see why he wouldn't do even better with those fast-growing counties in Hawaii. Eggs Igino had sold the GMACs and the Freddie Mac convertibles and the Aussie 8s of '03. And that was to the pension funds! There was no telling what he might do with a more aggressive account. So what if there was no new office in the works? Assigning him Hawaii would convince Eggs that there was.  <p>
The next attack could come from anywhere. The economic forecasts were useless. The fundamentals went ignored. The Federal Reserve was unpredictable. Money supply meant nothing in a global market. The Americans followed the lead of the Japanese, and the Japanese followed the Germans, and the Germans followed the Americans. They waited for instructions from the top, but the standing order remained the same: Sell bonds. Nobody knew where the market was going, but those who knew less than the others lost their shirts and had their eyes ripped out and were made to swallow. In the morning, there was always the chance to make it back.  <p> Two days later, after the market had closed, Coyote Jack called Lisa Lisa into his office. He sat her down in a chair and paced behind her back.  <p> "I tried to line them up," Lisa Lisa said, when Coyote Jack wondered why the State of Hawaii hadn't bought any of the Freddie Mac adjustables. Lisa Lisa squirmed. Her feet snaked around the leg posts of her chair. "But Coyote--they're a state! They need their cash for social services. They don't have money lying around to dump into Freddie Macs."  <p> "Having no money is not an excuse. Our repo desk will loan them all they need."  <p> Lisa Lisa turned her head around, but Coyote Jack circled out of her view. She turned the other way, he dodged back behindher.  <p> Lisa Lisa fell forward in her chair. "You're being ridiculous, Coyote. You want me to put Hawaii in the repo market after all that's happened in Southern California?"  <p> "Why the heck not!? There's still no sign of inflation. You saw the PPI this morning."  <p> "It's more complicated than that. . . ." Lisa Lisa groaned with exhaustion. "I've got principles. I've got a reputation with my accounts. We've got to build back our trust."  <p> "What's so complicated about it? General Motors loans drivers money to buy a car, don't they? Why not loan Hawaii a little dough to buy some Freddie Macs?" He walked up to his fishbowl window and stared out over the sales pits. "You think you're entitled to that seat on the mortgage desk? You aren't royalty. This ain't no monarchy."  <p> Lisa Lisa bit her lip. "The State of Hawaii was nothing before I picked it up."  <p> "That was three years ago. What about this year? You taking a vacation this year? You doing the bubble bath this week?" <p> "Blow off, Coyote."  <p> "Don't ever talk to me like that unless you mean it, girl." <p> Lisa Lisa stormed out. She ran to her desk, grabbed her purse, and ran into the bathroom. At times like this Lisa Lisa wished she were not alone in the world. For a woman in the workplace, the need for constant affirmation was often the most threatening addiction of all. Lisa Lisa's fundamental weakness was that she was strong. She could yell on the phone and drag herself out of bed at 4 a.m. and make men fantasize with her in mind. She could run four miles in 23 minutes and down a martini without wincing. Lisa Lisa had so many strengths that she was weak with desperation. She was the oldest of three brown-haired sisters,but she was the only one not yet married. Someday it would make sense why she'd become what she'd become, because she didn't come this way to be alone.  <p> When she came back from the bathroom, she snuck in the backdoor and went into the kitchen. Eggs Igino was making a new pot of coffee. Eggs Igino, with his great ease with the world.  <p> "What gives, Lisa Lisa?"  <p> Lisa Lisa leaned up against the counter beside him. "Do you know what it's like to be a woman in this business?"  <p> Eggs Igino turned around, and she was only inches away. She reached up to his neck and straightened out his tie.  <p> She answered her own question. "You're not supposed to be a woman. You're supposed to check it at the door."  <p> Eggs put his hand on her back. "You all right?" he asked.  <p> Lisa Lisa pursed her lips and nodded, looking away to control her emotion. They were quiet. "I hate this job," he said finally. <p> Lisa Lisa wiped at the tears in her streaked makeup. She took a deep breath. "You're lucky," she said.  <p> "Me? Why?"  <p> "Hating your job is a luxury. I need my job. This is my chosen career. I can only afford to dislike little parts of it."  <p> Eggs looked at her. "We're salespeople. We answer the phone and tell people what they want to hear."  <p> Lisa Lisa shook her head. "I'd like to think I am a step up from that."  <p> "Believe what you want."  <p> "You're becoming like Sidney Greeder. Hating your job is just a convenient way to avoid responsibility for selling so many dubious trades."  <p> Eggs felt insulted. Sid Greeder walked around hunched over like an old decrepit man, muttering to himself. "There's a big difference between me and Sid Greeder," Eggs blurted.  <p> Lisa Lisa replied, "Yeah, like about four years on the job." <p> Eggs didn't know what to say. People rarely spoke this openly with each other at the office. All the joking around didn't make any of them true friends.  <p> "Hey, Eggs, you know, I don't live far from here. Would you walk me home?"  <p>
 They were at her apartment on Telegraph Hill. Eggs didn't know what he was doing there. She sat him down at her kitchen table and asked if he wanted a glass of water. She told him most people don't get enough water. Water and sleep. So he said okay and took a glass of water. She asked if he used salt on his food,and he said no. So she got out a vial of iodine and put a dropin his water, saying most people don't get iodine now that they don't salt their food. Then she went into the bathroom to touchup her makeup.   <p> "Coyote Jack's been talking about a Hawaii office," Eggs said, trying to make conversation.  <p> "Is that right?" Lisa Lisa said, from the far-off place in her mind.  <p> "I can't tell if he's bullshitting me. He might just want me to have something to look forward to, something to stick around for."  <p> "I go to Hawaii twice a year," she said, softly. "It's nice." <p> "It's a tempting thought all right. Then again, he might just be messing with my head."  <p> "Eggs?"  <p> "What?"  <p> "Do you have a girlfriend?"  <p> "Uh, no."  <p> "You know a lot of guys, they treat their girlfriends like princesses. Men have thoughts--all sorts of thoughts, dirty thoughts, mean thoughts, thoughts they're ashamed of, really--but they can't bear to share those thoughts with their girlfriend. They tell themselves that they don't want to hurt their girlfriend, or wife, or whoever. They think they want to protect her. But that's not it. You know what it really is?"  <p> "What?"  <p> "They're afraid. They're afraid of their own thoughts."  <p> Eggs nodded slowly.  <p> Lisa Lisa went on. "I didn't think you were the kind of man who was afraid of his own thoughts."  <p> "What do you mean?" he asked, stalling, a little ashamed.  <p> Lisa Lisa stopped and turned toward him. She rolled her shoulders back and tossed her hair. "I mean, what are you thinking about right now? Are you really thinking about Hawaii?"   <p> Eggs just watched her. He didn't say anything. She caught his eyes and stared him down.   <p> "Are you just looking at me, Eggs, or are you looking at me?" She stepped forward, then looked down, then looked up again at him. "You know," she said, "sometimes I look at you and I think you are just way too young, you're just a baby. But then there's times I'm just overwhelmed, because you're a baby, but, well, you're a really, really beautiful baby." Lisa Lisa kissed him on the lips very briefly, so that he would be left wanting more. His lips were big and soft and she had to kiss him a couple times, actually, to cover all of his lips. She kept kissing them.  <p> "What's going on?" Eggs asked, stopping.  <p> "Nothing," Lisa Lisa said, looking away. "Please, don't stop." <p> "This isn't right," Eggs said. He sat up and stared at her and saw her again as the Lisa Lisa he worked with. "I gotta go," he said anxiously, heading for the door quickly. "I'll see you tomorrow, okay?" The door shut.  <p> Lisa Lisa went into the bathroom. She looked at herself in the mirror.    <p> "Such a child," she said aloud, and tried not to think about it.  <p>
At 4 a.m., Lisa Lisa dragged herself out of bed and forced herself into her clothes. She walked the cold downtown streets to work,sheltering herself against the breeze that swirled at the corners. The streets were peaceful, almost sympathetic, and for a moment knowing that she was alone in the world felt liberating rather than sad. On the way into the building, the security guards told her she looked awfully nice, and she smiled. She rode up the elevator and strolled out onto the sales floor. She went into the kitchen, poured herself a cup of coffee, grabbed a plate of scrambled eggs and hash browns from the caterer's breakfast cart, picked up a copy of the Wall Street Journal, and moseyed to her desk as she glanced over the front page. She looked out the window where the sun shone orange against the other towers. Light banter came over the squawk box, and she began to takedown opening numbers and construct the story of overnight trading. She removed the wrapper from her breakfast and took a bite of hash browns. Slowly, the others straggled into the office.  <p> Lisa Lisa tried to concentrate on her work. She tried to push Eggs out of her mind. She watched as Coyote Jack came out of his office with a huge, proud smirk on his face. He walked directly to her desk. She thought he was going to apologize for the day before.  <p>
Eggs Igino was just walking across the esplanade as Lisa Lisa came bursting out of the building and onto the street, looking hysterical, angry, and blown to pieces. She threw her bag of belongings at him.  <p> "You little snot-nosed bastard!" She swung at him and missed. <p> "What the hell?" Eggs jumped back.   <p> "You knew all about this!" she cried. "Oh, you jerk, you knew all along that you were going to get my accounts. I wouldn't let you use me like that, I wanted to make you pay with your heart, and you were afraid, you're such a little boy, you're so scared . . ."  <p> "What are you talking about?" Eggs stammered. "Did you get fired?" <p> "Don't play dumb, you jerk. Of course I got fired. All that stuff about the Hawaii office, you knew damn well. Right, now you'll ask me who's going to get my accounts! I just can't believe you. I can't. Get away from me!"  <p> Eggs tried to grab her arm, but she swung at him again and ran off, clutching at her elbows.  <p> Eggs stood there for a long time, sorting through what she had said, putting it together. He thought about where he'd come from, and where he was headed, and he didn't know--had never known--what he was in it for. It was something he'd had to try, something he had to prove to himself, but once he was in it they kept setting up more and more challenges for him to prove himself against. He looked up at the building, to where it disappeared in the clouds above.   <p> "GET BACK TO WORK!" Coyote Jack screamed, looking through his internal window at where Nickel Sansome was slothfully padding about in his bunker. "You lousy paste-for-brains cockroach! Do you feel like being next?!" Coyote Jack slammed the phone backdown and paced his room in circles, pushing aside his furniture. Then he stopped at the window again and stared out at Eggs Igino's desk. He was dying to tell Igino that he would pick up the Hawaii accounts. The only trouble was that at that very moment, Coyote had no idea where Eggs Igino was.  <p> It was not like Eggs to be late coming to work. Not like him at all.  <p>
Eggs Igino reclined in his seat and rolled his head to the side, smelling the leather of the headrest. Out the small window the sun was just coming up, and they were the only bird in the sky. His head was throbbing. When the stewardess spoke to him, he jumped up in surprise, then asked for a tomato juice. He put his book down in his lap. There would be plenty of time to read on the beach when he got there. Lodged above the tray table beforehim was a GTE Airfone. He popped it free with a credit card but didn't make the call.   <p> Thinking back on the last few days, he pulled a paper napkin out of the seat pocket and began to write on it with one of his corporate pens in light blue ink:  <p> 1. Knowledge is Power!  <p> 2. Knowledge is not a Candy Bar!  <p> When you eat a candy bar, Eggs thought, the candy bar is gone. And if you give it to a friend, then he gets to eat it and you don't. Knowledge can't get used up, and you can't get rid of it by giving it away. Then again:  <p> 2b. Word Travels Fast.  <p> The power of knowledge was fleeting and temporary. We would all be powerless. Then he wrote below the other lines in large,energetic, slashing letters:  <p> 3. Power is Temporary!!!  <p> This was the third law of information economics. Lisa Lisa was living proof of that--and so was he. Eggs could call Coyote Jack when he got there. Maybe. Maybe he would wait a few days, give him a scare. Eggs Igino chuckled at the thought of Coyote Jack staring out over the sales floor, wondering where he'd gone. The tickets were open-ended, after all. Eggs didn't know when he intended to go back. Maybe he would take up surfing, ride the Blue Monster at Molokai. He set the phone back into the headrest. His eyes closed. He thought of the ocean, the power of the wave. <p>

