	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Americans and Their Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						It's not how much you make, but what you make of it. A groundbreaking survey of America's inner financial life.<p>(For June's cover story, Worth and Roper/Starch Worldwide conducted a groundbreaking survey to probe the America financial psyche.  Then we used the results to identify seven distinct money personalities.)<p>By Robert Sullivan<p>Your money or your life? Not a simple question, since most people can't seem to differentiate the two. Just read the dollar signs. Forty percent of Americans think about money more often than sex. Fights over money are the number-one source of marital discord (just slightly ahead of arguments about what television show to watch). Fifty-six percent of us say there comes a point in every marriage when money becomes more important than sex. Twenty-eight percent of the country rates making the wrong choice on a major investment decision as stressful -- more than are anxious about speaking in public or enduring a root canal. <p>Last fall, Worth and Roper/Starch Worldwide, one of the country's largest market-research firms, mounted the first extensive probe into the dark recesses of the great American money brain. We sent a battalion of pollsters door-to-door across the country. Knocking on some 2,000 doors, they asked each of our respondents 83 detailed questions about their personal financial lives: We wanted to know how Americans make, spend, squabble over, and think about money. The resulting report, entitled "The Personality Factor: A Worth/Roper Survey of America's Inner Financial Life," is a groundbreaking exploration of the murky interplay between our emotions and our wallets. <p>Why do some people control money effortlessly while others are controlled by it? Thirteen percent of Americans seem psychologically coded to accumulate money. About a quarter of the populace has a very difficult relationship with the dollar. The vast middle manages its money carefully -- though often overcautiously. Using a number-crunching technique known as segmentation analysis -- and some very powerful computers -- Roper's statisticians identified seven distinct money personalities: hunters, gatherers, protectors, strivers, nesters, splurgers, and idealists. One of these profiles describes the money personality of almost every American.<p>If the '80s focused on acquisition, the '90s are about holding on. This is a decade of anxious conservatism. Fully one third of the country describes itself as extremely unwilling to take any financial risk. When asked to name two or three qualities they associate with money, only a quarter of Americans identified freedom, pleasure, or achievement. Rather, in the current American mind-set, money represents security and comfort. <p>Americans don't mind saying they need money, but they're uncomfortable saying they want it. Although they feel the dollar's strong psychological pull, they're not quite sure where it's pulling them. For instance, half the population says it believes that money can't buy happiness. And yet nearly 70 percent of Americans maintain that doubling their earnings would make them a lot or somewhat happier. <p>What's more, financial comfort doesn't necessarily buy emotional ease. "There's absolutely no relationship between the amount of money one has," says Dr. Allan Scholom, a clinical psychologist in Chicago, "and the amount one worries about it." In short, it's not how much you make but what you make of it. Higher-income Americans are only slightly less likely to tie happiness to income. Sixty-seven percent of those earning more than $50,000 a year believe that higher salaries would make them happier. <p>Given this basic contradiction in how we set the emotional value of a dollar, it's not surprising that as money opens fears, it closes mouths. Among eight touchy subjects we brought up, money was the one Americans said they feel least comfortable discussing, well ahead of religion or politics, topics once considered taboo. While 58 percent say their spouse knows how much they make, just 15 percent say their best friend knows their income. "The two most difficult subjects for my clients to discuss are sexuality and money," says Laura Wimbish, an adjunct professor of clinical psychology at Northwestern University Medical School in Chicago. "While the sense of shame over sexuality is dissipating, the shame surrounding the topic of money is still there."<p>Why is money such a loaded subject? Because the way we see money gets to the root of how we see ourselves. Money equals character: When asked what feature they would most like to change about themselves, our respondents most frequently mentioned the amount of money they had. Money equals image: In general, Americans would rather be richer than thinner, smarter, taller, more patient, or better looking. Money equals control: Free spending is seen as a sign of weakness. Even as Americans want fatter bank accounts, they don't necessarily want to live more extravagantly. Sixty-five percent say they agree with the phrase "I most enjoy buying practical and sensible things." Only 20 percent say they "most enjoy buying things that are luxuries." <p>What's more, the time-honored work ethic still prevails, even in these modern times: 59 percent view hard work as the best way to get ahead. Only 34 percent cite intelligence as a crucial ingredient to success. Guts, street smarts, ruthlessness -- the values associated with the '80s -- lag far behind. <p>One might conclude that if we are averse to spending freely and still see ourselves as hardworking, we might also be more careful with money than ever. But relatively few Americans feel confident about handling their personal finances. (In fact, just 19 percent were able to correctly identify the Dow Jones Industrial Average as the combined prices of the stocks of 30 major companies on a given day.) It's as if people want to keep money at arm's length. Fifty-one percent of the country manages its money by merely dumping it in a savings or checking account. Only 5 percent of the country holds five or more different investments.<p>"(It) gives me some kind of content to remember how painful it is sometimes to keep money, as well as to get it," wrote Samuel Pepys, the 17th-century English diarist. "This morning came home my fine camlet cloak, with gold buttons, and a silk suit.... I pray God to make me able to pay for it." Today, on the cusp of the 21st century, our sentiments have scarcely strayed. The following profiles unlock the secrets behind the pain and the pleasure, the give and the get, that are inherently intertwined in the constant, conflicted greening of America.
---------------
Robert Sullivan has written for a number of national magazines, including Rolling Stone, Outside, The New Yorker and Vogue.<p>
THE PROFILES<p>
THE HUNTER<p>Percent of population: 13<p>Profile: Takes risk to get ahead<p>Patron saint: Bill Gates<p>Hunters, with a mean income of $44,000, earn more than any of the other money types. They are characterized by an aggressive attitude toward making, spending, and investing money, optimizing their financial resources every chance they get. Hunters describe themselves as "a bit extravagant." They unabashedly desire money, equating it with happiness, freedom, achievement, and power. And most of them have no reservations about talking about how much they have.<p>Hunters are by no means alone in placing such a high emotional value on the dollar, but they are distinguished by a general ability to make money; two thirds of them feel comfortable choosing investments, compared with barely half the public at large. More than any of the other money personalities, hunters believe that intelligence and guts are the keys to financial success. <p>True to their aggressive natures, hunters tend to have comparatively unsettled personal lives. After the strivers, they are the second most likely to be divorced. Those hunters who are married say they tend to win arguments over money but lose most others. Hunters are most likely to say their spouse calls the shots when they argue about disciplining the children. They are also most likely to be unable to resolve fights over their romantic or sex lives.<p>Take Jerald C., a 28-year-old who lives outside Denver, where he is an accountant for his family's manufacturing company. When it comes to money, he is confident about his abilities. "I'm definitely competent," he says. He doesn't understand why anyone wouldn't invest his or her money. "I can make more that way," he says. "I can't see letting it just sit in a bank in a savings account." Jerald reads the business section of the Denver Post thoroughly and faithfully, diligently investigating any potential investment possibilities. He is comfortable with risk, being of the belief that even a loss can be a gain when it comes to his long-term financial future. "Basically," he says, "it makes you a little wiser." When Jerald thinks about the future, he worries about things that he feels he can't control, such as his health, but he says he never spends a lot of time worrying about money. <p>Randy W. is an antiques dealer in his mid-30s who lives in Southern California. He and his wife run the kind of ragtag operation that borders on being a junk shop, but they often act as if they were trading pork-belly futures in the commodities pit at the Chicago Board of Trade. Just recently, Randy spotted a valuable collection of comic books and impulsively paid $3,500 for them.<p>"I know they're valued at over $11,000," Randy says. "I mean, who in their right mind wouldn't buy 'em? There's some things that are just obvious. When you can pay a nickel for something and then turn around and sell it for a dime, you should just buy it. You should double it or triple it. And if you can't sell it triple, then come down a little bit."<p>And then comes a little wrinkle of guilt. Like many hunters, Randy thinks of himself as extravagant, a feeling that might be a result of overzealousness in some members of this segment. He says, "I feel like I blow a little more than I should."<p><p>THE GATHERER<p>Percent of population: 19<p>Profile: Better safe than sorry<p>Patron saint: Warren Buffett <p>Primarily middle-aged, and with a mean income of $35,000 (just $1,000 more than the public at large), the gatherers make up the largest segment of the population. As investors, they tend to be conservative, and they subscribe to traditional values: Women shouldn't pay on dates. Friends shouldn't borrow from friends. While the gatherers are more likely than any of the other six segments of the population to have three or more investments, they also believe it is inappropriate to desire money too intensely. In fact, it is just this attitude toward money that makes the gatherers seem selfish. Forty percent describe themselves as "miserly but wise." Fully 100 percent are looking out for themselves when it comes to money.<p>Though gatherers are often tight with their hard-earned money, they are very comfortable with their ability to manage it. They know how money works, how to use it, and how not to use it, and they use it as they please. When 47-year-old Pamela S. speaks about money, she does so with a matter-of-factness that makes her sound like a bank president about to retire from a long and blissfully uneventful career. "I have no worries about money," she says. She does not live a lifestyle of either the rich or the famous, yet she and her husband, a physician in suburban Rochester, New York, consider themselves well-off. "I know I can afford to buy the things that I want," Pamela says. It's easy for her to feel this way; she is completely debtless. "We've paid off our house," she says. "We have no loans and only two credit cards, and we pay those at the end of every month. My husband and I are probably more traditional than most people in that we pay cash for everything." <p>Gatherers represent the mainstream of the American financial psyche. Modest, slightly puritanical, theirs are the values of Main Street, U.S.A. Of all the money personalities, they feel the most comfortable buying a new car, financing a house, or filing an insurance claim. But computers make them nervous. Fifty-one percent say they are uncertain about how to use one. <p>When it comes to money, gatherers are the voice of reason, archetypal of the anxiously conservative American investor. Thirty percent own stocks or bonds, as opposed to 23 percent of the rest of the country, but they are hardly gamblers. For them, money is security. They think of themselves as competent in financial matters, disciplined with spending; 73 percent of them agree that "with money it is more important to plan for the future than to enjoy what I have now." Eighty-three percent of gatherers -- more than any other money personality -- claim to be satisfied with the size of their paycheck.<p>But risk averse often translates into overcautious. Ninety-six percent of this group believes that it is better to be safe than sorry when it comes to making financial decisions. The gatherer tends to equate money with a sense of self, a sense of security. "A lot of people," says Northwestern University adjunct professor Laura Wimbish, "feel they've got to hold on tightly to their money for fear they'll never be able reproduce it if it all disappears."<p><p>THE PROTECTOR<p>Percent of population: 16<p>Profile: Puts others first<p>Patron saint: Paul Newman<p>After the hunters and the gatherers, the protectors are the most financially savvy group in the U.S. But protectors don't feel tied to money the way the first two groups do; they are much more likely to be concerned with other people. Money is simply a means of shielding others -- spouses, children, parents, or friends. <p>Seventy-five percent of protectors say that it is right to think of other people before yourself in financial matters. To them, money does not represent power or freedom but security. Protectors are predominantly women. They tend to be college educated. Of all the groups, they are the most likely to be married and least prone to divorce. Protectors are twice as likely to have worked for a political party as any of the other money personalities, suggesting a general sense of civic-mindedness. They are also among the most well-off of any of the segments. At $36,000, their mean income is second only to hunters'.<p>Around the house, the protectors tend to be pliable. Though they call the shots when it comes to housekeeping, they concede to their spouses many decisions about shared activities: what TV show to watch, where to go on vacation, which friends to spend time with, and even when to have sex. <p>Protectors don't gamble with their money. Michelle S., a 20-year-old secretary who lives with her husband and their children in a small town in Ohio, has half her money in stocks, half in a savings account. "We kind of play it safe and a little risky," she says. Like most protectors, she sees money as a means to buy security for her family. When she shops, she buys what she needs and what her children want. "It means a lot more to me to see the smile on my daughter's face than to have something of my own," she says. Any variation in her shopping pattern makes her feel guilty. "If I buy for myself, I think, 'Gosh, I shouldn't have bought that. I could have bought two things for my daughter.'" <p>Since protectors are not emotionally tied to their money, they do not equate financial success with self-worth. They are among the least likely to see work as anything more than a means to make money. "It wouldn't be such a big deal if anything happened with either of our jobs," Michelle says. Nor do protectors see financial failure as a source of embarrassment. Of all the groups, they are the least likely to be upset if they find out they've paid too much for something. <p><p>THE SPLURGER<p>Percent of population: 14<p>Profile: Travels first class or not at all<p>Patron saint: Elizabeth Taylor<p>Splurgers are the most self-indulgent of the seven money personalities. They have the fourth-highest mean income -- $33,000 -- and they are the second youngest of the segments; their mean age is 40. They are three times as likely as the overall public to say that they'd rather buy a luxury item -- whether or not they can afford it -- than a practical one. Though their chief monetary goal is financial independence, they are nonetheless risk averse, confining most of their investments to CDs and savings accounts. Second only to the hunters, 65 percent of the splurgers expect to be a lot or somewhat better off five years from now. <p>The splurger, in fact, most resembles the hunter -- but without the financial acumen. Splurgers don't consider the accumulation of money as an end in itself. Money is simply a means -- a means to consumption. Splurgers tend to be self-centered and somewhat impractical. They are the most likely to believe that similar economic backgrounds are a key ingredient to a successful marriage and most likely to disagree with the phrase "It's more blessed to give than to receive." Perhaps that explains why splurgers are the most likely to lose domestic arguments about whether to spend or save money. <p>Two thirds of this group say they are apt to buy really nice things regardless of how much they need them, in comparison to 36 percent of the general public. Splurgers consider themselves indulgent rather than practical, and they are almost twice as likely as the general public to agree with the statement "I try to go first class most of the time in dinners, traveling, clothing, cars." They are also almost twice as likely to agree with the statement "I am more impressed by someone who appreciates quality and buys only the very best." <p>Take Diane W., a 38-year-old who lives in a suburb of Denver. To her, having more money primarily means being able to take more vacations. It means taking time off from her work at a local printing plant and from her housework and taking a long trip with her husband and children. Waterskiing in Hawaii sounds nice to her at the moment, but in the past she's been to places all over the country. "I just want to get out of the grind, out of the school-homework routine," she says. "I want to get to actually enjoy something, something out of the ordinary." Diane feels she has a tendency to spend a little more than she should or than she actually has -- as a rule, she travels first class, for example -- but in matters of travel, she doesn't see any way around this. She'd rather not go than go economy. She's beginning to think about reeling in some of her shopping habits, especially since she doesn't always stick to necessities. "I usually spend money the way I want," she says, "whether I need something or not." <p>Chris F., an office clerk, has three children and her share of credit card bills. Nevertheless, when she sees a dress she has to have, well, she has to have it. "Some people will buy just clothing, for example,'' she says. "They'll go buy a remake of something. And I would rather have the something."<p><p>THE STRIVER<p>Percent of population: 13<p>Profile: Controlled by money<p>Patron saint: Tonya Harding<p>More than any of the other segments, the striver is controlled by money. Ninety-two percent say that money makes the world go round. They have the lowest mean income of any of the groups, $29,000, but even if a striver has money, it's doubtful that he or she will have a very healthy relationship with it. Eighty-five percent of strivers say they would feel "just terrible" losing money in the stock market. (By contrast, only 33 percent of the hunters, who accept risk as integral to financial success, are greatly upset by losing money on an investment.)<p>Strivers are twice as likely as the average American to think of money as power and, in turn, happiness. Almost 90 percent believe that one can never have too much money. Seventy-four percent will never be happy making only an average amount of money. And yet only 12 percent of the strivers consider themselves well informed on financial matters. While 51 percent of Americans describe themselves as basically competent with investments, only 33 percent of strivers feel the same way. The chances that a striver attended college are relatively low, and the lack of education puts strivers at a disadvantage. Fifty-eight percent do not know how to use a computer; 51 percent are at a loss when it comes to knowing how to finance a house.<p>At home, strivers tend to be domineering. Of all the groups, they are most likely to win fights over how the house is kept. They dictate the family's social life, and they tend to get their way in disagreements over their sexual and romantic lives. At the same time, they are the segment most likely to agree that sex takes a back seat to money at some point in a marriage. To a striver, all important household issues come down to money and who controls it: A striver thinks that the spouse who brings in the most money should call the shots. Needless to say, strivers are the most likely to be divorced. Those who are single tend to think that if they were better off, their romantic lives would go more smoothly.<p>Strivers are jealous of people who have money. Three quarters of them agree that "wealth makes people more attractive than they would be otherwise," as opposed to 15 percent of the general public. They tend to attribute financial success to luck or connections.<p>"Some rich people don't know they have money," says Louis A., a retired printer in Philadelphia. "They want to push their money around and expect better treatment, and I don't have a lot of time for that."<p>Nonetheless, strivers marvel at the success of others, even while they rail against those with money. Joann S. lives in Detroit, where she is an accountant for a small company. She works hard, coming home late every day -- she barely has enough time to take care of her daughter -- but the payoff she expects from all her labor never seems to come. In fact, everything seems to work against her. "People who have the wealth don't deserve it, and I think they are foolish with it," she says. She thinks the only reason she isn't richer is that she doesn't have the right connections. "I'm not political enough," she says. "I don't have any friends with any power."<p>Like the splurgers, the strivers are not savers. Says Elizabeth P., a 42-year-old grocery clerk in Pennsylvania, "I was born poor, and when I go out of this world, I'm going to die poor. I'm not one of these people who works their ass off and puts money in the bank so their kids can fight over it. I'm going to enjoy it myself while I'm alive."<p><p>THE NESTER<p>Percent of Population: 14<p>Profile: Needs just enough to take care of self<p>Patron Saint: Roseanne Conner<p>Of all the money personalities, the nesters -- mean income $31,000 -- are the least engaged with their financial lives. They aren't tied up emotionally with their money, nor are they very savvy with it. Their concerns mostly begin and end with themselves and their families. Like the protectors, nesters have pragmatic financial values, but where protectors primarily view money as security, this group translates financial well-being into comfort, simply because they seem to worry less about security. They think in terms of fulfilling their immediate needs. Nesters may not want much, but what they have, they see as theirs. Only 9 percent of nesters see money as something to leave for their heirs. Eighty-three percent of nesters believe that one has to look out for oneself when it comes to money. Only 60 percent of the general population shares that view.<p>"I don't want to sound greedy," says Kathie P., a 38-year-old secretary and mother of two in a small town outside of Pasadena, California. "I just want enough to get by." When she pushes herself to think extravagantly, she thinks of maybe being able to take a trip somewhere and not once having to worry about how much money she is spending. She doesn't think extravagantly often, though. "I don't want anything outrageous," Kathie says. She couldn't really care less about investments or finances much beyond the bills and her checkbook. "I just kind of go with the flow," she says. Despite this attitude of financial laissez-faire, Kathie believes that the only person who can help her make it through her happily modest existence is herself. "Nobody else is going to do it for you," she says.<p>Nesters are the least likely to make getting ahead a top priority, the least likely to agree with the statement "How much money I have says a lot about who I am," and the least likely to agree that a person can never be too rich. Two thirds of them are dissatisfied with their salary, but this discontentment is not driven by ambition. Just the opposite, in fact. Nesters are the segment most likely to quit work altogether were they to hit it big in the lottery. They are apt to have life insurance, but only 11 percent have three or more investments, the lowest of any of the money personalities. And money is not something they want to talk about. They are slightly less likely than the average American to be comfortable discussing their financial situation. The nester just wants to be left alone: 74 percent of nesters say that how they spend their money is nobody's business but their own.<p>"Money doesn't matter to me," says Dora G., a 28-year-old waitress who lives in Colorado. "It doesn't even matter when it comes to relationships. It doesn't matter to me if someone I'm dating has little money."<p>"It takes money to get along, but the Lord has blessed me with enough to get along," says Emma H., 82, who lives in a farming community in Texas. "I'm just happy to be comfortable. I feel like I wouldn't spend no more than I had to." She has lived her entire life in this fashion, and, like many nesters, she doesn't have much, but what she has is hers. "We don't like to have a lot of debt," she says. "We try to stay away from that as much as we can."<p><p>THE IDEALIST<p>Percent of population: 10<p>Profile: There's more to life than money<p>Patron saint: Allen Ginsberg<p>True to their name, idealists are the least materialistic of the money personalities. Accordingly, they have the second-lowest mean incomes: $30,000, and they'd be just as happy to make do with less. Money means nothing more than security. It is certainly not something to be trusted or relied upon -- 78 percent of idealists believe that money is the root of all evil. Eighty percent believe that "money means nothing without someone you love to share it with." Idealists most closely resemble nesters, but they are more generous. Nester tend to limit their modest involvement with money to looking out for themselves; idealists simply limit their involvement with money.<p>Consequently, idealists do not live by many hard and fast money rules. They don't link cash and happiness; they are the least likely to agree with the statement "The better my financial life, the better my romantic life." They tend not to think that a successful marriage depends on similar economic backgrounds, that the spouse who brings in the most money should have more power, or that there comes a point in every marriage when money becomes more important than sex.<p>When it comes to making or losing money, idealists are not emotionally involved.  Eighty-four percent report that they'd only be "a little upset" if they lost a lot of money in the stock market. Then again, idealists aren't very likely to put a lot of money into the stock market; only 7 percent own stocks, compared to 14 percent of the population at large. They aren't much more at home in, say, the local Ford dealership. Thirty-three percent of the idealists are uncertain or at a loss when buying a car.<p>"Material things aren't a big thing to me," says Barbara T., 29. "But I guess money is important. I mean, we have kids, and they need food, they need clothes." She is reluctant to acknowledge what she feels is the essential truth about money. "I hate to say it," she says. "But money makes the world go round." If she has money after paying the bills, she thinks of herself as fairly generous. She doesn't always have the money to give, she says. "but when we do -- well, I don't want to sound corny, but I think it's important to give back what the world gives to you." She is impressed with people who have a significant amount of money and yet are practical rather than indulgent with it. Ultimately, she believes that wealth means nothing. "You could have a million bucks, but if you don't have anybody to share it with, it's no fun."<p>When an idealist makes an investment, it's generally a modest one. Only 24 percent have two or more investments. They are the most likely money personality to hold term life insurance policies. Sixty percent have regular savings accounts -- the highest percentage of any of the personality groups. Forty-eight percent have checking accounts -- tying them with the nesters for the lowest percentage.<p>But in the end, idealists stand apart from the rest of the country in large part because of their almost complete indifference to the dollar. Forty-five percent of idealists say that a doubling of their family's income would not make them any happier -- a higher percentage than any other segment. "As long as we're good and healthy -- that's all that matters to me," says Marie F., a housewife and mother of three in rural Tennessee. If she won a million dollars, she doesn't think it would change her life at all. "I'd put it all back for the kids' education," she says. J.B., a 69-year-old retired engineer who lives in Georgia, concurs: "Money's a necessity," he says. "That's basically all that I look at it as. I don't feel like it gives a person any amount of power."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

