	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-What Happened to the January Effect?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Small caps could underperform for an entire year<p>Nobody knows precisely why the January effect exists, but every year, almost without fail, small-capitalization stocks rally from mid-December until late January, leaving their bigger brethren in the dust. In only 6 of the last 68 years have small-cap stocks failed to outperform large-cap stocks in that period, notes Claudia Mott, small-cap analyst for Prudential Securities.<p>Well, make that 7 out of 69.<p>It's not that small-company stocks did badly in January; it's just that they were supposed to do better. The major small-cap indexes, the Russell 2000 and the Wilshire Small Cap, turned in gains of 3.1 percent and 3.0 percent respectively in January. The S&P 500 returned 3.4 percent and the Dow 6.2 percent<p>Small-cap stocks didn't beat the Dow last year (see chart), but they did outperform the S&P, which badly lagged both the 30 Industrials and the Russell. But the absence of a strong January effect bodes ill for the sector in 1994. In five of the previous six years without a strong January effect, Mott points out, small caps lagged the S&P. In 1989, the last time a year opened without a January effect, small caps returned 8.1 percent, a far cry from the more than 25 percent returned by the S&P that year. Mott isn't willing to say this marks the end of the small-cap rally without seeing a further rise in valuations and a decay of fundamentals. In fact, she's projecting extremely strong first-quarter profits for her sector. Still, history would make anyone cautious.      <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

