<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-On The Brink</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-On The Brink</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Sociologist Barry Glassner focuses on midlife career changes as a defining event for many baby boomers<p>By Suzanne Costas<p>Psychologists and psychiatrists have long claimed that the midlife crisis is about death anxiety or facing mortality. Sociologist Barry Glassner argues that, to a greater extent than previous generations, today's 35- and 40-year-olds are acting out this issue in their careers. For baby boomers, the fear of extinction takes the form of worrying about spending their remaining years in unfulfilling jobs. Many are panicking and turning their work lives upside down.<p>For his just-published book Career Crash (Simon & Schuster), Glassner talked to 400 highly successful, college-educated people who had suddenly lost or left their jobs. Glassner is chair of the sociology department at the University of Southern California in Los Angeles. He was interviewed by Suzanne Costas, a senior writer at Worth.<p>
Q: What was the most startling discovery you made in the course of your research?<p>A: A couple of things surprised me. First, that career crashes are a predictable crisis in baby boomers' lives. Among people who luck out, who don't have career crashes themselves, few don't experience a crash secondhand, through a spouse. Second, I found that people don't go in any single direction when they crash. Before I started the research, I assumed there would be certain professions that everyone was moving out of and certain ones everybody was moving into. But for every lawyer who goes back to school to become a teacher, I found a teacher who was becoming a lawyer. A third big surprise was the preponderance of voluntary career crashes. More career crashes occur because people get to a point where they're miserable with what they're doing. They don't want to spend the next 40 years of their lives that way. The previous generation's professionals had pretty predictable career patterns. For baby boomers, that's not the case. A fourth surprise was that job leavers are often more unhappy, in the short run, than job losers. The person who loses a job expects to be miserable, but a person who has said, "Okay, now I'm going after my dream," is more prone to disappointment.<p>
Q: Why did you choose to examine the career crashes of baby boomers?<p>A: Actually, I wanted study why so many baby boomers are depressed the rate is about four times higher than for people who are over 65. When I started interviewing people, it came leaping out that what they were upset about was their work lives. Again and again they talked about how dissatisfied and depressed they were about this. I'm not suggesting that that's what causes these high rates of depression but rather that a source of widespread disenchantment and psychological pain is displeasure and discomfort with a career.<p>
Q: Are these people blaming their jobs for problems that a career change alone couldn't possibly solve?<p>A: I spent quite a while investigating that possibility. But that's not what was going on, usually. Their family lives and relationships were reasonably happy. But many thought if they really put their talents to the right use, they'd get out of the work world what they thought all their lives they were going to get out of it. For some that meant a lot of money. For others it was doing good or doing something creative. The entrepreneurs' stories were the most moving. They'd worked things out in great detail, and then they failed. Not only did they not make a lot of money, they went bankrupt. The good news is that most people I interviewed were better off after the career crash not right away, maybe, but before very long.<p>
Q: Some readers may think these people going through a career crisis are basically whiners and spoiled brats.<p>A: That's the most negative thing I've heard so far, and I've heard it from employers especially. They say, "If you can't take the heat, get out of the kitchen," or "A job isn't supposed to be fun." My response: This generation was promised fulfillment. They were promised by their parents and the media that their lives would be a constant learning experience, ever more progressive and rewarding. And the fact is that most work situations  most careers, these days  don't offer that. They don't even offer career advancement.<p>
Q: Your book is fundamentally similar to Gail Sheehy's 1976 best-seller, Passages. What does your work contribute that's new?<p>A: Using her term, I would say the career crash is a major passage, in many cases the major passage in midlife for this generation. The midlife crisis back then was characterized by concern about trying to be young again. For a lot of men, it meant leaving their wives for younger women. For many women, it meant coping with the so-called empty nest when the last of the children left home. But the baby boomers have now shifted the focus.<p>
Q: Is it possible that the career change you're talking about is just the chosen vehicle for this generation to go through a midlife crisis and is otherwise fundamentally no different?. <p>A: A generation gets to midlife, or any other stage in life, at a particular time in history. When the previous generation got there, the sexual revolution was going on, the whole touchy-feely, human-potential movement was going on, interest rates were going through the ceiling. Well, what's going on in the world as the baby boomers reach midlife? The work world is collapsing. There's a downsizing revolution. Corporate ladders are shrinking; the rungs above have disappeared. The main social changes and upheavals that are going on when you reach midlife have a lot to do with what your midlife crisis is about.<p>
Q: Some might suggest that the real challenge is to recognize that life is hard and that not all work situations will be perfect.<p>A: A very important step is to abandon what I call the 
three-S measure of success status, success, and security. That's what we're really talking about here. People think if they just get the right status, the right level of security, the right salary or income, their work lives will be wonderful. But then they have a conflict with someone at work, or the job gets boring again. So the real task during a career crash is to discover what is really important to you in life, to set things up in the next career or to focus on getting things that really make a difference. Some, for instance, figured out that what really matters is being able to use a talent they had neglected "I'm really good working with people, and I have a job where I never work with anybody."<p>But there are price tags. Often the price is lower income, which means a reduced lifestyle. Or it means relocating. And that cuts both ways. I interviewed a fair number of people who realized only during a career crash that they hated where they lived and knew there were places where they'd be happier. That's key. It's not about deciding you're going to go up in the hills and live off the land that usually doesn't work. Rather they may move where they can afford a bigger house or not have to commute. They plan their next career move based on things like that which, of course, you're not supposed to do in America. Career moves are based on making more money and having a more prestigious title.<p>
Q: So those who engaged in self-examination benefited most from their career crisis.<p>A: Yes. They focused on what really matters to them and what they have to offer, and then they put those two things together. It's like making an investment. If you do it well, do it wisely, you come out ahead.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
