		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Rags to Riches to Rap</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
A century ago, Horatio Alger assured America's youth that virtue could be rewarded with riches. The myth survives in today's pop culture, but it's not a pretty story. <p>By Richard Todd<p>"There are some boys, as well as men, who cannot stand prosperity." <p>--The World Before Him, 
by Horatio Alger<p><p>When Snoop Doggy Dogg, the militant rap star, was indicted on murder charges a week before his new record, Doggystyle, crested the charts ... when, during the same week, another rapper, Tupac Shakur, was arrested on charges of forcibly sodomizing a woman in a New York hotel room (three weeks after he had been arrested for allegedly shooting two Atlanta cops)--when these two incidents occurred late last fall, it seemed as if culturally we had crossed a dangerous line. The distinction between art and life had collapsed utterly; more to the point, "art" seemed to be inspiring death.<p>You could shrug this off; you could say, "Well, what's so surprising? Rap is to music as murder is to interpersonal relations." But, no, that isn't what most people felt. The (alleged) crimes were shocking. And here is why: These young men had made millions of dollars singing about street life, often advocating violence--but why did they have to go and do it? In a cover story (featuring an attitude-laden photograph of Mr. Dogg), Newsweek expressed the perplexity perfectly, in terms that were all the more meaningful for their banality: "These performers should be classic American success stories: young men of humble origins who through sheer talent and hard work rose to the mansions on the hill."<p>A thorough deconstruction of that sentence would take us deep into American mythology, into our confusion about money and success, and before long it would lead to one figure: the 19th-century writer Horatio Alger Jr. No one reads Alger anymore, but everyone remembers him as a symbol of the American Dream, the rags-to-riches story. His titles alone evoke this stirring notion: Do and Dare, Dan the Newsboy, Fame and Fortune, Frank and Fearless, Tattered Tom, Sink or Swim, Paul the Peddler, Rupert's Ambitions. Alger's--like Snoop Doggy Dogg's or Tupac Shakur's--subject matter was provided by the young men of the street. In a loopy way, not entirely cheerful to contemplate if you believe in progress, Horatio Alger was the Snoop Doggy Dogg of the 19th century. <p>All popular culture is best understood by the lie that it tells, and Horatio Alger is no exception. His lie, though, is more interesting than the one he is generally accused of. We usually take Alger as an apologist for naked capitalism and a staunch believer in the most private of enterprise, the lonely individual succeeding by dint of hard work. We still speak of a spectacular self-made success as a "real Horatio Alger story." Each spring an enterprising businessman receives the Horatio Alger Award at a lavish ceremony in Washington, D.C. For years social historians have rather sniffishly used Alger's once-popular books for boys as an emblem of the worship of success that has supposedly plagued our culture. <p>Poor Alger! He deserves better. Maybe not a whole lot better, because no one would accuse him of being a neglected genius. His work, which has gotten thoughtful attention from only a handful of literary scholars, is not art, and yet it suggests much about our culture--particularly our attitudes toward business and money.<p>The bare-bones plot is almost always the same: A young hero, in straitened economic circumstances, is cheated and mistreated by a corrupt world yet survives without losing his virtue. Material award awaits him, though often it is modest, such as a clerk's job in a countinghouse with brighter prospects ahead. The reward, moreover, tends to occur in the last few pages of the book and to be treated perfunctorily in a happily-ever-after sort of way. Struggling is more than half the fun. The important achievement of the hero is the maintenance of his principles. The novels are all intensely moral stories.<p>The attractive lie for Alger's 19th-century readers--youths and parents alike--seems to have been a sentimental affirmation of the integrity of character in a mean and tawdry world. This message arrived with a particular power because it spoke to the anxiety of the time (an anxiety that has perhaps not entirely vanished from our life).<p>So steeped in the culture of business are we, our thoughts organized in bottom-line language, that we forget how recent a thing the dominance of commerce is in our national life. But 19th-century Americans reeled under the burgeoning of business. Imagine yourself as a small-town American in 1850. Local lads left town with packs on their backs and ended up in the disreputable city; shifty-eyed drummers showed up selling snake oil--was this what was going to happen to our little boy? A historian named Karen Halttunen has chronicled these fears in an excellent little book called Confidence Men and Painted Women, which points out that the 19th century saw the wholesale rise of doubt and distrust in ordinary social relations as we became a rootless and ambitious society. <p>At bottom it was a psychological unease, a fear that the very nature of the self was undergoing some horrible change. If you stayed at home in your little town, you worried that the old virtues had been replaced by a new one called success, and that it was going to elude you. If you ventured forth in search of success, you worried about what you would have to do to achieve it. Who exactly would be the person who would arrive at the end of that perilous journey? Would you have to change utterly to accomplish what you wanted? Was it necessary to participate in the world of artifice and deceit in order to survive?<p>Along came Alger with the deeply comforting answer: No, you could have it both ways. It's not simply that you could "make it"; you could make it without being unmade. Virtue would be rewarded by Providence. But one should be clear that it was indeed Providence and not the "system" that cares for us. Alger, in fact, harbored dark views about the world that was emerging around him, about its materialism and greed, its encouragement of corruption. As one of his more recent and insightful critics, biographer Gary Scharnhorst, has pointed out, "Alger profoundly distrusted any behavior that was motivated by the desire to accumulate money."<p>Alger had a reassuring puritan conception of character--like grace, the important virtues seemed to be inborn. He came by his puritanism honestly, a New Englander with some 15 Mayflower ancestors, son of a minister. The family was poor but never unaware of its distinguished lineage. <p>Alger was a slight youth, short in stature, and--like an Alger character--when he entered Harvard, he was set upon in the Yard by a group of tough sophomores and thrashed. He survived and prospered academically and later called his Harvard years the happiest of his life. He went to divinity school, left without finishing, and toured Europe. (This seems to have been the occasion, according to one biographer, of his first heterosexual love affair, with a French tart, a traumatic enough event to discourage him from further efforts in this genre until late in his life.) He lived for several years in Cambridge, teaching, preaching, and writing fiction and verse. He accepted a job as minister to a church in Brewster, on Cape Cod, a move that proved disastrous yet decisive in the course of his life. He was soon driven away for (according to church records) "the abominable and revolting crime of gross familiarity with boys" (italics in the original). He fled to New York and ever afterward tried to conceal the Brewster episode, his short-lived career in the ministry, and whatever his homoerotic inclinations may have been. Effeminate lads turn up in his novels, and their mannerisms provide a sure sign of their moral decay. Heroes have manly gazes and clear brows, and their financial reward is often accompanied by prospects of a suitable marriage.<p>New York seems to have been good for Alger (as it has been for so many other writers greater and lesser). His own financial needs made him turn to a form at which he knew he could make some money, children's books, and the city seems to have turned him outward, made him into an observer. He became particularly interested in the plight of the urchin class and (one might speculate) sublimated his pederasty into advocacy for the lot of impoverished boys. He wrote his first successful series of books about a character named Ragged Dick for the explicit purpose of exciting sympathy for homeless children, and as he prospered, he became a prominent benefactor of the lodging houses that tried to ease their pain. <p>Two pleasing opposites animated Alger's novels: his moral homilies on the one hand, and on the other, his gritty descriptions of the perils of life in the city. For a modern reader, the pleasure of the books (and there is some) lies chiefly in his rendering of countinghouses and boarding houses, of the myriad lowlife charlatans waiting to strip a boy of his few pennies, as well as the heartily upright and honest poor (like the lovable Mrs. O'Keefe with her apple stand in Adrift in New York) who might be turned to for help. I expect that Alger's young readers may have found their joy in these books similarly: cozily experiencing the titillating horrors of urban life. It may be that for every youth who was persuaded to try his luck in the city, another ten imagined themselves getting hustled by a con man and decided to stay on the farm.<p>Alger's popularity had peaked by the 1880s, and by the end of his career he was writing with greater difficulty and less reward. His work had sustained him but not made him rich. By his estimate his lifetime sales amounted to 800,000 copies. In 1898 he went home to Massachusetts to stay with an aged relative and to die. Strangely, though, his greatest commercial success lay ahead, with a posthumous boom in interest in his fiction during the early years of the 20th century. A country that had by then been through two traumatic panics and felt its looming involvement in the dark turmoil of Europe may have been nostalgic for the simpler days of 19th-century capitalism. It seems to have been during this time, when his books were selling a million copies annually, that Alger's reputation began its ossification into the cliche of the success story. Readers stopped listening to the sermons and cut to the chase.<p><p>Reading alger now, one is struck by a paradox: Though the books are hopelessly antiquated, the dialogue stiff and laughable, the references entertainingly obscure, the essential theme is not dead. We still wonder what is necessary for success and fear the price in loss of self may be unacceptable. An apprehension about money still affects our lives and makes itself felt in the ambivalence--the mixture of veneration and suspicion--that we display toward the very successful. But it is not uncommon for literature to wear itself out on themes that are not themselves exhausted.<p>Certainly we cannot imagine our children being interested in books like the Alger books --our children are much more sophisticated, their ears bred to tune out anything that sounds remotely like Alger's starched pulpit sounds. Yet reading these books makes one reflect on the culture that children do absorb and what it is telling them about the "real world." To find an equivalent in popularity of the Alger books today, one has to turn to other media, to movies, CDs, television, and video games, and to their two essential ingredients, sport and violence. What is the message that lies therein? What now is the lie that we are telling to the children?<p>Gangsta rap, Mighty Morphin Power Rangers, Beavis and Butt-Head--these are not self-evidently identical phenomena, but if you take just a step back, they do indeed share something. They promise instant identity through power. It's as if our society had projected its fears of impotence and anonymity onto children and provided them with the illusion of an answer: Zap, slam dunk, blow him away. The wisdom of Snoop Doggy Dogg confers a moral blessing on such nihilism and stands the Alger story on its head: No matter what you achieve, you will always be a victim. If the 19th century feared loss of self, the late 20th seems to fear it hasn't a self to lose.<p>We lament, for good reasons, the way violence permeates popular culture. One doesn't have to be an alarmist to think that bloodshed in the movies is dangerously romanticized, that children have no idea what real violence is like until they try it, which movies tempt them to do, that many rudderless kids may be guided into crime by what is given them for entertainment. But one can feel sad about this for a more basic and mundane reason: It is so unrealistic--not about the nature of violence, but about the way the world really works. <p>Violence (and sports) offers very little in the way of career opportunity. Not many openings at all in the world for gunmen, drug lords, or slayers of Super Mario, or even, alas, for point guards. It is a striking feature of children's culture today that the world they will inhabit, a world of jobs and corporations, of getting by or getting rich, scarcely makes an appearance. The absence is true not only of the mass culture of the screen but of the more sophisticated literature for children that has blossomed in recent years. It tends to be inward and psychological and not show children--or adults for that matter--in contact with organizations. I asked a children's-book editor about this recently, and she said that business didn't appear in children's books these days: "The businessman may be that dumb guy from Wall Street Mom is dating while Dad finds himself as a carpenter in Vermont." I spoke to a prep-school headmaster a while ago who said that one of the most troubling things about his students was that many had no idea what their parents did for a living. Some of the parents did it rather well, too, but didn't think their kids would be interested. Another editor was trying to put together an anthology of literature about work for teenagers (some 40 percent of whom have worked by the age of 17). "The only problem," she said, "is that there is no such literature."<p><p>No more rags to riches! now it's just do it. It seems a shame, because the nascent world of the 19th century has come true: We are a business culture, one that still values, even insists on, some 19th-century virtues. And most kids will take their place in it--not as dramatically as Ragged Dick or Tattered Tom, but nonetheless it will be their lives. Too bad we don't have a new Horatio Alger Jr. to tell them what the world they're actually going to live in is like. <p>Richard Todd is a contributing editor at Worth.
 <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
