	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-A Farmer's Battle</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						When the great flood of '93 left Mike Pieper's farm under 16 feet of water, he undertook an extraordinary effort to clean it up himself.  At least it was a problem he could solve.<p>By Donovan Webster<p>Mike pieper is sitting in the stern of his green steel skiff, looking out across some of the prettiest farmland in southeast Iowa. It's mid-August; eight-foot cornstalks should be gleaming in the late-summer sun. But this year there's only water, muddy Mississippi River water as deep as 16 feet in some places. The great flood of 1993 has covered nearly everything in sight. Beyond the silent brown lake that covers the 3,200-acre Pieper farm, Crayola-green bluffs rise on the east and west horizons. The knoll on which the farm's 17 buildings sit pokes up through the floodwaters, but even on that higher ground a half-dozen barns and sheds are still submerged to their rooflines by water that has changed Mike Pieper's life forever.<p>Pieper dials the outboard's throttle back, and silence fills the air. The boat coasts past a trio of corrugated-steel silos, and Pieper, a sinewy bantam rooster of a man in blue jeans and a navy work shirt, speaks for the first time in half an hour. "Haven't been out here in six weeks," he says. "Haven't set foot in my own home in a month and a half. Unbelievable." <p>Finally--with the boat pushing a last, low wake across the water--the hull grinds against the dry, raised soil of the farm site. Behind him, the water is awash with sodden green cornstalks. The day is sunny and humid. Clouds of houseflies pulse beneath a pale blue sky. <p>"Okay," Pieper says. "Let's see what's left of the farm."<p>Pieper goes ashore, plunging his heavy boots into the saturated, yogurtlike mud. He's looking for a clear path to the farmhouse, 200 yards away. This is his first trip back to the farm since the Mississippi River levee, three miles distant, split in two spots on July 11, just outside the small farming community of Wever, Iowa. Since then, he and his wife and four children have been living in a cramped rental house a dozen miles away. He has spent endless days with federal and state bureaucrats and recently learned that the government and the Army Corps of Engineers will offer him virtually no help for months. (They'll focus on his troubles, they say, when the floodwaters recede and they've had time to assess the damage--sometime in early 1994.) <p>Yet, right now, Pieper's got some 15 billion gallons of water covering the five and a half square miles of his farm, with no way to dry it out. Like most farmers who reside near levees, he carries no flood insurance. "Living this close to a river, our annual premiums can run to near 20 percent of a farm's value," he says, "so we'd be rebuying this place every five years. Nope, better to gut out a bad year every few decades." Pieper thinks the flood will cost the farm $1.5 million. "It'll hurt us," he says, "but we'll swing it."<p>Buried in slop to his ankles, Pieper peers around one of the three quarter-mile-long buildings that housed his family's hogs and steps through the back door. Inside, the floors and stock pens are slick with four inches of sludge. The air is thick with buzzing flies and the stench of rot. He plods on, grabbing the gunky top rails of hog pens when he needs balance. Ahead of him, near the center of the building, a puffed, drowned dog has been pinned beneath the rail of a stock pen. Finally, after much scrambling and slipping, Pieper makes his way out the building's front door and back into sunshine. <p>Beneath his feet, the earth is alive with countless thousands of frogs. He walks across the farm's parking area and reaches his farmhouse. Though this is Pieper's first trip back, a pair of carpenters, 2 of the 20 workers the farm employs, have already started gutting the downstairs of the two-story white-frame house, leaving only wall studs in place. The windows have been knocked out by windblown waves, and since the waters have receded, the hot summer sun has compounded the damage, leaving the house parched and desiccated. But Pieper hardly acknowledges the sheer devastation and instead comments on early stages of the cleanup. "The guys could have done more," he notes disappointedly. Mildew coats the ceilings. Stagnant water covers a stairway that drops toward the basement. "They could have started pumping this," Pieper says, pointing. "We've got to get this place cleaned up."<p>Pieper goes back outside. He walks toward a warehouse that contains his engineering equipment and tools. To keep more revenue flowing into his farming operation, Pieper has diversified over the years in a half-dozen directions. Aside from controlling its land and livestock, Pieper Farms Corp. owns the local farm-supply store. Away from the corporation, Pieper himself is a partner in a high-tech ceramics-manufacturing company and a self-taught engineer who designs and fabricates prototype farm implements. (Recently, some of his creations and insights were integrated into Caterpillar's new and hugely successful Challenger series of tractors.)<p>Pieper enters the tool barn's gaping sliding door. Around the white walls, a brown line from the flood's high-water mark rises to six feet off the ground. Dozens of metal-cutting machines are covered in slime and rust. On the building's walls, scores of power tools hang on pegs; all have been ruined. Waterlogged engineering plans lie on Pieper's broad desk. To the desk's right, a wall of cubbyhole shelves brims with rusted screws and bolts.<p>"When the levee broke," Pieper says, removing his snap-brim hat and shaking his head, "we didn't have time to get this stuff out. Replacing it's gonna cost $100,000." He slaps the hat back on his head and heads outside. "I don't even know what the flood's done to my farmland yet," he says. "It may have destroyed that, too." As Mike Pieper stands there uncharacteristically still for a long moment, a huge, dark-green frog bounds across the shed's parking area and--splat!--lands square on his boot. <p>Pieper looks down and, seeing the frog scramble off his toe and leap away, begins to laugh. He tosses his hands in the air, then bends and drops his fists to his knees. It's another half minute before--still giggling--he recovers.<p>"Been a hell of a year for frogs," he finally says, straightening and shifting the hat back on his head slightly. "Been the worst year possible for me. But, man, it's been a fine year for these frogs."<p><p>"There's an old farm saying," says gregory Hanson, a professor of agriculture at Pennsylvania State University. "A drought will scare you, but a flood will kill you."<p>The latest figures available show that for many of the Midwest's farmers, 1993 will enter the books as the worst harvest in history. By mid-July of last year more than 8 million acres of farmland were underwater or uncultivated, with another 20 million adversely affected by the weather. All told--figuring crop losses, machinery damage, and home and building destruction--the flood will have washed some $25 billion from the national economy, and in the estimation of the U.S. Department of Agriculture, one of every ten farmers affected by the flood will be run out of business.<p>Mike Pieper should be the kind of farmer who can withstand a flood's deadly blows. One of seven children, he has made this farm his life. While his siblings all went to college or pursued professional degrees, Mike went to work on the farm after graduating from high school. Since 1974, he's worked seven days a week, from 7 a.m. to 11 p.m., tilling, building, tinkering, and fighting to keep hold of the Jeffersonian notion that a well-managed family farm remains the key to American prosperity. And for Pieper, the work has paid off. He manages the farm with his semiretired father, Bud, 69, and younger brother, Bill, 36, who had once intended to be a dentist but didn't like it and returned to the farm.<p>The Pieper farm is the biggest spread in the 17-farm Green Bay district, and Pieper, his wife, Cheryl, and their four kids make their home in a comfortable four-bedroom house just down the road from the homes of his parents and brother. He sends the three eldest children to private school, and--though he has taken only one vacation in five years--business trips in the past 18 months have delivered him to such places as Nigeria, Ukraine, and Australia. ("We all wish he'd take a little more time off," says his brother Joe, an engineer at Caterpillar in Peoria. "Cheryl and the kids try to get away every year, but Mike often stays on and keeps working.") <p>Thanks to an annual net growth of 14 percent, Pieper Farms has also become a textbook case in farm management--literally. Since 1987, Ray Goldberg, a professor at Harvard Business School, has followed it as part of a senior management seminar. And thanks to the farm, Mike has become something of an agrarian TV hero; for the past two years, he's been featured in a widely rotated television commercial for DuPont's Classic herbicide, a spot that ends with the slogan "What makes them better is you."<p>(All of these accomplishments have left some of the neighbors less than thrilled and perhaps a little jealous. In fact, when I first arrived in Wever last August, I stopped by the Beach Front, one of two bars in town, asking directions to the Pieper place. After a minute of letting the question hang in the air, a pair of surly-looking farmers glanced up from their beers. One pointed out a picture window toward the flooded eastern horizon, then added derisively, "Mike Pieper? You mean old Indiana Jones.... He lives thataway.")<p>Despite all the outside acclaim, his own family members aren't completely pleased with the way the farm has been run recently. A series of events--set into motion six months before the flood--has left the farm awash in family tension and hard feelings. In September 1992, after more than ten years of hemming and hawing, Pieper's six brothers and sisters, each of whom has an equal share in the corporation under an estate-planning arrangement with their father, decided to sell the farm. Though three of Mike's brothers have worked on the farm--including Bill, the latest of them--the Pieper clan has spread across the country. To them, the farm represents a chancy investment, and they do not want to leave control of their patrimony in Mike's hands.<p>As it is explained by an off-farm brother, droughts in 1986, '87, and '88 and the hard-bitten economics of farming have increased the corporation's value little since 1981, despite the steady growth. None of the shareholders has seen a dime from the farm except the ones who worked on it. To the nonfarming shareholders, the only constant has been volatility. So in September of '92--"Since it was always intended for one of us to own the farm, and we're not getting any younger," the brother says--the Pieper siblings came to Mike and Bill and told them it was time to liquidate. They figured they could take their shares of the corporation, each worth in the neighborhood of $300,000 (after taxes), and look for better profits elsewhere.<p>As had been the plan for years, the farm's shares would be sold to just one of the brothers. It seemed the only tenable way to keep a Pieper on the farm was to have just one brother own it, since, as Mike says, "owning a whole farm by halves won't cut it for anybody." Mike said he'd make a bid. As did Bill, the amiable bachelor who'd overseen the farm's 20,000-hog livestock operation since finishing college in 1981. Both brothers said they'd get their offering packages together by the end of 1993.<p>So, in the months preceding the flood, the only question that hovered above the Pieper farm was a simple yet brutal one. Which brother would buy the farm and ascend to the security of a hefty agri-corporation? And which brother would leave, with nothing but one seventh of the farm to show for his years of toil?<p><p>Then in the spring of 1993, the deluge began. From Minnesota to Kansas, from Nebraska to Indiana--across an area the size of the Midwest itself--a season of relentless rain fell on soil still saturated from winter snowmelt. The ground couldn't soak up the excess water. Heavy downpours of four inches weren't uncommon, and week upon week, the water started to back up. Throughout the Mississippi River basin, in places as far away as Nebraska and eastern Montana, the soil was so muddy that many farmers weren't able to get their seed in. And for those who did get their planting done, the mud and standing water often rotted seeds before germination could take place. <p>In the upper drainages, away from the Mississippi, the Midwest's wide, flat, braiding rivers began to swell. And after a while, the larger rivers downstream--the Des Moines and Iowa rivers in Iowa, the Missouri River in Kansas and Missouri, the Rock and Illinois rivers in Illinois--overflowed. In March there were 26 days without sun. In April there were 23. In May there were 21. By mid-June, even the Mississippi was filled, and the runoff had nowhere else to go. Predictions of a record Mississippi River flood began to circulate.<p>On the Pieper farm, just inside the Mississippi River levee in southeast Iowa, they'd seen this kind of thing before. In fact, in 1951, the year Bud Pieper got married and bought 146 acres of the farm he'd been renting in Iowa's lush Green Bay, the Mississippi rose up and flooded him out. But the experience didn't deter him from buying more cropland in the bay "whenever it became available and with what few dollars we had at the time." The floods threatened again in 1958 and 1973, but each time the water lifted quickly and dropped. Bud Pieper had always been able to get his crops in and out. In 1993, though, the water just beyond the levee rose and stayed. This flood--if it happened--was going to be different, and everyone in the Green Bay area knew it.<p>On June 28, three days after the Mississippi had risen seriously above flood stage for the third time in as many months, the 17 farmers in the 14,000-acre Green Bay Levee and Drainage District (the area protected by the 22-mile Green Bay levee) met in the offices of the valley's grain elevator, which itself is perched on the levee's edge to take advantage of river-barge loading available through the elevation. "Six inches of rain fell that night," says the elevator's manager, Nick Huston, a trim, chain-smoking man of 46. "We knew we had a big problem coming our way." <p>Because Pieper was the largest farmer in the Green Bay (or the Bottoms, as locals call it) and was "known as a go-getter with a good mind for engineer-type thinking," Huston says, Pieper took over the job of flood-fight coordinator. In that meeting, Huston got the other pivotal job, "as a sort of supply sergeant," he says. "I turned our office into a command center. We manned the telephones and the weather-station computer to get people the flood-fight materials they'd need while anticipating the lifting of the river." <p>Over the next 13 days, with the river rising as much as a foot a night, Pieper, Huston, and hundreds of volunteers worked around the clock, fighting to maintain their 22 miles of levee protection. Like the farmlands of the Netherlands--and thanks entirely to the levee--the Green Bay had been made into some of Iowa's most fertile farmland. Before the levee was built in the late 1800s, the bay was a swamp. Then, after the levee was in place, leaving the bay a full eight feet beneath the usual level of the Mississippi, the rich flood plain with its sometimes tricky water table could be tilled into astonishing fecundity.<p>Now, in late June of last year, the Green Bay Bottoms and every farm in it was in danger of being drowned. As the river grew nearer and nearer the top of the levee, Pieper, Huston, and the volunteers went through 600 rolls of snow fence and 150,000 sandbags in a matter of days. They brought in 13 bulldozers--summoned from across Iowa--to prop and buttress the levee. On the night of June 30, the Army Corps of Engineers, who were already spread thin across the Midwest, set up an Emergency Operations Center at the elevator offices, bringing some National Guard units with them to combat the flood. But the rain kept falling. As the river kept rising, Nick Huston got on the phone to building suppliers: He ordered every piece of wood and sheet of plastic he could scrape up, and the volunteers and Guard units--plus dozens of prison inmates in a paramilitary boot-camp program--went to work making a temporary plywood-and-plastic "flashboard" levee atop the soil.<p>On television, the rising water had become a national news story. Tom Brokaw and Harry Smith helicoptered above the swollen brown water of Illinois's Rock River. So far, no levees had broken, but, as the farmers of the bay knew, all the water in the Des Moines, Skunk, and Rock rivers was headed for the Mississippi and would fill the Big Muddy a few miles on either side of the town of Wever. The onrushing torrent would turn Green Bay Bottoms into ground zero of the great flood of '93.<p>As the situation grew more ominous, farmers in the bay began to divide their time. By night, they'd fight the flood; by day, they'd prepare their farms for the worst. On the Pieper farms, employees as well as friends and volunteers undertook a massive effort to protect the operation, moving more than 30 truckloads of hogs into spare pens wherever they could be found. (Some of the animals were trucked as far away as Minnesota.) On July 2, the Piepers had to sell 8,000 immature "feeder" pigs they were cultivating at up to 25 percent below profit. On the farm's crop side, Pieper had to move to higher ground 72 pieces of machinery as well as 130,000 bushels of grain stored in the farm's three silos. <p>Finally, on July 10, the flood crested. "We were all exhausted," Huston says. "Everybody was screwed down tighter than a drum." And, miraculously, throughout the day, the levee held. "When the crest passed at about 2:30 or 3:00 that afternoon," Huston says, "everybody was so high, any of us could have kicked a train right off its track."<p>But as the water began to fall, a new, even more dangerous stage of the flood set in. "When a crest passes," Huston says, "a vacuum develops out in the river." That's when the levee began sloughing into the river. At 1 a.m. on July 11--as Pieper, his army of volunteers, and the National Guard were just beginning to breathe a little easier--Mike Pieper took a call on the Motorola radiophone he wears on his belt. "It was the sheriff," Pieper says, "and he said, 'Hey, Mike, we've had a report there's water on the blacktop.'"<p>At the moment Pieper was at his house, securing it for the night. He ran out to his truck and drove toward the levee's lowest zone--its furthest downstream point--where the break was reported. "I got to where our farm-supply store is, " he says, "about 200 yards from the levee, and there was water covering the road. So I drove out into the water a little ways and stopped the truck. And I was PO'd. I thought, 'Oh, shit, it's true.'" After a minute of sitting in his truck and thinking, Pieper opened the truck's door to see if there was a current. "I saw this leaf or something drift past in the darkness," he says, "and I knew the water was moving. I knew that, somewhere, the levee had busted.<p>"I got on the phone," Pieper says, "and I called the the flood-fight office and said, 'Everybody, everybody, the levee has broken. Get out of there. Get out.' I sounded a little frantic, they tell me, but I wanted everyone to get out of there safely." <p>After that, Pieper says, for a long few minutes he shut off his truck and listened to the water as it moved across his farmland, purling and gurgling against his truck tires. "It was really quiet, almost peaceful," he says. "The night was black, and I just sat in my truck and watched the water finger its way across the low spots and into the bay, like watching a growing bad dream."<p>Officially, at 1:05 a.m. on July 11, 1993, the Green Bay Drainage District became the first Mississippi River revetment to wash away in the great flood of '93. Ultimately, the river would fill some parts of the bay to 16 feet, just as it would drown two thirds of the 1,100 other levee districts across the Midwest. In the bay, the river pressed through the levee at a pair of gaps whose length totaled 1,400 feet. The incoming tide crushed empty grain silos like Styrofoam cups. It lifted petroleum tanks from their moorings, leaving them drifting with the wind and current across the bay's ten-mile width. Woodchucks and ground squirrels had to be rescued from treetops, while coyotes--always heard in the bay but never before seen--drifted around the newly made lake on logs, helpless as castaways. Before the flood stabilized, 60 billion gallons of water spilled out of the Mississippi River and into the Green Bay Bottoms. It took two complete days for the river to cover the bay's 14,000 acres. <p>Two weeks after the levee broke, mike Pieper stood among the sandbags and snow fences and stared across the flood. He'd tried to play along with the program. He had dutifully attended the daily Corps of Engineers and emergency-aid meetings, which were held in the fire station in Wever, on higher ground overlooking the flooded bay. Some time during the second week of sitting around, Pieper grew weary of the bureaucrats and their public-policy programs. The government, he discovered, was offering some assistance--on its own timetable--and was not giving out any money so that Pieper and the other farmers in the bay could help themselves. "Everything they were proposing had strings attached," Pieper says. He'd had enough of "the kind of people who propose ideas but never act on them."<p>The only objective, from his perspective, was to get his farm dry as soon as possible. And because the drainage district's usual pumping station, at a confluence of drainage and irrigation canals near the grain elevator, had been destroyed, Pieper began to cast for alternatives. He got on the phone and called around the country, trying to find some kind of auxiliary pumps--but no such things even existed. So the next day he jumped into a skiff and, using a rope with a rock tied to one end, took some depth soundings. When he'd found the bay's lowest altitude spot--the place where the water was deepest and where, eventually, the last of the drained flood would end up--he drove some long stakes into the lake bottom that had once been his farmland. After that, he came ashore, pulled a measuring tape from his belt, and lifted a stick from the ground. <p>Over the next hour, Pieper, leaning on his self-taught engineering skills, reasoned and figured. Using the stick he'd lifted, he etched a pump design into the sand, then copied it roughly--in blocks and circles--onto a sheet of paper. He made some more final measurements, double-checking the sand for a set of "mental blueprints I could carry around," and went home to bounce his scheme off a couple of phone-conferenced engineers. <p>In early September, the water is still standing 14 feet deep across the Green Bay District, but Pieper is ready to do something about it--personally. Using the empty hulk of an old department store in the bluff-top town of Fort Madison, eight miles south of Wever, he has put his farm employees to work building pumps, an effort paid for with $28,000 of the farm's money. Against the sound of blowtorches and arc welders, Pieper says, "We were the first drainage district to get our paperwork into the Corps of Engineers, and they told us they'd respond in 26-plus weeks. I'm a farmer. I can't wait for the corps to think about draining my land next February or March. I'll need to be planting crops then."<p>The crew is in the midst of fashioning nine 80-foot lengths of pipe--each one 36 inches in diameter--into pump tubes. Inside three of the tubes, they mount boat propellers. The nine tubes will be trimmed and married together to make three 280-foot-long siphons. The propellers are each powerful enough to suck floodwaters into the pipe and will push the water 25 vertical feet over the levee and down into the river. They will be attached to drive shafts, which, in turn, will be powered by three 18-wheeler truck engines. When the pumps are operational, Pieper will trailer the device onto the levee, drop the propellered ends of the pipes into the bay, and begin pumping the floodwaters at a rate of 135,000 gallons a minute. "After that," he says, "all we'll have to do is close the levee, keep the pumps going 24 hours a day, and wait a few months."<p>Most of the other farmers have apparently decided to wait for help. All summer and into the autumn, across the Green Bay Bottoms, few can be found. On rare occasions, Pieper sees his neighbors returning home for a day or two, monitoring the flood and wringing their hands at their waterlogged houses. "Most farmers," says Nick Huston, "they're purely farmers. They're not like Mike, who's a problem solver before he's a farmer. Most of the other folks in the bay, they farm--which isn't a criticism, since that's no easy thing--but most of them, they've just disappeared. They'll come back when the water's gone."<p>For Pieper, the successful draining of more than 14,000 acres has taken on a greater meaning. It would prove that he deserves the farm his brothers and sisters had decided to sell. Mike says he doesn't know what has become of the other bay farmers. "I hear tell that some of them are living on high ground with their families and in-laws until the water recedes," he says. "They're helping out on other farms where they're needed, returning the favor to those farmers who helped us during the flood fight. Which is great. It's fine for them. But I've got to keep working down here. I can't wait that way."<p>He isn't entirely alone in his efforts. His brother Bill is hard at work cleaning out the farm's three quarters of a mile of hog barns. Bud Pieper pitches in, and a cousin, Karl Pieper, who's also a farmer in the bay, is helping Mike with the pumps. One afternoon, as the pumps are being trucked in, Pieper drives along the levee for a distance to where another of the area farmers, Squirt Blanchard, has started helping to reclaim the bay. To do this, Blanchard has spent the past week driving a Pieper Farms bulldozer back and forth across the levee, shaving the top from it and using that excess sand and earth to close the levee's gaps. "The Corps of Engineers owns the levee," Pieper says as he watches Blanchard move sand toward a 923-foot levee break, "and I'm not sure the corps is going to like us closing their levee for them. But," he says, throwing up his hands, "they know where to find me and Squirt if they want to toss us in jail."<p>As the building and moving of the pumps nears its completion, there are endless problems to attend to: More iron has to be machined; the universal joints in the driveshafts aren't sturdy enough; extra steel has to be ordered for the pumps. And always in the back of Mike Pieper's mind are the larger issues that compel him to push himself ever harder.<p>Beneath the floodwater, for instance, he still doesn't know what his farmland looks like. It may have been carved into an untillable canyon by the rushing flood (or covered by a layer of sand, making it equally unfarmable). And of course he's still got to come up with the money to buy the farm by the end of the year: Between the farm and its related businesses, he estimates he'll need around $2.5 million. "I'm not educated like the rest of them," Pieper says. "They've all got college degrees to fall back on. Farming on this farm, it's all I know."<p>So Mike Pieper often stays up late into the night, working on whatever needs tending to. To construct his farm bid, he spends a few evenings a week with Harry Tucker, a supervisor for the University of Iowa's Farm Extension Service in the nearby city of Burlington. Then he goes home and works at his desk, running down John Kincaid, the technical manager for the Army Corps of Engineers in Keokuk, making equipment orders for the pumps, and poring over the fiduciary tables that will help him thread the farm-finance needle. Late at night, he might drive over to the spot on the levee where the pumps are being assembled. "But most nights," he says, "when I can't find anything else to do for a few hours and my head hits the pillow, getting that money together is all I think about. Sometimes it's just easier to stay awake."<p><p>
FEATURE:  A FARMER'S BATTLE (2)
FEB 94<p>A FARMER'S BATTLE (1)
By Donovan Webster<p>
On the pieper spread, there is often talk of the "last generation of family farm," and Mike doubts his 13-year-old son, Zachary, will make farming his career. "A lot of farm kids," Pieper says, "they've seen what happened to their folks during the farm crisis. They don't want to work that hard."<p>In 1946, when Bud Pieper and his four brothers returned home from World War II, only two of them went back to work on the 200-acre farm in central Iowa run by their parents. "There were too many snouts in that trough already," Bud says, "and I just thought there was a better future for me somewhere else." For three years, he stepped away from farming entirely, going to work in the production-control department at A.O. Smith, a company that makes glass-lined hot-water heaters. Then, in 1948, Bud Pieper's father came to him with a proposition. "He'd make the payments for me on a farm here in the bay, and we'd split the harvest at the end of the year," Bud says. "It was a good deal, and I took it."<p>The ground in the bay was rich but unimproved ("I had to pull shrubs and trees out to get good fields," Bud says). In three years, he'd farmed the rental property well enough that he and his new wife, Glorine, bought their own 146-acre place in the bay, and from that rich ground grew the 3,200-acre Pieper farm of today. "We came into the bay at a lucky time," he says. "A lot of older farmers were here then, and each year one of them would want to sell a 100-acre parcel here, a 300-acre piece there, and we'd buy everything we could."<p>By 1981, three decades after Bud had purchased his first land in the bay, the Pieper farm spread across 2,500 acres. The commercial hog operation he'd started with "a few pigs out in a pen" had grown to move some 10,000 hogs for slaughter through its barns every year. What had started as a typical family farm had grown, 30 years later, into a state-of-the-art operation. Over the next decade, under Mike and Bill's management, the farm would add 700 more acres and the livestock would double in number. <p>A corporate farm like the Pieper operation is potentially lucrative, but the downside is perilous. And basically, it all comes down to the weather. In the last decade alone, the Pieper farm has survived three droughts and now this flood. Fortunately, a few good crop years --plus the dependable cash flow generated by the hog operation--have kept the farm afloat. But the corporation is mortally tied to the vagaries of crop farming, and thus diversification seems to be the only long-range solution. The issues this has raised, in large part, have led Mike's brothers and sisters to opt for liquidation. "The decision to sell the corporation," Mike says, "isn't about something that happened among the kids 35 years ago--who liked who better or who treated who badly. It's business." Mike would like to manage a farm in which he is free to invest its assets as he sees fit. The other shareholders favor a less aggressive approach. For instance, in 1981, Mike was able to buy the local supply store with the corporation's money. But he hasn't found corporate support for some more ambitious projects: When he traveled to Nigeria last spring, he was there to discuss building a huge fertilizer plant with government officials. The corporation showed little interest in investing.<p>As Mike Pieper wrestles with the life-and-death issues of the diversification required to protect his farm, he mourns the passing of a way of life. According to Pieper, something will be lost when, in another few generations, the once-abundant small farms across the United States have been absorbed by the larger corporate ventures. "There'll be a loss of self-reliance," Pieper says. "Our work ethic may even suffer, not to mention what'll happen to the fabric of rural America. One of the underpinnings of what's made our country the way it is will have been eroded down."<p><p>Cheryl pieper is medium-sized and blond. A native of Bradley, Illinois, she came to Iowa in 1978 as an elementary-school teacher. "There was a job here, and I needed the classroom hours to complete my master's degree in education," she says. "So I moved to Fort Madison, and I was introduced to Mike through a friend."<p>After a year-long courtship, they were married in 1979, the year the two took up residence on the farm. "We had Zack pretty quickly after that," she says, "and I gave up teaching and became a farm wife, helping out with the books and working at the kids' school, eventually joining the school board." <p>Sitting in her kitchen and listening to Cheryl Pieper, it's obvious the years on the farm have been good ones. "You get a good crop year in the bay," she says, "with the corn all tall and green and the beans growing, and it's the most beautiful, most positive place in the world." <p>Cheryl's home in the bay, she says, has been a fine place to raise children, and she's always enjoyed being part of the Pieper clan. In fact, she says, throughout the 15 years she's lived on the farm, family relations have always been friendly and supportive, with "something new and interesting always coming along for Mike and me." It is, by all outward signs, a solid, sturdy marriage, though one that, because of Mike's long days of work, has left Cheryl to do much of the child raising herself. Still, the Piepers eat breakfast and dinner together most every night, and you can see that they're justifiably proud of the family and the life they've put together. In fact, it is Cheryl who, one night after a big pot roast, asks if I've seen the DuPont ad with Mike and the farm in it. When I say no, she leads me to the VCR and--after asking Zachary to wire the thing correctly to the TV--we slip the videocassette inside. In the ad, which shows Pieper standing next to one of his corn-planter designs on a snowy winter day, the sales tag rings out: "For people who like to do things their own way, DuPont Classic...."<p>These days the DuPont slogan has taken on new meaning. Between the impending sale of the farm and the subsequent flood, relations with the family have become tense. Mike and Bill, who didn't have much contact before the decision to sell, have become even more distant and often try not to be in the tool barn at the same time. And it's Mike who seems to be pressing harder for his siblings to bend to his wishes--or be damned. Late this summer, as the floodwaters covered their fields, the brothers and sisters had a revelation: No one really knew how much the farm was worth. To divine the corporation's price, they've decided to enlist an agribusiness consultant, the Ferguson Group  in Peoria, Illinois, to appraise the farm's value. The fee for the appraisal, they say, will be picked up by the corporation. It's a decision that turns Pieper blisteringly angry. He's afraid the outside appraisal will place an unrealistically high price on the farm, putting it further from his reach. With the help of Harry Tucker, Mike has been quietly building his own idea of what an accurate bid package represents. <p>After seeing the Classic advertisement, we go back upstairs. As we sit back down at the kitchen table, a high-pitched cacophony piles in from the other room. A second later, five-year-old Jillian charges into the kitchen, closely followed by eight-year-old Lindsey. As Jilly climbs into her mother's lap--screaming "Save me! Save me! Save me!"--Cheryl is a picture of parental calm. She strokes the red ringlets of her daughter's hair, then sets her youngest back on the floor again. As her daughters run off, Cheryl turns back to the conversation. One of the obstacles to Mike's being sold the farm, she says, is that the other brothers and sisters are very conservative with their money and investments. "And, well," she says, "Mike has a more aggressive style of doing business than they might like. I'm sure it makes the other kids a little nervous. "<p>I ask her what'll happen if Mike is denied, if the farm is sold to Bill, or--if both offers are found unacceptable--the thing is gaveled away in an auction. "If Mike doesn't get the farm," she says, her voice firm and solid, "we'll have lost everything. I really don't know what we'll do."<p><p>In early fall, the pumps go in, the levee is bulldozed shut, and by October, with the onset of the new school year, a sense of structure has finally returned to the Piepers' life. Around the rental house, Cheryl finally finds time to do the household cleanup. In her free time--of which there is precious little--she's started going out to her farmhouse in the bay and, working with a few friends, has begun scraping away the flood damage.<p>Down on the Green Bay levee, week after week, the 18-wheeler engines have been roaring, pumping roily streams of floodwater over the levee and back into the Mississippi. After a month, the floodwaters have dropped enough that automobiles can again drive on the roads farthest from the levee. One October evening, as the sun sets, Pieper takes me on a drive to inspect some of the recently flooded land. We roll along, looking at the slick, lifeless sheen of the silt-blackened fields. Beached fuel tanks and abandoned tires protrude from them at odd angles. Pieper talks of the bid package he's started to arrange. "We're putting together a solid deal," he says. "It's based on how much the land is worth after the flood, with capability to be back at top capacity in five years. We think it'll point up some of the overpricing that these fellas from Peoria might try to build in." <p>His offer, Pieper says, will be an extremely flexible one, which asks for owner financing over 18 years but which he can tailor to most any whim the stockholders toss his way. "If they think I'll make more money faster than predicted," he says, "I'll build in a sliding scale. So on those years we do better--okay, I'll pay more."<p>At many of the flooded houses around the bay, vans and buses, many with out-of-state license plates, sit in the driveway. When we roll past one flood-ravaged house with a van carrying Wisconsin tags, Pieper stops his truck and backs up. "Let's go in here," he says. "You've got to meet the Amish."<p>Shortly after the flood hit, David O'Rourke, the minister of the United Church of Christ in the nearby town of Denmark, Iowa, spearheaded a coast-to-coast relief effort. Over the past month, 750 volunteers--from the Church of Christ, the Mennonite church, and the Amish faith, among others--have migrated to the bay for one- and two-week stints as volunteer carpenters. <p>Finding the help was only half of O'Rourke's goal. He has also been lobbying construction-supply companies, working to get as much as $60,000 a week in donated Sheetrock, insulation, and hardware. He's also gotten food-processing companies to pitch in, and Hormel, Dial, and Armour have kept the relief workers in cold cuts, bread, cereal, and bottled water for weeks now. <p>We head inside the farmhouse, where, upstairs, some Mennonite and Amish men and women are screwing down new Sheetrock panels over bright pink insulation. On our way back outside, we run into Mahlon Gingrich, a farmer from Spooner, Wisconsin, who also happens to be head of the Mennonite Disaster Services. He's been in the bay now for more than a month, since the cleanup began. "We had to take a boat to some places first," the short, sturdy Gingrich says. He goes on to trace the painstaking treatment that's been required to clean the 37 flood-damaged houses in the bay, basically rebuilding each one from the inside out. First, he says, the houses need to be gutted. Then the aid workers clean out the insulation and muck, finishing by washing the remaining shell of a house from top to bottom with bleach. "From teardown to finished, painted walls," he says, "the whole thing takes about three weeks."<p>We get back in the truck and roll on. In the distance, toward the levee, a sea of mirror-flat floodwaters still coats half of the bay's floor. Along the water's edge, hundreds of herons and egrets are standing perfectly still, waiting for a shad minnow or frog to blunder into range. Beyond them, a three-quarters moon is rising above the Mississippi's bluffs. Still, inside the truck cab, only talk of money fills the air. Pieper says that, as a contingency, in case his brothers and sisters won't agree to the owner financing they've originally offered, he's also been looking into bank loans, which would still allow him buy the farm outright. It has been a frustrating search. Because of the type of loan he's asking for--a total farm mortgage in the millions of dollars--he's got to show substantial collateral. "And all I've got to show as collateral is my record as a successful farmer on the farm I'm trying to buy," he says. "The bank will do it, but I'll really have to play ball." To get the loan, he'll virtually have to accept the bankers as partners.<p>We keep driving through the bay. Away from the truck the reexposed land looks like tar. On some of the farms, furrow lines are still evident, and the land will in all likelihood be tillable after another few weeks of drying. For an endless-seeming moment, Pieper pauses, his face screwed tight in consternation. "Anyway," he finally adds, glancing out the window into the last light of the day, "whatever happens with me and this farm, the soil all around the bay here isn't as ruined as I'd feared. Least we've got that to be happy about."<p>It's nearly thanksgiving before mike and Cheryl Pieper's farmhouse begins to resemble its old self again. Because they're conscious of the advantages they have over other bay residents--their larger, more prosperous farm, their rental house in town--they've asked to have O'Rourke's disaster workers help them last. And long before the workers arrive, in early November, the farm's carpenters have gone a sizable distance toward fixing the house up. They have drained the basement and cleaned the place out; they have rewired and reinsulated. New windows and Sheetrock have been installed, and the kitchen and family rooms have new cabinetry in place, too. Each day, while the kids have been at school, Cheryl Pieper has been at her flooded-out husk of a home, working alongside the carpenters. She's been cleaning and painting the second floor, which--while never under water--suffered substantial mildew and humidity damage over the summer. It's been a long, hard job, but by the closing weeks in November, the house is inviting and livable again.<p>One night, after Mike has finished his farm duties for the day, he joins Cheryl in the basement to do a little cleanup and painting. It's about 7:30, and with carpet layers coming tomorrow, Cheryl has enlisted the older kids--Zachary and Kimberlee--to help her clean. As she paints the sloping ceiling above the cellar stairs, she's talking about the rental house and the family's summer.<p>"It's amazing what we've learned to tolerate," she says, painting long, even strokes down the wall. "We don't keep the rental place clean like we keep our own house. It's always a mess. It's resembled our lives over the past few months: chaos." <p>In their rehabbed farmhouse, however, order has already reasserted itself. In the four bedrooms of the house's second floor, the kids have started moving back in. There are new linens and bedspreads fitted on each of the childrens' mattresses; even the grout in the bathroom glistens. Cheryl's glad to be past the big stuff, she says; happy to be so nearly moved back home. Then, as she finishes her painting, working along the bottom of the stairwell ceiling, there's an audible catch in her throat.<p>"Hey, Mike," she says. "They missed a spot."<p>Pieper, who has been painting the stairway's rail, stands up and follows his wife to the bottom of the steps. There, just where the stairway's sloping ceiling joins the drop ceiling of the basement, there's a two-inch gap. Somehow, the carpenters neglected to put a new piece of fascia over the old, flood-browned ceiling. And through that little break--nothing more than a slit--you can see the flood, the impending farm sale, and all this year has wrought come washing momentarily out, moving in a grimace across Cheryl's face. <p>"Aw, it's just a little stain," Mike says.<p>Lifting her paintbrush, Cheryl starts pressing paint onto the gap, moving the end of her brush, hoping to cover the flood. Each time she tries to paint over the stain, though, its anemic brown comes back through. Behind her glasses, her eyes glisten. "Sometimes it feels like we're never going to get past this," she says to her husband. "We're never really going to get past the flood, are we?"<p>Mike bends down and dips his brush in the can of white paint at their feet, then straightens and begins painting the gap, too. "It's just what's left of a little water," he says, moving his brush back and forth. "It's nothing."<p>Over the next 20 minutes, Mike and Cheryl Pieper lay coat after coat of paint on the last stain left on their house by the great flood of '93. Each time they finish painting, the stain bleeds back through. <p><p>On saturday, november 27, with very little fanfare, Mike and Cheryl Pieper move their family home. It's two days after Thanksgiving--nearly six months after they were displaced by the flood--and the house, a moldering mess even at Labor Day, is now a showplace of new appliances and fresh paint. Over the next week --in circling, countless laps from the rental place in Fort Madison--Cheryl will transport the family and its belongings back home, back into the well-ordered life it was forced to abandon in July.<p>For Mike, the days after Thanksgiving are especially sweet ones. Despite the sale of the farm still looming in his thoughts, on December 2--seven weeks after he fired up the 18-wheeler motors for the first time--the bay is pumped dry. And as he walks the mucky farmland near where the paired levee breaks occurred, Pieper is pleased to learn that, even right against the breaks in the levee, the soil hasn't been scoured out. Only two of the bay's farms have been ruined. "A lot of the current in the flood," he says, "flowed in through the upstream break and out through the downstream one. It didn't flow inside the bay and eddy and press. We just got lucky." <p>Now, with the bay empty, Pieper, his cousin Karl, and a half dozen of the farm's workers have started dismantling the pumps and transporting them to the tool barn, where each one will be cleaned up and refitted. After fielding a number of inquiries, Pieper will be renting his pumps to the 18,000-acre Indian Graves Drainage District, just north of Quincy, Illinois. Like all the Mississippi River drainage districts around Quincy, Indian Graves is still under water, and after six months of wrangling, the Army Corps of Engineers has finally started closing levees, and the drainage is ready to be pumped.<p>Pieper now shows a respect for the Army Corps he didn't have a few months ago. "The corps is just way undermanned," he says. "They can't stay staffed up for the 500-year flood. Now that the actual flooding is past, that the situation is stable, they've really moved much faster than we were led to believe. Hell, they've moved like a lightning bolt."<p>Away from Pieper's house, out across the bay, the soil has finally dried enough that farmers can again drive their implements onto it. And in many of the fields, which are being dusted with the season's first snow, the farmers are busy plowing and disking their land, re-oxygenating the soil while also folding the new layer of silt in with the tilth. Mike was able to turn his fields weeks ago; the lightweight, aluminum-bodied tractor prototypes he created a few years back move better across soft muddy soil than do standard tractors. Now, the ground beyond Pieper's white farmhouse stretches toward the horizon like soft brown corduroy. All that remains is for Mike Pieper to buy the place.<p>On December 6, after months of planning and figuring, Pieper submits his offer to his six brothers and sisters, the Pieper Farms Corp. stockholders. After months of figuring, the bid has come in a few hundred thousand dollars higher than expected. "I'm willing to work with them," he says. "If I make more money than I'm projecting, I'll dump the excess profit into paying off the note faster. Whatever they want. I'm willing to go that extra mile on this thing."<p>His offer is dismissed summarily. Further, with his eldest brother, Joe, age 40, functioning as spokesman, Mike is told that the decision to sell the farm has now been pushed back to the spring of 1994. <p>"The reason they've put off the sale," Mike says, "is total bullshit. The shareholders say they're not ready to sell, and they've got a bunch of reasons. They say that--for sure now--they're going to bring in that guy from Peoria and that Bill hasn't had time to put his bid together, that he's been too busy." Pieper adjusts his hat. "Well, I've been busy, too," he adds, "and I got my bid in on time. What's brother Bill been doing that I haven't?" <p>Hoping to get a true fix on the circumstances of the farm sale, in the weeks preceding the year's end, I contact a number of the Pieper brothers and sisters. As Mike has intimated, they are scattered across America. Barb, a wireless-computer-technology representative, lives and works in the Chicago area. Matt is a Pepsico distributor in Plano, Texas. Joe is a Caterpillar engineer in Peoria; Maggie is a nurse in Hallmark, Missouri; Jean is a Peoria homemaker. They are all reluctant to speak about the farm's sale--and the surrounding acrimony. Off the record, they each fear "fueling the fire of an already difficult situation," or being shown as "saying something that might be misinterpreted."<p>Like the members of so many farm families, each of the Pieper shareholders I spoke with was quick to point up that, more and more frequently, the situation that they've found themselves in isn't unique. "This is happening to farm families all across the country," says Barb. "The issues this sale has brought up, the bitterness of it--unfortunately, it isn't something rare among farm families anymore."<p>As for Mike, with his offer rebuffed, he says he's finished. "I did what I was supposed to," he says. "I got my offer in by the end of the year, even though I was also busy draining the bay, and--pfffft--they aren't going to see that offer again. It was all or nothing, get your package on the table before the end of 1993, and I did; and I didn't get jack for it. Nope. Nope. That's the last bid they'll see from me." <p>He doesn't see the point "in putting seed in the ground on a farm I may not own come fall." If Pieper does leave, he says, he probably won't use his share of the corporation's buy-out to start another farm. He doesn't have the energy, he says, to begin again, since transforming a "from-scratch" farm into what he wants would take 15 years or more.<p>Instead, Pieper says, he'll look for a job as a plant manager (he's already received an offer from a large fertilizer company), or maybe he'll cash in his collaborations with <a name="NYSE:CAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10304"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Caterpillar</b></a> and others and become some sort of farm-equipment designer. Whatever he does, he says now, when the spring of 1994 rolls around, it's very possible won't be planting any seed on the farm he's spent his life building up and tending. It's possible, of course, that his intransigence is just a negotiating ploy, but he claims his decision to leave is final.<p>"This whole thing has been my choice," Pieper says, "but I can't help being a little angry. I spend my life tending my family's farm, sweating my sweat, doing the work of three men while my brothers and sisters go to college, and when I hit middle age, they all just try to screw me out of the deal. Somehow, it just doesn't seem right." <p><p>One evening in early december, i climb into the cab of a Quincy-bound truck with Mike Pieper. Together, with a load of pump equipment in the back, we make the hour's drive south toward Indian Graves, talking on and off along the way. He has just learned that his brother Matt is considering giving up the soda business and returning to the farm in a partnership with his brother Bill. It's an arrangement that would virtually assure that the corporation won't be sold to Mike. As we skirt the line of bluffs that over the course of last summer girdled in the mighty river the way a man-made levee system couldn't, I ask Pieper if he blames the flood for the changes that have visited themselves upon his once-secure life.<p>Pieper smiles and shakes his head. "Nah," he finally says. "A farmer can't ever blame his luck only on nature or the weather." He steers the truck away from the river and toward the higher ground. "There's so many other things involved," he says. "To blame the flood for what's happening to me, that'd be cheating." <p>Donovan Webster, who wrote about Greenpeace in the June 1993 issue of Worth, is a freelance writer living in Chicago.<p><p>

