	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Givings and Misgivings</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Givings and Misgivings</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Children ask for a lot at the holidays. Many parents feel powerless to say no. Are we trying top give our kids everything we didn't get? A father grapples with the monster behind the tree.<p>By James Kaplan<p>"Dad," my five-year-old son said to me a couple of months back--it was August, the weather saunalike--"I can't wait till Christmas."<p>A small inner voice cried, Oh, no. Still, I was curious to know just what he had in mind. Please, I prayed, no more action figures. The inside of our house, no doubt like many of yours, is strewn with these grotesque and bellicose boy dolls, each of which, at six and eight and ten bucks a pop, has held my son's loyalty for a period approximating the life span of a mayfly. Their limbs and accessories lie scattered in every corner, like the aftermath of some action-figure plane crash. <p>"Why can't you wait for Christmas?" I answered, with as much sweetness as I could muster.<p>" 'Cause the living room will be covered in toys," he said.<p>Well. I restrained myself from the obvious comeback ("But it already is"). For even as the child in me knew exactly what he was talking about--the dream of abundance starts early and takes hold powerfully--the grown-up in me was filled with dread and distaste at the thought of the coming holiday. <p>My dislike, of course, had nothing to do with Christ or his birthday--but then, nor do most aspects of the holiday itself. You may go to church on Christmas; you may light candles on Hanukkah; you may observe all seven days of Kwanza. You can't avoid Christmas as an economic avatar. American retail sales last December, buoyed by consumer optimism after the presidential election, jumped from $156 billion in 1991 to a healthy $169 billion and change. The average American family, according to the National Retail Federation, spent $400 on holiday gifts. <p>But let's look at that $400 for a second. The figure looks way low to me. I suspect that in trying to sound prudent and average, that average family failed to report Sega upgrades, miscellaneous Lego mini-sets, or assorted last-minute doll accessories that somehow managed to add another $379.95 to the already strained Visa balance. <p>"Two thirds to 70 percent of the [retail] toy business happens in the fourth quarter," says Jodi Levin of the Toy Manufacturers of America. Which means, since toys are a $17 billion business in the U.S., that Americans laid out, very conservatively, $10 billion on toys last Christmas. In a country where fourth-quarter consumer spending is regarded, with almost superstitious awe, as a major economic indicator, where a good Christmas can make the whole country feel zesty (and last year--up 8 percent over the previous December--was zesty indeed), $10 billion is nothing to sneeze at. <p>And I helped. A lot.<p>A quick rundown of last year's Christmastime credit-card receipts, many of them from the dreaded <a name="NYSE:TOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11495"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toys "R" Us</b></a>, shows me that, astoundingly enough, we seem to have spent on our two children alone close to what that putative average family spends on all its gifts put together. <p>Are we insane? Are we wealthy? No and no. This sum does not reflect purposeful lavishness on our part. We had a clear enough idea of our financial horizons, so we didn't intentionally go overboard. We did not go out and purchase miniature English riding habits for our five-year-old and two-year-old boys. We didn't buy state-of-the-art learning computers. We just got a lot of not very expensive kid stuff, and it added up.<p>Here's some of what we bought just for the five-year-old: One Decepticon Transformer and one Slag Transformer, at about $15 each. Tyco's Doodle Dome, for about $20. A large basic Lego set, at $25. A Playmobil Civil War set, for $16. A Nerf missile launcher, at $20. Then there was the cellular-phone pencil case, at $15; the bug-catching set, with butterfly net and magnifying glass, at $15; and $30 or so worth of books. Not to mention another $30 on miscellaneous stocking stuffers: plastic dinosaurs, Crazy Foam, a Ninja Turtle watch, a Koosh.<p>Two hundred dollars. One child.<p>How did this happen? Was there a game plan? Was there a budget? No to both, even though I agree there should have been. Here's how it works in our house: We love our kids, and we want them to be happy. So my wife begins to see things, soon after Labor Day, that would be perfect for them for Christmas. She buys them. She stores these things in the basement and our closets. Soon she forgets what she's bought and buys more. <p><p>As christmas approaches, we both lose track altogether, panic, and go out and buy even more stuff. Then, usually at the very last minute, once my older son has received whatever arcane messages television and catalogs and his peers have sent him and decided what he really, really wants, I myself cruise our local suburban-blight shopping strip, scan the hopelessly picked-over merchandise, and settle (all faint hopes of fiscal sanity thrown to the winter winds), not for the desired toy, which has long since been snapped up by other desperate parents, but for something else that costs just as much or more. <p>Throughout this process, my dialogue with my son about his presents is minimal--although I'm sure he'd prefer it otherwise. My pretext is secrecy; the reality, I think, is that I'd rather not face what's really going on. <p>What is going on?<p>Much as sex attacks the brain's seat of reason, Christmas shopping for our kids melts down the higher mental functions of otherwise responsible adults. Just as we will walk through fire or face down armed muggers for our offspring, we will also go into debtors' prison to do right--or what we suppose to be right--by our children at holiday time. <p>But what, precisely, is right? What has to do with us and what has to do with them? If doing right means compensating for our own past deprivations, maybe we ought to think twice about it. If it means assuaging a guilty conscience, maybe we should think three times.<p>We all make mistakes as parents. Some of us make bad mistakes. Could it just possibly be a further, deeper mistake to assume that a token--no matter how expensive--can redeem us in a child's eyes? Of course children are happy when they get toys; they're also happy when they get candy. But there's happiness, and there's happiness. The greatest presents of my childhood, the things I remember with acute joy, had contextual value--some sort of tie to an emotion, a person, a discovery. More often than not, this value was utterly accidental. But the context was crucial, since the greatest present we can give our children is our presence, our absolute attention. How barren to presume that a thing, in the absence of that attention, can compensate.<p>How barren, but how common.<p>"Any manager of a Toys 'R' Us, if he's worth his salt, quickly learns to recognize a certain type of single parent who comes into the store on a Saturday or Sunday afternoon," says David Liebowitz, senior vice president and director of research for Republic New York Securities Corp. "This is the parent who gets the kids on alternate weekends or once a month or whatever it is. And that manager can tell by looking at that parent precisely, to the dollar, what he or she is going to spend. I call these purchases conscience gifts."<p>Or does doing right by our kids mean fulfilling that old dream of abundance? And is that dream a lodestar for our lives or a nightmare trap? And if it is a trap--as I believe it is--how do we begin to help ourselves and our children climb out of it?<p>Whether guilty or simply holiday-addled, we have holiday fever stamped into our genetic circuits. And the toy companies know it. "Parents are going to buy toys for their kids at Christmas," says Noah Manduke, a senior vice president and account director at Ogilvy & Mather in Los Angeles, which creates much of Mattel's advertising. "They may not buy a house; they may not buy a car. But they're going to buy toys."<p>"The toy industry has not had a down year since the assassination of President Kennedy," Liebowitz says. "Even if times are harsh, we will not take it out on the children. The children of America will not be denied."<p>We have made a beginning of discussing economic realities with our five-year-old. Throughout the rest of the year, when he points at some $27.95 gewgaw, we can say, "That's a really big toy, honey. We'll have to save that for a special time."<p>But then comes Christmas. What do we say then?<p>And what do we say to him about the junk? What about the action figures and other plastic crapola that in his broadly tolerant toy worldview is just as good as what seems "better" to his parents? Do we forbid it? Discourage it?<p>And how do we save ourselves from our own worst emotional and economic instincts where Christmas is concerned? <p><p>Was christmas better once? when i was a kid, maybe? Or am I fooling myself? Let us consider Mr. Machine. When I was ten, 30 or so years ago, Ideal's Mr. Machine, a top-hatted transparent walking robot with visible gears, was quite simply the coolest toy I had ever seen up to that juncture in my life. I wanted it desperately, or thought I did, and its nefariously infectious television jingle--"Here he comes, here he comes, greatest toy you've ever seen/And his name is ... Mr. Machine!"--bored the message into my head. As Christmastime approached, the commercials increased, and my need sharpened. The only problem was that Mr. Machine cost some 20 bucks, and 20 bucks for a toy in the early '60s was big money. Or so it probably seemed to my father, the holder of the purse strings, who wisely saw where Mr. Machine was headed--straight (and fast) toward the scrap heap of holiday history. He was willing to go over the toy budget if doing so involved electric trains. Electric trains were likely to stick around for a few seasons; moreover, he could play with them, too. I never got Mr. Machine, but I did get electric trains, and they did indeed last a long time, and I remember them with keen pleasure.<p>But I also remember Mr. Machine, the toy that got away.<p>Did my father explain to me that we couldn't afford to buy both Mr. Machine and electric trains? Did he explain to me that Mr. Machine was junk? <p>He didn't. When it came to child rearing, my parents were of the generation that believed, as John Wayne said in the movies, "Never apologize and never explain--it's a sign of weakness." For various reasons, our parents were more assured in their grown-up-ness than we are. And coming out of radio days, they could credibly profess the kind of ignorance about toys and toy ads that men commonly claim when it comes to buying women's underthings. Not to mention the fact that they remembered the Depression, which they could invoke with convincing authority when it came to limiting domestic spending.<p>Maybe, too, Christmas threw my father into the same kind of non-conversant state it throws me into now. Maybe, when I wanted nothing more than to talk about Mr. Machine, he wanted nothing more than to escape.<p>And then, perhaps my father didn't really understand the concept of a toy that wasn't a miniature version of something real. After all, he grew up before the Great Toy Blitz. I came just at the start of it. Let us examine that significant year of 1963: the era of Mr. Machine and the last down Christmas for toy retailers for 30 years. In that year, Mattel's net sales (almost all of it domestic at that point) totaled about $96 million, or around $480 million in today's dollars. Hasbro's 1963 sales were $13.4 million--about $67 million today. Last year, Mattel's worldwide net sales, including the sales of its new acquisition Fisher-Price, totaled $1.85 billion. (Barbie alone accounted for over $1 billion of that.) Hasbro's sales last year totaled $2.54 billion.<p>The earth's population has increased by 40 percent over the past 30 years; the toy business has grown by about 500 percent. Advertising has risen commensurately.<p>For the period between Halloween and December 25 this year, toy companies will spend, at the very least, $1 billion on advertising. <p>My five-year-old, who watches up to two hours of cartoons daily on several cable channels, gets around 40 minutes of toy commercials--more toward the holidays--in with the mix. He stares at these ads as raptly as he stares at Captain Planet or Looney Tunes, and he decides he wants many of these things they advertise, these growling, whirring, grotesque, testosterone-fueled figures and vehicles. He also studies avidly the daily avalanche of catalogs that come in the mail. And he decides he wants many of these things, too. There are nice things in the catalogs--more so than on TV. There are science sets and magic sets and Lego vehicles that get even me excited. And he wants it all.<p>When it comes to Christmastime and toys, my son and I are peas in a pod. Like him, I grew up in front of a television. My generation, the first to have been nurtured on the tube, is also the first, where our own children are concerned, to stare ourselves in the face. In a very real sense, our Kids "R" Us. Unlike my father, I've been there. "You saw it on TV? You have to have it? I know, I know."<p>I'm in it as deep as my son. An Infiniti commercial can pluck my heartstrings, even if my American Express payment is a little late this month. It started quite early, this gnawing feeling: I deserve; nothing is ever enough. I've seen my five-year-old, time after time, receive a much-desired toy one day, then put it aside grumpily the next day because "it's not special anymore." He wants something new. Does this mean he's a bad kid? A spoiled kid? Have my wife and I done something terribly wrong?<p>Whatever happened to sugarplums? I'm talking, of course, about the sugarplums that danced in the sleeping heads of kids in Clement Clarke Moore's A Visit From Saint Nicholas. One wonders what happened when the kids next door came over on Christmas day. ("Whadja get? Whadja get? Sugarplums? Yeah, me, too. Only look--mine are bigger!") <p><p>As toy volume has mushroomed, toy selling has changed from an art to a science, with appropriately clinical overtones. The stakes are so high that getting inside kid's heads--so that kids can ultimately get inside their parents' heads--has achieved paramount importance. On the first floor of its corporate headquarters in El Segundo, California, Mattel has its own testing facility, called, with rather chilling corporate euphemism, the Imagination Center. There, behind one-way mirrors, executives and advertising people can watch children play with the goods and assess the sales potential. The children are allowed precisely one half hour in the center. They are given toys as payment for their participation.<p>At Hasbro headquarters, in Pawtucket, Rhode Island, it's one big room, also with a one-way mirror, called the Fun Lab. The children who participate don't receive toys, but they do get a T-shirt and a small toy, and as a Hasbro company spokesman tells me, "We know it works because the kids keep coming back."<p>The kids like it, in other words. Why shouldn't they like it? And why should they have any idea what they're actually doing?<p>It's all clean and corporate and not unworthy: The process addresses important safety and age-appropriateness issues. When challenged on the moral worth, the imaginative capital, of a product like--just for example--Kenner's The Littlest Pet Shop, the toy people can riposte with: "The kids keep coming back."<p>"I think Christmas is less excessive than it used to be," a Hasbro executive insists. Like many other toy people I talk to, he prefers that I not use his name: High volume equals high stakes, which equals high tension. Toy companies, in marked contrast to their product, are just as grim as arms manufacturers when it comes to back watching. "There was a time not too long ago," the executive says, "when things were bad--when a parent would try to make up for his or her own shortfall throughout the year, when people would say, 'The hell with the budget.' I think parents are getting away from that. I think people are getting more sophisticated."<p>Is this really true? And, if so, could sophistication--as in computer games and teaching toys--just be another way of opting out of talking with our kids?<p>"Parents are spending much more on their kids than they used to," says Selina Guber, president of Children's Market Research of New York. "Toys have become more expensive. You also have far more dual-income families"--hence more absent, and guilty, parents--"and you have baby boomers, who have fewer children and are more interested in educational toys, which are quite costly. And children are more involved in family life than they used to be--parents are apt to go along with what kids want."<p>How do kids know what they want? The toy companies tell them. Relentlessly. "Seventy to 80 percent of all TV advertising comes in the fourth quarter," says Ogilvy & Mather's Manduke. "Particularly the big-ticket items, like video games and accessories. Happy Holidays Barbie retails for $35; they don't even market it until November and December. Mom's propensity to buy a $35 doll just doesn't kick in till then. But in that period, they'll sell a million units."<p>Does Manduke feel conflicted about what he does for a living versus his own three-year-old child's still-to-be-awakened mercantile consciousness? "Absolutely," he says. "Yes, I'm concerned about the blitz of TV pitches he's going to encounter. There's no question that television advertising is creating demand among children. That's what we're in the business of doing.<p>"But I put it back to the parents," he says. "Parents have the ability to limit and focus TV watching and toy buying. They don't have to just walk down the aisle of Toys 'R' Us and throw everything in the car. The burden of striking a healthy balance for kids falls back on the parent."<p>He's right--but it falls so heavily.<p><p>I went to fao schwarz, looking for the magic of christmas past. It had passed. "Our serious escalation begins November 1," said John Eyler, president and CEO of the company, as he walked me around Schwarz's flagship Fifth Avenue store in New York. It's quite a store: a kind of toy-buying theme park, running at a jazzed-up '90s pace, from its giant robot elevator and its wall of video monitors advertising Nintendo's Mortal Combat game to its crisp, customer-beckoning displays for such big-ticket gizmos as CD-I and 3DO video game machines. <p>I remember FAO Schwarz from my youth as the very Temple of Toys, a pricey but creamily magical emporium, with a touch of Olde New York (and old Europe): heavy on the dolls, stuffed animals, and wooden trains. Any lingering resemblance to that misty old Babes in Toyland tonality is fleeting at best. These days Schwarz (which everyone in the company carefully pronounces "Shworz," rather than "Schwartz," as though to avoid any uncorporate taint of ethnicity) is a 26-store chain, a multimillion-dollar business owned by the giant Dutch conglomerate K.B.B. Miracle on 34th Street is dead. As if to emphasize this fact, Barbie's white fiber-optic eyes, on the big sign in the Barbie store-within-a-store at FAO Schwarz Fifth Avenue, follow the shopper with a cold technological insistence.<p>Nor does Eyler, the Schwarz CEO, bear any resemblance to some avuncular--or even flinty with a heart of mush--ideal of a toy-store boss. Gray-haired but boyish, smooth-faced and cool-eyed, he is the very model of the modern young chief executive. His business card has FAO Schwarz's rocking-horse logo on it, but that doesn't mean he's sentimental about toys. This is war, and he knows it. Yet it's a war in which Schwarz has captured what he considers the high ground. "Our merchandise overlap with Toys 'R' Us is only about 20 percent," Eyler says. "A third of our merchandise--take an item like Rockette Barbie--is exclusive with us. Another third you'll find at just a few specialty stores."<p>He looks me straight in the eye. "We do no promotional advertising at all," he says. The withering implied reference to Toys "R" Us's TV and Sunday-supplement insert blitzes isn't lost on me: The "I don't want to grow up/I'm a Toys 'R' Us kid" jingle plinks insipidly in my mind's ear. "We've never had a sale," Eyler says. "And the toys in FAO Schwarz aren't stacked up out of reach on shelves. Every toy in the store may be played with. Instead of spending money on advertising, we spend it on our selling associates. Our people aren't just salespeople. They're really expert toy consultants."<p>In confirmation of this, winsome, perky, stupefyingly well-informed selling associates pop out at every turn as Eyler and I walk around the store. Granted, the presence of the Big Kahuna can't help having a galvanizing effect--but one gets the sense these toy consultants would be galvanic on their worst day. They know their merchandise cold. <p>Things at Schwarz Fifth Avenue are heating up. "The month between Thanksgiving and Christmas accounts for about 25 percent of our overall volume for the year," Eyler says. "The Fifth Avenue store is open from nine in the morning till nine at night for the holidays, and by 10:30 in the morning, we're at full store capacity. A line forms outside, and the wait to get in can be anywhere from three minutes to an hour."<p>The preparation for this onslaught begins soon after the previous Christmas, in January, with cleaning, painting, and preventive maintenance. "By May we're beginning our final preparations," Eyler says. "The merchandise is in, and the primary maintenance has been taken care of. Then in July, August, and September, we install the holiday displays. By November we're ready. We install 40 extra cash registers for Christmas."<p>And how does this Christmas look for FAO Schwarz? We're standing by the foot of the escalator, where a big talking stuffed bear in a red BMW convertible gives directions to the store's various sections when the appropriate button is pushed. "Most retailers think it's going to be flat to 3 or 4 percent [up]," Eyler says. "On one hand, we've never been better prepared for Christmas. On the other hand, there's so much uncertainty this year--about the tax bill, about the health-care plan. My biggest concern is if the health-care issue lingers throughout the holiday. Uncertainty is the worst enemy of the retailer." We glance at the bear, which is telling a couple of openmouthed kids how to get to the Lego department. But if the bear knows anything about the effects of the health-care package, he is not talking.<p><p>You'll look in vain for holiday magic at Toys "R" Us. "All we do for Christmas is put in extra stock," says Carol Fuller, the company's spokesperson, with admirable bluntness. "There aren't any special aisles or anything. Everything is chainwide, so everything is the same." That's a lot of sameness--450 U.S. branches (a few more may have sprouted up while you read this article) and 208 international stores. The chain, Fuller says, feels its hot items this Christmas will be Playskool's Talking Barney ("because anything Barney sells," she says), Kenner's Baby All Gone, Hasbro's Baby Cries So Real, and--pushing many an average family toward, and perhaps past, its $400--Mattel's My Size Barbie, at a walloping retail price of about $129. And by the way, when Toys "R" Us announces its What's Hot List, it isn't just being wishful. Fuller can't remember the chain's ever being wrong about predicting a bestseller. "Our buyers sit here and talk to vendors all day long. It's experience," she says.<p>Isn't it amazing? The stores know just what we have to buy for our kids. The kids know just what they want. Seamless.<p>So here I am, finally, inevitably, with the wife and kids at our local branch of the Big T. It's a gray fall Saturday with spurting showers: the kind of dark day conducive to fiscal introspection and family quarrels. The Christmas season has begun. How can I tell? It's not the crispness of the air (the air is soggy) or the seasonal decorations (they're not up yet, nor, at the ever-functional Toys "R" Us, will they be); it's the stock. The aisles of the store, which in spring and summer often have a dispirited, depleted look to them (this is especially true of the video games and electronics sections, whose big-ticket offerings go begging when the holiday screws aren't on), are full to bursting. The place looks almost cheerful. Almost. If you look up, the corrugated ceiling is there to tell you what this really is: a warehouse. No, it's more than a warehouse. Warehouses are largely quiet and passive. This is a machine.<p>As we round a corner, an angry dad with a tattooed bicep has turned on his young son. "Let's get outta here," he shouts. The kid flinches. An inauspicious omen. Fortunately for us, the true pressure isn't on yet. Today is a day more for quiet contemplation in the aisles of Toys "R" Us than for the full-out, 12-hour mania that is on its way. Today is just a walk-through. The ceiling-high racks of stuffed animals stare impassively. The boxes upon boxes of Baby Alive, Baby All Gone, and Baby Check-Up await the onslaught. In the aisle devoted to the Barbie Shop--a billion dollars of business gets you a whole aisle--Army Ken at $19.99, Caboodles Barbie at $12.99, and Earring Magic Barbie at $10.99 are ready for the grabbing. Down in Manhattan, so are Rockette Barbie and Madison Avenue Barbie, each $65, exclusive to FAO Schwarz. The extra cash registers are in place. All over the country, the toys and the commercials are ready to go, as we the unready brace for the seemingly inevitable once more.<p>In a few weeks, at the last moment, my five-year-old will once again receive the final word on What He Really Wants. Last season it was Kenner's Bat Cave Command Center, a 30- or 40-buck bunch of plastic that, by the time I arrived at Toys "R" Us late one desperate close-to-Christmas night, was long gone. I remember staring at the packed, Command Center-less shelves in stunned disbelief: How, amid so much plenty, could the one essential item be missing? The single shell-shocked-looking stock person I was able to collar registered little emotion as he told me that the Command Center wasn't likely to be back before Christmas: What's Hot had become What's Gone.<p>The Bat Cave Command Center was missing at every store up and down the strip, of course, and I bought my son the Transformers instead, which went the same way the Bat Cave Command Center would have gone--into oblivion on December 26th.<p>But then, all at once, it hits me.<p>It doesn't have to be this way. I'm not the angry dad! <p>I'm not the dad who throws presents at his kid to feel I've done a decent job. I'm the dad who actually talks to my son, because I actually enjoy it and because he actually teaches me things. And I teach him things, too. So couldn't one of the things I teach him be that Christmas can be a few good presents, presents we could have fun with together or at least talk about? <p>And couldn't one of the things he teaches me be what he wants, and why? Because now that I think of it, just as my father never asked me why I wanted Mr. Machine, I never did ask my son why he really wanted that Bat Cave Command Center.<p>If he'd told me, I would have found it someplace. I swear.<p>James Kaplan's nonfiction portrait of JFK International, The Airport, will be published in June 1994 by William Morrow.<p>

