	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Moby Malls</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Across America in search of the Great White Sale<p>By Michael Lewis<p>In the decades since world War II, there have been two great changes in the way Americans shop. The first is the gradual shift toward a pattern of consumption that has little to do with the simple satisfaction of needs. The second is the sensational rise of the shopping mall as a place to satisfy this peculiar lack of needs. In 1946 there were eight shopping malls in America. In The Death and Life of Great American Cities, Jane Jacobs's 1961 classic on the decline of American civic life, the term mall is used only to designate any public space designed for foot traffic. Yet in America between 1970 and 1990, 25,000 shopping malls were built, each one more alluring than the last to the person whose only real need is the need to shop. <p>The prospect of 25,000 malls probably sends shivers of pleasure up most American spines. But there is also a loud minority of artists, intellectuals, and puritans who deplore the pleasures of the mall and view the modern American shopper as a kind of pervert. Having spent a good part of the boom years outside the country, I had always felt neutral on the subject. To get my fix on the modern mall, I would have to immerse myself in state-of-the-art mall culture. I selected three of the most famous malls that have gone up in the last several years, and I would spend two days in each of them. They were chosen for diversity--of place, of style, and of ownership. About the only thing they shared was size and age. These malls were new and they were big. <p><p>Horton Plaza: San Diego
Horton Plaza sits incongruously in the middle of downtown San Diego, looking as if it is dressed and waiting for a ride home to the suburbs. Built by the Hahn Co. in 1985, Horton Plaza's outdoor arcade is a delightfully improbable combination of Moorish palace, art deco studio, French brothel, and Florentine villa. At 1 million square feet, the shopping area falls right on the line drawn by mall jocks to separate the wimp mall from the he-mall. <p>What distinguishes Horton Plaza from most malls is not only that it has no roof but also that it affords views of the surrounding city. From the top floor, a shopper can gaze out over colorless, product-starved, crime-ridden San Diego and take pity on the people outside of the mall. This sensation is fully consistent with the intentions of the developer of Horton Plaza, Ernest W. Hahn. In speeches to fellow mall tycoons, Hahn has said, "The role of the developer is really now that of a sort of small city builder. He's no longer just creating stores and being the landlord." And in many ways, Horton Plaza does resemble a small city. It offers food, clothing, shelter, a police force, a government of shopkeepers, and even a curious form of citizenship--something called Club Horton:If you join, you may win $500 worth of free shopping.<p>I arrived at Horton Plaza intending not to buy anything--because I didn't need anything--but to watch other people shop.  Emerging from the parking garage were insatiable-looking types whom I followed for a while, carving half-mile loops around each of the mall's five levels. The huge majority of encounters between objects and people were flirtations that led nowhere. In Brookstone on  level one, two middle-aged men stood conspiratorially in front of a rack of plastic indoor sporting goods. One fingered the Hot Drive plastic three wood and golf ball set. "This is something else I use around the house," he said. "Maybe I should get one," said the other. But he didn't. Ten minutes later, a group of children gathered around a small, dark, sinister object resembling a miniature outboard motor. automatic nose-hair clipper, said the overhead sign. "Let's get this for the butthead," said one. But they didn't. <p>On the third circuit I spotted an empty bench in the shade not far from Lady Foot Locker. How nice it would be to sit in the sun and watch the traffic of freshly shod females. This innocent desire led to what I believed to be an innocent purchase of a copy of Lord Byron's Don Juan (to hide behind), which was on sale at Doubleday Book Shop, and a tall cafe latte with almond and chocolate sprinkles from one of the mall's many caffeine outlets. Ten minutes later a lovely lady in tennis shoes emerged from Lady Foot Locker on the arm of a man in a maroon and white striped long-sleeve cotton shirt that tapered neatly down the front and billowed like a spinnaker off the back. It was, I was forced to admit, far better looking than anything I owned. It looked, in fact, a lot like a shirt I'd seen at Abercrombie & Fitch. <p>I can't fully explain how, but this first tiny flicker of materialism somehow set fire to a Yellowstone of wants deep in my soul. Amid so many vendable goods, the ordinary process of free association was clearly fraught with danger. To think of a thing was to desire it; one desire led to another. Just as the desire for the good opinion of the Lady Foot Locker clientele propelled me into the Abercrombie & Fitch shirt department, the desire to do justice to the three new shirts sustained an hour in the Gap. The desire to alleviate the weight of my new shopping bags led me to a cafe the next level up, where Eric Clapton's new CD was playing. From my cafe table I could see the record store, and the flames leapt over from my inner fire trench and ignited another grove. I was off. Acquiring the disc, I remembered that I needed a disc cleaner. And that is when I stumbled back to Brookstone.<p>Now, no sane person would ever go out looking for the stuff Brookstone sells; indeed it's hard to imagine Brookstone outlets without shopping malls to put them in. Brookstone sells nothing but things that you know you don't need until you happen upon them in a moment of weakness: gopher traps, automatic nose-hair clippers, ultrasonic yard guards, one-handed battery-operated pepper mills, deer alerts, single-handed spring-action rasps, fast convenient garlic crushers, and giant bird frighteners. As I replaced the one-handed battery-operated pepper mill, I thought smugly that the world divides neatly into two kinds of people: those who have the inner strength to resist Brookstone and those weak-spirited souls who cannot. Then I laid eyes on the automatic beverage warmer. The automatic beverage warmer was a nifty electric square a bit larger than the bottom of a teacup. Having spotted it, I forgot all about the CD cleaner and realized, for the first time in 15 years of coffee drinking, that I was ever so slightly bothered by the shifting temperature of the coffee on my desk. <p>But enough of my personal descent. What grew clear over two days in Horton Plaza is that, contrary to popular opinion, the shopping mall has far more to do with spending time than with saving it. People may come with some goal in mind, but they seem quickly to forget what it is. None of the dozens of people whom I stalked did anything so simple as walk in, find a store, buy something, and leave. They arrived and set out in some direction only to be diverted by the design of the place, which required them to loop past stores they never intended to visit in order to reach their putative destination. The common observation that people in shopping malls seem to have so little control over their purchases leads others to conclude that they are being manipulated. But are they? <p>To answer the question, I called Jon Jerde, the Los Angeles architect who designed Horton Plaza. Before I was able to ask him anything, he told me--in the tone of voice used by one expert when speaking to another--about all the idiotic questions he is asked by laymen who think mall architects manipulate shoppers with sinister, unseen powers. As uninterestedly as I could, I asked him, What evidence of his ability to manipulate shoppers did these questioners offer?<p>"Oh, you know," he said, "the way the elevators are spaced out, thereby inducing you to walk out of your way and confront the beasties in the bushes. But look, if I was that good, I wouldn't be doing what I'm doing. I'd be rich. And anyway, impulse buying is just natural in our society. Impulse buying may be close to orgasm as the first reason that capitalists get out of bed in the morning." <p>What opened Horton Plaza to the charge of being sinister wasn't the location of the elevators but how effortlessly it gave you what you wanted: It was so pleasant to be inside. Then, too, the assault mounted on your senses by the mall fostered introversion, narcissism, and a certain lack of awareness. Why reach out when everything around you is trying to reach in? I found it surprisingly easy to sneak around behind people and snoop on their private moments at the sales racks. If people in malls so often look as though they are in a dumb trance, it's only because they are. Lulled by "Italian street music" in the corridors, seduced by the pleasing diversity of their surroundings, the shoppers give freer reign to their flightiest compulsions. <p>The most curious of these was the urge to acquire useless shards from the real world outside the mall. One of the most popular stores in Horton Plaza was the San Diego City store, owned by the city of San Diego. It consisted entirely of artifacts of civic life outside the mall: old street signs,  fire hydrants, water meters, traffic lights, fireman's boots, bus token machines. Just as all sorts of things become art when they are hung on a museum wall, all sorts of things become merchandise if they have a price tag. Since everything on sale here was at once worthless and priceless, the prices seemed somewhat arbitrary. The store manager had no idea how the city decided to charge $150 for an old traffic light. <p>Among the more popular items was a $30 sign, riddled with bullet holes, that said no shooting within city limits. One of the bullet holes looked as if it were made with a TOW missile. "What made this?" I asked the clerk. "I don't know," he said. "The police department takes them out and shoots them for us."<p>It was the end of my second day and time to move on. As I left, a delicious shudder passed through me: Here was an imitation of a genuine city sign being sold by a genuine city inside an imitation of a genuine city. <p>
Cherry Creek Mall: Denver
Not until you become one yourself do you realize how many signs and signals in our society are directed at the pro shopper. As the desk clerk handed me the key to my hotel room--in an Italianate Loews in suburban Denver--she said something I would not normally even have heard, much less salivated over: "We offer a complimentary shuttle service to the Cherry Creek Mall."<p>The next morning a friendly young man  drove me to the mall. "What brings you here?" he asked. "I came to shop," I said. That failed to impress him. "A magazine is paying for it all," I said. "All right!" he said, and high-fived me over the front seat. On the way to Cherry Creek, he described some of the many hotel guests who flew in from Texas just to shop at the mall. One woman--"a friend of the Kennedys"--came up three times a year from Dallas. She would ask him to let her off a block away from the mall for fear that she would be seen in a limo and charged higher prices. <p>I had a bad feeling about Cherry Creek the minute I arrived. It was spotless, white, wide-open as an aircraft hangar, and as free of unseen forces (that is, charm) as it was when it opened in the summer of 1990. On the heels of Horton Plaza, it felt sterile. The genius developer James Rouse has said, "Shopping is the most democratic of all experiences. It includes everyone, and a [shopping mall] is the most democratic institution in the marketplace." Cherry Creek shows what happens when the mall strays too far from this noble credo. It runs 1,390,000 square feet and holds 130 shops--give or take a few. But unlike Horton Plaza, it does not have much egalitarian ambition. <p>The source of the problem is the ratio of fancy national chain stores to small local shops. The Cherry Creek shopping experience is dominated by Lord & Taylor, Saks Fifth Avenue, Nieman-Marcus and Foley's. Such heavy reliance on the glitzy chains suggests anxiety in the soul of the developer, in this case the Taubman Co. It's like inviting a celebrity to your party because you don't think anyone would show up otherwise. This struck me as a gross failure of imagination. Shopping malls offer a sense of order like exists in no city. All stores open and close together. Everything in them is new and improved. The lightbulbs always shine. When you add to this the requirement that all the customers be rich, you've sacrificed whatever diversity and unpredictability a mall might contain. Cherry Creek was about as convivial as a hospital ward. Even the handful of teenage boys exercising their God-given right to hang over the mall railing and peer down women's blouses seemed slightly unsure whether they belonged. <p>Turning quickly from the department stores, I began my mall weave, ignoring the intense pantie vibes emanating from Victoria's Secret and landing in the Body Shop. The Body Shop complicates mall values by introducing an awareness of the world outside and a concern for people who live in places where they don't have malls. In the Body Shop you need a machete to hack through the forest of depressing leaflets about the rain forest to get at the colored soaps and erotic Japanese Washing Grains. <p>The propaganda seemed not to have the slightest effect on the eager American consumers who went there to shop. The manager of the Body Shop in Horton Plaza had told me, "The ladies go berserk here. It's like a bigger bathroom for them." <p>Now, if you go into any public establishment and ask the owner about his clientele, he is very likely to say, "We get all kinds." Not so the Body Shop. The Body Shop gets one kind. And there she was! The lone woman in magenta who circled the Cherry Creek store wasn't shopping; she was strip-mining. In 17 minutes she opened and inhaled 16 bottles, scratched and sniffed 27 soaps, and mauled five soft sponges and two Footsie Rollers. She bought one green sea-turtle endangered-species soap for $1.40 and left behind an ecological disaster. <p>The only place in every mall more intent than the Body Shop on making you a better person is the Nature Company, which has all of the Body Shop's moral ambition with none of its style. Inside every Nature Company store stands a meter that insists, absurdly, that if you deposit 25 cents you will save 90 square feet of rain forest. And--presto!--all of a sudden you have gone from blissful absorption in mall life to a sense that if you keep your change, you are murdering trees. <p>The stores themselves are filled, as you would expect, with books and trinkets meant to rekindle a love of nature. But because they are intended not to give pleasure but to make you feel guilty for having failed to save the environment, their net psychological effect is to make you want to run out and kill something small and furry. Especially when you are aware that some percentage of your donation will go straight into the coffers of the Taubman Co. Dour nature lovers sit at the back of the stores beneath photographs of endangered species. They read brochures, drink Rain Forest Herbal tea and watch short nature films of the genre known as Bugs Fucking to Mozart. I suppose it is true that we organisms are in this thing together. But the forced self-righteousness of the Nature Company struck me as a basic violation of the moral code of malls, which is: <p>1. Every Man for Himself, Especially During a Sale. 
2. Don't Park in the Handicapped Slots. 
3. Don't Eat Frozen Yogurt While Pawing the Merchandise. 
4. Don't Leave the Clothes in a Steaming Heap on the Floor of the Changing Room. 
5. And if you're over 18, Don't Steal. <p>It's enough to make the serious shopper run to Brookstone and buy a dozen of those vibrating lawn stakes that send gophers sprinting for the hills and make groundhogs quake with fear. Luckily, I had a plane to catch. <p>The Mall of America: Bloomington, Minnesota 
The payoff. The Mall of America is by a couple of million square feet the largest mall in America. When it opened last year, it was spoken of in the same breath as electricity, the cotton gin, and the first landing on the moon. The Mall of America likes to recite statistics about itself: 4.2 million square feet, including communal areas, 358 stores, 46 temporary cart stalls, 12,000 permanent employees, 12,750 parking spaces, 20 acres of roofing. To its credit, it has preserved the balance between small and large stores. And though it hopes to draw a third of its business from tourists, it has so quickly integrated itself into the life of the Twin Cities in the year that it has been open that it could probably provoke a popular uprising by closing its doors. The Junior League met once in the amusement park in the center. It has nine nightclubs, eight art galleries, and a historical research center. It has its own newspaper, which includes reports of unusual incidents in stores. The day I arrived, Bakers Shoes reported, "A lady from Nebraska was going to send her daughter back on an airplane because she didn't have enough room for her in the car with all the packages they had accumulated over the weekend they spent in Minnesota." Huzzah! <p>Jon Jerde, the Horton Plaza designer, also  had a hand in designing the Mall of America, of which he is rightly less proud. "I stood there the day of the opening," he says, "and I said, 'My God, this is not what it appears to be.'" What it was, he wasn't so sure. But he felt the sheer scope of the place somehow altered the people inside.<p>This is only partly true, I think. Along the longest shopping corridors that Jon Jerde will ever design, the two main beliefs that govern state-of-the-art shopping malls--including Horton Plaza and Cherry Creek --are simply pushed to new limits. The first is that the bigger the mall, the more it will appeal to consumers (and the more free publicity it will receive when it opens). The second is that the mall should be not merely a place to shop but also a place to recreate. About an eighth of the floor space in the Mall of America is given over to an amusement park called Camp Snoopy. And the stores strive to divert their customers in all sorts of seemingly unprofitable ways. For example, the Oshman's Super Sports USA store contains a basketball court, batting cage, archery range, golf simulator, and ice rink. After every meal I wandered over, shot a few hoops, played three holes, and took a few dozen cuts at a hard softball. <p>Anyone who has tried to fit a large bucket of popcorn between his legs during a movie knows that there are limits to the joy of bigness. The larger and more complex the mall becomes, the more it tends to mimic the society outside of it. Already there have been three violent incidents in the Mall of America: One woman reported a sexual assault, a man has been shot, and an off-duty Minneapolis cop was arrested for leaving one of the mall's bars and shooting off his gun in the fifth level of the parking garage. This is very bad news because one of the reasons people go to malls is that they are not like the surrounding cities. <p>What's more, as a mall expands, it begins to consume itself. It defeats its own purpose of putting everything you need within walking distance. The Mall of America raises the possibility of employing a team of Sherpas to pack your booty out. The only people larded with possessions, I noticed, were an overweight middle-aged couple on electric scooters. Their baskets were so full they could hardly see the road, and so they ricocheted off the potted plants and vanished down one of the long corridors to the envy of us all. <p>So for two days I snooped around the place struggling with my inner shopper and interviewing salespeople. Despite the fact that I didn't see many people buying much, all of the salespeople seemed to be "exceeding their quota." (At the heart of the American economy lies this paradox: Even while it is on the skids, every salesman is more successful than ever.) But when you spend two days in any mall, you acquire goods by osmosis. And eventually there came the most poignant moment in any pro shopping career: when the compulsion to buy more stuff requires you to buy more luggage to put it in. <p>Hovering over a black leatherette sack fat enough to hold a newly acquired mini basketball goal, I acknowledged my debt to all those who have done so much to promote the cause of insatiability. Truly, in this world, there is no such thing as too much. The woman at Bentley's Luggage & Gifts said that my predicament was considered normal within the some 4,000 walls of the Mall of America. That's why she was exceeding her quota. <p>Of course, when I finally got home, I found that I didn't much like anything I had bought, except for the indoor mini basketball goal. The human imagination imputes greater value to objects when they belong to someone else, and so we end up buying all sorts of things that give us  far less pleasure than anticipated. I am told that the purist postpones consummation. He browses. He fends off vampirish sales clerks with those silver-cross words: "Just looking." But the thing is easier said than done, especially when one has the capacity for deep regret. It is easier to leave the mall than to get the mall to leave you. In the days that followed my trip, I began to recall the many flirtations I had enjoyed: the olive sports jacket in the Gap ; the Bang & Olufson CD player ; the AT&T phone with the visual display; the gopher traps. <p>I am haunted by objects. <p>
Michael Lewis is a senior editor at The New Republic.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
