	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Po' Boys on Parade</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Po' Boys on Parade</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> PO' BOYS ON PARADE  <p>Ninety-four years ago Thorstein Veblen gave us his Theory ofthe Leisure Class.  Today, he'd probably wonder: Where's theleisure? Where's the class?  <p> By Richard Todd  <p> We have all been influenced by Thorstein Veblen's classic study,The Theory of the Leisure Classwhether we've read it or not.It was Veblen, writing in 1899, who gave us the term "conspicuousconsumption" and thus altered our sense of the role rich peopleplay in our society. I turned to Veblen not long ago becauseI was feeling perplexed about society, particularly about whythose in its upper reaches seemed to be letting me down.   <p> For instance:  <p> The New York Times Magazine features a cover story on DavidGeffen, a name vaguely known to me. He has a billion dollars,made in the record and movie businesses, and he rides aroundtown (New York) wearing jeans, a Gap T-shirt, and a white painter'shat turned backwards. He stops in to see his friend Calvin Klein.Geffen admires the blue jeans Klein is selling. Klein tells him,"It's the poor look. This is the '90s. You don't want to lookrich."  <p> I meet a young friend for lunch, a beautiful woman of (as theyused to say) "independent means." "I must tell you," she says."I have a personal trainer. Edward." "And how is Edward?" I ask."Well, our first session he made me do 500 sit-ups. Then I threwup." I was curious about how Edward, who I learned was beingpaid $60 for a 40-minute session, had made her do 500 sit-ups."He just yells, Go! Go! Go! Go! Go!' "  <p> William Gates, the richest man in America, has completed hishouse, a $35 million mansion. It is built largely underground.  <p>  <p>Before we go on, a quick Veblen refresher. In The Theory of theLeisure Class, Veblen, an economics instructor at the Universityof Chicago, perceived that the accumulation of wealth led tomore than material pleasures. Even in America's supposedly classlesssociety, there was a ceremonial quality to being rich. Veblenwas writing in an age that had seen the splendid excess of therobber barons and the formation of the great industrial fortunes,of gold dinner services and palazzos imported stone by stone,of Vanderbilts and Morgans and Rockefellers. It was his drollinsight that this indulgence wasn't purely self-indulgence. Therewas a trickle-down effect, too: Society's most privileged were"solemnly" obligated to demonstrate to their inferiors how tospend money.   <p> Like an anthropologist on a South Seas island, Veblen delineatedthe tribal mores of gilded-age wealth, laying bare the pretensionsof the rich in wonderfully ironic prose. Objects that might seempure indulgence, he pointed out, were in fact useful and necessaryas emblems of one's station. "Waste" was not waste at all, buta way of proclaiming freedom from want.  <p> And there was nothing more important to waste than time; thusthe leisure class. A suitable indolence demonstrated how farremoved one could afford to be from work, and from this followeda consistent logic of leisure time. Sports and games were valuedfor the nonproductive time required for learning them. Elegantmanners reflected idle hours of instruction, and clothes weremore attractive for their impracticality.  <p> What, then, would Veblen make of a billionaire in a backwardspainting cap, cruising around working the phones in his limousine?I don't know, nor am I sure what he would think of servants hiredto perform torture, or of captains of industry who bury theirhouses.  <p> In other words: Where's the leisure? Where's the class?  <p>  <p>One of the difficulties of talking about class in America isdefinition. Although Veblen doesn't specify the boundaries ofupper-class life, it's plain that neither he nor his readerswere in any doubt about their own location on the social scale.Not so for today.  <p> During last year's presidential election campaign, one got asense of the popular conception of the upper class when BillClinton found it acceptable to propose increasing the taxes ofonly "the rich"; to wit, those earning more than $200,000 annually.(Of course, the number has subsequently been revised downward,but that's another story.) Two hundred thousand dollars is alot of money in a country where one out of ten people dependson food stamps. It puts you in the top 2 percent of the nationsocio-economically, and that itself ought to qualify you to jointhe leisure class. But it's not my impression that many peopleearning $200,000 a year feel rich, much less leisured.  <p> Let's conjure up such a household. I see a couple the age, well,of the president and his wife. Theirs is a blended family, livingcomfortably on Russian Hill in San Francisco, with two college-agekids (by earlier marriages) and a little girl of their own whoattends a private day school. They have a cabin in Sonoma County,and both work. Nice. But not, perhaps, sybaritic. To borrow aneconomist's term, their TMT index (tuition, mortgage, taxes)claims about $140,000 of their income, and after items like insurance,food, and clothes, there isn't an enormous amount left over forLeisure Class dues. Nor do they have a lot of timein the corporatelife, it's not easy to coordinate vacations; last year they hada week together. Spent it scuba diving in the Galapagos. Swalloweda lot of salt water, got great slides. Husband came home witha sinus infection.  <p> Even at higher reaches, inside the charmed circle of the top1 percent of earners (entry level currently $350,000), life oftenfails to provide the insouciance that Veblen evoked. The nationgot a glimpse into a household well into the 99th percentileearlier this year during poor Zo Baird's 15 minutes of fame.Twelve-hour days, a long commute, and baby-sitter problems. Nota restful life. Tell Zo about Veblen's theory about domestichelp, that having a maid is a matter of merely symbolic importance.Tell Zo about Veblen's sense of the ornamental role of upper-classwives!  <p> Being well-to-do in America is a paradoxical business. Comparedwith much of the rest of the world and all of human history,it means being absurdly privileged, but it also means being harried,stressed. And indeed this is a condition that seems to have beenelevated into a virtue.   <p> Stress, not bountiful ease, seems to be the lifestyle lessonthat the upper-class models for the rest of the society; busy-nessis becoming our liturgy, if not our national religion. Idle hoursare to be filled with purpose. The New York Times reports thatthe fashionable aide for Hollywood stars to have is a "politicalconsultant," someone who can brief you on political issues whileyour trainer hollers at you. Suffering is chic even on holiday;one of this year's favored vacation spots is Siberia.   <p> Still, with personal fortunes now mounting into the billions,there ought to be a few people with time to call their own. <p> According to Forbes magazine's most recent listing of the richestAmericans, some 50 individuals (or family groups) now enjoy fortunesof more than a billion dollars. This is different from earning$600,000 or $800,000 a year as a corporate lawyer, differentfrom having a million or two put away. One billion dollars doessuggest, at the very least, a life of ease, with time to offerone's less fortunate fellows a lesson or two in graceful living. <p> But the thumbnail sketches Forbes provides of its richest peoplecan be disheartening for those of us who like to imagine thatsomewhere there are people who are showing us how it's done,illuminating through their purchases and their play, as Veblensaid, "what scheme of life the community shall accept as decentand honorable."  <p> Here are some phrases from the mini-biographies of the richest:"Shoots hoops in backyard," "I'm basically a peasant," "allegedvacation spot: Disney World," "works, on average, 12-hour day.Enjoys running, even off job," "Got to get to work. Got to paythe bills," "somehow I've gotten more seedy as time goes on,""flies coach."  <p> Flies coach?!  <p>  <p>The late Sam Walton, who flew coach when he wasn't piloting himselfin a light plane around his empire of melancholy discount stores,was asked why he didn't get himself a better car. He made a pointof driving to the office in a battered pickup. He replied, "AmI supposed to haul my dogs around in a Rolls-Royce?"  <p> Walton lived in a modest ranch house. Just like the modest housethat Warren Buffett, the billionaire genius-investor, still hasin Omaha (purchase price: $30,000), though, as Michael Lewispointed out in The New Republic, Buffett doesn't actually livein the ranch house. He also keeps a lavish apartment at the Plazain New York and a beach house in Malibu.  <p> And then there is Ross Perot, whowhatever one might think ofhis ideologyno one would confuse with an arbiter of taste. <p> It is my theory that something is going on with the very rich,and even with the relatively rich, that was not predicted byThorstein Veblen. For lack of a better term, let us call it CovertConsumption.  <p> Do not misunderstand. I do not think that human nature has radicallychanged, or that greed has been eliminated from our culture.When billionaires get together to play, they must still derivepleasure from comparing toys. David Geffen has a $26 millionGulfstream jet; surely this must give him some sort of snug satisfactionas owners of lesser airplanes step aboard ("Hi! Like my jet?Like my painter's hat?"). But stylish public behavior for thecontemporary billionaire includes a po' boy routine.  <p> In broader, social terms, one sees the same phenomenon in thecircled-wagons habit of the very rich. Once people built mansionsin the cities that generated the wealth; now they commandeerwhole other towns, such as Aspen, and turn them into privateplaygrounds.  <p>  <p>It is altogether fitting that the apotheosis of covert consumptionshould be the richest man in America, William F. Gates, 37 yearsof age, founder and chairman of the Microsoft Corporation. Hecommands a fortune totaling $7.3 billion. This is really quitea lot of money when you consider that the amount in excess of$7 billion would itself make him one of the richest people inthe country.  <p> Much has been written, understandably, about the technologicalgenius of this man and about his business prowess, but he hasnot been credited as a person of style, his style being the apparentlysuccessful effort to shrug off centuries of social expectations,to have no style. For the social historian, a figure larger thanlife. The Vanderbilt of today. But so covert is his consumptionthat we have only glimpses of his styleor lack of it.  <p> Gates abhors vacations, but has been persuaded to take them.According to "a former girlfriend," "one of our trips had a physicstheme. We collected tapes by guys like Richard Feynman and readall sorts of books."  <p> He is known for his personal dishabille. Dandruff litters hisshoulders. He wears color-coordinated outfits, of the kind hismother used to lay out for him in boyhood. Some days are beigedays, some days are green. Recently, though, he seems (on theevidence of a news photo) to have bought a business suit.  <p> He is, as one novelist has said, the best subject for fictionour age has produced.   <p> His consummate word of contempt is "random."  <p> It is his mansion that says most about him. This house, witha little less than an acre of floor space, is built into theside of a hill. It is virtually invisible. Tunnels connect manyof its partsits library, its vast garage. The land it lies beneathhas been rigorously inspected by the architects and landscapedesigners to make certain that only indigenous trees and plantsare present. As nearly as possible, he has built the house asif it were not there. Its statement is that it refuses to makea statement.  <p> The best part is the art collection. There is no art collection;instead, Gates has installed high-resolution television screensthroughout the house, on which he can access images of up to100,000 paintings to which he has bought the electronic rights. <p> One can see why he would not collect art: It's too random. Andthere is another reason, a concept of the cybernetic age: Informationis more valuable than the thing, any thing.  <p>  <p>Across the country lives another billionaire, the 86-year-oldPaul Mellon. He lives in a manor house on a 4,000-acre estatein Virginia. He does collect art, by which he means actual paintings,Renoirs, that kind of thing. He has fewer billions than Gates(two fewer). He describes himself as "picture poor." I see himsuddenly with a rush of pity. He represents an old paradigm:the belief that the world has an inherent order, that it's avast English landscape in which, according to one's rank, onelives atop the hill or in the valley, grandly or humbly, andthe more money one has, the more right and duty one has to support,conserve, and, by God, to own beauty.  <p> This is all fading, I see now. Mellon represents the past. Gatesstands forisa future of irresistible abstraction, lightnessof being, freedom, disengagement. He seems to reject the veryconcept of a social order, and with it, any responsibility hemight have to it.   <p> It ought to be a good thing for all of us, the Age of the UnpretentiousBillionaire, the triumph of the Anti-Leisure Class.  <p> Why then do I feel strangely nostalgic for the robber baronsof Veblen's day? They built their mansions foursquare on NobHill or Fifth Avenue, right out in the open for everyone to admireor mock. Their carriages had clear glass windows and they strodeinto their pews on Sunday morning. Nor were they busy or "stressed."They gave orders, sailed off to Europe for six weeks, came backto find the orders carried out. They had a vision of the world.Andrew Carnegie put libraries in countless towns across Americabecause he thought they would glorify America and Andrew Carnegie.John D. Rockefeller handed out dimesseed moneyto worthy-lookinglads. Their vision was not complicated; it was gloriously vulgar:Be like me! But in all their arrogance, and thievery, at leastthey acknowledged the rest of the world.  <p> I'm beginning to think, honestly, that Veblen was a little roughon the leisure class. He didn't see what was coming down thepike: people who would want all the money and not even want togive us a little style in return.  <p>  <p>Richard Todd is an editor at Houghton Mifflin, where he has hisown imprint.  <p>  <hr>  <p>Copyright 1993 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved. <p>
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
