				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Beware the Color Mafia</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Beware the Color Mafia</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Advisor  
<p>
 BEWARE THE COLOR MAFIA 
<p>
Today's color scheme can be tomorrow's headacheespecially when
it comes time to sell a house  
<p>
 By Margaret Opsata  
<p>
 As disco music blared, lady liberty and Uncle Sam announced
the finalists: H-Blue-O, Purple Haze, Kilim, Grunge, and 37 lucky
others.   
<p>
 A high school talent competition? An audition for Star Search?
No, a recent meeting of the 1,300-member Color Marketing Group,
a little-known organization that represents about a thousand
major U.S. manufacturers and dictates the colors that appear
on everything we buy, from apparel and automobiles to wall coverings
and washing machines.  
<p>
 The Color Marketing Group's stated mission is to analyze social
influences and "scientifically" translate the result into a palette
of 40-odd colors for which Americans will clamor two years hence.
After pondering such weighty matters as "the economy, the environment,
international politics, changing social issues, and cultural
events," CMG decided that in 1995 we should be swathed in such
hues as Manatee (a "medium-dark, muted brown [that] reveals a
hint of warmth hidden within"), Raintree ("this soft blue-green
leads us away from teal into a new level of sophistication"),
Artemisia ("a beautiful silver-green, a healing color from the
garden to bring into the home"), H-Blue-O ("an aquatic addition
to our palette, it speaks of clear, clean waters and inspires
new hope for the future"), Purple Haze ("spiritual and gender-neutral,
it layers purple with a smoky complexity"), Kilim ("borrowed
from ancient textiles, this sun-washed natural red links us to
our multi-cultural heritage"), and Grunge ("this gray-green reflects
youthful rebellion against establishment brights").   
<p>
 To hear the members tell it, theirs is a difficult, thankless
task fraught with peril. "If we are early with a color, it will
absolutely die on the shelf. If we are late, we only catch the
end of the color," explains Melanie Wood, a CMG board member
and corporate director of design at Mannington Mills, Inc., in
Salem, New Jersey.   
<p>
 In most cases, however, CMG's color forecasts become self-fulfilling
as member designers dash back to their drawing boards and specify
the newly selected colors for their product lines. Soon CMG's
predictions are splashed across glossy advertising layouts, paraded
on couture runways, even seen in Murphy Brown's newsroom. The
goal, of course, is to convince consumers that their lives will
not be complete unless they are wearing, walking on, washing
with, and eating from these "with-it" colors.   
<p>
 CMG and its members, who seem so astute when it comes to predicting
color preferences, grow vague when asked how long any particular
color will remain in vogue. But a quick analysis suggests that
colors selected by the group have a longevity of only one or
two years before they and their fanciful names disappear from
the leading edge. Indeed, not a single color from the 47 that
CMG designated for 1993 remains on the palette for 1995.   
<p>
 Of course, when you're buying relatively low-cost clothes that
wear out in a relatively short time, staying in style with the
latest fashions can be fun with no downside. But when you're
buying or redecorating a house, the stakes are much higher. It's
hard to think of anything that dates a home, and drags down its
value more, than carpeting and appliances in trendy colors from
decades past.  
<p>
 A more prudent approach is to make as few color statements as
possible on walls, carpets, cabinets, and appliances. "Keep these
neutral by using off-white, beige, or taupe, then add your color
punch with accessories: bright towels, pretty kitchen canisters,
matted prints, and so on," advises Kenneth Charbonneau, color
and merchandising manager at Benjamin Moore & Co. in Montvale,
New Jersey. "If you must use fun' colors, put them in selected
areas like a child's room or the powder room." When accessory
colors go out of style, as they inevitably will, the items can
be replaced easily and inexpensively.   
<p>
 Redecorating a kitchen is among the biggest challenges that
homeowners face, because kitchen color statements generally are
made not with $5 prints and $10 towels, but with $1,000 appliances.
Unfortunately, millions of Americans were seduced into buying
these appliances in once-trendy Harvest Gold, Avocado, and Coppertonecolors
that now are as old-fashioned as leisure suits. Outmoded but
still-functioning appliances in these dated hues can be repainted,
but the result is usually disappointing; true enamel paint must
be applied at high temperature under pressure, and this is rarely
done because of the cost.  
<p>
 Not surprisingly, some designers propose an "avant garde" approach"Surround
Avocado appliances with '90s colors that have some pizzazz, perhaps
a lightened fresco green and some yellow, then pop it with magenta
or fuchsia," suggests onebut people who don't want to breakfast
in an Andy Warholesque setting may have no choice but to replace
all the appliances, as they would when one finally wears out.
Anyone redecorating a kitchen today should consider only two
colors for the appliances: white or stainless. "White is definitely
the color American consumers prefer, but stainless is the better
long-term purchase," says Richard Holbrook, whose Pasadena, California,
firm designs appliances for Thermador and Casablanca Fan Company.
He points out that companies serving the European market, which
tends to be three to five years ahead of the United States, exhibited
largely stainless and mirrored-glass-plus-stainless products
at the recent 1993 International Appliance appliances at the
high end," Holbrook says, suggesting that white, long thought
to be a timeless color, may itself be on the way out.   
<p>
 On the selling side, homeowners preparing a house for sale should
resist the impulse to repaint and recarpet every nook and cranny.
"We all presume to have the best of taste, but others rarely
agree," says Benjamin Moore's Charbonneau. Instead of trying
to predict whether buyers would prefer Gray Moss or Cornmeal
in the master bedroom, focus on getting the house in clean, move-in
condition and let the new owners repaint.   
<p>
 When repainting is necessary, worry less about the interior
than about the front exterior and the entryway. "The sale is
lost if the buyers mentally reject the house before they get
inside," says color-forecaster Margaret Walch. Painting the front
door is an easy and inexpensive way to project clean-and-well-cared-for.
And if only one room is repainted, make it the one behind the
front door. When it exudes cleanliness and friendliness, the
prospective buyers will be predisposed toward the rest of the
house. They are more likely to accept structural shortcomings
like a narrow flight of stairs or an undersized bathroom window
they may encounter later on their tour.   
<p>
 When buying a house, new owners should encourage the seller
to take along any carpets, curtains, or kitchen appliances in
unfashionable colors. Doing so will rid the place of unwanted
hues and can often be used as a bargaining tool to negotiate
a lower purchase price, since many sellers are tickled radicchico
to receive the unexpected windfall.  
<p>
 Of course, color problems are only opportunities for the color
mafia. Some design professionals, like Walch, contend that mismatched
color schemes are actually "in" these days. "Happily, the whole
'50s idea of matching sets is a very antiquated one," reports
Walch. "The new color psychology is that things that are slightly
off are pleasing," Walch reports. Other designers, like Wood,
believe that old and new shades can be aesthetically blended
by using "bridge" colors. "Currently, for example, a soft, warm
peach would take us from the red/blue-based colors we had in
the past and move us over to the warmer yellow-based colors that
we are experiencing now," Wood says.  
<p>
 Bridge colors, mismatches, and avant-garde solutions; consumers
are no match for a group of determined designers who use double-speak
to defend their penchant for annually producing a new palette.
The odds are particularly stacked against homeowners who make
color choices they'll not only have to live with for years, but
will probably have to sell to someone else later. Since they
cannot win the color game, they probably should not even try.
Resist decoratiing in colors that are destined to disappear quickly
from showroom floors, leaving the home a veritable museum of
last year's art.  
<p><p>
<p>
Margaret Opsata has written about real estate investments for
the past 20 years.  
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
