	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-To Move or Not to Move?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jeff Blyskal<p>So, you're a San Francisco power couple making $100K a year each and it's career-crossroads time. Do you pull up stakes and head east to, say, New York or Boston? Do you stay put? Or do you just chuck the apartment in the city for a house in the burbs?<p>Tough emotional choices, to be sure, but they deserve economic consideration, too: Relocation can involve big cost changes in everything from rents and mortgages to taxes and costs of living. One way to eyeball these differences is with ReloSmart, a relocation software program from Right Choice.<p>To test this program, I imagined a San Francisco couple grossing $200,000 a year, paying $1,512 a month in rent for a 1,200-square-foot apartment, $1,700 a year for auto insurance, and $75 a month for electricity. A rudimentary financial profile, I know, but that's pretty much all ReloSmart wanted to know in order to calculate the big-picture cost changes associated either with renting a similarly sized apartment in New York City, Chicago, or Boston, or with purchasing a 2,000-square-foot home in Scarsdale, New York; Wellesley, Massachusetts; or San Rafael, California. (The software covers hundreds of U.S. cities.)<p>Chicago turns out to be the best choice. Moving there yields a rather broad-shouldered reduction of $18,000 in annual costs, primarily from cheaper rents and significantly reduced state and local income taxes. ReloSmart also shows what happens when that $18,000 is invested yearly in a vehicle that returns 6 percent for 30 years: It becomes $1.46 million.
Relocating to New York City, on the other hand, will cost the couple more than $23,000 per year in higher state and local income taxes and in miscellaneous expenses. ReloSmart doesn't define these miscellaneous expenses -- at nearly $18,000, they're the largest portion of the increased costs -- but I imagine that they include $75 parking tickets and $3 cups of latte. A potentially greater sacrifice: That $23,000 invested at 6 percent could be worth $1.87 million in 30 years.<p>ReloSmart is a good scratch pad, charmingly simple and useful in 
its narrow way. (Forget about multimedia dazzle.) But its limited range and power would prevent me from paying an overpriced $80 for it. Then again, I'm not planning to move anywhere soon.<p>FROM BAY TO....
The change in yearly costs for the model couple to relocate from San Francisco to: 
Chicago: -$18,487
Boston: -$4,824
San Rafael: +$7,504
Scarsdale, NY: +$8,229
Wellesley, MA: +10,521
New York: +$23,632<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
