	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Where is Thy Sting?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Where is Thy Sting?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Where is Thy Sting?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Columns  <p> WHERE IS THY STING? <p>Your financial afterlife doesn't have to be as scary as the fright-mongers would have you believe  <p> I can make you shudder with two words -- estate planning. These words trigger basic anxieties: fear of death, fear of probate, fear of taxes, and fear of lawyers.  <p> Only one of these fears, however, is at all reasonable. So gather your courage, and we will take a run through the bogus ones. <p> FEAR OF PROBATE <p>Probate is what happens when you -- ah, sorry -- die, leaving the disposition of your property outlined in a will. It's a procedure in which a state court supervises the executor of the will, who is responsible for collecting and distributing your assets. (Somethings don't pass through probate -- property owned jointly and insurance and pension benefits with designated beneficiaries.)  <p> Sounds harmless enough. So why is this process often referred to as the "anguish of probate"? Why all the articles, books, and even seminars explaining how to avoid probate? Because, according to the fright-mongers, probate involves exorbitant fees and unconscionable delays. Indeed, to hear them tell it, probate hasn't changed since Dickens gave us Jarndyce versus Jarndyce, a case that dragged on through generations, slowly stripping the estate of all value. <p> It is true that probate costs, which consist largely of lawyer and executor fees, are set high by some states. For example, in Florida and California, attorney fees average around 3 percent of the value of the estate, and executor fees in Arkansas and Wyoming start at 10 percent of the estate. The total average cost ranges from 5 percent to 8 percent.  <p> Nevertheless, most lawyers will waive the state schedule of fees and charge on an hourly basis. So even if you have a huge estate, if it is simple and your records are good, the costs can be quite reasonable. In New York State, for instance, a paralegal can fill out four to six pages of probate forms for about $200. Executor fees can also be waived. However, when the executoris a beneficiary of the estate as well, it sometimes makes sensefor the executor to charge the maximum, because this expense reduces the taxable value of the estate.  <p> It's also true that there is normally a period during which property is frozen and untouchable until the will is admitted to probate. But "horrible and unnecessary delays are unusual," according to Amy Bermingham, a trusts and estates lawyer at the New York City firm Ehrenkranz & Ehrenkranz. In New York, for instance, probate generally takes between one and four weeks. David Stack, a trusts and estates lawyer at McLaughlin & Sternin Millbrook, New York, says, "I can get a will probated in Dutchess County in three days."   <p> Even when probate takes a while, there are remedies, such as obtaining a preliminary letter of permission to administer the estate's assets. For example, just days after the chairman of a major broadcasting firm died, the executors obtained a preliminary letter that allowed the sale of company stock belonging to the estate.  <p> Simply put, probate is largely benign. Nonetheless, the anti-probate lobby, which consists  mainly of financial planners at banks and brokerage houses, relentlessly pushes its favorite alternative to probate -- the trust. Property held in trust does not go through probate.  <p> A trust is a legal relationship wherein one person holds property for the benefit of another. The grantor transfers his or her personal ownership of property to the trustee, who agrees to manage and distribute it according to the grantor's directions.  <p> The most popular trust is something called a revocable living trust, which, as its name implies, allows you to change or revoke the terms of the trust while you are still alive. Trusts do have some advantages over wills. If you own real estate in more than one state, putting that property into a trust will help avoid ancillary probate. Another consideration is privacy. Unlike wills and the probate process, the passing of property through a trust is not usually a matter of record. (In New York, some trusts, including living revocable trusts, are a matter of public record.) <p> But the drawback of a trust is that it is an empty vehicle.It must be funded. That is, after you have drawn it up, you have to put property into it: the title of your car, the deed to your house, your stocks and bonds, and the like. You have to draw up papers to assign tangible personal property -- such as furniture and silverware -- and change the name on your bank and brokerage accounts to the name on the trust.   <p> To be effective, every piece of important property should be owned by your trust. Of course, new purchases must be made in the name of the trust. Simply put, funding a trust is a hassle. <p> Trusts also cost money. Besides the costs involved in transferring property, there are lawyer fees to establish the trust. These costs are generally lower than those for probate, but not always. And some states impose waiting periods for creditors to file claims against estates with living trusts; this can delay the distribution of assets for several months.  <p> FEAR OF TAXES <p>Since most states' estate taxes involve only minor claims, this is really a fear of federal taxes. On the face of it, this anxiety seems sensible -- the Internal Revenue Service is very grabby. <p> Any estate that's worth more than $600,000 is subject to taxes. And putting your assets in a trust offers no special or clever way of avoiding taxes. Your estate gets taxed whether the property goes through probate or through a trust.  <p> Six hundred thousand dollars is not the Richie Rich figure it seems to be, however, because it includes everything you own. Everything. And once you start adding up all the everythings, you'll be surprised how fast the numbers mount.   <p> Start with your financial assets -- not just stocks and bonds but pension benefits and other retirement assets, such as IRAs; indeed, the face value of your life-insurance policy can put you way over the threshold. (The average face value of a policy in 1994 was $87,000; for people with incomes of over $100,000, it was $404,000.)  <p> Then add in all the rest: your house, weekend cottage, car, furniture, and other personal property such as jewelry and your beloved china-dog collection. "A lot of people who don't think they are rich make the mistake of thinking their estate consists only of financial assets," says Barbara Paul Robinson, a trusts and estates lawyer at Debevoise & Plimpton in New York. Moreover, all this everything is valued at fair-market value -- not what you paid for it. So any appreciation -- on your house or china-dog collection -- could easily raise the tally.  <p> The amount of your estate subject to taxes is the gross value minus debts, charitable contributions, property given to a spouse, funeral expenses, and estate-administration fees and costs. That net is called the taxable estate. Then various credits are subtracted from the taxable estate -- the most important one being the unified credit for gift and estate taxes, which can shelter up to $600,000 of value. The resulting figure, if it is over $600,000, is the number to which taxes are applied. And -- wowie -- what rates! <p> The threshold rate of the gift and estate taxes starts high-- 37 percent -- and quickly rises step-by-step to a confiscatory 55 percent on a $3 million estate. Consider what the rate does to the estate of Cain and Abel's parents. The taxable portion of their estate of $3 million, which is divided equally between their two children, should make easy millionaires of each offspring. Instead, the 55 percent bracket leaves the kids with only $675,000 apiece.   <p> But there are two ways to minimize taxes and thwart the feds: Leave all your property to your spouse or to charity. The first method, which is known as the unlimited marital deduction, is, in fact, unlimited. You can pass all of your property to a spouse without paying federal taxes. The second -- leaving your entire estate to charity -- also totally avoids taxation. These two ploys can also be used in a more limited way to reduce the value of your estate before the tax rate is applied. Federal taxes are triggered only when you want to leave property to anything or anybody else.   <p> The $600,000 credit, incidentally, is applied automatically, but you cannot take full advantage of it unless each spouse has at least $600,000 worth of property in separate accounts. (Joint ownership of property does not qualify.) Then the first spouse to die has $600,000 sheltered in his or her estate to pass onto heirs other than a spouse, and when the second spouse dies, another $600,000 can also pass to heirs without being taxed.  <p> Another way to unload taxable value from your estate and benefit non-spouses -- while you are still alive, that is -- is to take advantage of what's called the annual exclusion. This allows you to give up to $10,000 a year, every year, tax free, to as many people as you wish.  <p> And finally, there is what David Stack calls "the last, great massive loophole in estate taxes" -- an insurance trust.   <p> If you own your insurance policy, it is taxable; if someone else owns it, it isn't. So who should own an insurance policy on your life? There are two choices: somebody else, such as your children, or an irrevocable trust. The irrevocable-trust route allows you to leave the money to your children and your spouse.The trust must be irrevocable, however, because with a revocable trust, you have control over it and thus are presumed to own it.  <p> These, of course, are just basic ploys; there are fancier ones that your lawyer would be happy to explain to you. And this brings us to the last fear.  <p> FEAR OF LAWYERS <p>Although this anxiety seems justifiable, it's a waste of time. Given that the tax code is the most complicated body of law to see the light of day and given that lawyer-driven laws demand lawyer-driven strategies, you should think of your lawyer as a necessary friend. (I admit that this is a toughie, mostly because lawyers don't make it easy. Consider the following: The bound galleys of the American Bar Association's recently published guide to estate planning bore the oxymoronic, off-putting, but ultimately hilarious subtitle All the Law Every Decedent Should Know.)  <p> In short, fear of probate is unfounded, fear of taxes is reasonable but can be worked around, and fear of lawyers is misplaced exasperation. <p> Susan Lee, a contributing editor, is an economist and the author of "Hands Off! Why the Government Is a Menace to Economic Health," to be published this month by Simon & Schuster. E-mail her at sclee12@aol.com.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investment Strategies, Family Finance, Insurance Industry, Estate Planning

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
