	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Shelter Your Legacy</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Shelter Your Legacy</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Shelter Your Legacy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> SHELTER YOUR LEGACY <p>Single-premium life insurance can save estate and income tax <p> By Tom Nawrocki  <p> If you're over 55 and have at least $600,000 in net worth to protect for  future generations, consider single-premium variable life insurance. The set up is simple: You make a single after-tax payment -- from $10,000 up -- into a policy, then direct that money into any number of investment vehicles. All growth is tax-deferred, and reallocating your investments doesn't incur capital-gains taxes if you, say, cash out  of an equity fund to get into a money-market fund. And unlike single-premium variable annuities, the death benefit is income-tax-free.   <p> If you don't need to use the money and simply want to ensure that your wealth is passed along to your heirs, have a trustee buy the policy with your money; with this move the death benefit becomes estate-tax-free as well. But this option does preclude you from choosing the investment vehicles for the money. That responsibility falls to the trustee.  <p> Single-premium variable life insurance fell out of favor inthe late 1980s when it lost some tax advantages, but it still compares well with the more popular variable annuities, says Edward L. Bayarski, president of Montauk Insurance Services in Red Bank, New Jersey. "The new generation of single-premium variable-life products are actually significantly better than those available during their heyday," he says. Many of the new plans allow more diversification than they once did, with a wider range of fund families and investment products to choose from. And the policies are more liquid than annuities, with 90 percent of their value available as a loan.    <p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


