<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Paying Freight for Your Child's B.A.</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Paying Freight for Your Child's B.A.</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Kathleen Murray<p>Even if bondholders hadn't suffered disastrous losses and the average stock fund hadn't lost money last year, parents of young children would still be anxious about college costs. A four-year degree at a private college or university__never mind graduate studies__could cost over $130,000 by the time your seven-year-old goes off to school, based on figures provided by the College Board, a college cost tracking firm in New York City.<p>There may be a rich few for whom this kind of money represents an out-of-pocket expense, but most of us must plan well in advance to pay these bills. Mutual funds__particularly growth-stock funds__are still the best way to save for college over anything but the very short run, says Don Phillips, editor of Morningstar Mutual Funds. "Yes, you've got a little more risk, but you're also likely to get a better return," he says. The right funds can even help parents who get a late start accumulate a respectable pool of money for their kids. "The main thing is to get started," says Lisa Osofsky, a CPA and financial planner in Iselin, New Jersey. "Then at least you have a base to build on."<p>Dollar cost averaging (investing a set amount each month or quarter) can minimize the impact of market volatility. Most mutual funds have automatic investment plans, which draw regular contributions as low as $50 from your bank account.<p>The amount you'll need to invest will vary according to your income, your child's age, and how much of the bill you intend to pay. Say you have a seven-year-old daughter. If college tuition, room, and board continues to rise at their current rate__about 6 percent annually__her total four-year tuition will be nearly $54,000 at a public school and over $130,000 at a private one. To raise $130,000, you'll need to set aside about $7,105 a year until she graduates in an investment that returns at least 6 percent annually (to help you figure out how much you'll need to save annually until your child reaches college, see the table below).<p>Years to Public Private
college costs costs<p>1 $23,147 $59,398
2 11,911 30,564
3 8,169 20,964
4 6,302 16,172
5 5,184 13,303
6 4,441 11,396
7 3,912 10,038
8 3,517 9,024
9 3,210 8,239<p>10 2,967 7,613
11 2,769 7,105
12 2,605 6,684
13 2,467 6,330
14 2,349 6,029
15 2,248 5,770
16 2,161 5,545
17 2,084 5,348
18 2,017 5,175
Notes: Based on current $6,502 public and $16,685 private annual tuition, room, and board costs. Amounts are based on a 6 percent after-tax return and 6 percent college inflation rate. Each amount includes additional inflation costs incurred during college years. Source: Eileen M. Sharkey, CFP, of Denver.<p>That's a sizable chunk of money, which is a good reason for turning to stocks. Bonds and other fixed-income instruments may be less risky, but putting your money in bonds paying 3 to 4 percent annually won't give you the returns you need. Phillips's personal favorite for college savings is <a name="FUND:VWUSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VWUSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard U.S. Growth</b></a>, a large-cap stock fund with a $3,000 minimum investment. The fund captured a five-$ rating in our November cover story, "Best Funds," because of its low fees and solid one-, three-, and five-year total returns. Another reason Phillips likes it is that it's full of well-known stocks like <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Walt Disney</b></a>, the kind kids are likely to recognize. "It's a good way to share with them how you're saving," he says. <p>Washington, D.C., financial planner William Brennan likes <a name="FUND:MUTHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MUTHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mutual Shares</b></a> and <a name="FUND:MQIFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MQIFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mutual Qualified</b></a>, because in addition to growth they offer limited amounts of taxable income. We gave both these funds five-$ ratings in November. Brennan says, "My overall strategy is to try to keep the income down and focus on growth."<p><a name="FUND:TWGTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TWGTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Twentieth Century Giftrust Investors</b></a>, a five-$ irrevocable trust fund often used specifically for college saving, is also worth considering. However, any money in this fund goes in your child's name; once it's there, you can't move it.<p>What should you avoid? Obviously, speculative or high-risk funds aren't suitable for something as sensitive as your child's education. Save the sector funds, small-cap, biotech, or start-up company funds for money you're less likely to need. You should also resist the urge to try to time the markets. Once you've selected a strategy or investment, stick with it. If you have less than ten years before your child's freshman year, start moving some of your money into fixed-income funds. Jeff Merriman, vice-president of Merriman Investment Management in Seattle, suggests dividing your investment between a fund like the four-$ rated <a name="FUND:VFINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VFINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Index Trust 500</b></a> and a conservative bond fund. When your kids are within five years of college, consider short-term bond funds. <a name="FUND:VSGBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VSGBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Fixed Short-Term Federal</b></a> invests in bonds with maturities under three years and returns averaging 7 percent (we gave this fund five $ in our December ranking of the best bond funds). And don't forget U.S. Treasury bills. You can now lock in a five-year rate of 7 percent__not bad if you want a guaranteed return up to the moment you send your child off to school. By the time junior is a senior in high school, most advisors recommend switching to a more liquid investment, like a money market fund, to get ready for tuition payments.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Education Industry, Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
