<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Debt Doctors:  Angels of Mercy?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Debt Doctors:  Angels of Mercy?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Debt Doctors:  Angels of Mercy?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>Debt Doctors: Angels of Mercy? 
Why credit counseling may not be what it seems.<p>By Eric Tyson <p>After three years of penny-pinching, the Federal Reserve says consumer debt is on the rise again, meaning more business for outfits like Consumer Credit Counseling Service (CCCS), a debt-counseling organization. In 1993, more than 645,000 debtors channeled $1.14 billion through CCCS's 1,100 offices in the U.S., Canada, and Puerto Rico. CCCS promotes itself through advertisements as a "nonprofit community service." Many of its clients don't realize, though, that the service is funded by 10,000 creditors, 31 percent of whom are credit-card issuers. <p>The bottom line: CCCS may not provide the objective help debtors need. <p>CCCS sells a monthly installment plan, typically a three-year payoff agreement, whereby it arranges with creditors to chop a debtor's interest costs by as much as 20 percent (the amount varies by creditor). In return for a fee as high as $20, enrollees mail CCCS a monthly check representing the principal and interest they owe, which is then divvied up among the client's creditors. <p>Mona Jefferson, a 49-year-old insurance- company manager and single mother in northern California, signed on for such a plan in 1993. By that time, Jefferson (her name has been changed to protect her identity) had racked up more than $130,000 in bills, thanks to large family medical expenses. When the local insurance industry slowed down, she took a 20 percent cut in income, to $90,000. Faced with $12,000 in monthly expenses on a $7,500 monthly income, Jefferson tried unsuccessfully to unload her $238,000 home. <p>Attracted by CCCS's ads, Jefferson signed on for a three-year debt-reduction plan. For a $20 monthly fee, she agreed to mail CCCS a check for $3,741 each month. CCCS then arranged to have interest charges on a few of her accounts knocked to zero, but for the most part she had to pay in full.<p>However, CCCS offered help only with Jefferson's $130,000 in unsecured debt. It didn't provide her with much-needed budgeting advice, as she had expected, nor did it help her deal with her $2,300-a-month mortgage costs. "All they wanted to know about were my credit-card and credit-line debts," she says. End result: Jefferson could only make ten months' worth of payments, largely because she borrowed $28,000 against her 401(k) account. Even this wasn't enough. Unable to keep up with her enormous monthly payments, Jefferson finally turned to San Francisco bankruptcy attorney Harry Orr. Last August she filed Chapter 7 in order to wipe out $100,000 in debts. A year later, Jefferson says, "A more appropriate name for this organization would be the Credit Card Collection Agency." <p>About 75 percent of CCCS's roughly $130 million annual budget comes from the credit industry (called "contributions" in CCCS marketing materials). Creditors voluntarily pay CCCS on average $12 for every $100 in outstanding debt it collects for them; CCCS doesn't collect payment from every creditor. CCCS also pockets the $20 in monthly service fees it collects from consumers, which, along with grants, rounds out the remaining 25 percent of its budget. In addition, CCCS receives free office space in some locations. Until last April, the CCCS office in San Francisco was located in a well-appointed downtown space provided free of charge, courtesy of Bank of America, one of the nation's largest credit-card issuers.<p>Also, it is not clear whether CCCS lives up to its IRS status as a tax-exempt, nonprofit, 501(c)-3 organization providing educational counseling. Durant Abernethy, president of the National Foundation for Consumer Credit in Silver Spring, Maryland, says, "To be a member of the National Foundation they [local services] truly have to be a nonprofit human-services organization as opposed to being in business for money." Yet its practice of neglecting to tell consumers about all practical options is troubling. Anthony Mancuso, author of "How to Form a Nonprofit Corporation" (Nolo Press), explains: "For educational purposes, a nonprofit organization should be there to benefit the public and explain the full range of options." <p>Bankruptcy, for example, is an option CCCS does not fully discuss with debtors. Although its brochures claim, "We discuss all your options," in the CCCS video "Going Broke in America: Bankruptcy and Your Alternatives," bankruptcy is downplayed. Furthermore, the average CCCS customer is dangerously loaded with more than $19,600 in consumer debt on just $24,000 in annual gross income, yet CCCS advises only 9 percent of its customers to seek legal help. Abernathy believes "that the fact they've come to us is better for their credit report than going bankrupt. Bankruptcy is appropriate for some people. "<p>Jefferson's CCCS counselor never broached the subject with her, either. "Counseling implies a range of options," she says. "I was offered one solution, a forced-payment plan." <p>Many consumers know that bankruptcy filings remain on their credit report for ten years or more; fewer realize that debt- repayment plans can also show up as uncollected debt on credit reports for seven years. Jefferson says her CCCS counselor kept her in the dark about this, too. <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
