<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-When the Kids Scream "I Want!"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-When the Kids Scream "I Want!"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
That's your cue to start teaching them about saving.<p>By Neale Godfrey<p>What's the most important thing children should learn about money? "Saving it," most parents answer. The same parents, strangely enough, are responsible for America's savings rate, the lowest in the industrial world. <p>In any case, "saving it" is only partly correct. Spending it wisely is also a critical skill for children to learn.<p>Before your child can spend wisely, however, he or she must have learned how to save money. There are three fundamental reasons to save: emergencies, major purchases, and retirement. A child can readily understand the second reason; start your instruction in saving by explaining that.<p>To save money, children need a few tools. The first is a dependable source of income, from an allowance or work. They also need a place to keep their savings, a piggy bank or a real financial institution. And they need close supervision. A system that relies too heavily on self-discipline is all too likely to fail, just as it has failed from time to time in your case.<p>Start your children on an allowance by age three. At that age, most children are aware of the relationship between money and shopping. All they need to know is that when people leave money in a store, they are allowed to walk out with something they want or need.<p>An allowance should be earned for chores beyond the routine duties of caring for possessions or helping with the dishes. Receiving money is a natural consequence of performing work competently. Without chores, an allowance becomes an entitlement, fueling and energizing the "I want, I want" syndrome.<p>Don't pay half a week's allowance for chores half done. Make it all or nothing. But don't underpay, either. An allowance of 50 cents a week is way too little these days and may provide a negative incentive. Children won't work well for poor pay any more than you will. A good rule of thumb:a dollar a week for each year of age.<p>Once the child has some money in hand, provide three plastic jars labeled "quick change,""medium-term savings," and "long-term savings." Have your child put a third of each week's allowance into each of the jars. Quick change offers cash for candy and other instruments of instant gratification. Medium-term savings are for purchases that will require a few weeks of saving to finance. Get a picture of the desired item and paste it to the jar to remind the child why the money is being saved.<p>Long-term saving is important even though your children's idea of long term is probably next week. Eventually a child will understand that we all need to save for purchases or situations that are decades away, and by that point he or she will have acquired the habit of saving. <p>Encourage your child to save by matching each dollar he or she saves in the long-term saving jar with one from your purse or wallet. Kids don't have to understand the ins and outs of 401(k) plans to comprehend the benefits of a matching contribution from you. Be sure to relate your contribution to the idea of compensation for work done well, just as your employer does.<p>Three jars make a start, but you will soon acquire more: a taxes jar, a penalty jar, and others. An especially important one for many parents is the charity jar. At a very young age, children should be required to contribute to it weekly. Let them decide on the recipient.<p>Dealing with money occupies or preoccupies most of us for most of our lives. If we were ill prepared to deal with it, we can help prepare our children better. Who knows? If our kids do better than we have done, perhaps America's mediocre savings rate may even increase.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

