<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-A Debt in the Family</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-A Debt in the Family</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Taking the peril out of playing banker to your kin.<p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>For centuries, philosophers and economists - as well as people who actually know something about human behavior - have advised us not to lend money to our loved ones. Most everyone who has gotten such advice has proceeded to ignore it, repeatedly. As Shakespeare wrote, a "loan oft loses both itself and friend."<p>Don't even bother asking yourself whether you ought to help out the next time your best friend, your sister, or your son-in-law asks for a loan. You'll come up with the money. Besides, there are other, much more interesting questions you can ask yourself. Such as: Should I insist on paperwork? What sort of terms are appropriate? If the loan is going toward an investment, how should it be structured to maximize the benefits (or minimize the losses) for borrower and lender? Should I even assume that the loan will be repaid?<p>The answer to this last one, at least, is easy: No, you should not. "If you can't afford to lose the money, don't even think of going through with the loan," advises Stuart Kessler, a senior tax partner with the accounting firm of Goldstein, Golub, Kessler & Co., based in New York City. Accountants estimate that somewhere between 20 percent and 50 percent of loans between friends and relatives are never repaid. Compare these figures to the default rates on credit card debt: typically around 4 percent. <p>Some personal loans do get repaid; loans made for emergencies, for example, are usually made good. But more often than not, personal debts are forgiven without ever coming to the attention of accountants. Loans for a down payment on a house or college tuition are the most likely to be transformed into "gifts." <p>Business loans to family or friends have a tendency to turn into tax write-offs, anticipated or not. The high failure rate of start-up companies explains this tendency only partly. Such borrowers have a habit of considering family or friends as co-investors who know well what they're doing - that is, taking a big risk - and seem unconcerned about any obligation to repay. <p>After all, if failure strikes, the unfortunate borrower has lost his business; isn't that suffering enough without further impoverishing himself to repay his family or friends? And what are family and friends for, anyway?<p>There's some validity in such rationalization. Consider what happens if the business becomes wildly successful, another Snapple or Cisco Systems: Will friends and family cheerfully accept the return of their modest loans plus modest interest while the borrower's equity makes him millions of dollars or more? Will a warmhearted thank-you note or an invitation to dine on the newly acquired yacht really compensate the lenders who made it all possible? Not very likely, even if the same lenders would have been overjoyed simply to get their money back had the business floundered.<p>One way to avoid the otherwise inevitable hard feelings that come with financing friends and family is to negotiate an equity kicker or a higher interest rate to be paid if and when the enterprise succeeds. Just keep in mind that if the business really does become a Snapple or a Cisco, a higher interest rate alone won't satisfy personal lenders. Lacking equity, lenders may be satisfied only with outright gifts of very large sums of cash or securities.<p>Whenever you lend money to someone you love or like, formalize the deal with a written loan document. It can be, but need not be, drawn up by a lawyer. A businesslike agreement has several virtues. It adds solemnity to the deal and acts to remind the borrower that repayment is expected. A loan agreement also helps counteract the human frailties that sometimes transform such deals into disasters.<p>"Without a written agreement, people may have conflicting ideas about the terms," says Lew Altfest, president of L.J. Altfest & Co., a New York City financial-planning firm. "One side hears, 'Pay me when you're comfortable.' The other hears, 'The loan will be paid off shortly.' "<p>Altfest, as it happens, learned this the hard way. Around five years ago, he extended a large business loan to a relative without bothering to execute a contract. He now believes he'll never see a nickel back. The business is floundering, and the borrower pretends the loan doesn't exist, according to Altfest. That attitude is typical but quite galling nonetheless.<p>The most useful loans for both borrowers and lenders carry an interest rate higher than the lenders could get on savings instruments but lower than the borrowers could obtain from institutional lenders. Tax laws permit some leeway in setting interest rates on such loans. To avoid income taxation created by unrealistically low interest rates, the borrower must impose a rate that varies from 4 percent to 10 percent, depending on the loan's duration. Get a rate idea from the Applicable Federal Rates table published monthly by the IRS. In general, the longer the term, the higher the rate. "If you want, you can always select the lowest possible rate by structuring the deal as a short-term renewable loan," Stuart Kessler points out.<p>Such flexibility offers ways of reducing income and estate taxes. A parent could lend money to a child at, say, 4 percent, while the child invests it at a higher rate. When the parent dies, the loan becomes part of the parent's taxable estate. But the income earned by the child's investments will stay out of the estate and be taxed at a lower rate. <p>Lending to children gives parents a way to help out their offspring in the here and now rather than from the hereafter. On the other hand, most parents know that easy money can corrupt all too easily. Common sense dictates that parents lend only to children who have shown financial responsibility, although parents will undoubtedly continue to ignore common sense in that area.<p>Restraint can weaken the corrupting potential of easy loans. Your child could settle for the cash to buy a used Jeep, for example, as opposed to a new Porsche. Your heart will prevail, but consult your head anyway. <p>Most of all, be aware than lending money is more than just lending money. It represents a control mechanism in relationships where issues of power and control are potentially destructive in the best of circumstances. Those issues will lose their potency if you prepare to accept a loss cheerfully and to forgive the loan as a gift, if necessary. Be sure you're prepared - both financially and emotionally - for the worst.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Small Business Ownership, Government Adgency, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

