<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-When Kids Return Home to Nest</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-When Kids Return Home to Nest</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Avoid problems by getting them to sign a lease<p>By Neale S. Godfrey<p>Remember the empty-nest syndrome  - the trauma of suddenly finding that you've got the big family house all to yourself? To more and more people, this syndrome is becoming a memory. The National Association of Homebuilders confirms that fewer heads of households aged 25 to 29 now own their own homes compared with 1982. Back then, 38.6 percent of this age group owned their homes; today that number has dropped to 34 percent.<p>One reason for this trend may be that young people are unwilling to make sacrifices such as buying a home that is smaller, less luxurious, or in a seedier neighborhood than the one in which they last lived with their parents. They may also be less willing than past generations to move in with roommates or share their housing with nonfamily members. In any case, why should they sacrifice, if there's an open-door policy back at the family manse? <p>Still, there's one device worth considering that parents and children may have not thought of: a written and formal lease or an oral, more informal one. The lease does not require legal advice. Its point is to lay out rules, quietly and unemotionally, that you and your adult children agree upon. It's a working document between grown-ups. <p>Your child may actually welcome the lease. It will spell out his or her obligations and may even relieve some feelings of dependency. Even if your child cannot share the financial burden, he or she can help with the household chores.<p>Your lease should specify the amount of rent to be paid, if any; the term of occupancy; the proration of utility, telephone, and other household costs; car privileges; issues about pets and overnight guests; and kitchen privileges and duties. <p>You may reduce the trauma of working out a lease with your child by offering to help him or her get a job. Or you could go one step further and help design a budget for your child that will help him or her reach the goal of independence. In any case, if your children are living with you, you have a right to know their finances and how they plan to become financially independent.<p>If the lease doesn't work and re-emptying the nest begins to look attractive, parents can do what other landlords do - deliver oral warnings. If that doesn't get results, you could always turn to the courts and have them instigate proceedings as they would against any other deadbeat tenants. This is most certainly playing hardball: Both you and your child will be summoned to housing court to discuss possible damages, even eviction. Not pretty and, with any luck, not necessary.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
