<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Do Your Folks Need Money Help</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Do Your Folks Need Money Help</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Detecting the symptoms of serious financial trouble <p>By Jonathan Pond<p>Not until they reach their forties do most Americans become aware of this sobering fact: In all likelihood, they will spend more years caring for aging parents than their parents spent caring for them. <p>This is a responsibility most people freely accept. When the elderly need help, however, their children may be the last to find out about it. The trick is to spot trouble before it becomes full-blown. Specialists in family economics say that there are a number of warning signals. <p>--Changes in lifelong patterns of money management. Be on the alert for any sudden and uncharacteristic compulsion to avoid spending. It may suggest hidden money problems. This may be from a fear of outliving one's assets, but it is often a sign of something more serious. <p>--Increasing insurance coverage. The elderly are easy marks for dishonest insurance salespeople. Help your parents gauge the need for and the cost of any new insurance before they buy it. Be extremely wary of "pension-maximization life insurance," a single-life annuity product that is typically sold to pensioners about to retire, with the promise of higher monthly payouts to the beneficiary. A joint-survivor annuity is better. <p>Don't let your parents buy Medicare Gap insurance without shopping among insurers--premiums vary widely. Long-term care or nursing-home insurance is another offering to weigh carefully. It's expensive and often covers much less than buyers think. Consider alternatives to nursing homes, like home sharing, professional home care, and continuing care communities. <p>--Inattention to routine money matters. Paying bills late, threats of utility-service cutoffs, and filing income tax returns late or not at all are obvious indications of trouble. When one parent dies, pay special attention to the way the surviving parent handles money chores. You may have to take over. Execute a power of attorney or create a living trust; both allow you to manage your parents' finances without legal or management fees.<p>Advise your parents never to rush into a purchase or investment. Ask them to consult you on expenditures of $500 or more.<p>It's harder for children who live far away from their parents to watch for symptoms of fiscal dysfunction. Community programs can often help with housing problems and arrange such things as neighbor visits, deliveries of hot meals, legal counseling, and transportation. The National Association of Area Agencies on the Aging (1112 16th Street NW, Suite 100, Washington, D.C. 20036, 202-296-8130) can provide information.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry, Family Finance, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

