<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-True Consequences of NAFTA</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-True Consequences of NAFTA</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
There are a few details no one mentions about free trade--like how it will save the Social Security system<p>By Walter Mead<p>This is not the way nafta, the north american free Trade Agreement, was supposed to work. Its enemies--most quotably H. Ross Perot--predicted a giant sucking sound as U.S. jobs drained south into Mexico. Its backers painted rosy scenarios of new jobs on both sides of the border. No one imagined armed insurrection in Mexico with helicopter gunships rocketing the outskirts of tourist enclaves and army units executing rebels in the ruins of once-sleepy market towns.<p>But this is exactly what happened in early January. To mark the inauguration of the free-trade agreement between the United States, Canada, and Mexico, hundreds of Indian peasants seized six towns in Chiapas, Mexico's poorest and southernmost state. The rebels were explicit: Their rebellion, though caused by longtime poverty and exploitation, had been timed to coincide with NAFTA. The agreement, a rebel spokesman told the New York Times, is a death sentence for the indigenous people of Mexico. <p>That spokesman was perhaps a little dramatic, but unlike either the U.S. press or politicians in either country, he did articulate the true consequences of NAFTA. The NAFTA treaty is more than a free-trade agreement; to Mexico's rulers it is part of a planned national-development strategy that will change the face of Mexican agriculture and drive millions of peasants off the land. The consequences of this policy will not be limited to the occasional flash of bloody protest in the wretched boondocks of Mexico's poorest backwaters. Over the next generation, tens of millions of Mexicans, many of them displaced farmers, will cross the Rio Grande in a great wave that will affect the United States as much as did the immigration from southern and eastern Europe from 1870 to 1914. These immigrants will create whole new industries and--baby boomers take note--fund Social Security in the 21st century.<p>Anyone who knows the history of industrialization could have predicted all this. <p>Let's start with the demographic facts. According to the 1990 census, in that year there were almost 13.5 million U.S. citizens and permanent residents with a Mexican background. This was a 55 percent increase from the Mexican American population in 1980, and immigration is still on the upswing. Immigration from Mexico to the United States averaged slightly less than half a million people per year during the '80s, according to the Immigration and Naturalization Service. In 1991 that shot up to 946,200 new permanent legal immigrants from Mexico. To that add several hundred thousand illegal immigrants, some temporary and some permanent. A study by the Institute for International Economics estimates that total immigration from Mexico to the United States, legal and illegal, is now running at between 1.7 million and 2.3 million people each year. Even if all immigration from Mexico stopped tomorrow, natural increase would bring the total Mexican American population to 27 million by 2025. <p>But immigration won't stop tomorrow. If it simply continues at current rates, and if the Mexican American birthrate remains at its present level, there would be 74 million Mexican Americans in 2025 out of a total U.S. population of somewhere near 350 million. (That's equivalent to 80 percent of the current 92 million estimated population of Mexico.) By way of comparison, the Bureau of the Census estimates that by 2025 the African American population of the U.S. is expected to be 48 million people. <p>Will this really occur? Demographic projections are notoriously inaccurate; economics is perhaps the only academic discipline with a worse track record of prediction.<p>But trends inside Mexico that NAFTA will certainly accelerate give this prediction validity. Of Mexico's 92 million people, the 30 percent who work on the land produce only about 9 percent of Mexico's gross domestic product. Mexico's small family farms are much less productive than similar farmland worked with the capital-intensive methods practiced in the U.S. and Western Europe. <p>If Mexico is ever to become a rich modern society, most of these farmers will have to leave the land. This isn't anything to celebrate; it simply seems inevitable. In all industrializing countries, farms become larger and more efficient, and fewer and fewer hands are able to feed more and more mouths. In 1900, 39.2 percent of the U.S. population lived on the land. Today, 1.9 percent does. <p>Mexico's ruling party, the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), has decided that NAFTA is the way to speed up this process. As agricultural free trade is gradually phased in, more efficient U.S. farmers will gain access to Mexican markets and the price of grain will fall. This is why the Indians of Chiapas are so angry about NAFTA. The price for their corn will fall; many will have no choice but to abandon their subsistence farms. <p>NAFTA will also accelerate Mexico's shift to the kind of agriculture that can more effectively compete with U.S. farmers. Low Mexican labor costs will allow large commercial fruit and vegetable farms--modeled on the the enormous agribusinesses of California --to win a sizable share of the North American market for fruits and winter vegetables. U.S. consumers will pay lower prices; Mexico's agricultural sector will be more productive. Mexican peasants, however--if they lived in the U.S. we would call them family farmers--will be ruined in large numbers. They will have to leave the land.<p>They won't all find jobs in Mexico. NAFTA won't increase employment opportunites in Mexico's cities fast enough to handle the flood of former farmers. According to studies--prepared by pro-NAFTA think tanks, please note--the end result of NAFTA will be an increase of up to 10 percent in immigration from Mexico to the United States for the next 20 years.<p>For Mexico, this means serious discontent on the farms and in the slums of the big cities. Desperate farmers will stage incidents like the one in Chiapas. Urban workers will discover that NAFTA cannot raise their wages or improve their living standards if new unemployed workers swamp job markets and keep wages low. This combination is an explosive one in Mexico's history; it recalls conditions that bred the Mexican Revolution earlier in this century when the country overthrew a government following policies very much like those of President Salinas.<p>There is a small but real danger that Mexican unrest even on a small scale could start a vicious cycle that would block Mexico's development and plunge the country into anarchy. A few more incidents like the battle in Chiapas--next time perhaps with tourists murdered in Cancun or Acapulco--would make foreign investors nervous. The flow of investment would slow, worsening economic conditions, increasing social unrest and violence, and in turn slowing investment even further. <p>But forget all that. (I spelled out some of the investment implications of that scenario in the September 1993 Worth.) Let's assume things work fairly smoothly--that workers move without violence from Mexico's farms to its cities and then to the United States.<p>Gloom-and-doomsters, one of whom governs California, predict terrible things from the Mexican immigration. These soothsayers argue that given their huge numbers and the ease with which they can travel back and forth to the old country, Mexican immigrants will be U.S. citizens legally, but they will remain a separate people with special loyalties and a completely different culture and language.<p>Such scenarios don't seem very likely. Mexicans who live in the United States seem to be assimilating like previous generations of immigrants from other countries. They are learning English; they are entering American politics; they are giving every sign of sharing the American dream. That doesn't mean they aren't proud of their heritage, but it does mean that Mexican immigration is fitting more or less into the pattern of previous immigrations.<p>These new immigrants are going to be a huge economic blessing--a gift bigger than anything that the baby-boom and the X generations can even imagine. For shrewd investors, of course, there will be huge fortunes to be made. Tip for venture capitalists and wanna-be mutual fund managers: Spend some time in the bodegas of California, Texas, and the Middle West. Find out what Mexican-Americans are buying; find out which companies have learned to work in this market. If you've got capital to invest, help some of these small private companies grow and ultimately to go public. If you're a mutual fund manager, put together a portfolio of Mexican American stocks and send me a prospectus. This sector of the economy will almost certainly outperform the rest of the economy for the next 30 years; the time to learn this market is now. <p>But Mexican immigration is going to make money for millions of people who never put a dime in the stock market. All these immigrants--hard-working people who are very loyal to their families and very ambitious for their kids--will need housing. They are going to be willing to work hard for modest wages. They will save money to pay for education, and they will borrow money to build businesses. Economic growth is going to be faster than it would be without the new arrivals. <p>Best yet, from the standpoint of everybody over 20 in the United States today: This huge new immigration is going to bail out the Social Security system. That's right; cheer up. Mexican immigrants tend to be younger than the average citizen, and they tend to have more children. This means that--as long as we aren't stupid enough to put legal residency out of reach for these immigrants--there will be more workers paying into Social Security just when today's workers are set to retire. <p>Let anti-immigration countries like France and Japan worry about funding their old-age pension systems. The United States, this multiracial, multicultural, multireligious country that shouldn't work, but does, continues to attract immigrants. Out of our own self-interest, we should welcome these new immigrants, do our part to understand their goals and their cultures, make sure that we have a public school system that gives their kids a good start in life, and then sit back to enjoy the benefits that their presence will bring us. <p>Walter Mead is the senior policy advisor at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance: Jamie McClelland.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

