<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Keeping It in the Family</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Keeping It in the Family</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Tips for passing on a family business<p>By Jim Melloan<p>What's the number one problem facing successful family businesses today? For many, it's keeping the business in the family. Current statistics show that about 40 percent of family businesses survive into the second generation, and only 12 percent survive to the third. Says John Messervey, director of the National Family Business Council in Lake Forest, Illinois, "Passing on a business is like getting a set of golf clubs and having just one game to break 80. You only get one shot at it."<p>The foundation for a smooth transition from one generation to the next needs to be laid early, through clear communication and clear structure. To help beat the odds, the pros suggest business owners consider the following:<p>--Keep roles clear. Mike Henning, an Effingham, Illinois, family-business consultant, has advised the patriarch of a business to buy several hats and label them dad, boss, grandfather, etc., so that his relatives/employees will be clear on which role he is playing when addressing them. Several of his clients have taken his advice literally--he's seen the hats. <p>--Recognize that the dynamics of a family business and the solutions to the problems it encounters may not seem rational to outsiders. "Profit is not always a motive in a family business," says Don Schwerzler, president of the Family Business Institute in Atlanta. "Often the objective is to reach ever-higher levels of break-even." That is, a growing business may be able to increase salaries and benefits while still not carrying anything to the bottom line.<p>--Appoint an independent board of directors that doesn't simply consist of Dad's old cronies. All of the principal employees, family and not, should be subject to the board's periodic review. And the appointed successor, should, of course, be approved by the board. <p>--Send children to work outside the family business early in their careers. It will build a sense of self-worth that they don't get by going straight to work for Mom or Dad. In a survey of family businesses, second-generation owners cited this as the number-one factor in successful transitions. And it was the number-one regret of those who hadn't done it.<p>--Pay children according to their position, experience, and competence, just like other employees. Parents often think they should pay their children equally, but equal pay for unequal work and commitment can be perceived as unfair. <p>--Form a family council, and hold regular meetings where members can be clear about what they want, what they expect, and how the business has affected the family and vice versa. It will form the groundwork for the future power structure of the company once the current generation has passed it on. The more honest people are at these meetings, the better the prospects for a smooth transition. <p>--Set up an estate plan now. The top estate-tax rate is 55 percent, which means that without planning, the heirs could have to come up with tax payment equal to over half the value of the business to avoid liquidating it. There are many strategies for passing on a business with a maximum amount of assets intact, but they require time to evaluate and, in many cases, years to implement. <p>--Appoint a successor as soon as possible. It's best to achieve a family consensus on who the new head of the company will be. And not just the top position but the entire pecking order will have to be negotiated. Agree on a date when the new regime will take effect--often bosses will promise the business to their children but can't let go, and the kids will spend most of their adult lives just hanging on and waiting. <p>--Draw up a strategic plan with the intended successors for sustaining and growing the business. "You can't take it for granted," says Messervey. "You don't want to become the last wagon-wheel manufacturer in the state."   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Business
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
