<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-10 Tips For Parents</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-10 Tips For Parents</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
The holidays raise the stakes in parent-child relationships. It's an emotional - and memorable - time. Here are some guidelines for families to consider:<p>By John Koten<p>The holidays raise the stakes in parent-child relationships. It's an emotional --and memorable--time. Here are some guidelines for families to consider:<p>1 Listen to your kids. be aware that your thoughts about what to get them may be overly influenced by your own childhood experiences. So have them make a wish list--and ask them questions about it. Remember that the kids' gifts are for them, not for you.<p>2 Help your children feel involved. Give them a role they can play in the family's celebration of the holidays. For example, make it their responsibility to make ornaments for the tree or to decorate presents.<p>3 Don't be afraid to say no. It is often the answer children really wants to hear, especially around the holidays, when they are prone to overstimulation. As long as "no" is a considered response, they'll view it as a sign of strength and feel reassured that their parents are, in fact, willing to be parents. <p>
4 Dismissing a child's request out of hand may mean missing a more important message. Unreasonable demands are often a cue to ask your kids, "What's going on?"<p>
5 Holiday presents shouldn't be undermined by threats to use them as a disciplinary tool. There are better ways to let your kids know if they are being naughty or nice. Taking a gift away--or conditioning it on a certain type of behavior--destroys the whole message of the holidays.<p>6 It's important for children to have a chance to learn the joys of giving. But they often need a lot of help to give gifts they can feel proud of. Take an active role as their assistant.<p>
7 Help your children develop skills as consumers by showing them how to evaluate the merits of the things they ask for. Talk them through their choices. Will the attractive toy shown on television really do what it says it will do? Don't just make these decisions for them.<p>
8 Telling your children they can't have something because "it costs too much" runs the risk of making them anxious about their own worth or about the state of the family's finances. It's better to explain why they can't have something in terms of limits. Educate them about prudence and wastefulness. Also remember that while you may appreciate how difficult money is to come by, your kids probably don't.<p>
9 Understand the role of peer pressure in your child's requests. This is a good opportunity to listen to your son or daughter's feelings about their relationships with friends. Competing with other parents in gift giving isn't a solution.<p>
10 Preserve the magic of the holidays. Traditions help a child to better understand the true spirit of giving and receiving.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
