	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-"Tell My Mom I Need It"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>
Marbles, no! Barbie, yes! The kids weigh in.<p>by Will Dana<p>When it comes to christmas, kids aren't playing around. They know what toys are out there and exactly how much they cost, and on the whole, they'd rather be playing video games."If you really want something," said Brian, ten, "you got to know what it costs. You watch for the price to go down, then you ask for it."<p>Brian was one of two dozen toy experts consulted recently during a long afternoon of hard play and frank talk. With the help of Creative & Response Research, a Chicago-based firm specializing in focus groups, we gathered a carefully screened sample of 7-to-11-year-olds, put them in a room decked out with the year's top playthings, and waited for them to do what kids do best: make spontaneous, wise-beyond-their-years comments. From behind a wall of one-way mirrors, we noted their reactions. It was like a cross between Romper Room and a Skinner box.<p>The girls were more at home with traditional toys; the boys went for anything that came in a large box or looked like it was from outer space. The one mechanized girls' item we screened, Baby Walk 'n Roll, Mattel's high-end, remote-controlled walker doll, was generally sniffed at. The older girls thought it was too young for them. Only a girl from the younger group said she loved it. "I like to control things," she said.<p>Happy Holidays Barbie--cloaked in a red dress that even Liberace might have found garish--managed to jump the age barrier, as Barbies have for almost 35 years. She was hands-down the most popular toy among both the 7-to-8-year-old and 10-to-11-year-old girls. Colleen, an intense, quiet 8-year-old, regarded the doll as an object of transfiguring awe. "You're supposed to keep them in the box and never touch them," she said. "It costs like $30," said Adrienne (she was $3 low). "It could be worth a lot when you're 30 or 20."<p>Thirty dollars happened to be the price at which most of the girls considered a toy out of reach. The boys had more expensive tastes; their price threshold hovered around $50 or $60--the price of a typical video game cartridge. Almost all of the boys had at least one video game system, Nintendo or Sega. (Luckily for their parents, none seemed aware of the new $700 Panasonic 3DO system.) Brian and Kevin said they each get about ten new video games a year. <p>The boys' favorite was the biggest and most expensive toy in room, the Jurassic Park Command Compound Playset, which costs $50. It was so big you'd have to have a redwood tree in the living room to get it under. "Tell my mom I need it," urged Justin, who is eight. Kevin offered that he "would throw my Nintendo out the window for it." Though size counts, it doesn't guarantee satisfaction. When it was time to play with the toys, the boys soon abandoned the Jurassic Park monolith in order to shoot each other with a Nerf Master-Blaster, a portable missile launcher that shoots small foam smart bombs with special-forces-caliber speed and accuracy.<p>At the end of the session, we ushered in the parents to see how well they could predict what their child had put at the top of the most-wanted list. Only one parent guessed right; the average mom or dad was a month or two behind on the wish list. When one mother was informed that her son desperately wanted Sonic the Hedgehog, she looked at him quizzically and said, "I thought you told me you had enough video games." It wasn't that parent and child weren't communicating: Mom and Dad had just heard enough.<p>Amid the shower of whizzing Nerf balls and electronically synthesized dinosaur whoops, Nick, a stocky 11-year-old in a Bulls sweatshirt, looked over a small sack of marbles as if they were disease carriers from another planet. "What are these?" he asked suspiciously. "Do they bounce?"<p> <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
