<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-A Toy's Path to Holiday Stardom</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-A Toy's Path to Holiday Stardom</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Dolls may look like cheap plastic, but that cheap plastic takes years of intricate planning to create and package. Between a doll's conception and its selling point, there's a lot more than meets the plastic-lidded, spring-loaded eye. This is the story of one such product: <a name="NYSE:MAT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10966"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mattel</b></a>'s Baby Walk 'n Roll. <p>By Russell Miller.<p>1. A NEAT IDEA!
July 1991: Freelance toy inventor Larry Blaustein arrives at Mattel Toys headquarters in El Segundo, California, to pitch his idea for a doll that scoots around in a radio-controlled walker. His timing is perfect. Mattel executives are looking to fill their high-end large-doll slot for Christmas 1993. They want something cute. Something that looks zippy on TV. Something that'll sell for about $30 wholesale.<p>2. THE GREEN LIGHT
September 1991: Mattel decides that the walker-doll is telegenic and, moreover, that it might be a good time for dolls to evolve into the realm of radio control. On September 10, Blaustein is told his idea is a sell.<p>3. BABY GETS A NAME
What's an experimental prototype without a secret moniker? From on high comes the order: Blaustein's doll, for the time being, shall be known as "R.C. Walker."<p>4. A VISIT FROM REAL LIVE KIDS
Early 1992: Marketers peer through one-way mirrors as little girls are interrogated about toys. In what Mattel calls "viability tests," kids and their moms watch mock commercials for various products, then are set loose in the aisles of make-believe stores, using play money to "buy" the toys they want most. R.C. Walker is declared huggable.<p>5. A VOTE OF CONFIDENCE
On March 12, Mattel president and COO Jill Barad puts her seal of approval on the cheery lass. R.C. Walker will be the lead large doll for Christmas 1993.<p>6. THE PRICE IS SET
Through the spring and summer, engineers tinker with R.C. Walker prototypes. They disguise the radio- control unit as a pink heart. Designers also try out a "giggle feature"--a tiny sound box built into the walker. The innovations test well: Mattel sets the doll's wholesale price at $44.99.<p>7. ADVICE FROM FRIENDS
Summer 1992: Representatives of major retail chains trek to Mattel to offer suggestions. "We give them input," says Melody Young, a buyer for Toys "R" Us. "The hair, the face sculpting, the outfits, accessories--that kind of thing." Given the fact that Kmart, Target, Wal-Mart, and Toys "R" Us make up a full 70 percent of the company's U.S. business, Mattel listens.<p>8. PRIMPING AND PREENING
Fall 1992: The doll assumes its final form. The radio controller is overhauled again, morphing into a rattle shape intended to bring out the nurturing mommy that's hiding inside every little girl. The name R.C. Walker, perhaps because it sounds more like a rural sheriff than someone in need of hugs, is changed to Baby Walk 'n Roll.<p>9. THE PRICE FALLS
Fall '92: To reflect the most recent read on consumer tolerance, the doll's price has been scaled back to $39.99. A factory in Hong Kong begins to stockpile plastic baby parts.<p>10. SHE IS NOT ALONE
All is not well for Baby Walk 'n Roll. In the wee world of toy marketing, there are whispers on everybody's lips; Tyco has spawned its own walker doll for Christmas 1993. It costs only $29.99 wholesale.<p>11. A DAY AT THE FAIR
February 1993: Baby Walk 'n Roll meets the press at the American Toy Fair in Manhattan. For the first time, the Mattel doll goes head-to-head with its evil twin: Tyco's Baby Giggles 'n Go. Baby Walk 'n Roll is tough plastic; Giggles 'n Go is more huggably soft (if you ignore the seemingly bulletproof abdomen where her batteries are housed). Walk 'n Roll makes a giggle and a squeal, both of which issue from her walker; Giggles 'n Go has just the little giggle--but it comes from her very own tummy! <p>12. IT'S A GIRL!
September 1993: Baby Walk 'n Roll is alive--at least in the form of TV commercials scattered throughout the Saturday morning kiddie programs and on Nickelodeon. The ad has the doll being brought to show-and-tell at an elementary school (a school that, by the looks of it, has been overrun by teenage actors). "Right," sneers one boy. "Like there's a baby with radio control?" Within 20-odd seconds, though, the young cynic is won over, thus legitimizing the doll for four-to-eight-year-old girls across the country.<p>13. ONE THOUSAND THOUSAND DARLINGS
Mattel declines to specify exact numbers, but probably about one million Baby Walk 'n Rolls have been produced--a legion of dolls the size of Milwaukee. The goal: "Clean sell-through"--the blessed state where every unit finds a home. Unless the doll, which retails between $45 and $50, is incredibly successful, it will never be manufactured again. <p>14. WAR
The campaign is in full swing. Between Thanksgiving and Christmas, <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald</b></a>'s Happy Meals carry Baby Walk 'n Roll coupons on every bag. Meanwhile, Mattel operatives monitor toy stores across the country, beaming sales info back to the war rooms in El Segundo, where marketing execs stand ready to launch last-minute emergency promotions.<p>15. IT'S CHRISTMAS
December 1993: Even if Baby Walk 'n Roll is a modest success, it will pull in more than $30 million before passing from the stage. Next year at this time, while hundreds of thousands of walker babies stare spookily from the corners of dusty attics, an all new, visually exciting Mattel baby will be haunting young female minds. In El Segundo, they're already playing with it.<p> <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
