<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Assistance From a Distance</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Assistance From a Distance</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
If you can't be on hand when your parents are in need, here are some ways to help<p>By Mary Rowland<p>Angela heath, a gerontologist in New Carrollton, Maryland, recently wrote a book called Long Distance Caregiving: A Survival Guide for Faraway Caregivers. The book provides excellent advice on how to care for an ailing relative who lives far away. When her grandmother in Cincinnati suffered a stroke last spring, Heath followed all her own advice, hooked into the elder-support networks in the area, and made two trips to Cincinnati, where her parents also live. <p>Heath did all the right things. So why does she still feel so guilty? "For me the guilt has to do with not being able to give the necessary emotional support to my mother and grandmother," Heath said. "I feel bad because they always love when I come home, and I'm so busy I can't go often enough. I feel guilty because I do this for other people all the time, and yet I haven't been able to provide my own family with what they need."<p>And so it goes. An objective observer would say that Heath has done a great job marshaling resources for her grandmother. But when it comes to our own particular family situations, logic deserts us. Few things make us feel so emotional--and so guilty--as the suspicion that we are not doing all we should for those who count on us. <p>When experts like Heath fall prey to these destructive feelings, we can all take heart. But Heath's experience should also remind us that we need to educate ourselves on caring for distant relatives. It helps to be prepared. <p>Dee Lee is another elder-care specialist who recently had the opportunity to put her expertise to work. Lee has spent the past ten years as a financial planner for the elderly in Harvard Massachusetts. In August, her husband's mother, 82 and crippled with arthritis, fell in her home in St. Petersburg, Florida. Lee's father-in-law, who is 87, was rushed to the hospital with a bleeding ulcer<p>Lee and her husband, Doug, were faced with the decision of whether to move the couple to a nursing home. "If they would only come to New England, I could get them great services," Lee says. "But they don't want to do that. And it is so frustrating to try to deal with a traumatic situation 1,000 miles away."<p>Although it's never possible to remove all emotion from such a situation, there are things that long-distance caregivers can do to improve their chances of dealing effectively with a crisis. "Get smart on all the options before a crisis hits," advises Marie Lipari, a work/family consultant at Hewitt Associates in Lincolnshire, Illinois. "Many times, when elder-care needs arise, it happens very quickly." <p>Heath's book, published by Upper Access Books, She tells you how to tap into the aging-care network by calling Eldercare Locator Services (800-677-1116). The network provides a wealth of information. Sometimes all you need to do is describe your situation, and they can tell you what you need and what's available in your area. Heath suggests organizing your files into six areas:<p>Assessment--keeping notes on your parents' condition. <p>Medical Information--should include data on doctors, insurance policies, medications.<p>Travel--organizing your visits.<p>Community Resources--a formal network of available support services. <p>Informal Network--a list of friends, neighbors, doctors, and others who might be needed in the future.<p>Legal, Financial, and Insurance--should include your parents' attorney, banker, financial planner, insurance agent, legal documents, Social Security numbers, and location of wills and other important papers.<p>Employers can also help. "About 15 percent of companies offer a resource and referral service for elder care," Lipari says. In most cases, there is a toll-free number where you can get details on services available in your parents' community. Many employers--about 81 percent--also offer employee-assistance programs. Some of them include elder-care referral services. You may also get counseling sessions for yourself at no charge.<p>When working out these plans, be careful not to make decisions for the individuals involved. Ask them their preferences. Do they want to remain at home? Most elderly Americans do. In that case, finding the services to make that possible should be high on your list. "It's important that older adults maintain control over their lives," says Joan E. Mintz, a New York gerontologist and former deputy director of the New Jersey Division on Aging. "Even if Mom loses her keys once in a while, the family shouldn't make a decision that she can't drive anymore. Mom should be part of any decision that is made about her."<p>It is also wise to plan how you are going to talk to your parents about these issues. "If your mother is very independent but she breaks her hip, that doesn't affect her mind," says Heath. "You can talk things through with her and plan together what you will do." That approach won't work, though, with a parent who has a mental deficiency or is dependent and shies away from decisions. "Then you may have to take the lead and say, 'Let me help. I'll feel better when we have this settled,'" says Heath.<p>The holiday season can be a good time for families to get started on parental-care planning, but some work must be done in advance. If a number of siblings will be home for the holidays, discuss the plans in advance. Caring for an elderly relative can cause extreme tension between other family members because everyone typically has a different idea of what should be done and how. <p>In Heath's family, there is something of a natural division of labor. Her brother, who is financially successful, takes care of the money issues. Heath, because of her expertise, is responsible for the research. One unmarried sister, who lives in Cincinnati, does the on-the-spot follow-through. And a third sister assists the other two whenever necessary.<p>To make a holiday meeting more productive, consider taking the following steps beforehand:<p>Get a phone book for your relative's city.<p>Conduct a conference call with other family members. Discuss the agenda for your meeting.<p>If one of your parents has a health problem, schedule an appointment with his or her physician while you're in town.<p>Make a list of friends and relatives you can visit who might be part of an informal network willing to check on your parent when you're not around. If your parent is ailing, you might make arrangements with some of them to stop in once a week for lunch or a chat.<p> Schedule an appointment with a minister, priest, rabbi, or someone else who is close to your parents. Find out what social activities your parent attends. See if the church or synagogue has special resources that can provide support when you need it. Many churches have volunteers who take elderly people grocery shopping or drop in for regular visits.<p> If your parents are over 65, they are eligible to belong to the local council on aging, .a support group that may go by different names in different communities. Call for information on the type of activities this group sponsors.<p> Stop in at your local library. The librarian often has a good idea of what is going on in town and what resources are available.<p>Keep your eyes and ears open. Help may come from the most unexpected places. For instance, Doug Lee was taking a shuttle van back to the St. Petersburg airport and fretting about his invalid mother. A fellow passenger quickly volunteered to stop in and visit once a week. "I do this type of thing for my church all the time," she said. "I'd be glad to add your mother to my list."<p>Mary Rowland, a columnist for the New York Times, writes about personal finance from New York City.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
