<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-How to Break a Will</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-How to Break a Will</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Homeowners can save money by paying attention to those mysterious little policies they bought with their homes<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>A year after moving into their dream house, a Cabin John, Maryland, couple received a chilling letter from the Washington Suburban Sanitation Commission. Their home had been built illegally across a sewer easement, the letter said, and was scheduled for demolition. This was the first the panicked homeowners had heard about any easement, which had not shown up on the title search they paid for when they bought the house.<p>But the couple had also bought a policy along with the title search when they closed on their house. Like most homeowners, the Maryland couple had not completely understood what title insurance was or why they were advised to buy it. They saw it as simply another of several mysterious expenses that appeared on the settlement sheet and had to be paid before they could move into their home. Indeed, when the bombshell letter arrived from the sanitation commission, the couple's lawyer had to remind them that they had even bought title insurance in the first place.<p>Fortunately, they had. The title insurer intervened and agreed to pay the costs of rerouting the sewer line and relandscaping the grounds: an $80,000 construction bill, plus the cost of reconnecting the diverted sewer to adjacent homes and preparing new surveys for the affected properties, as well as all legal expenses involved.<p>In addition to title insurance, home buyers are often advised to buy private mortgage insurance and credit life insurance. Although these three types of policies together generate millions of dollars in insurance sales every year, few people understand what such insurance covers, whether it is a good investment, or even what it costs. And even those who do notice the thousands of dollars in premiums they're charged most often figure it's insignificant compared with the amount of their mortgage anyway. But in many cases, homeowners end up paying too much, paying for too long, or paying for the wrong kind of coverage.<p>Title insurance, the coverage that saved the Maryland couple's home, covers the cost of defending or settling claims that were not discovered during the title search. Buyers are not always told that there actually are two types of title insurance: lenders' coverage, which costs a onetime premium of about $2.50 for every $1,000 borrowed and which every mortgage company requires before agreeing to underwrite a home loan, and owners' coverage, which costs an additional onetime payment of $3.50 per $1,000 and is optional.<p>As the names suggest, the first coverage protects the interests of the lender while the second safeguards the interests of the homeowner. Unfortunately, these interests are not always identical, but more than a few buyers incorrectly assume that they are automatically protected when they purchase coverage for their lenders. The real estate agent or lawyer who handles the closing is supposed to clear up this confusion, but since commissions or fees are generally not paid for recommending buyers' coverage, advisors sometimes neglect it. Title companies themselves have little financial incentive to help out. "With only a onetime premium involved, companies have no money for advertising to consumers," explains H. Randolph Farmer, a senior vice president at Lawyers Title Insurance in Richmond, Virginia.<p>Other times, buyers decide not to purchase insurance because the threat of title problems seems so remote. Actually, disputes arise with surprising frequency in the 1990s. In addition to undisclosed easements, they can include liens placed by contractors who were owed money by previous homeowners and improperly surveyed property boundary lines that inadvertently caused a driveway or fence to be built on a neighbor's land.<p>Fraud and forgery are other leading causes of title problems. A party to an acrimonious divorce does not want the former spouse to share in the proceeds of a home sale and hires an impostor to sign relevant documents while masquerading as the marriage partner. Relatives eager to dispose of an inherited property casually forge the signature of a family member who opposes the sale. One audacious case involved an army officer's home in Georgia that stood vacant while the owner was stationed in Germany. "A woman boldly visited the county courthouse, gathered the pertinent facts about the property, forged a deed conveying the house to herself, recorded the forged deed, and posted a for sale sign in the front yard," recalls Farmer of Lawyers Title, which handled the case. When the major returned from overseas, he found his home inhabited by strangers who had innocently purchased the place believing the title was clear. Eventually they were forced to move, but their title insurance allowed them to recover their investment.<p>In fact, deceptions are becoming so commonplace that some title-insurance companies conduct identity checks at the closing table. Even so, the industry's loss-adjustment expenses are currently running about double the historical average, according to Gary Garrity, vice president of the American Land Title Association in Washington, D.C.<p>Homeowners may well ask why they should pay the cost of a title search and then pay again to insure against errors that occur during the search. The truth is, lenders don't object because homeowners are paying for the coverage. And because few home buyers protest, the practice has become entrenched within the real estate industry.<p>Even though home buyers pay the bills, lenders rarely let homeowners choose which title insurer to use. Instead, the lender typically selects a company, orders a policy, and presents it to the owner at the closing table. However, any consumer who wants to comparison shop is theoretically free to do so. Because rates are regulated by state insurance commissioners, buyers probably will not notice much difference in price among title insurers in their area. What will distinguish the companies is the level of service they offer. Some respond promptly to claims while others ignore policyholders, so it is worthwhile to seek references from real estate lawyers who are familiar with all the companies. Buyers should also contact the Better Business Bureau and the consumer-affairs department of the state insurance commission, which may know of past problems.<p>Homeowners who fail to purchase title insurance for themselves when they acquire property can buy it at any time, although they must pay the cost of a new title search. Those who presently are insured should consider increasing their coverage if their home has increased in value, unless their policy is automatically adjusted for appreciation and inflation.<p>Although the public is rarely told of its existence, a discount on lenders' insurance is available to people who refinance their mortgages if the title has been searched within the past ten years and the new policy is written by the same company. To obtain the savings, they must request a title-insurance reissue rate when making a loan application.<p>Homeowners also should remember that owners' title insurance extends from the day they purchase until the day they sell and even continues after death if title to the property remains in the family. Thus, someone who refinances does not need to purchase owners' title insurance at all because the original policy is still in effect. Unfortunately, says Benny L. Kass, a real estate attorney with Kass, Skalet, Segan, Spevack & Van Grack in Washington, D.C., "a lot of people who refinance are being sold new owner's coverage by settlement companies and lawyers who are basically dishonest."<p>Some of these same shady characters may fail to explain private mortgage insurance. PMI helps people obtain a mortgage when they have not accumulated enough to make the traditional 20 percent downpayment. The insurance, which costs homeowners between $3.50 and $5.00 a year per $1,000 borrowed (or about $1,500 a year on a $300,000 house), covers the lender in case of a default, allowing bankers to make loans they might otherwise refuse to underwrite.<p>The concept of PMI is excellent, but its execution is fraught with pitfalls. For starters, the insurance is offered by only eight companies, which seem bent on keeping as much distance as possible between themselves and the home buyers who purchase their premiums. "Mortgage insurers work with lenders, who choose an appropriate PMI program for each borrower. Generally, the consumer does not even know who the insurer is," says Suzanne Hutchinson, executive vice president of the Mortgage Insurance Companies of America, the Washington, D.C.-based trade organization for the industry.<p>Should homeowners care which company gets their PMI payments? "I would say not," responds Charles M. Reid, president of United Guarantee Residential Insurance in Greensboro, North Carolina. "It is a free marketplace, and a lender is going to do everything possible to [find] a very competitive monthly payment for the borrower."<p>That assumes that bankers shop as hard to save our money as we would. Consider that after shoehorning buyers into PMI programs not of their choosing, lenders are not required to notify homeowners when they've acquired enough equity so that the PMI can be canceled. "It is up to the homeowner to keep an eye on that because most lenders don't track it," says Bonnie O'Dell, director of consumer information at the Federal National Mortgage Association.<p>Some lenders even require that PMI be carried for the length of the loan, no matter how far down it is paid. No federal regulations have been written to prohibit this clearly unfair practice, so the only way for homeowners to climb out from under unwarranted PMI premiums may be to refinance their loan.<p>PMI borrowers should periodically review the amount of equity in their home in order to cancel the insurance or, if necessary, refinance at the earliest opportunity. Although it takes almost 11 years to achieve 20 percent equity in a 5 percent down, 30-year fixed-rate loan at 7 percent interest, rising property values or home improvements can cause the equity to appreciate much more rapidly.<p>Regardless of how much or how little equity they have in the home, those who refinance, as well as new buyers, are wise to resist sales pressure from their lender to buy credit life insurance, which pays off the mortgage if the homeowner dies. "Credit life is usually a rip-off," declares Peter C. Katt, a fee-only life insurance advisor in West Bloomfield, Michigan. Indeed, he points out that when the National Association of Insurance Commissioners studied credit life insurance in 1991, it found that only 39 cents of every premium dollar is ever returned to the consumer.<p>The credit-life industry can maintain its whopping 61 percent margin because its insurance costs from about 2 to 4.5 times as much as term life insurance, which can also be used to retire a mortgage upon death. For example, term insurance for a 35-year-old male nonsmoker currently costs 92 cents per $1,000 of coverage, while credit life for the same individual costs $4.08 per $1,000. Credit life insurance salespeople would argue that their premiums never increase while term insurance grows more expensive each year as the person ages. But they fail to point out that credit-life coverage decreases as the mortgage principal is paid down, while term insurance coverage remains constant. (To reduce term insurance in tandem with the mortgage, request a lower level of coverage every year, which will also lower the annual premiums.) The difference in premiums is less dramatic when homeowners are older, but credit life never proves to be the more economical deal. "Credit-life premiums rarely cost less than twice what someone can pay for term insurance," Katt says.<p>It is custom and lender clout, rather than any equitable division of personal responsibility, that makes title and private mortgage insurance a necessity for American homeowners to buy in the mid-1990s. Fair or not, prudent consumers have little choice but to pay for these two products. However, unless home buyers can't get life insurance any other way, there's no good reason to enrich a credit-life company.<p>Margaret Opsata has been covering real estate issues for 20 years.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry, Homeowner

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

