<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-The Adam Smith of Silicon Valley</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-The Adam Smith of Silicon Valley</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Economist Paul Romer preaches the gospel of growth<p>By David Samuels<p>"Many of you probably know Paul as the father of Amy, who was with us last year," singsongs Carla, the teacher who runs the fifth-grade Future Club at the Nueva School in Hillsborough, California. "But he also has another job -- which is called being an economist. Some of you might have read about him in Newsweek. And when you come to that article, which I put in your packets, you will find that Paul was written up as a revolutionary in economic theory. He has some very interesting ideas about how economies grow." <p>Standing before the classroom, Stanford professor Paul Romer looks more like a freshman Republican congressman -- with blow-dried hair touched with gray and boyishly handsome features -- than a revolutionary. Nonetheless, at the age of 41, Amy's father, the son of Colorado governor Roy Romer (whom he advises), is perhaps the most innovative American economist of his generation.<p>In a series of papers since the mid-1980s, Romer, who did his graduate work at the knee of the influential University of Chicago economics faculty, has compelled his entire profession to rethink its fundamental belief that the potential for growth, and hence for world prosperity, is limited because supplies of labor, capital, and raw materials are limited. Not true, Romer argues. Ideas and the technologies they create are the real engines of growth and wealth. And since human invention is infinite, so too must be the possibilities for economic growth. <p>The subject, as anyone who watches TV news knows, has become the world's central economic problem -- the key to resolving everything from wage and living-standard stagnation in developed nations to controlling population growth in emerging ones. As The Economist magazine has editorialized, understanding and fostering growth is "surely the most urgent task in economics."<p>"What do we mean when we talk about an economy?" Romer asks the fifth graders, a purple marker poised in his hand. "A real economy is a very complicated thing, but there are three simple things that show up in every economy: There are people. There are rules and institutions. And there are physical opportunities. <p>"You have to take people pretty much as they are," he says, accompanied by the tire squeal of his marker on the white board behind him. "For example, it would be better if everybody in the world was more generous or thoughtful, or if people cared about each other more. And it would also be better if we had more plants and animals, or more oil, or more sunshine on the East Coast. But we can't really change the physical opportunities. What we can change," the economist explains, drawing a thick purple line beneath the word, "are the rules people use to interact with each other." <p>At the end of the question-and-answer period, a fifth grader in a pink flowered dress fixes the economist with a very serious and slightly puzzled look. "There's one thing I don't understand," she says. "What exactly does an economist do?"<p>It is a question that Paul Romer asks himself, too. "I think the essence of being an economist," he says as we drive to the Hoover Institution on Stanford's campus, where he is a senior fellow, "especially a Chicago economist, has to do with learning to turn off all your emotions and say, 'Let's think abstractly about adoption or crime.' We have a name for people who are innately really good at this," Romer adds with a rueful grin. "They're psychopaths, people who are incapable of feeling guilt, or remorse, or any emotional reaction. So there's a good reason, I guess, why one looks with a degree of nervousness at people who are really good at this activity."<p>The stretch of interstate between the Nueva School and the Hoover Institution displays Paul Romer's idea-driven economy in action. The leafy venture-capital parks of Sand Hill Road, nestled into the Palo Alto Hills, irrigate the computer firms and biotech start-ups down in Silicon Valley with streams of cash, fertilizing the dreams of the chemists, biologists, software engineers, and Stanford professors who have transformed this once sleepy college town into a wide-open gateway to the world economy of the 21st century. "We used to use iron oxide to make cave paintings," Romer says as the office parks go whizzing by, "and now we put it on floppy disks. The point here is, the raw material we have to work with has been the same for all of human history -- there's the stuff in the earth's crust and the stuff in the atmosphere. So when you think about growth, the only place it can come from is finding better recipes for rearranging the fixed amount of stuff we have."<p>Romer, who has two children, compares the labor-plus-capital approach -- axiomatic among economists from David Ricardo in the 19th century to Milton Friedman today -- to the Play-Doh Fun Factory, a bright plastic toy that comes with an assortment of dies that turn lumps of Play-Doh into lengths of pipe or beam. "It's a good illustration of what most people think about when they think about growth," Romer says, "the combination of raw material (the Play-Doh) with capital (the Fun Factory) and labor (what the child does when she pushes down the lever) in order to create a more valuable good." <p>What the Fun Factory metaphor leaves out is the multiplying effect of technological invention on our limited stocks of labor and capital. "There's only so far you can get if what you're doing is processing more and more Play-Doh," Romer says, pointing to the explosive growth of the U.S. economy since 1870 -- which can hardly be explained by increases in our stock of steam engines and waterwheels. It can be explained, Romer believes, only by a succession of new and ever more profitable inventions -- like the microchip, the product of a set of ideas that enabled the alchemical conversion of sand into powerful microprocessors and a huge new source of wealth.<p>In this view, our material future is bounded only by the capacity of the imagination to generate new ideas, which are, for practical purposes, infinite in number. "Think of a manufacturing process with 20 steps," Romer explains in his office at the Hoover Institution. "The number of possible combinations is 10 to the power 18, the number of seconds which have elapsed since the big bang.<p>"Another property that distinguishes ideas from objects," he says, "is that millions of people can use the same idea at the same time, for almost nothing. Producing the first copy of Word might cost <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> millions of dollars. Every copy after that, however, is essentially free." <p>Romer was not the first to think about the effect of technology on economics. In the 1950s, the Nobel Prize winning economist Robert Solow suggested that labor and capital could add up to more than the sum of their parts through improvements in technology, an effect that became known among economists as the Solow residual. But if technology was important, Solow believed, it also developed according to a logic of its own and could be ignored by economists.<p>This was the situation when Romer began publishing his work on economic growth in 1986, a line of inquiry that culminated in two widely influential papers in 1990 and 1991. It was this work that gave economists a way to bring technological change -- the most obvious characteristic of modern society -- back inside their economic models. <p>The impact of Romer's emphasis on ideas and growth, says Stanford economist Paul Krugman, "was like when the German general slaps his head in The Longest Day and says, 'Normandy. How stupid of me.'" And David Warsh, economics columnist for The Boston Globe and the author of Economic Principals, says, "The next generation of economists will learn a very different kind of economics because of the work that Paul Romer has done."<p>In America, the faith that economies could be reduced to simple mechanical models and driven, like a car, faster or slower culminated in the Keynesian revolution of the 1950s and 1960s, in which economists, like Paul Samuelson and Robert Solow of MIT, believed (and convinced the Kennedy administration) that, just as physicists discovered the laws of nature, economists could uncover the laws of economic life and use them to create an endless era of stable prosperity that would banish the ghost of the Great Depression. <p>Then came the oil shocks of the 1970s, runaway inflation, ballooning deficits, and work by Chicago-school economists like Milton Friedman, all of which demolished the theoretical basis of Keynesianism. By the end of the decade, the dream of a small cadre of experts directing the economy through precisely calibrated interventions in interest rates and government spending had been destroyed. Having lost its role as the power behind society's throne, economics itself seemed to lose its bearings, drifting into the creation of internally consistent mathematical models that bore no conceivable relation to the world of economic affairs. As Robert Heilbroner and William Milberg write in The Crisis of Vision in Modern Economic Thought, the "'high theorizing' of the present period attains a degree of unreality that can be matched only by medieval scholasticism." <p>As a graduate student and young professor, Romer, too, was seduced by counting angels on the head of a pin (in his case, this meant rapturously tracing the apparent similarities between the geometrical shapes called convex sets and elements of Samuelson's general equilibrium theory of wages and prices). But his interests soon shifted back to the shapeless, intractable question of how the world works. And how to make it work better. <p>With one hand on the wheel and one hand pointing to the lights of San Francisco Bay, Romer is wondering: Why not build a free-trade colony somewhere in Africa that might do for that continent what Hong Kong has done for Asia? Why not turn the city of Detroit or East Saint Louis, Illinois, over to <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a>, or to Lee Kuan Yew of Singapore, and allow city residents to vote with their feet? In his most recent paper -- on the Social Security system and why New Dealers insisted on defining the program as an entitlement, even at the expense of achieving broader coverage -- Romer applies the tools of evolutionary biology, history, and political science to the kinds of messy questions about values that economists since the days of Adam Smith have avoided. <p>"Smith not only wrote The Wealth of Nations, he also wrote The Theory of Moral Sentiments," Romer points out. "Seventeenth- and eighteenth-century liberal thinkers wrote about what democracy meant -- not just as a system of material payoffs, but what that system meant for the kind of people it created."<p>It's rumored that Romer recently turned down an invitation to be considered for the Federal Reserve Board to stay with his family in California, and he rarely appears on the editorial pages of establishment newspapers. However much he wants his work to move the world, Romer often seems palpably resistant to spelling out its practical implications. Nonetheless, his attempt to pierce the mystery of wealth creation will be hard to ignore in our technology-driven world economy. "It has big implications for trade," says David Warsh, "and it has big implications for science policy. The debate is just beginning."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

