<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Bring Your Money Home</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Bring Your Money Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Bring Your Money Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Cover<p>BRING YOUR MONEY HOME
Feeling gloomy about the U.S. stock and bond markets? Try looking at them as a foreigner might.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Does president clinton understand how to lead an economy? Is the Federal Reserve pursuing the correct money strategies? Do American corporations still have the right stuff? <p>Questions like these often preoccupy U.S. investors, especially during periods when our own stock and bond markets appear to be faltering or weak. Yet important as they are, they also can lead to myopia. Why? Because in a global economy, all things are relative. It's crucial to focus not only on how we are doing as a nation, but also on how we are doing compared with everyone else.<p>At the moment, the parochial view is awash in gloom. We see a huge federal deficit, rising interest rates, a dollar that won't buy what it used to, and a bumbling, squabbling government. We see an economy once dominated by assembly lines and blast furnaces transforming itself into one populated by rotisserie-chicken outlets and espresso bars. We wonder if we are better at generating lawsuits than jobs, better at manipulating paper than creating useful products.<p>Seeing only trouble at home, many investors in recent years have become fervent global players, racing to the latest emerging market that can tout double-digit growth. Americans have been plowing their money into places like India and Peru at unprecedented rates. To some investors, over the rainbow has come to mean far from 
Kansas__and all the other contiguous states to boot.<p>This trend away from U.S. markets started five years ago. From 1985 through 1989, the U.S. took in more capital than it exported; an average of $60 billion washed onto our shores each of those years. But in 1990, the flow reversed direction. That year, the nation exported almost $15 billion more in capital than it imported. In 1993, net capital exports approached $17 billion as U.S. investors snapped up $128.6 billion in foreign investments. <p>Where was all this money going as it left our shores? The outflow was almost evenly divided between foreign equities and debt. Asian equities alone accounted for $17.1 billion of the total invested overseas in 1993, a 90 percent increase from the previous year. Mexican equities, which later hurt so many investors, received $5.3 billion from Americans in 1993, while the rest of Latin America got $7.3 billion.<p>Many pioneers of the overseas boom were well-rewarded. Malaysia returned 123 percent in 1993, South Africa 84.4 percent, and Singapore 74 percent. Meanwhile, stay-at-home investors pocketed comparatively paltry 10.1 percent returns that year. Some of those undoubtedly decided they should join the global treasure hunt, too.<p>Until the recent debacle in Mexico stemmed the outflow of dollars, Americans were investing virtually everywhere. Turkey, with a stock market a mere ten years old, attracted $34 million last year. Vietnam, a nation without a stock exchange, bagged $106 million.<p>As we've pointed out in these pages before, there is certainly a place for global investing in a well-diversified portfolio. Study after study has shown that investors who put at least some portion of their money to work overseas do better over the long run than those who adopt a more isolationist strategy.<p>Nevertheless, we also think the current pessimism about U.S. investments is overblown. Step back from our messy political sideshows. Let go of last year's disappointments in the stock and bond markets. And forget, for the time being, about whether or not the Federal Reserve will achieve a "soft landing" for our economy. Instead, look at the U.S. as a foreigner might.<p>What other nation has as diversified and vibrant an economy? What other nation offers the security and stability of the U.S.? Indeed, where would any other nation on the planet first go for help if it were in trouble? The answers to those questions should be obvious.<p>America's economy? It is proving to be surprisingly strong, and inflation is nowhere to be seen as yet. The dollar, although now near a historic low, is still the currency of choice around the world.<p>America's corporations? They've revamped themselves to become more productive and efficient. They continue to lead the world in scores of industries, including some, such as automobiles, in which they were written off just a few years ago. <p>America's markets? They are the most liquid and well-regulated in the world.<p>The outlook for the U.S. is never easy to divine in the precise terms that many of us seek. Yet the big picture is a positive one, especially when compared with the prospects for any other economy on the globe.<p>Although we at Worth have been wary about U.S. stocks and bonds for over a year now, our view is that the worst is probably over. In fact, we think things are starting to look pretty good for certain U.S. investments__whether in bonds or in select sectors of the stock market. More and more, we find ourselves agreeing with folks like John Manley, quantitative strategist and director at Smith Barney in New York, who says, "I see a better market ahead because there are signs the economy has moderated." Or Edward Keon Jr., senior vice president at IBES International, an investment information company in New York. Keon says he believes earnings on the 500 stocks in the Standard & Poor's index will rise around 12 percent in 1995. Although that would be well below 1994's 19 percent earnings growth, Keon argues that because long-term interest rates will be stable, a 12 percent earnings rise will translate to much bigger gains in stocks than seen last year. <p>Optimists like Keon and Manley remain in the minority on Wall Street__for understandable reasons, given the market's performance in 1994. Last year was a bad one, a year when thousands of individual stocks got pummeled and many U.S. securities did far worse than the performance of the broader market averages might suggest.<p>Analysts and investment-newsletter writers still seem to be licking their wounds. In early February, 57 percent of the revisions in analysts' earnings forecasts were downward adjustments, while raising only 43 percent of their estimates. The Hulbert Financial Digest, which ranks performance among 162 investment newsletters, says stock-only advisors are recommending having more cash than equities. <p>Nevertheless, we think there are some compelling reasons to question this mood. The most salient: the overall safety offered by U.S. stocks and bonds__an allure that may once again cause a positive inflow of capital to this country in coming months. We think investors around the world are about to send their money back to work here, as they did through the 1980s. Such capital inflows are not yet visible in Federal Reserve data, but some analysts see anecdotal evidence that this already may be happening. Once established, this trend will attract further investment, both domestic and foreign.<p>The U.S. is a safe haven. With fledgling stock markets everywhere bouncing around in the wake of the Mexican peso devaluation, dazed investors want the stability and liquidity of U.S. markets. Indeed, as the Mexico crisis unfolded, dealer firms reported unusually large buy orders for U.S. Treasurys in late December and early January. Record demand from individual investors occurred in the December and January two-year Treasury auctions and in January's five-year auction as well. <p>Treasurys also have become a magnet to investors because of their relatively high interest rates. The same interest rate hikes that made 1994 woeful for most U.S. debt and equity holders now make our debt an attractive buy. Investors purchasing 30-year bonds recently received yields of 7.7 percent. Compare this with the longest-term yields investors can find elsewhere: 7.6 percent on 30-year German bonds, 4.8 percent on 20-year Japanese debt.<p>If investors perceive that the Federal Reserve has done all or most of the rate-boosting that's required to slow the U.S. economy, strategists believe we'll see an even greater stampede into U.S. debt markets. Already, the 30-year Treasury yield has fallen from its November 1994 high of 8.17 percent.<p>The dollar may prove to be another plus. Although peaks and valleys are exceedingly tough to call in currency markets, some observers believe the dollar is now in the process of bottoming (see "Better Days Ahead for the Buck?" on page 72). A rising dollar would obviously make U.S. holdings even more attractive to foreign investors. <p>Albert Friedberg, director of the Friedberg Mercantile Group, a commodity-trading advisor in Toronto, says flatly, "Fundamentals are coming into place for a renewed and significant rise in the U.S. dollar." Specifically, Friedberg believes that the money supply, essentially the amount of liquidity afloat in the banking system, is now shrinking for the first time in five years. "Adjusted [bank] reserves have fallen at an annualized rate of 11 percent since immediately after the [Fed's] August tightening,"Friedberg notes. The result, he says, has been a notable weakening in the rate of growth for two important measures of the money supply: M1 (commercial bank deposits, currency in circulation, and other liquid holdings) and M2 (M1 plus savings accounts, money market fund holdings, and other fairly liquid instruments). The fewer dollars out there, the more valuable they become. <p>Another favorable sign for our markets: U.S. corporate executives, directors, and managers recently have been buying up shares in their companies at a fierce rate. In the past, such insider transactions have proved prescient. According to Vickers Stock Research in Huntington, New York, the eight-week insider sell-to-buy ratio now stands at 0.94. When that ratio falls below what Vickers calls a neutral level of 2.25__meaning 2.25 shares sold per 1 share purchased__the markets climb. During the past 20 years, the ratio has dropped below 1 on only eight occasions, and on average, the market moved 23 percent higher in the ensuing 12 months.<p>The index of electric-utility stocks is also sending upbeat signals. Almost without fail, a stagnating Dow Jones Utility Average precedes overall market tops, while a rebounding average precedes recoveries in broader indices. The Dow Jones Utility Average last peaked in August 1993. That turned out to be about six months before the overall market indices hit their highs. Now utilities are rebounding off a mid-November 1994 low. In the first six weeks of the year, the index was up 6.53 percent. Because utilities are interest rate sensitive stocks, their rally is an indication that the market believes rates probably won't rise much more. That's good news for both stocks and bonds.<p>The same could be said for the index of net new business formation in the U.S., now at its highest level since March 1980. According to Michelle Colley Laughlin, chief economist at Sanwa Securities in New York, this barometer of entrepreneurial activity is a fairly reliable predictor of future economic trends. For example, she notes that the index topped out in January 1990, six months before the July 1990 peak in the business cycle. Then, in late 1990, it fell to a cyclical low, roughly six months before the "official" end of the recession in early 1991. Laughlin believes the index's recent surge__up more than 5 percent in the past three months alone__will translate to 1.6 million new jobs by the middle of the year. <p>Congress could provide a further boost to the U.S. as an investment haven if it reduces the capital-gains tax. If this happens, stocks of growth companies, small and large, would rise. When the capital-gains rate began to fall from 49.1 percent in 1978 to 20 percent in 1980, valuations on small-cap stocks almost doubled, from a price-to-earnings ratio of 8.6 to 16.5 (see "When Taxes Fall, Stock Values Rise" on page 69). <p>How should investors who are interested in bucking the bearish view look to maximize their potential for profits in 1995? Those seeking income might do very well by joining in the stampede for low-risk Treasury notes with maturities of two to three years. Although these holdings are no longer the bargains they were just a few months ago, their yields__7.15 percent to 7.30 percent__are still attractive on an inflation-adjusted basis.<p>Going further out in Treasury maturities is trickier. Although some strategists think that locking in 7.7 percent for 30 years is a good bet, there is still a risk that inflation will creep above 3 percent by the end of 1995. This would have a much more deleterious effect on a 30-year bond than it would on a shorter-term holding.<p>As for stocks, even the market optimists hesitate to advise a big plunge into equities just yet. Jeffrey Applegate, chief investment strategist at CS First Boston in New York, is a believer in stocks for the latter half of 1995 but is concerned that the overall market could decline somewhat by midyear if the Fed raises rates yet again. <p>Nonetheless, history shows that it's better to be early on a move that follows a stock market correction than to be late. That's because up moves often occur in relatively short bursts. In October 1966, for example, when the S&P had declined 22 percent from a previous year's high, the index rebounded 18 percent by the following January. The S&P finished the 12-month period from the October bottom with a 33 percent gain; more than half of that was achieved in the first three months after the low.<p>A similar updraft occurred in July 1984, after the market dropped 14 percent from its 1983 high. By July 1985, the S&P 500 had risen 30 percent; almost half that gain came three weeks after the 1984 low. "Typically, a rebound from a trough in equities is fairly strong and fairly compressed," says Applegate.<p>Certainly, not all stocks are good bets. The next winners are likely to be congregated in a few sectors. Most will be growth stocks, but not all growth stocks are likely to participate. That's because consumer stocks__durables such as automobiles and home electronics and nondurables like retailers and packaged-good manufacturers__are likely to lag other sectors. In 1994, credit card debt grew 17 percent, up from 12 percent in 1992, so consumers now have limited access to credit. Also, if the consumer economy continues to surge, threatening inflation, the Fed will raise rates to slow personal income growth. <p>Companies that should outperform the market, according to strategist Applegate: "Stocks with sizable levels of non-U.S. sales and profits__say 40 percent to 60 percent__and producers of capital goods and equipment." Capital-goods stocks will do well partly because the Fed essentially has told corporate America that it won't let up on its inflation fighting until industry adds more production capacity. These investments have also resulted in sharply improved profit margins and productivity gains, particularly among U.S. manufacturers. This has translated to top performance for stocks in the capital-goods sector__including technology, basic industries, and heavy-equipment makers. Since this investment cycle began more than two years ago, the index of capital-goods stocks has outperformed the S&P 500 by 9.53 percent. Look for good buys in sectors where the U.S. is the global leader, including technology giants Motorola and Intel, farm-machinery manufacturer AGCO, battery-maker Duracell International, and Gillette. <p>Economist Keon at IBES thinks that shares in basic industries__steel companies, chemical makers, paper manufacturers__will rise in 1995 and 1996 because global demand and continued productivity growth in the sector will create higher profit margins. "This recovery has been fairly mild, but the much better earnings you're seeing show how much more productive companies are," he says. <p>Capital-goods makers are well positioned right now because labor constitutes an increasingly small share of production costs, allowing companies to pour cash into equipment that increases productivity rather than into higher-cost labor, according to Applegate. As a result, he expects after-tax profit margins of 5 percent for 1994, 5.5 percent for this year and 6 percent in 1996. The previous record margin in an economic expansion was 5.4 percent in 1988. Small-capitalization technology companies that make equipment for use in manufacturing may also do well, says Applegate. <p>Although the memories of last year's losses in U.S. stock and bond markets remain painful for many investors, this is probably not the best time to go hunting for greener pastures abroad. Especially not when some of the best opportunities may be right under our noses.<p>- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - <p>
Greener Pastures Right Here at Home<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>
None of the six global market strategists we consulted envisions a raging bull running through U.S. markets this year. But all have increased their exposure to domestic investments in recent months. We'll let them explain why:<p>
Michael Metz, chief investment officer, Oppenheimer & Co.<p>"Relatively speaking, the U.S. is the most attractive market in the world, including all the emerging markets. We have political stability and controlled inflation. We are competitive worldwide and are still in an expansionary period. The valuations may be on the rich side, but every market is overpriced."<p>
Robert C. Elliott, senior executive vice president, investment policy, Bessemer Trust<p>"We have increased our domestic weighting because we really believe that the Fed can engineer a soft landing and that we are near the end of interest-rate hikes for a while. Therefore, we think economic growth in the States will be sustainable at around 2.5 percent. Corporate profits will still grow at an attractive level. We also believe the dollar is very undervalued and will improve. NonU.S. investors, like the Europeans, who always feel the dollar is going to weaken, will finally commit more money to the U.S. Most currency moves go well beyond valuation levels, partly because of the people who are involved in the trading and speculation."<p>
Jim Kermes, chief investment officer, Northern Trust Co.<p>"The economic cycles of foreign countries are behind ours, so they have more interest-rate increases to go. You see a lot of growth in Europe, and I don't know what is going to happen in Japan with the cost of rebuilding Kobe. So we expect some price weakness abroad, with less chance for price declines in the U.S. The way we see the economy playing out is that we won't have a recession but we will have a slowdown in growth. Greenspan is conscious of not driving a stake into the heart of the economy, so we're optimistic he won't overdo it this time."<p>
Brian A. Berris, partner, Brown Brothers Harriman<p>"We have made a modest increase in our U.S. equities position. The disappointing performance of the stock market, despite strong corporate earnings, has resulted in price-to-earnings multiples that have shrunk dramatically in the last 12 months. Couple that with a better flow of funds from foreign markets and the current stability in equities, and the result is a very attractive investment."<p>
Donald Straszheim, chief economist, <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a><p>"The U.S. is more competitive than it has it been. Cost cutting and restructuring have been going on for 13 years here versus only two years in Europe and Japan. Every time you see a restructuring and 5,000 people are laid off, a big capital-reinvesting plan is implemented, and technology and equipment is purchased. Because of this, it will be hard for Japan and Europe to keep up with us and even harder to catch up. We led the way out to a recovery, with the other English-speaking countries second and Japan and the rest of the world third. I like capital goods and high-technology companies."<p>
Eric Miller, chief investment officer, Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette<p>"We did move some cash into equities because more portfolio money, including mutual funds, is going to be staying at home. You could see it happening even before the Mexico crisis. Stocks are fairly priced right now, but we'll probably see better returns from bonds. Certainly the psychology of that market has improved significantly." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Government, Economy, Investing Strategies<p>

