	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Portents of Inflation</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-The Portents of Inflation</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>THE PORTENTS OF INFLATION<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>Trading in U.S. Treasury securities__$200 billion worth every day__makes up the world's biggest and most liquid market. Yet this huge global bond bazaar, around which all other debt and equity markets orbit like moons around a sun, itself obeys only one master: inflation.<p>"Inflation and growth are the biggest things; the market reacts to inflation," says Debra Packman-Landis, Treasurys strategist at Smith Barney in New York City.<p>Bond yields, in fact, are set at Treasury auctions to reflect inflation expectations, and they in turn affect the flow of money into global stock markets. All this makes inflation perhaps the most important influence on any portfolio. The problem is that inflation is a lagging indicator__it doesn't show up until well after it has begun to ravage the economy and our bank accounts. Prognosticators, therefore, must analyze leading indicators, tea leaves pointing to hidden pressures in the economy. <p>For example, December inflation was a modest 2.7 percent, down from 3.1 percent last summer, yet the Fed raised interest rates in January, after six increases in 1994. "The economy is expanding at an inflationary rate," says Anirvan Banerji, an economist at the Center for International Business Cycle Research at Columbia University. "Those signs are seen in the leading indicators."<p>Some investment houses track hundreds of indicators in their search for inflation insights. Obviously, this sort of scrutiny would be impossible for an individual. It may also, however, be unnecessary. CIBCR's inflation barometer, a standard for most economists, uses only seven measures, all of which investors can easily track. A majority of these measures, listed below, must fall in concert for inflation to decline in six to nine months, as it has 11 times since 1949.<p>1. Journal of Commerce Industrial Price Index, created by CIBCR, comprising prices of 17 commodities like textiles and metals.<p>2. Import prices, as measured by the Bureau of Labor Statistics.<p>3. Federal and nonfederal debt, as measured by the Treasury Department.<p>4. BLS's ratio of employment to the overall population, which shows how tight the labor market is.<p>5. National Association of Purchasing Management's monthly report, which measures the percentage of managers reporting increased prices at the wholesale level.<p>6. NAPM's delivery-time report, which measures the percentage of managers reporting longer delivery times, suggesting changes between supply and demand.<p>7. A quarterly Dun & Bradstreet survey measuring the number of businesses expecting to raise prices in the coming quarter.<p>These anticipatory numbers are more important than ever. Under chairman Alan Greenspan, Banerji says, "for the first time, the Fed has raised interest rates in response to the leading inflation indicators, rather than waiting for inflation to hit first."<p>CIBCR's indicators have been rising for a year, signaling that inflation could begin to accelerate at any time. However, some minor relief arrived in early February, when the percentage of purchasing managers reporting slower deliveries declined.<p>"We expect inflation to reach about 3.5 percent by the summer," says Banerji. "It won't look like runaway inflation to Main Street, 2.7 percent to 3.5 percent, but the value of bonds on Wall Street might drop."<p>Since 1979, the center, founded by Geoffrey Moore, Alan Greenspan's college statistics professor, has been unerring in anticipating the business cycle, give or take six months, Banerji says. Recorded inflation data are available from the Bureau of Labor Statistics (202-606-6994). An annual subscription to NAPM's monthly Report on Business is $150 (800-888-6276); CIBCR's daily fax (212-280-4420) is $4,500 annually. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

