<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Would Uncle Sam Lie to You?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Would Uncle Sam Lie to You?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Would Uncle Sam Lie to You?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Experts<p>WOULD UNCLE SAM LIE TO YOU?
When it comes to employment and economic growth, Washington doesn't need good news to publish good numbers.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Every week, the U.S. government unleashes a fusillade of economic data that stock and bond investors await with fear and trembling. Is the economy booming or stumbling? Are jobs being created? Is the trade deficit up or down? Depending upon the answers Uncle Sam provides, markets can soar or plunge; fortunes can be made or lost.<p>Recent case: On September 2, Treasury bonds quickly jumped up a point, then plunged a point and a half after the government released August's unemployment figures, a closely watched indicator of the economy's strength. What caused the whipsaw? Initially, the employment numbers looked weak to traders in the bond market. Weak employment numbers are anti-inflationary -- good news for bonds. But after traders scrutinized the data, they realized the numbers weren't so wimpy after all -- bad news for bonds. <p>Obviously, government economic statistics are of paramount importance to investors. They are absolutely relied upon by professionals and individuals to measure the economy's progress. Without access to these crucial statistics, investors would be flying blind.<p>But is the economic data that emanates from our capital reliable?<p>Recently, a couple of veteran economists have been saying the answer is no. They contend that recent changes in the ways several key figures are assembled by the folks in Washington tend to obfuscate the economic picture. The changes make our economy look much rosier than it is, the economists say.<p>Albert Sindlinger is one of these critics. Sindlinger is worth listening to in part because of his unusually long perspective: At 87, he has perused government statistics since 1928, initially working for Herbert Hoover. Some 70 years ago, Sindlinger created the consumer-confidence survey, still used today to take the consumer's pulse. An economist in Wallingford, Pennsylvania, he and his staff conduct 5,000 phone interviews a month on consumers' incomes, job security, and local business conditions. From this research comes his view of how the consumer and the economy are doing. <p>Speaking of the recent changes in how certain economic numbers are compiled by the government, Sindlinger says, "Each administration wants to put its best foot forward. Statistics don't lie, but you can sure lie with statistics."<p>Sindlinger's biggest complaint is with the unemployment figures. He takes great exception, for instance, to the Clinton administration's claim of having created 4.3 million jobs in its first 19 months in office. He reckons that 2.5 million of those -- 52 percent of the total claimed -- are what he calls phantom jobs, nonexistent. Fantasyland.<p>How can this be? Phantom jobs creep into the picture in a line in the unemployment data called bias factor, a component used since 1983 as a way to measure the growth of small businesses. Ordinary unemployment data, compiled by the Bureau of Labor Statistics, focused only on jobs created in industrial and service sectors, yet when the country was emerging from the recession of '81, many jobs were created by small businesses. The BLS estimated this growth at 155,000 jobs. This figure, in turn, was used to derive something called the "bias factor." Since then, bias-factor estimates have been used to figure monthly job data.<p>Back in 1983, the number of jobs in the bias factor was around 10 percent of the total being created nationwide. The economy was humming; gross domestic product was growing -- up almost 8 percent in 1983 and 11 percent in 1984. Now, the bias factor accounts for over half the jobs allegedly created, even though, as Sindlinger maintains, the economy is not doing nearly as well. <p>Still, the bias factor chugs on, piling up supposedly new jobs: In the most recent unemployment announcement, 158,000 of the 179,000 rise in nonfarm payrolls, almost 90 percent of the gain, resulted from the bias factor. Bias-factor figures are guesses and, to Sindlinger, completely untrustworthy. <p>Walter Williams, an economist at Econometric Publications in Ridgewood, New Jersey, and co-editor of The Straight Shooter, an economic-analysis newsletter, is also extremely dubious about the quality of government statistics. In addition to the misleading nature of the bias factor in job creation, Williams believes that the Bureau of Labor Statistics is undercounting about 5 million of what he calls hard-core unemployed workers. New questions put into the BLS's survey this year eliminated from the labor-force count a category of what the government calls discouraged workers, those who have stopped looking for work during the prior year. These unfortunates are not considered discouraged -- and therefore are no longer tallied -- because they have been discouraged for a year or more. That's because after a year, the government thinks these people just don't want to work, which in Washington is somehow different from being unemployed. As a result, says Williams, 90 percent of the 5 million discouraged workers have vanished from the unemployment rolls. <p>This helps keep the unemployment rate at a relatively acceptable 6.4 percent; a more accurate number, according to both Williams and Sindlinger, is 10 percent. "The Clinton people are bragging about the jobs they created," says Sindlinger. "Well, the jobs they've created are all on a computer program." Indeed, the Department of Labor's inspector general's office is auditing job figures put out by the BLS in response to allegations of dubious bookkeeping.<p>Another calculation that Williams considers unacceptable is the way wages and salaries are now reported by the Bureau of Economic Analysis. This is a key report: Wages and salaries are the single largest income account in gross domestic product.<p>The trouble, as Williams sees it, began in 1992, when the BEA reported wage and salary increases of 5.6 percent, which contributed heavily to GDP growth of 2.6 percent, according to the bureau. But the BEA's rosy wage and salary number looks extremely suspect when placed beside the Internal Revenue Service's reports on wage and salary growth. The IRS says that '92 wages and salaries were up only 2.2 percent. With this figure, growth in the nation's GDP in 1992 shrinks to minus 1 percent. <p>Which number do you believe? Williams says the IRS is a much more credible source, even if you add to the equation incomes that are too small to be reported or that are hidden from the tax man. The BEA, on the other hand, simply uses estimates of employment, wages, and hours as surveyed by the Bureau of Labor Statistics.<p>Here's something else that buttresses Williams's argument: A review of BEA and IRS reports on wages and salaries back to 1979 shows that there has never been a discrepancy in the figures as large as the nearly $100 billion gap that appeared in 1992. During that time, the disparity between wages and salaries reported by the two outfits each year never exceeded $20 billion.<p>Data regarding the U.S. merchandise-trade deficit is another area that doesn't pass the smell test these days. Although the components and the manner in which the trade numbers are collected had been constant since 1948, last year the Clinton administration decided to add a new figure to the compilation -- services. Unlike the trade balance in merchandise, which is negative, the trade balance in services is a surplus, so the overall monthly deficit comes in lower. <p>"The administration didn't like the widening trade deficit," says Williams. "So they added surplus of services. Before this, the trade numbers had been reasonably accurate." Now they are not. Why? Because there's no reliable way to measure the output of services on a monthly basis. But the Commerce Department guesses at it and throws it into the mix.<p>Understanding how the reporting of these numbers has changed in recent years is instructive on several counts. The Clinton administration, naturally, wants the economy to look robust so consumers feel good. People vote their pocketbooks: Since 1916, the incumbent party in the White House has lost every presidential election when real growth in disposable income came in below 3.9 percent for the year. Clinton wants to be a two-termer, so he must do whatever he can to make consumers believe they're better off. Furthermore, Clinton needs at least 3 percent GDP growth to keep his federal deficit-reduction plan on track. If growth drops below that rate, tax receipts won't be sufficient to reduce the deficit as planned.<p>But Sindlinger believes the public isn't gulled by funny numbers out of Washington. His case: If Americans thought the economy was as strong as the economic statistics are telling us, Clinton's approval rating would be around 60 percent, rather than the 40 percent he presently earns. Says Sindlinger: "You can fool Wall Street and you can fool the press, but you can't fool Main Street. The public simply knows better." 
---------------
Gretchen Morgenson is executive editor of Worth.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Government, Employment

					</font>
