	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Is Deflation the Real Danger?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Is Deflation the Real Danger?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Is Deflation the Real Danger?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Experts
IS DEFLATION THE REAL DANGER?That's right, deflation. The economy moves through cycles of inflation and deflation, and the signs point to a change.<p>
By Walter Mead<p>
A Tennessee politician once told me about a candidate for public office who was being interviewed by a local reporter. <p>
"What do you think about inflation, Congressman?"<p>
The candidate paused to think and then replied: "I'm agin' it. We've got too much inflation coming out of Washington, D.C., and it has got to stop."<p>
"Then what do you think about deflation?" the reporter asked. <p>
"Well," the politician said, "I'm agin' that too. I don't like inflation, and I don't like deflation. What I want to know is, why can't we just stick with plain old-fashioned flation?"<p>
When the central banks of most of the developed world are so obviously fighting inflation, it's easy to forget that the financial history of the capitalist world is the record of swings between the extremes of inflation and deflation. Yet investors who find themselves on the wrong side of one of these swings will certainly come to regret it, for the difference between the two extremes is far from insignificant. <p>
In inflationary times, when the purchasing power of a dollar is declining, investors want to own things. Stocks, which represent ownership, are thus better investments than bonds in such periods. Deflation works just the opposite way. The prices of things decline, and the value of a dollar increases. <p>
It's hard for the current generation of investors to imagine such a development, perhaps, but it's going on right now in industries that produce computers. A dollar today will buy far more computing power than a dollar would have yesterday. Or think of all the homeowners who bought homes in the 1980s in the belief that house prices would keep rising forever. When real estate prices fell in many markets, these people faced large and totally unexpected capital losses.<p>
Such isolated economic incidents, of course, aren't enough to make an era deflationary. To envision deflation, extend trends like these across the entire economy. Imagine simultaneous bear markets in stocks, real estate, and commodities. Add unemployment: Deflation is almost always accompanied by mass layoffs as whole companies go broke or lose big chunks of their business. During the Great Depression, millions of people woke up one day to find that the value of what they owned had shrunk and their jobs had disappeared. The Dow Jones Industrial Average sank from a high of 381.17 in 1929 to a low of 41.22 in 1932. The Dow did not regain its 1929 level until 1954.<p>
Bonds of blue-chip companies and governments, of course, are stellar performers in periods of deflation, as their steady stream of interest payments is worth more in goods every day. <p>
At the moment, inflation rules our thoughts. We live and invest in an era of inflationary expectations. Deflation has been almost forgotten; it is inflation that haunts the dreams of investors and central bankers as they sleep. <p>
Fair enough. But nothing lasts forever. The familiar business cycle, for example, guarantees that inflation follows deflation, which follows inflation. During an economic expansion, demand rises as the economy heats up. Shortages of workers lead to higher wages; this new purchasing power increases the demand for goods, and this pushes up prices throughout the economy.<p>
In recessions, things work the other way around. Falling demand leads to layoffs, and layoffs reduce demand even further. Wages and prices both fall until the economy is ready -- either on its own or with the help of the government -- to recover.<p>
But business cycles are relatively short-term oscillations between inflation and deflation. Longer-term forces are also at work, producing much more persistent trends. Over time, the economy seems to behave a bit like the climate. The short-term business cycle rises and falls like the temperature each day, but just as these daily cycles take place against the background of the seasonal change from summer to winter, so do the fluctuations of the business cycle occur in economic "winters" and "summers." <p>
We have had five of these economic seasons in the past 150 years of American history. An inflationary economic summer that included the Civil War and ended in the 1870s was followed by a deflationary winter that lasted until the First World War. During this deflation, the world economy was unusually vulnerable to panics and crashes. Stock markets swooned on the least provocation, and it was difficult for the economy to sustain stable growth. Temporary thaws were inevitably succeeded by a return to seasonable cold -- just as the temperature in a Maine winter has a hard time climbing above freezing for more than a few days.<p>
Summer returned as the world economy heated up with the First World War. From 1914 until the Great Depression, inflation was a more worrisome possibility than deflation. Economies boomed with the slightest excuse, and stock prices soared on any financial rumor.<p>
Winter returned with a roar in the stock market crash of 1929 and the ensuing depression, but by the 1960s the world was back in high summer. Recessions were short and expansions long and robust; prices, of course, tended to rise, but the inflationary temperatures didn't really warm up until the 1970s. Ever since, the world's economists and policy makers have concentrated on holding inflation at bay.<p>
This season will end, like all the others. But when? Are we still in midsummer, a season extended by the clever actions of central bankers? Or have we entered the economic equivalent of autumn, a period when deflationary forces are becoming more important? Nobody really understands long-term economic changes well enough to predict the exact timing of the onset of a new cycle. But an increasing number of signs point to approaching changes in the economic climate.<p>
Fans of Sherlock Holmes appreciate the importance of the dog that didn't bark -- a significant clue. So too should investors. As readers of this magazine keep reminding me in their letters, the United States is running a large budget deficit. These huge annual deficits have now been a part of our life since Ronald Reagan's first budget back in 1981. But inflation is lower today than it was before this inflationary period of budget busting. We have had the furnace on full blast since 1981, but the house isn't getting any warmer. This may be telling us something about the deflationary climate outside. <p>
The long-term rise in the unemployment rate is also a deflationary sign. Thirty years ago, unemployment in Western Europe rarely got above 4 percent; today it rarely gets below 7 percent. Something similar, if less dramatic, has happened in the United States. Thirty years ago we sang dirges and worried about a depression if unemployment in the U.S. reached 6 percent. Today when unemployment sinks to 6 percent we sing hosannas -- and worry about inflation. <p>
Two of the leading theories about why economies move through long-term cycles also suggest that the world economy is moving into a deflationary era. Proponents of the generational theory, for instance, say that policy makers, like generals, are always fighting the last war. A generation that grew up hating and fearing deflation will be slow to recognize inflation and bad at stopping it. For instance, the generation that remembered the inflation associated with the American Civil War was so worried about controlling inflation that it tightened the money supply even in the face of the persistent deflation and economic depressions of the 1880s and 1890s. The inflation associated with World War I may have helped bring on the Great Depression; policy makers were trying so hard to keep inflation at bay that the Fed raised interest rates in 1929.<p>
Our leaders today are as fixated on inflation as any of these predecessors. They are used to thinking that recessions are temporary inconveniences, while inflation is the real problem. That bias leads them to focus on keeping labor costs down by firing all the striking air-traffic controllers, as Ronald Reagan did, or to put increasing trade with China above pressing the Chinese government on its labor practices, as Bill Clinton has done. These policies, right or wrong, both arise from a conviction that the supply side of the economy is the important one.<p>
During the 1980s, policy makers tended to forget about the demand side. But economies don't just get into trouble when supply-side shortages cause prices to rise; they also slide downward when weak demand makes prices fall. Supply-side economics generally aims to increase the supply of goods at a given price level -- by cutting taxes, the cost of labor, and other factors that drive prices up.<p>
This is smart thinking when prices are on their way up, but if the demand side of the economy is weak, supply-side economics just makes things worse. If workers already can't buy enough cars to keep the economy moving, cutting their wages isn't going to help.<p>
Another view, however, holds that changes in the global economy, like the shift from an inflationary to a deflationary environment, are usually driven by big changes in technology. Here it's important to understand that any technology has both inflationary and deflationary tendencies over different time periods. For example, the explosive growth of railroads in the mid-19th century, financed largely with foreign capital, started a boom in the U.S. Add in the massive debt-financed spending of the Civil War, and, presto, inflation.<p>
But as new railroads opened new farming and mining areas around the world to commercial exploitation, supply of such goods as wheat rose faster than demand -- leading to the falling prices of a deflationary era that lasted until World War I.<p>
Something similar happened in the 1920s. The new mass-production techniques pioneered by industrialists like Ford led to huge productivity increases. At first this set off an investment-led industrial expansion; factories were built to produce cars, refrigerators, and other goods using the new improved techniques. But once again, supply outstripped demand, and the global economy tilted toward deflation in the Depression.<p>
In the 1980s and early 1990s, we have seen another global expansion based on enhanced productivity. The use of computers in manufacturing and services has helped slash production costs. So has the industrial revolution in the third world. Factories in China and Bangladesh now produce goods for markets in Indianapolis and Oakland.<p>
Right now, it's impossible to tell if this technological boom will follow the pattern of the railroad-led boom in the last century. This investment will certainly create its own demand, and the boom will feed on itself. People building new factories in the low-wage countries of Asia and Latin America place lots of orders for new equipment and construction materials. New factories need new power sources and new highways. During this expansionary phase, the danger is that the world's demand for certain kinds of goods -- capital goods certainly, but also raw materials such as concrete, copper wire, and fiber-optic cable -- will outstrip supply, sending prices into an inflationary spiral. In periods like this, central banks must guard against economies that tend to overheat. <p>
But sooner or later, the new factories will come on line and begin pumping goods into the economy. If the supply of new goods is greater than the demand for them, then the economic dynamic will change. Prices will fall, factories will become unprofitable, companies will default on their debts, and layoffs will reduce demand even further. <p>
As high-wage workers in advanced western economies lose their jobs either to machines or to low-wage workers, economic demand stagnates and falls, even as the global supply of goods increases. The supply-side boom of the global expansion gives way to a demand-side bust.<p>
Nothing is certain in economics. The governments of the world could pursue policies that try to create demand by raising wages in the developing world as quickly as possible. Investors who see signs that demand-creation policies are cropping up in China, Malaysia, or the U.S. shouldn't worry about a deflationary winter. On the other hand, if policy makers stick only to the strategies of inflation-fighting, it might be wise to get your portfolio a nice fur coat.---------------
Walter Mead is the senior policy advisor at the World Policy Institute at the New School. 
Research assistant: Adam Feibelman<p>
KEYWORDS: International Politics, Internatonal Economy, Stock Market Trends, Bond Investing, Economic Trends

