<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-America's Inflation Anxiety</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-America's Inflation Anxiety</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1994  <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> AMERICA'S INFLATION ANXIETY <p>How inflation became the bete noire of the economy -- and changedthe national character.  <p> By Joseph Nocera  <p> Earlier this year, when Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspanbegan pushing up interest rates -- an action that killed thebull markets in both stocks and bonds -- he cited a single reasonfor bringing the party to an end: the threat of inflation. WasGreenspan throwing out the bull with the bathwater? After all,it wasn't as though inflation had become a big problem. The consumerprice index was still signaling modest price increases (an annualrate of about 2.5 percent). Plus, it had been well over a decadesince any serious bout of inflation had infected the nation.Yet Greenspan said the phantom loomed so huge on the horizonthat radical measures had to be taken. He cited half a dozensignals, among them: The economy was overheated; the growth inGNP was at levels not seen in decades; the price of gold wasrising. Inflation, he seemed to be saying, was so great a scourgethat we would be better off living with less economic growth,higher interest rates, and an end to the bull market.   <p> A strong case can be made that in his obsession with inflation,Greenspan is fighting the last war. The national economy haschanged markedly in the past ten years, and it's quite reasonableto argue that ongoing productivity improvements and heightenedglobal competition will go a long way toward keeping inflationin check. Yet for anyone who lived through the age of inflation-- the period from 1978 to 1982, when rising prices chipped awayat our national self-confidence -- it is not hard to understandwhy the Fed chairman would find inflation so overriding a concern.Even now, after all this time, it is nearly impossible to overstatehow frightening inflation was at the time, how dramatically itchanged us. It had as profound an effect on one generation ofAmericans as the Depression had on a previous generation.   <p> Inflation splintered the status quo every bit as much as theVietnam War did. It helped fuel the rise of special-interestpolitics, causing Americans to become selfish in a way they reallyhadn't been before. If during the Depression people respondedby helping each other out as best they could, inflation had theopposite effect. It created an ethos in which people felt justifiedin cutting special deals for themselves, even when the net effectof those deals was to make things worse for everyone else. Whenevera union chief won a demand that his members receive wage increasesexceeding the cost of living, inflation worsened. Whenever theelderly lobby won a demand that automatic cost-of-living adjustmentsbe tacked on to Social Security payments, that action also fueledinflation. When government officials argued that the "spiralof inflation" could only be stopped if Americans were willingto sacrifice for the common good, they got nowhere.  <p> Inflation changed politics, too. Just as the Depression pavedthe way for Franklin Roosevelt and 20 years of Democratic controlof the White House, inflation helped bring down Jimmy Carterand set the stage for the Reagan-Bush years. Despite a numberof memorable achievements, the enduring image of Carter is thepicture of a sincere, pained man pleading with the nation toaccept its part of the shared sacrifice that he felt was requiredto beat inflation.   <p> Most enduringly, inflation altered the relationship of the middleclass to its money. The old behaviors and values that had beenswept in by the Depression -- thrift, an aversion to financialrisk, a belief that the bank was the only safe place for one'smoney -- were washed away by inflation and replaced by a newset of behaviors and values. If you want to understand why peoplebegan running up credit card bills or why they began moving theirmoney out of trusty savings accounts and into money market fundsand other more exotic financial vehicles, then you have to understandwhat happened during the age of inflation. Quite simply, inflationmarked the moment when the financial life of the middle classcould never again be simple or ordered or easy.   <p>   <p> It is almost impossible to know what causes inflation. Thatis mainly why it is so difficult to eradicate once it sets in.The classic definition calls inflation the result of "too muchmoney chasing too few goods." That's the simplest explanation,and it also explains Greenspan's actions: By raising interestrates, he is effectively making money itself more precious.  <p> It is almost universally believed that inflation's initial spurwas Lyndon Johnson's infamous "guns and butter" strategy of thelate 1960s: his decision to finance the Vietnam War effort andthe Great Society programs by creating a budget deficit insteadof raising taxes. Yet the experience of the 1980s strongly suggeststhat budget deficits are not inevitably inflationary -- as longas government resists the temptation to print more money to payoff its own debts.   <p> Many conservative economists, such as Milton Friedman, linkthe age of inflation to Richard Nixon's 1971 decision to takethe dollar off the gold standard. OPEC also played a crucialrole in reducing the purchasing power of the dollar; the cartelraised oil prices at will during the 1970s, creating severe economicproblems in America. There were food shortages that had inflationaryconsequences, as any shortage must. And during the 1970s, productivity-- which had risen steadily for two decades -- stopped goingup. Thus, large wage increases were not matched by productivityincreases. To oversimplify, more money was chasing the same goods. <p> The crucial point is that once the cost of living began to rise-- for whatever reason or group of reasons -- it was extraordinarilydifficult to get under control. Inflation became a psychologicalphenomenon as much as anything. Americans were used to a risingstandard of living and, at least back then, saw no reason whythis shouldn't continue. When inflation picked up, workers wouldclamor for higher wages. Businesses, anticipating wage hikes,raised prices to protect their profit margins. Which triggeredmore inflation. Which triggered a new round of wage demands.Which triggered a new round of price increases. The expectationof inflation actually created inflation. Cost-of-living allowancesbecame a fixture of every union contract and government program,virtually cementing the upward spiral in place.  <p> Presidents and their advisors tried to control it. Nixon, seeingprices shoot upward during his first term, imposed wage and pricecontrols for three months. This was a disastrous experiment.Once the controls were lifted, prices simply exploded. Then,after the first frightening outbreak of double-digit inflationin 1974, Gerald Ford instituted his widely ridiculed Whip InflationNow program, complete with WIN lapel buttons. Still, within twoyears, the rate of inflation as measured by the CPI was lessthan 5 percent a year. Ford's problem was that in focusing exclusivelyon inflation, he had ignored rising unemployment. But then, inthe eyes of most economists, that was the classic trade-off:To beat down inflation, it was generally believed, you had tobe willing to create some economic suffering. Unemployment hadto rise. This would increase competition for jobs and make unionsthink twice before asking for fat wage increases. As the economyslowed, companies would also have more trouble pushing throughprice increases. The problem of "too much money" would be solved. <p> And then came Jimmy Carter....  <p> Carter came to office in 1976 with almost no understanding ofmacroeconomics and with a stunningly unrealistic view that hecould handle everything at once. He planned to get inflationunder control, to bring down unemployment, to balance the federalbudget, and to add dozens of new federal programs. As for theclassic trade-off between inflation and unemployment, Carterwould not face the notion that it even existed. Advisors whourged him to get "his" recession out of the way early, as theyused to phrase it -- were ignored. "High unemployment is a morallyunacceptable way of combating inflation," he said in his firstpronouncement on the subject, "and I totally reject that approach." <p> So what did that leave him with? Not much, as it turns out.Carter seemed to think that he could kill inflation merely throughpersuasion. He thought he could talk America in off the ledge.His inflation-fighting plans always revolved around a complicatedseries of voluntary wage and price guidelines that both businessand labor were supposed to abide by. Voluntary guidelines couldwork only if Carter enforced them from the bully pulpit of theOval Office. Yet when it came to doing so, Jimmy Carter was infuriatinglytimid. Within the White House, for instance, he would encouragehis staff to stand up to labor, then the greatest special interestof them all, but in the end, he would always capitulate. Thishappened most vividly in late 1977, when the administration'ssudden change of heart allowed the United Mine Workers to extracta 37 percent wage increase from the nation's coal companies aftera bitter strike.  <p> It was the same with big business. The administration's Councilon Wage and Price Stability -- the White House bureaucracy chargedwith monitoring the guidelines -- would catch some company raisingprices far beyond the maximum allowed and would bring these violationsto the president's attention. Carter never did anything aboutit. The strongest action he ever took against any company wasto cancel a scheduled lunch at McDonald's because it had raisedthe price of Big Macs.  <p> Inevitably, inflation began creeping up soon after Carter tookoffice. Having fallen to 4.9 percent in 1976, Ford's last yearin office, the CPI rose to 6.7 percent in 1977, Carter's firstyear as president. Then, in the first three months of 1978, foodprices rose 15 percent, gasoline 11 percent, and medical costsmore than 9 percent. Inflation crept forward so steadily, soresolutely, that many concluded that rising prices were partof the natural order of things. Charles Schultze, head of theCouncil of Economic Advisors, came to the astonishing conclusionthat the core inflation rate -- the amount of inflation thatresulted "naturally," without any external events like an OPECprice hike or a sudden food shortage -- was 6 percent.   <p> By the end of 1978, inflation stood at 9 percent, nearly twiceas high as when Carter took office. Inflation had become a seriousmenace. "It is impossible to overestimate the importance of theinflation issue," began a late-1978 memo written by Gerald Rafshoon,the president's media advisor. "It affects every American ina very palpable way. It causes insecurity and anxiety. It threatensthe American Dream." In this, he was surely right.  <p>   <p> If you're too young to have been fully aware of the age of inflation,or if you've washed away the memory in the intervening decadeof bull markets and low inflation, it's worth taking a momentto conjure it up again. To do so is to understand what's motivatingAlan Greenspan right now.  <p> During the age of inflation, Americans had to wait in line forhours to buy gasoline -- at prices that were twice what theyhad been just weeks before. A trip to the supermarket was a debilitatingexercise; from one visit to the next, one's money bought palpablyless. Theodore White, the great chronicler of presidential campaigns,would later recall the way Americans "winced and ached. Somemysterious power was hollowing their hopes and dreams, theirplans for a house or their children's education. ...  (T)hosewho still held war bonds  ...  or put their money in savingsbanks -- all those had been cheated. What they saved today would ...  be worth half as much five years later."  <p> That's what inflation felt like.  <p> And no one could do anything about it except adjust. Americanscoped with this new economic reality just as they had once copedwith the reality of the Depression. Those who lived on fixedincomes devised strategies to keep their income rising. Wivesjoined the workforce by the millions. "It turns out that peoplecan scramble and keep up longer than you think they can," economistBarry Bosworth, one of Jimmy Carter's chief inflation fighters,once remarked. That of course is also what made stamping outinflation so difficult: Americans spent as much time adaptingto it as they did complaining about it.   <p> In retrospect, three changes seem most significant. First, homeownership took on a new kind of importance: a financial importance.As inflation drove up the price of houses, people began not somuch buying homes as investing in them; the down payment wastheir equity stake. For most families, the house was their largestand most important financial asset, the one asset whose valueseemed to go in only one direction: up. When people latched onto this fact, a mad scramble ensued, as Americans used everydollar and bit of leverage they could find to buy the most expensivehouse possible. (Between 1975 and 1978, home mortgages in Americarose from $479 billion to $737 billion.) Years later, Americanshad become so accustomed to seeing their houses rise in valuethat they forgot they could lose value as well. When home pricesdid finally begin going down, at least a little, in the early1990s, it came as an enormous shock.  <p> Second, people began taking their money out of bank passbookaccounts -- where, by law, interest was fixed at 51/4 percent-- and began putting their savings in money market funds. Thesefunds were offering market rates of interest, which during thepeak years of inflation could get as high as 17 and 18 percent.This wholesale transfer of money would have consequences thatare still felt to this day. At that moment, banks and S&Ls losttheir grip on the middle-class saver, a grip that they've neverbeen able to regain. Instead, the brokerage houses and mutualfund companies that ran the nation's money market funds gainedaccess to millions of Americans who had never before even thoughtabout investing. This is when the old Depression-era fear offinancial risk came to an end; even though money market fundslacked federal deposit insurance, people were willing to usethem because they offered the only hope of having their savingskeep pace with inflation. It also began the slow process by whichmillions of people went from being savers to being investors.Once their money was in money market funds, it never returnedto the bank. And once the 1982 bull market began, it was almostnatural for that money to make its way into stocks. Mutual funds,which were insignificant prior to the 1980s, now hold $2 trillionin assets and are among the most powerful of financial vehicles.Their current prominence is directly traceable to the age ofinflation.  <p> Finally, the age of inflation induced Americans to borrow asthey'd never borrowed before. In just three years, 1975 to 1978,consumer borrowing increased by 60 percent, a rate of increasethat hadn't been seen since the 1950s. But in that earlier time,interest rates were low, consumer desires were exploding, andthe rapidly expanding middle class was full of optimism aboutthe future. The conditions for borrowing were ideal. In the 1970s,by contrast, interest rates were at historic heights, and Americanswere decidedly pessimistic about the future. Yet the middle classin the 1970s was outborrowing its 1950s counterpart. Historically,whenever consumer debt reached 2.5 percent of total consumerdisposable income, it would be followed by an immediate slowdownin borrowing. In 1978, consumer debt regularly topped 3 percentof disposable income, yet there wasn't so much as a hint of aslowdown. Thrift, perhaps the most powerful of all financialhabits, was suddenly outmoded. In a time of double-digit inflation,simply saving money wasn't virtuous; it was foolish. It meantpaying for tomorrow's more expensive goods with yesterday's diminisheddollars. Borrowing, on the other hand, meant purchasing yesterday'sless expensive goods with tomorrow's inflated dollars.  <p> In a paper titled "Social Changes Affecting the Consumer FinanceIndustry, Period 1980-2000," Dana Bramlette and Anthony Weiner,two futurists at the University of Southern California, codifiedthe changing values evolving from the age of inflation. Speakingof the baby-boom generation, just then inching toward middleage, they declared, "The traditional values espoused in PoorRichard's Almanack (have been) turned upside down," replacedby a new set of cultural assumptions, such as:  <p> 1. It doesn't pay to save for a rainy day.  <p> 2. Buy now, pay later: Prices will invariably go up, and thepurchasing power of your dollar will invariably go down.  <p> 3. Stretch your financial obligations over as long a periodof time as possible.  <p> 4. Borrowing improves your credit rating.  <p> 5. Pay your bills as late as you can (without jeopardizing yourcredit rating).  <p> Thus did America cope with inflation; thus did America change. <p>   <p> The most memorable political figure to emerge from the age ofinflation was not Jimmy Carter but one of his aides -- a rathertoothless aide, as it happens, with a title that was all butmeaningless. The aide was a genial, uninhibited, outspoken professorof political economy, on leave from Cornell University, by thename of Alfred Kahn; his title was inflation czar. Within theWhite House, he had no power. Nor did he have the temperamentto acquire power. What he had, mainly, was the kind of irrepressiblecandor that one rarely sees in a political figure.  <p> Kahn is the only presidential aide in history to call the Araboil producers "schnooks." He once described Carter's wage andprice guidelines -- which he himself was supposed to be administering-- as "those stinking guidelines." Another time, after he hadsaid once too often that he thought the country was headed fora "real depression" if inflation wasn't stopped, he got a callfrom Stuart Eizenstat, Carter's chief domestic advisor. "Fred,"said Eizenstat gently, "please try not to use that word. It scarespeople." A few days later, Kahn was delivering his stock speech,and when he got to part where he usually predicted a depression,he said, "We're going to have a  ...  I don't care what you callit. Let's call it a banana."   <p> It wasn't candor that made Fred Kahn wrong for the job, though.He simply had nothing to add to the administration's store ofanti-inflation ideas, something he freely admits. "I could neverthink up enough magic bullets," he says now with a small sigh.Eventually, he came to the conclusion that no one could -- noeconomist, at least. Inflation, he once wrote Carter, wasn'tjust a matter of economics. "It is a deeply sociological, psychological,political phenomenon. It is  ...  a reflection of a society indissolution (resulting from) a weakening of the social fabric....  To turn responsibility for devising policies and programsfor dealing with that kind of deeply social phenomenon to a groupof professional economists is in very large measure to turn itover to the wrong kinds of people."   <p> Undoubtedly, such sentiments were more correct than not. ButCarter didn't need a philosopher. He needed a hit man. Kahn'sappointment coincided with the onset of double-digit inflation.And there wasn't a thing Kahn or anyone else in the administrationcould do about it. In December 1978, OPEC raised oil prices 14percent. The following month, the producer price index, an importantinflation indicator, rose 1.3 percent in a single month, whichtranslated to a 16.8 percent annual rate. In April 1979, theTeamsters announced a new three-year contract that called fora 30 percent wage hike. Over the course of the spring of '79,meat prices rose 85 percent. And then that June, OPEC did itagain, announcing a near doubling of oil prices, from $12.50a barrel to $22 a barrel. Carter, returning home from a summitmeeting in Tokyo, skipped a planned trip to Hawaii to take commandof the looming crisis. He did so by making a speech -- the mostfamous speech of his entire presidency, and one that would hauntthe Democratic Party for the next decade and more.   <p> The speech has since come to be labeled the malaise speech,though as has been often noted since, the word malaise was neveractually uttered by the president. Its tone, however, was unquestionablygloomy, brimming with the notion that we had lost our way asa nation and that inflation was part of the proof of that.  <p> The speech had been the subject of vigorous argument withinthe White House. Of the Carter aides who believed the malaisespeech was a terrible mistake, the most vehement was Vice PresidentWalter Mondale; his argument was directly connected to his senseof how people were reacting to inflation. "He rejected the diagnosisthat the country was suffering from some sort of ... emotionalcollapse," wrote Elizabeth Drew in The New Yorker. "He arguedthat the need was not to scold people for being 'selfish,' butto respond to what was bothering them."  <p> To read old memos written by Carter's advisors is to wonderif they were living in a parallel universe. "Our (anti-inflation)activities have to be visible, sustained and planned," a Carteraide named Anne Wexler wrote the president, echoing the wordsof a hundred similar missives. "They must build on each otherand reinforce a constant theme, rather than appearing to be adhoc reactions to current developments." But what activities wasshe talking about? And how would they be planned? And how wouldthey reinforce a constant theme? And what was the theme, anyway?Inflation fighting had devolved into wheel spinning.  <p> A large part of the problem was that there weren't enough peopleworking in the Carter White House who were personally affectedby inflation. Many of Carter's aides were in their 20s or early30s -- chief of staff Hamilton Jordan, for instance, was 32,press spokesman Jody Powell just a few years older. Young andsingle, living in one-bedroom apartments and making more moneythan they'd ever seen in their lives, they were oblivious tothe psychological and economic pressures inflation placed onmiddle-class families. "Back then, a prime rate of 20 percent(a figure reached in 1980) didn't mean a thing to me," says DavidRubenstein, who was all of 26 when he worked as a White Housedomestic policy aide. "Now I think, 'My God! How did people buyhouses? How did the economy function?'"  <p> Kahn's aide Al From, who now runs the Democratic LeadershipCouncil, an organization founded in 1985 to push a centrist Democraticagenda, was one of the few in the Carter White House who actuallyfelt the pressures of inflation. Though less powerful than thelikes of Jordan or Powell, he was older. He owned a house andwas raising a family, for which he was the sole provider. Perhapsthat is why he was one of the few Carter aides who could clearlysee how fundamentally pointless the administration's anti-inflationprograms had become.  <p> Again and again, From tried to make the White House see thatall the anti-inflation programs in the world didn't mean a thingif they didn't drive down the rate of inflation. But his colleaguesdidn't understand -- not until it was much too late -- that inflationwas the overriding concern of the middle class. It used to infuriateFrom the way the liberals in the administration tried to castinflation as an issue affecting only the weak and the poor: "Sucha portrayal of inflation's impact is likely to create a negativereaction among the much broader constituency of middle Americanswho are reeling from high inflation," he fired back. "(I)ts greatestdanger is to our economic security, the security that most Americansare seeking." Unemployment was the historic Democratic issue,but unemployment only affected the unemployed. Inflation affectedeverybody. That was the cruel political calculus.  <p>   <p> In the fall of 1979, the central battle in the war against inflationmoved away from the White House. That October, with the WhiteHouse efforts having proved ineffective, the battle was joinedby Paul Volcker, who three months before had been appointed byCarter to head the Federal Reserve. Volcker's efforts were sustainedand serious, and they caused wrenching hardships. But when hewas done, he had successfully broken the back of inflation. Fromthat point forward, inflation fighting would always be the Fed'stop priority.   <p> Volcker's weapon was the Federal Reserve's control of monetarypolicy -- that is, the ability to control the nation's moneysupply. Traditionally, the Fed had influenced the money supplyindirectly, by fiddling with interest rates, moving them up ordown a quarter of a percent at a time. Volcker was convincedthat this approach was too incremental. He decided that the FederalReserve should control the growth of money directly, by regulatingthe amount of money the nation's banks had to hold in reserve."In effect," he later wrote, "our emphasis would shift from controllingthe price of money to its quantity." He was choosing, that is,a radical solution, never before tested in the real world, thathad long been promoted by a group of conservative economistsknown as monetarists. Their champion was Milton Friedman, a staunchproponent of the idea that the best way to influence the valueof the dollar was to restrict the total number of dollars washingthrough the economy. To fight inflation, this essentially requiredkeeping the growth of the money supply in line with the growthof the economy.  <p> "More focus on the money supply ... would be a way of tellingthe public that we meant business," Volcker wrote. "People don'tneed an advanced course in economics to understand that inflationhas something to do with too much money. If we could get outthe message that when we say we're going to control money, wemean we're going to deal with inflation, then we would have achance of affecting ordinary people's behavior." But that's notwhat happened at first. Interest rates, loosed from their moorings,went crazy. The prime rate, which had been hovering in the 12percent range, jumped to 15.75 percent that fall. And inflationitself kept rising. In January 1980, the Labor Department confirmedthe country's worst fears: The CPI had risen 13.3 percent in1979 -- the largest one-year increase since the late 1940s.  <p> Two days later, Carter released his annual economic report toCongress, which has to rank as one of the most pessimistic documentsever issued by an American president. In the report, the administrationsaid that it anticipated that the gross national product woulddrop by 1 percent in 1980 while unemployment would rise to 7.5percent. In other words, the president of the United States waspredicting that the country would be thrown into a recession-- in an election year! This wasn't just an unusual admission;it was unheard of. In the same report, Carter predicted a secondstraight year of double-digit inflation, something America hadn'tseen since World War I. A new word was added to the nation'spolitical discourse: stagflation. This wasn't supposed to bepossible under the theory that described the seesaw trade-offbetween inflation and unemployment. Now, it appeared, the wholeseesaw was sinking into the muck. Volcker again: "(T)here wasa palpable sense of growing political panic as well as economicdistress."  <p> Panic and distress accelerated in the following month. On February22, 1980, the Labor Department announced the sharpest rise yetin the CPI -- 1.4 percent, a figure that projected to an annualrate of 18 percent. While this might seem like just another numbinginflation report, it was not. The nation seemed to be seizedby the notion that the great postwar economy was on the vergeof disintegrating. The rise in the CPI was the highest one-monthgain since the Arab oil embargo of 1973. And it was accompaniedby the news that the major banks were raising their prime rateby three quarters of a point, to 16.5 percent -- the single largestone-day rise in a decade. When the bond market opened the followingMonday, it crashed.  <p> The news had a galvanizing effect on the Carter administration,which reacted, for the first time in four years, with a realsense of urgency. Carter announced that inflation had reached"a crisis stage" and asked his advisors to come up with yet anotherinflation-fighting plan. Shortly afterward, he and his aidesbegan a series of extraordinary private meetings with the congressionalleadership in a dramatic attempt to rewrite the 1981 federalbudget, which Carter had submitted to Congress a few weeks earlier.That original budget, which assumed a deficit of $15 billion,had been greeted with derision, especially on Wall Street, whichsaw an out-of-balance budget as sending "the wrong signal" aboutinflation. Three weeks later Carter announced that the budgetwas in balance -- and he unveiled a new, tougher inflation policy.Naturally, it resulted in the biggest disaster of all.  <p> Little in Carter's tough new inflation policy was new or tough.Except for one new wrinkle, it was (sigh) typical Jimmy Carter.Along with new wage and price guidelines and a freeze on federalemployment, Carter had slipped in a program to place federalcontrols on consumer credit. He was trying to rein in creditcard debt, which of course had accelerated greatly. This wasthe first inflation-fighting idea that Fred Kahn could claimcredit for. Kahn believed that Americans were using their creditcards to sustain a lifestyle that inflation was pushing out ofreach, an act of trying to keep pace with inflation that onlyfueled it.  <p> What happened next was amazing. The entire country simply stoppedborrowing. "No one had ever seen anything like it," recalls Volcker.Kahn made speeches suggesting that people cut up their creditcards, and thousands did so and sent their sliced-up cards tothe White House to show that they supported the president's program. <p> It was quickly apparent that cutting up their credit cards wasthe worst thing they could have done, for both Carter and themselves.For months, consumer borrowing was the only thing that had keptthe recession at bay; when the borrowing stopped, the economycollapsed -- "within a matter of days," says Volcker. Embroiledin a nasty fight for the nomination, grappling by then with thehostage crisis in Iran and the Soviet Union's invasion of Afghanistan,with his popularity at an all-time low -- this was the momentthat Jimmy Carter finally got "his" recession.  <p> As quickly as he decently could, Volcker undid the credit controls.By July, they were gone. He also temporarily loosened the moneysupply to revive the economy. Meanwhile, the balanced budgetwas quickly jettisoned as Congress added billions in additionalspending to put some life back in the economy. Interest ratesplummeted, the recession ended almost as quickly as it had begun,and even the CPI slowed down for a few months, though not enoughto prevent a second consecutive year of double-digit inflation. <p> But it was too late for Jimmy Carter. Everything he had triedhad failed, and he had nothing left. He was done trying to fightinflation. Not long before the election, Kahn tried to get Carterto take a large army contract away from Kerr-McGee, an Oklahomaoil company, which the Council on Wage and Price Stability hadfound in violation of the price guidelines. But then the armyweighed in, claiming that the Kerr-McGee contract was importantto national security, and that was that.  <p> And all the while, Carter's opponent in the general election,Ronald Reagan, was using inflation as a stick to bludgeon thepresident with. The first page of the first campaign memo Reaganreceived, back in 1979, had said, "By a wide margin, the mostimportant issue in the minds of voters today is inflation." Henever forgot it. "When (Carter) took office," Reagan used tosay in his stump speech, "inflation was 4.8 percent, and he saidhe was going to do something about it. And he did. It's now averaging16.4 percent." A week before the election, the two men held theirone and only debate. Reagan was well ahead in the polls, buttoward the end of that debate, he administered the coup de gracewhen he looked into the camera and asked: "Are you better offthan you were four years ago?"  <p> Thanks to inflation, we were not better off, and we knew it.At that moment, Jimmy Carter's last, flickering hopes of winningreelection were gone for good.   <p>   <p> In the end, of course, Volcker's monetary solution took, butit was a brutal thing to live though. In 1980 and 1981, the policypushed the nation into the most wrenching recession since theDepression. That recession wrung inflation out of the economy.And Ronald Reagan did his part, too. When the nation's air-trafficcontrollers went out on strike in 1981, six months into his presidency,Reagan took the kind of action that Carter never could. He firedthem all. As cruel as this action was, it sent an unmistakablesignal: Inflationary wage settlements were over. Companies couldforce tougher terms on labor, and the government would not interfere.Whatever one thought of this stance as social policy, as economicpolicy, it worked.   <p> The CPI rose just 3.8 percent in 1982, and it stayed in thatgeneral range for the rest of the decade. That's not to say thatpeople didn't continue to treat their homes as an investment,to chase the higher yields they had become accustomed to duringthe age of inflation, and to continue to rely increasingly oncredit cards and consumer borrowing. They did all of these things,and they do to this day. The age of inflation had done its work:As surely as had the Depression, it had changed the way the greatAmerican middle class thought about and dealt with its money. <p>--------------- <p>This article is adapted from "A Piece of the Action: How theMiddle Class Joined the Money Class" by Joseph Nocera, copyright1994, to be published this fall by Simon & Schuster.  <p>  <hr>  <p>Copyright 1994 Capital Publishing Limited Partnership. All rightsreserved.  <p>  <p>
