				<font size=6><b>94/06-How Much Higher Will the Fed Take Rates?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
It depends on how soon the economy slows.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>In early April, any bond trader with two Treasurys to rub together knew that short rates were going to 3.75 percent. Indeed, the Federal Reserve bumped rates to that level on April 18. The dust had barely settled on the rate hike when bond traders started talking of a move to 4 percent, possibly around the Fed's mid-May meeting.<p>The question of the hour: Will a boost to 4 percent be the last? Answer: It depends. Until the economy responds with slower growth, the Fed is likely to keep raising rates. Signs that the economy is slowing aren't easy to spot, but bond traders are scanning the horizon. "What the bond market wants to see is good news in the tea leaves," says Barbara Kenworthy, fixed-income-portfolio manager for Dreyfus. Good news, to the bond market, is slow growth.<p>Look hard, and you'll find some such news. Commodity prices have come down a bit - April's rate hike choked a rally in gold. Housing sales have slowed, and auto sales are growing at a slightly less explosive rate - although that may be because manufacturers can't keep up with demand, which could be inflationary. Long bond rates, beyond 15 years, moved lower the day after the Fed's April hike.<p>Bond traders think they see the light at the end of the tunnel. "When we had the first 25 basis-point hike, everybody was saying 50 to 100," Kenworthy says. "Now that we've had a 75 basis-point hike, there's not so far to go. If we can just get to the point where people believe the Fed."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
