	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Sure, Its Growing, But How Fast?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Sure, Its Growing, But How Fast?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
After the quake and the snows, it's all guesswork<p>By Jim Jubak<p>Listen carefully and you can almost hear economists ratcheting up their forecasts. The economy is much stronger than these folks thought it would be when they made their predictions in December 1993. But the California earthquake and a winter of storm upon storm make the numbers for the first quarter tricky guides for the rest of 1994. For instance, was January's 22 percent drop in housing starts simply a result of the weather? How strong would the economy have been without weather-related events? And how have they changed the trend line for the year? <p>At the end of 1993, the consensus expected growth of 2.5 percent to 3.5 percent in 1994. That was when everyone still thought growth in the fourth quarter of 1993 had been 5.9 percent.<p>Now that 5.9 percent has been revised to 7.5, the consensus for 1994 has risen to between 3 percent and 4 percent. Jeff Thredgold, chief economist at KeyCorp, the nation's 11th largest bank, sees 3.5 percent growth for the first quarter, "once you cut through the noise from the earthquake and the snow." Growth, Thredgold says, will be 3 percent to 3.3 percent for the second and third quarters.<p>As for the fourth quarter, amateur economists should watch mortgage rates, says Thredgold. Rising rates will definitely throw cold water on home building and associated industries. If rates rise to 8.5 percent in the fourth quarter, take 0.3 to 0.5 percentage points off of the growth rate.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
