<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Deficit Dove</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Deficit Dove</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p><p>By Suzanne Costas<p>Northwestern University economist Robert Eisner has a different view of the budget deficit from most of his colleagues. He thinks it's largely benign and that President Clinton's newfound budget-cutting zeal has more to do with politics than with securing the nation's economic future. Eisner has written a new book explaining this nearly heretical position--The Misunderstood Economy: What Counts and How to Count It, published this month by Harvard Business School Press. He talked with Worth senior writer Suzanne Costas.<p>
Q: Can we really afford to be so unconcerned about the deficit? Mainstream economists have argued that the deficit threatens to sap the country's long-term economic health, that it leads us to consume too much and save too little.<p>A: We should not only be unconcerned, but we should reject that argument vigorously. Ross Perot has said we're spending our children's money. That's ridiculous. Our children's money hasn't even been printed yet. Whenever our children need money, [Federal Reserve chairman] Alan Greenspan or his successor can print them all the money they need. What our children are going to need to be productive are factories, plants, equipment, buildings, houses, and most important, education, the know-how to be productive citizens. <p>
Q: During his presidential campaign, Clinton promised increased investment in social programs. But the budget he presented to Congress in February offered primarily steep spending cuts. Why?<p>A: My gut feeling is that he still wants to invest in our future. But he's been influenced by stupid dogma. People think we haven't got the money, but the fact is, money can be gotten. The problem is a self-created one. Clinton can't spend without cutting elsewhere, because that's what's been legislated. The big economic package Clinton got through last year stipulates that you can't increase spending in one place without cutting it somewhere else. But he hasn't seen fit to defy that, to ask that it be changed. Except for emergencies like earthquake relief, it leaves him seriously bound.<p>
Q: You claim that deficits are okay provided income is growing faster than debt. But that hasn't been happening.<p>A: It's true that income hasn't been growing faster than debt. But depending on what happens with health care, the latest budget figures for fiscal '95 indicate that the deficit will be about $170 billion. That's less than what you'd need to keep the ratio of debt to general domestic product constant. By the end of fiscal '95, the debt is projected to grow about 5 percent and the GDP is forecast to grow about 6 percent. This implies that the ratio of debt to national income will not be rising.<p>
Q: What do you think of Greenspan's decision to raise short-term interest rates?<p>A: I think it's a bad thing to do. It only discourages investment spending. Those who want to reduce the deficit should deplore what Greenspan has done. One of the things that's brought the deficit down has been low interest rates. But from my point of view, what's bad about raising interest rates isn't that it will raise the deficit, but that it discourages investment in business and residential housing.<p>But there's a strong feeling among bankers that inflation is terrible, and bankers have a big influence on the Federal Reserve. They raise a hullabaloo. Bankers lend money long-term, and they borrow short. If inflation rises, the bank finds it has to pay a higher rate of interest, yet it's stuck with returns on loans it made at a lower rate of return some years ago. So banks take a licking if inflation goes up.<p>
Q: According to your calculations, the deficit isn't as large as we think it is. How did you reach that conclusion?<p>A: That's a fairly simple matter. If the government spends $200 billion more than it takes in a year, then at the end of the year the public has $200 billion more of government bonds than at the beginning of the year. Bonds, bills, treasury notes. But remember, at the moment there's an outstanding government debt of more than $3 trillion. Then there's inflation of 3 percent over the last year. Well, that means that the existing $3 trillion in bonds that the public already holds loses 3 percent of their value. They're worth $90 billion less because of inflation. So I would say the real deficit is not the $200 billion more of government bonds that the people hold but the $110 billion more they have after adjusting for inflation.<p>There's another important correction. When private business reports a profit or loss [on its income statement], it only includes in its account of costs the depreciation on past investment, which is virtually always less than the expenditures for a new investment. Now, if corporations included all of their current capital outlays instead of depreciation, which is what the federal government does, many, if not most, businesses would be reporting losses. So if you replace what the Office of Management and Budget has called investment-type spending with an estimate of depreciation on the existing capital, you'd knock off another $80 billion to $90 billion from the measure of the deficit.<p>
Q: Former senator Warren Rudman and other deficit hawks say your theories are fairy tales and that you forget we have to pay interest on the money we borrow. Fifteen cents of every dollar earned goes toward paying interest on the government debt. How do you respond?<p>A: That argument is completely fallacious on several counts. For one thing, the interest is not nearly as large as people make out, although that's not my main argument. It's about $200 billion a year at this point, and $200 billion is about 3 percent of GDP, so it's three cents on every dollar people earn, and that's no huge amount. The second thing wrong with that argument is the interest is not a burden on the American people. The interest is paid to the American people. In fact, I could argue that we'd be better off if the government were paying more interest. A lot of people who are receiving this interest are people living on their Treasury bills and bonds, either directly or through their pension funds or insurance policies or whatever. If you want to imagine that people pay taxes to pay the interest payments, okay. They're paying taxes and they're getting interest back, so it's a wash.<p>
Q: Some other economists argue that the real reason the public hates deficits is that voters simply don't trust the government. Aren't you sidestepping that issue by concentrating on recalculating all the numbers?<p>A: Well, there are a lot of things mixed in. We don't feel that we're getting our money's worth, that's true. To a considerable extent, it's a kind of selfishness, which is almost inevitable because too many of our taxes are not tied directly to what they deliver. Everybody wants to cut spending but not the spending for their district. It's the same with taxes. People want to see their taxes cut but not their benefits. I've long suggested we ought to earmark taxes and mean it. We have taxes for airport-construction funds, for example, but then we don't use the money for that purpose. There's also a certain amount of racism fueled by ignorance. I think there's a notion that the taxes being paid are helping the poor, and there's this notion that the poor are black, that they're loafers, that they're all on drugs and having illegitimate babies. That's what a lot of people have in mind when they say they want their taxes cut.<p>
Q: In other words, you are saying that a large measure of our problem is that the public assumes the government should run its finances like a family does, that it should watch its spending and avoid debt. <p>A: The remedy for recession, from the individual's point of view, is to pull in his horns. Paradoxically, if everybody does that, it simply makes matters worse. A business firm may feel it's a good idea to lay off employees and economize, and they're right. But if all the businesses lay off employees, they hurt each other. Those employees who've been laid off are no longer the customers of the other firms. What's true for the part is not necessarily true for the whole. That's the reason it's very important that the federal government be free to spend.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Politics, Government, Economy
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
