</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Domestic Saints in the Next Revolution</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Domestic Saints in the Next Revolution</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>In the last 20 years American women saved the economy; in the next 20 they could bring back the servant class.<p>By Walter Mead<p>Happiness, say the Japanese, is an American salary, an English house, Chinese food, and a Japanese wife. Unhappiness is English food, a Chinese salary, a Japanese house, and an American wife. The Japanese and other global sexists couldn't be more wrong. <p>In the long run the economic vitality of this nation's women is the single most important edge the U.S. has over its major industrial rivals in the race to build a 21st-century economy. Along the way, American women will create the most profound change in our society since the emancipation of the slaves. At least one part of that change, however, will seem ironic. The greater participation of women in the workforce on a more equal basis--a movement toward economic equality built on an end to discrimination based on gender--will wind up increasing the economic stratification of women. We will witness the rebirth of the servant class. <p>Real inflation-adjusted wages in the United States have been falling since 1973. That would have spelled disaster for countless families if women hadn't picked up the slack. Real family income has actually managed to rise during a period of falling wages, because more women have gone to work.<p>Women and the two-income family have also bailed out the U.S. economy. Falling family incomes would have meant disaster for the entire economy; if consumers can't buy, producers can't sell. The current economic recovery is based on an upsurge in consumer confidence and a climb in consumer spending, much of it financed with debt. The two-income family not only gives households more money to spend but more confidence about spending it. In an economy of continuing layoffs, most families have figured out that two incomes are more reliable than one. <p>Nothing indicates that women will play a smaller role in the U.S. economy in the future. In the closing years of the 20th century, 51 percent of the new entrants in the American labor force will be women. And this workforce will be better educated. In 1960, 5.8 percent of American women had completed four years or more of college education; in 1992, 18.6 percent had. By educating and employing its women, and by reducing sex-based discrimination in the workplace, the United States is in effect doubling the size of its pool of talented workers and entrepreneurs at a time when all of the industrialized world is worried about looming labor shortages created by a graying population.<p>Reaching this point has been a long, slow slog. In the 1830s and 1840s, less than 5 percent of free married women worked outside their homes--and 70 percent of those working women were employed as domestic servants. By 1870, only 13 percent of American women worked outside the home. (Of course, most women worked in the home or on the farm; the 19th century in the United States was not an age of female leisure.)<p>The 20th century saw a steady increase in the number of women working outside the home and an even greater expansion in the opportunities open to them. By 1970, 40 percent of American women worked outside the home; by 1991, census figures showed that 69 percent of working-age American women participated in the labor force--compared with 89 percent of working-age men. <p>The expansion in opportunities for women has been even more dramatic. In the 1950s, 2 percent of M.B.A. graduates were women; by 1989 that figure had jumped to 37 percent. As late as 1970 only 18.5 percent of all managers, executives, and administrators in the United States were women; in 1992, 42 percent of them were. <p>Not that the problems have all disappeared. Only about 5 percent of America's senior executives are women. And most women who work don't make very much money. The figure that we all know--that the median earnings of women are only 70 percent of men's --understates the way that women are disproportionately concentrated in industries that don't pay much to anyone. According to the Institute of Women's Policy Research, only 10 percent of working women make more than $12.67 an hour; 45 percent earn less than $6.33 an hour.<p>These are serious problems, but the long-term trend is clear. Large and increasing numbers of women are entering professions once closed to them. Each succeeding generation of women enjoys more opportunity and fairer treatment than their mothers. Even professional economists--trained to look for the dark side of almost every trend--can imagine a day when women will finally receive the equality they should have had all along. <p>Well, American women anyway. Women in Germany and Britain are perhaps a generation behind their American sisters in penetrating the upper levels of business and the professions. In southern Europe they lag even farther behind; in Japan, women face almost insuperable obstacles. The percentage of American women in administrative and managerial positions is almost twice as high as in Germany and almost five times higher than in Japan. <p>Many people think we have already seen most of the economic and social effects of the emergence of working women. Not so. Before this revolution is finished, our society will organize both work and family in very different ways from those we know today. <p>For example, in the past, work was often divided into higher-paid "men's jobs" and lower-paid work reserved for women. Women were secretaries, telephone operators, and receptionists. American education benefited from a large supply of intelligent professionals who had few alternatives to teaching as a career; the Catholic church, for example, was able to staff its parochial schools with women for whom that and nursing were the sole professional choices. <p>The quality of workers available in many of these low-paid but demanding fields has declined as educated women seek better-paid employment. What was once "women's work" has been redefined as "entry level." Young people just out of college now do photocopying and faxing--hoping to learn enough to help them move up the ladder. A hierarchy based on race and sex is yielding to one based more on age. <p>Look at another example. Before the 19th century, Europeans and Americans--like many people all over the world--tended to work and live in the same place. Master craftsmen lived above their workshops; merchants lived over their stores. Apprentices, helpers, and servants lived and sometimes ate with their boss. <p>This began to change with the industrial revolution. A separation took place. Work and the workplace belonged to the dark world of Darwinian struggle in the satanic mills. The home, where women were generally confined, became the abode of domesticity, of sweetness and light. Women--"hearth angels," some called them at the time--were carefully insulated from knowledge of the dark forces of the world of work. The sentimentalization of home life meant that women received respect in society--as mothers and wives--but were denied any real place in the world. <p>What we see today is the reversal of this process. As women move from the sphere of domesticity back into the world of work, workplaces are becoming more domestic and homes are becoming more involved in work. The working and living places of tomorrow will be more like what our ancestors knew than like the suburban segregation of the recent past. <p>As work places increasingly offer parental leave and elder- and child-care benefits, family concerns and sometimes family members are seen and heard more frequently at the office. Meanwhile, the office is also moving closer to home. The daily rituals of the American workplace--long commutes to offices and factories far removed from neighborhoods and the schools--only made sense as long as employees had no serious family responsibilities. The entrance of women into the mainstream of the workforce and the changing division of labor at home, with husbands taking on more domestic responsibilities, imply revolutionary changes in the American office. Companies will move to smaller buildings scattered in the suburbs and linked by faxes, modems, and, perhaps, video-conference facilities. Today, 7 million Americans work at home; experts predict 25 million telecommuters by 2000. <p>Other changes may be less benign. Because people tend to marry those of similar social and educational background, the continuing rise of women in the professions is likely to increase social stratification in the United States, as women with high incomes marry men with high incomes. Joint incomes of $200,000 per year or more will not be uncommon in those families. On the other hand, in families where both husband and wife are in unskilled, low-paid jobs, incomes will lag farther behind. Their income deficit will effectively double.<p>The wealthy double-income families will have the ability to hire the day-care workers, nannies, and housekeepers that they need to keep the domestic establishment humming while both partners pursue high-pressure careers. The dual-income economy will also provide a steady supply of low-paid women who must work to keep their families above water. My father's mother, like most of her generation, assumed that even middle-class people had servants. That time may be upon us again.<p>Although at least some of the changes wrought by this new economy will be a mixed blessing for some individuals, the news for the economy as a whole is solidly positive. Eat your heart out, Japan. The United States is going to keep surprising the rest of the world with its dynamism and creativity until other countries figure it out:  Women are half of the human race. To discriminate against your mothers, sisters, and daughters on behalf of your fathers, brothers, and sons is, as Antoine Boulay de la Meurthe once said of one of Napoleon's missteps, worse than a crime. It's a blunder.<p>Walter Mead is the senior policy advisor at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance: Jamie McClelland.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/6pages.gif"><br>About 6 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
