				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Markets Say Glass is Half Empty</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>Good inflation numbers aren't enough anymore<p>By Jim Jubak<p>The numbers gave wall street a choice--and the Street picked gloom. An investor couldn't ask for a clearer indicator of the psychology that is emerging in the stock and bond markets.<p>February 17 began with a bond-market rally leading the stock market upward. Consumer prices were unchanged in January, the Labor Department announced as the market opened. Analysts had been expecting this inflation indicator to come in at 0.3 percent. With inflation even weaker than predicted, interest rates on 30-year Treasury bonds fell to 6.39 percent, from 6.46 percent the previous day.<p>But that was only half of the day's news. By 11 a.m. the markets had reversed. A survey out of the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia reported solid growth in manufacturing in the region (once thought to be good news) and an upturn in prices. Just over 30 percent of the purchasing managers in the businesses surveyed reported paying higher prices. That level is the highest since December 1990.<p>Forced to pick between good national inflation news and bad regional inflation news, the market headed down. The long bond sank in price and rose in yield to 6.54 percent. That marked the first time the bond has been above 6.5 percent since August 1993. Now that bonds have reached that interest-rate marker, traders are looking at a move toward 6.75 percent. Investors who look at the economy and don't see inflationary signs to justify the market's move should remember that mass psychology is extraordinarily good at fulfilling its own prophecies. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
